<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPIDER' COULD DROP IN AT LAKERS CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Desperate to strengthen their frontcourt,
the Los Angeles Lakers are on the verge of signing an aging power
forward with a bug-like nickname who won championships with the
Detroit Pistons and Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Worm. The Spider.
</P>
<P>
   John ``Spider'' Salley, 35 years old and retired since 1996, is
expected to sign a contract with the Lakers sometime in the next
few days, sources said Tuesday. He's a curious choice, having
retired three years ago, his contact with the NBA since limited to
a seat in the NBC studio next to Hannah Storm.
</P>
<P>
   But at 6-11 (and last he played, about 255 pounds), the
gregarious veteran could compete for a job backing up at center and
power forward. The Lakers have just four players to play the two
positions and no real bruisers after Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Salley probably will get a non-guaranteed contract and be
invited to training camp, which begins Tuesday at UC Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th overall pick in 1986, Salley played six seasons in
Detroit, winning championships in 1989 and '90. He earned a third
ring playing for the Bulls, under current Lakers coach Phil
Jackson, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A defensive specialist, he blocked 100 or more shots in six of
his first seven seasons. In 10 NBA seasons, which also included a
short stint with Toronto and three years with Miami, Salley
averaged 7.3 points and 4.7 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rambis signs: Former head coach Kurt Rambis, who previously
decided to stay with the Lakers, made it official, signing a
contract to become a front-office consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, his position is adviser to the president/basketball.
His role is ambiguous but will entail consulting withowner Jerry
Buss, executive vice president Jerry West and general manager Mitch
Kupchak.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime assistant and former player, Rambis coached the
Lakers after Del Harris was fired in February. He was replaced by
Jackson in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt has long been a fan favorite, as well as a favorite of
those of us in the Lakers family,'' Kupchak said, ``and we're
pleased that he will remain a part of our organization.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Celestand signs: The Lakers announced the signing of rookie
guard John Celestand. The second-round pick signed a one-year,
partially guaranteed deal for the rookie minimum of $301,000. The
money will become fully guaranteed if he makes the 12-man roster or
starts the season on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Celestand is the third point guard on the roster, behind
returning starter Derek Fisher and second-year man Tyronn Lue. The
Lakers continue to pursue veteran Ron Harper and have expressed
interest in Brian Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   First-round pick Devean George has not signed a contract and the
stalemate in negotiations could potentially keep him out of camp, a
team source said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
