<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-ANDERSON-     09-29 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-ANDERSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Rockets' long wait to reel in free agent Shandon Anderson ended
Tuesday when Anderson agreed to terms and arrived in Houston to
sign with the Rockets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week before the start of training camp in Austin, Anderson
agreed to a contract worth $4.3 million over two years and will
hold an option for a third season at $2.42 million, according to
sources close to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The third year was considered an important protection for
Anderson, allowing him to hold the option of remaining with the
Rockets for a third season to become a ``Larry Bird'' free agent.
That would allow him to re-sign for a contract in excess of the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson opted not to take a three-year contract, thus
preserving the option to seek a new deal in two seasons, the first
chance the Rockets have to be under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson holds Bird rights with the Jazz and could have remained
with Utah for far more than he will receive from his agreement with
the Rockets. Anderson also considered the Golden State Warriors and
Indiana Pacers, both of whom could have been under the salary cap
after the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, heading into his fourth season out of Georgia,
preferred the role the Rockets could offer to start as a shooting
guard. He also wanted to live in a more urban setting than Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz owner Larry Miller said last week that Anderson no longer
would consider returning to the Jazz, but last-ditch talks
continued through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the Rockets' prime free-agent target outside of the
organization and considered the NBA's top unsigned free agent, and
agent Dan Fegan flew to Houston on Tuesday but were not available
for comment. A news conference is scheduled for 10 a.m. today to
announce the signing. Rockets officials, citing team policy, would
not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, already over the salary cap, could offer only the
$2.1 million salary-cap exception. That exception is available only
every other season for teams over the salary cap. They also have a
$1 million cap exception available this season or next.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 25, averaged 8.5 points and 2.6 rebounds per game last
season as a Jazz reserve. The Rockets envision him as a starter at
shooting guard and as a backup to Scottie Pippen at small forward.
He also would fit in with plans to adopt a more up-tempo style of
play and is considered an excellent defender at either position.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's signing could send Rockets free-agent guard Sam Mack
to Golden State or Indiana. Mack's agent, Bill Duffy, said the
Rockets have told him they probably would not bring back Mack if
they could sign Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door is still open,'' Mack said. ``But now we need to sit
down and decide what they (the Rockets) want to do. I'm still their
player; I still have my Bird rights; they could still sign me. It's
just an issue of what they're willing to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to both teams (Indiana and Golden State) every day.
Both teams are interested. They want to sign me. But they want to
see what move Shandon makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever said salary negotiations would be easy? It's a long,
drawn-out process. The key is to wait and be patient. I can't
control what the (Rockets') staff is thinking. They might see some
fit for the team that I don't see right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The fit that drew the Rockets to Anderson was to add his defense
and offensive versatility to the similar skills of Pippen, Steve
Francis and Cuttino Mobley. After waiting so long to complete their
pursuit of Anderson, they finally had the chance to see each of
their major offseason acquisitions in town at the same time
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Anderson and Francis arrived Tuesday to handle the
logistics of their moves, Kenny Thomas, the Rockets' first-round
draft pick, and Tony Massenburg, acquired with Francis from
Vancouver, began workouts at the Rockets' training facility.
</P>
<P>
   Those pieces began to come together, but Pippen's future with
the Rockets remained less certain. Pippen trade rumors have become
an almost daily source of amusement or annoyance for the Rockets.
But though Rockets officials would not comment on trade
speculation, sources said virtually every rumored deal has been
either unattractive or impossible because of salary-cap restraints.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is ironic given the sudden wave of Pippen reports that
the past two days have been devoted almost exclusively to closing
the deal with Anderson, there have been offers made to acquire
Pippen. The Lakers' offer of Glen Rice, Robert Horry and a third
player included to make the cap manipulations work _ a trade that
would have to be a part of many of the rumored deals _ has long
been unavailable. Even before the Lakers opted to at least try to
make their current mix work, the Rockets were hesitant to trade
Pippen largely for a player, Rice, in the last year of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Of the offers the Rockets have received to deal Pippen,
virtually all have been in exchange for high-priced, expendable
players, rather than for a replacement superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Other deals also have proved equally trying. Forward Don
MacLean, acquired from Orlando in the Francis deal, was added in
part to make it easier to pare the roster than if the Rockets had
kept every Grizzlies player included in the deal to make the
salaries match. But at $2.8 million next season, and $9.3 million
over the next three seasons, MacLean has been difficult to move.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Maloney, the fourth point guard last season, is a base-year
player and to be included in a trade would have to be dealt for
another base-year player with a similar salary if both teams are
over the cap, as most are by now.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the roster has begun to take shape. Charles
Barkley remains unsigned but has committed to return to the team.
But like Mack, the other free agents _ Anthony Miller and Stanley
Roberts _ do not fit into the team's plans. Miller is close to an
agreement with the Dallas Mavericks, his agent Tony Dutt said.
Roberts said Tuesday he is scheduled to work out for the Milwaukee
Bucks today.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' second-round picks, center Tyrone Washington and
forward Venson Hamilton, have signed to play in Europe, Washington
in Italy and Hamilton in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   As far as players the Rockets would attempt to add, the Rockets
could face a decision with the last roster spot currently
available. (Although teams can bring as many as 20 players to camp,
the rosters must be at 15 players with three on the injured list at
the start of the season.) With Anderson and Barkley, the roster
will include 14 players.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' next decision could be whether to add depth at
center or small forward/shooting guard. Center Thomas Hamilton
remains a project, but Massenburg could prove a sufficient backup
for Hakeem Olajuwon while Hamilton continues to develop and work on
conditioning. Mobley is the only true shooting guard reserve, but
the Rockets could play Bryce Drew and Francis together in a
backcourt if needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
