<SLUG> BC-NY-ACTOR-SUIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY ACTOR FILED NOTICE OF INTENT TO SUE CITY OVER ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photois being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An actor who plays a leading role in the Broadway
musical ``Ragtime'' and who was mistakenly arrested two months ago
at his Harlem apartment building filed court papers on Tuesday
stating his intent to file a lawsuit against the city in federal
court next month.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, Alton Fitzgerald White, and three other plaintiffs,
all of whom are black, allege that police officers stopped them
solely because of their race, even though they did not fit the
description of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, the four men filed official notice with
the city of their plans to seek at least $3 million in punitive
damages and the establishment of a court-monitored program that
would insure that the Police Department adequately disciplined
officers who stopped suspects solely because of their race, a
practice known as racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis M. Steel, the lawyer for the three men arrested with
White, said on Tuesday that he believed that racial profiling was a
systemic problem. He said a monitor needed to be in place to
oversee training and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   White, who spoke about the arrest at Rice High School in Harlem
on Tuesday, said he was in the vestibule of his building on July 16
when police officers stopped him and the three other men. The
officers, he said, told the four men they were looking for four
black men with guns. The four men were arrested, handcuffed and
strip-searched before being released five hours later.
</P>
<P>
   White's lawyer, Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New
York Civil Liberties Union, said, ``he wants to see systematic
changes. He does not want to see that happen to anyone else in the
city, specifically African-American males.'' Siegel said his client
would not settle the lawsuit without assurances that there would be
wide-ranging changes in police practices.
</P>
<P>
   Senior police officials publicly apologized to White and the
three other men, Ronald C. Jackson, 28, a student affairs
coordinator at Columbia University; Marcus McCollum, a public
relations director and Christopher Montgomery, 24, a graduate
student at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   After the arrests, Marilyn Mode, the chief spokeswoman for the
Police Department, said the men were not picked up because of their
race, but because they fit a description of drug dealers given by a
resident. She said strip-searching was routine procedure in all
felony drug cases. Her office did not return telephone calls for
comment on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
