<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REACT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX: MALONE'S NOT IN JEOPARDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The firing of Los Angeles Dodgers president and
CEO Bob Graziano, the latest bombshell to rock the foundation of
the once-stable Dodgers, shouldn't have an impact on changes the
club wants to make in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, who received a vote of
confidence for his own job security from Rick Welts, president of
Fox Sports Enterprises, said the organization's plan of attack
remains the same even after Tuesday's firing of Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Bob and I always kept Rick and ownership
abreast of what the plan is and what direction we're heading,''
Malone said. ``They were aware of our plan for the offseason. It
will continue in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Welts will sit in for Graziano while a successor is found, but
he reiterated his commitment to Malone and the general manager's
ability to turn around the dormant organization. Malone was signed
to a four-year contract by Graziano last September.
</P>
<P>
   Welts said the decision to oust Graziano, who served in the
organization for 14 years, had nothing to do with the team's
mediocre performance despite an $80 million payroll. The Dodgers
entered the day 74-82 and 22 games behind second-year franchise
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Malone is not going anywhere next year,'' Welts said.
``The baseball operations is in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson and Malone will meet with the rest
of the Dodgers' baseball decision-makers during this season-ending
road trip to decide their final course of action heading into the
offseason. Among the topics will be the future of the coaching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, Malone and Johnson repeatedly talked
about paring the club's payroll while upgrading the talent. Both
stated that trading a high-priced veteran is a possibility since
the team, in its current state, would have a $92 million payroll
next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also are saddled with burdensome multiyear contracts
on several players the Dodgers may shop during the winter. Included
in that is second baseman Eric Young and, despite the public
outburst against management, the ultra-popular Raul Mondesi. They
each are signed through 2001 at a combined $29.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, fan favorite Eric Karros has one more year left on
his contract and Malone said, at this point, he won't talk about a
contract extension. Johnson said the Dodgers might move one of
their experienced pitchers as well, and all signs point toward
right-hander Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had conversations with Kevin and Bob from a field-level
standpoint about some of the things I'd like to change,'' Johnson
said. ``I don't know (Fox Group chairman and CEO) Peter Chernin or
(Fox Entertainment Group Co-COO) Chase Carey. I don't know how much
communication there is between them. The general manager makes
(player-personnel) decisions, but if you're talking about a lot of
money, ownership has to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox showed its willingness to get involved since purchasing the
Dodgers from Peter O'Malley last March. Chase himself was
responsible for the trading of then-franchise catcher Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Carey and Chernin helped lure free-agent pitcher Kevin Brown.
They signed off on the seven-year, $105 million contract that
includes chartered flights for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Dodgers can continue down their planned path for
the offseason, but that could change with the appointment of the
new president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to go out and hire someone else in that
position, what impact is he going to have in trades and free agents
and payroll?'' Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield said. ``You
don't know what's going to happen. It's an unstable situation. This
has been the most stable organization for a long time. I think
they're searching for an identity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
