<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PUSHES RECORD, RE
 JECTS TALK HE GOT ANY SPE
 CIAL TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By CHRIS MOESER 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  PHOENIX - Responding to ongoing
stories about his privileged back ground, George W. Bush on Sept.
28 denied suggestions that he received preferential treatment in
joining the Texas Air National Guard and again when he bought the
Texas Rangers baseball team in 1989.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an interview with The Arizona Republic, Bush sought instead
to highlight his record as governor, suggesting the stories were
idle spec ulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just what happens when you're running for office,''
Bush said. ``People speculate on all kinds of things. The truth of
the matter is I put together the group that ended up buying the
team (Rangers) from Eddie Chiles. He wanted to sell, and I
purchased.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, based in part on earlier reports, said
Sept. 28 that Bush got preferential treatment when he bought the
team in 1989 from Chiles, a longtime friend of Bush's father,
former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The story suggested Bush's invest ment group was unable to put
together a deal until Baseball Com missioner Peter Ueberroth
intervened to attract another investor, Richard Rainwater of Fort
Worth. Ueberroth reportedly encouraged Rainwater to join the deal
``out of respect'' for President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The story also suggests that Bush borrowed most of the $606,000
he invested in the team _ less than 2 percent of the total
investment. He earned $14.9 million when the team was sold last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I was the buyer of choice. Eddie Chiles decided
he wanted to sell to my group. What ended up happening is the
commis sioner came into Dallas and said we needed more Texans in my
group,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard and I put our groups together and became partners.
It's a very successful franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is clearly tiring of the questions about his family ties.
When the National Guard issue was raised, Bush brushed it aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to try to write something negative, just say he's
George Bush's son. I can only tell people what the facts are,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Guard unit that I joined was looking for pilots. They were
out actively recruiting for pilots. I put my name in the hat . . .
I flew, and I was proud of my service.''
</P>
<P>
   A former speaker of the Texas House said Sept. 27 that he called
the head of the Texas Air National Guard at the request of a
longtime Bush family friend to help Bush join the guard in the
midst of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But Ben Barnes said no one in the Bush family asked for his
help.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his background and upbringing, Bush responded
only that he grew up in ``a house of love'' before launching into a
de fense of his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you need to do is go over to Texas and ask people
to go check. I was the first governor ever elected to back-to-back,
four-year terms. . . . And I've got a record,'' he said, supporting
education, tax cuts, welfare reform, and faith-based pro grams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing of having run and won and then put
yourself on the ballot for confirmation one way or the other is,
people get to make a decision based not only on some one's brains
but on someone's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeated calls for commentator Pat Buchanan to remain a
Republi can. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has called on Buchanan to
leave the party. Buchanan may bolt to the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he would stay in the Republican primary so we can de
bate ideas and see whether Re publicans endorse my ideas or his
ideas or Senator McCain's ideas,'' Bush said. He said he rejected
Buchanan's suggestion that the United States should not have de
clared war on Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he chooses to bolt the party, there's nothing I can do
about it. What I then need to do is convince Republicans who may
follow him that a Republican president is one who works with the
Congress'' and gets things done.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also outlined his efforts to fight for Hispanic votes in
the race and broaden the appeal of the GOP. He praised McCain for
also reaching out to Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a series of Republican voices saying, `We
hear.' Step one is to ask for the vote,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I've done a good job of in Texas is
rejecting the politics of pitting one group of people against
another. I've been a uniter, not a divider.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has opposed English-only re quirements and California's
Prop osition 187, which denied benefits and education to children
of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredibly important mes sage to Hispanic moms and
dads to say that . . . your children will learn to read and write
in English because we understand English is the gate way to being
able to access the American Dream. But instead of saying English
only, what I've said is, I support English plus. English em powers
people to realize their dreams, plus I respect the Hispanic
heritage,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference, Bush was asked a question in Spanish
and responded in kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child ought to be educated, regardless of the status of
their parents. I can understand the reasons the people of
California expressed themselves the way they did, but I just happen
to have different point of view,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed a vigorous campaign in Arizona, hinting about a
debate and havinge ``an active TV buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is an important state. It is in play . . . I intend to
campaign hard here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
