<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-YANKS-ORIOLESXXX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT ORIOLES, 9-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Somewhere there is a college genius flopped on a
fraternity couch who can relate to the New York Yankees. The final
exam is imminent, but there's no sense of urgency. The final exam
is coming, but there's no sign of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees probably haven't approached every test _ the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, the Kansas City Royals _ as seriously as they
should have, but they'll probably be O.K. They still have the
wherewithal to ace the American League playoffs. The Yankees edged
closer to clinching the A.L. East on Tuesday night, reducing their
magic number to two by thumping Baltimore, 9-5.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez drove in four runs and with 102 runs batted in for
the season, he became the fourth Yankee to drive in 100 or more
runs this season, joining Bernie Williams, Paul O'Neill and Derek
Jeter. The quartet is the first to accomplish this feat since Joe
DiMaggio, Joe Gordon, Bill Dickey and George Selkirk did so for the
1939 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' second baseman, left the game
after his second at-bat with what the team described as a slightly
sprained left thumb, and X-rays showed no broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch swung and missed at a pitch, immediately released the
bat with his left (nonthrowing) hand and grabbed for his thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees Manager Joe Torre and the trainer Gene Monahan went to
speak to Knoblauch, who went on to finish his at-bat _ grounding
out _ before being replaced for the bottom of the third inning.
Knoblauch, who wore a soft cast on his left hand after the game,
declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Any substantial injury to Knoblauch's thumb would be a problem,
of course, because his left hand is dominant in his swing. He uses
the left hand to pull the bat and snap its barrel through the
strike zone. Opposing teams usually try jamming Knoblauch, anyway,
and would have greater reason to do so if his hand is weakened.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees slogged through their brutal 10-6 loss to Tampa
Bay Monday, they realized they played without enthusiasm, Martinez
said, without intensity. Torre watched silently, visibly upset; any
thought balloons that might have been attached to Torre certainly
would've contained a fair share of profanity. ``We saw Joe's
face,'' said Martinez, referring to the Torre, ``and we realized''
how poorly they played.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles took a 4-1 lead after two innings, against the
rookie pitcher Ed Yarnall. But in the third inning, Derek Jeter
singled and Bernie Williams walked, and Martinez strolled to the
plate as the potential tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Martinez determined to forget about his
batting average, which has hovered around a disappointing .260 most
of the season, and just concentrate on having good at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Torre and others noticed the difference in batting practice the
last couple of days: Martinez was driving the ball to both sides of
the field. ``You know it's a real good sign when he's going gap to
gap,'' said Scott Brosius, the third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Baltimore's Sidney Ponson in the third inning, Martinez
turned on a 97-mile-an-hour fastball and launched the ball into the
seats, his face splitting into a smile as he rounded the bases. The
Yankees went on to roll over the Orioles, capitalizing on some of
the 11 walks issued by Baltimore. D'Angelo Jimenez, Knoblauch's
replacement, broke a 5-5 tie in the sixth inning with a two-run
single.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees would have to collapse like _ well, the Mets _ to
finish behind Boston in the A.L. East. Their focus now, Brosius
said before the game, is to get back to playing well again, and to
win the home-field advantage through the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 95-62, one game behind Cleveland (96-61) for the
best record in the league, and one game ahead of the Texas Rangers
(94-63) as the other two division leaders also won tonight. The
Yankees beat the Indians in 7 of 10 meetings this season, and
bested the Rangers in 8 of 12; should they tie either team, the
Yankees would have the home field advantage based on their regular
season pre-eminence in head-to-head games.
</P>
<P>
   They have two more games left with the Orioles, three more in
Tampa Bay over the weekend. Torre was not talking about having the
home field in the playoffs after the game. He just wants the
Yankees _ the best and brightest in the league, on any given day or
week _ to get back to playing consistently. ``We need to win
games,'' Torre said. ``That's our priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The final exam is imminent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
