<HEADLINE>
LINE STARTS FORMING HOURS BEFORE KRISPY KREME OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS SIEROTY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Welcome to Krispy Kreme. We are now serving our
hot glazed doughnuts. How may I help you?''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, a few political proclamations and music from
The Profit and Loss Dixieland Band, Krispy Kreme Doughnuts opened
the doors and drive-through Tuesday of its second store in Southern
California and first in the San Fernando Valley. Hundreds of hungry
commuters had been waiting up to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   David Daniel, a 31-year-old coordinating producer with the
Turner Entertainment Report, arrived at 3:45 a.m. Daniel, a
resident of suburban Encino, said he wanted to be first in line for
the opening at 6 a.m. because he thinks Krispy Kremes are the best
doughnuts in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Georgia for eight years and got hooked on them
there,'' said Daniel. ``This is the first time they are going on
sale in Los Angeles, the greatest city in the world, and I figured
why not be the first one to purchase the best doughnuts here.''
</P>
<P>
   He was outdone, however, by Jim Wallace, 73, of the community of
Van Nuys, who walked through the front door moments before the
store was to open and bought the first Krispy Kreme Original Glaze
doughnut for 70 cents. Wallace described the doughnut as ``out of
this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Store manager Dave Woodard asked the retired driver from
Rockwell Industries to sign the dollar bill he used to pay for the
doughnut. The bill will be framed and hung on the wall behind the
counter. For his efforts, Daniel was the second customer and spent
$21.21 for four dozen Original Glazed doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis King, who brought along Gail Foster, drove from suburban
Simi Valley to Van Nuys for 11 dozen. She said she used to drive to
the other Southland location in La Habra occasionally to satisfy
her craving for the doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Fanaticism was definitely the flavor of the day, sprinkled with
nostalgia. Hundreds of people waited an hour or more after the
store opened to place their orders. Scores of media representatives
recorded every passing doughnut hole. A helicopter pilot was cited
for illegally landing his aircraft near the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commander'' Chuck Street, a well-known radio helicopter pilot
working as an independent contractor for KIIS-FM radio, was cited
by the Los Angeles Fire Department for landing on private property
to cover the opening of the doughnut shop, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Humphrey, a fire department spokesman, said Street
violated a city ordinance that requires pilots to get a permit to
land from the department so it can ensure adequate resources for
crowd control and safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street was very kind and complimentary and said he didn't
realize Van Nuys is part of Los Angeles,'' Humphrey said. ``There
was never a safety issue. He simply forgot to notify the fire
department of his expected landing.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. City Councilman Joel Wachs, whose 2nd District includes Van
Nuys, appeared at the opening celebration and, on behalf of the
City Council, proclaimed Tuesday as Krispy Kreme Day in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago someone became president by offering a chicken in
every pot. So I can run for mayor on a Krispy Kreme in every
kitchen,'' joked Wachs, a previous and possibly future mayoral
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Glickman, president of Great Circle Family Foods, the
exclusive Southern California franchisee of Krispy Kreme, said he
has very high hopes for the company's new Van Nuys store, which he
expected to sell 50,000 doughnuts by the end of the first day _
about 46 doughnuts per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme Doughnuts opened its first Southern California
store in La Habra in January, and in nine months the store has sold
more than 10 million doughnuts, an average of 44,000 per day,
Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response to Krispy Kreme in Southern California has been
great. We are producing as many doughnuts as we can and are selling
out of them every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said two more stores _ one at the Block at Orange
Shopping Center in the city of Orange and one just outside the
Ontario Mills Mall at Ontario _ will be opened this year, and the
company is considering more shops around Los Angeles County,
possibly in the West Valley and in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !ital! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Lisa Van Proyen contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
