<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SHOULD TAKE A LOOK AT AN O'MALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now that they've disposed of Bob Graziano, the
Dodgers ought to woo an O'Malley to succeed him. That's right. One
of Peter O'Malley's children.
</P>
<P>
   Not THAT Peter O'Malley. The last thing the Dodgers need is the
same old blood that circulated in the organization for decades.
We're thinking more along the lines of a transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   We're thinking of Susan O'Malley, the president of the
organization that runs the Washington Wizards and Capitals and the
middle of five children of the onetime president of the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   The old boys' network hasn't exactly been a rousing success for
the Fox ownership group. So why not let O'Malley into the club?
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers want someone with experience operating a sports
team, O'Malley is doubly qualified. If the organization is looking
for someone who can schmooze Corporate America, O'Malley can do
that.
</P>
<P>
   She has spent the past few years cinching corporate sponsors,
securing marketing deals and selling luxury suites for the MCI
Center, a two-year-old, state-of-the-art facility that houses both
the NBA's Wizards and the NHL's Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley, 38, has the experience and expertise to do what
Graziano could not. She can return the Dodgers to their rightful
place as the most progressive and innovative organization in
sports. Rick Welts, the president of the Fox Entertainment Group,
suggested ownership will settle for no less.
</P>
<P>
   Welts also said there are ``no age or gender requirements'' for
Graziano's successor. Good.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a sports person and a business person the Dodgers want,
O'Malley's their person.
</P>
<P>
   She relayed word Tuesday through a spokesman that she had not
been contacted about the job. Let's hope Welts was simply going in
alphabetical order and hadn't gotten past the L's (well, he did say
he spoke Tuesday morning to Dodgers executive Tommy Lasorda, who
professed no interest in Graziano's job).
</P>
<P>
   Because if the Dodgers want their next president to unearth
additional revenue streams in Chavez Ravine, the better to keep
Dodger Stadium competitive with all the state-of-the-art stadiums
springing up like mushrooms after a rain, O'Malley can do that.
</P>
<P>
   She could take that $40 million in scheduled improvements to
Dodger Stadium and turn it into a mint. With her marketing savvy,
the Dodgers would be competitive from a revenue standpoint. And
pennant races notwithstanding, isn't that really the bottom line?
</P>
<P>
   Abe Pollin, the chairman of the Washington Sports and
Entertainment Group, has said O'Malley ``did a terrific job of
revitalizing the organization from top to bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been described as an excellent motivator and adept spin
artist, conjuring an image of Lasorda in nylons and high heels.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley cares what the consumers think. She has been known to
call season-ticket holders at random to solicit their feedback.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers want their next president to rededicate the
Dodgers to community service, O'Malley can do that, too. She's so
persuasive, she'd have Raul Mondesi reading to first-graders in
Boyle Heights and Kevin Brown delivering Thanksgiving turkeys to
families in South Central L.A.
</P>
<P>
   And she'd practice what she preaches. O'Malley is in the
business of making money, but she's no mere mercenary. Her future
plans include starting her own charitable foundation.
</P>
<P>
   If it's innovation the Dodgers desire, O'Malley can provide
that. There's a reason ``Advertising Age'' has listed her among the
top 100 marketers. She is creative and calculating and in today's
clime, there's no better combination.
</P>
<P>
   When Welts said, ``Bob has a different set of experience than
what I think we need, what I want,'' he meant Graziano was first
and foremost a CPA.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley is a saleswoman at heart who has grown up in the sports
arena. She is one of the most senior-ranking women in professional
sports. If she isn't on Welts' short list of candidates to succeed
Graziano, it is simply not long enough.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
