<SLUG> BC-REACT-COVERUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS, TEACHERS UNION SAY LIVES ARE IN DANGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Students, parents and the teachers union reacted
with outrage Tuesday to a new report that accuses Los Angeles
Unified School District of concealing and minimizing environmental
hazards at schools, including several in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played politics with the health and safety of students
and teachers. To me, that's a criminal act,'' said Day Higuchi,
president of United Teachers Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Higuchi said he wants to know which teachers worked at the
schools during the periods of time described in the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any one of them develops cancer, No. 1, there's a humongous
lawsuit and, more than that, you're playing with people's lives,''
said Higuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental safety reports were downplayed or problems were
underreported during a 10-year span at schools including Portola
Middle School in suburban Tarzana and Van Nuys Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   At Portola, maintenance workers might not have been informed of
the presence of asbestos, the report said. At Van Nuys Middle
School, district health and safety officials are accused of
underreporting the amount of asbestos present in the air on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Parents whose children attend those schools were outraged by the
report's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those actions are completely unethical and criminal,'' said
Stephanie Carter, a leading proponent of district breakup and
parent of a former Portola Middle School student.
</P>
<P>
   ``To endanger the lives of children is wrong and to knowingly do
it to protect your job and to protect any kind of political agenda
is completely unethical,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Valdivieso, whose son attends sixth grade at Van Nuys
Middle School, said she was disturbed by the report's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That alarms me,'' Valdivieso said. ``I wouldn't have my kid
here if there's a danger of asbestos.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Valdivieso, 11, said he doesn't feel safe at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's something wrong, they should correct it at once,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tosca Broadous, who was waiting in her car outside Van Nuys
Middle School to pick up her sister, a teacher, called for the
district to answer the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be honest about what they're doing and not put
anybody's health in jeopardy,'' Broadous said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Delgado, principal of Van Nuys Middle School, said his
campus is safe even though an unusually high level of asbestos
prompted the evacuation of the library and administration building
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the entire school has been made safe and
construction workers are replacing all the school's floor tiles,
considered to be the source of the carcinogen-causing material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident that the school is safe,'' said Delgado,
who sent letters home to parents and held an information meeting at
the time of the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Lawler, principal of Portola Middle School, said his
campus is safe but that he does not recall the incident cited by
the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be absolutely stunned if it happened while I was here
for the past three years,'' Lawler said. ``It's hard to believe
that work got done without informing (workers) of the presence of
asbestos.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Dixon-Davis, a community activist whose son attends ninth
grade at Chatsworth High School, said the report reveals systemic
flaws in the Los Angeles Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   She said district employees who want to reveal wrongdoing are
reluctant to do so for fear of reprisal by the school board or
their superiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People cover up,'' Dixon-Davis said. ``It's a bureaucracy and
there needs to be a way to break this open.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
