<SLUG> BC-KCC-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS OK WESTERN RESOURCES MERGER WITH KANSAS CITY POWER &AMP;
LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS _ Kansas regulators Tuesday approved the merger of
Western Resources Inc. and Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co., but on
terms not quite as attractive as the utilities had once expected.
</P>
<P>
   Western Resources, whose stock price has dropped by more than
half in the last two years, has said it needed an order from the
Kansas Corporation Commission that would not harm the company
financially.
</P>
<P>
   Western wouldn't say Tuesday whether the terms of the order met
that standard. The Topeka, Kan., utility company said it was
considering its options, which include rejecting or accepting the
state's order or asking Kansas regulators in the next 15 days to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the complexity of the issues and the significant
financial implications on our company's future, we are reviewing
all of our options regarding the conditions outlined in today's
order,'' said David Wittig, Western's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory commission had already indicated that it would
not approve the merger with the conditions the KCC staff had
crafted in an agreement with the utilities in May.
</P>
<P>
   The staff agreement would have permitted the merged company to
retain four years of merger-related savings _ about $180 million.
In addition, $300 million of the deal's acquisition premium would
have been paid over several years by consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's order would put more pressure on the merged
company to find merger-related savings. And none of the acquisition
premium would be permitted to show up in customer rates.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators said they would allow the merged company to
retain all the merger savings in the first four years and an
additional $179 million of savings spread over the next 35 years.
The amount could total $359 million _ in today's dollars _ although
that could go up if there were more savings than expected in the
first four years.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas ratepayers would not receive the $45 million in rate
credits that was in the staff agreement. But there would be a rate
freeze for the first four years and then hearings would set new
rates. In theory, because the merged company had cut costs, that
should result in lower electric rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reasonable and appropriate for these savings to be
shared between ratepayers and the shareholders,'' the commissioners
said in their order.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the critics of the May staff agreement said Tuesday's
order, while not perfect, was a better balance of interests of the
utilities and customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't fault the commission for their efforts at balance,''
said Walker Hendrix, counsel for the Citizens' Utility Ratepayer
Board.
</P>
<P>
   But the big battle would come four years down the road when new
rates would be set, which would be when consumers would see any of
the promised savings.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Peterson, an area attorney representing several Johnson
County cities in the merger hearings, said the commission's order
would give the merged company more than he would have preferred.
However, a major issue with his clients was their opposition to the
acquisition premium in rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to say we would probably not be on the forefront
of an appeal,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   And Jim Zakoura, an attorney representing several industrial
customers in the hearings, said he too saw the commission's order
as a mixed bag. He would have preferred less of the savings going
to the merged company after the rate freeze but said the order was
a big improvement in not allowing the acquisition premium to show
up in rates.
</P>
<P>
   His clients haven't decided whether to ask the commission to
reconsider some of the order's provisions, Zakoura said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the commission balancing between the company and
ratepayers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So now the regulatory approvals are in hand or a decision is
near. Missouri and Kansas have given their OKs. Federal regulators
still have to vote, although their staff has an agreement with
Western and KCP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators were once considered the chief obstacles to getting
the deal completed. But Western's low stock price is now an issue,
as well. Shortly before a deal would close, either utility can walk
away if Western's stock is at or below $29.78 a share. It closed
Tuesday at $20.81.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger closed at that stock price, KCP&AMP;L shareholders
would get about $8 a share less than originally expected, when
Western's stock was in the $40s.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L spokeswoman Pam Levetzow said the utility was reviewing
the Kansas order and what effect, if any, it has on the merger. As
for what KCP&AMP;L would do if Western's stock doesn't recover: ``We
aren't prepared to talk about that yet,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
