<SLUG> BC-KC-RAIL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS $120 MILLION TO WOMAN INJURED AT RAIL CROSSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Jackson County jury on Tuesday decided that
the nation's largest railroad company should pay $120 million in
punitive damages to a Sedalia, Mo., woman severely injured in a
1997 train crossing accident.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors said they wanted to force Union Pacific Railroad Co. and
other railroads to pay to upgrade crossing signals.
</P>
<P>
   The punitive award is on top of the $40.4 million in actual
damages awarded a day earlier to plaintiff Kimberly Alcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Juror Vicky Willers of Independence said Tuesday that railroads
must pay for the signal improvements, rather than wait for
government agencies to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their railroads; it's their tracks _ they're
responsible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff lawyers hammered Union Pacific in the trial for not
having paid to quickly install lights and gates on a crossing just
south of U.S. 50 and east of Warrensburg, Mo. The railroad knew
that the crossing on a gravel county road was dangerous, they
argued.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months before Alcorn was injured in August 1997, state
officials had told the railroad that the view at the crossing was
90 percent blocked by brush and terrain. The company and state
officials started the long process to get a government subsidy to
pay Union Pacific about $200,000 to install lights and gates.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, four months before Alcorn's accident, an Amtrak
train struck a truck at that intersection, killing a 22-year-old
man. The railroad still did nothing, contending that such crossing
upgrades were the state's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 29, 1997, an Amtrak train going 65-70 mph struck the car
in which Alcorn was riding. She suffered brain damage, more than 20
broken bones and other injuries. One of her two teenage daughters
testified at trial that their mother no longer took care of them,
but that they took care of her.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found Amtrak at fault for 25 percent of the $40.4
million in actual damages but not liable for punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Union Pacific lawyer Ted Williams told jurors that
his company had properly been working with the state to upgrade the
crossing signal. Such upgrades are a state responsibility, he said,
and railroads pay to maintain them after they are installed.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific nationwide pays $26 million a year to maintain
crossings and $14 million a year for safety training programs such
as Operation Lifesaver, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a company that doesn't care about crossing
safety,'' he said, and he asked jurors to assess no punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff lawyer Grant L. Davis told jurors Tuesday that Union
Pacific had a net worth of $6.9 billion, but not even one employee
to study whether crossings needed to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   They do pay for crossing-signal upgrades in certain situations,
Davis noted: ``They do it when there's something in it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   They knew the crossing where Alcorn was injured was deadly, but
they did not think that was their problem, and they don't like to
pay to maintain upgraded crossings, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   All railroads stopped paying for upgrades after federal and
state subsidies for them were introduced in 1973, Davis told
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   He summarized the railroad's attitude since: ``It's not our
deal; it's not our duty; we don't have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell them otherwise, Davis asked jurors, and he requested a
punitive damage award of up to $689 million.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, several jurors told Davis in unison that
something has to be done about the railroads before others are
maimed or killed in crossing accidents. ``Today!'' one juror
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Davis, a Union Pacific spokesman, declined to comment on
the verdict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
