<HEADLINE>
ACLU QUESTIONS DEPICTION OF MOSES, BURNING BUSH ON KU SEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ First it was the fish on the city seal in
Republic. Now it's Moses and the burning bush on the University of
Kansas seal.
</P>
<P>
   Republic stopped using the fish symbol this summer after the
American Civil Liberties Union argued that it was the equivalent of
a municipal endorsement of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Now the ACLU's KU chapter in Lawrence, Kan., is questioning
Chancellor Robert Hemenway about the university's seal.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter this month, the ACLU said the depiction of Moses and
an accompanying Bible inscription might violate the Constitution's
``strict wall of separation between church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemenway responded Monday, saying the seal generally was
interpreted as representing a scholar's quest for knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view the seal of the university as one of its valuable
assets, one that has served the university well for over 120
years,'' Hemenway wrote in a letter. ``I will not hesitate to
defend fully the continued use of the seal.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU is not threatening to sue at this time, said Dick
Kurtenbach, the group's executive director for Kansas and western
Missouri. The KU case, however, is similar to the Republic case in
some ways, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle is certainly the same: whether or not a
governmental entity can _ and to what extent _ endorse a particular
religious belief. That was clearly the issue in Republic, and
that's what this issue with the university is about.''
</P>
<P>
   The fish has been a symbol of Christianity since the time of
ancient Rome. City officials in Republic, in southwest Missouri,
argued that the fish was intended only to send a message of moral
values and to promote ``a universal symbol of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Springfield ruled in July that the portrayal
of the fish ``impermissibly excludes other religious beliefs or
nonbeliefs and _ intended to or not _ depicts Christianity as the
religion recognized and endorsed by the residents of Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about KU's seal came up recently, Kevin Sivits,
president of the ACLU's KU chapter, said Tuesday. Someone called
the chapter to ask about the seal, and an ACLU attorney was asked
about it on a radio program.
</P>
<P>
   As word has spread, the KU chapter has received almost a dozen
calls from students who say the seal offends them, said Sivits, a
KU senior.
</P>
<P>
   Hemenway's letter said there was no ``definitive information
about who designed the seal or what the intent of the designer was
in choosing the depiction of the seal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Latin inscription that surrounds the seal translates to ``I
will see this great sight _ why the bush is not consumed,'' the
letter said.
</P>
<P>
   A KU spokesman said fire symbolized knowledge in many stories
over the years. Moses is thought to represent the humble attitude
of the scholar who recognizes the unquenchable nature of the
pursuit of knowledge, spokesman Todd Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   University departments and staff may use the seal on their
letterhead and business cards, Cohen said. It is also used on
diplomas and other official documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seal has been around longer than the Jayhawk, and it's
pretty deeply ingrained in the university's culture,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sivits said he did not know what the seal meant before his
chapter began looking at it. A lot of people probably do not know
what it means, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that ``just because it's obscure doesn't mean
it's all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
