<HEADLINE>
NORTH TEXAS STAR KICKOFF RETURNER STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ Even when North Texas was 3-8 last season, the
Eagles' kickoff return capabilities were enough to concern any
opposing coach.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the return of Broderick McGrew, however, that threat
hasn't continued. McGrew, the nation's leading kickoff returner
last year with an average of 32.6 yards per return, is averaging
17.7 yards on nine returns this season.
</P>
<P>
   UNT's opponents have used a variety of tactics to negate his
impact. Some have kicked away from him, either at freshman Aaron
Holly or short. LSU kicked it as deep as possible, forcing McGrew
to field the ball more than five yards into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one area that needs to come on,'' UNT coach Darrell
Dickey said. ``All the other teams know about Broderick McGrew from
last year, and they are spending more time containing him and
working on keeping us from breaking a long one.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrew's longest return this year is 35 yards. Last year he had
a 100-yarder, a 64-yarder and a 46-yarder. As a team, UNT is
averaging 13.9 yards per return, next to last in Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some good returns,'' Dickey said. ``We just need to
provide a little bit better field position for that \Roffensive\S
unit.'' Briefly The UNT volleyball team remains winless in Big West
Conference play. The Eagles, 4-10, dropped their 23rd and 24th
consecutive conference matches last week despite winning the first
two games of Thursday's contest against Boise State. ``The Boise
match was by far the best match we've had all season,'' UNT coach
Donna Martin said. ``Inexperience maybe created some doubts or
questions as to whether we could win that match.'' UNT's last
conference victory came in 1997 when it knocked off Cal State
Fullerton in five games. Tennis coach Dan Traxler has no problem
setting an early standard for his team. ``I guarantee this will be
the best year we've had since I've been here,'' said Traxler, who
is in his third season. If that's the case, UNT will have to
overcome quite a bit of inexperience. The Eagles open their season
Friday and Saturday as the host of the UNT Invitational. UNT has
seven newcomers, including 15-year old Siayareh Rambally, a
freshman who graduated from Allen High School three years early.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
