<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' TRAINING-CAMP DECISION EXPECTED NEXT MONTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said the team will
probably make a decision about the 2000 training camp site some
time next month.
</P>
<P>
   And it will either be Wichita Falls or in the Rio Grande Valley,
where McAllen, Edinburgh and Mission have joined forces to build an
elaborate sports complex with the hopes of luring the Cowboys, and
several major-league baseball teams for spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Both sites, polar opposites in the far north and far south parts
of the state, have their advantages and disadvantages. But this
decision will likely come down to which site offers more: more
fans, different fans, more interest, more money.
</P>
<P>
   And the more Jones talks, the more it looks like the Cowboys
will start the next decade like they did the last with a new
training camp home. Jones ended 27 years of training camps in
Thousand Oaks, Calif., when he moved the site to Austin in 1990,
where the Cowboys stayed for eight years before moving to Wichita
Falls after the 1997 camp.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's all contingent on whether Rio Grande Valley
consortium can get a facility built in time, but Jones likes the
prospects of moving to South Texas. The fans there don't get to see
the Cowboys that often and will likely be more rabid about seeing
them, and in turn, spend more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wichita Falls is closer to Dallas,'' Jones said. ``But on the
other hand, we could go to an area of the state where people don't
come to games as much as people who are closer to the area. That's
one of the things I think training camp should be about. They have
a lot of fans in that area that can create an exciting
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's the other X-factor. The training camp will be
close to the Mexican border, giving the Cowboys access to more
dollars _ excuse me, I mean giving fans in Mexico a chance to see
their beloved Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get the exposure to Mexico; I like that,'' Jones said. ``We
could get quite a bit of interest. That's a direction I'm trying to
take the Cowboys, as evidenced by the fact we've very aggressive
about playing games in Mexico. We really do want to take our team
and really address the fact that Vaqueros De Dallas is very much
sensitive to the fan support of our Hispanic base.''
</P>
<P>
   Wichita Falls has great facilities and the support of the
players and coaches. Both are likely cringing at the idea of
traveling so far south, which would make off-day trips home more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   However, 50,000 fans attended training camp in Wichita Falls
this year _ roughly half of what the Cowboys drew in Austin every
year, which means that marketing numbers were down, T-shirt sales
were down and money was down. With more than $137 million in
contracts committed to Troy Aikman and Deion Sanders, maximizing
financial potential is a must. Coryatt gives money back The Cowboys
have finally completed their business with departed linebacker
Quentin Coryatt. The former Texas A&AMP;M star, an off-season
free-agent signee who decided to retire a couple of weeks ago
because of chronic injuries before even playing a game with the
Cowboys, returned the team's $1 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt will count $225,000 on the team's salary cap this
season. However, the Cowboys will get credit for that amount on
next year's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   What's unusual about this story is that is was so non-combative.
But Coryatt, who didn't want to be accused of getting paid for not
playing, was very cooperative. A lot of players wouldn't have been.
Of course, it helps when you have a bank account strong enough to
return $1 million. Inspiring cheerleaders Much has been made about
the United States' spectacular Ryder Cup victory. What has not been
talked about locally is the role the Cowboys cheerleader's played
in Sunday's amazing comeback.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting Saturday night, the U.S. team, along with their
families and Texas Governor George Bush, shared inspirational
stories that brought many to tears. Later during that same meeting,
the players were shown taped messages from the Cowboys cheerleaders
and actress Pamela Anderson Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the U.S. team made history.
</P>
<P>
   Jones joked that he will keep that in mind when the Cowboys get
into a tight situation. Cardinals have long way to go Regardless of
whether the Cardinals beat the Cowboys on Sunday _ and that looks
unlikely _ they still have a long way to go in their drive to
become an elite team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Any momentum the Cardinals gained in last season's playoff
victory over the Cowboys was fumbled away with three holdouts: Rob
Moore, Mark Smith and L.J. Shelton. And though the players are all
aboard now, not having everybody pulling in the same direction at
the start of training camp could prove to be a setback this young
team might not get over.
</P>
<P>
   Is anybody surprised they are 1-2 and showing no evidence of
improvement from a year ago?
</P>
<P>
   Yardsticks First down During the 1990s, the Cowboys have an 8-2
record in games following a bye week. That mark includes seven
consecutive victories and a 5-0 mark at home. East streak The
Cowboys have won nine consecutive regular-season games against NFC
East teams dating to last season. The record for consecutive NFC
East victories is 14, set by the Cowboys in 1993 and 1994. Third
and short Looking for a key to the Cowboys' success this year? The
stats say credit the run, not the highly publicized passing game.
The Cowboys rank first in the league in rushing but only 12th in
passing after two games.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
