<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-MURDER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE CHARGED IN DEATH OF MISSOURI TEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 16-year-old Northland boy begged for his
life before he was stabbed to death by an acquaintance Saturday
night as three teen-agers stood nearby, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Weber was killed because some in a loose-knit group of
friends in a Kansas City, North, neighborhood believed he was going
to tell authorities about a planned armed robbery of a grocery,
said Clay County Sheriff Bob Boydston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In years past, a fistfight would have broken out over
something like this,'' Boydston said. ``Now, they think about
planning a murder. It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Three adults, all former Winnetonka High School students, were
arraigned on murder charges Tuesday in Clay County Circuit Court.
Pleas of not guilty were entered for all three, who were being held
in the Clay County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   - James W. Boyd III, 19, of 4605 N.E. Chouteau Drive, is accused
of repeatedly stabbing Weber in the torso with a knife, according
to a probable-cause statement.
</P>
<P>
   - Brett L. Johnson, 18, is accused of conspiring to murder Weber
and helping to lure him into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   - Lindsay Harper, 19, is accused of conspiring to lure Weber
into the woods. Harper is a student at Central Missouri State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Clay County Prosecutor Don Norris said Tuesday that he would
seek the death penalty for those convicted of the killing. Norris
said he planned to ask a grand jury today to return capital murder
charges. He also will seek to have a 16-year-old boy certified to
stand trial as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   A Clay County deputy spotted Weber and three of the suspected
attackers together at 5 p.m. Saturday in a traffic stop, Boydston
said. The sheriff said the killing probably occurred shortly
afterward, sometime before sunset, on an isolated hilltop in a
wooded area east of Northeast 36th Street and North Brighton
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was planned several days before it occurred,''
Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   Weber's body was found Monday. A witness was shown the body
Sunday by one of the men charged and later led authorities to the
scene, Boydston said.
</P>
<P>
   Weber's family could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Boydston said Boyd had planned to rob a grocery. For a reason
unknown to authorities, he believed Weber planned to tell
authorities about the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd answered questions quietly in the arraignment. He told the
judge he was unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   He was being held without bond.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's lawyer, Sean O'Brien, said his client was a normal kid
who once swam for a church swim team.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien recently helped reduce death-penalty convictions to life
in prison for Faye Copeland, believed to have been the nation's
oldest woman to sit on death row, and for Missouri's youngest
death-row defendant, Heath Wilkins, who was sentenced to die at 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim told the police he didn't do it,'' O'Brien said. ``As far
as I can tell, he's got two people pointing the finger at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson told authorities he was to distract another witness so
she would not see the murder. He told police he tripped over
Weber's legs as the group left the scene and that he watched Boyd
throw the knife used in the murder into a lake. Norris said the
knife had not been found.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also said he was unemployed. His bond was set at $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Harper told police she was with the group in the woods when
Johnson pulled her aside to look at the scenery. She told police
she heard Weber scream, ``Jim don't do that, please don't do that,
I will do anything,'' according to court records. Johnson then told
her, ``You know Jimmy is not leaving the woods,'' she told police.
Harper told authorities she heard Weber take his final breath as
they walked from the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's a victim in this thing,'' said her attorney,
Bill Quitmeier of Parkville. ``She wasn't part of the planning and
didn't know it was going on until it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper was frightened and feared for her life, Quitmeier said.
She was present because she was friends with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel she's innocent,'' he said. ``She's a tender-hearted
kid and would not be part of it. She's cooperated totally with the
police. I counsel people to be careful about the company they
keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper was a member of Winnetonka's 1997 volleyball team and a
member of the choir in 1998, according to the school's yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   Her bond is set at $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   - The 16-year-old boy, who is over 6 feet tall and the biggest
of the defendants, stood behind Weber so he could not escape when
the attack started, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Norris said the youth was in juvenile custody. A hearing to have
the boy certified to stand trial as an adult is Oct. 28, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weber was in a car with Boyd when a deputy stopped them on
Saturday because he suspected they might be drag racing, Boydston
said. No citations were issued. Johnson and the juvenile walked
from a house to the car, and they drove off together.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a loosely knit group that ran together,'' he said.
``The roots of their association are in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   No gang activity or drug activity was involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of all of three charged expressed shock over the case,
saying the defendants appeared to be nice, normal teens.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Harbin of Kansas City, North, said her 17-year-old son
used to ``hang out'' with Boyd, Johnson and the juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   Harbin described Johnson as shy and ``happy-go-lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbin, however, said Boyd was ``a creepy kid'' who had books on
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Boydston said Weber's body might not have been found in such a
remote location had the witness not come forward.
</P>
<P>
   The witness contacted his attorney, who contacted the sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he did a very brave thing,'' Boydston said about the
witness.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd asked the witness to help bury the body and led him to the
site, the sheriff said. Boyd also told the witness that they had
been planning to kill Weber for a month, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   They attempted to bury the body but failed because of rocky
ground, Boydston said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd told the witness he intended to cut the body up for
disposal, according to court records. Two other witnesses told
authorities they were present when Boyd and Johnson conspired to
kill Weber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little surprised by the viciousness of it,'' Norris
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
