<HEADLINE>
TRIPLE-OVERTIME LOSS TO TAR HEELS IN '57 IS ONE THAT GOT AWAY FOR
KU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With less than a minute to play in the 1957 NCAA men's
basketball championship, Kansas led North Carolina by five points.
Game over, right?
</P>
<P>
   Sure ... three overtimes later.
</P>
<P>
   On that evening of March 23 in Kansas City's Municipal
Auditorium, the two teams, battled in one of the longest, and
closest, basketball games in NCAA history. Despite sophomore Wilt
Chamberlain's 23 points and 14 rebounds, the Jayhawks lost to the
Tar Heels, 54-53.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in any game I ever played with Wilt, he was dominating,''
former Kansas co-captain John Parker said. ``They did like anyone
else and they sagged all over him, and the officials didn't call
all the fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive three-overtime game the undefeated
Tar Heels had played, and it took a minor miracle for them to force
one overtime, let alone three, against Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after all these years that's a hard game to forget
because we really should have won,'' Parker said. ``We never
thought we were going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   UNC managed to rally from the five-point deficit in the final
minute to force a 46-all tie. The teams scored two points apiece in
the first and second overtimes combined, setting the stage for a
frantic final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas led, 53-52, with six seconds remaining, when the
Jayhawks' Maurice King was whistled for a foul on Joe Quigg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never saw King foul anybody, and if they had ESPN then I
bet we would have seen that play 100 times on TV that night because
he never fouled him,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Quigg sank both free throws and then blocked the
ensuing pass-in attempt to Chamberlain to secure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Chamberlain was named the tournament's Most
Outstanding Player, prompting an altercation between him and UNC's
Pete Brennan. That galvanized a heated exchange between KU coach
Dick Harp and Tar Heels coach Frank McGuire. But things did calm
down, and the KU players managed to keep their compusure during the
awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got into the locker room after that we all started to
cry and let our emotions flow,'' Parker said. ``You don't get very
many chances to win a national championship, and we had just lost
one.'' Tomorrow: Don Budge wins first Grand Slam in 1938
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
