<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SHUT OUT MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Johnny Oates' vantage point in the Texas
Rangers' dugout gives him a perfect view of two vitally important
things as the season dwindles down: the out-of-town scoreboard and
the pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   The former gave the team's manager no satisfaction Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians and New York Yankees both won, allowing
the Rangers no chance to make up ground in the quest for home-field
advantage in the first round of the playoffs. If the postseason
started Wednesday, the club would open in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The latter, though, almost made up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fassero, Mike Morgan, Danny Patterson and Danny Kolb
combined to pitch a five-hit shutout as the Rangers routed the
Seattle Mariners, 10-0, at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire pitching staff did a good job,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers tied the 1977 team for the most victories in club
history, but the record would be more significant if the Rangers
had picked up ground on the Indians or Yankees. They remain two
games behind Cleveland and one behind New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than 93, but we'd like to win enough to get that
home-field role,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The four pitchers who worked Tuesday night would just like to be
in the playoffs, no matter where the Rangers play their first game.
</P>
<P>
   Oates is expected to carry 11 pitchers into the playoffs.
Starters Aaron Sele, Rick Helling, Esteban Loaiza and John Burkett
have four of those spots, and relievers John Wetteland, Jeff
Zimmerman, Tim Crabtree, Mike Venafro and Mike Munoz are assured of
another five.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Fassero, Morgan, Patterson and Kolb battling for the
final two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who pitches is in competition,'' Oates said.
``Everybody we saw pitch tonight, there's a reason for
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   All four gave Oates reasons to consider them.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero made his bid first, and pitched four shutout innings. He
allowed one hit, a single by Mike Blowers in the fourth, but walked
four. The bases on balls contributed to a high pitch count, which
prevented him from working the required five innings for a victory.
He was on a limit of 75-80 pitches and was pulled after throwing 73
through the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty good considering I hadn't thrown much in 13
days,'' said Fassero, who had worked only one-third of an inning
since going five in a start against the Minnesota Twins on Sept.
14. ``I walked guys, but I wasn't all over the place. They were
close pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero did his best work in his final inning. He walked Edgar
Martinez, and Blowers followed with his single. But Fassero struck
out Jay Buhner and David Bell and got Dan Wilson on a fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that bothers me is the four walks, but the
bottom line is he put four zeroes up there,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan followed with three shutout innings and was credited with
the victory to improve to 13-8. He allowed three hits, all singles,
and didn't walk anyone. It was his first appearance since a
disastrous outing against Tampa Bay on Sept. 19, when he allowed
five runs on five hits in 11/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson followed with a perfect eighth inning that included
strikeouts of Ken Griffey Jr. and Martinez to run his scoreless
streak to six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kolb finished off the shutout with a shaky ninth _ he gave up a
hit and a walk _ but an injury might knock him out of contention.
He's pitching despite a stress reaction in his right elbow, and he
said he felt it Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got through it, but there's some tenderness there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Oates saw nothing to separate the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pitch well, it just makes it harder for them to make
the decision,'' Fassero said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
