<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M OFFENSIVE LINE COULD GO WITH BACKUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Through the years, Texas A&AMP;M football
coach R.C. Slocum has referred to plenty of positions manned by
unproven players as ``question marks'' for the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual punctuation mark never appeared on an A&AMP;M depth
chart until yesterday. Now, it's there for all to see at left
tackle: two question marks, next to the phrase ``to be
determined,'' in the No. 2 spot behind starter Tango McCauley as
the fifth-ranked Aggies (3-0, 0-0) prepare for their Big 12 opener
against Texas Tech (1-2, 0-0).
</P>
<P>
   If McCauley is unable to overcome a sprained ankle that limited
his participation in yesterday's practice, ``to be determined''
will describe A&AMP;M's left tackle situation heading into the 6 p.m.
game Saturday in Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   A converted defensive lineman, McCauley moved up to No. 1 after
Shea Holder suffered a season-ending knee injury Saturday in a 23-6
victory against Southern Mississippi. Holder, a fifth-year senior
from Lamar High School, tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his
right knee and will need reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   If McCauley can't play against Tech (he's listed as
questionable), the Aggies will protect the blind side of
quarterback Randy McCown with a redshirt freshman who spent last
week playing a position other than left tackle. That description
could fit either Michael Mahan or Taylor Whitley, who have been
shifted from right tackle and right guard, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Aggies managed only 299 yards against
Southern Mississippi, playing with a reshuffled offensive line is
``a big concern'' to tailback Dante Hall, who managed 23 yards on
16 carries against the Golden Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   J.B. Grimes, the Aggies' offensive line coach, said he is
confident in his backups. But none, including McCauley, have much
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern about Tango is consistency. He has great
ability but he needs to do things right all the time,'' said
Grimes, who considers McCauley, a sophomore, his best available
option at left tackle. ``But it takes time to get those
fundamentals down. And he's only played three games at offensive
line in his life.'' Disregarding the hype Although the Aggies have
been installed as 17-point favorites, Slocum said it would be
unrealistic to expect anything but a tight battle against a Tech
team that will be coming off an open date and playing to silence
the critics of embattled coach Spike Dykes. None of the past five
games in this series have been decided by more than seven points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a close, tough game. The only people who
will be surprised by that are the ones who have their heads stuck
in the sand or don't realize what college football is all about,''
Slocum said. Hardeman improving Slocum said fullback D'Andre
Hardeman, slowed since the season opener because of an ankle
sprain, is close to 100 percent. Hardeman will be available
Saturday, but Ja'Mar Toombs will be the starter, Slocum said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
