<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU WANTS TOMLINSON OVERLOAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU finally racked up a 1999 victory last
weekend, largely through the execution of one obviously simple
plan:
</P>
<P>
   Putting the ball in the hands of LaDainian Tomlinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we didn't do at Northwestern,'' coach Dennis
Franchione said, ``but it will be a priority from now on. We need
to put the ball in his hands 25 times a game ... actually, 25 to 30
`touches,' counting pass receptions. It's been a goal, but we
weren't able to do it two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs gave Tomlinson the ball 40 times against Arkansas
State, and he responded with 269 yards and two touchdowns, sparking
a 24-21 victory and earning Western Athletic Conference Offensive
Player of the Week honors.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson is the WAC's leading rusher and ranks second in the
nation at 177.7 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be an increased `LaDainian Watch' in the
future,'' Franchione said. ``Everyone we play is going to have to
try to stop the tailback. But there may be some things we can do to
make sure they don't stop LaDainian.''
</P>
<P>
   This could mean an increased emphasis on the passing ability of
freshman Casey Printers _ who completed 5 of 10 attempts for 88
yards in his first start _ with Tomlinson on the receiving end.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the WAC officiating crew assessed the Frogs 135
yards in penalties, Franchione quipped, ``I don't know if this is
the Conference USA factor or what, but LT had at least one 50-yard
run nullified.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Printers' debut, Franchione said, ``He certainly did not
put any limitations on himself _ or us _ with his play. He broadens
us with his ability to throw the ball downfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione added, however, that Patrick Batteaux's hand is
healed well enough for him to play against Fresno State on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may use both quarterbacks,'' he said. ``There may be
situations in that game where the talents of one or the other will
be best for us.'' Fuller honored Safety Curtis Fuller has been
named to the American Football Coaches Association Good Works Team,
honoring athletes showing exceptional dedication to community
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very encouraging because of some of the players I know
whose names are on the list,'' Fuller said. ``This is a special
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Fuller has been involved in a project with
the Richland Hills Church of Christ that sends young people to
various places in Mexico on building projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult thing we did was putting a new roof on a
church in a place called Valles, in only seven days. It was 108
degrees at 10 a.m. and 115 by three in the afternoon, when we had
to come down off the roof. But we got it done.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
