<HEADLINE>
`TERRIFIC' PRACTICES HAVE STARS COACH HITCHCOCK SMILING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Practice once again had Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock smiling yesterday. Now, he's just waiting to see that
energy finally translate into a game. ``Our practices have been
terrific all year,'' Hitchcock said. ``Our problems have been in
games. I don't think our players have pushed at all like they're
going to in the regular season.'' He said he hasn't had to say much
though. Players have started feeling that Friday opener creeping up
and have taken appropriate action. ``We're not doing the only
pushing here,'' Hitchcock said. ``The players are really pushing
each other to get those strong details in.'' Sharing secrets Guy
Carbonneau, Brian Skrudland and Derek Plante gathered in a small
circle as practice wound down yesterday. They took turns practicing
faceoffs and sharing tricks of the trade. ``They've taken hundreds
of thousands of faceoffs,'' Plante said. ``Carbo gave me some tips
and so did Brian. I learned so much.'' Did they give him any ways
to cheat? ``I can't reveal these secrets,'' Plante said. Marshall
doubtful for opener Ken Hitchcock said Stars winger Grant Marshall
(groin) is doubtful for Friday's opener against Pittsburgh.
Marshall went through a full practice Monday but was sore
yesterday. ``There is absolutely no regression, no problems with
it,'' Hitchcock said, ``but he felt the effects of his first full
practice.'' Hitchcock said not only was Marshall's conditioning not
good enough, but he wouldn't be able to play his physical style of
game. ``For the way he has to play for us to be effective, he's got
to have no qualms about his ability to play that physical game.
That takes a lot out of you,'' Hitchcock said. ``To me, he has to
go through a lot more to be ready.'' Language barrier Stars winger
Jamie Langenbrunner says he still can't say hello to his newest
linemate, Pavel Patera. ``Somebody told me the word in Czech,''
Langenbrunner said, ``but I can't say it.'' Patera doesn't speak
English. Langenbrunner and Joe Nieuwendyk don't speak any Czech.
Patera doesn't speak any English, although, he's started taking
lessons. ``If Roman Turek can learn \REnglish\S as quickly as he
did then that's a good thing for Pavel,'' Hitchcock said. ``We
learned that English lessons were one thing, and cartoons were the
second thing. Once Pavel and his family get up to speed watching
cartoons things will work out pretty well.'' Until then,
Langenbrunner said hand motions and smiles will have to do. ``We're
working on it,'' Langenbrunner said. ``Hockey is pretty
universal.'' Inexperienced defensemen Ken Hitchcock said don't be
surprised to sometimes see the Stars' two newest and least
experienced defensemen, Alan Letang and Brad Lukowich, paired. ``I
think it depends on the opposition,'' Hitchcock said. ``If we see a
very physical team, that obviously pulls \RJamie\S Pushor into the
lineup, but if we feel that there is going to be more of a speed
game out there, that will change our thinking.'' Hitchcock said
Letang is one of the best passers on the team and might make the
Stars a better transition team.  &LR; tagtop:Jennifer Floyd, (817)
390-7760  &LR; tagbottom:jenfloyd &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
