<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND GENEROUS AFTER REACHING MILESTONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ John Wetteland went through his usual routine
after striking out the final batter to preserve the Texas Rangers'
3-2 victory against the Seattle Mariners on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He exchanged a hug with catcher Ivan Rodriguez, shook hands with
his teammates and looked for a youngster in the stands to give the
ball to.
</P>
<P>
   Only then did he hear public address announcer Chuck Morgan say
that Wetteland had just converted his Rangers-record 43rd save.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was a club record while I was trying to hand the
ball to a fan,'' Wetteland said. ``At that point it was too late. I
had already picked her out.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had realized it was a club record, he might have kept the
ball instead of handing it to a young girl. But he didn't really
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cool with that,'' he said. ``I like it that way. That
means I truly was taking it one day at a time like I always say and
just preparing that day as if it were just another day. That's the
beauty of it. She gave me a big hug. It was great.'' RECORD NOT
IMPORTANT
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have 94 victories, one short of setting a club
record. With five games remaining, there's a good chance they will
get it.
</P>
<P>
   That goal, though, is secondary to passing the Cleveland Indians
or New York Yankees and securing home-field advantage for the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of an afterthought,'' first baseman Lee Stevens
said. ``We could set a record for victories and not get home-field
advantage. That wouldn't do us any good.''
</P>
<P>
   The record is important only if it keeps the Rangers home for
the first two games in the divisional round. ALICEA FACING DEADLINE
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alicea did some light jogging Tuesday but appears no closer
to being ready to play. The reserve infielder has been out since
Sept. 13, when he pulled his right calf muscle during a game in
Kansas City, and time is running out for him to return in time for
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully he'll be able to play this weekend,'' manager Johnny
Oates said. ``I think it would be very important he could play some
before Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Alicea will be considered for the postseason roster,
even if he doesn't play, if the club's medical personnel are
convinced he's healed before the Rangers open the playoffs Tuesday
or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if he can play a couple of games, but it's
not imperative,'' Oates said. ZEILE HURT
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile strained a muscle in his right lower
chest wall on a checked swing during his at-bat in the fifth inning
and was unable to play the field in the sixth. He was replaced by
Jon Shave.
</P>
<P>
   The injury raises a red flag because Zeile, who never asks out
of the lineup, said he couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been here over a year and never said anything negative
about being hurt,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile is listed as day-to-day. NUMBERS GAME
</P>
<P>
   _ Rafael Palmeiro tied Juan Gonzalez's club record when he hit
his 47th homer of the year in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ivan Rodriguez's single in the fifth inning was his 194th hit
of the season, breaking a tie for second for the most hits by a
major-league catcher. He was deadlocked with Ted Simmons ('75
Cardinals) and Joe Torre ('64 Braves). He is seven behind Mike
Piazza ('97 Dodgers) for the record. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
