<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-REPEAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SUMMER WITH STANLEY CUP, STARS HAVE PLENTY OF MOTIVATION TO
REPEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Strange what you find in the trophy case. For
some it is the Stanley Cup. For Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, it is a
reminder of how to convince his championship team that it is time
to stop dwelling on the magic carpet ride that led to the
franchise's first NHL title last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go anyplace where I don't run into the Stanley Cup,
and I'm to the point where, like \RMonday\S at a golf tournament,
I'm sick of seeing it,'' Hitchcock said. ``I've seen more of the
Cup than I've seen of my wife. I think the players are to the point
where this thing, by it being around so much, might have helped us.
We're all like, `Enough is enough, let's play.' I think that's the
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Stars will be reminded once again of their recent
glory when the championship banner is unfurled and the players are
introduced at Reunion Arena before the season opener against the
Pittsburgh Penguins. When the opening puck finally drops, the Stars
will begin the long, arduous task of defending their NHL title.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Stars can't get on with the business of defending
the title until the memories from last spring are filed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just went through an incredible run in May and June and
somehow, we have to let that go and try and get your game at a high
level again,'' said center Joe Nieuwendyk, who was on the 1989
Calgary title team that failed to repeat. ``That's a tough thing to
do because everyone wants to talk about last year. You get more
media attention, television, radio. More fans loiter around at the
rink. That will make it harder. But somehow, we've got to put last
year behind us and go play.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, only one NHL team, the Detroit Red Wings, and five
professional sports franchises overall, have repeated as champions.
The Stars, just 2 1/2 months removed from that wild, post-midnight
locker room celebration in Buffalo, will attempt to join the Red
Wings by repeating with a roster that includes seven new players.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hitchcock figures the task of repeating this season will be
much more mentally taxing. He said he has already seen the
``pitfalls,'' of a club that is not mentally sharp during the
exhibition games, a club that sometimes is, ``not placing
importance of playing strong every night, blowing off poor
performances, taking for granted good play.''
</P>
<P>
   To counteract that, Hitchcock said he has spoken to team leaders
such as Mike Modano, Sergei Zubov, Mike Keane and Derian Hatcher
and implored them to talk to the younger players about keeping
their focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you work hard and get results like we had, you like to
have the flowers,'' center Guy Carbonneau said. ``You like to hear
how good you are, but that can be dangerous because that can lead
to being overconfident. And when you go into a game thinking, `Hey,
we won the Stanley Cup,' that's when other teams, who are giving it
a little bit extra, can get you.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, to keep his players from looking too far ahead,
Hitchcock had the first team meeting in which he specifically
addressed the club's work schedule for the next several weeks. He
worked down to the smallest detail, such as days off and off-ice
training days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five-game segments keep you focussed on the now,'' winger
Brett Hull said, ``because you can't start thinking about the
Stanley Cup on Oct. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock conceded, however, that the club's focus is ultimately
his job. ``I've got to make sure they enjoy the daily \Rstuff\S,''
he said. ``That's my responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   And it'll be up to the players to play. Each night, the Stars
expect to get the `A' game from an opponent that would love to say
it knocked off the defending Stanley Cup champions. And each night,
the Stars know they must meet the intensity level of their
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have a great start,'' Carbonneau said. ``We've
got to go into every game business-like and make a statement like,
`All right, we won the Stanley Cup last year, but we're not done.'
We need to let that word go around the league, that we're not going
to fold, and that we are going to be hard to beat.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
