<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS BEAT FULL HOUSE, LEAD ASTROS IN NL CENTRAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Prepare yourself for the surprise of the 1999 baseball
season. The Cincinnati Reds are leading the National League Central
Division with less than a week to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, who finished 77-85 and in fourth place a year ago,
assumed that lofty position with a 4-1 victory over the Houston
Astros in the opener of their two-game series at the Astrodome
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 54,037, a record for an Astros game at the Astrodome,
watched in anger and frustration as the Reds outpitched, outhit and
generally outhustled the two-time defending division champions.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Reds a one-game lead over the Astros with
each team having four games remaining. It's the first time they've
held a one-game lead in the division since July 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to start jumping up and down in the streets,''
Reds manager Jack McKeon said. ``We're going to stay the same way
we've been all year, calm, cool and collected. They're the ones
that have to live up to their advanced billing, not us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have lost seven of 10, but it could be worse. They
could be the free-falling New York Mets, who lost their seventh
consecutive game Tuesday night and remained 1 1/2 games behind the
Astros in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not thinking about the Mets,'' second baseman Craig
Biggio said. ``We're focused on the division. As long as we have a
chance to win the division, that's what we're fighting for. When
you see the '97 division title banner hanging out there and the '98
division title banner, it makes you want to hang another one.''
</P>
<P>
   They won't unless they can put the brakes on their own slide as
well as do something to halt the Reds' relentless momentum. The
Reds have won seven of their last eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played good baseball tonight,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said. ``We pitched well, but we didn't play well. At some
point, we've got to start playing better, or we won't be in the
playoffs, and we're running out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker admitted the Reds are playing with a different mind-set
than the Astros. The Reds, with their paltry $33 million payroll,
weren't expected to contend. The Astros, like the Rangers, entered
the season feeling the need to do better than just win another
division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a young team and you haven't been successful in a
while, you have nothing to lose,'' Dierker said. ``When you've won
a few times and you've had the lead all year and all of a sudden,
you start to lose a few games, then you get that fear, you can't
afford to lose. It's a different psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it seemed Tuesday night. Reds pitcher Pete
Harnisch breezed through eight innings on 75 pitches, allowing just
four hits, before rookie reliever Scott Williamson finished up.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Astros 20-game winner Jose Lima gave up four
runs in the first three innings. Right fielder Derek Bell, who
missed 2 1/2 weeks with a pulled ribcage muscle, made the second
inning worse by letting Eddie Taubensee's single get past him for
an error.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed Dmitri Young to score from first, and Taubensee
ended up at third. He scored on Pokey Reese's single, giving the
Reds a 3-1 lead at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing great,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell
said. ``They have momentum, but one win by us (Wednesday) changes
that. Then it becomes a three-game series, and the team that does
the best over the weekend wins the series.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
