<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SENIOR-TENNIS-CIRCUIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIOR TENNIS TOUR EARNS RESPECT OF GOLFING COUNTERPART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jimmy Connors knows success when he sees it.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senior PGA Tour started gaining fans, making money and
having competitive golf every week, Connors decided to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to get all the guys I played with over the course
of my career who had been out of tennis for a number of years and
try to get them back into the game,'' said Connors, who won eight
Grand Slam titles in a 20-year career. ``My idea was to be around
my buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   Several senior golfers have said a senior tennis tour can be a
part of the landscape in professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tennis' start has been great,'' said CBS golf analyst
Gary McCord, who plays on the senior golf tour. ``People grew up
with a lot of these guys in the '70s, and they still want to follow
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Connors and ProServe co-founder Ray Benton formed The
Champions Tour, a series of tennis events for competitors age 34
and older. The tour, in its sixth year, has modeled itself after
golf's Senior PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fans that come out just like they do,'' said Henry
Brehm, executive producer of what is now called the Worldwide
Senior Tennis Circuit. ``We have some comparisons to senior golf,
like the money and the big-name players. If you look at senior
golf, a lot of those guys didn't think they'd end up where they are
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior tennis tour, which makes a stop at the Four Seasons
Resort at Las Colinas for the second consecutive year starting
tonight, had a slightly faster start than senior golf but doesn't
plan to grow to the same size.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 _ its first year _ the tennis tour had three
tournaments. With Nuveen as its primary sponsor, the tennis tour
offered total prize money of $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   The senior golf tour, which was born when corporate sponsorships
weren't such a big part of professional sports, started in 1980
with two events and $250,000 in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The tennis tour has 21 events this year, and the golf tour has
45, including some of the unofficial stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're kind of maxed out as far as events,'' Brehm
said. ``I don't think we want to have as many events as the senior
\Rgolf\S tour. The guys can't go from week to week like when they
were younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior golf events offer larger purses and more money for the
champions. Tom Watson took home $195,000 by winning the Bank One
Championship in Dallas earlier this month, and this weekend's
singles champion in Irving will win $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Senior golfers have traditionally resisted the notion of their
tour being pure nostalgia. Senior tennis players appear to be
preparing a similar case for their tour.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe, a seven-time Grand Slam winner, said he plays to
win every tournament. Connors, before injuries slowed him down at
age 47, dominated the tour in its early stages. The two players are
still fierce competitors.
</P>
<P>
   After Connors' victory against McEnroe in last year's final at
Four Seasons, the pair refused to shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of the guys are still playing at a high level,''
said Jimmy Arias, who opens the Four Seasons event tonight against
Mel Purcell. ``I don't think the play would be the same if, say, we
were 50 years old. But I still think a lot of us are competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Players under 40 are beginning to assert themselves in senior
tennis, as seen with Mats Wilander, 35, beating Mikael Pernfors,
36, to win the BTI Champions of Atlanta tournament last week. But
the tour must have the bigger _ and older _ names to survive,
several players said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour needs a Connors and a McEnroe to keep this thing
going,'' Arias said. ``Back in the 1970s, these guys saved tennis.
It's because of them \Rthat\S people come out to events.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour has been everywhere this year _ from New York to St.
Petersburg, Russia _ yet it hasn't been a success at every site. In
Irving and Atlanta, ticket sales have been sluggish because fans'
entertainment budgets have been stretched by the many options for
professional sports, Brehm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some markets are more successful than others,'' he said.
``We've had good success in New York and had a terrific event in
Chicago. There are some tough sells ... but we've tried to build
small stadiums so the fans can be right up on the action.''
</P>
<P>
   At Four Seasons, the capacity will be 2,100. In last year's
final, at the same site, a crowd of 2,827 showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a good time, but when we walk on the court we
want to win,'' said five-time Wimbledon champion Bjorn Borg, who
will not play this week in Irving. ``It is a great atmosphere
around the tournaments and that is why all of the players support
the circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Connors organized it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
