<P>
   NY-Y2K-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Jo Jo, a deluxe Upper East Side
restaurant, celebrated New Year's Eve in characteristic style last
year: it opened early and kept going until 5 a.m. As night turned
to dawn, the restaurant remained packed. And how will Jo Jo mark
the New Year's Eve ushering in the next millennium? By shutting
down for the night. And that is not unusual. While many restaurants
are planning extravagantly prepared and stratospherically priced
meals to mark the millennium, a growing number of New York's best
restaurants have quietly decided to stay dark for the night. By
Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   NY-Y2K-LARDER (New York) _ It's looking more and more like a
long shot, but what if a Y2K computer glitch does black out our
whole technological infrastructure? It'll be bad enough going
without light or heat or water for who knows how long. But where in
the name of Eli Zabar is a person supposed to get his or her fix of
fois gras and prosciutto di parma? Living up once again to its
reputation for self parody, Manhattan is now becoming ground zero
for widespread foodie panic _ all right, limited neurosis _ about
Y2K. By Rick Marin.
</P>
