<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS PLAY GAME TO FORGET IN 10-0 WAXING BY RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Before he talked with reporters Tuesday
night, John Halama talked with Jamie Moyer. For at least 15
minutes, the rookie and the veteran analyzed what had happened: a
10-0 loss to the Texas Rangers in which Halama lasted four innings,
allowing six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Halama was disappointed in the outing, his seventh loss in his
last nine decisions. He asked Moyer if he was reading into it too
much, or if his problems were just a matter of location.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I was just up in the zone and couldn't get it down,''
Halama said. ``I was up in the zone more than I was all year.
Usually you adjust and start getting the ball down, and today I
just battled. One of those days.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Halama pitched at The Ballpark in Arlington, it
was one of his best days _ he threw a shutout. This time, he gave
up two homers, including Rafael Palmeiro's 47th, and three runs in
the fourth, then allowed three singles before being lifted in the
fifth. All three runners scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made adjustments, and I didn't make them today,'' Halama
said. ``They got me. It's a learning experience. It's been a year
of a lot of schooling, whether it be from opposing hitters, from
Jamie or other pitchers _ even Jeff helped early, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be former Mariner Jeff Fassero, who threw four
shutout innings in his start for Texas. Fassero, pitching for the
first time in 13 days, allowed four hits but was not sharp, walking
four. If he makes the Rangers' postseason roster _ which is by no
means guaranteed _ it will probably be as a long reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know definitely going into the winter, I'm going to change
some of my workout routines, do some extra stuff,'' said Fassero,
who has a 6.06 earned-run average since being claimed off waivers
Aug. 27. ``I know the velocity's still there, there's just
something missing, and I'm going to try to get it back this winter.
I'm going to get back to where I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama's drop-off has not been nearly as dramatic, but he has
not had the same results in the second half as he had early on. At
the All-Star break, Halama was 7-2 with a 2.89 ERA. Since then, he
is 4-7, 5.76. He has lasted six innings while allowing no more than
three earned runs just three times in his last 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's struggled here his last half-dozen starts,'' said manager
Lou Piniella. ``He's gotten the ball up more than he was early in
the year. Remember, he's not a power pitcher. We were a little
concerned about September for a few or our younger pitchers.
They've never pitched this late in the season. He's a little tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my first full year in the major leagues as a
hitter, I never thought September would end _ you get tired, and
then you know what to expect. It's a good experience for him, for
all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama (11-9), who is scheduled to start the season finale
Sunday but may be replaced to give Ken Cloude or Denny Stark an
audition, said he didn't feel tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched last year until Sept. 25 (in the Class AAA
playoffs),'' Halama said. ``I'm not using tired as an excuse. You
find a way to get some energy or whatever up here. It was just a
matter of not getting my pitches down.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Mariners to 77-80, meaning they'll have to
win all of their remaining games to finish above .500.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have one more win than they did last year _ so that
goal has been reached _ but .500 is looking more and more like a
lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it means something to me, and I'm sure it means
something to the team,'' Piniella said. ``We're trying, (but)
leaving home one game under .500 and playing good teams on the road
is not the best possible scenario. We had chances at home and we've
had chances all year. It seems like every time we get to that
number, we take a step backward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
