<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-LONG-SHOT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MAVERICKS BALLBOY HAS CHANCE TO MAKE THE ROSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Nine years ago, Robert White worked as a ballboy for
the Mavericks, a job in which he had to mop the sweat off the
Reunion Arena floor during games.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a glamour detail would come along, and White would
get to rebound for Hakeem Olajuwon, Karl Malone or Patrick Ewing
during pregame shootarounds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, White has a shot to play against Olajuwon, Malone and
Ewing, among others. The Lancaster resident has gone from Mavericks
ballboy to Mavericks team member. He is going to training camp with
the team next week and seems to have a shot of making the team's
12-man roster.]
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got NBA size, and he certainly has athleticism,''
Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson said. ``But with him, he's
got to bring his A-game consistently. Sometimes he'll slip back
into mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's got the size, the stroke and the skills.''
</P>
<P>
   White, 23, still has a way to make the NBA. But the 6-foot-7,
215-pounder _ he doubles as a small forward and shooting guard _
impressed the Mavericks coaching staff so much that they included
him as part of an Athletes In Action team they sent to London to
play this past summer. That came after he impressed them with his
play in pro summer leagues in Los Angeles and Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   White's saga seems more befitting a ballboy than a ball handler
at the elite level. But the 1995 Lancaster High School graduate has
put in the sweat to reach the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say when I was sitting under the basket as a ballboy,
I was thinking, `Man, I wish I could play in the NBA,' '' White
said. ``At that age I was intimidated to see all of those big guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then I've had a dream and desire to one day get there.
But at that age I was so caught up in never being in a big arena
like that before, and there I was standing next to big Karl Malone,
Terry Davis and all these players. At that time I was thinking, `I
have a ways to go to get up to their level.'''
</P>
<P>
   White made a splash at this level in July, when he played for
the Momentum Sports in the Los Angeles Summer League. That team was
coached by the first draft pick in Mavericks history _ former NBA
All-Star Kiki Vandeweghe.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Rockets were so impressed with White's performance
that they invited him to play for their summer league team in the
Rocky Mountain Revue in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   In the LA Summer League, White was sometimes pitted against the
likes of Phoenix rookie Shawn Marion, who was the ninth pick of the
June NBA Draft. The former ballboy more than held his ground .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think getting out to LA was great for him, because he had a
chance, number one, to be coached by Kiki Vandeweghe,'' said Mark
Slough, White's agent. ``The second thing is out in LA he played
against Shawn Marion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Robert and Shawn are 6-7, and Robert's like, `Hey, I can
play with this guy.' When he was out in LA his confidence just
grew.''
</P>
<P>
   White was drafted by the New Mexico Slam of the International
Basketball League _ a first-year pro league that is perhaps a level
below the Continental Basketball Association, the NBA's
developmental arm _ this summer. He is negotiating to play for that
franchise. But it is clear that his eyes are set on making it in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time I never did want to play basketball,'' White said.
``I always liked soccer, and I never really showed any concern that
I could do anything in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was able to overcome some obstacles and I kept putting
in the work.''
</P>
<P>
   White grew from a 5-foot-8 eighth-grader to a 6-3 freshman. As a
high school senior, he only averaged eight points for a Lancaster
team that lost to Lincoln in the '94 regional finals.
</P>
<P>
   White wound up playing for tiny Southern Nazarene University in
Bethany, Okla. As a junior at the NAIA school, he averaged 15
points and five rebounds, and this past season he averaged 17
points and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   White was able to parlay both of those seasons into honorable
mention All-America status. Now he's looking for a much higher
honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I would be as far as I am right now,'' White
said. ``But you always have your hopes, your dreams and your drive,
and with that drive, God gave me the opportunity, and it came to
pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson genuinely likes White's chances of making an NBA roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really in a good position that he can be a real
attractive two-guard,'' he said. ``I talked to the coach of the IBL
team that drafted him and told him what I thought of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like him, and he's close to being in the NBA.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
