<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-ROUND PICK PLANS TO STICK WITH MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rookie Leon Smith said he plans to sign a three-year, $1.7
million guaranteed contract with the Dallas Mavericks within the
next two weeks, but he's not sure whether he'll be in Dallas when
training camp starts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Tuesday from his home in Chicago, Smith said he is busy
trying to hire an agent to represent him. He said he recently fired
agent Dan Fegan, who also represents free-agent forward Shandon
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like I needed somebody more geared toward giving
me some more personal attention,'' Smith said. ``He didn't tell me
what was going on. I was left hanging out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've narrowed it down now to between two agents, and I'll
probably make a decision sometime next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mavericks have said they prefer Smith go through a
year of seasoning in the Continental Basketball Association or
International Basketball League, assistant coach Donnie Nelson
wouldn't rule out the possibility of Smith securing a roster spot
with Dallas this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agent thing is up in the air, and it could be very well
that he decides to do something different,'' Nelson said. ``It
could also be that he decides to stay (with the Mavericks). But
that's also up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as he signs his contract, he comes to training camp
and he gets paid this year. But he needs to have some kind of an
adjustment period between high school and the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who graduated from Chicago's Martin Luther King High
School this year, said he has had no conversations with
representatives from the CBA or the IBL. But the 6-foot-11 forward
did say he can't wait to discuss his future with Mavericks
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be talking to the Mavericks within the next couple of
days,'' Smith said. ``Coming to the Mavericks' training camp sounds
good, but I really don't know what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks acquired Smith in a draft day trade with the world
champion San Antonio Spurs. The Spurs selected Smith with the final
pick of the first round, then traded him to the Mavericks for a
pair of second-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Smith acquitted himself well two months ago when the
Mavericks participated in the Los Angeles Summer League.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people saw him actually in action in Los Angeles, they
saw what he's capable of,'' Nelson said. ``And the more people had
a chance to kind of get to know Leon, they found out he wasn't a
bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 18, had been a ward of the state of Illinois since he was
four years old. He bounced from group home to group home, but is
now on the verge of living the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon's basically a good guy that, forced into a situation, had
to make a decision,'' Nelson said, referring to Smith's decision to
turn pro or go to college. ``He had no propensity or no skills of
the academia areas, so it was a hard decision for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the fact that he's got all this information, and
when you see his basketball skill level, I don't think you want to
bet against Leon.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he arrives in Dallas won't be soon enough for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working out, I'm in good shape, and I want to be in
Dallas this season,'' Smith said. ``I just want to be the best
player that I can be and work as hard as I can and really show the
fans that I was worth being drafted.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
