<HEADLINE>
CONNORS, WILANDER HEAD IRVING EVENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A total of 21 Grand Slam titles will be
represented during the PricewaterhouseCoopers Champions senior
tennis event starting today at the Four Seasons Resort and Club at
Las Colinas.
</P>
<P>
   The $150,000 event, which will award $40,000 to the singles
champion, will be headlined by defending champion Jimmy Connors.
Play starts at 7 p.m. today with two matches and concludes Sunday
with the singles and doubles championships, both starting at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Connors is joined by former ATP Tour players Guillermo Vilas,
Mats Wilander, Mikael Pernfors and Andres Gomez. Bjorn Borg, a
winner of 11 Grand Slam titles, pulled out of the event last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Worldwide Senior Tennis Circuit's Irving event is the 13th
of 21 on the $3.6 million tour. The 1999-2000 season includes
events in Tokyo, London, Paris, New York and St. Petersburg,
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Wilander won his second senior tour title of the season Sunday
with a three-set victory against Pernfors at the BTI Champions of
Atlanta. Wilander defeated Connors in the semifinals of the Atlanta
event.
</P>
<P>
   Connors' opening match this week is at 7 p.m. tomorrow against
the winner between John Lloyd and Jose-Luis Clerc.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's final at Four Seasons, Connors defeated John
McEnroe in a spirited match that had both players yelling at either
the fans or the line judges. Connors eventually stormed off the
court after an exchange with a fan, and McEnroe had to persuade him
to return and finish. When the match was over, the players left the
court without shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   Some local players are involved in this year's event.
</P>
<P>
   Val Wilder of Euless will team up with two-time Australian Open
singles champion Johan Kriek in doubles. Their opening match is at
7 p.m. tomorrow against Mansour Bahrami and Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our chances,'' Wilder said. ``I think Johan is a very
quick doubles player, but I will need to play well. If I can hold
my serve, I think we can compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Poorman and Michael Grossman of Dallas will team up to
face veterans Mel Purcell and Tim Wilkison at 7 p.m. Friday. The
winning doubles team will receive $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity of a lifetime,'' said Poorman, who
works at the new Southlake Tennis Center. ``I've watched these guys
throughout their careers. I think we've got a shot to win, but we
have to play aggressively. I mean, we are playing against Dr. Dirt
\RWilkison\S and Purcell. It's going to be tough.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
