<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF LOSS TO CARDINALS STILL GALLS COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys coach Chan Gailey is not Knute
Rockne inside the locker room, but even Rockne might have skipped
the big pep talk this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Arizona Cardinals return to Texas Stadium for the
first time since delivering a 20-7 knockout punch in the first
round of the playoffs Jan. 2 and, in effect, trashing the Cowboys'
NFC Eastern Division-sweeping season. Gailey does not have to
remind his team about what happened then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll ever forget that game,'' Gailey said
Tuesday. ``Revenge' or `payback' is not a war cry ... but anybody
who was in that locker room after the game remembers what it felt
like.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey still has not been able to watch the videotape of that
game from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the whole thing,'' said Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll ever watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   How far has he gotten?
</P>
<P>
   ``Far enough,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey isn't real talkative when it comes to re-enacting the
accounts and images of that Jan. 2 game. Jake ``The Snake'' Plummer
and the Cardinals basically came to town and had their way with the
Cowboys' defense, while Gailey's then-struggling offense failed to
even put up a fight because of personnel lapses and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But nine months later, it's the Cowboys who are 2-0 with weapons
galore, and it's the 1-2 Cardinals with the offensive problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's Plummer, with one touchdown and nine interceptions, who
ranks last in the NFC and next-to-last behind only Baltimore's
Scott Mitchell in the NFL in passer efficiency rating.
</P>
<P>
   It's Arizona with the injuries. Just as Deion Sanders returns to
the Dallas secondary, Cardinals big-play wide receiver Rob Moore
will miss Sunday's game because of a strained hamstring, which he
suffered in Monday night's 24-10 home loss to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's place will be taken by fifth-year journeyman Andy
McCullough, a former NFL Europe standout who spent last season with
four NFL teams _ Miami, Detroit, New Orleans and Arizona _ mostly
on their practice squads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to have (McCullough) play more like a veteran than
a rookie,'' Cardinals coach Vince Tobin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin tried to explain away Plummer's difficulties by saying
that his quarterback hasn't had much practice since suffering a
sprained thumb on his throwing hand Aug. 21 during a preseason game
against Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get more practice this week ... and that ought to
help,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody is feeling sorry for the Cardinals around Valley
Ranch. Especially not Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if there was any chance that he worried that his
players may be overconfident about this game in light of how the
Cardinals have been playing, Gailey replied, ``None.
</P>
<P>
   ``None.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if this has everything to do with the Jan. 2 game,
Gailey replied, ``Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said that the playoff elimination game
against Arizona led directly to the off-season signing of center
Mark Stepnoski, along with the drafting of pass-rush specialists
Ebenezer Ekuban and Peppi Zellner, because of Plummer's
twice-a-year presence in the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepnoski was the key move,'' Jones said Tuesday. ``We got him
(as an unrestricted free agent from Tennessee) so we could be more
effective both in (pass) protection and the running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also did something as subtle as draft (seventh-round tight
end) Mike Lucky because of his ability to block in double-tight end
situations. And because Plummer likes to buy time by stepping up in
the pocket, then going outside and behind the pass rush, we drafted
Ekuban and Zellner to take away those running lanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones doesn't enjoy looking back at the Jan. 2 loss to the
Cardinals. But he has watched it on videotape several times.
</P>
<P>
   Just not alongside his head coach. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Right tackle Erik Williams (strained quadriceps) is expected
to practice with the rest of the Cowboys on Wednesday, while right
guard Everett McIver (strained hamstring) remains more iffy, Chan
Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornerback Kevin Smith is expected to resume team practice
today. He hasn't played since the Aug. 9 Hall of Fame game in
Canton, Ohio, because of a bulging disk in his back. As far as
being ready for Sunday, Smith has been put ``more in the McIver
category,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornerback Deion Sanders will put his left big toe (late April
surgery) to the test at right corner and on punt returns Sunday.
This will be Sanders' first game action for the Cowboys since the
Jan. 2 playoff game. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
