<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN KINGS ZIG-ZAG TO PLAYOFFS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ New arena, new coach, new scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Old baggage.
</P>
<P>
   That best describes this season's Los Angeles Kings, who have
failed to make the National Hockey League playoffs for five of the
past six years and who open the regular season on Saturday in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings leave the Forum for the state-of-the-art Staples
Center, and they bring along new coach Andy Murray and former New
York Islanders scoring star Zigmund (Ziggy) Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   But how do they handle the baggage?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my credibility is on the line with these players,''
said Murray, former coach of the Canadian national team who vows to
use players who are performing, regardless of name or contract
status.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Credibility) is all you really have in this business,''
Murray said. ``I'll never compromise that just to please people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fresh faces, the Kings are fundamentally unchanged,
haunted by the same questions that have dogged the franchise since
it advanced to the 1993 finals and came, perhaps, one illegal stick
away from the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Kings play the type of premier defense needed to be
successful in a league that demands it of its best teams? After
winning the Norris Trophy for best defenseman in '97-98, Rob Blake
had a sub-par season in '98-'99.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Kings have the speed to compete in a league that becomes
faster each year? Can they score? Particularly, can they conquer
their power-play demons? And will players respond to a coach who
has yet to prove himself on the NHL level?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to try new things,'' said winger Glen Murray.
``Nothing worked last year, so the way we look at it, trying new
things is good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also find themselves embroiled in another contract
dispute with a defenseman. Last year Aki Berg sat out the entire
season, opting to play in Finland. This year Mattias Norstrom has
not come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a step forward and making the playoffs two years
ago, the Kings took two steps back in a nightmarish season that
ultimately cost coach Larry Robinson his job.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a nice guy whose ability to motivate and discipline
players was often questioned, is contrasted nicely by Murray. He
plans practices to the minute, has motivational slogans posted in
the dressing room and already has shown a willingness to let his
players know just where he stands.
</P>
<P>
   In exhibition play, Murray hasn't backed down from anybody. He
got into a shouting match with Craig Hartsburg when he felt the
Mighty Ducks coach wasn't controlling his players in the
brawl-filled finale at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   He also made it very clear to Bryan Smolinski, who was acquired
from the Islanders in the Palffy trade, that he expected more
effort and dropped him to the fourth line, promoting journeyman Len
Barrie to the second.
</P>
<P>
   Murray hasn't been afraid to put some pressure on Smolinski, who
has scored as many as 31 goals in a season but slumped to 13 and 16
the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we are getting with Palffy,'' said Murray. ``The
unknown is Bryan Smolinski. The success of the (Palffy) trade
hinges on Smolinski.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings finished 11th in the 13-team Western Conference with a
32-45-5 record last season and the fans stayed away in droves _ not
exactly the kind of momentum management was looking to build on as
it prepared to move into the spacious Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings weren't just bad, they were slow and boring. Los
Angeles scored just 189 goals, the third fewest in the league. Luc
Robitaille scored 39 of those, nobody else more than 18. The lack
of scoring and excitement forced general manager Dave Taylor to
make changes.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who last coached a prep school team in Minnesota, was
the unlikely choice as coach and 11 players from last year's team _
including regulars Ray Ferraro, Doug Bodger, Russ Courtnall, Yanic
Perreault and Olli Jokinen _ are gone.
</P>
<P>
   Jokinen, the team's first-round pick (third overall), was dealt
to the New York Islanders in Taylor's move to bring the Kings some
goal-scoring and star power in the form of Palffy, a three-time
40-goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   So there is a new look and a new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is great so far,'' Robitaille said. ``The energy is
great.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the always optimistic Robitaille knows the Kings will
be treading water without Norstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' he acknowledged, ``is great except for Matty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
