r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     09-29 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS EAGER TO MAKE AMENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Mighty Ducks were satisfied simply
to make the Stanley Cup playoffs last season. Perhaps too
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing the home stretch with a 1-5-2 record, they were
swatted aside by the Red Wings in a four-game sweep that left them
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't feel good about making the playoffs, about how we
lost to Detroit . . . how we finished,'' Teemu Selanne said. ``We
were horrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't close to winning a game and if you can't win a
game, how are you going to win a series? We have to have more grit,
be smarter, (have) more discipline _ everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Craig Hartsburg has lectured on those very topics
throughout training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to become a more tenacious team,'' Hartsburg said.
``We took steps last year, but . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's habits. You don't win doing things once in a while, you
win by doing it every night. Character is no excuses, it's about
winning the 1-0, 2-0 games and showing up for a game after two
weeks on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   After going 26-43-13 and missing the playoffs in 1997-98, the
Ducks improved to 35-34-13 last season and finished sixth in the
Western Conference. But they squandered a chance to finish fourth
or fifth with their late-season swoon. Instead of playing a Phoenix
team they matched up with well, the Ducks were wasted by the Red
Wings in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a learning process,'' Selanne said. ``We learned
how much it really takes to have success in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players and management learned that lesson. The Ducks
didn't make a lot of changes over the summer, but general manager
Pierre Gauthier and Hartsburg realized the defense needed more
skill.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a plain-wrap style during the regular season, the
defensemen helped the Mighty Ducks cut their goals-against total
from 261 to 206.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Red Wings it was all too obvious the Ducks'
defense needed to move the puck more quickly, make better outlet
passes to relieve the pressure caused by Detroit's forechecking,
and get the puck to Paul Kariya and Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   On draft day, Gauthier, with the aid of Phoenix, addressed that
issue. He traded the Ducks' first-round draft choice and center
Travis Green to the Coyotes for former Ducks No. 1 pick Oleg
Tverdovsky, who had been traded away in the deal that brought
Selanne to Anaheim. In the third round, Gauthier selected Swedish
veteran Niclas Havelid.
</P>
<P>
   Havelid should get plenty of playing time this season, but it's
Tverdvosky who could make a big difference if he plays to the
potential the Ducks saw when they made him the No. 3 overall pick
in 1994. The 23-year-old should give the Ducks their first
defenseman capable of jumping into the play and carrying the puck
out of the Anaheim zone on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier also signed 1998 first-round pick Vitaly Vishnevski, a
defenseman. He will start the season at Cincinnati, but it wouldn't
be surprising to see the hard-hitting 19-year-old Russian in
Anaheim before the season is over.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier's only other major move in the offseason was trading
minor-league goalie Patrick Lalime to Ottawa for veteran winger Ted
Donato, who is expected to fill the hole left on the second line by
Tomas Sandstrom's return to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some changes but not too many because we want to keep
this team together,'' Gauthier said. ``We didn't want to disturb
the chemistry. Chemistry and team play are more important in
hockey, more than other sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier and Hartsburg are depending on young players like Matt
Cullen, Antti Aalto, Ruslan Salei and Mike LeClerc to continue
their development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youngsters had ups and downs last year,'' said Gauthier.
``This year should be a breakthrough year for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are to be better as a team, our young players have to be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the veterans and coaches will make sure nobody gets
too satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes . . . myself, Paul, Teemu, Steve
(Rucchin),'' said goalie Guy Hebert, who knows returning to the
playoffs is no sure thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
