<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9804 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     09-29 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S STAVE OFF ELIMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Randy Velarde admitted coming back to Anaheim
this week would have been a lot sweeter if his Oakland A's had a
legitimate shot at making the playoffs. Instead, the A's were on
the verge of being eliminated from playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde and the A's staved off elimination for at least one more
day with a 9-3 victory over the Anaheim Angels Tuesday before
17,981 at Edison Field. Mo Vaughn's 31st homer of the year gave the
Angels a 2-0 lead in the first inning, but the A's Jason Giambi
snapped a 2-2 tie with his 33rd homer of the season to give the A's
a 4-2 lead in the fifth. Giambi, a 1989 graduate of South Hills
High, reached base five times with three hits and two walks. The
A's broke the game open with a four-run seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the win, the A's still need to win their remaining five
games and hopgames to forge a tie for the A.L. Wild Card spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels traded Velarde and pitcher Omar Olivares to the A's
for three minor leaguers on July 29, all but signaling the end of
the season for the Angels and creating new life for Velarde and
Olivares.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was exciting to leave the situation in Anaheim,'' said
Velarde, who went into Tuesday's game hitting .314 with 16 homers
and 71 RBIs. ''I went from a team that pretty much came to the
field, played the game every day and had no emotion, to going to a
team that was in contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde was quick to add that he didn't think the Angels weren't
playing hard. It's just that there was nothing to play for.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think effort was ever in question,'' Velarde said.
''Injuries were a common denominator here. Injuries are always a
part of a season, but to be decimated the way these guys were the
years I was here was confusing. You lose three or four marquee guys
... you take away three or four marquee guys, that will cripple any
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde was one of the players that had problems with former
manager Terry Collins. When asked about Collins, Velarde at first
declined to comment, then relented.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tough job,'' Velarde said. ''The manager takes a lot of
responsibility. Nobody questioned his heart or enthusiasm for the
game. It all comes down to production and getting guys ready to
play. And that wasn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde said he never expected to be traded by the Angels. In
fact, he said he was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ''My name was never mentioned in rumors,'' he said. ''The day I
was traded my mother-in-law had a heart attack. It all happened in
a 12-hour span. I was on an emotional roller coaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde, who is a free agent after the season, said his agent
has talked to the A's about returning to Oakland next season. But
he wouldn't rule out anything, even returning to the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ''One thing I've learned in this game is never say never,'' he
said. ''It all comes down to if Oakland wants me back, or if
Anaheim wants me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disparity in the standings, Velarde said he doesn't
see much difference between the A's and Angels of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see a lot of similarities between this team and Anaheim,''
he said. ''They're both young and talented. The biggest difference
is this team's power production is more consistent than
Anaheim's.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, who will start tonight's game for the A's, has gone
7-2 with Oakland since the trade and is 15-11 overall. He, too,
will be a free agent at the end of the season and hasn't ruled out
returning to Anaheim if the price is right.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy to come back and see the guys,'' he said. ''I liked
it here in Anaheim, but Oakland has been great to me too. I do like
the team here (Anaheim) ... we just had a bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   As bad a year as it was for the Angels, they were in a position
to knock the A's out of the race. Angels interim manager Joe
Maddon, however, said there was no added motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't even thought about that,'' Maddon said. ''What our
agenda should be is to play as well as we can, period. If we knock
somebody out of it, great. We just played three totally intense
games (in Seattle). I can't imagine paying with any more intensity.
If we play these games with that level of intensity, I'd be
happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
