<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9809 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLA     09-29 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM. Calif. _ Mo Vaughn said recently the Anaheim Angels
players should not forget this season and what it's felt like, so
they'll do everything they can not to let it happen again. For
general manager Bill Bavasi, however, the 1999 season ended and was
forgotten after July 31.
</P>
<P>
   That was the date of the trading deadline, and the time Bavasi
and his staff began looking to the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the players' point of view, (Vaughn's) right,'' Bavasi
said. ``They have to suffer with it, let the pain set in and let
the throb go away in the off-season. Realistically, for myself,
(assistant GM) Ken Forsch and (director of scouting) Bob Fontaine,
Aug. 1 was the day we started evaluating and preparing for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the end of the season gets closer, I immerse myself in
preparing for next season, they (the players) I have made that
trade (Omar Olivares and Randy Velarde to the A's for minor
leaguers) if I wasn't looking to next year?''
</P>
<P>
   Closer Troy Percival was expected to meet with trainer Ned
Bergert and team medical director Dr. Lewis Yocum after Tuesday's
game to decide on Percival's availability for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Percival, who has been bothered by a sore right shoulder, says
he wants to keep pitching through the end of the season. But the
Angels are likely to shut him down and not take any chances on
furthering the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Garret Anderson has been bothered by a sore left foot
the past couple of weeks, but has remained in the lineup. An MRI
revealed no abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson went into Tuesday's game leading the team in games
played (151), at-bats (599), runs (84), hits (180), total bases
(278) and doubles (34).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what he does is undervalued,'' Angels interim manager
Joe Maddon said. ``He's somebody who answers the bell every day.
It's an undervalued asset. His arm gets sore, his leg gets sore,
but he plays through it. I think he's under-appreciated. He has a
certain gate about him sometimes, but he cares, he wants to win.
He's done a great job this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and A's play the second game of their three-game
series tonight at 7:35. Brian Cooper (1-1, 4.30 ERA) will start for
Anaheim against Oakland's Omar Olivares (15-11, 4.08).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
