<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9820 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-29 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHAT the Astros need right about now is Ben Crenshaw _ if not his
sweet swing, then some inspiring words.
</P>
<P>
   What once looked like a better team than the Reds, wasn't. What
once played like a better team than the Reds, didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Astros bats went dormant. Jose Lima found the rough. And Derek
Bell misread the green in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Bell thought the baseball would break to the left,
but really it rolled through his legs and broke the Astros' backs.
Somebody must have stepped on his line.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in the span of one week an Astros division lead that once
was 3{ games has turned into the Astros suddenly finding themselves
one game behind the Reds with just four left. What once was a team
that could tear off 12-game winning streaks has turned into one
that has lost eight of its last 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the best thing we've got going for us is that the
Mets are playing as poorly as we are,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   That much is true, if not the kind of inspiring words that will
have Dierker answering to the name ``Knute'' any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The pain of the Astros' 4-1 setback to the Reds on Tuesday night
was cushioned by the Mets' 9-3 loss to the Atlanta Braves. The
Mets' loss means the playoffs remain a possibility for the Astros
no matter how bad things get in their four remaining regular-season
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can back into the postseason as a wild-card entry if
they can stay ahead of the struggling Mets. Some might even say the
Astros would be better off earning the wild-card spot over the
division title, because it would mean they likely wouldn't have to
twice face Diamondbacks ace Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But something is wrong with this Astros picture.
</P>
<P>
   What once was considered a team of destiny, with Lima talking of
``angels'' in the clubhouse assuring postseason success, has become
stagnant and uninspired, to say nothing of uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Gentle Ben even would rage if he saw what a Dome-record 54,037
fans saw Tuesday night. In a word, the crowd was spectacular. The
wild fans cheered every moment, chanted names, brought banners,
called out the Reds and gave the game a legitimate postseason
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   There was a prevalent feeling on this night it would be Lima
Time. There was a feeling Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio and Co.
somehow would find a way; that the Astros would put these upstart
Reds in their place, all right.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, after so much Pete Harnisch magic and
questionable Astros decisions on and off the field, maybe the
Astros put the Reds in their place.
</P>
<P>
   First place.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost in what led to the disappointing effort, you have to
look at the decision to start Bell in right field. Certainly, you
can understand why Dierker would want Bell in the lineup if Bell
was sharp and ready.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are not Bell's biggest fan, you have to admit Bell
has seen plenty of big games and his defense in right field is as
good as the Astros can get.
</P>
<P>
   But why put him in the starting lineup on his first day back
from a rib-cage injury? Why start Bell in this critical game when
all he has had in terms of rehabilitation was a few swings in the
Instructional League?
</P>
<P>
   It was Bell's second-inning error in what was then a 1-1 game
that led to a pair of Reds runs and a 3-1 edge that Harnisch never
relinquished. One inning later, the Reds scored another run when
Lima, who was decent after a rocky first couple of innings, left
one too many pitches over the plate. Reds catcher Eddie Taubensee
singled and drove in Barry Larkin, who opened the inning with a
double.
</P>
<P>
   Bell also grounded into a double play, ending all hopes of a
rally, after Ken Caminiti opened the fifth inning with a single and
got the crowd riled up. Bell finished 0-for-3, and the Astros never
had a chance, but don't blame just Bell or just a lineup that
mustered only four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker should _ and did _ share the blame for this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them a couple of runs,'' he said. ``If it's a 2-1 game
(in the late innings), then maybe there are some things we could do
differently. As everyone could see, Derek didn't look like he was
ready to catch up to this kind of pitching. Probably, I shouldn't
have expected him to.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Astros, this poor effort was not the end of
the playoff chase. Tonight, with Mike Hampton on the hill, things
could turn around and this race could be all square again.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody call Gentle Ben.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
