<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 03:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9827 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-INFECTIONS-HOSPITALS-     09-29 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFECTIONS-HOSPITALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EXPERTS BARE HOSPITAL INFECTION HAZARDS  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some of the hazards of health care were on
display Tuesday at a meeting here of medical experts, as
researchers discussed the latest findings on hospital-acquired
infections and the dangers of supposedly life-saving medical
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Such infections have long been recognized as a huge, if
underappreciated, problem. The latest statistics show that about
200,000 to 400,000 people pick up some kind of infection in
hospitals every year, and 70,000 of the infections are fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the usual suspects of germ-laden catheters and unwashed
hands, doctors delved into some lesser-known risks Tuesday during
the annual scientific meeting of the American Society for
Microbiology, which ends Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the menace of fake fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Shelly McNeil and colleagues at the University of Michigan
decided to examine the problem after noticing that about 12 percent
of the university hospital's staff nurses were sporting trendy
acrylic nails, sometimes extending an inch or more beyond the ends
of their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary study showed that 73 percent of nurses who were
wearing the fake fingernails harbored harmful bacteria on their
hands, compared with just 32 percent of nurses without the acrylic
nails.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil then found that even rigorous hand washing did little to
rid the enhanced fingertips of potentially nasty bugs: Ninety-four
percent of those who had bacteria on their hands while wearing the
nails still had a pathogen present after hand washing.
</P>
<P>
   She recommended the hospital adopt an official policy to
``discourage'' acrylic nails, but she said this involved ``a huge
political issue'' that has yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing experts noted that the study looked at a relatively
small number of hands _ only 41 nurses were enrolled in the
Michigan study _ and did not determine whether any patients
actually contracted an infection at the hands of a nail-wearing
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't taken a stance on this,'' said Kay McVay,
president-elect of the California Nurses Association. ``One study
does not make it necessarily true or untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Other studies showed risks seemingly lurking behind every corner
in the hospital. At Tuesday's conference, two long aisles full of
posted research summaries on so-called nosocomial, or
hospital-acquired, infections amounted to a health care chamber of
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   One Israeli research team found that even after years of
education, only about 75 percent of staff washed their hands. In
the typical health care establishment, the compliance rate on hand
washing is an abysmal 40 percent or so.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Witt, head of infection control at Kaiser Permanente's
South San Francisco medical center, said keeping everything clean
is sometimes taken for granted even in the best-run facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of day-to-day, very mundane things, like getting
everyone to wash their hands, or showing people how to change
dressings right, how to use antibiotics wisely, isolating people
with drug-resistant infections,'' he said. ``It's a challenge. We
tend to annoy people. We're seen as neurotic sometimes. But the
fact is, infection control is an underrecognized issue in
determining quality of care.''
</P>
<P>
   Just being transferred from one hospital to another, or even
from one ward to another in the same facility, can be hazardous to
your health, according to research by a French team.
</P>
<P>
   Of 89 patients with infections who were investigated in that
study, 55 percent had been transferred from another ward or
hospital. The risk of infection in the transferred group was five
times that of patients who stayed put.
</P>
<P>
   Another study found ``a serious problem'' of bacterial
infections caused by pacemakers, with little research to suggest
how to handle the problem. The study found 17 infections in 1,182
patients _ for a relatively high infection rate of about 1.2
percent. Experts concluded that the only effective way to cure such
infections is total removal of the pacing system.
</P>
<P>
   Medical-device makers are now coating some products with
anti-microbial compounds to eliminate the problem. But some devices
tend to be ignored as risk factors not worth doing anything about.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Dr. Eric Van Wijngaerden showed three infections for
every 1,000 patients receiving an arterial catheter, which unlike
venous catheters are not usually coated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant risk,'' he said. ``There are some novel
techniques that can be used to reduce this kind of risk, but it's
not being done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Technical skill can make a big difference in how effectively
infections are kept at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's biggest trauma center, for example, documented only
44 fungal infections in 21,267 patients examined over a four-year
period, a rate of just 0.2 percent. That compares with about 6
percent to 10 percent at most trauma units, said Dr. Manjari Joshi,
who presented the results Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She attributed the low rate of trouble to rigorous cleanliness
and deliberate underuse of anti-infective agents, which can make
problems worse by breeding drug-resistant strains.
</P>
<P>
   Another European study looked at whether infections were reduced
after a hematology ward was moved into a new facility operated
under strict isolation protocols, in which visitors had to wear
surgical caps and masks.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that infections were getting worse. Study authors
attributed the problems to a changeover to less-experienced
physicians, who were evidently taking longer to insert catheters.
That appeared to increase the chance of bacteria on the skin making
their way to deeper tissue, said the lead study author, Dr. J.L.
Nouwen.
</P>
<P>
   That supposition is still being investigated, but in the
meantime, the strict isolation of patients was dropped when it was
found that patients were being infected by bacteria they were
carrying on their own skin, not germs picked up from anyone else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
