<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOSE-BLOWING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BLOWING MAY BE BAD NEWS FOR YOUR NOSE  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Blowing your nose during a cold may increase the
risk of sinus infections, doctors reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be the most elaborate analysis ever done on
the subject, top cold experts and a mechanical engineer at the
University of Virginia set out to find the source of infectious
agents discovered lurking in the usually sterile sinus cavities of
cold sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   Results showed the average nose-blow produced far more pressure
inside the nose than did sneezing or coughing. The pressure was
more than enough to propel quantities of germ-laden mucus the
opposite direction intended _ into the inner recesses of the nose
where they could cause infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised to find nose-blowing produced such
substantial intranasal pressure,'' said Dr. Birgit Winther, who
presented the results Tuesday at a scientific meeting of the
American Society for Microbiology in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A further check with CT scanning techniques confirmed the
movement of mucus into the sinuses. Still, the study authors
stopped short of recommending that millions of cold sufferers try
to avoid blowing their noses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen,'' conceded Dr. Jack Gwaltney. ``You
just can't expect someone with a cold is not going to blow his
nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he recommended early treatment of colds with an
antihistamine and one or two tablets of over-the-counter-strength
ibuprofen in order to cut down on nasal secretions. But some
experts say that antihistamines can make matters worse once a cold
is in full swing by making mucus thicker and harder to clear.
</P>
<P>
   Further studies are needed to clear up the matter of which
nose-blowing techniques might pose the greatest risk. The Virginia
researchers did not attempt to distinguish one nose-blowing style
from another, although Gwaltney said the study has already toned
down his personal method of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been blowing my nose much less vigorously lately,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 0321EDT &QL; 
