<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NOTHING TO LOSE BUT OUR CHAINS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ These are the climes that fry men's soles.
</P>
<P>
   Women are smarter (stop the presses!); they put on sneakers for
the walk to work.
</P>
<P>
   When it gets this hot in San Francisco, it can mean only one
thing: Baseball season is over.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a warm morning Tuesday that I decided to stroll up
Market Street. Started at the Embarcadero, not far from the future
site of the 60-foot statue of Cupid's bow and arrow, to be sculpted
by Claes Oldenburg.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Market Street is Java Junction, the world capital of
coffee stands. There is approximately one coffee-oriented retail
outlet for every person who works in the Financial District.
</P>
<P>
   Between First and Fifth, I passed four Starbucks, and I was
starting to worry that maybe the heat had gotten to me and I was
walking in circles.
</P>
<P>
   So I began dropping doughnut crumbs. Then I looked behind me and
saw that I had created a pigeon conga line.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks, you know, has its own CDs, its own magazine, its own
language  &UR; (barista, grande),  &LR; maybe its own Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no Starbucks near where you work in the FiDi, call
'em, they'll come out and build one.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to San Franstarbucks.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just Starbucks. The only businesses that aren't
taken over by the chains are shoe-shining and prostitution,
although I later saw some hookers who are part of a corporate
entity.
</P>
<P>
   And soon we will be getting our shoes shined at Starshine (TM)
stands, by genial  &UR; buffistas. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IT WAS ONLY 10 o'clock, but already it was hot enough to make me
dizzy, especially considering the caffeine buzz and the sugar rush
from the doughnuts, and I was starting to feel like Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers quarterback has taken more hits than the lingerie Web
site of Willie Brown's secretary.
</P>
<P>
   We'll know Steve's in serious trouble, concussion-wise, when the
49ers center starts wearing a cue card on his rear end _
``Hut-hut!''
</P>
<P>
   Market Street is a sociological journey. As people walk up the
street, money leaks out of their pockets and they gradually sink
into despair and disrepair. Between Second and Sixth, their
pinstriped suits and jaunty walks become raggedy shirts and
defeated trudges.
</P>
<P>
   By the time you get past Seventh to U.N. Plaza, you can be
pretty sure that if anyone tries to sell you anything, it won't be
an IPO or a Frappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE PLAZA, I ran into a bumper-to-bumper traffic jam _ of
shopping carts. The next city crisis: A shortage of parking spaces
for shopping carts.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the carts were piled amazingly high with a wild
assortment of objects (one had an electric fan, a child's toy,
magazines). The Plaza looked like a SFMOMA exhibit of cart art. Who
needs Oldenburg?
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of folks were relaxing in the shade of the plaza trees,
but don't tell the anti-homeless crusaders. They'll discover Dutch
elm disease in the poplars and show up at the plaza with chain
saws.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza's fountain had no water. What, the heat has sucked the
fountain dry?
</P>
<P>
   Dave, a worker from the DPW, told me the fountain pumps have
been busted for a long time, the water had become green and
stagnant, generally not a good thing, and the DWP was fixing it,
``So the homeless will have a place to cool off.''
</P>
<P>
   In the plaza, a flock of pigeons was dining on a buffet of
popcorn and bread. Starving people; stuffed pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   Pigeons might be a nuisance, but at least we don't have turkey
vultures like the ones that are plaguing Merced, pooping and
barfing on cars and people. What is that, a vulture fraternity?
</P>
<P>
   WALKING BACK down Market, I encountered a quartet of hookers
chatting among themselves on the traffic island at Jones St. They
didn't look like typical Tenderloin trollops, but rather like
Hollywood starlets dressed as hookers.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what they were. A film crew was shooting a scene at the
corner and the girls were extras, relaxing between takes.
</P>
<P>
   Typical Hollywood: Go to the city's hotbed of prostitution and
BYO hookers. Coulda hired the real thing at a fraction of the cost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
