A9953 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-LUSCIOUS-TRESSES-ART-     09-29 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUSCIOUS-TRESSES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUSCIOUS TRESSES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE of Meg Ryan is available FREE OF CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by
e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when you order the
article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BRIDGET FOLEY 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Not all fashion trends begin on the runway or on the street.
Sometimes they start on the movie screen, where a new look or
hairstyle can inspire millions of imitations. Hollywood's star
hairstylists are well aware of their power _ to keep it, they're
willing to put up with all sorts of problems that ordinary stylists
never have to face.
</P>
<P>
   Consider continuity. ``One Fine Day'' takes place over the
course of about 24 hours, but the filming took three months. Louis
Licari of the bicoastal Louis Licari Haircolor Group had to make
sure that Michelle Pfeiffer's hair was the same color throughout
the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tricky,'' says Licari. ``Most people's haircolor can
vary _ no matter how slightly _ with each visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Basinger's upcoming film, ``I Dreamed of Africa,'' takes
place over the course of about 10 years, but it was shot in just a
few months. Jonathan Antin colorist Lorri Goddard racked up the
frequent flyer miles _ first to Africa, then to Italy _ every time
Basinger needed a different shade of blond.
</P>
<P>
   Period pieces come with their own unique hurdles. Jewel's very
contemporary 'do didn't fit into Ang Lee's upcoming Civil War
drama, ``Ride With the Devil,'' so hairstylist Jonathan Antin
straightened out the layers to make the style more '60s _ 1860s,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes an actress must be drabbed down for a role. When Susan
Sarandon played the ailing ex-wife in ``Stepmom,'' Licari couldn't
wait for her copper color to tone down naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is called color removal, but we speed things along
using hot oil treatments,'' he explains. ``They help lift the
pigment faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Constant color changes can sometimes be too much for an actress
to bear. Ashley Judd was in tears when Candace, the colorist at
Beverly Hills' Sublime Salon, showed up on the set of ``Norma Jean
and Marilyn'' for an emergency fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her hair was supposed to be dark brown, but it was pink,''
recalls Candace. When someone goes from blond to brown, hair needs
to get a ``filler'' first to fill in the porous hair, so the darker
shade will take. Obviously someone had skipped this step with Judd.
</P>
<P>
   Licari has gone through a similar series of extreme color
changes with Cate Blanchett. After going dark brown for ``Oscar and
Lucinda'' and deep red for ``Elizabeth,'' Blanchett went very blond
for a film she was working on at the time of this year's Academy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to get it progressively lighter,'' he says. ``It's
gentler on the hair if you have that luxury of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The all-time champion of color changes may be Helen Hunt. Since
she had to film ``As Good As It Gets'' simultaneously with her
sitcom ``Mad About You,'' she went from Carol Conelly drab to Jamie
Buchman blond ``practically every other day,'' remembers stylist
Darrell Redleaf-Fielder of Nubest &AMP; Co. ``I had to mix two shades
to cut through that golden blond hair. Then she'd wash the brown
out the next day. When I saw that movie for the first time, I
practically bit all my nails off.''
</P>
<P>
   A subtle color treatment may be crucial to making a character
believable, but it's a great new cut that can spark a big trend in
the real world _ and make a star out of its creator as well.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Bruce Paltrow went for his usual trim at
L.A.'s Prive Salon, he brought along his daughter, Gwyneth. Owner
Laurent started asking her about the character in her next film,
``Sliding Doors,'' and suggested a drastic cut. The next day,
Paltrow was back with then-boyfriend Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was more nervous than she was,'' laughs Laurent.
``But that haircut really changed my whole career. I was in every
magazine after that haircut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actors are very confident when undergoing a new look,'' says
John Freida hairstylist Sally Herschberger, who's responsible for
Meg Ryan's flopsy-mopsy hairstyle. ``They get it. They're excited
about the process.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, says L.A. salon owner Allen Edwards, actors'
motives are similar to those of salon clients everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real people are constantly reconsidering how they want to look
to those around them,'' he says. ``How different is that from what
actors and stylists do for a role? We're all playing our own
roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, ours don't usually come with a rigid production
schedule. Then again, we don't have our own trailers, either.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bridget Foley is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
