<HEADER>
A9961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN30-CO     09-29 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Take your shoes off and set a
spell
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Friends in Bryan-College Station, Texas, were
telling me about a young couple from there who recently moved to
Lufkin. It seems they're having their problems adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   Do tell?
</P>
<P>
   I was born here 58 1/2 years ago. I'm still having trouble
adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   What it was for them, they ate out at one of our finer diners
recently and were surprised to see people at the next table who
weren't wearing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the young couple had failed to note the sign at the
door of the restaurant:
</P>
<P>
   ``No Shirt, No Shoes, No Problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we're laid-back hereabouts, even by backwoods standards.
</P>
<P>
   Our city motto reflects as much. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're gonna live in Lufkin, get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, I personally find it a sad commentary on our community
when someone from that citadel of sophistication, Bryan-College
Station, home of the Texas Aggies, would find Lufkin somehow
lacking in couth.
</P>
<P>
   People everywhere have heard of the Aggies, even though they may
have a hard time believing what they've heard.
</P>
<P>
   One quick example: When Texas A&AMP;M installed artificial turf at
its football stadium, Aggie engineers couldn't figure out why it
had cost $100,000 more than a similar field at the University of
Texas in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   UT engineers, called in as consultants, spotted the difference
right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours,'' they explained to their A&AMP;M cohorts, ``didn't include
a sprinkler system.''
</P>
<P>
   But my purpose here isn't to tell Aggie jokes. It just so
happens that my oldest daughter is an Aggie grad, and that's no
joke. Leastwise, I'm not laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I'll tell you a Lufkin story _ not a joke, but true and
correct.
</P>
<P>
   This was some years ago when I was still editor of the Lufkin
Daily News. Back then, perhaps more than now, the paper ran
pictures of dead things.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly during deer season, we ran pictures of dead deer _ almost
always with their tongues hanging out _ along with the proud
hunter. Sometimes the hunter's tongue would be hanging out, too,
but not always.
</P>
<P>
   In season and out, we printed pictures of other dead trophies as
well.
</P>
<P>
   I remember when a couple of fellows brought in the last black
bear ever killed in East Texas, shot while trying to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind they had no bear hunting license. It made no
difference to them, hunters that they were. It sure didn't make any
difference to the bear.
</P>
<P>
   But my best story is about the old boy who brought in a couple
of wolves he'd killed, loaded up in the bed of his pickup truck. I
still have that picture. The look on his face tells you how proud
he was of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad I didn't see the picture before it ran in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't take notice of it until the next day when I heard that
the fellow's neighbor was angry at the newspaper about the photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he want to be in the picture, too?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, heavens, no,'' I was told. ``Them was his two German
shepherd dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes will happen in the newspaper, but I always thought that
was one we could have avoided. The flea collars should have tipped
us off.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, we try our best to make our newcomers feel at home.
They're always easy to recognize. They're the ones wearing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
