<HEADER>
A9971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     09-29 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, Sept. 29, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-PEDESTRIANS (San Francisco) _ Since the 1950s, San Francisco
pedestrians have faced a steady risk of being killed by motorists.
But pedestrian advocates complain that the city's solution so far
has focused primarily on enforcement of traffic laws, while
experience elsewhere indicates measures that slow traffic _ longer
walk signals, more medians, fewer one-way streets _ work better. By
SARAH YANG.
</P>
<P>
   SF-COLORED-TIRES (San Francisco) _ San Francisco is on the road
to becoming the first city in the nation to ban the sale of
brightly colored tires that can leave behind tread marks in red,
blue or yellow. The proposed law also would hold tire manufacturers
responsible for cleaning city streets marred by the colored skid
marks. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-MUSEUM (Washington) _ To the sounds of Indian drums and
ceremonial chants, officials break ground for the latest addition
to the Smithsonian Institution complex in Washington, the National
Museum of the American Indian. The museum, featuring 800,000
Native-American objects assembled from 1903 to 1957 by the late
George Gustav Heye, is scheduled to open in 2002. By BILL CRAIG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (San Francisco) _ Although negotiations regarding
China's admission to the World Trade Organization bogged down again
in Washington, D.C., China will eventually join the WTO _ and that
is a good thing. That was the consensus of China experts gathered
in San Francisco on Tuesday on a panel convened by the Commonwealth
Club of California. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   HAMBRECHT-&AMP;-QUIST (San Francisco) _ In 1980, between October and
December, investment bankers Hambrecht &AMP; Quist of San Francisco
brought Genentech and then Apple Computer to the public market _
back-to-back coups. Then over the years came Adobe Systems, one of
the stellar performers in software, Amazon.com and Netscape, and
650 other emerging growth firms. Now, H&AMP;Q is being bought by Chase
Manhattan Bank. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SMASHMOUTH (Undated) _ Smash Mouth guitarist and
songwriter Greg Camp isn't into violent rock riffs or
cynical-'cause-it's-cool posturing. He'd rather make happy hit
records and play with his 9-month-old daughter, who is on the road
with him and his wife. By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BERENGER-PROFILE (Undated) _ Actor Tom Berenger, an Oscar
nominee for ``Platoon,'' talks about movie making, history and his
latest film, ``One Man's Hero.'' By LOUIS PARKS
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Reviews of recent video releases of the
``Monty Python'' TV series and ``Wallace and Gromit.'' By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-KINGS (UNDATED) _ Director David O. Russell's third
film, ``Three Kings,'' is set in Iraq just after the Gulf War. By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-RATTO-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ With all the scripted
hoopdeblah surrounding the closing of that venerable old orchard we
know and lie about as Candlestick Park, there is a sense of comfort
in knowing that some people still know the value of a good
surprise, delivered well. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For those trying to score tickets
to the last Giants game at Candlestick on Thursday, Sherry Davis
has a question: ``Where were you on a cold Tuesday night against
Montreal?'' Davis, the Giants' biggest fan with the loudest yet
gentlest voice at Candlestick, also said, ``They could have gone
this past weekend. It was beautiful.'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Bolton Landing, N.Y.) _ I was at the annual
meeting of the Business Council of New York. I'd just moderated a
panel discussion. Then somebody sent me to a booth at the back of
the conference building to pick up my bag of complimentary gifts
such as corporate golf shirts and pens and God knows what other
goodies. I was just going for mine when a tiny version of me,
dressed in a white robe and wearing a halo, popped up on my right
shoulder. It was my pain-in-the-butt conscience. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICIANS-COURAGE (San Francisco) _ When asked, most of my
physician colleagues do not describe themselves as courageous. But
actually, courage is an everyday matter in medicine. By LINDA HAWES
CLEVER.
</P>
</TEXT>
