<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9972 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN30-COX     09-29 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The view of reality is magnet
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I shouldn't even let myself (ITAL) think (END ITAL) about
getting involved.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those infatuations where you can see the end miles
ahead of you, and it can only end one way: tears, recriminations,
abandonment. I know. It has always ended this way before.
</P>
<P>
   Dare I hope this time might be different?
</P>
<P>
   After ``Northern Exposure,'' I vowed, never, ever to get
involved with a television show again. For once, I had fallen in
love with a hit show _ not one of those one- or two-season wonders,
``Homefront'' and ``My So-Called Life'' _ and still I had been
deserted with little warning.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I would flirt with commitment, but only flirt. At the
first sign of emotional engagement, I'd be outta there, proving how
easily I could live without that cad, television.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time in recent years I have entertained a mild
crush, more manufactured than real, as crushes tend to be. There
was the occasional Tuesday night dalliance with the amusing ``Spin
City,'' or the Monday night date with ``Chicago Hope,'' which
seduced me with a fabulous cast and good writing, but ultimately
turned me off with its unbelievable, over-the-top plot lines. (An
episode begins promisingly, for instance, with three women stranded
in a cabin during a storm, unsnarling knots in their friendship,
only to end with their killing an intruder. Yep, happens to me all
the time.)
</P>
<P>
   There was no longer anything on prime time TV that resembled my
life, any life I had ever lived, or any life anyone I knew had ever
lived.
</P>
<P>
   But one indolent evening early last season, that changed. After
watching ``Spin City,'' I tuned into ``Sports Night,'' a new series
about the lives and loves and impossible longings of the staff of
an ESPN-style nightly cable news show.
</P>
<P>
   Here were characters I recognize, situations that resonate. They
were more glamorous, true, with better bodies and hairstyles and
one-liners, but they reminded me of being young and working in a
newsroom. It could be any staff that is young, clever, ambitious,
simultaneously insecure and too-full-of-themselves. It could be any
group of young people consumed by both career and romance,
feverishly trying to sort out their personal and professional
lives.
</P>
<P>
   When I talked ``Sports Night'' up to my friends, it was a
naysayer, ironically, who hit on the show's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's all about (ital) relationships, (END ITAL)'' he
groused. ``How realistic is that?''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's not as realistic as shootouts in emergency rooms
or any of the other highly probable events you're likely to see on
prime time. Who wants to watch a show about relationships when you
could be watching court battles over who invented the face-bra?
</P>
<P>
   Silly me, to become wrapped up in the romantic intrigues of Dana
and Casey and Dana and Gordon and Dan and Rebecca and Dan and
Bobbie and Natalie and Jeremy. This week, the new season premieres
and forces a decision: Do I stay with these people or not? Last
time I let this happen, I became attached to the quirky yet utterly
believable populace of ``Northern Exposure's'' Cicely, Alaska. And
then they dumped me, without so much as a post card since.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I'll tune in. With dialogue this good, characters
this real, I won't be able to resist a relationship with my TV this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I know, sure as Rhett knew Scarlett, it will all
come to a bad end.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: marymccarty(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
