<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9973 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN30-COX     09-29 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Since 1776, Britain hasn't quit griping
 &HT;    EDs: Moving in (k) Commentary and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Is there any group outside of an elementary
school swing set who can whine as spectacularly and annoyingly as
the British? What a bunch of crybabies.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits, which conveniently rhymes with twits, got a major
itch in their tweeds when the Europeans hawked up a big one and
lost golf's Ryder Cup to the American team.
</P>
<P>
   What really soured the Brits' Earl Grey was the Americans
streaming prematurely onto the 17th green after Texan Justin
Leonard sewed up the match by making a 45-foot putt.
</P>
<P>
   The British media got their noses out of joint because the
Americans _ wives, caddies, fans _ ran onto the green before
Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal could putt. Yes, the Americans pulled a
no-no in golf. They tramped all over Olazabal's putting line before
he'd had a chance to finish.
</P>
<P>
   But to hear the Brits howl about it, you would have thought the
Americans had mooned Buckingham Palace. Which is a pretty good idea
because it would make for a great European vacation slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joy of Ugly Victory Brings Out the Ugly American,'' said the
Guardian. ``Let us be painfully honest about it,'' wrote columnist
Matthew Norman in the London Evening Standard. ``Yes, (Americans)
are repulsive people, charmless, rude, cocky, mercenary, humorless,
ugly, full of nauseatingly fake religiosity, and as odious in
victory as they are unsporting in defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, mister, eat my easy-iron khakis. If it had been a British
sports demonstration, instead of screwing up his putt the British
would have trampled Olazabal like a June bug on the back porch.
Don't take my word for it. Follow any stampede in England and see
how often it breaks out into a football match.
</P>
<P>
   At least Americans don't stomp on one another unless there's a
good reason _ like a Beanie Babies sale at Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the British are so upset is that they used to be big
_ back when having season tickets to weekend beheadings was a big
deal. Since then, the country has been largely irrelevant. The
British haven't had anybody who was worth a pack of tea bags since
Winston Churchill, except for those two TV cooking show loads, the
``Two Fat Ladies.'' And one of them just passed away, leaving
England one fat lady short of a full load.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the royal family. Is there a larger group of
deadbeats? Three words come to mind when I think of the queen of
England: GET A JOB. What does this broad do to rate such a big
house? I keep expecting the queen to show up with a cardboard sign
that says, ``Will wave for food.''
</P>
<P>
   They say there will always be an England. Why? Because someone
has to come in second. It's been a bad 200 years for the English.
In that time they have accomplished only two major invasions _ the
Beatles making it onto Ed Sullivan, then the taking of the Falkland
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The Falklands. That's not the sort of achievement that makes you
want to rush into the streets shouting, ``We're number one,'' is
it?
</P>
<P>
   How are you going to make a T-shirt out of whipping the Falkland
Islands? What would it say on the front? ``We Kick Sheep Butt''?
That's not exactly bragging rights. And why do they call it Jolly
Old England anyway? Do they enjoy getting their fannies
paddled?John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
