NYT-09-29-99 1112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9974 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN30-COX     09-29 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courting Pat Buchanan not worth Bush's time in White House race
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If Patrick Joseph Buchanan isn't a racist, fascist
and bigot, then he needs to stop imitating those traits.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidate Gov. George W. Bush should reconsider his
request that Buchanan stay in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   People have to bend over backwards to make even the weakest
argument that Buchanan is a misunderstood patriot. If it looks like
a duck, quacks like a duck, waddles like a duck and has feathers,
it's a duck.
</P>
<P>
   For years _ decades _ Buchanan has carefully chosen his words
right up to the narrow edge or racism and anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is intelligent enough to use his skills as a precise
writer and a gifted speaker to appeal to the worst instincts in
human nature and still give himself just enough room to deny the
obvious bigotry of his words.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the younger does not want Buchanan to attack him as as he
did Bush the elder. Bush also fears losing the votes Buchanan might
take with him if he leaves the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush should not stoop to cater to votes Buchanan might bring
to the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is a bigot's man through and through. He's made a
career appealing to white supremacists, anti-Semites, isolationists
and lock-and-load yahoos.
</P>
<P>
   The apple doesn't fall far from the tree. In this case, Pat
Buchanan says he was greatly influenced by his father, William
Baldwin Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan the elder was a devoted follower of the America First
Committee, a pro-Nazi, anti-Semitic, nativist and isolationist
movement. The elder Buchanan also admired fascist dictator
Francisco Franco of Spain and America's infamous red-baiter Sen.
Joseph McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Buchanan also has expressed admiration of fascist
dictator Franco and has described Hitler as ``an individual of
great courage ... extraordinary gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   The man Bush doesn't want to leave the Republican Party is an
admirer of the ``Boer Republic'' and once applied to be ambassador
to South Africa's white racist government that routinely tortured
and murdered citizens of the ``wrong'' color.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan wants to use immigration laws to block entry to the
sort of people who will water down the European white culture in
America. He has supported stationing U.S. troops across the
1,900-mile border with Mexico and referred to Mexican immigrants as
``Jose.'' At the same time, he has invited white people in Canada
to become U.S. citizens. He has said ``Englishmen'' will assimilate
better than ``Zulus.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Buchanan has supported Nazis accused of war crimes
while belittling Holocaust reports. He has called Congress
``Israeli-occupied territory.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who once referred to AIDS as ``nature's awful
retribution'' against homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's campaign co-chairman in 1996 made repeated speeches
to neo-Nazis and white supremacists.
</P>
<P>
   Now in a new book, Buchanan argues against going to war with
Spain, getting into World War I and believing that Hitler was a
threat to the United States. He even implies that the
Nazi-controlled government in France wasn't so bad and might have
been hunky-dory elsewhere as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should have taken his lead from Sen. John McCain, another
Republican presidential candidate. When told of Buchanan's latest
published demagoguery, McCain told Buchanan to take a hike and take
his tainted votes with him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' should not include having
compassion for Hitler, anti-Semitism, racism and grotesque
intolerance in exchange for a few votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should show that as president, he would put principles over
politics. He should say adios to Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
