<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS30-TAKE     09-29 1819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS30-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Do hurricanes south of the Equator spin clockwise, and if so,
why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, they do. The Coriolis force (sometimes called the
Coriolis effect) is the reason. In 1835, French scientist
Gustave-Gaspard Coriolis determined that as air begins flowing from
high to low pressure, the Earth rotates under it, making the wind
follow a curved path. In the Southern Hemisphere, the wind turns to
the left of its direction of motion, but it's slightly overbalanced
by the pressure gradient force, which points toward the center of
the force. The result: Hurricane winds flow clockwise around a low.
It's just the opposite in the Northern Hemisphere, where the winds
flow into a low-pressure area in a counterclockwise direction.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, some people think the Coriolis effect explains what
makes the water in a sink or toilet rotate one way as it drains in
one hemisphere, the other way in the other hemisphere. Others argue
the Coriolis force is noticeable only for large-scale motions, such
as winds, and that other forces account for the drain effect.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of information can be found online at these sites:
www.sunynassau.edu/users/fanellis/oceanology/Coriolis.htm and
www.usatoday.com/weather/wcorioli.htm
</P>
<P>
   Q: It seems to me that rain from hurricanes would be salty,
since they pick up salt water after passing over oceans. Is that
true?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's likely that rain produced by hurricanes does contain
some degree of salinity, because they have drawn in droplets
whipped off the ocean surface. But hurricanes also draw in water
that has evaporated off the ocean, diluting any salinity that might
be present. Also, once hurricanes leave the ocean and move over
land, the amount of salinity in the rain probably would decrease. A
spokesman at the National Hurricane Center in Miami said that, to
his knowledge, the salinity in rain resulting from a hurricane has
never been measured, so statistics are unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The lighthouse on Cape Hatteras, N.C., was moved inland
recently. How did it do in the two hurricanes, Dennis and Floyd?
</P>
<P>
   A: It did just fine, said Paul Winegar of the National Park
Service. The tower's relocation, 2,900 feet inland from its
original location, was completed in July. It was a good thing, too,
Winegar said, because the original site ``got a lot of high
water.'' While Dennis dumped a lot of rain on Cape Hatteras, Floyd
wasn't as bad because it went to the west of the lighthouse and the
national park.
</P>
<P>
   The lighthouse's relighting ceremony, originally scheduled over
Labor Day weekend, was canceled because of storms. It's now
scheduled for Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you list the religions of the world with the most
adherents?
</P>
<P>
   A: The numbers in several sources vary and aren't up to date,
but they are the latest available and should give you an idea.
</P>
<P>
   Among Christian religions, World Book Encyclopedia (1999), lists
Roman Catholic followers at 1.04 billion; Protestant, 382 million;
and Orthodox, 173.6 million. Among non-Christian religions, it
lists Islam at 1.01 billion; Hinduism, 751.3 million; Buddhism, 334
million; Chinese folk religion (a system of beliefs including
Confucianism and Taoism), 141 million; Judaism, 12.9 million; and
Shintoism, 3.3 million. World Book notes that its figures are from
1993, and credits them to World Christian Encyclopedia and the
American Jewish Committee.
</P>
<P>
   World Almanac (1999) lists, among Christians, Roman Catholics
with 1.04 billion; Protestants, 391 million; and Orthodox, 223
million. Among non-Christians, it lists Muslims, 1.15 billion;
Hindus, 747 million; Buddhists, 353 million; Chinese folk religion,
363 million; Jews, 14.9 million; and Shintoists, 2.7 million. It
dates the statistics to mid-1997 and credits as its source the 1999
Encyclopedia Britannica Book of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The Guinness Book of Records (1999) calls the Baha'i faith, with
about 6 million people, the ``biggest religion without any rites.''
World Almanac, meanwhile, indicates 7.67 million Baha'is, while
World Book Encyclopedia lists 5.5 million Baha'is.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can kudzu be used for animal feed or for any other commercial
use?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cows, goats and other animals love it, says Wayne McLaurin,
horticulturist with the University of Georgia Extension Service.
Kudzu, a legume, is nutritious for cud-chewing animals, and letting
them eat it is one of the few ways to get rid of it. Kudzu has a
very large tuber underground that resprouts each year. When it's
eaten back, the tuber is weakened and eventually killed. It takes a
long time, McLaurin adds, but it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   While the tuber is used in commercial starch production in
Japan, other commercial uses are limited. Kudzu can't be baled, for
example, because it tangles up in the machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will Atlanta Falcons running back Jamal Anderson still
receive his multimillion-dollar salary, now that he is injured and
most likely out for the remainder of the season?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. His salary _ $32 million over five years _ is guaranteed
by contract. Falcons spokesman Aaron Salkin said there was a time
when teams used a split contract, paying one amount if the athlete
played the normal full schedule and another if placed on the
injured reserve, but that doesn't happen any more.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is considered the richest person in the world?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Guinness Book of Records 1999 reports that Microsoft
Corp. chairman and co-founder Bill Gates is now No. 1, bumping the
Sultan of Brunei to No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you list the states where all the Miss America winners
have come from, how many women were from each, and the years? It
seems like a lot have come from a few states.
</P>
<P>
   A: California crowns the Miss America sweepstakes with six
winners (1925, '41, '43, '46, '55, '83).
</P>
<P>
   Ohio and Pennsylvania are next with five each: Ohio ('22, '23,
'38, '63, '72, '78; the same contestant won in '22 and '23); and
Pennsylvania ('24, '35, '36, '40, '54).
</P>
<P>
   Four states have had four: Illinois ('27, '69, '91, '98);
Michigan ('39, '61, '70, '88); Mississippi ('59, '60, '80, '86);
and Oklahoma ('26, '67, '81, '96).
</P>
<P>
   Five states have had three: Colorado ('56, '58, '74); Kansas
('66, '68, '97); Minnesota ('48, '77, '89); New York ('45, '76,
'84); Texas ('42, '71, '75).
</P>
<P>
   Eight states and the District of Columbia have had two: Alabama
('51, '95); Arizona ('49, '65); Arkansas ('64, '82); District of
Columbia ('21, '44); New Jersey ('37, '84); South Carolina ('57,
'94); Tennessee ('47, '87); Utah ('52, '85); Virginia ('79, '99).
</P>
<P>
   And eight have had one: Connecticut ('33); Florida ('93);
Georgia ('53); Hawaii ('92); North Carolina ('62); Missouri ('90);
Wisconsin ('73).
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky got its first winner ('00) last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In an item about past Miss America winners from various
states, Q&AMP;A listed two for 1984, one from New York and the other
from New Jersey. How could that be?
</P>
<P>
   A: The original 1984 Miss America was Vanessa Williams,
representing New York. She relinquished her title July 23 of that
year when it was revealed that nude photographs of her would appear
in Penthouse magazine. It was the first time in the pageant's
history that a Miss America had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Pageant officials in Atlantic City, N.J., immediately named
Suzette Charles, who as Miss New Jersey had been first runner-up,
as the new Miss America. She served out the remaining two months of
the 1984 reign.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, now known professionally as Vanessa L. Williams, went
on to become a singing, dancing and acting star. Charles, who has
done some entertainment work and briefly hosted a TV show in
Atlanta in the early 1990s, married a doctor in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The new Miss America was called the first Kentuckian to win
the title. But I remember that Venus Ramey of Stanford, Ky., won
the title years ago. What state did she represent, if not Kentucky?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ramey, the 1944 Miss America, did indeed hail from Kentucky,
but won the title representing Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One more beauty queen question: Q&AMP;A reported that Heather
Renee French, the newly crowned Miss America, was the first
Kentuckian to win the title. I thought Phyllis George was first. Am
I correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: George, from Denton, Texas, was Miss Texas before winning the
Miss America title in 1971. She became the first lady of Kentucky
when her husband, John Y. Brown Jr., was elected governor in 1979.
Brown made his fortune with Kentucky Fried Chicken. George later
went on to work in network TV news and sports, write two books, and
found By George, a food products company.
</P>
<P>
   Q: South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu recently quoted
Mohandas Gandhi as saying something to the effect that politics
cannot be without conscience, science without humanity, wealth
without work. Can you give me the exact quote?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's from a list that the Indian nationalist leader
(1869-1948) once said caused all violence in human life: wealth
without work; pleasure without conscience; knowledge without
character; commerce without morality; science without humanity;
worship without sacrifice; politics without principle; and rights
without responsibilities. The list was publicized widely when it
was quoted at Hubert H. Humphrey's funeral by President Jimmy
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Bill Gates is pledging $1 billion for minority scholarships.
Can you define who are the qualifying minorities, and how one
applies?
</P>
<P>
   A: Scholarships and fellowships will be available through the
Gates Millennium Scholars Program for 20 years, starting in the
fall of 2000, for outstanding low-income African-American, Native
American, Hispanic-American and Asian-American students. The United
Negro College Fund will administer the program.
</P>
<P>
   Students must be nominated by a high school principal or
teacher, or a college professor, president or dean. Applicants must
be U.S. citizens; have a minimum grade-point average of 3.3 on a
4.0 scale; be a high school senior applying to an accredited
college or university; or a college student planning to continue
undergraduate study; or a college senior or college graduate
enrolled or about to enroll in graduate school (graduate students
must be enrolled in a degree program in engineering, mathematics,
science, education or library science); demonstrate significant
financial need; and have demonstrated leadership commitment through
participation in community service, extracurricular activities, or
other activities that reflect leadership abilities.
</P>
<P>
   More information: online at www.gmsp.org, or call 877-690-4677.
Starting Nov. 1, applications will be available from nominators or
can be downloaded from the Web site. Applications must be received
by Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
