<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9979 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS30-TAKE     09-29 1615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS30-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take one of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him: q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Former President Jimmy Carter recently stated that he was one
of the last people to speak with Elvis Presley before he died. I
have never heard or read anything about this. Do you have any
details about this meeting?
</P>
<P>
   A: They didn't meet on that particular occasion. What Carter
told students at Emory University in Atlanta at a recent town hall
meeting was that he was one of the last people to speak with
Presley before the singer died on Aug. 16, 1977. The conversation
was by telephone, when Presley called Carter at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carter biographer Douglas Brinkley, Carter's White
House diary showed that the conversation took place between 5:18
and 5:24 p.m. June 14, 1977. Carter had met Presley previously,
backstage at the Omni in Atlanta, when Carter was governor of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone conversation took place during what was said to be
the ``roughest part'' of Presley's life. In the conversation,
Presley asked Carter to pardon a sheriff friend of his in Memphis
who was in trouble. Carter explained that a person who hadn't yet
been tried or convicted could not be pardoned.
</P>
<P>
   After Presley died just two months later, Carter issued an
official White House statement. At the time, it was unheard of for
a president to make an official statement about a rock star's
death. Carter called the singer ``unique, irreplaceable and a
symbol the world over of the rebelliousness and good humor of this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Mikhail Gorbachev and his late wife, Raisa, have any
children?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, one. As reported after Raisa Gorbachev died of leukemia
Sept. 20, the couple had a daughter, Irina.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did the Social Security Administration begin payroll
deductions from employers and employees? What was the percentage
rate?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Social Security Act was signed by President Franklin D.
Roosevelt on Aug. 14, 1935. Taxes were collected for the first time
in January 1937. Between 1937 and 1949, the tax rate was 1 percent
each from employer and employee, said Social Security
Administration spokeswoman Patti Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard on numerous occasions about a secessionist
movement in Hawaii on the part of people there who think statehood
was a bad thing. Do you have any information about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is a movement toward sovereignty among descendants of
native Hawaiians, but how significant in size and strength it is
remains in question.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 73 percent of Hawaiians who voted in the Native
Hawaiian Vote favored an election of delegates to propose a native
Hawaiian government. Last July 27, delegates of the Native Hawaiian
Convention began their next step toward self-determination, a
convention with 79 delegates whose plan _ with no specific
timetable _ was to develop a constitution on a form of native
Hawaiian government that then would have to be ratified by all
native Hawaiians.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by the Honolulu Star-Bulletin, such ratification is
a lofty goal, since only 41 percent of Hawaiians statewide
participated in the 1996 vote, while just 8.6 percent cast ballots
in an election of delegates last January. But a survey released
last month by the Office of Hawaiian Affairs stated that one-third
of all residents support the restoration of Hawaii as an
independent country.
</P>
<P>
   Some non-native Hawaiians, meanwhile, claim that the 1996
referendum discriminated against non-native Hawaiians and was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the overthrow on Jan. 17, 1893, of the Kingdom of
Hawaii, a fact that was recognized by U.S. Public Law 103-150, the
``apology resolution'' to native Hawaiians. It was passed by
Congress and signed by President Clinton on Nov. 23, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the sovereignty movement have established a Web
site _ www.hawaii-nation.org _ where more information on their
cause can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know what has happened to Allan Nairn, the American
journalist detained by the Indonesian military? He gave an
interview by cell phone to ``The NewsHour With Jim Lehrer'' Sept.
14 and I haven't heard anything further.
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the few Western journalists to remain in Dili, East
Timor's provincial capital, in recent weeks, Nairn was arrested
Sept. 14, questioned by the Indonesian military, and deported. He
flew from Jakarta, Indonesia, to Singapore on Sept. 20, where he
told reporters that he hoped to return to East Timor as soon as
possible. Immigration officials in West Timor said Nairn had
entered the country illegally, listing on his visa that he was a
tourist, rather than saying he was a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was arrested and deported, Nairn, 43, of New Jersey,
had been interviewed by NPR's ``All Things Considered'' and had
described in detail the rampaging and terrorism he said he saw
being conducted by the Indonesian troops and their militia
auxiliaries.
</P>
<P>
   Nairn had been in trouble with Indonesian authorities before
with his reporting on Timor violence, including being banned from
Indonesia and occupied East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of the recipients of this year's Kennedy Center Honors is
Sean Connery. Aren't they for American artists only?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The lifetime achievement awards are given to those who
have contributed ``a body of work in the United States,'' and
aren't restricted to U.S. citizens or people born in the United
States, said a Kennedy Center spokesman. Actor Connery, who was
born in Edinburgh, Scotland, is one of two honorees this year not
born in the United States; the other is comedian and pianist Victor
Borge, a native of Copenhagen, Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of precedent. Since the honors were established
in 1978, other foreign-born honorees have included, in 1978,
pianist Arthur Rubenstein, who was born in Lodz, Poland; pianist
Rudolph Serkin, 1981, Eger, Bohemia; opera composer Gian Carlo
Menotti, 1984, Cadegliano, Italy; violinist Isaac Stern, also 1984,
Kreminiwez, Russia; cellist and conductor Mstislav Rostropovich,
1992, Baku, Azerbaijan; and conductor Georg Solti, 1993, Budapest,
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners this year are dancer Judith Jamison, actor Jason
Robards and musician Stevie Wonder. The awards will be presented
Dec. 4, followed by a gala performance the next day which will be
televised in late December.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I served on the escort carrier CVE 71, USS Kitkun Bay, in
World War II. Do you know its final disposition?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kitkun Bay (named after a body of water in Alaska), which was
launched Nov. 8, 1943, in Vancouver, Wash., was scrapped early in
1947 after an illustrious career in the Pacific. It suffered damage
in two incidents, with 17 total dead and 38 wounded. In addition to
the Presidential Unit Citation, Kitkun Bay earned six Battle Stars
during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our youth group is trying to put on a safe trick-or-treat
carnival, and all of us grown-ups can't agree on what night
Halloween is observed when Oct. 31 falls on a Sunday. Some say it
never is on a Sunday, and others say it's always the last night of
October. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: Halloween, the occasion for trick-or-treating, isn't a
holiday whose observance is established by law; it's a tradition.
And the tradition is that it is Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween developed from ancient new year festivals and
festivals of the dead. In the 800s, the Christian church
established All Saint's Day on Nov. 1 so people could continue an
observance they had celebrated before becoming Christians. The
evening before All Saint's Day became known as All Hallow's Eve, or
All Hallowe'en. The observance also is traced to the Celtic
festival of Samhain. The Celts' new year began on Nov. 1, with a
celebration beginning the previous evening.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly those who don't want a trick-or-treat carnival to be
on a Sunday can stage it on another day. Some people, needless to
say, don't approve of it all, no matter the day or date.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ken Bode was an excellent moderator for the PBS program
``Washington Week in Review,'' but he left the show earlier this
year without any explanation. What was the reason?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bode's five-year run as host of the venerable program came to
a sudden end in February because, he said, the new programming
chief of the PBS station that produces the program wanted to take
it in ``a different direction.'' He said he disagreed with changes
in the show pushed by Dalton Delan, a former cable programming
executive who had worked at HBO, among others.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by The New York Times, Bode was edged out in a
search for ``more edge and attitude'' by station executives at the
PBS Station. Sharon Percy Rockefeller, WETA-TV president, said
there was never any intention of diminishing or compromising the
program. She added that all 50 national programs produced by WETA,
including ``Washington Week in Review,'' are being analyzed at the
behest of the station's board.
</P>
<P>
   While Rockefeller said Bode was not forced out, adding that his
contract wasn't renewed ``in the way he wanted it to be,'' Bode
himself said this to The Chicago Tribune: ``I've never been fired
before. Journalists always have to quit on principle or be fired on
principle. I just don't know which one happened to me.'' Bode, by
the way, is dean of Northwestern University's Medill School of
Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
