<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-JEWISH-COOKING30-COX     09-29 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-COOKING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jewish Sukkot celebration and its outdoor meals became the
foundation of Thanksgiving
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you've caught sight of neighbors dining in a
makeshift backyard hut this week, chances are they're celebrating
the ancient Jewish holiday of Sukkot.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day fall festival, which began Friday night,
commemorates the 40 years the Jewish people wandered in the
wilderness after fleeing Egypt. The sukkah (booth) that families
around the world construct for the holiday are reminiscent of the
temporary structures in which their ancestors lived in the desert.
The little booths also were used by farmers in ancient Israel to
save time during the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sukkot, the Feast of Tabernacles, was the most important
thanksgiving festival,'' explains Marc Gruber, senior rabbi at
Dayton's Temple Israel. ``The Pilgrims modeled their Thanksgiving
on Sukkot.''
</P>
<P>
   The sukkah is a place for festive gatherings: Families often eat
meals there during the holiday and invite friends to share the
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each Jewish holiday has special foods associated with it and
has aspects that are religious, historical and seasonal,'' says
Gruber, who last year invited his entire congregation to an open
house in his sukkah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's traditional at Sukkot to use seasonal foods and to put
everything in a casserole so you can carry it from your kitchen to
the sukkah,'' says Gruber.
</P>
<P>
   A one-dish meal has other advantages: It typically remains hot
throughout the meal and also keeps the family warm on a chilly fall
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Typical dishes might include beef or lamb stews, sweet-and-sour
stuffed cabbage, noodle kugel or puddings, goulash, vegetable
tzimmes (made with sweet potatoes and carrots), seasonal fruit
salads and filled pastries.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be Jewish to enjoy these one-pot recipes at
this time of year. They're great for a tailgate party or
neighborhood potluck.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber, who's been cooking since he was a child and does much of
the cooking for his family, became a vegetarian in 1972 and labels
himself the ``veggie rebbe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to cook with my mom and learned to read with the 'Betty
Crocker Children's Cookbook,' `` he recalls. ``I have early
memories of making apple crisp and serving it with cream or ice
cream.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be Jewish to enjoy these one-pot recipes at
this time of year. They're great for a tailgate party or
neighborhood potluck.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber says he tries to eat two meals each day in the sukkah
during the holiday. He and his wife, Renee, have three sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids like the holiday because it's fun,'' he says. ``It's
picnicky, campy. It's filled with sights, sounds and senses.'' Some
families even sleep in the sukkah.
</P>
<P>
   The little booths typically are decorated with gourds, fruits
and vegetables, strings of cranberries and popcorn, Indian corn.
</P>
<P>
   These days there are modular and fiberglass sukkahs, canvas
versions with zippers and windows, and portable sukkahs for travel.
</P>
<P>
   But lots of families still prefer creating their own. Renee
Gruber notes her husband's sukkah-building skills have improved
through the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He began building sukkahs when we lived on Long Island in
1985,'' she remembers. ``It was windy there because it was near the
ocean and it was always hurricane season, so the sukkah would look
good when we first put it up but it would collapse with the first
strong winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Rochester it was so cold that you could freeze in your
sukkah and be eating in the snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's fall weather is more conducive to sukkah-building.
``Eventually, we figured out the best construction and our sukkahs
have been standing ever since,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Micah Gruber, 12, says Sukkot is his favorite Jewish holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was real young I've always helped my dad put up the
sukkah,'' he says. ``I like being out there. Now that I'm older, I
know more about the holiday and I still like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Gruber gets a kick out of sharing a story that took place
some years ago when his family was living on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always buy strings of twinkly lights at the end of December
and save them to light our sukkah,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Queried Micah, age 5, one wintry night: ``Hey, why does everyone
have sukkah lights on their houses?''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Moss writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: meredithmoss(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
