<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-JEWISH-RESOURCES30-CO     09-29 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-RESOURCES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holiday recipe resources
 &HT;    c. 1999 Dayton Daily News
<TEXT>
<P>
   A number of new Jewish holiday cookbooks recently have hit the
shelves. Here are a few highlights:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The New Jewish Holiday Cookbook: An International Collection
of Recipes and Customs by Gloria Kaufer Greene (Times Books,
$27.50) is organized by holiday. Chapters include histories of each
holiday and recipes ranging from traditional to nouvelle. This
revised cookbook is filled with 260 recipes drawn from many
countries, including Algeria, Greece and Cuba. Each recipe is
clearly marked as dairy, pareve or meat. Recipes for Sukkot include
fruit-and-vegetable tzimmes, cranberry relish and instructions for
making a gingerbread sukkah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I first created a gingerbread sukkah many years ago because
our family did not yet have a life-size sukkah of our own,'' the
author writes. ``I figured that if my family couldn't eat in a
sukkah, at least we could eat a sukkah!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jewish Holiday Style: A Beautiful Guide to Celebrating the
Jewish Rituals in Style by Rita Milos Brownstein (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$27.50). Brownstein is a Jewish Martha Stewart who has come up with
lots of creative ideas for enhancing your holiday table. Recipes
are included, but the emphasis is on projects: The book contains 85
full-color photos and step-by-step project illustrations. Here's
your chance to observe sukkot with a seaside motif, create a matzo
vase or guest pillows for Passover, make Purim graggers
(noisemakers) and tzedakah (charity) boxes for collecting coins.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Light Jewish Holiday Desserts by Penny Wantuck Eisenberg
(William Morrow, $25): Calculate the fat and cholesterol in the
typical Jewish holiday meal and you'll know why this cookbook is a
winning idea. Eisenberg's book is organized by holiday, and she's
come up with light versions of classics such as Rosh Hashanah honey
cake and Hanukkah latkes. She celebrates Sukkot and the autumn
harvest with Pear Varenikes in Chocolate Sauce, Cranberry Pear
Fluden (or ``flat cake'') and a Lemon Mousse Charlotte that has
only one gram of fat per serving.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shabbat Shalom: Recipes and Menus for the Sabbath by Susan R.
Friedland (Little Brown, $24.95) will help Jewish families move
beyond brisket and roast chicken as they commemorate the Sabbath
each Friday night and Saturday. Friedland is the author ofThe
Passover Table, and all of her recipes are kosher.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
