<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9984 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA30-COX     09-29 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: Couple swaps Florida for Fairbanks
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRBANKS, Alaska - In 1996, Terry and Jane Reilly forsook their
homes in West Palm Beach, Fla., to live much of their lives in
brutal cold and unending darkness. And when I say forsook, I mean
forsook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accepted a 60 percent cut in income to move here,'' says
Jane, 44, a longtime sunny Florida resident and former insurance
agent with her family's business, Sam Irvine &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came for the job, not the weather. Terry teaches
Shakespeare at the University of Alaska. We love it here.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't particularly care for the winters that average 20 and
30 degrees below zero, nor are they fond of days that begin at 11
a.m. with a 40-watt sunrise, followed by a return to pitch darkness
at 2 p.m., and no relief until spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a weird place,'' says Terry, 45, who
coached girls' soccer in Florida and taught home-bound students.
``Winters are dark and you kind of go into hibernation mode, and
now you've got midnight tee times and you see people painting their
houses at 2 a.m. People don't sleep in summer. The sunlight
energizes them.''
</P>
<P>
   The extreme cold isn't so bad, the Reillys say. But their
protests sound suspiciously like Arizonans' apologies for their
``dry'' heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dry cold,'' explains Terry. ``And Fairbanks is in a
valley sheltered by two mountain ranges, so there's very little
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, when you check the temperatures and see that it's 60
below in Fairbanks, you've got to understand that that's at the
airport, the lowest point in the valley where the coldest air
sinks. Up on the ridge overlooking the city and the magnificent
Alaska range, the temperature might be only 30 or 40 below.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't even cancel school at 40 below,'' Terry says. ``How
bad could it be?''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty bad, if, as a tour guide told me, at 50 below zero you
throw a cup of scalding coffee in the air and it freezes into a tan
ice fog that floats away.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty bad if, as a political canvasser told me, when you open
the door on a minus 45 degree day, the cold air flowing into the
house hits the warm air inside creating a heavy cloud that covers
the cat and then rises to obscure the television set.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty bad if, as Jane told me, at 70 below zero last winter,
tires froze so solidly that when driving was attempted the tires
fell away from the rims.
</P>
<P>
   It is a 45-degree day in late May as Jane explains that her
commitment to raising her 5-year-old son, Casey, in Fairbanks is
conditional on her returning to Florida every
</P>
<P>
   December to get her personal solar cells recharged.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I miss,'' she says, suspending a forkful of the smoked
Alaska king salmon she and her son caught last summer, ``is diving
under a wave in Florida and coming
</P>
<P>
   up in bright, hot sunlight and feeling the sunlight on my body.
It's the intensity of sunshine, the feeling of it on my back and
face, that I really miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Unmistakable signs of Alaska
</P>
<P>
   You recognize three kinds of roads: under construction, under
repair, shouldn't have been built in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   You take for granted the ``cabin culture'' of university
students who live without plumbing or electricity, ride their bikes
to school, shower at the gym and charge up their laptop computers
to go home to study by kerosene lamps.
</P>
<P>
   You design Halloween costumes to fit over a snowsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Sexy lingerie is a flannel nightgown with only eight buttons.
</P>
<P>
   People hoard airline miles by charging everything possible, and
some have even arranged credit card mortgage payments to reap the
travel bonus.
</P>
<P>
   You aren't asked ``What do you do,'' which would probably be
answered with something like ``hunt'' or ``fish.'' Instead, it's
``What do you do for money?''
</P>
<P>
   Your water costs 6 cents a gallon and it's hauled by a water
dealer and pumped into your 1,500-gallon underground reservoir.
(Some folks save by fetching it
</P>
<P>
   themselves for 2 cents a gallon.)
</P>
<P>
   You see a file cabinet in someone's back yard and assume it's
where ice cream is stored. In cold weather, folks simply throw
their frozen food in the trunks of their car, sometimes forgetting
about it for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   People refer to ``outside'' and mean anywhere outside of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   You come to recognize the 5-gallon buckets many students and
some professionals carry around as Alaskan brief cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was moosed-in'' is a common reason, not an excuse, for
getting to work late. If there is a moose between you and your car,
you wait.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of too many people going into the woods to winter
in a tent heated by a wood stove to think it remarkable. It may not
be understandable, but it is not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of a 10-year-old 5-wheel drive with stuck windows, a
cracked windshield and a bent coat hanger for a radio antenna will
ask $6,000 and get it.
</P>
<P>
   Dog owners who don't want a bear infestation on their property
and a decline in the dog census quickly learn to lock up their dog
food.
</P>
<P>
   You know four seasons: Winter, still winter, not winter, poor
sledding.
</P>
<P>
   Your snow blower gets stuck on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   The high ratio of men to women has been reduced to this
observation for husband-seekers: ``The odds are good, but the goods
are odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
