<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-MUSEUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORK BEGINS ON AMERICAN INDIAN MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL CRAIG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The sounds of Indian drums and ceremonial chants
echoed on the National Mall a few hundred yards from the Capitol
dome as ground was broken for the National Museum of the American
Indian.
</P>
<P>
   The 250,000-square-foot building is scheduled to open in 2002.
Its estimated cost is $110 million, of which $36.7 million has been
raised from more than 250,000 individuals, corporations and
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is the latest addition to the Smithsonian Institution
complex.
</P>
<P>
   The groundbreaking ceremonies on Tuesday were opened by a color
guard of Indian military veterans marching to the beat of a large
drum manned by the White Oak Singers, a ``powwow group'' of
Native-American men living in the Washington area. The site was
blessed through elaborate traditional rituals in native languages
by members of the Piscataway tribe, which originally inhabited the
area, representing the East; by Quechuas from Peru, for the South;
by native Hawaiians representing the West; and by an Inuit woman
from Canada for the North.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for native people throughout the Western
Hemisphere,'' said Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., who
appeared on the podium in full tribal regalia. ``We are asking the
Earth Mother to loan us a small piece from her bosom to build this
museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers included Smithsonian officials and Sen. Daniel K.
Inouye, D-Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   They paid tribute to those who worked to create the museum and
expressed the hope that the building will provide a place for
others to learn not only about the past of Native-American
cultures, but about their present and future contributions.
</P>
<P>
   W. Richard West, the museum director who is a member of the
Southern Cheyenne tribe, echoed a sentiment heard from Indians in
the audience, many in traditional dress, when he said that the
museum ``will show the world what we truly are.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum was established by Congress in 1989 to acquire the
800,000 Native-American objects assembled from 1903 to 1957 by the
late George Gustav Heye, a wealthy New Yorker. It is one of the
world's largest collections of such material and includes objects
dating from 8000 B.C. to the mixed-media design prepared for the
cover of the groundbreaking program.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the collection is from North America, the
rest from South and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   The museum includes two other facilities: the Heye Center, an
exhibition and education facility opened in 1994 in the U.S.
Customs House in lower Manhattan, and a cultural resources center
finished in 1998 in Suitland, Md., to store the bulk of the
collection and to house a library and archives.
</P>
<P>
   The curving architecture planned for the Mall building was
designed in consultation with Native Americans and represents
natural land forms. The grounds on the 4.25-acre site will be
landscaped with indigenous trees and plants.
</P>
<P>
   The site, at Fourth Street and Independence Avenue, is described
as the last plot on the Mall that is suitable for a museum. Urban
archaeologists working there in recent years uncovered the colorful
past of the area, which was a notorious 19th-century neighborhood
until it was cleared as part of a beautification effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1150EDT &QL; 
