<P>
   ABORT: Key supporters of Missouri's latest anti-abortion law all
but concede that U.S. District Judge Scott Wright will declare the
measure unconstitutional. Assuming that happens, one supporter of
the new law said, appeals on the issue mean the law will not become
effective for at least another 18-24 months. Will Sentell. 20.
</P>
<P>
   RAIL: The jury's $160-million verdict against Union Pacific and
Amtrak this week demonstrates the problems with fixing rail
crossings. Despite warnings and accidents, it can take years to get
lights and gates on dangerous crossings. That's because the system
is so complicated. Railroads wait for government to pay them to put
in the signals. Missouri only has enough money to pay for 40
signals a year and more than 2,000 crossings need them. Railroads
say they spend money on safety programs and it's the state's
responsibility to put in crossings. Experts say parceling out the
responsibility results in deaths. Joe Lambe. 25.
</P>
<P>
   CDROM. Holdover. Kansas lawmakers are betting $150,000 that an
interactive computer game that allows seventh- and eighth-graders
to play the role of a state senator or representative will help
students learn about Kansas history and how the Legislature works.
Jim Sullinger. 22.
</P>
