r f BC-HAMBRECHT-&AMP;-QUIST-HNS     09-29 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMBRECHT-&AMP;-QUIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHASE ACQUISITION WAS PACESETTER IN SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the last three months of 1980, investment
bankers Hambrecht &AMP; Quist of San Francisco took Genentech and then
Apple Computer to the public market in back-to-back coups.
</P>
<P>
   Then over the years came Adobe Systems, one of the stellar
performers in software, Amazon.com and Netscape, and 650 other
emerging growth companies.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist provided research, sales and
trading services, merger and acquisition advice and venture capital
_ and a seat at the tables of power in the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   If the company that grew to some 900 employees after its
founding in 1968 carried an air of independence, that is gone now.
The Chase Manhattan Corp. on Tuesday acquired Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for
$50 per share in cash, a total of $1.35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht &AMP; Quist becomes the third San Francisco-based
investment bank within two years to be acquired by a large
commercial bank on the East Coast. BankBoston Corp. bought
Robertson Stephens Inc. last year and NationsBank _ now BankAmerica
Corp. _ bought Montgomery Securities in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that West Coast underwriters have been in the heart
of the action and have grown with the technology industry and are
natural targets for acquisition by a bank seeking underwriting
capability,'' said Michael Flanagan, an analyst at Financial
Service Analytics in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple, Genentech, Netscape _ those are watershed events,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht &AMP; Quist was founded by William R. Hambrecht, then a
securities dealer at A.C. Allyn &AMP; Co., and George Quist. They used
their own money and funds from investors drawn to the excitement
and the risk of Silicon Valley's computer and technology
industries.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fortune magazine, one of the first venture
capitalists, Arthur Rock, a former investment adviser for the
Rockefellers, moved to San Francisco and together with Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist formed a syndicate called ``The Group,'' which helped fund
start-ups like Teledyne, Memorex and Scientific Data Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht &AMP; Quist had a lead in the Internet field by being one
of the first venture capital outfits to invest in Netscape
Communications, which created a wildly popular commercial Web
browser.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the investment, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist was suffering
from a serious public relations problem: Employees of one of
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist's technology companies, MiniScribe Corp. of
Longmont, Colo., had shipped bricks rather than hard drives in an
attempt to boost sales figures. ``A bad thing to do unless you are
in the brick business,'' wrote Netscape co-founder Jim Clark.
</P>
<P>
   According to Clark, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist's investment banking
division was hurting because of the publicity and ``they needed a
high-profile deal to become a major player again.''
</P>
<P>
   Quist died in 1982 and Hambrecht left the company in 1998 to
start W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co., which uses the Internet to raise money
for small companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht &AMP; Quist went public in August 1996. It is traded on
the New York Stock Exchange. It now has offices in San Francisco,
New York, Boston, Atlanta, Newport Beach, London and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Change for H&AMP;Q was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen the real advent of the electronic underwriter and
we have seen increased strength from existing bank underwriters,''
Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist added to the Chase portfolio, ``it
is not enough,'' he said. ``I believe H&AMP;Q is a little too small
(the 11th largest of its kind) to satisfy all of Chase's investment
banking needs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
