<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ARDIE-CORRECTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARDIE DAVIS WRITES BBQ BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ardie Davis has been hitting the barbecue sauce pretty hard.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is he has probably drunk a swimming pool's worth of the
stuff over the years yet still always manages to keep enough sauce
on hand to fill up a good-sized bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   While working on The Great BBQ Sauce Book (Ten Speed Press,
$15.95), Davis was on a first-name basis with the UPS driver who
dropped off ``hundreds'' of long-neck bottles, funky flasks, clunky
moonshine jugs and mayonnaise jars containing the condiment on the
doorstep of his Roeland Park home.
</P>
<P>
   As traditional tomato-based, vinegar-based and mustard-based
sauces duked it out with more exotic gourmet versions spiked with
raspberries, papaya, mango or Scotch bonnet peppers, Davis ended up
collecting so many bottles of the stuff that his wife, Gretchen,
felt compelled to ``allot a certain amount of space'' in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   As readers flip through Davis' 160-page illustrated guide,
they'll find descriptions of more than 300 commercially available
barbecue sauces are divided into ``sweet,'' ``tangy'' and ``fiery''
chapters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone looking to buy a sauce, they want to know if it is
sweet or tangy, and if it was going to bite them,'' Davis says.
``Regions don't make sense anymore because we're so global, and you
can find just about any sauce on Web sites or through catalogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Published last month, The Great BBQ Sauce Book already has sold
10,000 copies and has gone into its second printing. This is Davis'
second book. He is also author of The Kansas City BBQ Pocket Guide
(1992, Pig Out Publications).
</P>
<P>
   Like fine wine, Davis says, the best sauces have their own
distinct nuances. Some sauces are ``hickory-kissed'' while others
finish with a ``peppery heat.'' There are sauces spiked with a hint
of garlic or ``embellished with molasses.'' Some ``make your mouth
feel mellow'' while others are ``hot enough to make your tongue
tingle.''
</P>
<P>
   From the gritty taste of Kansas City's legendary Arthur Bryant's
to Big Bob Gibson's Bar-B-Q Original White Sauce, an oddly speckled
mayonnaise indigenous to parts of Alabama, Davis says he didn't
find any sauce so disagreeable that he was forced to spit it out,
although he concedes that he tasted ``plenty that were just
so-so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if anybody in this city, including myself, has tasted
and judged as many sauces as he has,'' says Rich Davis, inventor of
the original K.C. Masterpiece and no relation to Ardie Davis. ``No
one has focused that finely on the barbecue sauce world.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctoring the sauce
</P>
<P>
   Davis grew up in Oklahoma City, where his dad, a backyard
barbecuer, used to buy the most inexpensive barbecue sauce on the
supermarket shelves and doctor it up to suit the family's tastes.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he moved to Kansas City in 1977 that Davis
discovered his passion for barbecue sauce. In 1984, on the patio
and deck of his home, he organized the first Diddy-Wa-Diddy
National Barbecue Sauce Contest, featuring 104 commercially
available sauces.
</P>
<P>
   ``What triggered the idea for the contest was reading Jane and
Michael Stern's Road Food,'' Davis says. ``They listed 80-some
barbecue restaurants in the book. I knew I wasn't ever going to be
able to travel to all those restaurants so I started writing them
and asking for their sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1987 the contest had grown so large it was renamed the
American Royal International Barbecue Sauce, Rub &AMP; Baste Contest.
The 16th annual contest, sponsored by the Kansas City Barbeque
Society, will be held Saturday at the Governors Exposition Building
at the American Royal complex and is expected to feature more than
400 sauces, including several from foreign countries, making it the
largest sauce contest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I started the (barbecue sauce) contest, I just had my
radar out for sauces, and word of mouth just got out,'' Davis says.
``People would send me sauces and want me to taste them and give my
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   At Davis' urging, Karen Putman finally decided to bottle her
raspberry-flavored barbecue sauce. A red-headed woman who in the
early days sweated it out with her mostly male competitors at
barbecue contests, Davis dubbed her the Flower of the Flames, a
name that stuck and now appears on the label of her barbecue sauce
which she bottles in Lenexa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a really wonderful palate,'' Putman says of her
friend and mentor. ``Plus he loves barbecue. He can eat barbecue
for breakfast, lunch and dinner _ and snacks in between. No matter
where he goes or what he does, he always picks up more sauces to
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people maybe taste as many sauces, but sometimes they're
overly critical,'' says Brian Heinecke, director of public
relations for the National Barbecue Society. ``They tend to narrow
their focus to only sweet ketchup, tomato-based tastes. Ardie has
an appreciation for the breadth of styles ... so people seem very
open to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People put a lot of ego into their sauces,'' Davis says, ``so
when I'm writing about them I was always mindful that it is
precious stuff to the people who make it. It's sort of `love me,
love my sauce.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Alter-barbecue-ego
</P>
<P>
   A shy, soft-spoken, thoughtful man, Davis re-creates himself
through barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   By day he commutes to Topeka, where he is the commissioner of
advocacy services at the Kansas Department on Aging, a position
appointed by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   But on the weekends he transforms himself into the gregarious
Remus Powers, Ph.B., a persona that pays tribute to the stories of
Brer Rabbit and a man he knew simply as ``Powers'', a ``James
Dean-type'' automobile mechanic Davis admired while growing up. The
Ph.B. denotes a ``doctorate in barbecue'' _ an honor conferred on a
handful of experts ``who have made a significant contribution to
barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   His alter-barbecue-ego is easy to spot at barbecue contests. He
wears a black derby, bow tie and a white apron with three rib bones
pinned to it. A white ceramic spoon on a gold string tied to his
apron is at the ready whenever a spontaneous sauce tasting presents
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a charter member of the Kansas City Barbeque Society, has
another passion: writing. For the last decade he has written a
monthly column for the organization's newsletter under the pen name
Remus Powers, Ph.B.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wears the costume when he administers the oath he wrote
for judges at the American Royal Invitational Barbecue Contest,
part of which pledges to preserve ``truth, justice, excellence in
barbecue and the American way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I love barbecue is it's a community builder, and I
think barbecue brings people together in a positive way,'' Davis
says.
</P>
<P>
   From his home office _ a room in a basement that is no wider
than most men are tall _ Davis has literally carved out a niche for
himself. The stone walls of his tiny shrine//office are covered
with a mishmash of barbecue memorabilia _ pins, newspaper
clippings, cartoon pigs and the odd empty barbecue sauce bottle.
</P>
<P>
   He's known to his friends as a sort of barbecue philosopher.
Carolyn Wells, longtime friend and executive director of the Kansas
City Barbeque Society, sums up his dual passions this way: ``He's
transferred his love of barbecue into the book. It's obvious it's
part of his soul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
