<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE TO THE NET THAN THE WEB, LIKE INTERNET RELAY CHAT, FOR
INSTANCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recently stopped using America Online and signed up with a
local Internet provider. I like it a lot so far, but there's one
thing I really miss from AOL _ chat rooms. A friend of mine pointed
me to chat Web sites, like www.talkcity.com, but they're just not
the same. He also suggested I check out IRC. I tried but was
completely bewildered! Can you tell me about IRC and how to use it?
</P>
<P>
   A: What's fascinating about the growth of the World Wide Web is
how it has overshadowed and even consumed other aspects of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a lot of newcomers to the online world think the Web is
the Net. But many of these other components still exist, and they
are just as useful.
</P>
<P>
   IRC stands for Internet Relay Chat, and it's very similar in the
way it looks and works to the chat rooms on America Online. But the
trick is that you have to connect to a server somewhere on the
Internet first before you can enter an IRC ``channel,'' the
equivalent of a chat room. This is like plugging into a switchboard
before you can place a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   There's another complicating factor. There are different IRC
networks, and each one has its own set of channels. For example,
there might be a channel called games on EFNet, another on DALnet
and a third on the Undernet. So, if you are trying to find someone,
or arrange a meeting with IRC, you will need to decide which
network to use.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've chosen a network, you'll need to pick a server. You
can find a server via the Web pages of the various networks, and a
good list of the networks is at NewIRCusers.com. (It's an excellent
place to get started if you're new to IRC.)
</P>
<P>
   In order to get online, you'll need software. Just as you needed
to get separate e-mail and Web browser software when you left AOL,
you'll also need a program _ called an IRC client _ to get onto
IRC.
</P>
<P>
   There are several good ones for both Windows and Macintosh
systems. One of the most popular for Windows is mIRC, available at
www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/Park/6000/index.html. Another chat
client, MSN Chat, comes with Microsoft's Internet Explorer 5.0.
Macintosh users can try Ircle at www.ircle.com or MacIRC at
www.macirc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've set up this software and pointed it at a server and
a network, it will display a list of channels to join. Most IRC
clients let you either double-click on a channel, or you can join
it by typing /join channelname, where channelname is the name of
the channel you want to join.
</P>
<P>
   If you can to create a channel that doesn't exist, just do a
/join channelname, where channelname is the name of a channel that
does not exist, and it will be created for you.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware that there is no global moderating service for IRC
channels, as there is for AOL's chat rooms. If someone does or says
something offensive online, you can complain to a channel's
operator _ if he or she is present. Some channel operators have set
up software-based moderators, called 'bots, that may watch for
offensive language or online behavior, but that's usually not the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've got Windows 98 on my computer and I was wondering if it
comes with any kind of FTP program or utility.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it does, but it's not one you'll want to use _ unless
you like text-based FTP programs, which are dismal.
</P>
<P>
   Bring up an MS-DOS window (there should be an MS-DOS Prompt icon
in your Programs folder off the Start Menu) and enter FTP sitename,
where ``sitename'' is the name of the FTP site you want. You'll see
that it's pretty primitive. Unlike a browser-based FTP connection,
you even have to login on your own.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet, if you'd rather not use a browser, is to grab a
shareware FTP program, such as CuteFTP (www.cuteftp.com) or WS-FTP
Pro (www.ipswitch.com). They are much easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-24-99 1643EDT &QL;
</P>
