<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO FOR CHINA IS A GOOD THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Trade specialists believe China's eventual entry
into the World Trade Organization will be good for the economies of
that country and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The expected boost in trade when China enters the WTO is rooted
in standardized rules binding the 134 member states, according to
Joe Harrison, president of the California Council for International
Trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When China is a member of the WTO, it must have a level
playing field in its domestic market for foreign companies,''
Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, that would mean greatly reduced tariffs for
California's important agricultural exports, said Ann Veneman, a
Sacramento lawyer and former Secretary of the California Department
of Foods and Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presently, China's tariffs on U.S. foodstuffs average 20 to 40
percent, compared to U.S. tariffs on imported food that stand at 5
percent,'' Veneman said.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO, established in 1994, has power to oversee trade
agreements, enforce trade laws and settle disputes between
countries over such issues as tariffs. China is the only major
economic power that is not a member of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   WTO rules would mandate a reduction in China's tariffs to an
average 17.5 percent by 2004, should China be admitted to the world
body at the WTO's November meeting in Seattle. No one on the panel
was willing to say that China's admission was certain.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison and Veneman were among the specialists who participated
in a panel discussion sponsored by the Commonwealth Club of
California. The meeting was called to focus on China and the
California economy. As the international trade lawyers and
businesspeople in attendance made clear, expansion of the
California's trade with China is closely linked to WTO membership.
</P>
<P>
   China, which has included Hong Kong since 1997, accounted for
$16 billion in two-way trade of merchandise for California alone in
1998, according to Harrison, who said the state exported $6 billion
in goods to China and imported $10 billion worth.
</P>
<P>
   A planned meeting between U.S. and Chinese trade officials on
China's entry into the trade organization was called off Tuesday
when China's lead negotiator did not attend the meeting in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be another meeting. We just haven't figured out the
logistics of when,'' U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky
said.
</P>
<P>
   China and the United States have been wrestling for years over
China's entry into the WTO. Negotiations have been stalled recently
in part by Beijing's anger over the U.S. bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade this spring, and political opposition in
Congress. Harrison described it as an ``absurd coalescence of the
Far Left and the Far Right voting against China.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, Beijing's centralized command economy
is loosening, creating opportunities for foreign and Chinese
entrepreneurs, said Robert Theleen. Theleen is chairman of
ChinaVest, a venture capital fund that owns 160 Domino's Pizza
outlets in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company deals much more with municipalities and the
private sector than with the national bureaucrats in Beijing,''
Theleen said.
</P>
<P>
   Standardization of intellectual property law in China is
crucial, given that high-tech and entertainment companies lose
billions each year to piracy, said Chinese-born intellectual
property lawyer Janie Fong.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of such rules, ``nontraditional enforcement, such
as inspectors dropping in on factories'' often works better than
lawsuits, Fong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
