<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTER-SCREENS-     09-29 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-SCREENS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA FIRES ITS ROUNDS IN THE FLAT-SCREEN WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBARA, Japan _ In the center of this verdant peninsula, just
east of Tokyo, is one of the world's largest computer-screen
factories, where hundreds of humming robots and uniformed workers
in clean rooms assemble 200,000 flat panels a month.
</P>
<P>
   The factory operates around the clock. Workers have taken no
vacations for more than a year. But they still cannot work fast
enough to feed the enormous appetite for the flat-panel screens,
used in computer notebooks, video games, communications terminals
and now, increasingly, in desktop monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are operating nonstop at full capacity, and we
have more orders than we can possibly fill,'' said Zenzo Tajima,
product manager for Hitachi Ltd.'s displays division, which expects
its sales of the flat screens, known as liquid crystal displays, or
LCDs, to more than double this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Business is booming for flat-screen manufacturers across Japan,
South Korea and Taiwan. The main reason is a surge in demand from
consumers and businesses around the world for personal computers
and other electronic devices that feature the flat screens, which
are increasingly appealing because they save space, look stylish
and are technologically capable of providing brilliant color images
and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the screens is so strong that Asian producers cannot
fill 10 percent to 20 percent of orders, industry analysts and
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake that struck Taiwan last Tuesday could worsen the
shortage if manufacturers based there cannot quickly restart
production. Power failures could delay screen-making assembly lines
on Taiwan for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Screen makers will see a huge jump in revenues this year,''
said David Mentley, a vice president at Stanford Resources Inc., a
market research firm in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that the sales of advanced flat screens used
in laptops and desk monitors will reach $11 billion this year, up
from $7 billion last year, and that sales could reach $15 billion
in 2000 and $17 billion in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   While the shortfall has been a boon to screen producers after
years of oversupply that depressed prices and profits, it has
created big headaches for computer makers like IBM, Dell Computer
and Toshiba, which are scrambling to satisfy the appetite of
customers for notebook computers and large desktop monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage has come at an awkward time. The back-to-school
buying season has been under way for weeks, and the year-end
holiday gift season is just a couple of months away. Many parents
and students are shopping for personal computers. Moreover,
companies are upgrading their computer equipment in advance of the
new millennium. Many want to get rid of the clunky cathode-ray tube
monitors that dominate their desk space and replace them with flat
screens.
</P>
<P>
   But computer industry analysts say that neither large nor small
customers are finding the discounts on notebooks and other computer
equipment that they encountered at this time last year. That partly
reflects the limited supplies of screens, which have helped push up
the prices that screen manufacturers are charging computer makers
by about 20 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers also find that they often cannot buy the machine they
want without a long wait.
</P>
<P>
   Adriana Maixner, a first-year MBA student at Babson College
outside Boston, said Dell Computer's representatives told her it
would take at least three weeks to ship a popular $2,800 laptop
model with a 14-inch screen. Dell, which helped pioneer direct
sales of computers to consumers, typically can ship an order within
five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they told me, that there's one supplier for the
entire industry for this size screen,'' Ms. Maixner, 26, said.
``And they said, `You're welcome to call anyone else, but you're
going to have the same problem anywhere.'''
</P>
<P>
   Neisha Frank, a spokeswoman for Dell Computer, acknowledged that
the shortage had forced the computer maker to extend its normal
lead time for product delivery. ``Some large corporate customers
cannot get what they want right away,'' Ms. Frank said. ``Yes, we
could be selling more if it were not for the LCD shortage, but
exactly how much more, who can say?''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, corporate customers are waiting several months
for delivery of popular models of computer notebooks and large
desktop monitors with advanced flat screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``All personal-computer makers are feeling the impact of this
shortage, because they can't make or sell as much product as they
would like,'' Masahiro Ono, a Tokyo-based analyst for Wahlberg
Securities, said. ``They also can't offer low discounts that
consumers like, because the companies are paying more for what used
to be an insignificant part of the computer _ the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM said that the company was experiencing record demand for its
Thinkpad notebooks and that despite the screen shortage, it was
meeting the needs of most long-term customers. New customers,
however, are facing delays, which the company declined to quantify.
</P>
<P>
   Rick McGee, an IBM vice president, said that because of the
shortage, IBM was paying 30 percent to 40 percent more for flat
screens but that the increase had not been passed on to consumers,
because the company had significantly reduced the cost of other
components in its computers.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. computer companies said the shortage had affected them
only slightly. ``We haven't had trouble getting a steady supply of
LCDs from our supplier, but it has been hard to get them at a good
price,'' Ray Aldrick, a spokesman for Hewlett-Packard Co., said.
``It used to be the processor was the most expensive part of a
personal computer, but now it's the flat panel display.''
</P>
<P>
   Gateway Inc., which recently introduced a desktop flat-panel
model, called Profile, said that it had encountered no difficulty
meeting demand for laptops or desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage in flat-screen production is partly rooted in
demand for larger screens in notebooks and desktop computers. At
the same time, Asian manufacturers, hurt by the region's severe
economic slump a few years ago, cannot increase production quickly,
because they failed to make necessary capital investments.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, responding to consumer requests for larger screens,
manufacturers shifted production of standard 12-inch displays to
13-, 14- and 15-inch screens. That reduced the number of screens
they could produce from the same raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in consumer tastes and the industry's seeming
inability to foresee it has also contributed to the shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers want bigger, finer-looking screens with brighter
colors and less battery power,'' said Aston Bridgman, a spokesman
for NEC Corp., which makes flat-panel screens. ``That's what's
driving this surge in demand for LCDs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many panel makers and industry analysts expect the shortage to
continue for another six months to a year, as worldwide demand for
computers continues to grow. Analysts, however, expect the shortage
to abate by the third quarter of 2000, when new factories begin
production. Eventually, supply will once again outweigh demand and
prices will drop, these analysts said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The industry shortage underscores how dependent the United
States is on Asia for flat-panel screens. While U.S. companies have
the basic technology to make them, they have been reluctant to
invest the hundreds of millions of dollars needed to build
large-scale factories.
</P>
<P>
   Japan accounts for about 63 percent of global production of the
flat-panel screens, while South Korea contributes 36 percent and
Taiwan about 1 percent, according to an industry study by ING
Barings Securities. The brokerage firm expects those percentages to
shift to 52 percent for Japan, 30 percent for Korea and 18 percent
for Taiwan next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``American computer companies had their chance to invest in LCD
manufacturing years ago, but they chose to let the Japanese and
Koreans duke it out, spending tens of millions of dollars on new
factories,'' Mentley of Stanford Research said. ``I don't think
that the LCD guys have a lot of sympathy for these computer
companies that have been squeezing them all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-27-99 2147EDT &QL;
</P>
