 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Cox Communications, Liberate Technologies agree on deal 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cable TV provider Cox Communications has inked a deal
with a software developer who will provide such interactive
services as online gaming and Internet access through the company's
digital set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is with Liberate Technologies, a software developer
based in San Carlos, Calif., that makes a product called the
Liberate Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Cox Communications plans to use Liberate's
technology to eventually offer a host of new interactive services.
But the company is still deciding exactly what applications to
offer, at what price and in what cities. It does plan to begin
testing the service by the middle of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is good news for another Atlanta-based company,
Scientific-Atlanta. It makes the digital network, called Explorer
2000, that will enable Liberate's technology to be used by Cox
Communications customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox is committed to bringing enhanced entertainment and
information services to its customers,'' says Tom Nagel, the
company's vice president of business development. ``Liberate's
open, customizable (sic) and highly advanced solution will allow us
to provide customers interactive features and services to enrich
their interactive television experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberate is no stranger to either Cox Communications or the
cable TV industry. The company has raised $50 million in financing
from Cox Communications, Comcast, MediaOne and other cable
operators.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors in Liberate include America Online, General
Instrument, Lucent Technologies, Nintendo and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   This investment has helped finance Liberate's development of
software that enables interactive services through the cable TV
industry's new digital cable networks. These networks are slowly
rolling out nationwide, including metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is the country's fifth largest cable TV
operator, with 6 million customers nationwide. While based in
Atlanta, the company's only Georgia system is in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
