 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Printing electronic postage stamps at home is an idea that might
stick 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someday soon, the conventional lick-it-and-stick-it-on postage
stamp may be as old-fashioned as the manual typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Several sites on the World Wide Web now allow you to buy U.S.
postage stamps online and print the stamps at home, either using
special printers or your regular inkjet. A lot of people think that
e-stamps, as they're called, will eventually become the routine way
to buy stamps. But for now, it's still an infant technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leaders in the online stamp business is a Web site
called E-Stamp at www.estamp.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the site explains and sells its service: ``With our
Internet Postage service you can buy and print your own postage,
right from your PC. No more trips to the post office. No more
waiting in lines.''
</P>
<P>
   To sign up with E-Stamp, you pay $50 for a little electronic
gadget E-Stamp calls a vault. That's where the electronic credits
for stamps are stored. You also get the software you need to print
the stamps, $25 worth of postage stamps, some mailing labels and a
CD that helps you find addresses and ZIP codes. After you've
started, you can buy more stamp credits from the Web site. You'll
pay what the company calls a ``convenience'' fee of 10 percent over
the face value of the stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The theory with E-Stamp and others is that you'll save money in
the long run because you can print out the right amount of postage
you need instead of just guessing and pasting on stamps until you
feel safe. The other advantage, which applies to all these
services, is the convenience of never running out of stamps (unless
you run out of money to buy more electronic stamps).
</P>
<P>
   The other big player in the electronic stamp arena is Pitney
Bowes (www.pitneybowes.com/). You've undoubtedly heard of that
company and probably associate it with the postage machines it has
sold to businesses for years.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the machines that allow businesses to print out
postage as they need it. In fact, these stand-alone postage
machines are the model for most Internet stamp services.
</P>
<P>
   Things are moving a little slow over at Pitney Bowes when it
comes to online postage. You won't find a mention of the service on
the home page. But if you click around enough (or just go to
www.pitneyworks.com/internetpostage/index.html), you'll find an
explanation of how Pitney Bowes is handling Internet postage.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get to the page, you'll find that the stamp program is
still in the beta test stage there. When checked last week, no new
beta test customers were being accepted. But, based on what the
page has to say about the program, it'll work very similar to the
E-Stamp program. You'll be able to print the stamps out with your
printer.
</P>
<P>
   Still another company offers online postage. That's Compaq, the
Houston-based manufacturer of personal computers. You can read
about the offer (which is identical to the E-Stamp offer, including
the 10 percent ``convenience'' fee) at
www.compaq.com/smb/onlineservices/postage.html. The reason, by the
way, that the two offers are identical is that if you press the
link to buy the Compaq service, you'll be whisked to the E-Stamp
page.
</P>
<P>
   SITES IN THIS ARTICLE:
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.estamp.com/
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.pitneyworks.com
</P>
<P>
   /internetpostage/index.html
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.compaq.com/smb
</P>
<P>
   /onlineservices/postage.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-28-99 1133EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
