<SLUG> BC-CPT-DELL-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Dell signs multi-billion dollar agreement with IBM 
By Jerry Mahoney  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp., continuing to expand its
offerings beyond the build-to-order personal computers that made
the company famous, said Monday it signed another multi-billion
agreement with IBM Corp. that will help Dell move up the computer
industry's food chain.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, the world's biggest computer company, will install and
maintain Dell equipment for government agencies, schools and major
corporate accounts in an alliance valued at $6 billion over seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate $16 billion pact announced in March that gives
Dell access to IBM components, Monday's deal adds up to the biggest
alliance in the industry's history, Dell Vice Chairman Kevin
Rollins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this as a strategic relationship that will continue to
evolve over time,'' Rollins said during a press conference in New
York. While Dell shows little desire to be Little Blue _ a smaller
version of IBM, _ the Round Rock-based company continues to add
products and services that broaden its appeal beyond the desktop
that launched its business in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Dell has announced a variety of programs _
from Internet access to an auction site for used computers and
accesssories to an online superstore of PC peripherals _ designed
to capture more of the consumer business.
</P>
<P>
   While Dell executives say those moves are a natural extension of
the company's contact with customers, they also provide continuing
revenue beyond the sale of a PC.
</P>
<P>
   What's pushing the changes at Dell _ and similar changes at
other PC makers _ is steadily declining prices for desktop
computers. Average PC prices are down about 13 percent from a year
ago, according to Forrester Research Inc., and after years of
growth, Forrester predicts consumer spending on PCs will begin to
decline next year.
</P>
<P>
   For all the attention focused recently on Dell's overtures to
consumers, the company is only No. 6 in the market, according to
another research company, International Data Corp. Consumers
account for only about 15 percent of Dell's sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they're ever going to succeed as much as they
would like to in the consumer space,'' said Forrester's Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement is a reminder that Dell's primary focus
remains large corporate, government and educational customers that
accounted for most of the $11.7 billion in sales during the first
two fiscal quarters. Sales of workstations, servers and
data-storage products used by businesses and other organizations
increased by 85 percent in the second quarter over the same quarter
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement surprised some industry analysts more than the
March deal because it means one IBM division will become a key
partner in Dell's efforts to win business that IBM's money-losing
PC division may also be bidding for. Even for a fast-changing
industry that is forcing former foes into strategic alliances, the
Dell-IBM agreement is unusual, said Eric Rocco, an analyst with
Dataquest Inc. in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a situation where Dell is using a neck-and-neck
competitor to do its service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell has similar service alliances with companies such as
GetronicsWang, Unisys Corp., NCR Corp. and BancTec, which provide
large Dell customers a range of services, from designing and
installing systems to offering simple repairs, known in the
industry as ``break-fix'' repairs.
</P>
<P>
   But with offices in 162 foreign cities, 131,000 employees and
22,000 field technicians, IBM significantly bolsters the services
that Dell can offer. Those services initially will be limited to
U.S. customers when the program is started in the first quarter of
next year, but they will expand overseas in subsequent months,
Rollins said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Senior Vice President Rosendo Parra said Monday that many
large customers indicated they would do more business with Dell if
they could get service from IBM. That created the dilemma of
forming a close linkage with someone that Dell regularly bids
against for corporate business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When customers first brought the companies together, it was
very awkward,'' Parra said. ``The thought was, here's one of our
competitors for hardware servicing our machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Monday's deal, IBM had to convince Dell that its
technicians wouldn't favor IBM PCs over Dell machines, Parra said.
</P>
<P>
   While Dell executives say computer services can be a $10 billion
business for the company in several years _ up from an estimated
$1.4 billion last year _ they have no plans to grow a large
computer-services organization. Dell's in-house service operation _
small by industry measures _ has only about 3,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dell executives point to Compaq Computer Corp.'s stumble this
spring as vindication for their strategy of partnering with
established service providers instead of acquiring them.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's problems, including staggering losses and the departure
earlier this year of its chief executive and a handful of other top
executives, are blamed in part on Compaq's inability to mesh
Digital Equipment Corp.'s culture with its own.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts nearly unanimously praised Compaq's decision to
purchase DEC in the months following the January 1998 announcement
because Digital had a worldwide services operation. At the time,
many pointedly warned that Dell risked falling behind its top
competitors unless it acquired a service provider such as Unisys or
what was then Wang Global.
</P>
<P>
   That advice is less common these days, as Dell has consistently
been the most profitable and fastest-growing PC company.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent meeting with analysts, Chief Executive Michael Dell
reiterated that he thinks his company can make money off the
burgeoning services industry _ expected to be a $500 billion market
by 2003 _ without a large in-house operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the sweet spot of profit opportunity for us is not
deploying arms and legs in a break-fix context,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-27-99 2159EDT &QL;
</P>
