<HEADLINE>
TYING ETHICS IN KNOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. _ I was at a fancy resort on Lake George,
at the annual meeting of the Business Council of New York. I'd just
moderated a panel discussion. Then somebody sent me to a booth at
the back of the conference building to pick up my bag of
complimentary gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The bags were just sitting there, one atop the other, bulging
with corporate golf shirts and pens and God knows what other
goodies. I was just going for mine when a tiny version of me,
dressed in a white robe and wearing a halo, popped up on my right
shoulder. I groaned. It was my pain-in-the-butt conscience.
</P>
<P>
   CONSCIENCE: Don't touch that! Don't even think about it. That's
graft.
</P>
<P>
   ME: Graft? Are you nuts? Everybody here gets one of those.
</P>
<P>
   CONSCIENCE: You're not a member of this group, are you? You
didn't pay a registration fee. You're a journalist, remember?
Journalists are not supposed to take stuff.
</P>
<P>
   I was just beginning to argue when another tiny version of me
popped up on my other shoulder. This one wore a bright red suit
with horns and a pitchfork. I recognized him instantly. His name is
Temptation. He drops by a lot, actually.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPTATION: Ah, don't be a jerk. You already turned your fee as
a moderator over to charity. You never touched the money. You won't
even get a freaking income tax deduction. Listen, you're in the
clear here. Besides, who'll ever know?
</P>
<P>
   CONSCIENCE: Don't listen to him! Has he ever given you any
advice you felt good about afterward?
</P>
<P>
   ME: Well, there was that time, before I was married, and ...
</P>
<P>
   CONSCIENCE: Don't even go there, Lynch. Just be a man and walk
away from that bag.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPTATION: Oh, get with the program. Everybody takes corporate
gifts. Just take a look at all those state legislators who got
wined and dined by Philip Morris, the tobacco conglomerate. The
Philip Morris lobbyist bought meals for Shelly Silver, the speaker
of the state Assembly. Also for Joe Bruno, the State Senate
majority leader. Meals were bought for Assemblyman Pat Casale, for
State Sen. Hugh Farley. Jim Seward, another state senator, also got
some good eats from Philip Morris. So did Assemblyman Ron
Canestrari. And you're sweating a lousy bag full of corporate
promotional items? What are you, a monk?
</P>
<P>
   ME: Hey, he's right, Conscience. Very few of our esteemed public
servants seem to harbor any reservations about taking corporate
gifts. So, why should I sweat it?
</P>
<P>
   CONSCIENCE: Oh, fine, terrific. So now the conduct of state
legislators is your standard of conduct, too. Isn't that wonderful?
You should be so proud of yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ME: Well ...
</P>
<P>
   TEMPTATION: Forget about it, Lynch. It wasn't just the state
legislators. How about Jim Natoli, Gov. George Pataki's director of
state operations, and his family? How about Rap Rappleyea, the head
of the New York state power authority? Philip Morris bought them
fancy meals, too. And you're sweating a windbreaker and a few
corporate memo pads?
</P>
<P>
   ME: Gee, I really don't know.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPTATION: Hey, look at it this way: Twice now, the governor
has made big, fancy trips to Hungary. He got into that Alex Haley
``Roots'' thing, I guess. And who paid for those trips? How about
the Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ME: Yeah? So?
</P>
<P>
   TEMPTATION: But who donated 30 grand to the chamber about the
time of those two trips? Philip Morris, that's who. And who'd never
given a nickel to that outfit before George Pataki decided to do
his ``Roots'' routine in Hungary? Philip Morris, that's who. And
you're sweating this little bag _ his little, tiny, insignificant
bag?
</P>
<P>
   ME: Conscience, you're right. I'm not taking this bag.
</P>
<P>
   CONSCIENCE: All right. Good for you, Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ME: Damn straight. I'm holding out for a trip to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
