<SLUG> BC-CPT-POWERUSER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Welcome to the new 'hood, and network 
By Gerry Yandel  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Normally, I hate moving.
</P>
<P>
   But this time it was different: I knew a computer network was
hidden in my walls, and it was just dying to be used.
</P>
<P>
   The Cat 5 cable snaking behind the Sheetrock all but screamed at
me while I puttered around, redistributing the contents of unpacked
boxes, shuffling furniture, hanging towel bars and installing
blinds.
</P>
<P>
   After a few weeks, when we could see parts of the floor between
the piles of belongings, I could contain myself no longer: I had to
test out my wiring and fire up the ethernet.
</P>
<P>
   Without really meaning to, I found myself standing in the
networking aisle of the local CompUSA debating quantity vs.
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Quality won out, in no small part because of the e-mails several
readers sent warning me against the perils of skimping on my NICs
and hub. So, even though they were twice _ and in some cases thrice
_ as much as other products, I stuck with 3Com and Intel for my
hardware, just as you all suggested.
</P>
<P>
   About $300 later, I walked out with a four-port Intel hub, a
3Com 10/100 NIC for my main machine and a 3Com LAN PC card _ which
was the real big-ticket item at $180 _ for the laptop.
</P>
<P>
   When I got home with the goodies, I had a simple plan: Wire up
the P166, take the laptop around to all the network jacks in the
house and check the connections.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I plan to set up a client-server network with a
proxy server to be able to share my Internet connection. But for my
tests I didn't need anything tricky or fancy. Both my machines use
Win95, and by all accounts setting up a peer-to-peer network was
supposed to be a snap.
</P>
<P>
   So I installed my NICs, plugged in the hub and promptly hit a
snag.
</P>
<P>
   I had no Network Neighborhood icon on my desktop.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those annoying icons Windows won't let you remove
from the desktop. So, earlier, I had used a program called TweakUI
to get rid of it almost as soon as I bought my trusty old P166 a
couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Once I restored the icon to its preordained place, the first
step was to make sure I had all the necessary clients, adapters and
protocols installed in my network settings.
</P>
<P>
   The Client for Microsoft Networks, Client for Netware Networks,
and file and printer sharing software was already installed by
default. There was also the dial-up adapter, which was put in when
I configured TCP/IP through Win95, and my new 3Com adapter was
listed as well.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Now to check the protocols.
</P>
<P>
   Small LANs like mine, which could have up to eight ports if Mrs.
Power User lets me put machines in the kitchen and dining room
(yeah, right), only really need to deal with three protocols in the
networking preferences: TCP/IP, for the Internet; IPX/SPX, used by
many games for speedy LAN play; and NetBUI for LAN file and printer
sharing.
</P>
<P>
   A TCP protocol was already set up for the dial-up adapter, and a
second TCP protocol appeared that was bound to my 3Com ethernet
card.
</P>
<P>
   Adding protocols is no more difficult than clicking on ``Add''
and finding them under the subsequent choices for Microsoft. There
can be some confusion when two protocols of each type appear in the
list, but one is for the dial-up adapter and one is for the NIC.
</P>
<P>
   The only real configuration needed is for the TCP/IP protocol,
which requires that each machine on the network have a unique IP
address, such as 10.0.0.1 for computer 1, 10.0.0.2 for computer 2,
etc. If your Internet service provider uses dynamic IP addressing,
which most of them do, you will want to leave the TCP bound to the
dial-up adapter alone and only specify IP addresses for the TCP
bound to your network card. (Also, make sure you don't enable file
sharing on your dial-up TCP protocol, which would open up your
drives _ and printer _ to the Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   Next, click the ``File and Print Sharing'' button and check the
box for sharing files. If you have a printer attached to the
machine, click the other box for printer sharing.
</P>
<P>
   The last step is to click the ``Identification'' tab to give the
machine a name and assign it to a work group, which should be the
same for all machines on a small network.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you will have to set up the network preferences for
each machine on your LAN, but that's part of the fun of being a
systems administrator, isn't it? Some more fun of being a sysadmin
is that Win95 makes you reboot every time you change anything in
your network preferences, which gets real annoying real quickly.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains is to go into Windows Explorer and right click
on each drive you want to share, give it a unique name and set the
sharing permissions to full access. Ditto for each printer.
</P>
<P>
   In my case, the whole process _ annoying reboots and testing all
my jacks notwithstanding _ took little over an hour. It would have
taken less except the laptop couldn't find my printer and I spent
20 minutes before I realized the printer wasn't on. (Hey, calling
this column Power User wasn't my idea.)
</P>
<P>
   Although file and print sharing is nice, the real reason for a
peer-to-peer home network is, of course, multiplayer gaming. (You
need a client-server setup with one machine as a proxy server to
share a modem on a LAN.)
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the first thing I did was to set up network
versions of some of my favorites: ``Quake II,'' ``Hexen II'' and
``Dungeon Keeper.''
</P>
<P>
   But my elation at my in-home game network was quickly snuffed
out ... when I realized the only multiplayer gaming I was going to
be doing was running between room to room making my Paladin punch
my Necromancer and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Because, I am sure Mrs. Power User would take a dim view of
recruiting our daughter Emily into a Hexen Deathmatch ... at least
until she turns 6.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-27-99 1144EDT &QL;
</P>
