<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LOOKING TRIMMER THESE DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Slowly, but surely, the Bruins' roster is coming into
much clearer focus.
</P>
<P>
   There were no surprises as the Bruins got down to 27 Tuesday,
and four more bodies must go by Friday to reach the NHL maximum of
23.
</P>
<P>
   Forwards Eric Nickulas, Andre Savage, and Jeff Zehr, plus
defenseman Elias Abrahamsson, joined Aaron Downey, Peter Ferraro,
Jay Henderson, Joel Prpic, and goalie Kay Whitmore on the road to
Providence. And goalie Andrew Raycroft returns to his junior team
in Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they just need a little more time before playing at
the NHL level,'' said Bruins assistant general manager Mike
O'Connell. ``They're just not ready yet. Guys like Prpic and
Nickulas, I think they both have a chance to play here, but just
not now.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how the roster shapes up currently:
</P>
<P>
   Goalies: Rob Tallas and John Grahame.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen: Ray Bourque, Hal Gill, Jonathan Girard, Kyle
McLaren, Brandon Smith, Don Sweeney, Mattias Timander, and Darren
Van Impe.
</P>
<P>
   Centers: Jason Allison, Shawn Bates, Mikko Eloranta, Marquis
Mathieu, Sean Pronger, and Joe Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Left wings: Dave Andreychuk, P.J. Axelsson, Ken Belanger, Joe
Hulbig, Antti Laaksonen, and Sergei Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
   Right wings: Anson Carter, Rob DiMaio, Steve Heinze, Cameron
Mann, and Landon Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   So, who goes? Who stays?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns has been using lines of
Allison-Carter-Andreychuk, Thornton-Heinze-Samsonov,
Eloranta-Axelsson-DiMaio, and Wilson-Belanger-Bates. That means
Pronger, Hulbig, and Mann could find themselves on the outside
looking in. Laaksonen, who sprained his ankle Saturday against
Buffalo, is likely to be sent down once he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   It's also likely that Girard, the Bruins' top pick (second
round, 48th overall) in the 1998 entry draft, will stick _ at least
for the first 10 games. If he plays more than that, it's counted as
a year against his contract. He started last year with the Bruins,
too, and played in three of eight games before being returned to
his junior team. That means Timander and Smith could be fighting it
out if Burns decides to keep three defense pairings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The word out of Harry Sinden's office regarding free agent
goalie Byron Dafoe is, well, there's no word. Dafoe said earlier
this week that he and his agent, Ron Salcer, were putting together
some sort of proposal to present to Sinden this week. As of
Tuesday, nothing had crossed Sinden's desk . . . Burns hasn't made
it official, but there's little doubt that Tallas will be between
the pipes when the Bruins open their 76th season Saturday against
Carolina at the FleetCenter. John Grahame, 37-9-1 last year at
Providence, will be his backup. Together, they combined for a 5-0-2
exhibition season record with a 1.82 goals-against average . . .
Hall of Famer Milt Schmidt has been named the Bruins' ``captain of
the millennium'' and will drop the ceremonial first puck Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
