<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-EXTREME-ATHLETES-2TAK     09-29 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTREME-ATHLETES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOKED ON THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER BONFANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a retired stunt man who has broken his back twice, it would
seem that Travis Tripp's days of living on, and off, the edge are
over. Better not tell that to Tripp. But the 32-year-old probably
wouldn't hear it anyway, hurtling downhill at 72 miles per hour on
an 8-foot-long board called a street luge. ``I'm totally addicted
to adrenaline,'' he says. ``I need a rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, extreme athletes of a similar ilk are getting
braver, bolder, and crazier. Extreme sports have taken on a whole
new degree of extremity, it seems, and today, ``extreme'' is what
used to be thought of as ``insane.'' Whether it's freeflying (a
speedier, less disciplined form of skydiving) or free soloing
(scaling mountains and icy ledges with no harnesses or ropes), why
do people take the risk?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not doing it for popularity or publicity,'' says
Jennifer Taylor, a sports psychologist. ``They do it to challenge
themselves physically and mentally to see if they can withstand the
pressure and . . . get in touch with who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes that risk their lives are masters of their crafts, with
exceptional mental and physical brawn, she adds. They push the
limits to test their skill. These sports, says Taylor, even provide
some with a spiritual sensation or an inner peace _ ``they're doing
something larger than themselves by meeting a challenge that other
people aren't up to.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor does find it difficult to justify the gamble these
athletes take with their lives. ``Part of me says that these people
are crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Extreme athletes test their mettle by jumping out of planes,
soaring off mountains, diving to the ocean floor, racing down
hills, and climbing rock faces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't skydiving extreme enough? Instead of falling through the
sky belly-first in the conventional manner, freeflyers fall head
first, or upright, or sideways _ or any other way they can think of
to achieve midair nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freeflying is whatever you want to do in the sky,'' says Jay
Moledzki, 26, a skydiving instructor at Airborne Adventures in
Northampton, Mass. ``It's about freedom of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   From altitudes of up to 14,000 feet, jumpers jettison themselves
from small propeller planes: in conventional skydiving, which
harnesses more air resistance, they fall for about 70 seconds at
speeds up to 120 miles per hour; in freeflying, jumpers reach
speeds up to 200 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my problems go away when I'm in freefall,'' says Jeff
Sherk, 31, skydiving instructor at Airborne Adventures, who
identified his problems as ``daily nuances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never happier than when I'm in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherk and Moledzki have more than 2,000 jumps each, a quarter of
which were in freeflying mode. ``I got tired of the discipline
involved in belly flying,'' says Moledzki.
</P>
<P>
   Maneuvering in freefall is no easy task, especially in the midst
of a 200-mile-an-hour dive. ``Everything is happening so fast, it's
a challenge,'' says Sherk. In 1998, according to the United States
Parachute Association, there were 47 skydiving deaths, or 1.44
deaths for every 100,000 jumps. (The association does not keep
separate statistics for freeflyers.)
</P>
<P>
   While they agree that freeflying is extreme, neither man sees it
as death-defying. ``Skydiving is perceived as dangerous, but it's a
lot safer than other sports,'' says Sherk. ``Hang gliding and
riding motorcycles scare me. I'll jump out of planes anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although hang gliding has become somewhat mainstream over the
last 25 years, a handful of extreme athletes _ or ``X-letes'' _
find their way to the summit of Mount Washington on the few days a
year when the weather permits to take an extreme sport to a higher
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nicolay, 46, director of Morningside Flight Park in
Charlestown, N.H., has flown off the ``Big W'' on a hang glider 20
times, the first instance in 1975, from the east side of the
mountain near the 6,288-foot summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scary place to launch from,'' says Nicolay. ``Your legs
shake, your arms shake, your mouth is dry, and everyone behind you
is telling you to hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The week around Labor Day is considered optimum launch time, he
says. The site is often too windy, which could send gliders into
the jagged rocks or onto the thick woods on the valley floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attraction is to emulate the birds,'' says Nicolay. ``It's
a solo experience, a person alone with the elements.'' During
placid flights when he has time to observe his surroundings, the
valley below him resembles the moon, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Niemi, 54, has flown off the ``Big W'' 34 times since
1974. ``Every single time, I get an adrenaline rush. It's the
tallest mountain in the area,'' he says. ``You know this mountain
means business, so you better mean business. It's very unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go for the fun, not to prove anything,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolay says, ``I realize that every time I get in the air, I
put my life at risk,'' but to him, the most extreme sport of all is
skydiving. ``They're a real wild bunch, them skydivers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the luxury liner Andrea Doria collided with the Stockholm
in July 1956 and sank 45 miles south of Nantucket, 52 passengers
died. Today, the toll continues to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Called the ``Mount Everest of dives,'' the 697-foot-long wreck
sits on its side 235 feet underwater and has become the ultimate
challenge for deep-water divers.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Chapski, 35, an electrical designer, has gone down eight
times. ``It's like space,'' he says. ``You're floating around where
few people have been, seeing a piece of history.''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, with strong currents and water temperatures
around the wreck in the mid-40s, divers use anchor lines off
chartered boats to guide them to the bottom. They wear dry suits
for the descent, which takes four minutes. It's complicated and
perilous, with divers breathing tri-mix, a combination of helium,
nitrogen, and oxygen (oxygen alone can becomes toxic at depths
below 200 feet). After 25 minutes of searching for artifacts, the
ascent takes up to an hour, with periodic decompression stops to
avoid air bubbles in the blood stream.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
