<HEADLINE>
UEFA CHAMPIONS CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Union des Associations Europeennes de Football always has
seemed to be a relatively benign organization. In theory, it is
among the five continental confederations that compose FIFA, the
world governing body of soccer.
</P>
<P>
   UEFA seemed to know its place, subservient to FIFA and
potentially subject to the demands of the powerful clubs it
ostensibly presided over. UEFA leaders seemed more symbolic figures
than hands-on dynamos. They allowed domestic competitions to run
themselves, and UEFA organized the European Cups and European
Championships, and collected a percentage from international
friendlies.
</P>
<P>
   But UEFA's hand has been forced in recent years, with the
emergence of a new breed of club owner and emergence of
television's influence. The threat of a European Super League
forced UEFA either to modify its competitions or cease to be even a
ceremonial factor. The stakes were increasing. Estimates of
soccer's value range as high as $500 billion, and 80 percent of the
game's money is invested in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The smiling suits of UEFA have adjusted, creating their answer
to a Super League _ the UEFA Champions League, which is attracting
huge interest, despite being a watered-down, ``decaffeinated''
version in the words of Johann Cruyff. Advertisers are paying $83
per thousand viewers for the Champions League, according to the
Sunday Independent, 12 times as much they pay for Formula One
racing.
</P>
<P>
   The Champions League is capitalizing on the novelty effect and
intriguing matchups such as Wednesday's Manchester United-Olympique
Marseille game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, UEFA seems poised to take on FIFA itself as the word
``friendly'' might no longer be a part of the UEFA vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Lennart Johansson, the UEFA president who was defeated by Sepp
Blatter for FIFA presidency, has proposed a competition for
European clubs that will eliminate ``friendly'' matches and also
end FIFA's proposal for a biennial World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before has football been as popular in Europe as it is
today,'' UEFA general secretary Gerhard Aigner said during a UEFA
conference in Geneva last week. ``This evolution has been taking
place for some 20 years, and the reasons for it lie not least in
the successful partnership with television as well as in the power
of attraction that football exercises like never before over the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless, the steep rise of club football has clearly
somewhat reduced the importance of the national teams. And no team
unites the interest of a country's people as much as the national
team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Competing influences
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona has been nicknamed ``Barcajax'' because of the
influence of former Ajax coach Louis Van Gaal and criticized
because the team's Dutch players outnumber Castellanos. But the
club still has a Spanish influence, exemplified by Dani Garcia, who
scored three times in a 4-1 victory over Real Betis as Barcelona
moved into first place in the Primeira Liga. Dani converted the
rebound of a blast by Rivaldo in the 43d minute to tie the score
and finished a pass from Sergi Barjuan two minutes later. Luis
Enrique and Dani scored in the fourth and fifth minutes of the
second half. Barcelona also leads Group B of the Champions League
but faces a difficult challenge from Arsenal . . . Practice might
be important for most players, but Romario apparently can excel
without it. Last week, Romario was fined for missing training by
Flamengo's director of football, Gilmar Rinaldi. But on Sunday,
after the intervention of club president Edmundo Santos Silva,
Romario was in the lineup against Vitoria and scored twice in a 5-2
victory. Flamengo is tied for first place with Corinthians with an
8-3-1 record in the Campeonato Brasileiro. Corinthians tied at
Recife, 0-0, and apparently has been struggling. Colombian
midfielder Freddy Rincon is suspended for a game after an
altercation with Palmeiras's Paulo Nunes and coach Luiz Felipe
Scolari. Palmeiras is in seventh place, 6 points out of first,
after a 1-1 tie with Santos. Paulo Rink set up Dodo for Santos's
goal in the eighth minute of the second half, and Evair tied the
score 12 minutes later . . . Brazilian professional leagues often
appear chaotic and poorly organized. There are 14,400 registered
players in Series A and B, plus another 400 a year who transfer
outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Honduras produces
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston aficionados probably appreciate Honduran soccer because
of the success of local amateur clubs, which sometimes included
players from the 1982 World Cup finals team. Honduras has not been
prominent in soccer lately but is still producing successful
players. Eduardo ``Balin'' Bennett missed a penalty, but set up a
goal as Argentinos Juniors upset River Plate, 2-0, in Argentina;
Milton ``Tyson'' Nunes is among the leading scorers in Uruguay;
Carlos Pavon Plummer, once a target of Revolution recruiting,
scored three goals as Atletico Celaya took a shocking 5-0 victory
over Chivas in Guadalajara; and Oscar David Suazo made his Serie A
debut with Cagliari in a 1-1 tie with Venezia in Italy. The Central
Americans who have had success in Serie A have been Julio Cesar
Dely Valdes of Panama and Hernan Medford of Costa Rica . . . The
first African to perform for a professional sports team in Boston
was Tewfik Abdallah, an inside right forward from Egypt who played
for Providence in the American Soccer League. Abdallah, nicknamed
``Toothpick,'' was in the starting lineup in the Boston
WonderWorkers home debut at the Walpole Street Grounds Sept. 13,
1924. Abdallah ``is a very aggressive player who uses the short
passing game and dashes into every play at top speed,'' according
to the Globe's George M. Collins. ``He is also a very deadly
shot.'' But Abdallah apparently missed a point-blank shot at an
open goal, ``sending the ball away over the tracks,'' as Boston
won, 2-1. Those were presumably more innocent times. Abdallah was
24 when he moved from International Sporting Club in Cairo to Derby
County in England in 1920. Lately, though, European clubs have been
exploiting much younger African talent and the alarm is being
sounded louder against this practice. ``FIFA has to introduce
something that will end the expropriation of young African soccer
players,'' Issa Hayatou, president of the Confederation Africaine
de Football, told a convention of player agents in Florence
recently. ``Agents take them for two lire, export them to Europe
with a tourist visa in a real trafficking of humans with the
illusion that they will play with a big club, then one is sold for
millions and they leave the others in the middle of a street.
Africa is being sacked without any recourse, the big agents make
dizzying profits, the system increases racism and soccer in general
loses.'' FIFA officials promised to make stricter regulations
during their convention in Las Vegas this week, held in conjunction
with the CONCACAF Champions Cup tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
