<SLUG> BC-KIOSK-BLUES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMED KIOSK SUFFERS OUT-OF-TOWN BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It's enough to make a hardened newshound
weep.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-Town News, the world-famous newsstand in the heart of
Harvard Square, packed with more than 3,000 different newspapers
and magazines from Africa to South America, is falling victim to an
era where readers are trading their ink-stained fingertips for
instant, fresh news on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   From the Los Angeles Times and Miami Herald to the Irish
Independent and Jerusalem Post, sales at the venerable purveyor of
international journalism are down as readers flinch at paying high
prices _ up to $9.95 for the Sydney Morning Herald, for example _
for newspapers, particularly foreign ones that are often a day or
two old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been a customer of Out-of-Town News for 25 years,''
said Carol Baroudi, the author of the popular ``Internet for
Dummies.'' ``But explain why I would go there for an international
newspaper, which is usually a day late and exorbitantly costly _
and get a ticket trying to park in Harvard Square _ when I can get
the news, current and for free,'' on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the explosion of online publications has cut
into Out-of-Town News' very reason for living _ hawking newspapers.
During World War I when the kiosk was in its infancy, its founders,
the Cohen family, sold newspapers at what is now the entrance to
the Harvard Square transit station, using a cigar box as a cash
register.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even though magazine sales are steady, the kiosk is having
to rely more on other things to make a buck such as candies,
souvenirs, paperbacks, lottery tickets, and film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even three weeks ago, I never thought I would be saying it,
but I now hear myself tell people, `Did you check the Internet?' ''
said Richard O'Connor, the kiosk's supervisor, wearing a blue,
cotton apron that recalled the old days of hawking newspapers on
city streets. ``We can't afford to just order one or two of
something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're a souvenir shop lately,'' added the kiosk's
assistant manager, Danielle Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Just four or five years ago, the kiosk had no problem selling
120 Sunday editions of the Los Angeles Times or 100 of the Miami
Herald, for example, to people who combed through real estate and
employment sections as they prepared to relocate, said Out-of-Town
News general manager Fred Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cohen lamented, he orders just 10 Los Angeles Times and
about eight Miami Herald's each week.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to give specific dollar figures, Cohen said that
since 1989 he has lost 60 percent of his newspaper retail income.
</P>
<P>
   Even The Boston Globe and The New York Times are not doing so
hot. Sales of those papers have dropped by 75 percent since the
early 1990s, he says, because of the Internet, increased home
deliveries and news boxes sprouting on more street corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom has just fallen out,'' Cohen said Tuesday. ``It is
a serious concern for us. I grew up in the business. I am oriented
to newspapers, and that is what makes me sad. We used to sell
thousands of Globes and New York Times every Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people, even college kids, who used to flock to Harvard
Square after classes to buy his newspapers, are now getting their
news from cable television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As for foreign newspapers, Cohen still enjoys a monopoly but it
may only be a matter of time, he said, before that market begins to
dry up. He still continues to order a steady number of foreign
papers because many are not on line _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That clock is ticking,'' he said. ``People just aren't willing
to pay. I mean, a London Sunday Times costs $7.95.''
</P>
<P>
   This past Monday, that day's Irish Independent newspaper and The
Jerusalem Post were already on line, whereas Out-of-Town News still
had Friday's editions of each on the stand for $3.25 and $4.50
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Ugo Della Croce, a professor and researcher from Italy working
at Harvard Medical School, said he used to regularly spend $2.50
for a copy of La Repubblica, one of Italy's national daily
newspapers. But that was the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it is on the Internet, I just take a quick look. It is
great for keeping up with the news,'' said Della Croce, 34, who
lives in Brighton. ``But if I want to read deeper, I prefer the
newspaper to bringing print-out sheets home.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, editors at international newspapers say their on-line
readership is exploding, although they also say they have seen
little change in their international sales.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem Post publisher Tom Rose, for example, said Tuesday
that his on-line readership is more than doubling each year, and
that the Post's web site gets an estimated 175,000 visitors each
day.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of ``our international edition remains flat,'' he said
in an electronic mail. ``We suspect two different classes of
readers: Younger ones on line, and older readers have the printed
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cohen said there is no danger that one of the
country's premier newspaper kiosks is in danger of closing, but
still he continues to struggle with ways to keep it from straying
too far from its beloved core mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I am here,'' Cohen said, ``I will always emphasize
the magazines and newspapers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
