<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-REBIRTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY BUY INTO A HARLEM REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Take a walk through Harlem on any work day, on
practically any block, and you see the signs of a community
lumbering back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Victorian brownstones, long abandoned and crumbling, are being
restored to their former luster. Art Deco apartment houses, wrecked
by defacement and neglect, are being gutted and rebuilt to a shine.
Trash-strewn lots are being cleared for construction of houses and
shops. Streets are being repaved, stoops resurfaced, cornices
replaced, cracks repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades have passed since the riots and recessions that
turned Harlem into a symbol of urban despair. Government
``renewal'' programs have done little but deepen the catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   But now, things seem to be changing. The romance of Harlem _ its
appeal as an African-American sanctuary _ never dimmed entirely.
This was where blacks first settled freely in great numbers, about
1910, where they formed elites, and nurtured artists _ Langston
Hughes, Duke Ellington, Jacob Lawrence, James Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects a rebirth of the Harlem Renaissance, but many are
talking about a revival of hope and normal life. It is happening
not just on West 125th Street, the celebrated strip where retailers
like Starbucks, Pathmark, and Blockbuster have laid down stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Less well-known but more dramatic, it is happening deep within,
on streets where people live.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are coming back to Harlem,'' said Karen Ansis,
properties manager for the New York Landmarks Conservancy, which
arranges financing for renovation. ``In many cases, it's people who
grew up here, moved away, and now want to live here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Harlem is changing so rapidly that some worry that it is
changing too rapidly, that, just as the economic boom is starting
to lift the fortunes of long-term residents, ``gentrification''
will price them out of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its outcome, the revival is happening for several
reasons:
</P>
<P>
   --The drop in the crime rate, which has been particularly
dramatic in Harlem (murders are down 81 percent from six years ago,
compared with 65 percent citywide).
</P>
<P>
   --The skyrocketing real-estate prices elsewhere in Manhattan
($400,000 buys a mansion in Harlem, but barely a one-bedroom condo
downtown).
</P>
<P>
   --A radical shift in thinking about urban policy, away from
arm's-length goverment aid and more toward hands-on private
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, in this predominantly Democratic city and even more
Democratic neighborhood, two Republicans helped set the stage for
this shift.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, shortly after being elected mayor, Rudolph W. Giuliani
decided to sell off buildings that the city government had
condemned and taken possession of long ago, but then did nothing to
maintain.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Governor George Pataki killed the Housing and
Urban Development Corp., a state agency that was created in the
1970s to funnel government dollars into Harlem but that ended up as
a power tool for Harlem's political bosses and their cronies.
</P>
<P>
   One former housing official described the bosses' set-up thus:
``These guys said, `Nothing gets done unless it gets done our way,
with our contractors, our pals.' So, nothing got done. These guys
singlehandedly set back housing and commercial development in
Harlem 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Kathryn Suggs, a top Harlem real-estate broker, said:
``When the city said, `Let's get rid of our housing stock,' and
then the HUDC was put out of its misery, the floodgates roared
open. Everything changed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, the number of city-owned properties in
Harlem has been slashed in half, from 12,161 to 6,265. In the past
two years, sales of private homes in Harlem have quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace Ford was one of Suggs's early clients. A corporate
lawyer at a Park Avenue firm, Ford bought and renovated a
dilapidated four-story house on West 144th Street in 1984, a full
decade before the boom.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, now 49, was born in Harlem, moved away as a child, went to
Dartmouth College and Harvard Law School, then decided to move
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered it culturally important, politically significant,
and socially comfortable to settle here,'' he said. ``You'd see a
different story in the development of Harlem if more Harvard Law
School graduates or Columbia Business School graduates wound up
living in Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, few black professionals of Ford's age find Harlem
alluring. But he does notice a huge wave of black _ and some white
_ professionals, in their 20s and 30s, heading his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see people moving to Harlem who, 10 years ago, would have
moved to New Jersey or Westchester County,'' Ford said. ``People
are coming with children.'' Ford married since arriving, and has a
2-year-old son. ``That creates a different kind of interest in the
community, a commitment to the future of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy and Jeffrey Ewing, black actors who live a few blocks from
Ford, moved here with their two daughters four years ago. At the
time, most of the neighboring houses were abandoned shells. Now,
they have all been bought and spruced up. The block association
petitioned the city to repave the sidewalks and plant trees. A pool
hall down the street, on West 143d and Broadway, was a big drug
hangout not long ago. The police shut it down, and the spot now
holds a nice new restaurant, one of several in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we moved here, friends thought we were crazy,'' said
Nancy Ewing. ``Now they come visit us, and they say, `Oh! This
looks nice!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not just rich and middle-class blacks are benefiting from the
resurgence. A half-mile southeast, on West 140th Street between
Frederick Douglass and Adam Clayton Powell boulevards, Mary Berry
lives on a block once dubbed the worst in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, nearly every building on the street was burned
out, on the verge of collapse, surrounded by hustlers and drug
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a terrible block,'' Berry said, sweeping the porch of
her apartment house. ``You couldn't sit out on your stoop, you
couldn't go down to the corner store, without being afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the buildings have been gutted, scoured, and restructured
into tidy one- to four-bedroom apartments, and residents can relax
outside all day.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation is the result of a private-public partnership
that lets local developers bid for city-owned buildings, then puts
the winners together with bankers, architects, and inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants who already live in these buildings pay no more than 30
percent of their income in rent; the rest is subsidized by the
city. New tenants can be charged more.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, tenants can take over the buildings themselves.
They each pay the city $250 _ and they own the apartment. (If they
sell it later, the city earns the capital gain.)
</P>
<P>
   In another program, developers buy city-owned brownstones for $1
each, then draw on neighborhood groups or brokers to market the
properties.
</P>
<P>
   John Cross bought 30 brownstones, all abandoned shells. He
priced them from $169,000 to $499,000, renovated them to each
buyer's desires, and sold them all in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Suggs was Cross's broker. ``We socked it to the buyers in
areas where prices were getting high anyway, and made them cheap in
places where they weren't,'' Suggs said. ``I had my vision of what
I want my neighborhood to look like. I want the mix of people to
stay the same _ private houses owned by people who have money,
right near apartments rented by people who don't, all riding
shoulder-to-shoulder on the subway. Harlem is going to get nice for
everybody, but it's not going to turn into SoHo.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone even to mention Harlem in the same breath as
fashionable downtown SoHo is a measure of how far things have come.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Wright, as Giuliani's housing commissioner, conceived of
many of the new policies, then chaired the Upper Manhattan
Empowerment Zone, which oversaw the area's retail development. She
is now president of Carver Savings Bank. Wright raises the same
issue as Suggs, but more as a question. ``The real tension now is:
How long will Harlem be economically diverse?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, a brownstone on Hamilton Heights, always one of
Harlem's grander areas, sold for $650,000. Similar sales followed,
and Suggs said one house is about to close for $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the bell, ringing away,'' Wright said. ``Pretty soon,
low-income housing could exist just as a balancing act,'' to keep
Harlem from becoming a land for yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Wright added, it is also possible that the advances
of the past few years could collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Harlem is a vast neighborhood and large chunks of it are still
barren or harrowing. Until a supermarket opened near his house this
year, Wallace Ford had to ride 30 blocks in a taxi to buy
groceries. Until a Dominos opened a few months ago, he could not
order pizza because no parlor would deliver to Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   This situation is changing, and it will keep changing because
more people like Ford will demand that it does. But these changes
take time and Wright wonders if Harlem will get the time it needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is pretty far out on the business cycle,'' she
said. ``Black or white, people with money aren't going to buy
houses unless they've got amenities in the neighborhood. And to get
enough of them, the business cycle has to last for a couple more
years. The question of the moment is: Will it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
