<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUMBLE, AND YOU'RE PUNISHED MERCILESSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stumble, and you're punished mercilessly
</P>
<P>
   It was just five months ago that we wrote a column marking the
day EMC Corp. edged longtime king of the hill Gillette Co. to
become the most valuable public company in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, EMC stock was worth a total of $72.3 billion,
according to data supplied by Bloomberg News. Gillette shares were
worth $40.1 billion, or about 45 percent less. If EMC stock
increased another $10 per share (it has in fact jumped more than
$11 in the last four weeks), EMC would be worth about double
Gillette's stock value.
</P>
<P>
   The startling stock trends affecting Boston-based Gillette, a
suddenly down-on-its-luck global consumer-product company, and EMC,
the data-storage powerhouse based in Hopkinton, say a great deal
about a broader market that swoons over technology and high-powered
earnings growth at the expense of practically all else.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction to glamorous tech giants, like Microsoft Corp.
and Cisco Systems Inc., seems so powerful that staggering stock
valuations are practically ignored. Stocks that thrive without a
sterling profit story are usually clustered among companies working
on the Internet, in telecommunications, or in biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   If you have been in most other stock market segments, too bad.
Among the broad losers of 1999: financials, utilities, health care,
and consumer staples.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, growth-oriented companies of any kind that stumble
are punished without mercy. Gillette stock, which lost $1 per share
Tuesday on another company warning of weak quarterly sales, is down
22.6 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many market analysts believe popular stocks have become so
expensive that investors must flock to an ever-shorter list of
companies with the most earnings power or prospects. And a fall
from grace is a long fall indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is chasing sources of assured earnings growth,''
said Jim Weiss, chief investment officer for equities at State
Street Research and Management in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the economy remains perfect, the market isn't
wildly overvalued,'' he said. ``When individual companies don't
live up to expectations, and that is the definition of the absence
of perfection, they get hit hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at a sampling of other struggling local stocks with
a value of at least $1 billion. There are lots of them.
</P>
<P>
   Keane Inc. (down 41.6 percent so far this year), American Tower
Corp. (down 32.3 percent), United Asset Management Inc. (down 32.2
percent), Staples Inc. (down 26.7 percent), and Harcourt General
Inc. (down 22.2 percent) have all been steamrolled because of some
disappointment or a perceived threat to their earnings power.
</P>
<P>
   The best local performers are overwhelmingly tech-oriented,
including Internet businesses (CMGI Inc. is up 267.8 percent and
Lycos Inc. is ahead by 73.8 percent), semiconductor companies
(Teradyne Inc., up 85.5 percent), and biotech entries (Biogen Inc.,
up 97 percent, and Millennium Pharmaceuticals, up 143.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the long-established investment strategy of
diversification is taking it on the chin. Mutual-fund portfolios
can look pretty pokey next to soaring tech stocks and the
explosions of Internet initial public stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is some frustration among mutual-fund
investors,'' said Cambridge-based investment adviser Marc O'Brien,
who directs his clients money mostly into funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A minority of clients are wondering why their accounts are
flat when they hear about how much money other people are making,''
he said. ``There's a disconnect between what people are reading in
the media and what they are experiencing in their portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only months ago that value-oriented stocks seemed to be
staging a comeback and investment managers hoped for a broadening
of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Returns at value funds that had taken a beating for several
years, like Vanguard Windsor, suddenly perked up. But the winds
shifted again when a market jittery over interest rates ran back to
a select few stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The average diversified US stock mutual fund had lost 5.7
percent for the third quarter, as of last week. Of 15 separate
stock fund categories, every one of them suffered some decline in
value during that period.
</P>
<P>
   But believers in a broader stock market, and a climate that
again embraces value investments, still think their day will come
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think the ingredients for a broadening into value are
there,'' said Steve Oristaglio, deputy head of investments at
Putnam Investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Value has really been about consolidating and restructuring.
We remain positive overall that these forces will ultimately find a
way into the stock market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
