<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, CLEVELAND STICKS BY ITS STRUGGLING TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All Chris Palmer has to do to realize he's not in New England
anymore is turn on his radio.
</P>
<P>
   The first-year head coach of the first-year Cleveland Browns has
a radio show on WMJI, the team's flagship station, and from time to
time he hears from listeners. But despite the Browns' 0-3 start,
which includes a 17-10 loss to the hated Former Cleveland Browns
(alias: Baltimore Ravens), not once has he heard anything like he
might have been bombarded with on WEEI in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   No ``Whaddya, outta ya mind wid dat call?'' Not a single charter
member of the whiner line saying, ``Get outta heah wid da
shotgun!'' Not even Butch from the Bowling Alley calling in to dub
him Palmer the Poodle or Chris the Crock.
</P>
<P>
   That stuff is reserved for men who coach in New England,
especially men who coach the Patriots. It is what Pete Carroll has
heard for three years and still hears from some corners even though
his team is 3-0 and leading the AFC East over the 2-0 Miami
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   While Carroll's ears turn red even when he wins, the coach of
the 0-3 Browns never has heard a discouraging word because the
skies are not cloudy all day in Ohio. At least not for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate to coach in Texas, Florida, and Northern
Ohio,'' Palmer said Tuesday from his office in Berea, Ohio, during
a break from his preparation of Sunday's game plan. ``Those are
hotbeds of high school and college football. They're places where
the fans are well-educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 0-3, and on the radio people are telling me to stick
with the young guys because they'll get better. The fans here have
been very reasonable. They understand the game here. They
understand the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the process has been a predictably slow one in which
his team was embarrassed on opening day by the Pittsburgh Steelers,
stymied by the Tennessee Titans a week later, and improved but
still fell 7 points short against the hated Ravens. Now he must
prepare for an undefeated team whose powerful offense he knows
well, too well to kid himself about what's probably coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Perkins (the Browns tight ends coach and former Patriots
offensive coordinator) and I were talking about them today,''
Palmer said of the Patriots. ``It's amazing that they only have 23
guys left from when we went to the Super Bowl, but that's the NFL
today. They still have seven of the 11 (offensive) starters,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us who went through the building stage there at
New England, we take pride in what they're doing. They're a mature
team that is playing excellent right now. I'm happy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Palmer, he probably is, but he's not so happy for his
own young team, which will try to match a very hot offense with its
own tepid pass rush, troubled secondary, oft-confused rookie
quarterback, and struggling offense.
</P>
<P>
   This game would seem to be a disaster in the making even under
the best of circumstances, but this week has been anything but that
because the first chinks in the wall of solidarity in Cleveland
have surfaced. After Sunday's loss in Baltimore, several young
Browns criticized Palmer's offensive approach. Wide receiver Leslie
Sheppard claimed his coaches were not making the necessary
adjustments to avoid predictability (where have we heard that
before?), and tackle Lomas Brown insisted that rookie quarterback
Tim Couch should not have been put in a shotgun formation on third
and 26 from the Browns' 13.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently, Sheppard forgot to mention the two passes he
dropped (including one on third down with the Browns trailing,
10-3) and Brown failed to point out that had his man, Peter
Boulware, not blown by him and flattened Couch, it would not have
caused the fumble that set up Baltimore's first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard said, ``Right now, we're not doing a good job of making
adjustments on what they're throwing at us.'' Asked if he was
saying Palmer's offense had become predictable, he replied, ``I
won't say that. I've got to watch what I say. You live and learn.
Sometimes you get in different places and you say different things
and they get twisted and turned. A better way to put it is we've
got to go out and execute better. I don't want to start
second-guessing his play-calling. He'll say, `Shep, catch that ball
on third down.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Apprised of this, Palmer laughed and said, ``I'll take the high
road on that. It's not a matter of adjustments as much as it is
execution. I think it's a good thing the players are frustrated
after a close loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure he does, as long as they keep their opinions to themselves.
When your offense is averaging 6.3 points a game after three weeks,
the only execution the players need to be concerned with is their
own if things don't improve. Yet in typically Northern Ohio
fashion, Palmer looked at his team Tuesday and saw progress, not
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Slow progress perhaps, but progress all the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're such a young team the guys are still just trying to find
their way out of the huddle,'' Palmer joked. ``I'd like things to
be a little bit better but I think things are playing out pretty
much the way we thought. We've improved each game on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, you want to do it overnight but you can't do all
the things we need to get done at once. If this was as easy as
A-B-C, we'd all have winning programs.''
</P>
<P>
   His point is painfully true. In an age of rampant parity (which
is mediocrity under a different name), the four teams that played
in the conference championships just eight months ago do not have
winning programs at the moment (a collective 1-11). So what did
they expect would happen in Cleveland three weeks into the Browns'
inaugural season?
</P>
<P>
   Pretty much what's happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot we've done that's been effective,''
fullback Marc Edwards said after the Ravens game. ``What is our
bread and butter? We haven't found that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us back to the critics of Palmer's play-calling.
When asked again how his internal critics could say a team is
predictable when its own players admit they don't know yet what
they do best, Palmer did what they do in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's predictable is that it's very tough to win in this
league,'' Palmer said. ``It's tough for everybody. It's tougher for
a young team like ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for him, people in Ohio with radios understand that.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
