<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-29 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO ERR IS HUMAN; TO RUN A CORRECTION IS JOURNALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Katherine Powers is in a terrible pickle. She is mired
in Correction Hell.
</P>
<P>
   It is, alas, a hell of her own making. A few weeks ago, in her
Sunday Globe book column, she wrote that the name of Magdalene
College, Cambridge, Mass., was correctly pronounced ``maudlin.'' A
grandee from the World's Greatest University (Harvard; more risible
than usual in this context) ``corrected'' Katherine. Letting slip
that he had studied at Oxford, this man proclaimed that it was
Magdalen College, Oxford, that pronounced its name strangely, not
its Cambridge counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine dutifully published a correction. And that was her
first mistake. Two Boston University toffs leaped to correct her
correction. ``Your corrector is incorrect,'' quoth old pal Chris
Ricks, correctly. So Katherine had to publish a second correction.
The names of both colleges are indeed pronounced ``maudlin.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kinsley, editor of Microsoft's on-line magazine Slate,
once wrote: ``We asked Bill Gates what should be done when people
complain about factual errors in Slate. His advice was `Have them
killed.' '' Good for Bill! I let a local bureaucrat ramrod an
inaccurate correction into my column a year ago, and believe me, I
haven't forgotten, Mr. Dunfey. (Or is it Dunphey?) On the other
hand, John Updike's film agent, Ken Sherman, whom I called ``Dan''
in a recent column, politely asked me to correct his name in a
future article. And I have.
</P>
<P>
   I am no stranger to the correction box. I don't know any
reporter who tries to make mistakes, or any editor who tolerates
them, but mistakes are made. I used to write a column called
``TGIW'' in addition to ``TGIF.'' After an embarrassing string of
miscues, one of my colleagues said the column initials stood for
This Guy Is Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an example of a mistake I made, and the consequences. I
wrote: ``There's a nice flap brewing at One Devonshire Place, the
32-story polished-steel monstrosity erected on the site of the old
Boston Globe plant.'' Apparently, this angered the building
management, because several days later, we published this helpful
note to our readers: ``CORRECTION: One Devonshire Place is not a
`32-story polished steel monstrosity' (TGIF, Sept. 9). The building
is 42 stories tall.''
</P>
<P>
   I am a pioneer in this field. While on leave from the Globe a
couple of years ago, I wrote an article for Slate that placed the
US-Canadian border at the 48th parallel. In fact, it is at the
49th. Now, in a digital medium like Slate, this kind of
typographical error could have been emended for all time with just
a few keystrokes. But instead of taking Bill Gates's advice and
having my critics executed, Kinsley wouldn't be denied ``the
opportunity for healthy self-flagellation that a correction notice
provides.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, my work is the subject of perhaps the first
cyber-correction in intergalactic history. Slate ``humbly
apologizes to all the United States citizens above the 48th
parallel, who we implied were living in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   So, you wonder: What is the Greatest Newspaper Error of All
Time? The Guardian of London had a habit of misspelling its own
name. To this day, it is mocked as the ``Grauniad'' by the
satirical weekly Private Eye. In 1990, The New York Times published
this doozie of a correction about former drug czar William Bennett
and US Representative Charles Rangel: ``It was Mr. Bennett who
called Mr. Rangel a `gasbag,' not the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week The Wall Street Journal, arguably the nation's
greatest newspaper (memo to file: write column on the adverb
``arguably,'' unwieldy synonym for ``not,'' as in: ``Titus
Andronicus, arguably Shakespeare's greatest play''), published a
grievous whopper. A front-page article about a softball team in
Weston, Mass. noted that the team, ``like the Boston Red Sox . . .
has never gone all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox of course won four World Series up to 1918, five
even, if you count the 1903 victory of their precursor team, the
Boston Pilgrims. The mistake will be corrected in Wednesday's
paper, according to a Journal spokesman. By way of an explanation,
he said: ``It has been so long since the Red Sox . . .'' But that's
when I put down the phone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
