<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0161 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-EXTREME-ATHLETES-2ND &LR;      09-29 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTREME-ATHLETES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... blood stream.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1981, Stan Bielenda, 63, has counted 12 Andrea Doria
diving deaths, including two this summer, and two off his own
charter diving boat in the 1980s. ``That's too many,'' he says.
Despite having certification, he says, divers are often too
inexperienced for this technical dive.
</P>
<P>
   One diver died of a massive embolism when he ran out of air at
50 feet and surfaced without decompressing. The other died of what
Bielenda calls ``china fever'' _ he got trapped in wires looking
for the ship's china. Bielenda estimates that 200,000 pieces of
china still lie in the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Chapski acknowledged that ``it's an extreme dive, absolutely.
It's physically strenuous.'' Yet the extreme sport he fears is
street luge _ ``I wouldn't do that!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wearing shoes with an inch of motorcycle-wheel tread as soles,
full-body leather suits, and helmets, street luge riders get set
and go. They careen down hills at speeds of up to 75 miles per
hour, shifting their body weight to turn and stop using only their
feet (the rubber platform shoes come in handy).
</P>
<P>
   At a recent practice session on a steep hill in Gilmanton, N.H.,
the Fire Department was on hand to control traffic and to offer aid
in the event of an accident. ``If you hit a tree at 70 miles per
hour going on that little board, chances are you're gonna need some
help,'' says Mark Wholey, a firefighter and emergency medical
technician.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Kayer, 36, co-founder of Subterfuge, a street luge store in
Loudon, N.H., says the sport evolved from skateboards about 20
years ago. Kayer has a metal plate in his knee from an accident in
which he also broke his right hand and chipped a bone in his left
hand. All this for hitting a bale of hay that served as a course
cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just a bunch of yahoos in the back yard,'' he says.
``No motor, no gas, no fumes. It's a pure sport in the sense of a
gravity sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Tripp, 32, co-founder of Subterfuge, competes
professionally. This year he hasn't placed lower than third in
seven meets and was the first New Englander to win a competition
out West.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Michael, 12, also competes. He doesn't worry about his
father because he knows he's in control and he's used to extreme
conditions. ``It's just normal for our family, I guess.'' Tripp,
who has bungee jumped, skydived, and jumped motorcycles, is a fan
of the extreme. But, he says, ``I wouldn't solo rock climb.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Synnott is someone who thrills in free-solo rock climbing
and ice climbing, which many athletes rate as possibly the
quintessential extreme sport.
</P>
<P>
   There are no ropes or harnesses in free soloing. There are few,
if any, second chances if someone slips climbing up rock or ice
faces. ``You can't fall,'' says Synnott, 29. ``Not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   A Wellesley, Mass. native who lives in Jackson, N.H., Synnott is
a member of The North Face climbing team. ``I think about
mortality, more than death. Everyone's going to die,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That inspires me to get the most out of my life, and these
adventures make my life better . . . I might as well really go for
it. I'm not banking on the afterlife. For me this is it, these are
my glory days.''
</P>
<P>
   Synnott has an 8-month-old son; his wife, Lauren, worries when
Mark free-solos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just drive myself crazy if I dwelled on it,'' she
says. ``If something were to happen to him, I'd want it to be
climbing, because that's just who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   He first began free soloing at 14, when he and a friend climbed
up 500 feet of a moderately difficult rock face. Most of his free
solos these days are on ice.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Synnott's climbing partner broke his back when he
plumetted 75 feet, bouncing off rocks and ledges on the way down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could die,'' he acknowledges, ``but I say `I'm not gonna,'
and I get this charge and grapple with it, hands-on. And prevail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
