<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-29 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE FOR BILL AND HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Responsibility President obviously feels no responsibility
to lead by example. In the twilight of his term and the sunrise of
his wife's candidacy for the Senate in New York, Bill and Hillary
Clinton needed a new address in the Empire State.
</P>
<P>
   They settled on a five-bedroom house in Chappaqua, N.Y. No one
expected Bill and Hillary to trade in the White House for a housing
project, but as they got deeper into the deal, it turns out they
were a little over their heads. The price was $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Owing $5 million to lawyers for the Whitewater and Monica
Lewinsky cases, Bill and Hillary apparently assumed that no bank
would give them a mortgage. If they were ordinary citizens, they
would be expected to pay down their debts. Or pick a less expensive
house. Or rent a pied-a-terre.
</P>
<P>
   But no, Bill and Hillary had to have this house. It was time to
go on welfare. They had $350,000 for the down payment. They needed
a mortgage for $1.35 million. They hit up their friends.
</P>
<P>
   According to published reports, they asked _ through indirect
means _ former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and former chiefs of
staff Erskine Bowles and Thomas McLarty to lend them the money.
Despite a reported combined net wealth of about a quarter of a
billion dollars, all three men turned Bill and Hillary down.
</P>
<P>
   The first family was stressed out. A source told The New York
Times: ``It weighed very heavily on Hillary. She was very worried
that they were going to lose the house. She was distraught.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, my. As if there were no other acceptable homes available in
woodsy, wealthy Westchester. This moment of self-absorption told a
lot about Bill and Hillary. This is the same first family that
boasts about kicking 6.5 million women off welfare, whether they
had decent paying jobs or not, whether they had decent housing or
not, whether they had decent meals or not.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, in boasting how the nation has cut the welfare
rolls almost by half, Bill said, ``Six and a half years ago, I
asked the American people to join me on a crusade to transform our
system of welfare into a system of work; to transform a system of
dependence into a system of independence.''
</P>
<P>
   A crusade it was. For six and a half years, Bill never missed a
chance to exploit perhaps the key issue that stole the centrist
candy from the Republicans. In 1994, Bill said, ``There's no
greater gap between mainstream American values and modern
government than we find in the welfare system. . . . For millions
and millions of people, the system is broken badly, and it
undermines the very values, work, family, and responsibility that
people need to put themselves back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Bill continued, ``I have always felt it was critically
important to fix our broken welfare system. It doesn't honor our
values of work and family and personal responsibility. . . .
Welfare reform must be about responsibility. . . . That way, we can
have a race to independence, not a race to the bottom. . . . It's
time to make responsibility a way of life. . . . Let's end the old
system that fosters dependence and let's give the American people a
new one based on independence, work, responsibility, and family.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Hillary ended the old system for low-income women with
uneven results. In some states, the welfare rules are so Draconian
that thousands of women were forced out of college _ the fastest
route to financial stability _ to take menial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first family, it's the same old system of finding
someone to enable their dependencies. Democratic fund-raiser Terry
McAuliffe agreed to guarantee the $1.35 million mortgage for the
first family. Charles Lewis, executive director of the Center for
Public Integrity, told the Times: ``This is a president who has
never had any compunction about going around with a tin cup. Most
people would have a very, very difficult time asking someone to
write a check for $1.3 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people would never think to ask in the first place. Most
Americans take their lumps while paying the bills and putting their
house on the line to secure home equity loans to send their
children to college. For six and a half years, Bill, the master of
the feel-your-pain handshake and hug, acted as if he felt this
angst. ``We have to change the welfare system so that it demands
the same responsibility already shouldered by millions and millions
of Americans who already get up every day, go to work, and struggle
to make ends meet and raise their children.''
</P>
<P>
   As we see Bill and Hillary pass around the tin cup, it is clear
that the medicine for low-income women was beneath them. Bad
publicity over McAuliffe's guarantee forced Bill and Hillary to try
to get a conventional loan. Buying a $1.7 million house is not the
same as being kicked off welfare for a $7-an-hour job. Still, it is
a chance for Bill and Hillary to make responsibility a way of life
not just for the poor _ but for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
