<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0167 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-29 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A LEAGUE OF HER OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in the commentary, ``k,'' and the sports, ``s,''
categories)  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For those trying to score tickets to the last
San Francisco Giants game at Candlestick Park on Thursday, Sherry
Davis has a question: ``Where were you on a cold Tuesday night
against Montreal?''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the Giants' biggest fan with the loudest yet gentlest
voice at Candlestick Park, also said, ``They could have gone this
past weekend. It was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that a big crowd is a better crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when we have a full house of 40,000 people it isn't
as good a crowd as when we have 8,000 people,'' she said. ``Some of
our best crowds are the small ones. Then you have the really
responsive fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who has been the Giants' home game announcer for seven
years, the only female announcer in Major League Baseball, has
never had much security in her job. Now that the Giants are moving
to Pacific Bell Park, her future is more uncertain than ever.
</P>
<P>
   This is a subject Davis doesn't talk about out of loyalty to the
Giants. She preferred to talk about Candlestick, and how it is that
anyone can be sentimental about the place.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of Candlestick in terms of home, where the plate has
been for four decades, and where the heart is.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you've made it and you're in this perfect environment of
a home, you start to miss the old home with holes in the roof,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where you grew up and your character was formed. You
achieved something. You have a sense of accomplishment, of having
lived through it, having persevered in it, and survived in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Candlestick, you definitely had to persevere, to earn a
badge of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentimentality is often written off as a cheap emotion, but at
Candlestick it is priceless and hard-earned.
</P>
<P>
   There are all the great players who have made their home on the
windy fields of Candlestick, guys like Joe Morgan and Willie Mays.
``On Sunday, I stood there and cried like a baby for the all-time
team,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   She also spoke proudly of the crowds that will never boo classy
former Giant Matt Williams, crowds that know how to appreciate
other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Well, she didn't mention the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Those night-game crowds of 8,000 knowledgeable fans always stuck
together, although perhaps the verb should be ``huddled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the one place where you want a really big person sitting
next to you to block the wind,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   She told me some of her only-in-Candlestick stories, such as the
time an umpire invoked the infield fly rule for a pop-up, but the
wind carried the ball so far that the infield fly was caught in the
deep outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time a sea gull was trying to fly against the
wind outside her booth, and deposited ``a foul pop-in,'' as she
called it, through the window and all over her program.
</P>
<P>
   The weather at Candlestick isn't so bad when you consider some
alternatives, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get rain in our area. I was in Chicago for the recent
series against the Cubs. One fan drove all the way from South
Dakota to a game, and it was rained out.''
</P>
<P>
   When I called Davis at home, she started to answer the phone by
saying, ``P.A. booth.'' That's how important her little
home-within-a-home inside Candlestick has been, a place where she
and a small crew coordinate music, scoreboards and Jumbotron video
like a live, unscripted accompaniment to (apologies to jazz) the
most beautiful of American art forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a couple of ballets that tried to capture
baseball,'' Davis said. ``They couldn't come close to capturing the
beauty of a double play.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something about her voice that irks a lot of fans.
Something feminine, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone doesn't like my announcing style, that's fine,''
Davis said. ``If you don't like me because I'm a woman, then you've
got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there are a lot of guys with problems who call
sports radio talk shows, guys who say they don't go out to the
ballpark to listen to women. Make that women as voices of
authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are 44 percent of the attendance,'' Davis said. ``If
there weren't women at the ballpark, there wouldn't be any baseball
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-29 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVELY CUISINE, BUT HOW TO EAT IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hazards of dining for a living would seem to be internal _
too much to eat leading to an expanding waistline or an upset
tummy. But lately the most frequent threats are not intestinal or
arterial, but sartorial. Food seems to be getting harder to handle,
and humiliation lurks for the awkward diner.
</P>
<P>
   Take the soup dilemma. Splashing is always the perilous part of
eating soup; one wants to sip the soup daintily without dots of the
liquid landing on one's shirt. (Dipping a tie into the soup is also
a danger for unfortunate males.) Usually, though, the risk can be
minimized by careful, slow manipulation of the spoon.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer I encountered soups with rafts _ tasty tidbits
forming little islands in the liquid. In one instance, clear, pale
green cucumber broth filled a large shallow bowl at 29 Newbury in
the Boston's Back Bay. Standing in it, adding to the eye appeal and
giving the cool broth a little heft, were two hollowed-out lengths
of cucumber filled with finely chopped tomatoes. Teensy watermelon
balls floated in the broth. Those were easy to scoop up, but the
cucumber towers were another matter. Too big to eat in one bite,
they weren't easily cut with a soupspoon either. In fact, a tower
fell over, creating a little fountain. In the end, the little
edifices were ignored, cute but a pain to try to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The morsels in the coconut dessert soup at Radius were too
enticing to leave behind _ miniature scoops of Thai basil ice cream
afloat on tuile cookie rafts. Sacrificing one's attire when the
soup splashed seemed a small price to pay for the haunting flavor
and scent of the basil. But I was thankful not to be dressed in
black that day.
</P>
<P>
   Soup's not the only hard-to-handle item in today's restaurants.
The current craze for height can create stacks of ingredients that
almost defy the diner to put fork to plate. This seems especially
true with appetizers _ but at least at the beginning of the meal,
the eater is still alert. That's a big advantage when deciding how
to approach an appetizer of fried tempura vegetables atop a
shredded mound of cucumbers at Atlantica in Cohasset. Chopsticks
would have helped here, since the thin curls of fried zucchini and
carrots skittered off the tines of the fork. The vegetables tasted
good, once they were wrassled into the mouth, but it was touch and
go for a bit.
</P>
<P>
   That was easy, though, compared to the napoleon, the latest
craze in stacking any sort of element. Last year, Amanda Hesser
wrote in The New York Times about napoleons fancifully constructed
of pastry and fruit, and those with layered meat and potatoes, and
rice wafers layered with peeky-toe crab salad. The Times, ever
thorough, ran an accompanying article describing exactly how to
plunge the fork into the napoleon so that it would stay intact and
not smoosh as each bite was taken.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenge, all right, to handle the implements just right
so you look elegantly knowledgeable while eating one of these
constructions. Perhaps it might be best to take the instructional
article along and read it aloud at table: First plunge the fork
straight down near a corner, then repeat at a slight angle to the
first, resisting the impulse to slant the tines, etc., etc., etc. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   No wonder chefs have begun to lower the bar a little, leaving
towers behind in favor of turban-like fabrications that often
involve complicated weaving patterns. Confronted with a salad that
looks like a bird's nest, the diner might be apprehensive. But
since the turban, or nest, or even a terrine, is usually two to
three stories, comparatively speaking, instead of a skyscraper,
it's much less obvious when the woven lettuces, or roasted
vegetables, or potato slices wrapped around fish start to
deconstruct. Just eat the scattered ingredients discreetly.
</P>
<P>
   None of this compares to the terror that Asian food can inspire.
You can take your embarrassing tales of swirling spaghetti that
refused to stay on the plate; your woeful stories of brittle-topped
desserts that shoot up into the light fixtures when you try to get
to the creme brulee; your sagas of struggling with boiled lobsters.
These don't hold a candle to the slithery ingredients of hotpots
and other Chinese delights.
</P>
<P>
   Successfully maneuvering chopsticks is one of those talents best
learned young, something I, like many Americans, neglected to do.
Although I can use them without disgracing myself, I watch my much
more proficient 13-year-old with envy. And no matter how
assiduously I practice, I can't figure out how to cut meat with
chopsticks. Of course, all around me at Chinatown restaurants,
Asian diners almost magically down chunks of pork or beef without
any trouble. I carefully watch and never see anyone struggling with
this, as the chopsticks fly back and forth across the dishes. Cold
jellyfish strands also present problems, akin to the spaghetti
dilemma, since the slightly bouncy strands often resist staying
firmly between the chopsticks. And those dumplings that spurt soup
when you bite into them take a special sort of grace under
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Simonds, who writes cookbooks on Asian food, explains that
if the food is in a bowl, ``it's a combination of a short distance
(to the mouth) and using the bowl to maneuver the food.'' Which
doesn't quite solve the large-bite question. A bigger mouth?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's sushi, a delight to the palate but a puzzle to the
awkward hand. You can eat sushi with your fingers _ it's perfectly
proper _ but to me it always seems to scream ``amateur.'' Holding a
curl of tuna over rice between the chopsticks is tricky, and woe to
you if you foolishly dip the rice into the soy-wasabi sauce,
instead of dipping the fish. Then you're left with drenched,
crumbled rice all over the table and a piece of fish in the
chopsticks. After a few times of ending up red-faced while others
stare, the fingers make obvious sense.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'm going to be huddled in Chinatown, trying to figure out a
dignified way to eat soup dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alison Arnett is the Globe's food critic.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
