<HEADER>
A0184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ENDANGERED-FLY-BOS &LR;      09-29 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDANGERED-FLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECTING A FLY MAY ENDANGER CALIFORNIA TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLTON, Calif. _ The scientists have packed up their gear. After
two years of sifting through the sand, field reports are being
readied. But word is already out in the desert east of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The fly lives.
</P>
<P>
   Putting an entomological twist to the NIMBY syndrome, some
people here had been half-hoping it was extinct, or at least not
breeding in their backyards anymore. To them, the Delhi Sands
flower-loving fly _ the only fly ever to make the endangered
species list _ has become an expensive, iridescent-eyed pest that
is threatening their economic survival.
</P>
<P>
   Barely an inch long, the fly has the full protection of the
federal government, which says the disappearing sand dunes that are
its only remaining habitat must be saved. The fly has also drawn
the full ire of local landowners and officials in five towns and
San Bernadino County. Its salvation, they say, has held up
development, cost jobs, and swamped them with debt.
</P>
<P>
   In the roughly six years since the fly was designated an
endangered species, construction projects worth hundreds of
millions of dollars have been stalled in the Inland Empire, as the
area about 60 miles east of Los Angeles is known. Single-family
homes and shopping centers have gone unbuilt. About $10 million was
spent to move the Arrowhead Regional Medical Center in Colton a few
feet after the fly was discovered nearby. The city of Fontana,
unable to collect taxes from developers who can't develop their
land, is set to default on about $46 million in bonds Oct. 1.
Officials say millions more in new development and new taxes may be
lost.
</P>
<P>
   All this, they complain, over a couple hundred insects at most,
according to a US Fish and Wildlife Service biologist.
</P>
<P>
   As Colton City Manager Henry Garcia put it, ``The appearance of
the fly has cost us big bucks. . . . There are no supporters for
the fly in the Inland Empire.''
</P>
<P>
   Even advocates for endangered species concede that winning
support for the Delhi Sands fly has not been easy. From the start,
its sentimental pull has been slight, more snail darter than
California condor.
</P>
<P>
   No one has printed T-shirts featuring the fast flier, which
looks more like a dragonfly than a housefly and lives but a week
after emerging from the sandy soil where its eggs are laid.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, someone might print a shirt featuring it in the
crosshairs. At a recent meeting, a local horse rancher lashed out
at wildlife service representives for choosing a fly over property
values and progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``People use the word `fly' in a derogatory sense, but it's a
very interesting creature,'' said Daniel Silver, coordinator with
the Endangered Habitats League in Los Angeles. ``It may be
important as a pollinator for plants we don't even know about. You
take away the fly, you take away the plants, you take away the
plants, you take away the animals. It's all connected. . . . But
it's not just the fly. It's the habitat. It's part of our
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the Inland Empire, locals seem more concerned with the
present. After years of negotiating with wildlife service
representatives, city officials say they don't have the money or
the resources to meet the agency's demand that they finance a
preserve for the Delhi Sands fly. This insect, they warn, could
bankrupt them all.
</P>
<P>
   The dunes, surrounded by freeways and residential spillover from
Los Angeles, do not come cheap _ and federal officials say they do
not have the money to purchase them.
</P>
<P>
   Land in the region goes for as much as $100,000 an acre, and the
federal government wants as many as 2,100 acres set aside for a fly
preserve. Buying the land outright would cost $220 million,
according to area officials. Rehabilitating and maintaining the
habitat could cost even more, they fear.
</P>
<P>
   The five cities and county facing the mandate have made a
counter offer of as much as 850 acres _ if the 280 acres proposed
for a preserve in Colton, ground zero for the Delhi Sands fly,
prove insufficient to rejuvenate the species.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say to the federal government, `Write us a check for $220
million and we're sure these property owners will sell you the
land,' '' said Ray Bragg, Fontana's redevelopment director. `` `If
you can't come up with the money, then take the fly off the
endangered species list because you aren't serious about trying to
preserve it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Jon Avery, a wildlife service biologist, stressed the
importance of salvaging the last remaining dunes system in the Los
Angeles basin. He noted that the fragile ecosystem is also home to
eight other species of insects found nowhere else and possibly to a
plant on the verge of extinction. He also said there are many ways
to fund the habitat, among them developer fees and so-called
mitigation banks that would allow developers to buy credits from
other property owners who cede their land to the habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of meetings, however, no solution that will save
the Delhi Sands fly and allow development to proceed appears
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot of folks are missing is that this fly is found
nowhere else in the world and that it's an ecosystem found nowhere
else in the world,'' said Avery. ``Every ecosystem has its
intrinsic value, and maybe we can't quite put a dollar vallue on
it. But every time one disappears, it's an indication that
something else is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong is clear to developers, many of them reluctant to
speak out for fear of riling the wildlife service and forcing
further delays. Their projects face costly, even ruinous delays;
federal regulations require area developers to conduct a two-year
survey proving their land is free of the fly.
</P>
<P>
   The survey for the Fontana Center, a proposed shopping mall in
Fontana that is now just overgrown ground, ended Monday. To the
owners' relief, not a single fly was found. City officials hope
that means something will be built and that some taxes will be
paid. The former owners refused to pay taxes after the fly halted
development, and the new owner has not paid either. Bragg said the
bill stands at about $19 million, including penalties and interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought the property knowing nothing about the fly problem,
and when we found out, we thought we could work out an equitable
solution,'' said Eric Scriven, vice president of Fontana Empire
Center, the land's would-be developer. ``We were hopeful. That was
a mistake in our thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver, of the Endangered Habitats League, lamented the
confrontational atmosphere in the Inland Empire and said he is
convinced that developers and the fly can not only coexist but
thrive. Otherwise, the Delhi Sands fly is likely to go the way of
the El Segundo fly, which succumbed when the soil where it grew
gave way to Los Angeles International Airport. California will have
lost something real but intangible.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Avery of the wildlife service emphasizes
preservation of the habitat, breeding flies would be pointless if
they have nowhere to lay eggs. The Delhi Sands fly once flourished
over 40 square miles in the Inland Empire, but entomologists have
so far been unable to breed it in captivity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, Colton's city manager, wonders if the federal government
is even interested in a compromise. He estimates that the stalemate
has cost Colton about $660 in economic development, as well as
idling a multimillion-dollar electrical substation built to support
the proposed commercial developments. The government, he added,
stands to lose nothing but time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their posture is obviously environmental filibustering,''
Garcia said. ``They don't have any money to buy the land. They
don't have any money to protect the land. They want us to do it for
them, but at what cost?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
