u i BC-MEXICO-MINING-BOS &LR;      09-29 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MINING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO SAID TO BE IGNORING MERCURY PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZACATECAS, Mexico _ Like a giant, well-preserved museum, this
arid central Mexican city prominently displays its Spanish colonial
relics with a distinctive 20th-century twist.
</P>
<P>
   The bull ring, Mexico's oldest, has been remolded into a
five-star hotel. The stately town market, which once drew chicken
and cheese vendors into its stone walls, now houses a spotless mall
where wines and Nikes are sold. And one of the city's oldest silver
mines is now the hot local disco.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spaniards' biggest leftover has become one of Mexico's
most serious environmental problems. Experts say thousands of tons
of mercury, imported to extract silver and gold from the hills,
have contaminated the soil and water at rates hundreds of times
above internationally accepted levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the contamination is there,'' said
Jose Castro Diaz, a biologist who specializes in toxic materials
for the government's National Ecology Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexican environmental and health officials, plagued by poor
record-keeping and inadequate resources, have failed to study the
area or its people comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
   Zacatecas illustrates Mexico's inability to keep its word on
urgent environmental matters, such as mercury, since the signing of
the sweeping North American Free Trade Agreement five years ago. As
part of NAFTA, Mexico pledged with the United States and Canada to
cut the amount of certain toxic substances such as DDT, PCBs,
chlordane, and mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the United States has halved its mercury emissions
through tougher detection and enforcement that has restricted
mercury use in everything from thermometers to coal-burning fuel
plants. Canada has sliced its emissions by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And Mexico? Its government says it doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   In Zacatecas, an area considered by many experts to contain the
heaviest concentration of mercury deposits left over from
colonial-era mining, the most thorough soil and water tests have
been conducted by foreign companies looking to invest here.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Some doctors blame the mercury for growing number of
illnesses, ranging from kidney infections to chronic bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern that Mexico hasn't conducted inventory studies
of its own, but it is a developing country that has to pick and
choose its priorities and may not be able to focus on this as
Canada and the US can,'' said Luke Trip, a Canadian environmental
official and chairman of a NAFTA task force studying the mercury
issue. ``The important thing now is to help the Mexicans build the
capacity to do a full-scale study.''
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian engineering firm found between 200 and 800 grams of
mercury per ton of soil outside Zacatecas around Lake Pedernalillo.
The accepted level of mercury adopted by the World Health
Organization is 1 gram per ton.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby farms use the lake's water to nurture corn, beans and
other vegetables for the area.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury is doing him in, former miner Rodolfo Garcia said. With
every delicate step he takes around his small cinderblock house, a
grimace of pain streaks across his wrinkled and unshaven face.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 53, has had two operations during the last year to
remove kidney stones that doctors said developed unusually quickly.
Another recent medical exam showed that his lungs are unusually
thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel older than I am,'' said Garcia, who has lost two
younger colleagues to similar ailments in the last two years. ``I
used to be strong and healthy, but now I can't even walk long
distances because it hurts too much and I run out of breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Mining is what created Zacatecas. The grassy hills in this
region were known to the Chichimeca Indians for their rich deposits
of gold, silver and nickel. Spaniards in search of the mythical El
Dorado, the golden city in the desert, colonized the city in the
1550s and continued clawing the area for precious metals. Zacatecas
soon became Mexico's dominant center for silver production,
accounting for as much as half of the country's output.
</P>
<P>
   To extract the gold and silver, the Spaniards used amalgated
mercury, which was imported by the ton from mines in Spain. It was
the process used for the next 400 years, even after the Mexicans
won their independence from the Spanish crown in 1821. The practice
finally was halted in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, officials must decide what to do with the residues that
have washed down the hills into nearby rivers, lakes and fields.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury, a naturally occurring toxic element usually found in
small amounts, can be converted into a highly toxic form through
mining. Mercury poisoning, which can happen through prolonged
exposure or consumption of contaminated fish and foods, can damage
human kidneys, livers and nervous systems and impair child
development.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mexican officials readily admit they lack enough funds
or technical know-how to thoroughly investigate the amount of
mercury contamination in Zacatecas, the government's passiveness
stands in contrast to its aggressive handling of lead poisoning
earlier this year in the northern city of Torreon.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, environmental workers descended on the city when a
local doctor revealed in April that hundreds of children had
dangerously high levels of lead in their blood. Government lawyers
immediately ordered the local mining company, Met-Mex Penoles S.A.
de C.V., to cut production in half and to pay for remediation
measures, including neighborhood sweeps and thousands of additional
medical exams.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Zacatecas case lacks an easily identifiable
culprit like a company, critics say the government has been
unwilling to accept responsibility for either removing the mercury
or providing health care to those who have been affected by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is simply minimizing the dangers because it's
not ready to handle a billion-dollar disaster, which is what we
have here,'' said Martin Sutti, a local miner who has worked with
the NAFTA task force on the Zacatecas issue. ``We have dozens of
cases of unexplained illnesses here and studies that show
contamination and our government has done nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Sutti held a government permit to dig for silver and
gold around the lake, but he lost the contract after failing to
pursuade foreign investors who balked at the higher costs that
would be involved in cleaning the contaminated sites. The area
around Pedernalillo is believed to have the highest concentration
of mercury in the entire Zacatecas area.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people have settled into this area, so the risk of
exposure is growing every day,'' added Sutti, 56, whose former wife
also has suffered from kidney problems.
</P>
<P>
   Zacatecas is not the only place that officials consider
potentially contaminated. Other heavy silver mining areas where
mercury was used for extraction include the state of Guanajuato,
Hidalgo and the southern city of Taxco.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is mercury the only potentially toxic material that must be
studied. Officials say tests for cadmium, lead and arsenic also are
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Castro and other Mexican officials say that once an action plan
has been drafted sometime over the next few months, they hope to
begin early stages of testing in Zacatecas. With help from the
NAFTA task force and other outside sources, they hope to have a
clearer national picture by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know where the sources of mercury are, we just don't have
the data yet,'' said Castro. ``We're trying to resolve a
400-year-old problem. Maybe we should set more realistic goals that
are different from the US and Canada, but we are starting to take
some measures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
