<HEADER>
A0221 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-PHYSICIANS-COURAGE-HN     09-29 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHYSICIANS-COURAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICING MEDICINE TAKES A DOSE OF COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA HAWES CLEVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Courage fascinates me. I want to try to
understand it, to have it.
</P>
<P>
   I read books about courage. And I read war stories. Not the ones
that describe terrain, battle lines, chain of command, troop
movements and regimental history, but the ones that show individual
grit and endurance, the ones that tell about someone who decided to
do a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust produced many stories of courage. Some were
written by Jews, such as Viktor Frankl and Elie Weisel, who
survived the death camps. Others had stories written about them,
such as the townspeople of Le Chambon, France, who saved Jews in
the very midst of the firestorm.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us feel we do not qualify to be included in a book about
courage. We have not put our lives on the line to save others.
</P>
<P>
   People who have done so can look back and say not only, ``I WAS
brave,'' but ``I AM brave.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the rest of us? Should a person get ``courage
credit'' for leaving a comfortable job for one with more challenge?
Or for standing up to a schoolyard bully or unfair boss? Or for
escaping an abusive relationship? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, most of my physician colleagues do not describe
themselves as courageous. The exceptions might include doctors who
track the Ebola virus or spend Saturday nights in hospital
emergency rooms caring for people with gang-inflicted injuries _
knowing that the emergency room might be invaded by other gang
members. They may think of themselves as courageous, and they are
right.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, courage is an everyday matter in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   I know one physician who cared for his two children and his wife
while she had chemotherapy. A cancer specialist, he continued his
practice during her treatment. Every day he saw patients with the
same diagnosis as his wife, many of whom were not doing well. He
wonders now how he made it through. I call him courageous.
</P>
<P>
   I know another physician who took care of his radiation therapy
patients at the same time he was receiving chemotherapy for his own
widespread cancer. He loved his patients and wanted to keep on
helping them. Love and courage are linked.
</P>
<P>
   I know three splendid physicians who were raised by psychotic
parents. One of the doctors now cares for her mother, along with
her responsibilities as department chair at a busy hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Is theirs a textbook definition of courage: to face a difficult
situation with bravery? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   I know a physician who trained and served in a violent part of
the world. Her hospital was attacked by security forces one night
and 68 colleagues were killed. She was away at the time but went
back to work as soon as she returned.
</P>
<P>
   Courage comes from the Latin ``cor,'' meaning heart. She has it.
</P>
<P>
   Her colleagues remark upon the quality of her smile and the way
it heals them. Heart, love and courage flow together.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I know a conscientious young physician who saw a
partner's patient in the emergency room one evening. Thorough
examination and testing did not reveal the cause of her difficulty.
There was nothing specific to treat.
</P>
<P>
   As she was leaving for home, the physician gave her his office,
beeper and home phone numbers and urged her to call if she got
worse. The patient agreed. She was brought in the next morning,
dead.
</P>
<P>
   As the physician told of this experience, he added, ``And I had
to see 23 patients in the clinic that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Crushed and burdened, he anticipated more burdens. Somehow, he
summoned the will to manage his devastation, harness his intellect
and practice good medicine for those 23 people despite his
heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Courage? As one colleague said, ``Courage is more everyday than
I realized.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Hawes Clever, M.D., is chairwoman of the Department of
Occupational Health at the California Pacific Medical Center in San
Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
