 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Crush '99'' by
wine writers Gerald Boyd and Janet Fletcher. This column updates
wine grape harvests throughout California until crush's end around
November.  
 CRUSH 99: Lower Quantity Yields Concentrated Fruit   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  After a cooler than normal summer and a late start
to the harvest, vintage 1999 is finally picking up around the west.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daryl Groom, executive vice president and winemaker for Geyser
Peak Winery, says that 1999 reds from Geyser Peak's Sonoma County
vineyards will be the best he's seen since coming to the winery in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   In Monterey County, Mirassou vineyards manager Mark Mirassou
says the 1999 wine grape harvest is producing ``lower yields but
intensely focused fruit.'' Mirassou says the winery's vineyards in
northern Monterey County are producing a lighter than usual crop,
allowing the vines to concentrate the remaining fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Chalone Wine Estates, with vineyards and wineries in California
and Washington, is predicting a  &LR; average to slightly less than
average yields and outstanding quality. Chalone Vineyard winemaker
Dan Karlsen reports riper fruit than normal at the Pinnacles
(Monterey County) estate, while Edna Valley Vineyard in San Luis
Obispo County is hoping for more warmer &LR;  weather to further ripen
the grapes.
</P>
<P>
   At Chalone's Canoe Ridge Vineyard in Washington, an average
yield is expected for Chardonnay, while most other varieties,
especially Merlot, is forecasted to produce a light crop. Similar
low-yield projections, especially for Cabernet Sauvignon and
Merlot, are expected from Staton Hills, Chalone's other Washington
winery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an uneven growing season, King Estate viticulture
director Brad Biehl believes grapes in Oregon vineyards will be
complex in flavor and aroma. He says that this kind of growing
pattern historically yields fruit with good flavors and color.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Livermore Valley, as wineries gear up to celebrate
the region's 150th grape harvest, growers and winemakers are
worried that the month-late start might push the harvest into fall
and the beginning of the rainy season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
