</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Sparklers Magnate Converts to Still   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Cordoniu, the Spanish sparkling wine giant, has
reinvented itself in California.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1991, Codorniu opened the doors to its California sparkling
wine facility, Codorniu Napa, in the rolling hills of the Carneros
region of Napa County. Earlier this month, Codorniu Napa morphed
into Artesa and in the process all but phased out the Codorniu Napa
sparkling wines. In their place the winery is producing six
remarkably good still wines under the Artesa label. Codorniu Napa
sparklers will remain in the market until 2002, when they will be
replaced by an ultra-premium sparkling wine called Joia.
</P>
<P>
   Transforming the winery and vineyards to Artesa, which means
``hand-crafted'' in Catalan, has taken three years and cost more
than $10 million. Artesa will be ``devoted to artisan winemaking,
hands-on crafting of small lots of wine from numerous
appellations,'' says winery president Michael Kenton.
</P>
<P>
   The first Artesa wines _ Napa Valley Sauvignon Blanc, Chardonnay
from Napa Valley and from Carneros and Pinot Noirs from Carneros,
Santa Barbara County and the Russian River Valley _ are all from
the 1997 vintage. Artesa's first release is 8,000 cases total, but
annual production is expected to reach 175,000 cases.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the quality of these initial wines, what is encouraging
is that Artesa did not fall into the trap of releasing debut wines
at $50 and above. The six new wines are priced at about $20 each,
although they will be available in many Bay Area wine stores and
restaurants, although not in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Artesa winemaker Don Van Staaveren, who made his name at Chateau
St. Jean, has redesigned the winery for small-lot production of
still wines and converted the vineyards over to grow Chardonnay and
Pinot Noir for still wines. His new wines are all about texture
while reflecting the specific characteristics of each appellation.
</P>
<P>
   Artesa 1997 Napa Valley Sauvignon Blanc is layered with smoky
oak, vanilla, spice and subtle grassy accents. The 1997 Carneros
Chardonnay is a full-blown barrel-fermented malolactic Chardonnay,
while the 1997 Napa Valley Chardonnay, with no malolactic, is more
citrus and crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Artesa's three juicy Pinot Noirs are from the three best Pinot
Noir regions in California. The 1997 Carneros Pinot Noir is spicy
with ripe black cherry and cranberry flavors, while the 1997
Russian River Valley Pinot Noir is more leathery with deep
cherry-berry flavors and boiled tea accents. Artesa 1997 Santa
Barbara County Pinot Noir is smoky, brooding and deeply flavored,
with good texture and length. For $60 or less for all three, wine
buyers can taste what California Pinot Noir is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Artesa has made an impressive debut in a highly competitive wine
market. If the company doesn't lose its way with too many wines at
higher prices, Artesa will be a brand to watch in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
