<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 AT THE SOURCE: Almond Time: Banner year for organic grower   By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 ESCALON, Calif. _  At John Lagier's fruit and nut ranch in Escalon,
the almond harvest is under way.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lagier's 36 acres of almond trees near this San Joaquin County
town are like a grain of sand on the beach when compared to the
480,000 acres planted throughout the state. But Lagier is an
industry leader, one of a growing number of almond farmers who are
trying to dramatically reduce the use of pesticides or, as in
Lagier's case, to farm organically.
</P>
<P>
   Almonds are a billion-dollar crop in California, comparable to
lettuce in value. The nuts are also one of the top consumers of
pesticides. To prevent fungal diseases in the spring and worm
damage later, many growers use preventive sprays, Lagier says.
</P>
<P>
   He takes another approach. After harvest, he applies compost to
the orchard. Then he plants a cover crop to provide a habitat for
beneficial insects. The cover crop, which he mows down gradually
over the growing season, also replenishes the soil by fixing
atmospheric nitrogen in its roots.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fungicides, Lagier sprays the leaves with compost
tea, made by filtering water through compost. The idea is to
blanket the trees with good microorganisms that can out-compete the
bad ones. ``It's not scientific,'' the farmer acknowledges, but it
appears to work.
</P>
<P>
   So why don't more almond growers farm organically? Because it's
a lot easier not to, Lagier says, and because their yields would
drop. He and other almond growers practicing sustainable
agriculture have to make up for their lower yield with higher
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Lagier Ranch orchard includes the main commercial almond
variety, the Nonpareil, as well as two other varieties needed for
cross-pollination. The trees bloom in late February in a fragrant
carpet of white, then mature their fruit over the next seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   By late September or early October, the almond hulls have
started to split and the nuts drop easily with a shake of the
branch. That means it's harvest time. A machine shakes the mature
almonds onto the orchard floor, a mechanical sweeper gathers them
into a row, and a mechanical harvester picks them up. Then they are
carted off to a processor to be hulled and shelled.
</P>
<P>
   The best almonds are large and plump, with no shriveling, the
grower says. Their skin is unscratched and neither bleached-looking
nor darkened. And of course they taste good, with no off flavors
that might be the result of poor storage. Almonds hold well in cold
storage, but because of their high oil content they can oxidize or
absorb flavors from other foods if improperly stored. At home,
Lagier keeps his nuts in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   This year's California almond harvest is projected to set a
record at 830 million pounds. Increased acreage, improved growing
practices and good weather have all contributed to the banner year.
Lagier expects a large crop, too, and says he may drop his $6 a
pound price at San Francisco's Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market when he
begins selling his new almonds in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
