<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 BEST WAY: Scrambled Eggs  By Nicholas Bundy 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; How do you like your scrambled eggs _ fluffy,
creamy or runny?
<P>
   What about dry and firm, with a touch of water? Or how about
with milk, half-and-half _ or nothing?
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle food department tested _ and tasted _ more than a
dozen batches of scrambled eggs for best texture and seasoning.
Each batch contained two extra-large eggs beaten with a wire whisk
with a dash of salt and pepper, and one tablespoon of either
half-and-half, 2 percent low-fat milk or water. Each batch was
cooked over medium to high heat for one to 11/2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT TO ADD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Department tasters preferred the eggs mixed with one tablespoon
half-and-half, describing the texture as moist and creamy while
delivering a slightly sweet aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   The eggs with 2 percent milk disappointed, yielding a watery
taste with little or no texture. Eggs with water added tasted fine,
but were stiff and rubbery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HOW MUCH TO ADD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After determining that we preferred eggs mixed with
half-and-half for texture, we varied the amount, making four
batches of eggs, using one, two, three or four tablespoons of
half-and-half.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was a tie. Department tasters divided evenly between
those who preferred eggs made with two tablespoons half-and-half
and with three blespoons half-and-half.
</P>
<P>
   The eggs with four tablespoons half-and-half developed
absolutely no consistency, took much too long to coagulate, and
left a crusty mess in our nonstick pan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   We found that two extra-large eggs scrambled with two
tablespoons half-and-half made for a light, creamy texture and
pleasant balance of flavor. Three tablespoons half-and-half made
for a richer consistency and more texture. But we also agreed that
when it comes to the best texture for scrambled eggs, much depends
on personal preference.
</P>
<P>
   As for when is the best time to add salt and pepper, the eggs
that were seasoned both before  &LR; and &LR;  after cooking had the most
complete and rounded flavor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      09-29 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute
Recipe takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast and
Fresh. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: A Little Creativity Produces 3 Ethnic-Inspired 
 Dishes   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  It can be very satisfying to set aside a day or
two to prepare a complicated, traditional recipe. Through the hours
spent following elaborate procedures, you get a sense of the skill
that has gone into making the recipe for generations _ and the
result is usually well-worth your toil.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But cooking can't always be an all-day, back-breaking affair. If
you're on a tight schedule, you often need to find creative ways to
build complex flavors.
</P>
<P>
   This week's Now &AMP; Later recipe, Polenta Pie with Pork in Salsa
Verde, derives from a Oaxacan specialty, green mole with stewed
pork. The traditional recipe calls for roasting and grinding
spices, mincing fresh herbs like cilantro and epazote, and roasting
and peeling chiles, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly as intricate as the classic Mexican dish, this
version of pork in green chile sauce simply mirrors some of the
same flavors with fresh salsa verde, a tomatillo and green chile
sauce. Though very acidic when fresh, the salsa mellows into a
flavorful sauce when stewed slowly with aromatic vegetables, pork
and stock.
</P>
<P>
   This stew is layered on top of a base of roasted polenta. The
final product, which is topped with sour cream and queso fresco, is
something like a chile verde casserole _ a delicious culinary
hybrid that works great in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, some techniques, such as Chinese stir-fry, are
traditionally fast and simple. The Fast&AMP;Fresh recipe this week,
Beef and Spinach Stir-Fry with Oyster Sauce, will be done in the
time it takes to steam rice. Simple dishes flavored with oyster
sauce are common in Cantonese cooking, which relies not so much on
spice but on the quality of fresh ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   The trick in stir-frying is not to overcook the meat. In this
recipe, the spinach is cooked separately so the liquid it releases
does not make the meat chewy. In the end, the two are brought
together with sizzling garlic and oyster sauce, a thick, savory
sauce flavored with oyster extracts.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-Minute Main Dish, Linguine with Vermouth and
Orange-Scented Shrimp, pairs intriguing sweet and savory flavors.
Fresh basil and orange zest brighten the sweet rock shrimp, and the
rich creamy pasta sauce gets a kick from vermouth and lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   BEEF &AMP; SPINACH STIR-FRY WITH OYSTER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound flank steak
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) bag cleaned baby spinach
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons oyster sauce (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Sesame seeds (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the flank steak flat on a work surface and cut it along
the grain into 2 or 3 long, 3-inch wide sections. Take one section
and cut it with a very sharp knife, this time against the grain, as
thinly as you can. The slices should be less than 1/8-inch thick.
Repeat with the remaining sections of steak. Season the meat slices
with a generous amount of pepper; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place a wok or large skillet over high heat. When hot, add 1
teaspoon of the oil and heat until sizzling. Add half of the garlic
and cook it until slightly browned, 1 to 2 minutes. Add a few
handfuls of spinach to the pan and stir over the heat. As the
spinach wilts, keep adding more, stirring constantly until it has
all wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Drain off the liquid from the spinach and remove the spinach
from the pan. Squeeze out as much liquid as possible with your
hands, then place the spinach on a pile of paper towels to absorb
more liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining teaspoon of oil to the pan; when hot add the
remaining garlic and cook, stirring until slightly browned. Add the
reserved meat and saute quickly, stirring often, until the meat is
just browned, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Return the spinach to the pan. Stir in the oyster sauce, season
with pepper and heat through.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with rice and garnish with sesame seeds, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Oyster sauce is available in most supermarkets. Lee Kum
Kee's Premium Oyster Sauce _ look for the label picturing a boy and
girl in a boat _ has the best flavor and is available at Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 240 calories, &LR;   &LR; 23 g protein, 1 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 13 g fat (5 g saturated), 57 mg cholesterol, 929 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   LINGUINE WITH VERMOUTH &AMP; ORANGE-SCENTED SHRIMP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds rock shrimp or medium shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   10 basil leaves, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1 pound linguine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vermouth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken stock or low-salt broth
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Basil sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Start bringing a large pot of salted water to a boil for the
pasta while you prep the other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil over medium heat in a large skillet. Add the
garlic and cook for 1 minute. Add the shrimp, basil and orange zest
and cook just until the shrimp turn pink, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the shrimp mixture from the pan. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   When the pasta water is boiling, add the pasta and cook until al
dente. Drain and return to the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Deglaze the skillet with vermouth, chicken stock and lemon
juice, then cook for 3 minutes over high heat. Add the cream and
heat through. Whisk in the butter and season with salt and pepper.
Add this sauce to the pot of cooked pasta and stir over low heat
until incorporated, about 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Portion the pasta onto serving plates and top with the shrimp.
Garnish each serving with a sprig of basil.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 880 calories, &LR;   &LR; 45 g protein, 92 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 30 g fat (12 g saturated), 325 mg cholesterol, 381
mg sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   POLENTA PIE WITH PORK IN SALSA VERDE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Pork &AMP; Salsa Verde
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds boneless pork butt or shoulder, cut into 3/4-inch
cubes, fat trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   About 6 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large red onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   8 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 serrano chiles, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried oregano leaves, crumbled (Mexican oregano
preferred)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 pints fresh salsa verde (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated queso fresco (see note)
</P>
<P>
   The Polenta
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups polenta
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano leaves, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated queso fresco
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pork in Salsa Verde:  &LR; Season the pork with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place a large, heavy-bottomed stock pot over medium-high heat.
When quite hot, add enough of the oil to completely cover the
bottom of the pot. Heat until almost smoking. Taking care not to
get splattered, add the pork in batches. Do not crowd the pan or
the meat will stew instead of fry. Brown the pork for a few minutes
on one side, then stir and brown again. Do not stir frequently or
the meat will not reach a golden-brown color. When the meat has
browned on both sides, remove from the pan with a slotted spoon;
set aside. Repeat with the remaining pork, adding more oil if
necessary, until all of the meat has been browned; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add the onion to the pan and saute in any remaining oil for a
few minutes until tender. Scrape the bottom of the pan with a
wooden spoon to dislodge any browned bits of pork. Add the garlic,
chiles and oregano and saute for 2 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Return the pork to the pan. Add the chicken broth and the salsa.
Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer uncovered until the
meat is very tender, about 1 hour and 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   During cooking, keep an eye on the level of liquid. If the meat
is not submerged, add water.
</P>
<P>
   When the pork is tender, season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the Polenta:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Combine the
water, cream and salt in a small saucepan and heat until almost
boiling.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the polenta, oregano and cheese in a large mixing bowl;
stir until combined. Stir in the hot liquid, making sure to
incorporate all of the ingredients and smooth out any lumps. Pour
evenly into two 13 x 9-inch baking pans.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 10 minutes. Stir, then bake 25 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees. Ladle the stewed pork
over the polenta. Dot with the sour cream, top with shredded queso
fresco and bake for 20 minutes, until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Notes:  &LR; Fresh salsa verde is becoming widely available at
supermarkets and specialty stores, along with fresh tomato salsa.
If unavailable, look for jarred tomatillo or green chile salsa,
available at Trader Joe's and in the Hispanic sections of some
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Queso fresco, a salty white cheese, also is available in many
supermarkets. It usually comes in 12-ounce rounds, just the right
amount for this recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 570 calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 29 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 38 g fat (17 g saturated), 141 mg cholesterol, 603
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
