<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0244 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-PASTA-SFCHRON &LR;      09-29 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-PASTA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Albona Beefs Up Chifeleti   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Bruno Viscovi's grandmother prepared chifeleti,
which he characterizes as a type of gnocchi, when he was growing up
in Albona on the Istrian Peninsula in Italy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Viscovi opened Albona Ristorante Istriano near North Beach,
he put this childhood favorite on the menu, accompanied by beef
sirloin sauce flavored with cumin.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful dish, with the golden brown gnocchi playing off
the rich, meaty sauce. However, Viscovi notes that it's an arduous
task preparing the sauce in small amount needed for the gnocchi so
he increased the amount in order to have enough leftover for other
uses. It's ideal as a topping for pasta with fresh gratings of
Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Albona is the only restaurant on the West Coast specializing in
the cuisine from this little-known Italian region, with influences
from Austria, Hungary, Croatia and Turkey. The combinations are
hearty, often featuring the unexpected sweet spices such as nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   Viscovi's unique food is served in a warm environment with
accents of mahogany and beveled glass. And one of the biggest
treats of all is that Viscovi is usually in the dining room, always
willing to weave a romantic tale of his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Albona Ristorante Istriano, 545 Francisco St. (near Taylor), &LR; 
 &LR; San Francisco; (415) 441-1040. Open for dinner &LR; 
 &LR; Tuesday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _  &UR; Frying the gnocchi &LR; . Bruno Viscovi says he's never seen this
technique used anywhere else; it was something his grandmother did.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The sauce. &LR;  Adding porcini powder, red wine, a little tomato
sauce and crushed red pepper flakes gives a complex depth of
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ALBONA'S PAN-FRIED GNOCCHI WITH SIRLOIN SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   The Gnocchi
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds large russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 quart vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds beef sirloin, trimmed and cut into 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled and finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 celery stalk, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   Bouquet garni: 2 springs each, fresh oregano, thyme, rosemary,
marjoram, bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon porcini mushroom powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 quart beef stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the gnocchi:  &LR; Place the unpeeled potatoes in a large
pot with enough cold water to cover. Bring to a boil, reduce heat
and simmer 45 minutes, or until easily pierced with a fork. Drain
and peel in a towel while still hot. Pass through a potato ricer
and spread onto a lightly floured surface. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Sift 13/4 cups of the flour over the potatoes and sprinkle with
the salt and nutmeg. Incorporate the ingredients into a mound, then
form a well in the center; add the butter and the egg. Briefly
knead the dough until it comes together, using the extra flour as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the dough to a thickness of 1/2 inch. Using a 11/2-inch
round cookie cutter, cut out the dumplings and set them on a clean
towel dusted with flour. Cover the dumplings with another towel and
allow them to rest while preparing the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce:  &LR; Heat 1/2 cup of the peanut oil in a large,
heavy-bottomed skillet. Working in batches, add the meat and brown
on all sides. As the meat browns, remove it from the pan to a
strainer set over a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   When all the meat has browned, add the remaining 1/4 cup peanut
oil to the pan and saute the onion in it until translucent, 3 to 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the carrot and celery and saute over medium heat for 10
minutes, stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Return the meat to the skillet and reheat. Increase the heat to
high and add the pepper flakes, parsley, garlic, herb bouquet,
mushroom powder and salt; cook for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually deglaze the pan with the wine, cooking until liquid
has evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce heat to medium and add the tomato sauce and cumin. Add
stock to barely cover the ingredients. Reduce heat, cover and
simmer until the meat is tender, gradually adding more stock as
needed. Remove from the heat. Skim off the fat and mix it with the
flour to make a paste. Stir the paste into the sauce and cook until
thickened. Cover and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To fry the gnocchi:  &LR; Heat the vegetable oil in a heavy,
high-sided pan over medium-high heat. Add the gnocchi, a few at a
time, and fry until golden brown. Remove with a slotted spoon and
drain on a paper towel-lined plate. Keep warm in a low oven until
ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Spoon sauce onto warmed serving plates; spread out
into a circle. Top with the gnocchi.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve the remaining sauce for another use (such as a sauce for
pasta).
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6 as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (using half of the sauce): &LR;   &LR; 450 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g &LR; 
 &LR; protein, 52 g carbohydrate, 14 g fat (5 g saturated), 92 mg &LR; 
 &LR; cholesterol, 370 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1424EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
