<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SPOT-BJT30-COX     09-29 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, Sept. 30,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, looking for a way to
rejuvenate his Democratic presidential campaign, has decided to
move his political operation to his home state of Tennessee and
challenge his sole rival (Bradley) to a series of debates. Campaign
chairman Tony Coelho and chief strategeist Carter Eskew will move
to Nashville, but it is unclear how many members of his senior
staff will follow. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BEATTY _ LOS ANGELES _ Warren Beatty, actor and Democrat, makes
a speech today that is expected to touch on global trade, campaign
finance and social justice. He may or may not say something about
running for President. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TIPPER _ Tipper Gore, wife of Vice President Al Gore, visits the
Atlanta airport to tour minority-owned businesses there and to
discuss her husband's commitment to affirmative action. (Judd,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ There's nothing like being on the hustings.
Today's presidential campaigns are media oriented, but the average
voter still wants to meet the candidate in person and look him/her
in the eye. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ISRAEL _ GRAJAR, Israel _ After two years in a country
just the size of New Jersey, I thought I knew Israel well _ until I
went to Grajar. If you could condense the confusion of the Middle
East down to one town, it might look like this little-known border
village. Here, they speak Arabic, practice the mysterious Alawite
religion, adore Syrian president Hafez Assad and hold Israeli
citizenship. No wonder no one can figure out whether the town
should stay with Israel or be turned over to Syria or Lebanon. And,
no wonder 25-year-old resident Yossef Salman is having trouble
getting permission to bring his Syrian wife from Damascus. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ALLIANCE _ MEXICO CITY _ One political player here calls
it ``the blunder of the century for Mexico's opposition.'' Late
Tuesday night talks definitely crumbled to forge a sweeping
coalition that could have probably defeated Mexico's Revolutionary
Institutional Party, or PRI, in next year's presidential election.
Most polls show that an alliance among virtually all of Mexico's
opposition parties _ from right to left _ would have driven the PRI
from the presidency after more than 70 in power. Polls also showed
that Mexicans wanted to see the formation of a coalition. But
opposition leaders failed to show leadership, analysts say. Now the
PRI's chances of winning in 2000 once again are better than they've
looked for a long time. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). 30. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA _ Q&AMP;A with Mary Brown Bullock, Agnes Scott College's
president who is a historian who takes the long view of China's
long and rich history. As the 50th anniversary of Communist rule
arrives (Oct. 1), she also does some gazing into China's future.
Bullock serves on the board of directors of the Committee for
U.S.-China Relations and is active in other China and Asia groups.
(Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTE _ WASHINGTON _ AAA, the auto group, issues a report that
it says will prove that cars and trucks are not the leading source
of pollution in U.S. cities. In fact, AAA will say that cars are no
longer even a major contributor to ozone-causing emissions. (Hill,
Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-COLLEGE _ WASHINGTON - New policies intended to
increase the number of Hispanic Americans who get college
educations could raise their combined salaries by $130 billion a
year, says a study to be released and discussed Wednesday by
officials of the Hispanic Association of Colleges and Universities
and of Educational Testing Service, which is best known for
administering SAT tests. Some old ways are mentioned again and some
new methods are proposed for boosting the very small number of
Hispanic Americans who go to college. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
12.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTHOUSE _ WASHINGTON _ Georgia's St. Simons Island Lighthouse
Museum is among the three winners of the National Award for Museum
and Library Services. The awards will be given in a White House
ceremony. (Dart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ENCEPHALITIS _ ATLANTA _ Checking on developments in the
encephalitis outbreak in New York, whether there's any indication
yet of the viral infection moving south. (Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-SUMMIT _ Curtain-raiser for the National Education
Summit, which begins Thursday. We'll talk with Georgia Gov. Roy
Barnes about what he hopes to get out of the meeting with other
governors that could help shape his vision for education reform in
Georgia. (Cumming, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTER _ DAYTON _ Now that we know how bad the foster care
system is, who is going to fix it. We get reaction from Ohio's
patchwork system of regulation to see what reforms are possible and
whether anybody will take action against SAFY or its boss, Bruce
Maag. (Wagner/Jaspin, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   DIAMOND _ Man sues ex-fiance to get back his $109,000, 5-carat
diamond ring (princess cut) (with two side diamonds of more than a
carat
</P>
<P>
   each). (O'Meilia, Pam Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. PLEASE NOTE:
SPORTS STORIES will have an E.T.A. of 9:30 P.M. If news, business
or features stories will move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet layouts are for sale over the web, through the New York
Times News Service's PageExpress service, at
www.nytsyn/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   If a budget line or story is marked with photos or graphics,
those are available from the New York Times News Service at
212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
