<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-R-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      09-29 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-R-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Sept. 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANK (Moscow) _ Demonstrating Russian government concern
over growing reports of money laundering and corruption there, the
country's prosecutor general, in an interview, says authorities are
investigating money laundering at a Russian bank called Flamingo.
By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CAUCASUS (Moscow) _ Developments in the Caucasus: Russian
bombing continues. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MAO-PAINTER (Beijing) _ A feature on the painter who has
been painting and repainting the Mao portrait in Tiananmen Square
for 27 years. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMF (Washington) _ President Clinton talks to World
Bank/IMF meeting about debt relief for poor countries. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-BISHOP (Baucau, East Timor) _ East Timor's second-biggest
city is surprisingly undamaged, thanks, apparently, to a bishop who
has tried to bring factions together. By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the spending
bills, including, possibly, a deal in the military spending
conference involving F-22. By tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-RACE-PROFILING (Los Angeles) _ California's governor has
vetoed a bill designed to stop racial profiling by california law
enforcement, saying the burden of tracking the ethnicity of all
motorists stopped by state and local officers was too great. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   BOGUS-POKEMON (Chicago) _ The booming popularity of Pokemon
monsters is drawing counterfeiters.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Vice President Gore provides
fundraising and spending information; shakes up his campaign staff
and plans to move the operation to Nashville. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-REAGAN (Simi Valley, Calif.) _ In a year when a lot of
Republican contenders are vying for the title of Ronald Reagan's
spiritual heir, John McCain may have snatched the biggest prize of
all: the tacit endorsement of Nancy Reagan. The two appear today at
the Reagan library. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   BEATTY-POLITICS (Los Angeles) _ Warren Beatty, the actor, gives
a speech, long awaited for the possibility he may announce his
political intentions. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INFANT-SLEEP (Undated) _ Children under 2 should never sleep
with their parents, the American Medical Association and Consumer
Product Safety Commission say in a study which is provoking furious
reactions from people on both sides. Over an eight-year period, the
researchers say, 515 babies and toddlers died in adult beds: 121
smothered when a parent rolled over on them and 394 were caught in
parts of the bed itself. By Erica Goode. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-MERCHANTS (Undated) _ Amazon.com says that starting
Thursday, any merchant can set up a store on its Web site for a fee
of $9.99 a month. The move will sharply broaden the products
available through the site before the holiday shopping season.
Shares of Amazon.com surge as much as 17 percent after the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LONG-DISTANCE (New York) _ Looking at Bell Atlantic's filing
to sell long-distance service in New York. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-REPORT (Undated) _ Looking at how mutual funds performed
in the quarter as well as at the monthly fund flow data due from
the Investment Company Institute. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA-OUTLOOK (Detroit) _ Looking at Toyota and its ability to
prosper even when the yen is strong as it introduces a new model,
Echo, which is priced under $10,000. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   MOBIL-EXXON (Undated) _ Looking at what's next for Mobil and
Exxon now that European regulators have approved the merger. The
European Commission has set some significant, although not
surprising conditions for its approval, including the sale of
Mobil's stake in a fuels production joint venture with BP Amoco,
the sale of Mobil's Dutch gas trading assets and a number of number
of stations. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-CHINA (Hong Kong) _ America Online has teamed up with
China.com Corp. to start an Internet service in Hong Kong. But it
is mainland China, with an on-line market projected to quadruple
from to 16.1 million in 2003 from 3.8 million users this year, that
is clearly AOL's target, despite recent concern over what Beijing's
policy is on foreign investment in Internet companies. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-BANK (London) _ The chief executive of the Bank of
Scotland, which has mounted a $34 billion hostile bid for National
Westminster, says his bank is in talks with ``a couple of large
U.S. companies'' about possible joint ventures. He also says that
Bank of Scotland had talks with Legal and General, which NatWest
had sought to acquire. Bank of Scotland reports a 12 percent rise
in first-half profits, higher than expected. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
