<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-ISRAEL-0930-C     09-29 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-ISRAEL-0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BEHIND THE MINE FIELD: LITTLE-KNOWN ARAB TOWN STUCK IN LIMBO
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For locator map purposes, Ghajar is a small town on the
Lebanon-Israel border where the border is intersected by the small
Dan River. From Metulla, on the Lebanon-Israel border, follow the
border east. It dips sharply to the southeast, then turns sharply
again due north. Then, it begins to bend from due north to
northeast. Ghajar is located at that bend.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GHAJAR, Israel _ High atop a mountain in the Golan Heights, the
750-year-old Nimrod castle reminds us that history here is a parade
of conquerors.
</P>
<P>
   Nimrod's stone walls and towers were built to defend Islam
against the Crusaders. But there were others, too _ Romans,
Mamlukes, Ottomans, British and, now, Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The fort is in ruins today. In an isolated village nearby, the
most recent conquest has left a bride and groom on opposite sides
of a border.
</P>
<P>
   Yossef Salman is caught in the limbo of his small village,
Ghajar (pronounced, ``RA-jar''), on the border of Israel, Lebanon
and Syria. In five decades, it has been passed among them, ending
up under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
   The people here are Arabs and speak Arabic. They practice the
mysterious Alawi religion and adore Syrian president Hafez Assad,
but they hold citizenship in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Salman lives across the street from a valley where Israel meets
Lebanon. But, Salman looks longingly toward Syria, home to his new
bride.
</P>
<P>
   They met in Amman, Jordan and married there in February. For
Salman, a college graduate disenchanted with the uneducated women
in his small hometown, 21-year-old Muna was a good match. She is
studying to be a flight attendant and shares his rare Alawi
religion.
</P>
<P>
   A peace deal between Israel and Syria could reunite them, but
that seems long in coming. Meanwhile, Salman has failed to win
Israeli approval to bring her to Ghajar and her in-laws don't want
her to go anyway. She still lives in Damascus, Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I will end this situation by divorce,'' Salman said.
``Her parents are not feeling well. They think there will be no
peace in the Middle East and (if she comes) they will not see their
daughter again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghajar itself, a village of small stone houses and boxy
apartment blocks, has the Twilight-Zone feel of a place trapped
between fluid borders and unstable times.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it is the only Alawi village in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Alawi are an offshoot of Islam. They believe in
reincarnation and deify Ali, a son-in-law of the Prophet Mohammed.
Syria's Assad is an Alawi, but Alawi are a minority throughout the
Arab world and, perhaps because of that, they refuse to talk about
their religion.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, Ghajar's location is such that you cannot go there
without feeling you've gone a bit too far.
</P>
<P>
   A tall security fence runs between the rest of Israel and
Ghajar, giving it a no-mans-land eeriness. Until a few years ago,
people needed approval from Israeli soldiers to pass.
</P>
<P>
   A well-paved street, running past a mine field and lined with
purple lamp posts, leads into this farming town of about 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people I met there refused to talk. That's unusual
in Israel, but typical of the Alawi and indicative of a town
uncertain of its place.
</P>
<P>
   According to Salman, Ghajar was part of Syria until 1967.
Residents still feel Syrian. Salman's father, Abdul Rahim Salman,
71, told me Assad is his hero.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Israel took over the Golan Heights to the east,
separating Ghajar from Syria. Months passed with Ghajar belonging
to no country and getting no services.
</P>
<P>
   Salman says the people of Ghajar made the controversial decision
to take Israeli citizenship in return for water, electricity and
free passage to their farmlands.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israelis tell me a different story. They say Lebanon had
held Ghajar until the mid-1960s. Then, to avoid involvement in a
water dispute with Israel, it gave the town to Syria, which lost it
in 1967. If there is a peace deal, they say, the town could go to
either Lebanon or Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Arabs in the Golan nearby had yet another take on Ghajar.
</P>
<P>
   Golan Arabs refuse Israeli citizenship and openly await a peace
deal that will bring back Syrian control. They say Israeli leaders
played Ghajar's two major clans against each other, tricking them
into taking citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   So, for now, everyone has a history to fit their needs. Israelis
see Ghajar as a lost village needing a custodian. Golan Arabs see
it as a village duped by sinister Israel.
</P>
<P>
   And the people of Ghajar, behind the fence and the mine field,
consider themselves Syrian but have citizenship Israel. Cautiously,
they hedge their bets for whatever turn of fate comes next.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad it won't come in time to save Yossef Salman's marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
