<HEADER>
A0348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-PEDESTRIANS-HNS &LR;      09-29 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-PEDESTRIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDESTRIANS FIND LIFE IN THE SLOW LANE FULL OF PERILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SARAH YANG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Since the 1950s, pedestrians have faced a steady
risk of being killed by motorists, and for the thousands of walkers
in this city of narrow streets and steep hills, it's a danger that
won't disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for pedestrians say the city's response to the deaths
so far has focused primarily on enforcement of traffic laws, while
experience elsewhere indicates measures that slow traffic _ longer
walk signals, more medians, fewer one-way streets _ work better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, enforcement only goes so far,''
said Zac Wald, director of the activist group BayPeds. ``Traffic
calming is the answer, but it hasn't been broached enough.''
</P>
<P>
   While the number of pedestrian deaths fell from 41 in the
1997-1998 fiscal year to 29 in the city's 1998-1999 budget period,
deaths are still occurring. Six pedestrians were killed in August
alone and another one died last week.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers are not always at fault, the police and safety officials
say. Still, a number of steps have been taken to improve safety for
pedestrians. The city has:
</P>
<P>
   _ Erected pedestrian safety signs near senior centers, and the
police are patrolling troubled intersections.
</P>
<P>
   _ Added two to six seconds to the signal time at more than 20
intersections.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sent police officers into the public schools to discuss
pedestrian safety.
</P>
<P>
   Most important to pedestrian advocates, the city budgeted
$750,000 this fiscal year to hire a traffic engineer, a pedestrian
safety coordinator and a school safety coordinator to study and
then work to improve traffic safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the big policy changes and traffic engineering projects are
still wending their way through the government.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic officials have authorized a ``traffic calming'' study in
one neighborhood where neighbors have been complaining about
speeders for years. But no one has been assigned to direct the
project.
</P>
<P>
   A broader plan to reset the pedestrian walking time at busy
intersections has been slowed by old, sometimes rusty signals.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian advocates such as Betsy Thagard, executive director
of Walk San Francisco, point to cities such as Portland and Seattle
as places where good traffic engineering increased safety.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, for example, has installed traffic circles. A study of
119 intersections where circles were built this decade found that
the accident and injury rates dropped 94 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the number of deaths in Seattle has decreased from 14
in 1990 to 11 in 1996, the latest figures available, and injuries
declined from 506 to 489 during that same time period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 25 years to get where we are,'' said Noel Schoneman,
division director for neighborhood traffic engineering in Seattle.
He noted the traffic program began in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that the decline in pedestrian injuries and
fatalities cannot be credited solely to the traffic circles, which
typically slow traffic. ``We're doing a much better job of keeping
drunk drivers off the road, triage is better and demographics
change,'' he said. ``Engineering plays a major role, but since I
can't draw a direct correlation, all I know is that we need to do
all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in San Francisco note that for every pedestrian who
wants traffic to slow down, there is a driver who will protest any
measure that could be seen as increasing gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   When Supervisor Mabel Teng proposed lengthening the walking time
for pedestrians along Mission and Market streets, two major
thoroughfares, angry drivers called to complain that it already
took them too long to drive across town.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some slowing down means saving one life, I'm willing to
take the criticism,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On one point both pedestrian advocates and officials in San
Francisco agree: Solutions in this city won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   An average of 48 pedestrians died each year in the 1960s,
decades before the deaths of 41 pedestrians during the 1997-98
fiscal year sparked a civic push for increased safety.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a chronic and costly shortage of parking spaces,
thousands of residents walk or take public transit to work, often
up and down steep hills that block visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Yet concern in San Francisco goes beyond sheer numbers of
deaths; it is also about who is dying.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 20 percent of the city's 755,000 residents are over age
65, a larger elderly population than in most other big cities, said
Abbie Yant, who heads Emergency Medical Services at the Department
of Public Health. And the elderly are far more likely to die after
being hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year 1998-99, 48 percent of pedestrians killed by
vehicles were 65 or older, up from 40 percent in fiscal 1997-98.
Moreover, pedestrians were mostly at fault in 58 percent of all
fatal accidents this past fiscal year, while drivers were blamed 42
percent of the time, according to police reports. The exact
opposite was true the year before, when drivers were reported at
fault 58 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors are at risk for reasons of natural aging,'' Yant said.
``Their gait is slower and they're not hearing as clearly. ...
(Plus) a lot of seniors grew up with a value system where, here's a
pedestrian, the guy on the (traffic) signal says walk, so you do.
That's not smart in today's environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
