<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE `SKINNY' ON A PLEASINGLY PLUMP SANDWICH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of Midwestern transplants sent an e-mail a couple of
months ago looking for a recipe for pork tenderloin sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   I've got to admit to a liking for these sandwiches myself,
although it wasn't until I received the message that I remembered
them. I put away my share of them at the Old Heidelberg restaurant
across from the journalism department at the University of
Missouri-Columbia during the 19-- _ well, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   (For those who find themselves driving through Missouri, the Old
Heidelberg is still open and still serving pork tenderloin
sandwiches.)
</P>
<P>
   However, I didn't have a recipe for these huge honking
sandwiches until ``American Home Cooking'' by Cheryl Alters Jamison
and Bill Jamison (Broadway Books, $30 until Jan. 31) landed, all
470 pages of it, on my desk.
</P>
<P>
   The Jamisons write that the sandwich is often called a
``skinny'' in the ``I'' states of Iowa, Illinois or Indiana. A lot
of these sandwiches would add up to more than skinny, but that's
for another day.
</P>
<P>
   PORK TENDERLOIN SANDWICHES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   _ Four 6- to 7-ounce boneless center-cut pork loin chops
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup stone-ground cornmeal, preferably yellow
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/4 cup all-purpose unbleached flour
</P>
<P>
   _ 11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   _ Vegetable oil or shortening for pan-frying
</P>
<P>
   _ Soft hamburger buns
</P>
<P>
   _ Lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   _ Ketchup, mustard or mayonnaise or a combination
</P>
<P>
   _ Dill pickle slices
</P>
<P>
   Place pork chop between 2 sheets of wax paper and pound with a
mallet to 1/4-inch thickness or less. The chop should be large,
round and lacy-edged. You should be able to see through the pork in
places. Repeat with remaining chops.
</P>
<P>
   On a plate, stir together the cornmeal, flour, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1/2 inch of oil into heavy skillet and heat it to 365
degrees. Dredge first pork chop heavily in cornmeal-flour mixture
and fry it until golden and crisp, about 2 minutes per side. The
chop will shrink by a couple of inches while frying, but will
remain large. Drain and repeat with the other pork chops, checking
temperature of oil each time.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot on buns (the pork will dwarf the bun, but that's the
way it's done) with lettuce, spreading the bread thickly with
ketchup or other condiments and serving pickles on the side.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SANDWICH WITH BUN: 545 calories, 22
grams fat, 37 grams carbohydrates, 47 grams protein, 134 milligrams
cholesterol, 300 milligrams sodium, 36 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
