<TEXT>
<P>
   Brazilian recipes to enjoy
</P>
<P>
   By Wendell Brock
</P>
<P>
   As Americans become better versed in Brazilian food, we wanted
to share some dishes outside the realm of feijoada and moqueca.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetarians will find that Tutu a Mineira _ served with the
traditional kale, boiled white rice and farofa _ is a complete
meal. If you don't feel like bothering with the polenta, the
chicken with okra works just as well with rice. Add the hearts of
palm salad, and you've a meal fit for company. And if you want to
make your Brazilian friends happy, make quindins. Chances are,
they've never eaten them in an American cook's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   To make farofa, which is almost always placed on the Brazilian
table as a condiment, toast 1 cup coarse manioc flour with 2
tablespoons dende oil or butter.
</P>
<P>
   Where to find Brazilian ingredients: If you can't find what you
need at your local Latin market, two travel agents catering to the
Latin American community also stock basic Brazilian products: Trans
America, 5299 Roswell Road, Suite 112, 404-252-7270; and
Expeditions Travel, 5801 Roswell Road, Suite C, 404-303-8787.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Salada de Palmito
</P>
<P>
   (Hearts of Palm Salad)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Keep the vinaigrette simple so the clean yet buttery flavor of
the hearts of palm shines through. One option: Mix together olive
oil, red wine vinegar, just a hint of Dijon mustard and plenty of
kosher salt and cracked black pepper. Served all over Brazil, this
recipe is very similar to the one at Paul Luna's new South American
restaurant, Loca Luna.
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) can hearts of palm, drained and cut in 1-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 head romaine lettuce, or other greens, washed and torn in
bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Liquid from bottled malagueta peppers to taste, optional
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Place the hearts of palm and greens in a large salad bowl. Add
onion.
</P>
<P>
   If using pepper liquid, add to vinaigrette. Pour vinaigrette
over salad and chill until serving time.
</P>
<P>
   Toss and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 114 calories, 2 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 80), 6 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 3 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Frango com Quiabo
</P>
<P>
   (Chicken With Okra)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   As a certified pod person, I was thrilled to see this okra stew
on nearly every menu in the town of Ouro Preto, in Minas Gerais.
It's good all by itself, but add the rich polenta that follows, and
it's extraordinary. If you are a skin lover, those chicken
cracklings will really rock your world.
</P>
<P>
   6 pounds chicken thighs and legs
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   4 medium onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups homemade or canned low-sodium chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds okra, trimmed and cut in 1/2-inch rounds (about 4
cups)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon preserved malagueta pepper oil or hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   Wash and dry chicken pieces. Pull the skin away from the flesh,
but do not detach it. In a large bowl, toss the chicken with the
garlic, salt and pepper and refrigerate for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat butter over medium heat. Add onions and
saute until they are light gold, about 10 minutes. Set aside
onions.
</P>
<P>
   In the same skillet, heat vegetable and olive oils over medium
heat. When hot, add chicken pieces and saute them until the skin
curls up crisp and golden, about 15 minutes. Drain on paper towels
and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the oil from the pan, add the stock and bring to a boil,
scraping up the brown bits that adhere to the bottom of the pan.
Reduce the heat and continue to cook at a low simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, generously coat a cast-iron skillet with vegetable
oil and heat over medium-high heat for about 5 minutes. Add the
okra and cook, stirring constantly with a wooden spoon, for about
12 minutes. The gum will stick to the sides of the pan. Remove the
okra from the heat. Cut away the curled fried skin from the chicken
pieces and reserve. Add the chicken pieces and onions to the
simmering sauce and cook for 15 to 20 minutes, until chicken is
cooked through. Add okra and season with salt and pepper. Add the
malagueta oil or hot pepper sauce and cook for another minute.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with the fried chicken curls and polenta (see recipe). _
Adapted from: Christopher Idone's ``Brazil: A Cook's Tour''
(Clarkson Potter, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 479 calories, 38 grams protein, 31 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 59), 11 grams carbohydrates, 140
milligrams cholesterol, 140 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Polenta com Milho Cozido (Polenta With Fresh Corn)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   6 1/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups polenta
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked fresh corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, bring the water to a boil over high heat.
Add salt and reduce heat to a simmer. Slowly add the polenta,
stirring constantly with a wooden spoon. Cook, stirring, for 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the corn kernels and cook another 5 minutes or until the
polenta is smooth and slightly stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the heat and stir in butter and cheese. Serve
immediately. _ Adapted from: Christopher Idone's ``Brazil: A Cook's
Tour'' (Clarkson Potter, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 225 calories, 5 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 27 grams carbohydrates, 27
milligrams cholesterol, 404 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Bobo de Camarao
</P>
<P>
   (Puree of Yucca With Shrimp)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 1 hour, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   My friend Eliane Oliveira introduced me to this dish at Dada, a
restaurant in the historic Pelourinho section of Salvador that
serves some of the best traditional Bahian cuisine in Brazil. The
tomatoes and dende give this version a gorgeous shrimp color.
Served as a first course, sprinkled with a little chopped cilantro,
it makes an elegant soup.
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds prawns (large shrimp)
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds cassava (also called manioc or yucca)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shrimp stock or light fish stock
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 large tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh or canned unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dende oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh cilantro, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Rinse, peel and devein shrimp, reserving heads if making your
own shrimp stock. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   With a sharp paring knife, peel away the cassava skin and cut
the cassava root in half lengthwise. In a large bowl, cover the
cassava with cold water and set aside for 1 hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if using homemade shrimp stock, combine the shrimp
heads, shells and enough cold water to cover in a saucepan. Bring
to a boil, skim, reduce the heat and simmer for 15 minutes. Strain
through a fine-mesh strainer and reserve the broth, about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mix the lime juice with the salt and white
pepper and mix until the salt dissolves. Stir in the shrimp and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the cassava and place in a large kettle of lightly salted
water. Stud 1 onion quarter with the cloves and add it and the
remaining quarters and bay leaf to the cassava.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a boil and cook for 20 minutes, or until the cassava is
fork-tender. Drain and cool slightly. Remove the fibrous central
cords from the cassava; remove the bay leaf and the cloves from the
onion quarter and discard. Set the cassava and onion aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat the olive oil over medium heat. Add the
chopped onions and garlic and cook until the onions are lightly
browned, about 8 minutes. Add the tomatoes, tomato paste and stock
to the skillet. Season with salt and pepper, bring to a boil,
reduce the heat and simmer for 10 minutes, stirring from time to
time.
</P>
<P>
   Working in two or three batches, in a food processor, puree the
boiled cassava and onions with the tomato mixture, adding the milk,
coconut milk and dende oil as you pulse the mixture. Place the
pureed mixture in a large nonstick saucepan and set over medium
heat. Add the shrimp and the cream, season with salt and pepper and
cook, stirring constantly, until shrimp are just cooked through. If
the mixture is too thick, thin with a little milk or stock. When
shrimp are cooked through, add parsley and cilantro and cook for
another 2 minutes. Serve with boiled white rice. _ Adapted from
Christopher Idone's ``Brazil: A Cook's Tour'' (Clarkson Potter,
$30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 516 calories, 32 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 40 grams carbohydrates, 190
milligrams cholesterol, 556 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Tutu a Mineira
</P>
<P>
   (Mashed Beans)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Soaking time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Minas Gerais, this is always served with a huge
spread of pork, sauteed kale, plain boiled rice and wedges of
polenta. I tend to skip the polenta, but by all means, have a
little bowl of farofa on the table to sprinkle on. The mulatinha
beans can be difficult to find, so any other kind of brown, red or
white bean works fine, as would black beans, although it won't then
be an authentic tutu. In Brazil, the addition of lard to this dish
makes it all the richer, so if you have a little pork fat sitting
around. . . .
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mulatinha beans, brown beans such as cranberry beans or
white beans such as navy or Great Northern beans, washed and picked
clean
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   3 cups beer or additional water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large tomato, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper, cored, seeded, ribs removed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup manioc flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon chopped fresh oregano or 1/4 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped green onions, green part only
</P>
<P>
   Soak the beans overnight in water to cover by several inches.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the beans and place them in a large soup kettle with water
to cover by 3 inches (make sure to use this much water, or you
won't have enough bean liquid to puree the beans; if that happens,
used canned chicken stock). Bring to a boil and skim off any foam
or impurities. Add the beer or additional water and bring to a boil
again. Reduce the heat to a simmer and cook for 45 minutes,
stirring from time to time so the beans do not stick.
</P>
<P>
   While the beans cook, put the olive oil in a saute pan and place
over medium heat. Add the onion and garlic and saute for about 5
minutes, or until the onion is translucent. Add the tomato and
green pepper and cook about 10 minutes, or until the pepper is limp
and almost tender.
</P>
<P>
   Add the manioc flour, toss and cook another minute. Add about 3
cups of bean liquid, a little at a time, until the mixture forms a
light, wet paste. Fold in the oregano and parsley and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When the beans are soft and tender, season with salt and pepper,
turn off the heat and set aside for 10 minutes. Drain the beans,
reserving the cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, pulse the beans on and off in batches until
smooth, adding a little bean liquid as needed to keep the mixture
loose. Continue to process until all the beans are pureed. All the
bean liquid may not be required. The consistency should be smooth,
soft and not heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually add the manioc flour mixture to the processor, working
in two or three batches if necessary. Place the puree in a clean
kettle and bring to a simmer, stirring constantly. Keep warm over a
pan of simmering water until ready to serve. When ready to serve,
sprinkle with the green onions. _ Adapted from: Christopher Idone's
``Brazil: A Cook's Tour'' (Clarkson Potter, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 169 calories, 10 grams protein, 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 7), 29 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 9 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Couve a Mineira
</P>
<P>
   (Greens Wilted
</P>
<P>
   in Olive Oil)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Couve means ``kale,'' but Brazilian cooks also make collards
this way. Use whichever greens you please. Collards are easier to
roll than kale. This is my preferred method for cooking greens _
and okra, come to think of it.
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh kale, or 1 big bunch collards
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, very thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Soak the greens in the sink to clean, or wash thoroughly. Strip
off stems and stack the leaves in a pile. Make a manageable bunch,
roll it tightly like a cigar and cut it crosswise in 1/4-inch
slivers. Heat the oil in a large, heavy skillet over medium heat.
Add onion and garlic, stirring until cooked through, about 5
minutes. Add the greens a batch at a time, stirring constantly and
adding more as they wilt. Cook until just tender but still bright
green, about 10 to 15 minutes. If the greens stick before they are
tender, add a little tap water. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 129 calories, 4 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 56), 13 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 49
milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Quindins
</P>
<P>
   (Coconut Macaroons)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 small or 12 large
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Some Brazilian cooks use an egg per quindim (oddly enough,
``quindim'' is the singular form in Portuguese). ``It's a fat
pill,'' I heard one well-dressed U.S. businessman say at a Rio de
Janeiro restaurant. ``It's a macaroon on steroids.'' This somewhat
lighter-than-usual recipe is from Jessica Harris' ``Tasting
Brazil.'' She uses light brown sugar to impart more flavor, but a
real quindim is bright yellow, not light brown. Reader Andrea Neves
shared a recipe with me that was very eggy and delicious _ like
grandma's custard. ``The secret,'' says Neves, ``is to cook the
quindins in a pan of water.'' We also like using mini-muffin pans
for a daintier look.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tightly packed freshly grated coconut
</P>
<P>
   5 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg white, beaten into stiff peaks
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a medium bowl, mix together by
hand the sugar, butter and coconut. Beat in the egg yolks one at a
time, stirring well. Fold in the beaten egg white. Grease 12 large
muffin molds _ or 16 mini-muffin molds _ and divide the mixture
among them. Place the muffin tin in a larger baking pan filled with
1 inch of boiling water to form a bain-marie. Bake 35 minutes, or
until the quindins are firm and golden. Let them cool in the tin
before removing.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (when making 16): 90 calories, 2 grams protein, 5
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 48), 10 grams carbohydrates,
101 milligrams cholesterol, 10 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Dona Moreira's Torta de Banana (Easy Banana Cobbler)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 very generous servings Preparation time: 15 minutes
Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who aren't true bakers, this dessert is
simplicity itself. It's a good way to use ripe bananas, and with a
little supervision, even the kids can do it. It also works well
with apples. Be sure to have some vanilla ice cream on hand to
dollop on while the cobbler is hot.
</P>
<P>
   12 tablespoons granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   10 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon powdered yeast
</P>
<P>
   Shortening or butter for the pan
</P>
<P>
   12 bananas
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a small mixing bowl, combine 10
tablespoons sugar, the flour and yeast. Grease a 9-by-13-inch
baking dish and cover the bottom with 1/3 of the flour mixture,
using a large spoon to spread it evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Peel half the bananas. Slice them lengthwise and place in the
baking dish. Sprinkle bananas with another 1/3 of the dry mixture.
Peel remaining bananas, slice and place on top. Spoon the rest of
the dry mixture on top to form the topping.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender, combine eggs, milk and the remaining 2 tablespoons
sugar. Pour over the cobbler. Dot with butter. Bake until brown,
about 1 hour. _ Adapted from: Dona Nair Galvao da Silva Moreira,
Sao Paulo, Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 399 calories, 9 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 20), 77 grams carbohydrates, 122 milligrams
cholesterol, 93 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
