<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brazil: Collards, peanuts, sweets _ the other South knows the
comforts of home
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The corn cake was unlike anything I had ever
tasted, and yet it seemed somehow familiar. Sweet and crumbly, just
a little bit savory, studded with kernels of fresh corn, this cross
between a bright yellow cake and a very rich corn bread was the
perfect thing to have in the morning with a glass of milk. But my
food memory was confused: My South Georgia grandmothers never made
this _ or did they?
</P>
<P>
   Returning home, I picked up Brazilian novelist Jorge Amado's
``Dona Flor and Her Two Husbands'' _ a Dickensian work of magic
realism about a cooking school instructor who conjures her dead
husband back into her bed _ and there was the corn cake: ``Sugar,
salt, grated cheese, butter, coconut milk, the thick and thin, both
are called for. ... The proportions depending on the taste; each
person has his preference _ some like things sweeter, some saltier,
isn't that so? And the batter very thin. A quick oven.''
</P>
<P>
   Twin passions. The living and the dead. The salty and the sweet.
I'm no Dona Flor, but what led me to Brazil in the first place was
my desire to understand its foodways. My ongoing quest is to
discover how the various cuisines of our African, European and
indigenous ancestors have been transported to the kitchens of our
time.
</P>
<P>
   And so, from the corn cake that my friend Adilson's mother made
to the eggy coconut macaroon known as quindim that is found all
over Brazil, I was forever reminded of the comforts of home.
</P>
<P>
   Okra, corn, peanuts. Greens, collards, pork. Shrimp, rice,
tomatoes: These are the ties that bind the American South with the
states of Bahia and Minas Gerais. And like Southerners, Brazilians
have a very sweet tooth. But what transforms Brazilian cookery into
a distinctive art of its own is its liberal use of bacalhau (dried
salt cod) from the Portuguese; native yucca in all its forms
(boiled, fried, ground into flour and meal); the orange-amber palm
oil known as dende; the malagueta pepper (a tiny, superhot chile
whose flavor cannot be compared to any other); and coconut milk.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in the northeastern state of Bahia, you'll find moquecas
(fish stews flavored with coconut and dende), bobo de camarao
(boiled and pureed cassava with shrimp); caruru (a Yoruban dish of
okra, shrimp and cilantro); and acaraje, a black-eyed pea or bean
cake fried in dende oil, sliced in half, stuffed with a large dried
shrimp and slathered with vatapa (a spread of crushed nuts, coconut
milk, dried shrimp and any number of other ingredients). With a
majority-black population, Bahia remains African through and
through.
</P>
<P>
   To sprinkle a hot steaming moqueca with farofa (manioc flour
toasted with butter or oil) and drizzle it with malagueta pepper
oil is to discover the Holy Trinity of the Bahian larder. The
crunchy farofa, the aromatic dende and the fiery pepper explode on
the tongue to evince a singular sensory experience.
</P>
<P>
   Down south a bit, in the state of Minas Gerais, you encounter a
rich cuisine that celebrates pigs, polenta and pods of okra _ and
some of the weirdest, brightest desserts I have ever seen (fruit
purees and curls of green mango soaking in syrup). There's Minas
cheese (a bland cow's milk variety that comes alive with a dollop
of sweet fruit) and turkey wrapped in banana and lime leaves.
</P>
<P>
   But the piece de resistance is tutu a Mineira, a brown-bean mash
that's always served with sauteed collards, boiled white rice,
wedges of polenta cake and every cut of pork imaginable _ pork
chops, sausage, cracklings and roast pork. This is the region's
answer to feijoada (the national dish of pork and black beans).
</P>
<P>
   I never got around to trying chicken cooked in its own blood,
but I did fall head over heels in love with frango com quiabo
(chicken with okra), a simple dish that saves the crisped chicken
skins to serve on a side dish of creamy polenta with fresh corn. I
am just mystified that we Southerners have never thought of
combining pan-fried chicken with stewed okra.
</P>
<P>
   If the Minas table represents country food at its very best,
then Sao Paulo, my final destination, is the epitome of all things
cosmopolitan. The world's third-largest city, with a population of
18 million and a lively mix of Japanese, Italians and immigrants
from all over the globe, it is ranked as one of the world's great
restaurant cities. Next time, I'll sample sushi and pasta, but on
this first trip I wanted to try what the locals eat.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what led me to the home of Dona Nair Galvao da Silva
Moreira.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that she was a terrific home cook and caterer, I asked
her son Ne if I might visit their home one day for coffee and _
perhaps _ a few recipes. Instead, I arrived to find a Saturday
lunch laid out for the entire clan, the four Moreira children, five
grandchildren and an assortment of aunts, friends, maids and
guests. First, Dona Moreira sent around a tray of bright red
cocktails. ``What's in this?'' I asked Ne, suddenly lifted by a
tropical rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy,'' he said, ``Just passionfruit, strawberries, vodka
and sugar.'' Muito bom!
</P>
<P>
   While Senhor Moreira, a native of Portugal who looks to be about
5 feet tall, sat by the pool sipping whiskey and trying to keep the
umbrella table from blowing away, the grandchildren wrestled with
uncles in a beautiful room appointed with family keepsakes and a
print by the Brazilian artist Alfredo Volpi.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I munched on little fried balls stuffed with carne seca
(dried beef) and tottered into the kitchen to see what was cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a magnificent feast.
</P>
<P>
   There were pork ribs on a tray with fried yucca, a molded ring
of pure white rice, a bowl of soupy beans, a platter of grilled
beef steak and farofa. There was a fresh green salad with hearts of
palm, a tray of tomatoes scattered with mozzarella and a basket of
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   And there was one dish I'd read about but never seen _ cuscuz
Paulista, a Sao Paulo staple. Nothing like the couscous we know
from Africa and the Middle East, this puddinglike mold is made from
manioc flour and a flaky corn flour that resembles cornflakes.
Mixed with shredded chicken or shrimp, it is decorated with sliced
tomatoes, hearts of palm, English peas and even sardines. To an
American palate, it is wonderfully weird.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Dona Moreira how she got her ribs so crispy, the
whole family started giggling.
</P>
<P>
   The secret? She fries them in lard seasoned with red wine and
garlic cloves. Awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must cook them in true pork fat, what we call banha in
Brazil,'' said Ne. ``Do not put into an oven, but directly over the
fire of the stove.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait to try it.
</P>
<P>
   Ne, a 31-year-old Clorox executive who is relocating to San
Francisco, said, ``We are very simple people, and our pleasures are
also simple: Let's cook something nice, sit around the table and
let the conversation go while we eat. This is how we have fun. The
consequences are that the whole family must urgently go on a diet,
but we can live with that!''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too.
</P>
<P>
   I can also live with the torta de banana, a Moreira family
favorite. In the States, we would call it a dump cake or cobbler.
But Dona Moreira adds yeast and eggs to give it lift, and once the
bananas caramelize and set, the dessert can be cut into neat
squares and put on a plate. You could add a dash of rum to some
whipping cream, or make a simple rum syrup and drizzle it on. Or
both.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks spent eating my way around Brazil, after
returning home to make quindim, tutu a Mineira and bobo de camarao,
I've decided that if we Southerners have anything in common with
Brazilians, it is our love of food.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if on cue, an e-mail pops up from my friend Eliane in
Salvador: ``Now, this is a promise: When you come back, you must to
cook some American Southern food for us. And, if you want, I can
see if it is possible to send you an acaraje by mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's a true friend. I just hope she remembers that I like
it with vatapa and the green tomato relish.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
