<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet offers ways to prepare your kitchen for turn of
millennium
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is your kitchen Y2K ready?
</P>
<P>
   With less than 100 days until the clock ticks to 12:01 a.m.,
Jan. 1, 2000, it is time to give kitchen Y2K readiness some
thought. Predictions about what will happen range from catastrophic
(no water, no gas, no electricity, with disrupted food supplies),
to mildly inconvenient, to absolutely nothing out of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   To keep your kitchen routine running smoothly, you have to
decide how much and what kind of food, water and other supplies to
have on hand. The advice of responsible experts ranges from having
enough for 72 hours to as much as three weeks. Experts also
strongly advise not to wait until the last minute to begin stocking
up.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is ready when you are and loaded with Y2K kitchen
information, although some of it is downright wacky. Some sites
that one suspects are pushing an agenda other than good advice have
been urging people to store enough dehydrated and survival foods to
last until the next millennium. Many pass along the particularly
odious recommendation that you horde in secret, lest a threatening
neighbor should find out you have all that food and come knocking
to ask for a couple of eggs on New Year's Day. Oh, and you'd better
learn how to grind all that wheat into flour before New Year's or
you'll really be in a pickle.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also sites full of reasoned, helpful advice on how
to prepare your kitchen, as well as explaining what this Y2K thing
is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Not to miss _ and maybe the only place you will need to visit _
is ``The Y2K Kitchen'' at www.y2kkitchen.com. The site is produced
by Sally Strackbein, a longtime computer professional and family
cook who has written a book of the same name but has generously put
loads of free information on her Web page. She writes in a jaunty,
humorous style about the background of the Y2K situation, while
imparting serious advice.
</P>
<P>
   Just print out her shopping list and head to the grocery store.
Her shopping tips are especially helpful and outline common
pitfalls for anyone who has never bought in bulk. Storing tips
include what to do with all that food once you've lugged it home.
Especially helpful in deciding what food to sock away are her
recipe guidelines, based on the assumption that we may have to do
our cooking on camp stoves, wood stoves or barbecue grills because
of interruptions in electricity or natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K recipes here are also a cut above. While some sites will
tell you how to boil bark, these sound fine at any time. She has
tested them all on her family and urges visitors to contribute.
There is lots of good information at this site, which has an active
forum; and it also touches on ethical and philosophical issues
related to individual and community readiness.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other sites you may want to visit:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cooking When the Power Goes Off'' at www.ext.vt.edu/pubs
</P>
<P>
   /disaster/490-307/490-307.html gives brief but vital safety
information about cooking by alternative methods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dealing With Disaster'' at www.naples.net/govern/county
</P>
<P>
   /emrgmgt/emrginfo.htm has straightforward information on what to
do with perishable food left in a refrigerator or freezer after the
power goes off.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information about storing water is at www.securbar.com
</P>
<P>
   /purewtr.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See www.realfood4realpeople.com/y2k.html for good tips and
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MORE RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   There are some pretty good basic Y2K recipes at 321website.com
</P>
<P>
   /members/home/data/willlorene/y2krecipes.html, but watch those
links _ there is lots of possibly irresponsible talk out there
about martial law, rampaging hordes, conspiracies and those pesky
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Canned Salmon Patties
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 6 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy,'' who submitted this pantry recipe, suggests serving
with instant mashed potatoes and canned peas. You can buy
single-serving packets of mayonnaise from food warehouse stores,
along with single-serving packets of sweet pickle relish. Mix for a
quick tartar sauce. The patties are a bit dry, so if you like add a
tablespoon of mayonnaise before shaping. And if you have some Old
Bay Seasoning, shake in a bit for spice.
</P>
<P>
   1 (8- to 10-ounce) can any brand pink or red salmon; drain,
reserving liquid
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup crushed saltine crackers
</P>
<P>
   1 egg (may use reconstituted dried whole egg or powdered egg
whites)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped green peppers (or dried ones, rehydrated in
reserved liquid)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped onion (or dried ones, rehydrated in reserved
liquid)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon margarine or oil, or cooking spray for sauteeing
</P>
<P>
   Place salmon in a bowl. Pick out and discard bones. Add crushed
crackers, egg, peppers, onion, salt and pepper. Shape mixture into
4 patties. Heat margarine or oil in a skillet, or spray with
cooking spray. Saute patties until brown on both sides, about 3
minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with egg): 230 calories, 14 grams protein, 14 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 55), 11 grams carbohydrates, 72
milligrams cholesterol, 394 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
