<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meringue puffs turn into light, crispy cookies
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lots of us remember meringue cookies, but our recall
takes us through a rainbow of colors and is sometimes dotted with
bits of candy, chocolate chips or nuts.
</P>
<P>
   When June Henderson of Alpharetta (Ga.) asked for ``white puffy
cookies,'' recipes floated in, offering a range of cooking methods
and mix-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Most often the methods called for preheating the oven, then
turning it off and letting the egg white-based cookies sit
overnight, a method that sounds iffy in this day of heightened
salmonella safety. We also tested a recipe that lets you cook the
meringues in a low oven in less than a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out neither method is recommended by the USDA Meat and
Poultry Hotline, unless you use pasteurized egg white products like
Just Whites, according to the USDA's Bessie Berry.
</P>
<P>
   So the choice is yours: risk or safety, ovenight or not. We like
both the quick version and an overnight one from Mrs. John W.
Everage Sr. of Birmingham, both with moist, chewy centers and
crispy outsides.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Forget About Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 cookies
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   In this recipe, the cookies sit overnight in an oven that has
been preheated and then turned off. The cookies are sugary-sweet,
crunchy on the outside and moist and chocolaty in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup broken pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup semi-sweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a medium bowl, beat egg whites
until stiff peaks form. Gradually add sugar, continuing to beat
until incorporated. Add salt. Fold in pecans, then chocolate chips.
Line two small or one large cookie sheet with parchment paper or
clean brown paper. Drop meringue by tablespoonfuls onto sheets.
They will not spread and can be packed closely. Place sheets in
preheated oven. Immediately turn off oven and let the cookies sit
in the oven overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 69 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 53), 9 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 15
milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Snow Meringues
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 dozen
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Marie Geesa of Doraville (Ga.) introduced this recipe by saying
it might not be the one June Henderson remembers, but its advantage
is not having to wait overnight for the cookies to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   4 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups (9 ounces) semi-sweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 275 degrees. Cut baking parchment or baking
paper to fit two cookie sheets _ do not grease. In a medium bowl,
beat egg whites until foamy. Add salt and cream of tartar. Beat
until peaks are stiff. Add sugar, 2 tablespoons at a time, beating
well after each addition. Fold in nuts, chocolate chips and
vanilla. Drop by rounded teaspoonfuls onto baking paper. Bake for
20 to 25 minutes or until golden brown, checking after 20 minutes
to make sure meringue hasn't dried out. With a spatula, remove to
rack to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 68 calories, 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 45), 10 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 18
milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Katherine Smith of Hiram hopes somebody copied two recipes for
kugel that she saw on a cooking show on television. Both noodle
dishes are baked; one included cottage cheese and the other had a
pecan topping and was poured into a bundt pan.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
