<HEADLINE>
HOME-PLATE SPECIALS, FROM PEANUT M&AMP;MS TO PORK TENDERLOIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ We'll get to the food, but first, let me tell
you a story.
</P>
<P>
   I'm supposed to be here _ it's written in my Month At A Glance.
``Interview Joe Macko, Visiting Club House Manager, The Ballpark in
Arlington _ 11 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm here to talk to Macko about feeding high-profile
millionaires night after summer night. Millionaires with names like
Ken Griffey Jr., Paul O'Neill, Darryl Strawberry. Big boys who make
big bucks playing the big game.
</P>
<P>
   I've checked in with security, made my way into the bowels of
the stadium and arrived at Joe's doors _ avoiding towers of hot-dog
buns on wheels and a tour group of elderly gigglers making faces
behind the media room's speakers' table.
</P>
<P>
   But no Joe. I bang on the metal doors. No answer. I try the door
handle. No luck. Then I try another. No go. And then a third. Aha!
_ this one works. And it's the right place. (A food editor can tell
these things _ this room is equipped with two stoves and a
glass-fronted refrigerator.)
</P>
<P>
   I walk into the next room calling for Joe, thinking perhaps he
hasn't heard my knocks. There's further evidence I'm in the right
place _ this room could be my neighborhood 7-Eleven. A plethora of
salty snacks in orange and yellow boxes march along a cabinet; the
cold case is filled with soft drinks and water.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall I go, calling his name.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Macko's kingdom is a suite of rooms strung under the stadium
directly behind the visitors' dugout. There's Joe's office, the
kitchen, the canteen, a bunkhouse and weight rooms. There's an
office for the managing coach. I turn the corner and _ omigosh _
there's Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Lined up in one large room are all the Baltimore Orioles. An
open locker is set for each Bird _ a sign with each player's name
and number oversees his personal equipment. And front and center _
there's Cal Ripken _ no, not in the flesh, but the stuff that
covers his flesh. Four pairs of gray-blue uniform pants, three
pairs of athletic shoes, a pair of Nike flip-flops. And yes, an
athletic supporter, right there, hanging on a hook. Oh ... my.
</P>
<P>
   I'm feeling, well, a little breathless. I've crossed the room
and am 2 feet from Cal's jersey. My father, an Orioles fan since
the Senators left D.C., would pop his buttons knowing my college
education had finally gotten me somewhere worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   I look at the next locker. Uh-oh. Albert Belle. Two gloves, two
pairs of pants, Reebok shower shoes, a bottle of Phisoderm, a
partly used stick of Sunny Magic. (I'm enough my father's daughter
that I know not to mess with Albert Belle, but jeez, I am a
reporter.)
</P>
<P>
   But Belle has cut through my fantasy haze. Where is Joe?
</P>
<P>
   I find a phone and call the public relations folks upstairs,
telling them there seems to be no Joe.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Days were when clubhouses were rollicking,
drink-some-beer-and-cuss-the-umpires dens. Even the rather staid
Rangers were known for some cutting up off the field. A former
pitcher, not to be named later in this story, is rumored to have
shot out the home clubhouse recliners with his shotgun _ clouding
the air and the room's blue carpeting with blasts of fiberfill. Joe
Macko was on the home side of the field then, in the old days at
the old stadium when food meant Gaylen's barbecue and stadium hot
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Now pumpkin seeds, sunflower seeds and, in Macko's clubhouse,
four varieties of bubble gum are offered instead of the tobacco of
years past. And SnackWell cookies are stocked alongside the M&AMP;Ms,
plain and peanut. For the player who has let the big-money contract
increase his snob factor, there are biscotti. But the snack that
disappears quickest? Every 10-year-old's favorite: Cracker Jack.
</P>
<P>
   But this food usually goes to the dugout with the players. If
they want a little something between the weight room and batting
practice, there are salad and sandwich fixings on ice in the
canteen.
</P>
<P>
   There's a George Foreman grill there, too, purchased for Wade
Boggs, who exists on chicken breasts. There's a cooker that's
usually spinning with hot dogs, except when the Yankees are in
town. George Steinbrenner's players aren't allowed the All-American
favorite because the boss says they're difficult to digest.
</P>
<P>
   One unidentified but well-placed source tells me you can often
tell a team's competitiveness by its dining habits. The New York
Yankees apparently eat sparingly before a game; some Kansas City
Royals have been known to tuck into three or four hot dogs
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   PowerAde and bottled water are popular with visiting players, as
is Dr Pepper, a Texas exotic. Protein-vitamin shakes are also big
among the boys. Players will often pop into the clubhouse during a
game to whip up the contents of a powder-protein pouch with some
water.
</P>
<P>
   It's after the game that Macko serves up the main event.
</P>
<P>
   He brings in chef Paul Sable from the Arlington Hilton to cook
up roast chicken, pork loin, tenderloin, macaroni and cheese _ real
food for real men. He's the only clubhouse manager in baseball to
do things in such style _ at Tiger Stadium, the visiting team can
expect delivered pizza.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Joe Macko is 71 and has spent 52 years in baseball. He's as big
as a bear, with hands the size of canned hams. When he arrives (his
Month At A Glance read noon) he's carrying 3 gallons of milk in
grocery bags _ in one hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's just one chore in his day of coddling the visiting Big Boys
of Baltimore. He and his five assistants will polish 80 pairs of
shoes during the week, wash and repair uniforms, try to accommodate
corporate autograph-seekers without annoying players, and set up
lockers.
</P>
<P>
   We talk for about 20 minutes, and he fields three phone-call
requests, one from the Dallas Chamber of Commerce, wanting to
deliver goods for my new best friend, Cal Ripken, to autograph. He
walks a fine line, Macko, knowing his job is to make the visiting
team as comfortable as possible but also understanding the draw
these players have for fans.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed, Macko acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, players hung around after the game,'' Macko
said, ``but these days, if they think they've been called wrong on
a play, they can pop in a videotape in here and see right away if
they were right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Players are certainly coddled more today, but they also work
harder than most fans imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players are usually in the clubhouse around noon. They might
work out in the weight room, then there's batting practice. They're
usually not back to their hotel until 12 or 1 a.m.'' Macko says.
``It's a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   Macko picks up a pair of uniform pants that the seamstress has
left; a good 3-inch patch has meticulously repaired a hole. Macko
has been in baseball long enough to not question such requests,
knowing that although a player may have three other pairs of pants
in his locker, these are his lucky pants. And he knows that
eccentricities and the coddling flow on both sides of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Gonzalez has about 10 or 12 pairs of pants in his
locker,'' Macko says. ``One pair might be 1 inch shorter than the
other, he might have a couple different waist sizes _ maybe he had
a big lunch or something. They all want their bottoms to look good.
They're real conscious of being pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
