<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     09-29 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN SHOW SHOULD BE BACK BY `POPULAR' DEMAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any drama talking boldly about ``the social order of things''
when it comes to the choice of friends is the result of someone
seeing too many teen movies, which is the built-in problem of
``Popular,'' an otherwise promising drama that could very well
prove entertaining and even thoughtful if it plays its cards right.
</P>
<P>
   Uneven pacing and clunky transitions keep the show from reaching
its potential, and the dialogue is so repetitive, constantly
dealing with popularity and acceptance, that it sounds as though
each character is saying the same thing but in different ways.
Worse, the teachers are as clueless as the young minds they're
instructing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the students populating Kennedy High are the stars
here, ``Popular'' zeros in on Brooke (Leslie Bibb) and Sam (Carly
Pope), natural-born enemies because of that whole ``social order''
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke is the blond cheerleader with the quarterback boyfriend
and loaded father; Sam is the dark-haired outsider with the single
mother. Brooke's friend, the annoying Lily (Tamara Mello), seems to
make her friend list according to parental income, so popularity
comes with a price tag.
</P>
<P>
   We're supposed to believe that Brooke is a pretty girl with a
heart _ simply a victim of her dad's wealth, if you want to look at
it that way. It's obvious that she harbors some of the same
materialistic image concerns of Lily, such as when her boyfriend
informs her of his intentions to quit the football team to
participate in a school play.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, Brooke warns him that they'll never make homecoming
court if he's ``a drama geek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' she says shortly after. ``I can't believe I said that.''
</P>
<P>
   The lines are blurred even more because Sam hates Brooke for
stepping over the little people, yet seems obsessed with those who
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dawns on you,'' Sam says when talking about popularity and
looks, ``you'll never be a `Seventeen' girl because they don't
allow air-brushing in real life.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they did, Sam would probably be the first in line.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the kind of ambiguity that would give ``Popular''
sizzle and set it apart from this season's busload of teen-angst
TV. What keeps me feeling that the series has potential are dead-on
scenes, such as when Brooke is looking in a full-length mirror and
pinching the fat around her waist. The girl looks like a pencil.
But there she is, asking Lily, ``Am I too fat?'' That's scary.
</P>
<P>
   Just as encouraging is what happens at the end of the second
episode (which I won't spoil here). It airs Thursday on WB, in the
series' regular day and time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm rooting for ``Popular,'' but I've got a feeling the series
will fall victim to the very dilemma it's exploring: In order for
it to be popular with viewers, it may opt for the easy way out, get
soapy and silly, and forget its original premise. Let's hope not.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
