<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GA-LIGHTHOUSE-0930-CO     09-29 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LIGHTHOUSE-0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ST. SIMONS ISLAND LIGHTHOUSE MUSEUM IS HONORED AT WHITE HOUSE
 &HT;    Attn Georgia Editors
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle categories
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton presented a
national award for public service to Georgia's St. Simons Island
Lighthouse Museum on Wednesday at a White House ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny museum housed below the landmark lighthouse has a
full-time staff of only three but won the National Award for Museum
Service along with Chicago's Lincoln Park Zoo and the Nevada Museum
of Art in Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``This national award is a tribute to the power of museums to
engage children, families and communities in towns and cities all
across America,'' the First Lady noted in prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The Lighthouse Museum was honored for an innovative heritage
education program that is used in every school in Glynn County _ on
the barrier islands and mainland _ and reaches over 11,000
students. Utilizing all the historic sites and museums in the
county, the program pushes students to examine their community's
history and how it relates to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach children that there are buildings in their hometown
that are just as historic and important as those in Washington,
D.C.,'' said Linda Orr King, executive director of the St. Simons
museum. The museum is operated by the Coastal Georgia Historical
Society.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in the U.S. Capitol before the White House
ceremony, King described how the staff recently implemented its
emergency plan as Hurricane Floyd threatened the island.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations began about five days before Floyd's predicted
arrival, she said. With the museum located a scant hundred yards or
so from the beach, the most valuable artifacts were taken to safer
sites. Shutters were battened down and windows sealed with duck
tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take care of the museum first, then your own house
and your own family,'' said King.
</P>
<P>
   Then the island was ordered evacuated. ``We just prayed
everything would be okay,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the hurricane veered to the north and largely missed
the south Georgia coast.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were given by the U.S. Institute of Museum and
Library Services, a federal agency based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Community outreach is an increasingly important part of museum
``vision,'' said Beverly Sheppard, acting director of the
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, museums are asking ``What is our purpose?'' and
``Who do we serve?'' she said. The three honored museums ``have
answered those questions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Park Zoo, which attracts four million visitors a
year, was honored for an intern program for needy high school
students and a development program for Chicago public school
teachers. The Nevada Museum of Art was honored for a program to
redirect kids involved in graffiti vandalism into art education and
an inter-generational arts program for families.
</P>
<P>
   Past winners have included the Corcoran Gallery of Art in
Washington, D.C.; Houston's Museum of Fine Arts; the National
Aquarium in Baltimore and the Brooklyn Children's Museum.
</P>
<P>
   As the St. Simons Lighthouse Museum joined this group, King
marveled at ``what can be accomplished (by) a small staff and
dedicated volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
