<HEADER>
A0408 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-FRAGILE30-COX     09-29 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-FRAGILE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `The Fragile' nails Trent Reznor's pain
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sufferin' succotash! Trent Reznor wants you to feel his pain.
</P>
<P>
   And there are oceans of it. The songwriter who performs as Nine
Inch Nails has just released what is only his third full-length
album in a decade, a cinemascopic double CD that maps the torture
in his soul while heeding the minimum nightly requirements for
decadent dance beats and eerie, penumbral grooves. After the
success of NiN's ``The Downward Spiral'' five years ago broke the
dense, S&AMP;M-spiked sounds of industrial rock for the Gap-browsing
mainstream, the sullen but chic Reznor has enjoyed visionary
status. Along with rap's growing influence, he made the current
bombast of heavy rock acts Limp Bizkit and Korn commercially
feasible, foisted Marilyn Manson on the world and did some
compelling soundtrack work with directors Oliver Stone and David
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Recording ``The Fragile'' must have posed a real trauma for
Reznor who, like such rock star/auteurs as Billy Corgan and the
Artist, is a perfectionist whose persona is inseparable from his
songs. Musically, he's risen to the occasion, creating often
complex and surprising soundscapes that can pulse demonically or
unfold as the quietly dramatic backdrop for a private psychological
movie reel. Lyrically, Reznor's still deeply immersed in a
crucifixion syndrome: He's the Jesus of nihilism. He begs us to
``taste the wealth of hate in me'' (``Somewhat Damaged''), concedes
that he ``tried to save myself but my self keeps slipping away''
(``Into the Void'') and observes that ``the heavens fall but still
we crawl'' (``The Way Out Is Through''). Reznor's introspective
rage sometimes yields to beauty _ stray glimmers of light pierce
his mine-shaft sensibility _ but for all the studio-crafted
complexity that surrounds it, the singer's worldview is punishingly
narrow.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fragile''
</P>
<P>
   Nine Inch Nails. Nothing Records/Interscope. 23 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
