<HEADER>
A0409 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS30-COX     09-29 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini music reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Eileen Drennen and Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Skin Deep''
</P>
<P>
   Sole. Dreamworks Records. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the name on the spine of this album, this is a Foxy
Brown record. No, not the Foxy Brown who raps, but Foxy Brown the
cocksure '70s film persona that the hip-hop artist modeled herself
after. Like the onscreen character, Sole is able to adapt to any of
the vibrant and almost sampleless backdrops: a carjacking (the
engaging ``Da Story''), a boyfriend cheating (first single
``4,5,6'' and the Latin-like ``It Wasn't Me'') or simply a party
starter (former No. 1 single ``Who Dat''). On this debut, Sole ably
plays the role of a swaggering, gun-slinging, skillful rhyme-sayer
backed by fellow Atlantan and underappreciated producer ``Tricky''
Stewart. But the scariest thing about this always collected cover
girl is when the dust she kicks up settles and the credits roll,
there probably won't be a hair on her head out of place.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Stars''
</P>
<P>
   Lori Carson. Restless. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   More spells than songs, Lori Carson's three-minute incantations
are hypnotic in the best possible way. Like a flame, they pull your
gaze into a place you probably couldn't get to on your own. On
this, her fourth solo album, her whispers seem more celebratory _
``in spite of everything,'' runs one chorus, ``I feel a little bit
hopeful again.'' She's always gonna be the girl who checks the
shadows first, she's just seeing more sun. There are layers of
instrumentation and programmed tricks _ in ``Breathe,'' a
high-pitched buzzing accompanies the lines ``synapses short-circuit
/ misfire away.'' Carson used a computer to wash the basic tracks
with more texture _ risky, since her songs are feathery to begin
with. But the disembodied atmospherics work, spinning around her
quiet soprano like a nimbus.
</P>
<P>
   _Eileen M. Drennen
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Tight Rope''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks &AMP; Dunn. Arista. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   With Ronnie Dunn's narcotic vocals and Kix Brook's boundless
cowboy energy, this hot country duo is at the point where they
could put careers on cruise control and still have hits. At the
recent Country Music Associations Awards, it certainly sounded like
their new CD might be a case of coasting when they performed the
sounds-just-like-boot-scoot assembly-line song ``Beer Thirty.''
About a third of the tracks here are, indeed, lazy retread riffs
and hat tricks off past hits. Even the first single, a cover of the
1980s John Waite pop tune ``Missing You,'' seems like a limp
attempt to cash in on the success of ``My Maria.'' But the
premonitions are wrong. On much of their seventh CD, Brooks &AMP; Dunn
deliver crisp country that is as satisfying as swigging Coca-Cola
out of a glass bottle. The nuggets are all tunes penned by Dunn.
``Going Under Gettin' Over You'' is a pedal-steel piner that has
the tall Texan spitting out whiskey-and-cigarettes lyrics. ``Hurt
Train'' weaves a lonesome Texas wind-sounding guitar behind Dunn's
moans of ``Here I sit loaded, wonderin' what went wrong/The whiskey
I can hold it, but I don't know how long.''
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Eileen Drennen and Miriam Longino write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
