<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0410 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-NEW30-COX     09-29 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-NEW30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amos finds a band for trip to `Venus'
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The girl with the piano clearly likes being part of a band. With
last year's ``From the Choirgirl Hotel,'' Tori Amos set a new
course with a full-time band and a more organic sound, and the
result was her best work yet.
</P>
<P>
   If this new album is any indication, Amos was happy with that
direction. ``Bliss,'' the lead track and first single, floats along
on a lovely piano figure until the band kicks in on the propulsive
chorus.
</P>
<P>
   That's a description that could be used for much of the last
album, too, but this isn't ``From the Choirgirl Hotel,'' Part 2,
though. There are tracks that might have come from any stage of her
career. The minimal, droning ``Suede'' could sit comfortably on
1996's ``Boys for Pele.'' The experimentalism of that album returns
in more refined form on several other cuts, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Amos' fiercely loyal fans longing for the early
girl-with-a-piano days will hear an echo of those years on the
final track, ``1000 Oceans,'' but she's come too far to play that
role very often without tossing in a few extras. ``Concertina''
sounds more singer/songwriter-like than anything she's done in
years, at least until the bridge, where a rumbling, phased guitar
throws the whole thing off-balance. It's a telling moment. She's no
longer content with traditional notions of prettiness, but Amos can
make the most disconcerting effects sound like a kind of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of this two-CD set is a memento of Amos' 1998
``Plugged'' tour, and, like many live albums, it doesn't quite
capture the electric atmosphere of the live shows. It's
well-recorded, expertly played and a great keepsake for the fans,
but hardly essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Venus and Back''
</P>
<P>
   Tori Amos. Atlantic. 24 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
