A0412 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MAIN30-COX     09-29 0258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MAIN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video of the week
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Mummy'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Mummy, make it stop! Yeah, that's a terrible pun, but it gives
you some idea of the sophomoric almost-humor that thuds throughout
this computer effects-laden box office hit.
</P>
<P>
   Just because a movie has desert scenery, a hunky action hero
(Brendan Fraser), hissable bad guys and supernatural hoodoo doesn't
make it an Indiana Jones movie. You'll miss Steven Spielberg's
masterful touch watching this petrified mix of retro adventure,
clumsy slapstick and minimal chills. The movie even begs the
comparison by having one character mutter, ``I hate bugs.'' It may
remind us of Indy's snake phobia, but also makes us miss Indy all
the more.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fraser plays an adventurer who heads into the Egyptian
desert with a comely Egyptologist (played with abrasive prissiness
by Rachel Weisz). Entering the cursed tombs, they encounter
voracious scarabs and a flesh-sucking dead prince, and a lot of
secondhand action and jokes. Stephen Sommers wrote and directed
``The Mummy,'' so he deserves double blame for the lameness. He's
also responsible for last year's awful ``Deep Rising.'' Apparently
the money guys at Universal forgot to watch that movie before
signing Sommers. Forget Imhotep. That's the real curse. (Priced to
buy: VHS $22.98; DVD, $29.98.)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
