<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Florida town an art, antiques mecca
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA, Fla. _ When the shade tobacco business went belly up
back in the 1960s, this little wide-spot-in-the-road town on U.S.
27 just about rolled up the sidewalks. Nothing much happened for
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   A renaissance began in 1984 when Lee Hotchkiss and Keith
Henderson moved their Tallahassee antiques shop to an ivy-covered
brick building at Main Street and Seventh Avenue in the heart of
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;H Antiques became the cornerstone of what is now one of the
Southeast's largest arts and antiques centers. This month,
Tallahassee Magazine bestowed its Best Antiques Shop award
collectively to all of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Although businesses have come and gone in the past 15 years,
there are nearly 40 merchants, galleries and cafes _ plenty to keep
a visitor busy for a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend the town will be abuzz with the 4th Annual Havana
Bead and Jewelry Festival at Havana's Cannery. And looking even
further ahead, Havana MusicFest 2000 is set for March 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   Havana (population 1,500) pushes ahead like the Little Engine
That Could despite the deaths this year of two of its biggest
boosters: watercolorist Lee Mainella, who founded the Florida Art
Center and Gallery, and Paul Nicholson, founder of the popular
Nicholson Farmhouse Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost two pillars of the community,'' says Sandi Beare,
co-owner of Mirror Image Antiques and self-appointed one-woman
visitors bureau. ``They are the type of people who inspire you to
carry on. We would be remiss if we did not continue'' what they
pioneered.
</P>
<P>
   While the town made its reputation as an art and antiques mecca,
Beare says, ``We are becoming an international design marketplace.
It's fun what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirror Image specializes in antiques (``no reproductions,''
Beare insists), collectibles, fishing collectibles and baseball and
sports memorabilia. The space also includes The Vault Art Gallery
inside a 1906 bank vault.
</P>
<P>
   Beare's father, Richard Beare, runs Lord Beare's Gourmet
Specialities in a small pantry in the back of the shop. Among the
dozens of items are English teas, McVitie's Original Digestion
Biscuits, Scott's Porage Oats, clotted cream and ready-to-heat
frozen entrees such as Cornish pasties and Scottish beef bridies.
</P>
<P>
   Next door is Little River General Store, where proprietor Rita
Love stocks kitchen gadgets, country gourmet foods, wooden and
metal toys (no plastic!), gardening tools, household cleaning
agents, natural health and beauty aids, Woolrich clothing and much,
much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a froufrou gift shop,'' says Love. ``Everything I
sell is useful and has a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an old-fashioned candy counter in the front of the
store. ``People come in all the time and notice the Necco wafers
and say they haven't seen them in years,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At H&AMP;H Antiques, where it all started, Hotchkiss and Henderson
are helping clients select furniture and upholstery from their
Norwalk line. They've expanded from antiques and now offer
custom-made heart pine and cherry reproductions made by local
craftsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday and Sunday, the town is packed,'' says Hotchkiss,
who lives above the store with her husband/business partner.
``People like it that you're usually dealing directly with the
owner of the store. You get better service.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the H&AMP;H team, Christy Parks Witt and her family live in the
hundred-year-old house where she runs her business, the Berry
Patch. The shop not only offers quality antiques, Heirloom lace and
a line of bath and home aromatherapy products but welcomes guests
to the Tea Room on Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great summer,'' says Witt. ``We're seeing a lot of
tourists, but the local folks are getting smart and keeping their
money in our county. Tons of people are moving in. You can raise
your family here. It's more like Mayberry RFD.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks away at Havana's Cannery is a
31,000-square-foot antiques mall with more than 100 antiques
dealers _ plus Rafters Interior Market and Shade restaurant. The
building was home to the Havana Canning Co., built in 1934 (green
peanuts were first canned in Havana in 1946) and, later, Cal's
Tupelo Honey. Owner Trey Morgan, a Tallahasseean who started the
antiques mall in 1994, still turns out small batches of sauces,
such as honey mustard, barbecue and citrus ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a spark here,'' says Morgan. ``It's been here awhile.
It's not an easy business we've picked, but I'm sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan predicts Havana's best days are yet to come. ``It takes
time. Lee Minella knew how to do it. He taught me. It's coming to
fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 south to I-185; continue until I-185
ends in south Columbus, then pick up U.S. 27 south. Follow this
highway; watch signs for turns, but stay on U.S. 27 through
Bainbridge and directly into Havana, which is 12 miles north of
Tallahassee. It's about a five-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open Wednesdays through Sundays (a few
are open Mondays and Tuesdays), most from 10 a.m. until 5 or 6
p.m., except noon-5 p.m. Sundays. The Cannery is open until 10 p.m.
on Fridays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free parking on street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are generally accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: No municipal facilities, but some businesses,
notably the Cannery, have public restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 850-539-4852.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nicholson Farmhouse: After a long day of shopping, you'll need
hearty sustenance, and you'll find it at this complex of old
farmhouses on a 50-acre tract of woods and pasture on Fla. 12, 3
1/2 miles west of town. The main dining room is in the 140-year-old
Nicholson House, where ``wet-aged'' steaks ($12.95-$25.95), lamb
chops ($17.95) and shrimp Nicholson Farmhouse-style ($18.95) are
among the offerings. Boiled peanuts are brought to the table with
the water. 4-10 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays. Reservations advised.
850-539-5931.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shade: As in shade tobacco. This diner inside the Cannery
features a tobacco-leaf decor and New Southern Cuisine. Lunch
specialties include a fried green tomato sandwich with goat cheese
crumbles or a fried catfish sandwich with jalapeno tartar sauce
(both $6, served with choice of hot stir-fried slaw, sweet potato
haystack or cheese grits cake); grilled country sausage with beans
and rice topped with the Cannery's own mustard sauce ($7). Save
room for homemade desserts. Lunch 11:30 a.m.-3:30 p.m.
Wednesdays-Sundays; supper 5-9:30 p.m. Fridays and Saturdays. 115
E. Eighth Ave. 850-539-3800.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dolly's Expresso Cafe: Lunch specials include a half Cuban
sandwich with a side of black beans and yellow rice ($5.40) and a
chicken salad plate ($6.50). Also, specialty coffee drinks, ice
cream and desserts. 11 a.m.-4:30 p.m. Tuesdays-Thursdays (until
5:30 Fridays and Saturdays) and noon-5 p.m. Sundays. 206 First St.
N.W. 850-539-6716.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Historic Havana House Bed &AMP; Breakfast: Bunking at this 1907
home in a residential area two blocks from the shopping district is
like staying with relatives. Your hosts will be innkeepers Bruce
and Shirley Gaver. There are two guest rooms with private bathrooms
in this renovated dwelling that was built by the first mayor of
Havana. The entrance is at the back door, where you're likely to be
greeted by Whiskers the tabby cat. There's a small garden as well
as a screened porch with a swing. Art and stained glass _ much of
it created by the Gavers _ along with antiques and collectibles
brighten the interior. Rates are $80 and $90, including a full
country breakfast. 301 E. Sixth Ave. Reservations: 850-539-5611 or
visit www.electro-net.com/(tilde)sgaver.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 4th Annual Havana
</P>
<P>
   and Jewelry Festival: More than 100 bead makers, distributors
and jewelry artists are expected to gather this weekend at The
Cannery, 115 E. 8th Ave. Hours are 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday and 11
a.m.-5 p.m. Sunday. Admission is $3. Information: 850-539-3800.
</P>
<P>
   Shop talk
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of shops in Havana
</P>
