<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0437 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-FAMILIES-GRIEF-2TAKES     09-29 2475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILIES-GRIEF-2TAKES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVES OF TEEN, HOMELESS VET FOLLOW TRAGIC PATH, LEAVING FAMILIES TO
MOURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photos available for nyt clients)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There are many ways to measure a life. Jobs held and
lost, lovers come and gone. But no one expects the sum of a man to
fit inside a paper bag.
</P>
<P>
   That's almost all Marceline and Thomas Ballenger have left of
their son _ the lunch sack Seattle police gave them. It is filled
with crinkled papers from temp jobs, grimy cards from shelters and
drug counselors: scraps of a street life that ended in the worst
way.
</P>
<P>
   David Ballenger was stabbed 18 times Aug. 9, allegedly in an
attack by three teenagers under the trash-strewn freeway overpass
he called home. One of his attackers reportedly boasted afterward:
``One less bum on the face of the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``bum'' flashes like a lightning bolt inside the Bay
City, Ore., living room of David's parents. The couple remember a
devoted son who worked hard (when he did work). A generous man who
loved Hank Williams music. A fragile man who wore his soul on his
shirtsleeves and balmed the sting of setbacks with booze. They say
David slipped away from life before it was savagely taken.
</P>
<P>
   Waves of grief crumple Thomas Ballenger's 72-year-old body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot sleep,'' he wails. ``Those boys have ruined whatever
days we have left.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife sits nearby on a couch and cradles the paper bag like a
newborn baby. She survived heart surgery this spring. But this sort
of hurt she has not known in her 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart was fixed, but now it is broken again,'' Marceline
Ballenger says, her eyes a fountain of tears. ``Nothing can take
away that pain. Everyone dies, but to die that way. ... David was
not a bum. He may have been homeless. He was not loveless.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of miles away, in his verdant Seattle back yard,
Patrick Caffee sits in the sun and grieves. It is hard for him to
accept that his son, Michael Vittorio Caffee, may have had a hand
in something so unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   He says Michael _ a dirt-bike rider and an aspiring chef who
liked to listen to the heavy-metal band Megadeth _ was with the
wrong crowd when events took a wild and tragic turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael wasn't the guy who (stabbed him). He was a kid who
just happened to be there,'' says Patrick Caffee. But his hopeful
note wavers when he realizes that his son could go to prison for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   No trial date has been set for Michael Caffee, 19, or the two
others _ Shelton Musgrave, 18, and Jay Stewart, 17, a juvenile who
will be treated as an adult. The three have pleaded not guilty to
second-degree murder and remain in jail. The Stewart and Musgrave
families declined requests for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a parent, I am worried about how he is going to be as a
human being after this,'' Patrick Caffee says. ``I don't want him
to become some animal.''
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy evokes a mystery for social workers, psychologists
and parents, who seek to know why youths turn violent, and what _
if anything _ such acts say about society.
</P>
<P>
   For many, David's death strikes a nerve because it involves
young people from decent backgrounds, preying on one of society's
most vulnerable, faceless groups: the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   For Patrick Caffee, for the Ballengers, each passing day brings
anger, sadness and a hard question: How did once-promising lives
collide on a summer evening near a freeway?
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) When I pass by all the people say
</P>
<P>
   Just another guy on the lost highway (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Hank Williams
</P>
<P>
   David Ballenger arrived by breech birth in Fresno, Calif., on
July 25, 1953 _ the middle child of parents who gave each of their
children names that began with ``D'': the eldest, Daniel; David;
and Diane, the baby.
</P>
<P>
   A picture taken just days later shows a sparkling infant with
fuzzy wisps of hair, chubby cheeks and blue-green eyes set off by
the slightly crooked smile that David would keep for life.
</P>
<P>
   He was a mother's dream, so quiet as an infant he had to be
awakened at feeding times. On his first day of school, his mother
escorted him back to kindergarten five times. ``He would just turn
around and beat a track back home,'' she recalled. ``I'd hear a
knock-knock at the door.''
</P>
<P>
   When David was 9, and his sister Diane was 2 months old, he
bought her a rubber duck. Later on, he added a Ringo Starr doll. He
was forever splurging allowance money on her.
</P>
<P>
   In David's younger years a slight speech impediment cropped up.
He tapped his blossoming humor to deal with it. One time David told
his mother he wanted a NAYonnaise sandwich. Fine, she said, but he
had to say mayonnaise correctly. He responded: ``I'll have peanut
butter and jelly, please.''
</P>
<P>
   The family moved around as Thomas Ballenger, a plasterer by
trade, sought places where construction jobs were plentiful. They
settled in Dixon, Calif., near the University of California at
Davis. After he fell off a ladder and shattered a leg, Thomas found
work as a barber.
</P>
<P>
   David attended Dixon High School, where he was a B to C student.
He joined the wrestling team and earned a certificate of award for
the sport when he was a senior.
</P>
<P>
   He had a knack for woodwork, carving boxes and ornate frames
around mirrors. He dabbled with ceramic arts, fashioning red and
blue vases that were smooth but askew. Imperfect. His mother held
onto the crafts as if they were priceless treasures, the way moms
do.
</P>
<P>
   David and his father loved to fish. ``We had a saying in the
family,'' Thomas Ballenger said with a rumbling chuckle. ```Put a
fishhook in the bathtub and David would catch you a fish!'''
</P>
<P>
   The boy liked to reach out to others in need. He helped tutor a
fellow high school student from Mexico. Under David's guidance, the
student graduated.
</P>
<P>
   In his senior year, David brought home a family of ducks that
had strayed from a nearby pond. He thought the ducks were homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Like most teens, David was eager to get behind the wheel. During
an early driver's test he exited a parking lot through its entrance
as the examiner looked on. He eventually passed and was soon
tooling around in his parents' pink Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   One night, he took the car out and returned it at the promised
time _ with a dent in the rear fender. David said someone had hit
the car and zoomed off.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as Marceline Ballenger was lying in bed at night, she
felt a tug.
</P>
<P>
   It was David.
</P>
<P>
   He could not sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama,'' the teen whispered, ``I can't lie to you. I bent the
fender on a fencepost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' his mother recalled, ``was the kind of kid he was.''
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) Your life is like a trigger
</P>
<P>
   Never trouble till you're squeezed (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Megadeth
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caffee was born Aug. 26, 1980, in Santa Fe, N.M., the
youngest child of Patrick Caffee and Donna Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Caffee and Ramirez divorced. Patrick Caffee, a union
electrician, returned to his roots in Seattle. He moved Michael and
his older sister Carleigh to a handsome, turn-of-the-century wood
home on a quiet drive in the Green Lake neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Michael attended Green Lake Elementary School. He was small for
his age but possessed an outsized spirit. He was held back a year
because of his slight frame and what appeared to be a learning
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways he was a typical, bubbly kid. He loved biking and
skateboarding and earned a nickname around the house: ``Crash
Caffee.''
</P>
<P>
   One time he was 15 feet up an apple tree, waving and yelling
like Huck Finn, when the branch snapped. He crashed. Another time,
riding his bike, he took an impossibly sharp turn. He crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael was disappointed to discover there were many Michaels at
his grade school. So he conjured another nickname, drawing on a
shortened version of his middle name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vito'' was born.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael got older, his trouble with reading and writing
worsened. He had trouble processing information and ``seeing the
big picture,'' his father said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Michael did not duck challenges. In the fourth grade, he
was narrator in a school Christmas play and memorized his lines,
his father said.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighborhood, Michael became known for his smile and
warmth; his good nature masked his increasing frustration with
school.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth grade, he transferred to Meany Middle School, where
class was a chore. Patrick Caffee decided a change of environment
might help.
</P>
<P>
   So Michael was sent to Albuquerque, where his mother works as a
receptionist in a public defender's office. He stayed in New Mexico
for grades eight and nine. But his grades continued to slip; he
skipped school to hang out with friends. His parents decided to let
him come back to Seattle for the rest of high school.
</P>
<P>
   Michael first went to Ingraham High _ his dad's alma mater _ and
then to Marshall Secondary Alternative School, which offers special
education programs for students with learning difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee said Michael's prospects at Marshall dimmed when
the school imposed stringent, test-based standards.
</P>
<P>
   One friend said Michael did not like some of his teachers at
Marshall and disliked some fellow students, particularly the ones
who were into drugs. Michael transferred to Nathan Hale High School
for the 11th and 12th grades; he is a few credits shy of graduating
with the winter class of 2000, his father said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee said his son was a joy to raise. Sure, there were
times when Michael _ like other kids _ chattered too much in class;
times when Michael got into scrapes and, more often than not, was
on the losing, bruising end.
</P>
<P>
   No worries. Boys being boys.
</P>
<P>
   Michael grew up and filled out a bit _ sprouting to 5 feet 9
inches and 145 pounds _ with blue eyes, brown hair and clean-cut
freshness, straight out of a ``Party of Five'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee said that the only trouble Michael got into with
the law as he grew up was when Seattle police scolded him for a
``capital'' offense _ he wrote his name in big letters in wet
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) Everything I loved, I lost, dear
</P>
<P>
   too many times I've watched my castles fall (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Hank Williams
</P>
<P>
   David graduated from high school at 17, then bucked his parents'
wish that he go to college. Instead he joined his older brother,
who had moved to Sacramento to work at a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Then David landed a job in San Francisco carrying hod _ a trough
that holds mortar and bricks _ for plasterers. Soon, he met the
only woman who ever really touched his heart. His parents have a
name for her _ The Fatal Woman.
</P>
<P>
   They said David rescued the woman and her two children from an
abusive man who had forced her to work the streets as a prostitute
for drug money.
</P>
<P>
   They dated for about two years. The woman decided to go on a
brief trip to visit her family, returning in two weeks with a
bombshell: During her time away she had aborted a fetus they had
conceived together.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just utterly devastated him,'' his mother said. ``He
could not handle it. That was the beginning. ...''
</P>
<P>
   David and the woman broke up, and he never forgave her.
</P>
<P>
   His father urged David not to wallow in grief. Grab life by the
reins, Thomas Ballenger said. If you don't find out what you want
do by age 30, he warned, it'll be too late.
</P>
<P>
   David listened.
</P>
<P>
   He headed to the military, pleasing his dad, who had served in
World War II aboard the USS Terror, a Navy mine-laying vessel.
</P>
<P>
   David chose the Army, figuring it would give him a marketable
trade. He enlisted in early 1977, records show, and was stationed
at Fort Knox, Ky. But David soon developed severe allergic
reactions _ ``constant breaking out in hives,'' one Army report
read.
</P>
<P>
   On March 15, 1977, he was honorably discharged as an Army
private. His parents said he was allergic to the wool fabric in
military uniforms, and to grass and weeds; military records also
show David complained about ``nerves;'' his sister said he always
broke out when he became nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Again, David was bitterly disappointed. He briefly returned to
his parents' home in California before embarking on a string of
run-of-the-mill jobs for several years across the West.
</P>
<P>
   In Wyoming, an employer promised him room, board and good pay.
When David showed up, the employer reneged. ``Gullible. That one
word sums up David,'' his mother said. ``He trusted everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   David briefly dropped off the family radar. He resurfaced at a
veterans rehabilitation center in Pocatello, Idaho, undergoing
treatment for alcoholism. It was the first glaring sign he was
medicating himself with the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, his parents invited him to their new home in
Bay City, a pastoral area of fog-shrouded beaches and green hills
along Oregon's northern coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Ballengers' beige and blue mobile home is in dairy country,
a dash away from the Tillamook Cheese Factory. David liked the
place, but trouble would not stay away.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, he was stabbed in the hand on a camping
outing. Reports of the incident are sketchy. Patrick Voris, an
ex-convict, was arrested and convicted in Tillamook County for
second-degree assault.
</P>
<P>
   David took several entry-level jobs in the area. Tax records
show he logged time with a fish and crab company, and also,
beginning in April 1997, at the Tillamook Country Smoker, which
touts its product as ``Beef Jerky That Won the West!''
</P>
<P>
   After two months, David was let go. Doug Lee, the company's
personnel manager, recalled David suddenly stopped showing up. Lee
said David told people he had gotten another job paying twice as
much.
</P>
<P>
   A month later David returned to the smoker and took a small
quantity of meat. He was charged with second-degree burglary, a
felony, and was sentenced to a short period in jail, plus 18
months' probation.
</P>
<P>
   David's parents dispute the account provided by the smoker
company and court records. They said David had been given the meat
_ about $11 worth, they said _ by a co-worker who had told him it
was too old to sell. When David got in trouble for having the meat
he took the fall because he did not want to get his former
co-worker in trouble, his parents said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, Thomas and Marceline Ballenger enjoyed
having David home. A neighbor learned David was living at home and
offered unsolicited advice to his parents: ``I would kick the bum
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ballengers don't have much to say to that neighbor any more.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, David figured it was time to move on. His parents
begged him to stay, but he wanted a change. He wanted to go to the
place he had remembered visiting with his family during the 1962
World's Fair _ a place where people were nice and jobs plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Destination _ Seattle.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
