</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV03-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP'S INTERNAL WARFARE IS MORE IDEOLOGICAL THAN THE DEMOCRATS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 3)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Internecine warfare early in a presidential
campaign is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the White House aspirants in each party have been
growling at one another so ferociously that they're making even
full-throated Jesse Ventura sound like tiny, soft-spoken Tinker
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Although both parties have intense leadership struggles, the
showdown in the GOP is more deeply ideological than that in the
Democratic Party between Vice President Al Gore and former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican battle is a classic confrontation between the
forces of centrism and those of the right _ a fight that the GOP
has repeated frequently since 1912 when former President Theodore
Roosevelt sought unsuccessfully to become future President Theodore
Roosevelt by wresting the GOP nomination from then President
William Howard Taft.
</P>
<P>
   It is a conflict that pitted internationalist Wendell L. Willkie
against conservatives Robert Taft and Thomas Dewey in 1940;
moderate Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower against Taft in 1952;
progressive Nelson Rockefeller against conservative Barry Goldwater
in 1964; conservative Ronald Reagan against Gerald Ford in 1976 and
Reagan against centrist George Bush in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The centrist candidate won the nomination in 1940, 1952 and
1976; the conservative, in 1964 and 1980. (In 1912, after Roosevelt
lost the Republican nod, he bolted the GOP, formed the Progressive
Party and ran as its candidate. He and Taft both lost to Democrat
Woodrow Wilson.)
</P>
<P>
   Recently Republican presidential contender Gary Bauer said in a
CNN interview, ``There is a very brutal battle under way for the
heart and soul of this party.'' Bauer hopes that conservative
fundamentalists, like himself, will prevail over the centrists.
</P>
<P>
   But that's like expecting a community college to rush out onto
the gridiron and defeat Penn State or Florida State. The odds are
that it won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Before he quit the campaign, Dan Quayle told a New Hampshire
audience that grass-roots conservatives are extremely concerned
that the GOP is veering away from its right-wing philosophy in its
eagerness to anoint Texas Gov. George W. Bush as the party's
candidate next year.
</P>
<P>
   Urging a debate among Republican contenders over ``ideas,'' the
former vice president suggested that party leaders who are flocking
to Bush are interested only in winning an election and not in
preserving party principles. ``A campaign without ideas,'' said
Quayle, ``is no campaign at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But the volatile and controversial Patrick Buchanan has
intensified the turmoil in the Republican Party with some explosive
ideas of his own.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``A Republic, Not an Empire,'' Buchanan lays
out a shocking and fraudulent revision of recent history.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the isolationist and protectionist xenophobe, Buchanan
asserts that America's participation in World Wars I and II was
totally unnecessary. He contends that the vicious aggression of
Nazi Germany in Europe and Imperial Japan in Asia did not endanger
the national interests of the United States and that therefore
America should have remained neutral.
</P>
<P>
   In his narrow analysis of historical events, he seems unable to
grasp the great truth of the century: America saved western
civilization and preserved its heritage by defeating the evil
German-Japanese-Italian axis in World War II and then by containing
communist expansion with aid to Greece and Turkey, helping Europe
with the Marshall Plan and NATO, and fighting communist North
Korea's invasion of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Those gargantuan achievements could not have been accomplished
by a nation hiding blindly in isolation behind its Atlantic and
Pacific moats.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's outrageous views prompted another GOP presidential
hopeful, Arizona Sen. John McCain, a Vietnam prisoner of war, to
declare that the bombastic commentator had severed his ties with
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of Quayle and the anticipated leap of
Buchanan to the Reform Party _ if it will have him _ the right-wing
team has been reduced to Bauer, Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes. The
centrist squad consists of George W. Bush, McCain and Elizabeth
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Before Quayle's withdrawal, New Hampshire Sen. Robert Smith, a
doctrinaire right-winger, and moderate conservatives Rep. John
Kasich, R-Ohio, and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander had
abandoned their quests for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, instead of dwelling on his philosophical differences
with Governor Bush, asserted that the greatest obstacle to his
campaign was the expectation that Bush could raise as much as $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   That is a formidable obstacle for any candidate to hurtle. Only
multimillionaire Forbes has the money to fight Bush
dollar-for-dollar. But McCain, by virtue of his honesty and
independence as well as his experience in the military, may
surprise us.
</P>
<P>
   As Bauer said, the battle now under way is for the heart and
soul of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 the right wing demanded ``a choice, not an echo.'' But
after Goldwater's defeat by Lyndon Johnson that year, the call that
conservatives heard was an echo. Richard Nixon was elected
president in 1968, and he, like his successor Gerald Ford, swam
triumphantly in the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as we know from history, the side that wins will not
prevail forever. At best, it will have a tenuous hold on the
party's ideology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
