<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0442 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-FAMILIES-GRIEF-2ndTAK     09-29 3051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILIES-GRIEF-2ndTAKE-SPI </SLUG>
  
 SEATTLE: Destination _ Seattle.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Italics) There's no turning back
</P>
<P>
   Even if we could (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Megadeth
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, friends and co-workers describe Michael Caffee as ``a
good kid.'' They said he is passionate about dirt-bike stunts and
will beg you to watch him perform; he enjoys cooking and took a
culinary class at North Seattle Community College; he's a ready
baby sitter for parents who have to run a quick errand; he doesn't
like to see other people in pain or being dissed.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Denise Watson said her husband asked Michael to look
out for her when she was home sick in bed and her husband was at
work. ``I woke up and saw Vito sitting on my bedroom floor watching
TV,'' she recalled. ``He asked me if I needed anything like juice
from the store.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, he missed the school bus by seconds. So neighbor Erik
Seth volunteered to drive him.
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, Seth heard footsteps on his porch. He looked
outside and found a thank you note in his mail slot.
</P>
<P>
   A former employer of Michael's marveled over his ``gift'' to
connect with people, young and old. At University House, a
retirement home in Seattle's Wallingford neighborhood, Director
Marla Becker said Michael made friends with the elderly residents
he served food to, and occasionally cooked for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed so natural for him. Not everyone has that ability,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   University House requires background checks of its employees, a
test that Michael passed.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his kitchen duties at the retirement home, Michael served
up unofficial fun: fast wheelchair rides for residents. But he quit
the job this summer because he did not like his hours and wanted to
do more cooking and less cleaning up.
</P>
<P>
   The money he earned from his jobs _ he also worked for Spud Fish
and Chips _ went to his passions. He bought a BMX dirt bike that
cost more than $1,000. More recently, he purchased a cutlery set.
</P>
<P>
   Michael is known for his loyalty to friends. Carl Buchanan, who
has known him since grade school, said Michael ``is like a
brother.'' ``He would always be there to lend a helping hand,
support, advice or even the money out of his own pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan said sometimes Michael would have words with other
kids at the biker hills at Lower Woodland Park and ``(tick) people
off.'' He recalled some childhood mischief: In grade school he and
Michael shoplifted baseball cards and gum from local stores. ``I
don't know if he got caught,'' Buchanan said. ``I did a couple of
times.''
</P>
<P>
   In middle school, they spent time at each other's homes
listening to rock music, talking about bikes. Recently, Buchanan
said Michael got stopped and cited by police for riding his bike
recklessly downtown; stunt bikers like to jump steps and other
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Michael occasionally cut class in high school
because he was restless and bored. ``I skipped school, too. I get
A's and B's. I'm not a bad person,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family say Michael is pals with Shelton Musgrave,
less so with Jay Stewart. Patrick Caffee said if Michael and
Shelton were at a party and drank alcohol, they would check on each
other to make sure the other person was OK.
</P>
<P>
   The boys know some of the local homeless men. It is as though
they are all part of an extended family linked by proximity.
</P>
<P>
   Pennyman always asks for spare change. Tobias Atara, a former
University of Washington engineering student, discusses
international politics when he is not holding a cardboard sign that
says ``Anything will help, Thank God for Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was David _ known in the Green Lake area by the
nickname ``One Man'' because he often said ``everybody should be as
one, man!''
</P>
<P>
   Michael thought David was ``nice,'' his father says.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee stands in his yard, filled with wood sculptures,
including a Komodo dragon that he says chipmunks keep stealing the
legs from. He tugs on his graying hair, pulled into a pony-tail,
exposing a weathered face.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to connect the dots. Figure it out. ``I didn't see it
coming,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, he wanted to give Michael, on the cusp of
adulthood, more freedom. Now, he cannot believe how Michael went
from putting his name in wet concrete to being accused of murder.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) No matter how I struggle and strive
</P>
<P>
   I'll never get out of this world alive (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Hank Williams
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, David Ballenger's downward spiral accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998 he and another man, Bobby Ray Hansbrough,
approached Robert Hunt, who was sitting on a toilet in a bathroom
stall at Woodland Park.
</P>
<P>
   One of them told Hunt: ``Drop your money, bitch. We are going to
rob you,'' according to a police report. Hunt, rattled, kept
looking at Hansbrough. David told him to stop staring ``at his
brother'' _ or else. Hansbrough hit Hunt in the head with his fist.
Hunt handed over his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants took four $20 bills, threw the wallet back at
Hunt and fled. A short time later, they were arrested. Officers
found a glass cocaine pipe with residue that tested positive for
cocaine. ``(David) attempted to conceal it by hiding the pipe in
the patrol car'' on the way to the station, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998 David entered an Alford plea to second-degree
robbery in the case _ he did not admit guilt but agreed there was
the likelihood of being found guilty if the case had gone to trial.
He was sentenced to nine months in jail, given credit for 95 days
served and told to pay restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Court records suggest David was making poor choices in company.
Hansbrough _ the man he called ``his brother'' during the attack on
Hunt _ had assaulted police in Florida in 1992 and had prior
convictions for robbery and burglary.
</P>
<P>
   After David's sentence ended in Washington in January 1999, he
was extradited to Oregon, where there was a warrant for his arrest
for a probation violation. He served nearly three months in
Tillamook County Jail, gained more than 30 pounds on jail food and
ballooned to 165 pounds _ the biggest his folks had ever seen him.
</P>
<P>
   In late March, David's mother had heart valve and arterial
bypass surgery. The day of the operation David called the hospital
several times from jail to check on her.
</P>
<P>
   After his release, he went back to Bay City to help her
convalesce, arriving a week before Mother's Day. He brought a gift
_ a handsome sketch of hearts and flowers, a makeshift card he drew
on an envelope.
</P>
<P>
   David stayed with his parents until the day after Mother's Day.
Then he returned to Seattle _ and more problems.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Tyree, a chemical dependency counselor with South King
County Recovery Services, saw David several times in the past year,
including just before his death.
</P>
<P>
   In early summer, Tyree picked David up in a van and took him to
a detox center in Kent, south of Seattle. When the van reached the
center's parking lot, David apparently reached through the rear
window, unlatched the locked door from the outside and bolted.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Tyree said, he drove David to Seattle's Harborview
Medical Center because David had expressed a desire to be committed
for psychiatric evaluation; Tyree could not commit him, but he
offered to drive David to the hospital's emergency room. It is
unclear whether David was admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he drank alcohol he could be real mean, real vulgar,''
Tyree said. ``Without the alcohol he mellowed out. He liked to
read.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 13 David went to the Downtown Emergency Service Center
in Seattle, records show. He filled out a registration card and was
photographed for a laminated ID card. His beard was full, hair
long; he looked tired and haggard.
</P>
<P>
   On July 26, the day after his 46th _ and final _ birthday, he
called his parents in Oregon. Marceline Ballenger said her son
sounded happy. He did not complain about being broke or homeless.
He phoned _ as he often did _ to say I love you.
</P>
<P>
   The call came collect from a Seattle bar.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Marceline Ballenger saw David, he was on a table
at the office of the King County Medical Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   She screamed: ``My baby! What have they done to my baby?''
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) Killing is my business
</P>
<P>
   and business is good (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Megadeth (Italics) A life has gone out with the tide
</P>
<P>
   That might have been happy some day (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Hank Williams
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 9 was a typically pleasant summer day in Green Lake. Kids
rode bikes, rollerbladers cruised sidewalks, swimmers splashed at a
local community center. Trouble was nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The following account of the afternoon and evening is drawn from
statements from Michael to his father, and on statements police
gathered from Michael, Jay, Shelton and others:
</P>
<P>
   Michael says he was riding his dirt bike near the Green Lake
Park bleachers in the late afternoon when he ran into a small group
of people that included Shelton, Jay and David.
</P>
<P>
   Michael needed to talk to Shelton about a problem: Earlier in
the day, Michael had been stopped by police and cited for driving
with no license and no insurance. He was driving Shelton's father's
car when he was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Michael told his father that Shelton, Jay and another friend
said they had been drinking at Jay's house.
</P>
<P>
   Michael and Shelton stepped away from the group to talk, Michael
says, and as they did they could hear the start of a dispute
between David and the others. Jay and the others were harassing
David about being homeless. A witness said Jay told David that as a
veteran, he should have more pride.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, Michael said, David walked away, but one
onlooker was concerned by the potential for violence in the
dispute, and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the teenagers ran into David again near the
Albertson's grocery store, where the dispute resumed. Again, David
left, walking toward his camp.
</P>
<P>
   According to law-enforcement sources, another 911 call came, and
Seattle police went to the scene. They stopped Michael, Shelton and
Jay a few blocks away from the store, and asked the teens to show
their knuckles _ apparently to look for evidence of a fight _ but
found nothing and let them go.
</P>
<P>
   Michael said Jay became enraged because he thought David had
called the police. Jay wanted to find David again, Michael said.
Michael says he tried to divert the others from David. Prosecutors
cast doubt on that claim. In any event, the teenagers ended up at
David's camp, near the east side of the Ravenna I-5 overpass.
</P>
<P>
   There, Michael says, Jay and Shelton attacked David, hitting and
kicking him, and Jay choked him.
</P>
<P>
   Michael says Jay then asked him for the 4-inch knife he was
carrying. He says he gave it to Jay, and watched in horror as Jay
stabbed David several times, then handed the knife to Shelton, who
also stabbed David repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Michael said that when it was over, Jay gave the knife back to
him, and he dumped it down a storm drain.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton denied having anything to do with stabbing David,
telling police he had only handed the knife to Jay.
</P>
<P>
   Jay admitted he attacked David, choking him into
unconsciousness.
</P>
<P>
   But Jay said Michael did the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael said Jay was worried about leaving his ``DNA'' on the
body. He and Shelton pulled off David's sweater, placed it on top
of David's bedding and set it on fire.
</P>
<P>
   After the killing, the three young men reacted in different
ways:
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Shelton went home and slept next to his father.
They said Jay Stewart, who sports a tattoo of the Grim Reaper on
his left shoulder, bragged to a friend about killing ``the bum,''
and said he intended to blame Shelton and Michael for the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Michael called his dad, saying, ``Something terrible has
happened.'' The next morning, Michael flagged down street workers,
who called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Officers found David, and interviewed Michael. At first, he
denied seeing David stabbed. Later, he admitted he had been there
and showed police the storm drain, where they recovered a knife.
</P>
<P>
   After learning David was killed, his mother looked to the sky
and saw a cross in the clouds _ a sign from David, she says. His
brother Daniel went to a fencepost near Sacramento where he and
David had left a small treasure a decade ago _ a coin on top of a
post with a rock over it. The rock and coin were still there. His
sister, Diane Jones, pulled out film footage that her family had
taken of the World's Fair visit. She wanted to see her brother's
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Ballenger and Caffee families have made
pilgrimages to the murder scene.
</P>
<P>
   Marceline Ballenger sat down in the blood-soaked patch of earth
by the overpass, hoping to get closer to her son. She picked up a
beer cap from the grass that she thought David might have touched.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee, too, has walked the embankment _ one of the
hardest walks of his life. He trudged through weeds. He stared and
stared. He would only find some measure of solace by going to a
public memorial service for David at St. James Cathedral. One of
more than 60 people to attend, he prayed for Michael _ and for
David.
</P>
<P>
   When the church arranged the memorial service, they knew little
about David's recent life _ and nothing about his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have invited his family,'' said Jerry Connors, a
pastoral assistant at St. James, ``if only we knew he had any.''
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) Now you'll know why death
</P>
<P>
   was summoned here tonight (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Megadeth
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee believes his son was horrified by the stabbing
and perhaps feared that Jay would attack him or Shelton, too.
</P>
<P>
   His son ``got stuck on stupid,'' Patrick Caffee says. ``He's 19
going on 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick said that after his son's arrest Michael wondered if
what happened would mess up Shelton's chance of being in the
National Guard. ``Still looking out for his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee said he may have failed his son by not hiring a
tutor to deal with his son's learning problems more aggressively.
``I should have paid a lot of money for a private teacher. Now, I'm
paying for a lawyer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Ballengers have no easy answers to explain
David's descent. Thomas believes David got sucked into the
free-for-all attitude of the hippie era _ and never pulled out. In
hindsight, Marceline says drinking _ coupled with bad luck and poor
choices _ played a role in his tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   ``David started getting into trouble from high school,'' says
his sister Diane, 36. ``My mother may not have known, but he was
hanging with the wrong people. I knew that even though I was 10
years younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane said her brother and his peers were experimenting with
drugs and alcohol. She said her parents _ loving and devoted as
they were _ were blind to what was happening at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did drugs in high school. But I got smart. At 19 I stopped.
At 20 I got married,'' Diane said. ``Many kids experience this and
at one point have to decide whether to take a right turn or a wrong
turn. I think David took a wrong turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his girlfriend had had that baby maybe he would have gotten
his life in order. Or if he stayed in the Army ...'' Her voice
trails off. ``You know, any one of those could have been the
turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Ballenger said: ``Whatever happened, David did not
deserve to be hunted down and killed like an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ballengers will scatter David's ashes in the woods near
Vancouver, Wash., this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) I mangle their faces till no features remain
</P>
<P>
   A blade for the butchering, I cut them to shreds (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Megadeth
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Caffee wants to hug the Ballengers.
</P>
<P>
   The Ballengers feel sorry for Caffee and the other boys'
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Two families mourning over ruined lives, lives intertwined
suddenly and forever. ``One Man'' and ``Crash Caffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Jones has found a place of reluctant forgiveness in her
heart for Michael, who came forward and told police where the knife
was. She thinks maybe he should get a slight measure of leniency
because if it hadn't been for him, she says, police may never have
gotten a break in the case. David could have been just ``another
dead homeless guy _ some statistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Flemming, senior deputy prosecutor for King County, is
handling the murder case. She said Michael's cooperation will be
taken into consideration, but pointed out flatly: ``He's an
accomplice to murder. He admitted providing the knife and disposing
of the knife.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemming added: ``He lied to police about what happened. He
didn't admit at first that he was present at the time of the murder
_ only later, when he had been placed under arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   In jail, Michael, who brushes his braces with a finger-sized
toothbrush, is being treated as a suicide risk.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) Some mother rocked him
</P>
<P>
   her darlin' to sleep
</P>
<P>
   But they left him to die
</P>
<P>
   like a tramp on the street (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Hank Williams
</P>
<P>
   One recent afternoon, Marceline Ballenger held up a picture of
her son. In it, he is full grown, with stylish sideburns, chiseled
cheekbones and a prominent nose _ evidence of the Native American
features he inherited from his paternal grandmother, who was
three-quarters Cherokee. He was the only child blessed with those
features.
</P>
<P>
   His mother recalls the day she came to Seattle to identify his
body. His sharp nose was smashed flat and pushed to the left. White
sheets were bundled around his neck covering the knife wounds.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) What have they done to my baby? (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her living room as sunlight filters in, she grips the
picture tighter. Something catches her eye: writing on the back of
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Marceline and Thomas Ballenger never noticed it before.
</P>
<P>
   The words are dated almost 15 years ago. Christmas Day, 1985. A
final gift from David _ homeless, not loveless.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Ballenger reads through tears:
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) ``I live by the name, I will always be proud to be a
Ballenger. Thanks for being the best parents anyone could ever
have. I always will be your loving son, one good, one bad. But I'm
proud to be always a son who will never put you down. I'm no one's
fool. I will stop by saying you can always count on me to be there
for you both, like you to me. All my love, David.'' (End italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
