<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Sept. 30. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-GANDHIS (Rampur, India) _ Maneka Gandhi is the other
daughter-in-law, the one who did not inherit the dynasty. And oh,
how the irony grates on her. After all, she is the one born in
India, Sonia Gandhi in Italy. She has been in politics for 20
years, Sonia for 2. She is the widow of Sanjay, the anointed son
who was a natural wielder of power and his mother's right-hand man.
Sonia's husband was Rajiv, an airline pilot, mild in disposition,
disinclined to the hard knocks of governance. ``That's what's known
as life,'' said Maneka. By Barry Bearak. With map.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-OUTLOOK (Warsaw) _ A decade after the change known to
Poles as ``the revolution,'' capitalism is very much in evidence
here. Banners advertising Internet services hang from Stalin's vast
Palace of Culture, mobile phones are de rigeur with the smart set,
western cars sit in bottlenecks where poky Fiat Polskis once made
their way down empty streets. But beneath this impressive veneer,
all is not well with the Polish success story. By Roger Cohen. With
map.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the spending
bills: Republican leaders have vowed daily, and fervently, that
they will not spend Social Security funds to run the government in
the coming year. Wednesday they unveiled a new $5 million campaign
of television ads renewing their pledge. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMF (Washington) _ President Clinton on Wednesday
announced a major expansion of American efforts to forgive the debt
of the world's poorest nations, saying that nations which meet
relatively stringent standards in reducing poverty would not have
to pay back any of the billions they borrowed from American aid
agencies. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   SMITHSONIAN-DONATION (Washington) _ A refugee from the 1956
Hungarian uprising who came penniless to the United States will
donate $60 million to the Smithsonian Institution, its largest
donation ever, the Smithsonian said Wednesday. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Shaking up his troubled campaign,
Vice President Al Gore said Wednesday he was relocating his
headquarters to his home state of Tennessee, a move intended to
symbolize a break from Washington and an effort to pare down his
bloated, top-heavy operation. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
