<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING PRESSURE-TREATED LUMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week this column focused on pressure-treated lumber _ how
it is made, the chemicals used and the possible hazards to humans
and the environment. The relative merits and risks of
pressure-treated lumber are the subjects of much debate. It is up
to the individual do-it-yourselfer to decide whether to use it
around the home.
</P>
<P>
   If you do decide to use pressure-treated lumber for a project,
it is important to choose the boards carefully, observe all safety
precautions and wear safety gear.
</P>
<P>
   First, choose a lumberyard that will let you take the time to
look through the lumber pile for the best boards. Wear gloves when
handling the lumber, and look for pieces with the fewest number of
splits, wanes and knots. Look carefully at the surface of the
boards; they should be free of any crystalline chemical residue.
</P>
<P>
   Try to choose dry lumber. If you build with wet lumber, it will
shrink and warp when it dries and distort your project.
</P>
<P>
   Each board should have a treaters' tag on one end. The tag will
tell you which company treated the lumber, the year of treatment
and also the agency that performed the quality inspection. More
important, an abbreviation on the tag will tell you what chemical
was used in the treatment. The initials CCA indicate chromated
copper arsenate, ACZA stands for ammoniacal copper zinc arsenate,
and ACQ means alkaline copper quat.
</P>
<P>
   The label will tell if the wood was kiln-dried after treatment
(KDAT), or air-dried (Dry). These designations certify that wood
has a moisture content of only 19 percent, which is much less than
lumber that has been shipped to the supplier immediately after
treatment. Of course, the dried wood will be more expensive, but it
will be less likely to warp.
</P>
<P>
   Not all pressure-treated lumber has the same chemical content.
The amount of preservative that remains in the wood fibers after
treatment is called the preservative retention level (PRL), and is
indicated by numbers ranging from 0.25 to 2.5. The number 0.25
means that the wood can be used for above-ground use in sills,
railings or joists. A rating of 0.40 means the wood is acceptable
for ground or freshwater contact and can be used for posts and
landscape timbers. A rating of 0.60 means the wood can be used for
structural poles in wood foundations next to saltwater. Wood that
has a .80 rating can be used as foundation piles immersed in
freshwater. Finally the highest PRL rating of 2.5 means the timber
can be used as pilings immersed in saltwater.
</P>
<P>
   You can saw and sand pressure-treated lumber with ordinary hand
or power tools, but always wear a dust mask and goggles to protect
your eyes. Even though the chemicals are forced into the wood, they
do not penetrate to the core if the boards are more than
three-inches thick.
</P>
<P>
   This means that if you cut a thick board, you will be exposing
wood that is unprotected by the chemical preservative. Therefore
you apply a preservative to these cut ends if they will be exposed
to the elements. Some suppliers offer a sealer called ''endcoat
preservative.'' It contains copper naphthenate and can be brushed
on to the board ends.
</P>
<P>
   Nails and screws designed for pressure-treated lumber are
available at home centers, but you can use any exterior-grade nail
or screw that is either galvanized or made of stainless steel. Do
not use aluminum fasteners because this metal may react with the
chemical in the wood. You can also use construction adhesive for
joining, provided it is labeled by the manufacturer as for use on
pressure-treated lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Another misconception people have concerning pressure-treated
lumber is that it is maintenance-free and can be left exposed to
the elements without any finish. This is not entirely true, and the
unfinished wood will still absorb water. When this happens it will
expand, warp and possibly crack.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of paints and clear finishes compatible with
pressure-treated lumber. In general, oil-based paint will adhere
better than latex. The wood must be thoroughly dry before you
attempt to finish it.
</P>
<P>
   After working with pressure-treated lumber, be sure to wash all
exposed body areas carefully. Also wash your working clothes
separate from other laundry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
