<SLUG> BC-CIR-PORN-SITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INTERNET DATING SITE, A STEAMY SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Bergin, the creator of an online matchmaking service,
recently used the Alta Vista search engine to determine how easy it
was to find her Web site, singleswithscruples.com. After typing
``singles with scruples'' into the search box, Ms. Bergin was glad
to see her site come up first on the list of results.
</P>
<P>
   But when she scrolled down the list, Ms. Bergin noticed that one
of the other results posted appeared to be a repeat listing of her
site. The title line, ``Singles with Scruples Dating, Friendship
and Matchmaker Services,'' as well as the descriptive sentence
beneath it, were word-for-word identical. Only the Internet address
was different.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Bergin clicked on the listing and saw what looked to be
an online dating site called Net Encounters, she grew more and more
annoyed that someone had used her domain name to attract Web
surfers to another dating site. But when she clicked on the site's
``Links'' icon and saw links to pornographic photos, she was
horrified. ``It was a pornography site disguised as a dating site,
and anyone looking for my site with a search engine could have come
across it,'' Ms. Bergin said. ``Needless to say, I was upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bergin's experience is similar in many ways to those of
other Web site owners affected by a large-scale fraud, described by
the Federal Trade Commission last week, involving a Portuguese
hacker and an Australian pornography company. In both cases,
so-called metatags _ key words and other indexing code _ were
cloned from other Web sites and used to direct Web surfers to
pornographic material.
</P>
<P>
   In the case involving the Portuguese hacker, the trade
commission said that up to 25 million Web pages may have been
affected.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of two other online dating services, www.lovecity.com
and togethernj.com, reported seeing cloned descriptions of their
sites attached to the Net Encounters site during searches conducted
on Alta Vista. In all three instances, the unsuspecting visitor to
Net Encounters is led to believe it is a dating site, and is asked
to submit personal information under the guise of submitting a free
personal ad, which the hacker can use for future solicitation. The
registered owner of the Net Encounters site is in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big problem for us and it leaves a bad taste for anyone
who deals with it,'' said Rob Piccola, president of Love City.
``We've built up a brand awareness over the past four years, but
now we have customers asking us if we're running pornography
sites.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case described last week, a federal judge ordered many of
the sites run by the Australian company and the hacker off the Web,
and Australian authorities said they were considering civil or
criminal charges against the company. The hacker cannot be located.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of legitimate Web sites who want to take action
themselves can sue under the Federal Trade Commission Act, which
prohibits unfair or deceptive practices involving commerce. ``The
FTC Act gives us a broad authority to make sure these
advertisements aren't misleading,'' said Dean Forbes, a staff
attorney at the commission.
</P>
<P>
   But like Ms. Bergin, whose business generates no income as of
yet, many site owners don't have the money to enter a protracted
legal battle. Ms. Bergin said she contacted Alta Vista and asked
the company to remove the Net Encounters listing, but that it still
appears when she searches for her site.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a small business, it's a pain in the neck that's not easily
disposed of,'' said Marc Brown, a lawyer who sent a letter to the
registered owner of the Web address for Net Encounters on Ms.
Bergin's behalf. Brown added that when the cloning involves a
hacker in another country, the challenge of enforcing FTC
regulations is greatly compounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be a case where private enforcement by lawsuits
will not work as well as public enforcement by the government, or
in some cases, two governments working together,'' said Tim
Stanley, chief executive of Findlaw.com, a legal site based in
Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives at Network Solutions, the leading Internet
domain registry, as well as at Alta Vista, say they have limited
ability to oversee the conduct of Web site owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's partly a balancing act between the majority of people who
are honest and who want to get on the Internet fast, and waiting
for the FTC to produce regulations that will protect domain names
and content,'' said Nancy Huddleston, a spokeswoman for Network
Solutions, which receives close to 13,000 domain name applications
per day. ``As the Internet grows, the problem will grow
proportionately with it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Emanuel, a spokesman for Alta Vista, said that the first
recourse for the owner of a purloined site should be to contact the
apparent perpetrator directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts the search engines in a difficult position, because we
can't legislate,'' he said. ``We add 600,000 site submissions a
week, and as people become more crafty and learn how to do it, it's
very difficult for us to weed this type of infringement out.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel said the company does have an active team dedicated to
spotting clones, and that it is working on a proprietary technology
that recognizes multiple key words in order to weed out duplicate
pages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
