<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERENCE-STAMP-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOGETHER ON SCREEN WITH THE STAR HE WAS LONG AGO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for LIMEY-FILMS)  
 (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ At the age of 60, white-haired and soft-spoken, Terence
Stamp has evidently come to terms with that other Terence Stamp who
became an overnight star in Peter Ustinov's 1962 movie version of
``Billy Budd,'' that high-living younger self who was a fixture in
English tabloids as an icon of the Swinging '60s.
</P>
<P>
   But he still can't help wondering why, when the 1970s arrived,
he vanished from the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a hit, which I now know is what separates the men
from the boys,'' he said, sipping tea in the relative anonymity of
the fourth-floor restaurant at Fortnum &AMP; Mason on Piccadilly. ``I
had all these critical successes, but none for the mass market. I
think perhaps I was so heavily identified with the 1960s that, when
they ended, something happened. I often say the work stopped. It
didn't actually stop, but all the good stuff dried up.''
</P>
<P>
   So he decided to be patient and drew inspiration from Muhammed
Ali, who, when banned from boxing, stayed in fighting trim for a
triumphant return. In Stamp's case, he spent much of the 1970s in
an ashram in India. And when directors began calling again, he,
too, was ready. Starting with ``Superman,'' his second movie career
has included ``The Hit,'' ``Legal Eagles,'' ``Wall Street'' ``The
Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert,'' and, most recently,
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in Steven Soderbergh's new movie, ``The Limey,'' which
opens in New York on Friday, the young and the old Terence Stamps
have been brought together in a novel way. ``The Limey,'' which is
slang for a Briton, has Stamp playing Dave Wilson, a tough Cockney
ex-con who travels to Los Angeles to avenge what he believes is the
covered-up murder of his daughter, Jennifer.
</P>
<P>
   But Soderbergh's clever twist is to weave in clips of a
boyish-looking Stamp playing Wilson as a young jewel thief more
than 30 years ago in Ken Loach's first feature film, ``Poor Cow.''
</P>
<P>
   The flashbacks provide the key to the new movie's denouement,
but they also show the young Wilson as he sets out on a life of
crime and explain why, after his latest long stretch in jail, he
feels driven to learn the truth about his daughter's death. Helped
by her Mexican friend, Ed (Luis Guzman), Wilson discovers that
Jennifer was involved with Terry Valentine, a record producer with
shady friends, played by Peter Fonda as an aging lothario with
nostalgia for the '60s (no, there are no clips from ``Easy
Rider''). And once Wilson concludes that Valentine had a hand in
Jennifer's death, the chase begins.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, then, it was his younger self that secured Stamp
perhaps his most important part in years, although in fairness,
Soderbergh and his screenwriter, Lem Dobbs, had already mentioned
him among the few actors who could play the lead role in ``The
Limey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I said it would be great to incorporate some earlier
footage, Lem said, `Then it's definitely got to be Terence Stamp,
because he was in this Ken Loach film where he actually plays a
thief,''' Soderbergh said in a telephone interview. ``We didn't
immediately write `Poor Cow' into the script, because we weren't
sure we could get the rights. But I felt he was still the right
person, so we were working on a shooting script designed for him
before he knew we were doing it. When we put it to him, he was very
intrigued by the idea, so we were off and running.''
</P>
<P>
   Stamp says he remembers less about his character in ``Poor Cow''
than about what he called the ``unnerving experience'' of
improvising in front of two cameras, with no script and little
guidance. But ``to pull the character from the earlier
performance,'' as he put it, his own upbringing in a working-class
family in the East End of London came in handy. In his youth, Stamp
had known many future Dave Wilsons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There but for the grace of God,'' he reflected. ``There were
guys in gangs near me who became lifers, who spent years in
solitary, who were something else when they came out, so that was
what I worked on. That guy wouldn't have aged the way I had aged.
He had spent over half his life in prison. The general feeling is
that prison either breaks you or makes you. Dave Wilson was like a
Zen monk, honed year in year out, in this cell, with all this
brutality. How has he survived, how has he risen above it?''
</P>
<P>
   For the role, Stamp adopts a strong Cockney accent peppered with
Cockney rhyming slang, which was easy for him since his own East
End roots can still be heard in his accent. That he does not sound
Shakespearean is, in fact, also a product of the '60s. At a time
when everything in Britain, from ``kitchen sink'' drama to the
Beatles, used regional accents, it was suddenly possible to be an
actor without sounding like Sir John Gielgud.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the young Terence Stamp, who left school at 16, the
idea of acting at first seemed as distant as his screen heroes,
Gary Cooper, Cary Grant, Errol Flynn and Leslie Howard. Until he
saw James Dean in Elia Kazan's ``East of Eden.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Dean, I felt empathy,'' he said. ``I thought, I
feel like that guy. And he's up there doing it. And that was the
first time I thought that maybe this is something I should have a
go at. This was the spark. Soon I was thinking, `If I don't attempt
this, I will miss my whole life.'''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Tom, a Thames tugboat pilot, discouraged him,
telling him, ``Son, people like us don't do things like that.'' So
he left home, won a scholarship to a small London drama school,
supplemented his income working backstage in a London production of
``West Side Story'' and eventually found work in regional repertory
theater. But he was luckier than most. One day, his agent arranged
for him to meet Peter Ustinov, who was trying to cast the title
role in ``Billy Budd.'' Overwhelmed by Ustinov's presence, Stamp
was barely able to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left, I thought, `I've blown that,''' he remembered
with a smile. ``He must think I'm a congenital idiot. But this was
my luck. He had seen the best actors, but he hadn't seen the
inability that Billy suffers from when he is confronted by
something he doesn't understand: he loses his power of speech.
Later, when I did a test, Ustinov said, `I'm going to insult you
and you try not to speak.' I was the only actor who didn't give in
to the temptation of screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Stamp's angelic appearance as much as his
performance served him well. In quick succession through the '60s,
he worked with William Wyler in ``The Collector,'' Joseph Losey in
``Modesty Blaise,'' John Schlesinger in ``Far From the Madding
Crowd,'' Loach in ``Poor Cow,'' Federico Fellini in ``Histoires
Extraordinaires'' (``Spirits of the Dead/Tales of Mystery'') and
Pier Paolo Pasolini in ``Teorema.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the steam ran out. His outing to Hollywood, in Silvio
Narizzano's Western, ``Blue,'' was disastrous, while his next
American movie, Alan Cooke's ``Mind of Soames,'' was not even
released. Soon the calls stopped coming. And to make matters worse,
his love affair with Jean Shrimpton, (italics)the(end italics)
model of the '60s, ended badly and left him broken-hearted.
</P>
<P>
   An escape route then appeared. While working with Fellini in
Rome, Stamp met an astrologer who introduced him to an Indian guru,
Krishnamurti. Now, with no work and no girlfriend, he headed to
India and settled in an ashram near Poona. When the call to work
finally came in 1978, he was ready to start his career afresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terence is one of those people who was absolutely content to
let his life lead him where it would and not worry about it,''
Soderbergh said. ``You get no sense of anxiety from him, no sense
of impatience, no sense of regret. And I don't think you ever did.
He's not the sort of guy who would sit around complaining about
life.''
</P>
<P>
   A sense of humor no doubt helps. Even after his acclaimed
performance as a flamboyant Australian drag queen in ``Priscilla,''
he noted, ``the only part I was offered was a guest role as a
transsexual on the TV series `E.R.''' No wonder, then, that he was
delighted to play Dave Wilson in ``The Limey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Steven that I really, really, really wanted the part,''
he recalled. ``And he said, `I don't know any other actor who wants
to be up there with himself 35 years ago.' It hadn't even entered
my head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
