<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SIM-MOB-GAME-NYT &LR;      09-29 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SIM-MOB-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPGRADING THE NEIGHBORHOOD, MAFIA-STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mob rule does for Sim City what ``The Sopranos'' did for family
drama. It uses Mafia mythology to goose a well-established genre.
Substitute a crime syndicate for city government. Badda-bing
badda-boom, you're playing a god game as the Godfather.
</P>
<P>
   Now you've got real-world hassles. You've got headaches. You've
got real estate. You've gotta build your one lousy plot of land in
Hick Town into an empire that stretches all the way to Capitol
City. So you start building. You've got construction costs. You've
got workers to manage.
</P>
<P>
   You need a steady supply of raw materials, so now you're running
a brick factory, a steel factory and a cement factory (also useful
when rival gang members have to be rubbed out).
</P>
<P>
   You've got tenants, which means you've got complaints, which
means you've got to turn some of those workers into fixers so they
can keep an eye on the neighborhood. As a landlord, you want to
keep things peaceful and quiet, so it pays to keep your tenants
happy. After all, their kids are your future work force.
</P>
<P>
   A few Deluxe Beds will do wonders for your labor supply. Also,
plant some trees. Tenants love trees, and the foliage makes it
harder for the police to stake out your buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, you need to upgrade the properties so you can
squeeze more cash out of them. You're renovating the diner into a
big restaurant, so you've got to buy a bunch of fancy equipment and
order some lunkhead to deliver it. You're converting the Peep Show
into a brothel (more human resources problems). You're trying to
turn your speak-easies and gambling dens into nightclubs and
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Liquor and gambling are both illegal, so you've got to pay off
the cops. They'll raid the joint if they're not receiving a large
enough cut (the amount of a ``contribution'' is set in a property's
data screen). If you suspect that there might be some suspicious
deaths on the property, it might be a good idea to increase the
bribe.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, your real estate is bumping up against other
families' territory, so their thugs start making trouble. So you've
got to hire some thugs to make some trouble with them. Dumping
bodies in enemy territory is a good tactic if you want the police
to harass your opposition. If they try the same tactic with you,
that funeral parlor business had better be up and running.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon you've got a block-by-block turf war on your hands.
</P>
<P>
   And God forbid a cousin should be in town during this time and
anything should happen to him because if one of the don's relatives
goes down on your turf, you're going to have some serious
explaining to do.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Godfather,'' Mafia leadership was a moral question. In
Mob Rule, it's a logistical question. This is organized crime. You
have to get organized! You need charts. You need tables. You need
information architecture, ya know what I'm sayin'?
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the data screen on each property has a small bar
above the bribe meter to indicate the level of police interest. To
reinforce the importance of this information, it also shows up as a
colored block on police radar _ red means a raid is imminent. The
same window also tells you how many police officers are on the
payroll and how much it's costing you each month.
</P>
<P>
   A status bar puts all the important data at your fingertips:
your bank balance, your supply inventory, your tenants' complaints,
warnings about potential conflicts (if you're putting out a fire on
the waterfront, you need to know whether rival gangsters are
attacking your bookmaker across town).
</P>
<P>
   As in Sim City, the important information is also displayed
schematically on the main map. But while Sim Citizens lead normal
boring lives, Mob Rule denizens have to deal with a lot more drama.
Their situations are more complex.
</P>
<P>
   The result is some fascinating innovation in icon design: an
X'd-out wrench (Factory or Resource Is Being Picketed by Thugs), a
stick figure gagged and bound (Tenant Being Held Hostage Here by a
Gang of Thugs) and a frowny face negated by a red circle-with-slash
(Tenant Has Been Kidnapped by a Rival Family). Flaming barrels
become territory markers.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' or ``Analyze This,'' Mob Rule succeeds
because it never takes itself too seriously. The premise lets you
indulge in the Mafia fantasy. The humor makes it a safe fantasy
(keep it campy and no one gets hurt).
</P>
<P>
   And like Hugh Grant's wise-guy impersonation, it's fun to watch
alone. But it's even more fun to toss back and forth with your
friends _ Mob Rule is outstanding on a computer network. Not only
can you compete against real human beings, but you can also speak
gangsterese while doing it. You can throw every line of every Mafia
movie into the mix. You can give yourself ridiculous mobster
pseudonyms on line.
</P>
<P>
   If Jimmy (the Turnip) Rigatoni thinks that he's going to mess
with family business from his desktop, he can fuggedaboudit.
</P>
<P>
   Mob Rule, developed by Studio 3, published by Simon &AMP; Schuster
Interactive; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98; $39.95; for teen-agers
and adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
