<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-TYPING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYPING FOR THE SHOW-AND-TELL SET: HOW EARLY IS TOO EARLY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading is one thing, but should we also be worried if Johnny
can't type?
</P>
<P>
   Long gone are the days of taking that first typing or computer
course in junior high or even high school. Computers and children
are coming together sooner than ever _ as soon as the child can sit
up, in some cases. But is Johnny going to fall behind his peers if
he can't type 20 error-free words per minute by age 12? Is Jane
doomed to a life of hunt-and-peck because she learned bad habits
early in life?
</P>
<P>
   The debate rages among frazzled parents and educators over the
right age to start teaching a child to type _ over when the
physical and mental skills are primed and ready. And there is even
a debate over whether it should be the schools or the parents who
are teaching that thing that is still called typing by many but is
now known in some circles as keyboarding. (There is a debate over
that, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Amy S. Bruckman, an assistant professor in the College of
Computing at the Georgia Institute of Technology, has done a great
deal of research on teaching children to use computers and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think if you get them around the fifth-grade level
to start using their fingers on the right keys and tell them to
continue to use good form,'' she said, ``as time goes on, they will
continue to become good typists in the process. I don't have any
empirical evidence for this, but I understand a lot of elementary
schools teach basic typing form in fifth-grade _ 10 years old _ and
you could go a little bit younger than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But practices vary widely. ``We have a preschool within our
school district, and we start them at the age of 3 on computers,''
said Nancy Dashner, one of two technology coordinators for the
Glenwood Community School District, which has 2,000 students in
Glenwood, Iowa. The children in the class can use an oversize mouse
to learn basic pointing and clicking in simple programs while
refining their motor coordination skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``In second-grade, we're not actually teaching keyboarding,''
Ms. Dashner said. ``Some people define that word differently. At
second grade, we start talking how the right hand uses the
right-hand side of the keyboard and the left hand uses the left.
From the research I've been reading, their fine motor coordination
really isn't physically there until third-grade, and even some
third-graders can't handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many experts believe that today's computer keyboards
are easier on the hands than the manual and electric monsters used
in the typing classes of yore, concerns may arise about starting
children with typing while their hands are still growing.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Alton Barron, a hand surgeon at the C.V. Starr Hand
Surgery Center in Manhattan, said that did not worry him. ``The
issue with kids is not the typing activity specifically,'' he said.
``It's really no different from them learning the Suzuki method of
violin or anything like that where they have repetitive,
independent finger motion. There is no developmental problem with
starting kids typing early.''
</P>
<P>
   But while learning to type in short, structured lessons is fine,
youngsters run the risk of developing repetitive stress injuries,
just as adults can, if they type too much and sit at workstations
that are not the right size for them. Deborah Quilter, an RSI
consultant, worries that no one seems to care about setting up
proper ergonomic workstations for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, the children are sitting on molded plastic,
inadequate chairs,'' Ms. Quilter said. ``The tables are too high.
There's no place for the keyboard or mouse at an appropriate level.
But more important than that is the child's posture. Children
slouch because the furniture doesn't fit them properly.''
</P>
<P>
   What has brought new urgency to the debate is the near ubiquity
of computers. Wendy Martin, a professor of American literature and
chairwoman of the English department at Claremont Graduate
University in Claremont, Calif., said her daughter had been about
10 years old when she started to show a desire to learn typing.
``She wanted to play certain games and also it was an awful lot
easier to do papers if you could type,'' Ms. Martin said. ``And she
wanted to do e-mail _ that's a powerful motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Kelly, a writer in Brooklyn, said his 7-year-old son had
taken to the computer at an early age. ``He has those CD-ROM games
on the computer, and that's how he's familiarized himself with the
keyboard,'' Kelly said. ``He knew what button to push before he
knew what it said on it.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much importance placed on technology as a means to get
ahead these days, it might seem that parents should work on typing
skills for their children early on _ perhaps as a summer project _
especially if that is not taught at a child's school.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side of the coin, however, is the view that if
fundamental computer skills are really important for children,
professional educators should be adding these programs to their
curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   Malinda Aston, the technical support director for Indiana
University's campus newspaper in Bloomington, pointed out that not
all families could afford a home computer. So schools should
provide equipment and instruction to prepare children for later
life, she contended. ``If it's going to be a priority, the schools
ought to take it on,'' she said. ``The kids that don't have the
option at home will be the ones who are behind, just like it is
with everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever typing lessons are given, they should not necessarily
involve time trials and accuracy ratings from the outset. Ms.
Dashner, of the Glenwood Community School District, differentiates
between ``keyboarding'' and ``keyboarding awareness''; the latter,
she said, focuses on correct form and placement of hands. ``We
start teaching home row in third-grade, but we don't define
words-per-minute until the sixth-grade,'' she said. ``Our emphasis
is not on speed, it's on accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   For the children in Ms. Dashner's school district, a minimum
speed of 20 words per minute with an 85 percent accuracy rate is
the goal for the end of sixth-grade. By the time the students reach
eighth-grade, 30 words per minute with 85 percent accuracy is
preferred. Typing 30 words per minute, she said, ``will let most
students type faster than they can write.'' And that, after all,
was the reason typing became popular in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   There are many typing programs on the market, but most are
geared to adults or older children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dashner, from the Glenwood Community School District, tested
a wide variety of software a few summers ago and found that much of
it did not meet her standards for younger ages. ``Some of the
keyboarding programs I saw really and truly are making kids do
things that are not age-appropriate,'' Ms. Dashner said. ``Plus we
have a multimedia generation here, so we've got to be able to pull
kids in. It's got to grab them.''
</P>
<P>
   Two recent offerings are aimed at children ages 7 to 10:
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY'S ADVENTURES IN TYPING WITH TIMON AND PUMBAA
</P>
<P>
   (Disney Interactive; $19.95; Windows 95 and later, and Power
Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   Familiar characters from Disney's 1994 animated film ``The Lion
King'' are reunited here on CD-ROM with the goal of teaching
children to type. Timon the meerkat, Pumbaa the warthog and Rafiki
the baboon provide 15 typing lessons, several keyboard games and
plenty of broad comic relief. Progress reports showing
words-per-minute typing speed as well as typing accuracy are
available after each lesson, and the child can print out an award
certificate at the end of the course.
</P>
<P>
   JUMPSTART TYPING
</P>
<P>
   (Knowledge Adventure, $19.95; Windows 95 and later, and
Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   Guided by a chatty little robot named Botley and his human
friend Polly, children using the Jumpstart Typing program are
guided through an animated world that mixes sports, science fiction
and typing drills. The program contains more than 30 timed lessons,
as well as video clips that show proper posture and hand technique.
A diagnostic test helps determine the child's typing ability at the
beginning, and the software adjusts itself to the user's level of
skill.
</P>
<P>
   Repetitive stress injuries, known as RSI, aren't just for
grown-ups anymore. Children may spend hours using the Web or
chatting on line, putting them at risk of developing a
keyboard-related injury.
</P>
<P>
   One list of guidelines for avoiding such injuries is offered by
RSI. Help (www.rsihelp.com/children.shtml), a Web site created by
Deborah Quilter, author of ``The Repetitive Strain Injury Recovery
Book'' (Walker, 1998). The list includes these tips:
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms: Teach children the warning signs of RSI, which include
tingling, heaviness or soreness in the neck, shoulders, upper back,
upper arm, elbows, forearms, wrists, thumbs or fingers. Tell
children to report any symptoms immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: Children need child-size chairs and workstations that
are adjusted for them. Make sure that the monitor is directly in
front of the child, with the top of the screen at eye level. Be
sure the keyboard and mouse are low enough to allow your children
to relax their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise: See that the child gets plenty of regular, vigorous
exercise, including activities to strengthen the upper body.
</P>
<P>
   Breaks: Tell the child to stretch frequently while at the
computer and get up often from the chair.
</P>
<P>
   Posture: Teach children not to rest their wrists on the desk,
wrist pad or armrests while typing or using a mouse or trackball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
