<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exorcising The Bin Hex
</P>
<P>
   Q. An e-mail message I received from an iMac has an attachment
encoded in Bin Hex. Can a Windows 98 machine decode it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you should be able to open the attachment from your
Windows 98 machine. It's just a matter of getting software that
will decode Bin Hex for you if your e-mail program can't.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Hex is used to convert e-mail attachments like graphics and
picture files, spreadsheets, documents and other types of files to
a format that will let them travel over the Internet along with
your e-mail text message. Other popular encoding formats used for
e-mail attachments include Uuencode and MIME (which is short for
multipurpose Internet mail extensions).
</P>
<P>
   Bin Hex attachments have the file extension .hqx after the file
name, and the format is a common way to send Macintosh files. Some
full-featured e-mail programs will automatically handle the Bin Hex
attachments for you, encoding them when you send and decoding the
ones you receive.
</P>
<P>
   If your e-mail program cannot handle Bin Hex, there are utility
programs available that can. Aladdin Systems has free file
expansion and decoding software available for downloading from its
Web site (www.aladdinsys.com/expander) with versions that will work
for Windows, DOS and Macintosh systems.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com. This column will answer questions of general
interest, but letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
