<HEADLINE>
`SECOND SIGHT': AS HE SLOWLY GOES BLIND, A DETECTIVE GAINS
INSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In creating ``Second Sight,'' Paula Milne began with an inspired
notion: A vigorous, brilliant police detective contracts a rare eye
disease that starts to rob him of his most important sensory tool.
</P>
<P>
   Too proud to give up the command of a high-profile murder
investigation, he tries to work around his new limitation. But he
cannot succeed alone, even as his other senses grow sharper to
compensate for his diminishing sight.
</P>
<P>
   So this tough guy must learn to lean upon a tough gal, his newly
installed deputy. She agrees not to tell the top brass about his
problem in exchange for her share of the glory when they crack
their case. In the process these detectives learn as much about
each other, and themselves, as they do about the people they are
investigating. Now that's a clever setup.
</P>
<P>
   But to write a riveting drama, Ms. Milne needed a second
inspiration for ``Second Sight'': a case to challenge and fascinate
her protagonists and her audience. Here, alas, she has come up
short, falling back on some hokum about a murdered college student
who left behind a trove of possible clues in a rambling videotape
diary.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects abound. Things are not always what they seem, even for
those with eagle eyes. But when you learn that the victim's
stepfather has an identical twin brother from whom he was separated
at birth, your own senses may detect the scent of an overripe red
herring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second Sight,'' which opens the 20th season of British imports
on the PBS series ``Mystery,'' is being broadcast in two 90-minute
installments. This story could have been more effectively told in a
single, shorter, faster-paced show.
</P>
<P>
   In the first installment you'll meet the unlikely helpmates,
Detective Chief Inspector Ross Tanner (Clive Owen) and Detective
Inspector Catherine Tully (Claire Skinner). Tanner is the
hard-driving, hard-drinking, hard-smoking kind, focused on his
career. He failed as a husband, but he cares deeply for his young
son, so you know there's a heart in there somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   You're less sure about Tully's heart. Her focus is firmly on the
job, too. She desperately wants to erase a black mark on her
record; she led a bungled ambush in which one of her subordinates
was gravely wounded.
</P>
<P>
   As played by these attractive actors, under the direction of
Charles Beeson, both detectives are so thoroughly focused that it's
hard to imagine either one having any kind of real relationship,
professional or otherwise. Sparks should flit between them, but the
kindling is just too soggy, thanks to all that self-absorption.
</P>
<P>
   They bicker at first sight, of course.
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Given a choice, Catherine, focus on the facts. There's
time for the psychobabble when we've got the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``Ah, left-brain approach. I know it well. Surely facts are
always open to interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly the banter of Nick and Nora. Or Mulder and
Scully, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting players are uniformly strong. Stuart Wilson is
memorable as the bereaved stepfather and, in the second episode,
the evil twin. But is the stepfather really bereaved? Is the twin
really evil? Is the twin really a twin? Wilson keeps you guessing,
especially when the tempo picks up in the second, more satisfying
installment, as some answers materialize fuzzily.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fuzziness is intentional. Rex Maidment's imaginative
camera work dramatizes Tanner's visual impairment, showing you the
things that the inspector sees, or thinks he sees.
</P>
<P>
   The film's off-kilter look often overshadows the logical
questions that linger even after the case is closed. For instance:
On a team of 20 or so elite detectives, how come only one notices
that the boss is going blind?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY: `Second Sight'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, (Channel 13, New York, at 9 Thursday night)
</P>
<P>
   Director, Charles Beeson; producer, David Lascelles; original
screenplay by Paula Milne; director of photography, Rex Maidment.
Executive producers: Tessa Ross for the BBC, Peter Ansorge and
Claudia Milne for Twenty Twenty and Rebecca Eaton for WGBH. A
production of Twenty Twenty Television for the BBC and WGBH Boston.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Clive Owen (Detective Chief Inspector Ross Tanner), Claire
Skinner (Detective Inspector Catherine Tully), Stuart Wilson (Adam
Bendrix and Jack Kenworthy), Phoebe Nicholls (Judith Bendrix), Tom
Mullion (Matthew Bendrix), Louise Atkins (Tracy Villiers).
</P>
</TEXT>
