<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0541 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MAP-SOFTWARE-2TAK     09-29 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MAP-SOFTWARE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC CARPETS FOR ARMCHAIR EXPLORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maps do more than lead you from point A to point B. For the
closet cartographer, a map's hieroglyphics reveal a portrait of the
world's countries, cities, mountains, plains and oceans through a
singular vocabulary of symbols, colors and typefaces.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, maps are a two-way street: they not only depict the
world for their readers but also say volumes about the people who
made them by what they include and leave out, where the borders are
and what a city is called _ whether Londonderry in Northern
Ireland, for example, is rendered as Derry, the Irish nationalists'
preference.
</P>
<P>
   A good map fires the imagination like a good novel. Here are
three CD-ROM sets to curl up with on a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC MAPS
</P>
<P>
   (National Geographic Society; $49.95; Windows 95 and later.)
</P>
<P>
   Generations of map lovers have delighted in all the sensations
associated with the maps that come tucked inside National
Geographic magazines: the crisp unfolding of paper and faint smell
of ink as the reader bends over the table and lingers on the
strange names of cities and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Geographic Society has collected every map included
in the magazine through 1997 _ all 535 of them _ on a set of eight
CD-ROMs. The first fold-out map, which shows the area from the
Meadow Creek Mountains in Tennessee along the French Broad River to
Asheville, N.C., appeared with the ``Round About Asheville''
article in the October 1889 issue. The last, from December 1997, is
a two-sided map of Mesoamerica published with ``The Royal Crypts of
Copan''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maps are intimately intertwined with the culture'' of the
National Geographic Society, said Allen Carroll, chief cartographer
at National Geographic Maps. ``The society's more-than-century-long
mission is to increase and diffuse geographic knowledge,'' he
added. ``People tend to think of photographs first, but I hope they
also think of maps.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Geographic Society, which has sponsored exploration
and anthropological and environmental research, formed its own
cartographic division in 1915. Its maps have since set the
standard: they are dense with raw geographical data on the physical
features of the world and the names and symbols humans use to place
themselves in that world. The maps in this collection offer a
window onto history, war, culture, science and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   And they can be downright beautiful. ``Bird Migration in the
Americas'' (August 1979) shows the migration routes of birds from
North America to South America with arrows sweeping down through
the bottleneck of Central America and fanning out toward Tierra del
Fuego. The continents are surrounded by drawings of the
ruby-throated hummingbird, the wandering albatross, the
blue-and-white sparrow and 64 other species, in full, flying color.
</P>
<P>
   Where the maps alone do not tell the story, there are insets. A
two-sided map that accompanied ``Panama: Ever at the Crossroads''
(April 1986) has a political map of Central America on one side and
insets and several smaller maps on the other, with insights into
archeological sites and the European invasions of the region by
explorers. It also shows the economic outlook, with a map showing
things like natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM collection also offers users historical perspectives.
A 1922 map of the world contains regions at both poles marked
``unexplored.'' ``The Antarctic Regions,'' a 1932 map, shows the
Polar Plateau with a largely empty interior, traced with the routes
of the early explorers: Shackleton, Amundsen, Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antarctica'' (1987) is fully mapped, with international
scientific bases and detailed topographical information like ice
thicknesses and mountains and glaciers, including Amundsen Glacier
and Grosvenor Mountains (named for Gilbert H. Grosvenor, the first
editor of The National Geographic magazine and the society's second
president).
</P>
<P>
   Among the many other map pairings that will interest history
enthusiasts are the theater of war in 1918, paired with a 1922 map
showing ``Countries as Established by the Peace Conference at
Paris,'' and a map of the races of Europe and Africa from 1918,
with ``Dawn of Humans'' (1997).
</P>
<P>
   To provide users with a context for the collection, the software
includes a history of cartography (``from the first line drawn in
the sand'') and a history of the National Geographic Society.
</P>
<P>
   There are also nine video tours, on topics like European
history, Canadian history and the environment. ``You can't assume
that everyone who picks one of these maps up is a map geek,'' said
Bob Madden, editorial director of the CD-ROM set.
</P>
<P>
   The set's most cumbersome aspect _ that it is included on eight
CD-ROMs, which users must slip in and out of the drive to view the
maps _ has been mitigated by several search and sorting provisions.
The maps can be searched on any of the CD-ROMs by categories like
politics or history, and by geographic regions like North America
or space.
</P>
<P>
   Each map can be viewed in a thumbnail version, and users can
call up a summary with the map's title, publication date, size and
geographic names; a list of the insets, and the title of the
article (if any) relating to the map. Users can also keep several
maps open on their screen, even after switching CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   The printing feature of the CD-ROM set is flexible: each map can
be sized to fit a standard page or printed on several pieces of
paper. The printouts are clear and easy to read, and the subtle
colors reproduce well. There is little to complain about in this
software, but it would be nice if the map summary had a synopsis of
the articles the maps appeared with and if the summary could be
called up from the map image and not just from the search page.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation within the maps is typical of map software: the
viewer can zoom in and out, using a thumbnail image to center the
map in the viewing window and a Find button to search for places or
insets. The maps can also be ``turned over'' so users can see the
back of any two-sided map.
</P>
<P>
   Users can view a list of alternative place names since borders,
cities and countries on maps have changed with wars, colonialism
and independence movements: Burma became Myanmar, for example, and
Leningrad became St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maps present a hierarchy of information,'' Carroll said. ``You
need a mental or visual starting point. With a map of central
Texas, there are a lot of lines and squiggles and names, but if
Houston and Dallas are in big type, you can say, `I know where I
am.'''
</P>
<P>
   Map-making today combines technology with graphic traditions,
Carroll added. ``If the information is not presented properly,'' he
said, ``it is almost worthless: counterintuitive software has the
important stuff buried, and a poorly designed map can be a jumble
of confusing code. We've all encountered ugly software, and the
same is true of maps. Maps should be as accurate as possible and as
beautiful as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   APPALACHIAN TRAIL
</P>
<P>
   (Maptech Windows; $39 for each CD-ROM, $139 for set of four;
Windows 95, NT and 98.)
</P>
<P>
   The Appalachian Trail _ 2,160.3 miles, from Springer Mountain in
Georgia to Baxter Peak in Maine _ is no walk in the woods. About
3,000 people a year try to hike the entire trail, which is in 14
states, but only 400 to 450 finish the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trip, hikers face physical challenges, like
blisters, Lyme disease, swarms of black flies, rain, cold and heat,
and they battle loneliness and boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers who travel a section of the Appalachian Trail make up the
bulk of the users, and they are the ones who would benefit most
from a set of CD-ROM maps that will be released in early October,
said Brian King, the director of publications for the Appalachian
Trail Conference, a federation of 31 regional hiking clubs that
maintain the trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help them identify the difficulty of a particular
section,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   The trail conference says that three million to four million
people travel part of the route each year.
</P>
<P>
   The map set has CD-ROMs for the New England, Mid-Atlantic and
Southern regions. A fourth covers a short stretch in West Virginia
as well as Virginia, which wins the prize for most trail miles:
more than 500. The CD-ROMs offer plenty of maps, photographs and
descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The information on the 95 mile-stretch of the Appalachian Trail
inside Shenandoah National Park in Virginia, for example, includes
the geologic and human history of the area, descriptions of animals
and plants, camping and fire regulations, and, as with all
sections, a trail guide.
</P>
<P>
   The guides featured in the CD-ROM set are from the books
distributed by the Appalachian Trail Conference. They include trail
mileage, elevation ascents and descents, locations of shelters and
sources of water. There is also a description of what a hiker will
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   A 2.3-mile stretch of the trail near Hawksbill Mountain in
Shenandoah National Park includes the altitude of Hawksbill at the
summit (4,050 feet, the highest point in the park), the mountains
visible from the trail, the places where the climb is steep, and
the places to find the three-toothed cinquefoil, which blooms in
late spring.
</P>
<P>
   The trail guides make the CD-ROM set most useful to armchair
hikers and people who want to plan short trips. A particularly nice
feature is that the guides are offered in northbound or southbound
versions (hikers traveling in the direction opposite from their
trail guide have to read from back to front).
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM set also shows the land for up to eight miles on each
side of the trail. But unlike most paper hiking maps, trails
intersecting the Appalachian Trail are often not identified, so
hikers who use the CD-ROM maps to hike these trails risk getting
lost.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM maps are easily navigated with a well-stocked
toolbar; several zoom settings; a search function for parks, lakes,
cities and other map features, and icons to link to the trail
information and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The Appalachian Trail is marked with small white rectangles
painted on trees and piles of stones called cairns in areas where
there are no trees. When you come upon it in the woods, stand with
the rising sun to your right. Baxter Peak is in front of you, just
a few miles, and Springer Mountain is almost right behind you.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, leave only footprints.
</P>
<P>
   TOPO USA
</P>
<P>
   (Delorme; $99.95, Windows 95, 98 and NT.)
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the Pacific Northwest on a flat map, with mountains and
national parks and forests surrounding Puget Sound and Seattle.
Now, imagine it as a three-dimensional topographical map: look
north past giant Mount Rainier into the Canadian Rockies, with the
mountains dropping down past Seattle to Puget Sound, only to fill
the Olympic Peninsula to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Some places just look better in three dimensions. With Topo USA,
the flat CD-ROM image can be transformed into a landscape. Now,
users have a bird's-eye view of anywhere in the 50 states: the
plains stretching northwest from Wichita, Kans.; the Pacific
coastline; the Mississippi River where it joins the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Users can search for a place on Topo USA, view a flat map and
watch as a 3-D image is built on the screen. The topographical
features can be exaggerated to throw peaks and valleys into greater
contrast and enhance the 3-D effect.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two navigation tools that mimic flight over the
landscape. In the first, users can select the pitch used to view
the map on a sliding scale between 15 and 90 degrees: at the lower
numbers, the landscape stretches out toward the horizon, and at 90
degrees, the view is from directly overhead. Since the image
adjusts as the pitch increases, the perspective for the user is one
of flying from far away to hovering over the map.
</P>
<P>
   The second feature is the rotation tool: it is possible to swing
360 degrees around the center point of the map. The perspective is
one of circling the landscape from high in the air: with Knoxville,
Tenn., as the center point, the user can rotate the view so it
first shows the Little Tennessee River winding southward with the
Great Smoky Mountain range to the east. Then the sightline is from
the peaks looking north and west toward Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the topographical sightseeing in Topo USA only
whets the appetite. For starters, the 3-D image is slightly fuzzy.
And because the images do not include buildings, landscapes built
around city and town maps seem empty.
</P>
<P>
   The filters for choosing natural and man-made components on the
map do not offer enough choices. Roads and cities, for example, are
included with parks and recreation on the map, so users cannot
simply select a geographic map with place names. The map is further
cluttered because the place names on the surface bend along with
the terrain in the 3-D images.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM, however, offers a lot of basic information, down to
individual streets and landmarks. So, users can see where Ben
Franklin was born in Boston at the most detailed setting, and
increase the scale to see the landscape from above. After all, why
just look at a map when you can fly over it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
