<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-THEATER-CELL-PHONES-N     09-29 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-CELL-PHONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THE PHONE HAD A CORD, YOU COULD STRANGLE THE USER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was an interruption whose time is coming far too
frequently. During a recent performance of ``Death of a Salesman,''
its star, Brian Dennehy, was startled to hear a cell phone ring
near the end of the second act.
</P>
<P>
   Even more disturbing was to hear the phone being answered, and a
woman in the audience clearly saying, ``It's almost finished,'' and
going on to make dinner plans.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Cahoon took an aggressive approach to a recent cell-phone
intrusion. When a phone rang during his performance earlier in
September as the transsexual rock singer in ``Hedwig and the Angry
Inch'' at the Jane Street Theater, his concentration broke, but his
aplomb didn't. Cahoon marched off the stage, pink fringe fluttering
on his denim dress, took the phone out of an audience member's hand
and answered it.
</P>
<P>
   Theaters in Manhattan, museums in London, wedding receptions in
Paris _ around the world, people are taking cell-phone calls in the
presence of strangers who are forced to listen to everything from
tearful marital conflicts to shopping advice.
</P>
<P>
   A cell phone is ``a pacifier for adults,'' said Maira Kalman,
the president of M&AMP;Co, a Manhattan product and graphic design
group. ``It makes you feel connected, that you're not alone in this
planet.''
</P>
<P>
   But anti-cell-phoners are not sitting idly by. At Le Cirque
2000, a waiter will materialize at any table where a cell phone has
come into view. ``We ask them to leave the phone with us, and when
they get a call, we will call them,'' the restaurant's owner, Sirio
Maccioni, said.
</P>
<P>
   At Lincoln Center, the New York City Opera and the Metropolitan
Opera post their own admonitions. At the Museum of Modern Art, come
mid-October, a prohibition will be printed in the information
pamphlets handed out at the front desk. But at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, there is no need to wrestle visitors into cell-phone
submission. The stone walls of the Beaux-Arts building are so thick
that cell phones won't work (except in the Great Hall, where they
function only half of the time).
</P>
<P>
   As rules of cell-phone etiquette are being established _ a sign
here, a murmur there _ the New York Times invited six
graphic-design companies to create a universal icon that says: Stop
cell-phone talk. The designers _ who have created everything from
universal-design kitchen implements to album covers to interiors
for the New Jersey Performing Arts Center _ have not yet been asked
to design an anti-cell-phone sign. But they're ready, with concepts
that range from anger to advocacy to ironic understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Ringing phones infuriate Ms. Kalman. Hence, the angry look to
her sign. ``It's a monster,'' she said of the design, a red face
with jagged teeth about to nosh on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Cellbuster, on the other hand, is purposefully jolly. Created by
Tucker Viemeister, working with Dylan Fracareta and Jarrod Linton
at Razorfish, a product- and digital-design company in Manhattan,
it is a jamming device with an insidiously funny logo: a cell phone
that looks a little like Casper the Friendly Ghost being squeezed
to near-suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it Cellbuster because we wanted a symbol that was
sort of fun, so people felt happy about it,'' Viemeister said. He
added that although the design is lighthearted, its effect would be
drastic: a Cellbuster on the ceiling of a restaurant would insure
that no diner could receive any calls. The device would block calls
by emitting bursts of static on the same radio frequency: a caller
would hear a message that ``you cannot reach the customer at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagram, a design consulting company in Manhattan, found the
threat of violence intriguing. A takeoff on the ubiquitous Heimlich
maneuver posters, its Cell Phone Victim poster provides simple
directions for the forcible removal of a cell phone: Push. Kick.
Pull.
</P>
<P>
   ``A `no cell phone' icon would be insufficient to address this
crisis, because the people most susceptible to it seem to have no
self-control,'' said Michael Bierut, who designed the poster with
Brett Traylor. ``The syndrome requires intervention, for their own
good, really.'' A second Pentagram design, slightly less violent,
shows a cell phone displaying the words ``shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Turner, a Manhattan graphic designer, took a kinder,
gentler approach. She created glow-in-the-dark rubber gloves, one
that says ``Turn It Off,'' the other ``Stop Talk Now.'' They could
be subtly raised in dimly lighted theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Sussman, a partner in Sussman/Prejza &AMP; Co., an
environmental graphics design company in Culver City, Calif., asked
her staff to design  &UR; anything but &LR;  a phone in a circle with a slash
through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too dull, too obvious,'' she said. ``It's got to be
universal, not obnoxious, hopefully funny, and you could put it
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by the project, Ms. Sussman's staff produced dozens
of signs, including Curb Your Calls (with a person holding a phone
at the end of a leash) and a stop sign with a phone in place of the
``o.'' Sussman/Prejza's sketch for Silence of the Phone shows a
phone-shaped face with stitches across the mouth, a reference to
Hannibal Lecter, the firmly muzzled cannibal antihero of ``Silence
of the Lambs.'' An especially witty alternative is a poster
depicting a flurry of words in various typefaces, the very
banalities that make up most cell-phone conversations (``Can you
hear me?'').
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Sagmeister and Jan Wilker, graphic designers in
Manhattan, took the obvious universal icon _ a phone in a circle
bisected by a diagonal slash _ and transformed it into a
site-specific solution: a plate flanked by a knife and fork.
</P>
<P>
   Sagmeister, who has designed a ``no smoking'' sign for Cathay
Pacific, said he would rather lunch with a smoker than a cell-phone
user. At least the smoker, he said, ``will blow the smoke away from
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
