<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0577 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     09-29 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., OCT. 17, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a one-story ranch house and the walls and ceilings are
painted off-white. There is a strange problem with discoloration on
some of the walls and ceiling of the corner bedroom. Light grayish
streaks have appeared in straight lines that seem to follow the
pattern of the wood studs inside the walls. It's almost as though
the studs were showing through the paint. Can you tell me what
could cause this?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a fairly common problem, which is usually referred to
as ``ghosting'' of the stud or beam patterns. It is actually the
result of tiny amounts of condensation that form on the inside of
insulated outside walls and the ceilings under insulated attics.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is not a good insulator, so the studs transmit cold to the
inside better than the insulation that is packed in between them.
As a result, the drywall that is directly against the studs gets
slightly colder on the inside than the rest of the wall or ceiling
which has insulation behind it.
</P>
<P>
   These cooler surfaces cause moisture in the air to condense
along the inside in lines that follow the pattern of the studs or
beams. This slight moisture catches and holds small amounts of dust
and even allows a slight amount of mildew to form in some cases _
thus creating the dark ``shadows'' that you see.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We remodeled our family room and added a new prefabricated
fireplace to this room. The prefabricated chimney for this
fireplace goes up along the outside and extends up past the peaked
roof. However, each time we use this fireplace we have a problem
with smoke drifting into the room. The dealer told us that this is
because the chimney is probably not high enough, even though it
does stick up above the roof. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   A: A chimney that is not tall enough is a common reason for a
fireplace smoking. The top of the chimney should stick up at least
two feet higher than the roof or any part of it (including the
peak) that is less than 10 feet away from that chimney. The same
applies to any other structure or part of the house that is within
10 feet of the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there should be a hood or cap on the top of the chimney to
help deflect downdrafts when it is very windy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The house we recently moved into has a glass enclosed stall
shower and after a year or so we started to see mildew forming on
the ceiling above the shower. We installed an exhaust fan and then
repainted that ceiling after washing the mildew off with Clorox and
water, but now the mildew seems to be coming back. What can we do
about this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: One possibility is that you did not remove all the mildew
before painting. If even a few spots remain it is likely to grow
back. After washing off the mildew (with a solution of one part
fresh Clorox and three parts water) wash again with a mild
detergent and rinse off with plenty of water. When you do repaint,
make sure you use a paint that is mildew-resistant, or has had
extra mildewcide added.
</P>
<P>
   Also, when using the exhaust fan make sure you keep it running
for at least 10 or 15 minutes after the shower is turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have light wood kitchen cabinets with a clear gloss finish.
I would like to remove the glossy finish and give the cabinets a
more natural looking dull finish _ like an oiled or waxed finish.
How can I do this without damaging the wood?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can completely remove all of the old glossy finish _
without damaging the wood _ by using a semi-paste chemical paint
remover. Just be sure you follow the directions on the can and be
careful not to scratch the wood when scraping the softened old
finish off. Then you can apply two coats of a clear penetrating
sealer such as Minwax Antique Oil or Watco Danish Oil. These dry to
a dull, satin sheen and will darken the wood slightly.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative method would be to apply two or three coats of
clear satin gloss or flat finish varnish that has little shine.
These will not darken the wood as much as the oils and they
eliminate the need for stripping off all of the old finish. All you
have to do is sand the old finish thoroughly to remove all gloss,
then apply the flat varnish directly over the existing finish.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``GHOSTING ON BEAMS AND STUDS'' goes
with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Dust and mildew adhere to slight condensation that
forms on the drywall surface behind which the colder wood studs or
beams are located.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0578 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-BUDG     09-29 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-BUDGET-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET: HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This column moved today:
</P>
<P>
   BERNARD GLADSTONE'S ``HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS''
for Sun., Oct. 17, 1999, which included:
</P>
<P>
   _What causes dark striping to appear on walls and ceilings
(comes with illustration).
</P>
<P>
   _How to prevent a fireplace from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   _What to do about persistent mildew appearing on shower ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   _How to change the finish on kitchen cabinets from high shine to
sheen.
</P>
