A0589 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-29 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BAD DAY FOR LENO, BUT NOT FOR AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jay Leno was in mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst day of my life,'' said the ``Tonight Show''
host as he began his opening monologue.
</P>
<P>
   And just exactly what happened, you might be wondering, to make
Leno so despondent?
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle quit the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sad day for stand-up comics from coast to coast, of
course, because Quayle was one of the great punch lines in the
history of political humor. A comedian could get a laugh just
mentioning Quayle's name.
</P>
<P>
   And few comedians mentioned Quayle's name more often than Leno
did. In honor of the onetime vice president's contributions to the
annals of comedic monology, Leno presented a hilarious farewell
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle will be missed on late-night television and in comedy
venues everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He will not be missed in the race for the Republican
presidential nomination _ a contest to which he contributed
precisely nothing. Quayle was a joke as vice president, and he was
an even bigger joke as a candidate for president. What in the world
ever made him think he had a chance of winning the nomination, much
less the presidency?
</P>
<P>
   We may never know the identity of the culprits who encouraged
Quayle to run for president _ who would admit to such a thing? _
but they did him no favor. Anyone who truly cared about the guy
would have counseled him to spare himself the embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   In his dropping-out-of-the-contest news conference Monday,
Quayle blamed front-runner George W. Bush's bankroll and a
front-loaded primary schedule for thwarting his bid to be president
_ excuses that betray the same lack of self-awareness that has
plagued Quayle since he burst onto the national scene in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle has always found somebody to blame for the public's
refusal to accept him as a serious political leader _ the media,
the ``cultural elite,'' assorted political enemies _ but he has
never placed the blame where it belongs: on himself. Quayle is not
considered a serious leader because he is not a serious leader.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Gallup poll revealed just how pathetic Quayle's fantasy
of becoming commander in chief really was: 61 percent of those
polled said they would never so much as consider voting for Quayle.
That's pretty much the definition of a no-chance candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   And if he'd been stubborn enough to stay in the race, that 61
percent would surely have increased. When it comes to the
no-way-no-chance-never-in-a-million-years scale of vote-getting
potential, Quayle is in a class by himself.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to just plain class, however, Quayle is nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   When Ohio Rep. John Kasich dropped out of the presidential race
a while back, he humbly admitted that the voters weren't interested
in what he had to offer and graciously declared his support for
Bush. Rather than pouting about his campaign being steamrollered by
the Bush fund-raising juggernaut, Kasich swallowed his pride and
signed on with the man whom most Republicans are counting on to
recapture the White House for the Grand Old Party.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, on the other hand, whined about Bush's dominance in the
money chase and petulantly refused to endorse the front-runner.
You'd think that endorsing Bush would be the least that Quayle
could do, seeing as how it was Bush's father who plucked this
then-Indiana senator out of obscurity and made him vice president
of the United States back in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Not that an endorsement from Quayle would be worth much to Bush,
or any other candidate. The legions of Americans who would never
consider voting for Quayle probably wouldn't put much stock in any
recommendation he would make.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Quayle departed the national scene more or less the
same way he arrived _ babbling like an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time to stay and a time to fold,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently racked with indecision about selecting a metaphor, if
not about the fate of his campaign, Quayle plodded on: ``There's a
time to know when to leave the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why Jay Leno is devastated. He'll never find
another stooge like Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
