<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VATICAN-FACADE-NYT &LR;      09-29 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-FACADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLORFUL ST. PETER'S RAISES EYEBROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Baroque architecture was much inspired by the theater,
and for centuries the grand facade of St. Peter's Basilica has been
the central backdrop for the religious drama of the papacy. This
week, with a show of fireworks and a solemn papal blessing by Pope
John Paul II, the Vatican is rededicating Carlo Maderno's
magnificent 17th-century facade after a three-year, $5.4 million
restoration that has revived a passionate debate over preservation
methods.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge faced by Maderno, a master of the Baroque, was to
provide a facade for the magnificent church, which was conceived by
the Renaissance architect Donato Bramante and crowned by
Michelangelo's immense dome over the altar.
</P>
<P>
   What provoked the current debate was the discovery that Maderno,
whose facade was built from 1607 to 1612, during the pontificate of
Paul V, appeared to have enhanced the effect of his architecture by
the discreet use of color. The restoration revived a dull straw
color along a broad expanse of the facade that contrasts with the
white of the travertine marble columns in front of it. The frame
around the central balcony from which popes for centuries have
imparted their blessing ``Urbi et Orbi'' (``To the city and to the
world'') is in delicate shades of red and green.
</P>
<P>
   Renato Nicolini, a former commissioner of culture in Rome's city
government, decried the restoration as ``post-modern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the desire to transform everything into a movie set,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo Bertelli, an architectural historian, was equally
dismissive. Belittling the facade's restored shade as the ``color
of tobacco,'' and using the English word ``beautification'' as if
to suggest a project inspired by Disney, he complained that ``the
televised image had won out over the real monument.''
</P>
<P>
   The restoration was prompted by a desire to beautify the
basilica, the central church of Christendom, and its piazza for the
Jubilee celebration next year for the start of Christianity's third
millennium. In recent months, workers finished restoring the
sweeping colonnade, which was completed in 1666 by Gianlorenzo
Bernini to embrace the immense piazza.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second time in recent years that the Vatican has
completed a major restoration, after the cleaning of Michelangelo's
frescoes in the Sistine Chapel, and the debate over the facade
seems to echo recriminations over the restoration of the chapel.
Art historians and restorers were stunned by the revelation of
Michelangelo's bright colors. Still, some feared that the work had
been permanently disfigured.
</P>
<P>
   Maderno's use of color was not the only striking discovery
during the basilica's restoration. Close measurements of the facade
with computerized equipment showed that the left side, as seen when
facing the basilica, was roughly 16 inches lower than the right
because of settlement in the unstable ground below. Maderno had
added bell towers at the extremities when Pope Paul deemed the
original facade too narrow for Michelangelo's massive construction.
</P>
<P>
   Bernini was commissioned in the 1640s to carry the bell towers
higher than the present height of the facade, but work was
interrupted and the construction dismantled when the building's
settlement rapidly accelerated, threatening the entire facade. The
restorers studied four tears in the facade that were partly caused
by settling that began almost immediately after completion.
</P>
<P>
   Car and bus exhaust added to the soot from centuries of
wax-torch illumination of the facade on high-feast days, dulling
the building's contours to a uniform gray. Such damage masked
details of a facade that Sandro Benedetti, a professor of
architecture at La Sapienza, the main campus of the University of
Rome, describes as ``one of the first works that open the chapter
of the Roman Baroque.''
</P>
<P>
   The facade is generating more public interest than usual because
of a broader debate about the colors of Rome as the city spruces up
for the Jubilee. As one after another of Rome's restored palazzi
emerge from beneath centuries of soot, bright pastel shades of
pink, gray and yellow are replacing the more familiar ocher and
terra-cotta hues that visitors have long associated with Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The new tints are a result of research into color samples and
early depictions of the city showing that in the 16th and 17th
centuries, when much of the Baroque city received its present
shape, architects favored such bright tones.
</P>
<P>
   Benedetti, who oversaw the facade's restoration, defended the
restoration of the original color. Detailed study of many samples
of stone extracted from the facade, he said, clearly showed a layer
of color between the stone and thick layers of pollutants.
Depictions of the facade in early illustrations, including a fresco
in the Vatican Library, also show the contrast in color between the
wall of the facade and the columns. Moreover, he said, documents of
the Fabbrica di San Pietro, the office entrusted since the 1500s
with maintaining the basilica, record the purchase of many brushes
to paint the facade.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent news conference, Benedetti explained that Maderno
used color to add depth and movement to the flat facade. ``It is my
task to interpret the meaning of those colors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some who agreed with the historical accuracy of the
restoration do not entirely approve.
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Portoghesi, a professor of architectural history in Rome,
acknowledged that the colors represented ``exactly what Maderno
did, the idea of his project.'' Yet he added, in a recent interview
with La Repubblica newspaper that ``the criticism is more than
justified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parthenon, for instance, was blue, red and cream,'' he
continued. ``But what would happen if some archaeologist dreamed of
painting the Parthenon the way it was? Certainly there would be an
insurrection.''
</P>
<P>
   Benedetti said the restoration was not a wholesale return to the
original. Not by chance, he said, had the restorers refrained from
restoring the color of the upper reaches of the facade, above the
line of columns. The paint there had been washed away so thoroughly
by centuries of rain that no traces of it could be found.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration ``was not aimed at an integral reconstruction of
Maderno's image, but rather to present it as transformed in some
places by the life of the monument,'' Benedetti said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, he said, was to preserve both ``the qualities invented
by Maderno and those transformations of a qualitative nature that
the centuries have left with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
