 &HT;    There is little fan forgiveness for WWF's `Unforgiven'
 &HT;    ANALYSIS
 &HT;    Every time it looks like WWF President Vince McMahon has added a
key piece, someone else goes down.
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'll have to forgive me if I didn't walk away from the World
Wrestling Federation's latest pay-per-view event _ ``Unforgiven'' _
less than impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I expect a little more. A little more action, a little
more excitement, a little more imagination and a few more surprises
from Vinny Mac and the boys from Titan Towers.
</P>
<P>
   With the company going public in a matter of days and another
pay-per-view on Sunday, the Sept. 26 show from Charlotte, N.C.,
could've been the first step to one of the biggest weeks ever for
the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the live show was well-attended and will probably generate
a solid rating from the pay-per-view television audience, but the
show was more like a newtork ``Raw'' or ``Smackdown'' in terms of
results instead of a cable offering. Triple H's win of the title
was expected and no new angles were started or even completed (Jeff
Jarrett and Chyna will battle again at the ``No Mercy''
pay-per-view).
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the WWF is that the success of its weekly
television shows has left the fans looking for more out of the
pay-per-views. It hasn't happened to date, but the WWF will have
many opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   As for now, every time it looks like Vince McMahon has added a
key piece, someone else goes down. Less than a week after adding
ECW star Taz to the fold, Ken Shamrock was shelved by a major
injury. The Ultimate Fighting Championship star has a neck injury
that could require surgery, possibly spelling the end of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   After the loss of megastar Shawn Michaels to career-ending back
surgery and the uncertain future of The Undertaker, McMahon will be
pounding the independent wrestling trail for more talent such as
Reckless Youth and Mike Quackenbush, or he might be interested in
bringing back old stars like Vader or Yokozuna.
</P>
