 &HT;    W C W
 &HT;    Brings it home
 &HT;    Sporting a new president, the federation sets its sights on
toppling the WWF
 &HT;    Photos by BITA HONARVAR / Cox News Service
 &HT;    Packed: Thousands of fans at WCW's ``Nitro'' in Atlanta enjoyed
the first wrestling event at the new Philips Arena and the first
one under new WCW President Bill Busch.
 &HT;    Put the hammer down: Buff Bagwell raises his arm in victory
after slamming on Vampiro during the ``Nitro'' show in Atlanta.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By John Allen and Todd C. Duncan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Some home cookin' seems to have hit the spot for the WCW.
</P>
<P>
   There was a giddy buzz backstage at the sparkling new Philips
Arena, future home of the Atlanta Hawks and Atlanta Thrashers. As
``Monday Nitro'' wrestlers and roadies shuttled back and forth, the
upbeat mood was apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great,'' said Goldberg, as he stopped to take a
photograph with a young fan.
</P>
<P>
   In the arena, thousands of shouting fans were shaking the walls
to welcome a new World Championship Wrestling back home for this
week's show. The show was the first televised event under the
stewardship of Bill Busch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what's going to happen,'' said Brad Johnson of
Knoxville, Tenn. ``I hope it's much of the same stuff. I admit it,
I love this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Nitro'' show seemed to indicate the open checkbook wielded
by former WCW chief Eric Bischoff was starting to close and it
looks like many other changes are sweeping over Atlanta-based WCW.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a month, Busch has begun to cut what is believed to
be a bloated WCW roster, cut down on the house shows, change
direction of story lines and put some organization into the TV
show.
</P>
<P>
   Busch's first ``Nitro'' show went off without a hitch for
television viewers, generated some interest in the upcoming
pay-per-view and had enough surprises to keep the audience from
switching the channel.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some of the behind-the-scenes differences that
can be attributed to Busch's reign:
</P>
<P>
   Cutting the fat
</P>
<P>
   One thing Bischoff had a problem doing was getting rid of
contracts on people who were not producing enough revenue. Maybe he
was ``Stone Cold'' with fear _ the fear that Vince McMahon's World
Wrestling Federation machine would turn another WCW castoff like
Stone Cold Steve Austin into a mega-star.
</P>
<P>
   Busch has chosen not to fear the unknown and has cut several
wrestlers. Wrestlers such as Brian Adams, Scott Norton and Horace
Hogan do not have a role since the New World Order broke up nearly
a year ago. With the expected departure of Randy Savage at the end
of the year, his brother Lanny Poffo has been dropped from the fold
along with former Savage sidekicks Madusa and Miss Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Having a plan
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest complaints backstage at WCW shows was a lack
of planning before live television shows. At one time, the shows
were staged minutes before they were aired.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not good enough for Busch, who is putting an end to
the ``on the fly'' bookings that have wasted a lot of money and
time while also causing a lot of friction among wrestlers. It was
common for WCW to fly in a group of wrestlers the night of a show's
taping and never use them. Busch wants story lines done a week in
advance of an event and eventually three months in advance of
shows.
</P>
<P>
   That planning will help ``Nitro'' promote future shows and story
lines, an example being the recent six-man tag team match in
Atlanta that was ``signed'' the week before so fans knew what they
would get.
</P>
<P>
   Less talk, more action
</P>
<P>
   The Nitro show has received an overhaul in terms of its
programming and all for the better. Boring opening matches have
been replaced by good matches like Chris Benoit vs. Dean Malenko
two weeks ago and Benoit defending his TV title against Ernest
Miller to open the Atlanta show.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the constant chat sessions have been limited to one per
hour instead of two-to-three.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything
</P>
<P>
   WCW has struggled for years to keep its 8 o'clock audience from
switching to the WWF at 9 p.m. One way Busch is seeking to halt
this is by scheduling good matches starting at 8:57 p.m. and
running them through the opening of WWF's ``Raw is War.'' In
Atlanta, headliner Goldberg began his match at 8:57 p.m. and it
lasted until 9:10 p.m. The move helps keep viewers from the opening
of the WWF show, which is the point where most of the night's
matches are made.
</P>
<P>
   Fans didn't seem to notice the behind-the-scenes differences and
simply enjoyed the wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing a good job. The flips were real good, '' said
Jason Holcomb, 8, of Atlanta. ``It's still cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
