<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0629 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MUNICIPAL-SITES-A     09-29 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MUNICIPAL-SITES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE PEOPLE, BY THE COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., Ind., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In San Diego, comments at public hearings can be submitted by
e-mail. Boston residents can use the city's Web site to complain
about broken street signs or to pay parking tickets and excise
taxes. And in Indianapolis, taxpayers can get electronic copies of
the city budget and rework them, then send them to Mayor Stephen
Goldsmith just to show him how they would do his job.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is called electronic government, and it means giving
people access to a wide range of municipal services and information
through the Internet. In cities across the country, it is rapidly
changing the way people interact with city halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think back to the banking industry,'' said Allan H. Dobrin,
New York City's commissioner of Information Technology and
Telecommunications. ``You basically had to go into a branch, stand
on line and see a teller. Now none of us do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That same kind of paradigm switch will happen in government
now. People will get all of their services without having to go to
a government office.''
</P>
<P>
   Municipal sites on the World Wide Web like NYC Link, New York's
site (www.ci.nyc.ny.us/home.html), already offer information about
services and events and let people get government forms, register
complaints or communicate with officials via e-mail. The site has
been available since July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of electronic government is to go beyond offering
information and communication by enabling residents to do business
directly with their local governments. By relying more on computers
and less on workers, cities hope to save money as well.
</P>
<P>
   Some city Web sites are already offering a number of services.
The Indianapolis site, Indygov (www.indygov.org), for example,
provides information about polling places, parks and zoning issues.
But the site also lets residents pay parking tickets and submit
applications for electrical permits. And in San Carlos, Calif.,
contractors will soon be able to schedule building inspections with
just a point and a click
(www.ci.san-carlos.ca.us/building/smartpermit.html).
</P>
<P>
   The move toward electronic government raises logistical
challenges and some legal issues, and there are questions about
security and privacy, similar to the ones that have arisen with
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But since this is government, there are also concerns about
making such services accessible to more people. While anyone can
get in touch with city hall on the phone or in person, many people,
particularly older or poorer ones, lack computers and Internet
access. So there is a concern that as more emphasis is placed on
electronic government, the result will be two tiers of service, one
for people with Net access and the other for the rest of a city's
residents.
</P>
<P>
   State governments and the federal government are also moving to
provide more information and services electronically, but on a
daily basis, people interact far more frequently with their local
officials and bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   No city is the clear leader in the move toward electronic
government, but several are in the forefront in making available
different types of services. Boston, for example, offers its
residents the quickest way to pay parking tickets: fines can be
settled as soon as someone types in a violation number and credit
card information (www.ci.boston.ma.us/transactions).
</P>
<P>
   San Carlos, Calif., a small city in Silicon Valley, is one of
the leaders in online building permits. Residents will soon be able
to go to a Web site and view plans for any development project
under way in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Local contractors can check the status of their permit
applications 24 hours a day without having to call a government
office, and they will soon be able to check on the next inspection
required for a project and to schedule it by clicking on a date and
time on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, contractors will be able to submit and pay for
their applications by computer, said Brian Maura, the assistant
city manager and the driving force behind the effort in San Carlos.
Maura said the most common question asked by contractors was,
```Who has got my permit now?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they can check it any time,'' he said, ``and they can even
check it when we're closed. It's the classic example of
self-service government.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Chamberlain, the owner of a construction company in San
Carlos, has used the new system and said he hoped that it would do
more than just keep him better informed. ``The permit processing
time out here takes forever,'' he said. ``By having a source to go
to, I think it puts the people who are doing the processing on the
line. Somebody is looking over their shoulder. That may help them
move a little faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Constituents are not the only ones who want government to be
more efficient. In Indianapolis, Goldsmith has challenged his staff
to come up with two ideas for new electronic services each week. In
response, the city now has a database of 158 potential new
services, including plans for an interactive community calendar,
said Ken Barlow, the project manager for the city's electronic
government effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are at 5 percent of what we should be,'' Goldsmith
said. ``We want to change the definition of customer service so
people don't have to go to city hall to do business with city
hall.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with some of the security and privacy concerns,
Indianapolis is requiring people who use certain electronic
services to make a final trip to city hall to put a signature on
file and sign up for a user name and password. ``Everything that
you submit with that user name and password, you have signed away
that you are responsible for that,'' Barlow said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is still a debate over which online transactions are
so sensitive that passwords should be required. Officials in
Indianapolis have still not decided, for example, whether to
require passwords for residents to have access to their tax bills
and whether that information should be made available
electronically to anyone who submits an address in the system.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While the city can allow certain documents to be submitted
electronically without signatures, others must be submitted on
paper and have a signature at the bottom to be legal. ``It gets
back to the big change from paper to electronic,'' Barlow said.
``Some of the laws are geared for paper.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, creating a true electronic government would
require a complete reconfiguration of the equipment and systems
that a city uses to do business. While many city agencies have
computer systems to handle all sorts of information, those systems
are designed for municipal workers to type in information that is
received from constituents by mail, on paper or over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Many cities have already adopted policies of not buying any new
equipment, and not even scheduling upgrades for old equipment,
unless the equipment can be used to connect through the city's Web
site with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and San Diego, officials are moving a little more
slowly toward electronic government, in part to be sure that the
services are provided ``end to end,'' which means that at no point
is information reprocessed by, for example, printing it out and
retyping it.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Grinnell, a spokesman for the city of San Diego, explained,
``What we have decided is not to have any of the fluff stuff but
actually do the whole gamut of the transaction without manual
intervention.'' In the meantime, he said, Mayor Susan Golding and
other officials accept public testimony as well as complaints and
requests for services by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, officials hope to be able to conduct virtually
all municipal business by computer within the next five years.
Eventually, they said, it will seem prehistoric to stand in line at
a government office to do things like paying taxes, fines and fees
or applying for various permits. The advertising and awarding of
city contracts will also be done electronically.
</P>
<P>
   New York has installed a high-speed internal computing network
that will connect all of the city's agencies and will serve as the
backbone of the city's electronic government effort. The city is
already working with International Business Machines to develop a
system that will serve as a one-stop online payment center, where
residents will be able to pay all fines, fees, taxes and other
municipal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies are seeking ways to profit from providing
Internet services for governments. The chief executive of Govworks,
Kaleil D. Isaza Tuzman, said his company, based in New York, might
charge transaction fees of a few cents for people using the sites
but hoped to make most of its money from advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a person going online to pay a $35 parking
ticket might pay the fine plus a fee of a few cents. Or that person
might get a discount on the fine in exchange for accepting
information from advertisers, like automobile insurance companies.
The advertisers would cover the discounts' cost.
</P>
<P>
   Once municipalities make many of their services available,
government technology experts say, local officials will have to be
careful to insure equal access. ``Not everyone has access to the
Internet,'' said Dale Bowen, the director of online services at
Public Technology, a joint research arm for three large
associations of municipalities. ``So how do you adjust for that?''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen's group, which acts as a coordinator for a group of
municipal Web site managers who meet to share ideas, recommends
that computers be provided in public libraries and that electronic
kiosks giving access to the city's Web site be installed in
government buildings. Many cities, like New York, have already done
so; New York has made kiosks available in all five borough halls.
</P>
<P>
   For the next several years, as the various components of each
city's electronic government are built, computer users will
probably find themselves able to conduct some transactions online
while still having to stand in line at government offices to
conduct others.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, for instance, excise taxes for cars and motorcycles
can be paid online, but the same tax for boats cannot be.
</P>
<P>
   As new services become available, officials say, the rewards
will come not just in time savings but in budget savings as well.
``As the Internet expands, we are cutting our bottom-line expenses,
and that's a huge advantage to your taxpayer,'' said Kyle Tager,
Boston's director of online services. ``Any time a person doesn't
have to pick up a phone and bother a city employee, it makes it
easier for everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
