   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ISRAEL _ GRAJAR, Israel _ After two years in a country
just the size of New Jersey, I thought I knew Israel well _ until I
went to Grajar. If you could condense the confusion of the Middle
East down to one town, it might look like this little-known border
village. Here, they speak Arabic, practice the mysterious Alawite
religion, adore Syrian president Hafez Assad and hold Israeli
citizenship. No wonder no one can figure out whether the town
should stay with Israel or be turned over to Syria or Lebanon. And,
no wonder 25-year-old resident Yossef Salman is having trouble
getting permission to bring his Syrian wife from Damascus. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ALLIANCE _ MEXICO CITY _ One political player here calls
it ``the blunder of the century for Mexico's opposition.'' Late
Tuesday night talks definitely crumbled to forge a sweeping
coalition that could have probably defeated Mexico's Revolutionary
Institutional Party, or PRI, in next year's presidential election.
Most polls show that an alliance among virtually all of Mexico's
opposition parties _ from right to left _ would have driven the PRI
from the presidency after more than 70 in power. Polls also showed
that Mexicans wanted to see the formation of a coalition. But
opposition leaders failed to show leadership, analysts say. Now the
PRI's chances of winning in 2000 once again are better than they've
looked for a long time. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). 30. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA _ Q&AMP;A with Mary Brown Bullock, Agnes Scott College's
president who is a historian who takes the long view of China's
long and rich history. As the 50th anniversary of Communist rule
arrives (Oct. 1), she also does some gazing into China's future.
Bullock serves on the board of directors of the Committee for
U.S.-China Relations and is active in other China and Asia groups.
(Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
