<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0638 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SWAN-GIRLS-ART-93     09-29 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SWAN-GIRLS-ART-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTOR FILLS GIRLS' DESIRE FOR THEIR OWN GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Janese Swanson, inventor and founder of Girl Tech
toys, has some ideas about what little girls like. Even during a
recent interview over lunch in Manhattan, she couldn't stop herself
from brainstorming, thinking of new toy ideas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while she picked over her grilled tuna, she had an
idea for placating picky eaters: jigsaw-shape cutters that would
turn a boring peanut butter and jelly sandwich into an edible
puzzle. Or for fidgety young airline passengers, a travel book with
see-through pocket pages to hold postcards, souvenirs and foreign
money.
</P>
<P>
   Want more ideas? Ms. Swanson has a million of them. But unlike
countless other mothers who fantasize about creating whine-stopping
diversions for their children, she sees some of her ideas hit the
market.
</P>
<P>
   At 41, Ms. Swanson is the creator of a line of affordable
electronic gadgets for girls. Some of her recent toys, which are
manufactured under Radica Games' Girl Tech brand, include the Door
Pass, which sets off an alarm if anyone tries to sneak into its
owner's bedroom, and the Beam-It flashlight, which works like a
projector to flash written messages (e.g., ``I luv U 4-ever'') on a
darkened wall.
</P>
<P>
   Her most popular creation has been the Password Journal, a
voice-activated plastic box the size of a book. The box holds a
diary that is accessible only if its owner speaks the password.
</P>
<P>
   The Password Journal costs $19.99, and girls from age 8 to 12
apparently think that this is a small price to pay to prevent pesky
siblings from snooping. In the months since the Password Journal's
debut in February, it has climbed onto the list of the top 10
best-selling toys nationwide in the youth electronics category,
according to the NPD Group in Port Washington, N.Y., which tracks
toy sales at major retailers. In June the Password Journal ranked
third when average unit sales for the stores surveyed were
tabulated, behind the Sing-A-Long Cassette Player and Flip Phone
Walkie Talkie, both from DSI Toys.
</P>
<P>
   In the toy market, where almost anything electronic is
automatically labeled a boys' product, the Girl Tech gadgets are
remarkable not just because they sell but also because they
contradict the sex stereotypes that the industry seems to hold
dear.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, they're not pink. For another, they have nothing
whatsoever to do with dolls or ponies. And perhaps most important,
they appeal to the idea that girls, like boys, enjoy playing with
gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swanson, who has a doctorate in education from the
University of San Francisco, is adamant about the fact that girls
should be allowed to revel in their, well, girlness without being
stigmatized for it. ``They don't like the same kinds of toys boys
like, but they still like electronic toys,'' she said. ``They need
opportunities to be mischievous and adventurous, but they also
really want to identify with their own gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Her approach seems to work. While some other putatively
girl-friendly ventures have stumbled recently _ most notably, the
highly touted Purple Moon software company, which is being bought
by Mattel _ Radica has plans to expand its Girl Tech line with two
new toys later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Janese understands what girls think is fun,
and she has managed to combine that with what she knows about all
the academic research about what fosters growth and independence,''
said Pat Feely, Radica's president and chief executive. ``Some
other people who tried this ended up with products that have a real
appeal to moms, but not to girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophically, Ms. Swanson's toys fall between ardently
pro-feminist software, like Purple Moon's Rockett series, and the
hot-pink Barbie laptop computer. In the early 1990s, while working
on her doctorate, Ms. Swanson interviewed 60 children to determine
if girls and boys played differently. She said she had concluded
that girls liked role-playing, just as boys did, ``but different
roles from the ones boys like, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake that some products for girls make is that they
don't take that desire into consideration,'' Ms. Swanson said.
``They focus on the everyday realities of their lives. But girls
don't need toys that focus on going to school or playing soccer
because they already do those things all day.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's another theme to Ms. Swanson's toys, it might be
privacy. Like diaries with a lock and key, the Password Journal and
Door Pass seem to feed the instinct for a secret life. ``They can
have adventures with their secret notebooks or can spy on their
little brothers who are trying to sneak into their rooms,'' Ms.
Swanson said.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that emerged from Ms. Swanson's own childhood, said
her mother, Jenna Plein. ``She had a notebook that she carried
around all the time, and she got terribly upset when her sister
would get near it,'' said Ms. Plein, a beautician who brought up
Janese (pronounced Jan-NIECE) and five other children primarily as
a single parent. ``She had to share everything _ her bedroom,
everything _ and the notebook was her one private thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The toys that Ms. Swanson played with as a child tended to fall
more into the category of debris. Discarded pieces of cardboard,
for instance, became sleighs she rode down the canyon near the
house her mother rented in San Diego. Then there was the family
blender, which she took apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't afford too many toys,'' her mother said. ``So she
was always inventing something on her own, or trying to figure out
how something worked. Come to think of it, the blender never was
put back together.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Ms. Swanson had dreams of becoming a doctor, but
those hopes were discouraged. ``In high school I was told that boys
become doctors and girls become nurses,'' said Ms. Swanson, who
graduated from Orange Glen High School in San Diego in 1975. ``I
didn't know any better _ I was the only one in my family who had
gone through high school at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she went through a succession of jobs, including:
</P>
<P>
   1. House cleaner. ``In grade school, I worked for my mom's
customers. She did their hair, I did their bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Sales clerk at Sears. ``I was the top salesperson in stereos
and radios. I made a lot of money for an 18-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Elementary school teacher. ``I just loved watching the way
kids' minds worked. Then the district had to cut 40 teachers. I
didn't have three years' seniority, so I got laid off.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Flight attendant. ``It was the early 1980s, and they made us
wear what they called regulation lips: red lipstick.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Model. ``One time at a job, this guy said, `Stick your tongue
out _ I need to see how your tongue looks.' This was for an ad
where you had to lick ice cream. I said, `Stick your own tongue
out,' and walked out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, after a brief marriage that produced her
daughter, Jackie, now 12, Ms. Swanson was hired by Broderbund
Software as a product manager.
</P>
<P>
   Two products she helped shape were the Treehouse and Playroom
series, which were among Broderbund's earliest early childhood
titles. She also worked on the Macintosh edition of the popular
Where in Time Is Carmen Sandiego?
</P>
<P>
   ``She sees the world the way it will be a year or two from now,
not the way it is now,'' said Tom Marcus, a former vice president
for business development at Broderbund. ``She showed a real passion
for that early childhood category long before it had market
acceptance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swanson said working at Broderbund had burned her out. ``It
was long, long hours, and they were paying me less than $40,000 a
year, and I was a single mother,'' Ms. Swanson said. ``I missed my
daughter, Jackie, who was in day care, so I started inventing
gadgets for her.''
</P>
<P>
   One was a recording device that Ms. Swanson hoped to install in
Jackie's day-care cubby and in her own office. ``I missed her so
much that I used to call my home answering machine to hear her
voice,'' Ms. Swanson said, ``and I thought this would let me talk
to her during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   That inspired Ms. Swanson's first commercial success, a handheld
recording device that changes a voice's sound so a speaker can
sound as if, say, she has just inhaled helium. In 1992, Ms. Swanson
left Broderbund to develop the technology, which she licensed to
both Yes Entertainment, which marketed it as the Yak Bak, and to
Tiger Electronics for its Talkboy FX.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after Ms. Swanson decided to create toys aimed at
girls, she founded Girl Tech as an independent company with
headquarters in San Rafael, Calif., where she lives. But the
venture floundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years after I founded the company,'' she said, ``toy
store buyers would say, `Can you make it pink?' `Can't you make it
for boys?' And I would say, `No, this is what girls like to play
with.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the industry's annual Toy Fair in New York City in
early 1998, Ms. Swanson met Feely of Radica. ``I have a daughter,
and I knew right away that Janese had zeroed in on how to make
something that girls would not find too boring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Radica acquired Ms. Swanson's company in 1998 for $6 million and
expects to sell $7 million worth of Girl Tech products this year,
Feely said. Not all of the current line has been successful. Ms.
Swanson is considering new packaging for the flashlight and said a
talking picture frame would probably be discontinued soon.
</P>
<P>
   In November, two new Girl Tech toys will go on sale nationwide.
They are a Keepsafe Box ($19.99), which has a remote-controlled
lock and is designed to store valuables, and Bug 'Em ($19.99), a
remote listening device that enables the user to eavesdrop on
conversations in another room.
</P>
<P>
   And after that? ``I think I really want to invent some gadgets
for women,'' Ms. Swanson said. ``I have some ideas about what they
might like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
