<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY SAYS CARS ARE NOT A MAJOR SOURCE OF POLLUTION
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cars and light trucks account for less than a
quarter of smog pollution in major cities, the AAA Motor Club said
in a study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Most smog comes from sources such as power plants and
refineries, AAA said in its study of 25 major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Auto emissions have been steadily declining since 1970, said AAA
spokesperson Susan Pikrallidas. She said that is mainly the result
of tighter federal emissions standards, more effective state auto
inspections and cleaner-burning gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``When trying to make the air cleaner, you can't continue to
bang on motorists because it's not their fault,'' said Lon
Anderson, another AAA spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Pikrallidas stressed that the study was based on data provided
by local governments, not AAA. The findings were not meant to
discourage car pooling or other measures designed to improve air
quality but to send the message that other pollution sources must
be curbed, Pikrallidas said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
