<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      09-29 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: WHEN AN AUTHOR IS PECKED APART BY CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, how would you like to labor on something for a year or two
or five or six and then be told it's rotten? It happens every day,
and it happens eventually to every author, no matter how applauded:
the howling wind of the bad review. Years of work, of lonely
intellectual wandering, hit by the blast. And how does the writer
learn the bad news?
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for writers to  &UR; say &LR;  they don't want to see
any bad reviews. Others avow they don't want to be told either the
bad or the good, and only the writer knows if a peek is sneaked.
Since not even Shakespeare got solely good reviews, all writers
have to learn to cope with  &UR; the reviewer. &LR;  For instance, the
novelist Mary Gordon, who has had high praise and low knocks, put
the predicament this way: ``A good review never feels as good as a
bad one feels bad. I never want to know either way.''
</P>
<P>
   And so this is how she deals with reviews now: ``My friends, my
editors, my agent, they were all told not to tell me. They put my
reviews in envelopes and send them to me, and I hide them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's always that helpful friend who will say, `Boy, did
you get it!' I just finished a biography of Joan of Arc. She used
to say, `If you do that to me again, I'll cut your head off.'
That's what I want to say.'' To reviewers and friends who blab.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of reviews is, of course, endlessly fascinating and
perhaps always frightening and mysterious and frustrating to people
in book publishing. So much so that Pushcart Press has published
``Rotten Reviews and Rejections,'' and has sold about 70,000 copies
in its various editions, mostly, one supposes, to writers and their
publishing colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   This highly amusing book is a collection of blurb-size excerpts
of bad reviews of the works of great and/or popular writers. It's a
feel-good book for authors. If Henry James and Mark Twain can get
bad reviews, the contemporary writer can ask, then what the devil
do reviewers really know anyhow?
</P>
<P>
   Writers react to reviews in as many ways as there are reviews to
react to. Mary Higgins Clark, the best-selling author of suspense
novels, sometimes finds reviews helpful. She describes their value
this way: ``I read any I get from my publisher's clipping service,
to see if there's a consistency in them. If everyone says that the
characters are wooden, then generally I would be concerned. I say
to myself, `Lady, what are you doing wrong?' But if one says the
characters are wooden and another says they leap off the pages,
that's not helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love good reviews and cordially despise the bad ones. They
are engraved on my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspense is not ``literary,'' so a writer of Ms. Clark's popular
success can become a joyful target for some reviewers, leaving her
open to a certain snobbish glee that comes from giving such a
writer a kick. But she uses it. ``I want to be good,'' she said.
``I don't want the book I'm writing to sound like the last one.''
</P>
<P>
   A cliche about writers is that they are somehow frangible,
although one would think it takes a pretty tough-minded person to
sit alone day after day and churn out 600 or more pages of
manuscript. Still, while no one really knows whether good reviews
sell books and bad ones kill them, there is agreement that positive
reviews are at least excellent for the psyche. So however the
writer feels about these evaluations, the publisher generally tries
to be as sensitive as the skin on a ripe peach when dealing with
the authors' reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Segal, senior editor at Knopf, said that bad or good,
``I want my authors to hear about their reviews from me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fax them a note, or I read them to them on the phone,'' he
said. ``I try to read all their reviews, and if they are negative
or unfair, I send them along to the writers who want them with a
note telling them my thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   He underlines good ones and puts them on the Random House Web
site, randomhouse.com, which is linked to Amazon.com and other Web
sites and in that way circulates the good. His attitude about
publishing ``is to inform the writer about everything,'' he said.
``I want them to be surprised upward rather than disappointed
downward. If an author really doesn't want to know about reviews, I
respect that, except if it's a rave. Then I take it upon myself to
share it with the writer anyhow.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Meyer, director of public relations for Simon &AMP;
Schuster, said: ``If there's a specially unfortunate review, I
consult with the book's editor, and we try to find a favorable
review to counter the bad. You don't want to shield the writer from
a bad review if the consequence is that the writer will hear about
it from a friend. It's better if there are several reviews
simultaneously, something to restore balance to the writer's
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Simon is review-hardened from his years as a playwright.
(His first book, the memoir ``Rewrites,'' received generally
favorable reviews when it was published by Simon &AMP; Schuster in
1996; his continuation of that memoir, ``The Play Goes On,'' just
arrived in bookstores.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You open the play and read 45 reviews right away,'' he said.
``A book is out a week or so, and maybe you've seen one or two
reviews. People take time with books, and the reviews are not as
damaging as the sudden newspaper and television reviews that don't
like a play, so we close it on Saturday. You don't close a book on
Saturdays.''
</P>
<P>
   As for authors who say they don't read their reviews, Simon
said, ``They're lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Except perhaps for Gore Vidal, the astonishingly eclectic writer
who himself is the subject of a biography by Fred Kaplan that is
being published by Doubleday in October. He has 100 publishers
around the world, many working in languages distant to his ear,
``so I'm fairly indifferent to reviewers,'' he said. ``When I'm
not, the public will hear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he learned anything from his many reviewers, he paused
a moment, and answered: ``Are you crazy? They should be learning
from me. But they're too dumb.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
