<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-BILOXI-WEEKEND-TEX     09-29 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILOXI-WEEKEND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CASINOS, BILOXI HASN'T FORGOTTEN ITS DEEP SOUTH ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BILOXI-ITINERARY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ On its September cover, Travel Holiday magazine
asked the question somebody was bound to ask: ``Is Biloxi really
the new Vegas?''
</P>
<P>
   Fair question. This spring, the Mississippi coast gambling mecca
welcomed its biggest and grandest and most Las Vegasy resort yet _
the much-talked-about Beau Rivage, a 1,780-room behemoth complete
with 12 restaurants, a European-style casino, Aveda products in the
marble bathrooms, a marina big enough to accommodate 200-foot
yachts, and a resident company of Montreal's Cirque du Soleil. Its
owner? Steve Wynn's Mirage Corp., which opened last year's
most-talked-about casino, the fine-art-laden Bellagio, in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   But the Beau Rivage is no Bellagio. And Biloxi is no Las Vegas.
We mean both of those in the best of ways.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, unlike Las Vegas, Biloxi has a long history, both
as a city and as a tourist attraction. It was founded on the Gulf
Coast of Mississipi in 1699 by French explorer Pierre LeMoyne Sieur
D'Iberville, on a site where American Indians had lived for
centuries. By the 1820s, city folk from New Orleans, attracted by
cool sea breezes, had begun building summer cottages here; by the
1850s, hotels lined the waterfront of what had become the Deep
South's most popular resort. (One of those, the Magnolia Hotel, wasand relocated and now houses the city's Mardi Gras museum.)
And through the first half of this century, upscale resorts and the
beach _ and, illegally but fairly openly, gambling halls _
continued to attract visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1969, the coast was battered by Hurricane Camille, and
though Biloxi rebuilt, tourism faltered. The '80s oil bust only
added to the decline. At Mary Mahoney's Old French House, an
old-fashioned restaurant of the sort found only in the South, where
the waiters wear boxy jackets and the ladies who lunch wear hats,
owner Bobby Mahoney confirms this turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late '80s, we were a tourist town without any
tourists,'' Mahoney says. ``We knew we had to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   That something, as it has been in so many waterfront towns, from
Atlantic City to Shreveport, turned out to be gaming. A referendum
legalized gambling on the coast in 1992, and the first Biloxi
casinos opened in August 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest ones tended to be smallish and relatively
unsophisticated; at least one was just a riverboat that was hauled
down the Mississippi from its former Iowa home. A few of the first
entries are already closed. But slowly, bigger companies moved in:
Isle of Capri built a big hotel and casino complex, as did Casino
Magic and the Grand Casino. In late '97, the Imperial Palace opened
an upscale 30-story high-rise, complete with a spa and an attached
movie theater and retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   And the growth continues; Circus Circus hopes to break ground
soon. A Hard Rock Cafe _ Mississippi's first _ is in the works.
Existing hotels are expanding, even though the area already has
more than 16,000 rooms, up from 6,000 the year gambling began.
Transportation has improved; some travelers still prefer to fly
into New Orleans or Mobile (both about an hour's drive away), but
this spring, Air Tran began direct flights into the small
Gulfport/Biloxi airport from several cities, including Fort
Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   With all that, however, just 25 percent of the tourism revenue
is generated by gaming, says Steve Richer of the Mississippi Gulf
Coast Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is because the beach came first. More than 50
charter boats offer sport-fishing trips or sunset cruises. Along
the 26 miles of man-made white sand beaches, beachcombers can swim,
parasail or rent Jet Skis. There are the requisite tacky souvenir
shops, miniature golf courses and ice cream parlors of any seaside
resort.
</P>
<P>
   And, though new casinos make the headlines, many locals are just
as excited about the planned fall groundbreaking for the new home
of the George E. Ohr Arts and Cultural Center. The museum is
dedicated to the once-obscure artist dubbed the Mad Potter of
Biloxi, both for his odd but beautiful pots and for his penchant
for crossing his eyes when being photographed and turning
cartwheels in the street, his trademark 2-foot-long handlebar
mustache following stiffly in the wind. Ohr created his intricately
shaped, oddly glazed pottery only until 1910, abruptly quitting
because he felt unappreciated. His works were rediscovered in the
1960s and really took off in the early '80s, when collectors like
Andy Warhol discovered them. Now they can fetch $40,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The simple museum is already a cultural center for the town,
with frequent displays by local artists, classes and lectures. But
the new $8 million Ohr-O'Keefe Museum, which will include a gallery
for works by African-American artists, should bring it to a much
larger stage, if only for its architect _ Frank Gehry, who designed
the decade's most acclaimed museum, the Guggenheim in Bilbao,
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The current museum is on the edge of the Vieux Marche, or Old
Market, a part of downtown with buildings dating from the early
1700s. The cobblestone streets are a nice place to wander or stop
for lunch, soaking in the history and reading the plaques that
decorate many of the old buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But occasionally, the history results in some uncomfortable
moments. A few miles west of downtown is the seaside Beauvoir, the
last home of Jefferson Davis, president of the Confederacy.
Visitors can tour his house, impeccably furnished; more than half
of the antiques were actually used by the Davis family.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum, in the Presidential Library that opened last
year, gently but firmly takes the Confederacy's side of things,
mentioning slavery only in passing. The grounds are also home to a
Confederate cemetery, which looks somewhat like a miniature version
of Arlington National Cemetery, with rows of simple headstones for
fallen soldiers. It also has a Confederate memorial inscribed: ``No
nation rose so white and fair. None fell so pure of crime.'' Surely
I am not the only visitor who stared at this monument in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the old South. The new South is better represented
by the Beau Rivage, which, though it has a Las Vegas pedigree,
isn't really all that Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Bellagio cost an estimated $2 billion, the Beau Rivage
cost an estimated $650 million. Where the Bellagio has
impressionist masterpieces and Jackson Pollock originals, the Beau
Rivage has 80-year-old live oaks lining the drive and magnolia
trees transplanted from old Mississippi homes growing in its atrium
lobby. And where the Bellagio's 3,000 rooms are on the edge of an
8-acre man-made lake, the Beau Rivage overlooks the Gulf of Mexico.
The real one.
</P>
<P>
   True Biloxi backers will also say that the Beau Rivage _ like
the other dozen or so Gulf Coast casinos _ has a distinct but
indefinable advantage over its western competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got real Southern hospitality,'' says Mahoney, the
restaurateur. ``You won't find that in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
