<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BEAUTY-BALL30-COX     09-29 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-BALL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Screenplay as salvation: `Beauty' became writer's catharsis
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to Oscar nominations, critics are
already using phrases like ``shoo-in'' and ``sure thing'' when
talking about one movie.
</P>
<P>
   Best actor? Yep. Actress? Very likely. Original screenplay? No
doubt. And ``American Beauty'' is the only film so far this year
that seems to be an instant contender for best picture of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The satiric but uplifting tragicomedy is the first feature film
from 42-year-old screenwriter Alan Ball. He seems to have come out
of nowhere. But actually, he came from Marietta (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   He lived there as a teen, going to Marietta High School, then
enrolling at the University of Georgia for his first year of
college. After that, he transferred to Florida State University in
Tallahassee. ``My mom still lives in Marietta, in the same house I
grew up in,'' he says. He visits occasionally, and flies his
mother, Mary, out to the West Coast once or twice a year as well.
</P>
<P>
   He may sound like an overnight success, but that's not exactly
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been paying dues as long as anybody else,'' says Atlantan
Priscilla Smith, a classmate and close high school friend of
Ball's, who remains in touch. The two played in the band together
(he was a drum major), edited the school newspaper on alternate
years, wrote a musical together two years in a row to promote
newspaper sales, and continued to collaborate after they'd headed
on to college: During summer breaks, they produced theater at Cobb
(Ga.) County's Civic Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cast him in his first role _ he played Alan in `Picnic,'''
says Smith, now a teacher of Spanish, English and drama at the
Horizons School. ``Since 1980 or '81, he's been out on his own
doing stuff, writing plays, working on a novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball hasn't had a Georgia address in a while. In an interview
with the Los Angeles Times, he described his neighbors in Marietta
as ``shut down and living in total denial,'' a theme that crops up
in his movie. ``To me,'' he added, ``it was a town I had to get out
of.''
</P>
<P>
   He lived in New York until 1994, when he moved to Los Angeles
after his off-Broadway play ``Five Women Wearing the Same Dress''
resulted in an invitation to write for the sitcom ``Cybill.''
</P>
<P>
   For better and worse, that experience led to his penning the
``American Beauty'' screenplay in his free time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you become a sitcom writer, especially for a star-driven
show, you have to divorce yourself from any really passionate
connection to your work, because it gets arbitrarily changed every
day,'' he says by phone from his Los Angeles office.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The Cybill Shepherd show became just a day job,
while his screenplay became his salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my last season writing for the show, I would just come
home and pour my frustration into this script. It was kind of a
cathartic thing for me. It was fun to believe in this world and the
characters _ it wasn't just factory work.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``American Beauty'' script was initially inspired by the Amy
Fisher trial, which took place when Ball was still in New York,
working for a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fascinated by that because I instinctively knew that
what we saw in the media and what really happened were probably two
different things,'' he says. ``I realized I would never know that
true story, and no one would, except the people who lived it.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Beauty,'' Kevin Spacey plays Lester, frustrated suburban
husband of workaholic Carolyn (Annette Bening) and father to sullen
teenage Jane (Thora Birch). Mired in middle-aged blahs, Lester
comes to life on seeing _ and falling for _ Jane's best friend, a
provocative teen named Angela (Mena Suvari). Meanwhile, Jane is
becoming mesmerized by the spooky boy next door ( Wes Bentley) who
videotapes everything. And Carolyn has a fling with a real estate
czar (Peter Gallagher).
</P>
<P>
   These sexual intrigues and misunderstandings converge one dark
and stormy night, resolving in a violent act that surprisingly
becomes a transcendent glimpse of the eternal in the everyday.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Not your basic Hollywood movie.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much he loved writing this quirky,
hard-to-describe script, Ball never expected it to get made with
virtually no changes. ``It's amazing to me. I thought I would get a
few (studio) meetings, and some suggestions to get into therapy,''
he quips. ``I never expected it to get made, much less by
DreamWorks.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when his agent told him that the script was being read
by Steven Spielberg, Ball thought it was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Like the plotline of the film, the meaning of the film's title
is something that was continually in flux. ``The title sort of
organically happened,'' Ball says. ``I sort of knew the title as I
was writing the screenplay, but it's like everything in the movie:
Things appear to be one thing on the surface, but if you look
closer they're richer and more interesting and complex than you
once thought. It's like the movie itself, which starts out as a
black comedy, then goes to a spiritual place. First you think (the
title) refers to the rose, then you think it's Angela, but
ultimately it's about the ability to see beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he's suddenly a hot commodity as a screenwriter, his
hands are tied for the next eight months with a new sitcom, but
this time, he's in charge; he created ``Oh, Grow Up,'' an ABC
comedy about grown men sharing a brownstone, based on some of his
own New York experiences. Once he's finished with the first season
(and gets to take a vacation) he hopes to finish his next
screenplay and continue to work in both TV and film.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent every day on the set of ``American Beauty,''
watching first-time filmmaker Sam Mendes direct, Ball is thinking
about spending time behind the camera himself. And then, maybe
he'll go back to the live stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do this as long as I can and still keep my
sanity, but then I'd like to open a theater somewhere,'' he says.
``I'm a living cliche: What I really want to do is direct, and my
heart is in the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE INTERVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening. Directed by Sam
Mendes. Rated R for strong sexuality, nudity, profanity, violence
and drug content. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 58 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's a beaut. The remarkable Kevin Spacey leads a
stellar ensemble cast (Annette Bening, Thora Birch) in a scarily
disturbing, daringly hilarious comedy-drama about the implosion of
the American family.
</P>
<P>
   Review byEleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
