<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-SHOWS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gucci revisits signature `rock star'-type silhouettes
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN _ It's not uncommon for designers to refer back in fashion
history while conceptualizing their collections. The best designers
admit, in fact, that they don't invent styles so much as re-invent
them.
</P>
<P>
   What is uncommon is for someone to take as short a view as Gucci
design chief Tom Ford. Sizing up his spring/summer 2000 clothes at
a Tuesday morning breakfast at the Four Seasons Hotel, Ford said:
``This collection may be the first '90s retrospective.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he had no intention of moving too far from the
sort of styles that brought him prominence. He was sticking with
the ``rock star'' image his clothes embody, particularly the
boot-cut pants silhouette he popularized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fitted flair is the most important pant leg,'' he said,
``because it makes you look tall, tall, tall, tall, tall and
skinny.''
</P>
<P>
   That visual effect was evident during Tuesday night's Gucci
runway preview. Leggy models wore fitted flairs in leather,
snakeskin, sequined, brocade and jersey knit, paired with matching
jackets that closed with a single silver pin, sheer silk pullovers,
or racy ruffled blouses that opened to the navel.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also showed plenty of his other two preferred pants: one
that skimmed the leg all the way down to the ankle, and another he
calls a ``training pant'' with zippers from ankle to calf. Most of
the (knee-to floor-length) skirts and dresses brushed the body
without clinging. Shoes were strappy, high-heeled and encrusted in
semi-precious stones; Ford's hosiery of choice, no matter what
color the outfit, was pale pink.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a smattering of blues, pinks and metallics, the
outfits were mainly black and white. Evening dresses were almost
all long, tight and backless.
</P>
<P>
   Prada
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Miuccia Prada reached back as far as four decades,
to the pioneering designs of Yves Saint Laurent, to create a
collection that's simpler, girlier and prettier than any she's done
in many seasons. Gone are the mirror fragment appliques, ``utility
chic'' zippers and Velcro, patchwork leathers and baby food color
schemes. Instead, Prada used such ultra-feminine design details as
wide, flat pleats on knee-length skirts, form-fitting knitwear and
blouses as airy as scarves. She hasn't given up on olive and brown
entirely, but this collection was infused with purples, yellows,
blues and creams. Prada's luxury fabric of choice was ostrich
leather.
</P>
<P>
   Men with style
</P>
<P>
   Over dinner at the magnificent restaurant Il Carpaccio, eight
American fashion editors compared notes on the Italian male's
unique style of dressing: How much aplomb they show in mixing
patterned shirts and ties. How even men in their 50s pull off the
peg-legged suit look as easily as guys in their 20s. How stylish
their shoes look, whether dressy or casual. How, unlike American
males, they don't hesitate to primp. We never could agree if it was
nature or nurture. But as we walked out into the balmy night, none
of us could keep from glancing, with curiosity and admiration, at a
dapper diner in the corner. He had on a yellow-blue-and-white plaid
spread-collar shirt with a mini-checked blue-and-yellow tie.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
