<HEADER>
A0658 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-BILOXI-ITINERARY-TEX     09-29 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILOXI-ITINERARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILOXI: WHERE TO GO, WHAT TO DO
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BILOXI-WEEKEND) (For use byNYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRIDAY NIGHT: After checking into your hotel, try the fancy
seafood-in-cream-sauce dishes at the formal Mary Mahoney's Old
French House Restaurant (Magnolia and Water streets; (228)
374-0163.) Dinner for two, about $50. Or, for a slightly more
relaxed atmosphere, head for The Porter House, (604 Porter Ave.,
Ocean Springs; (228) 875-3663), where locals line up for the
nouvelle Cajun-influenced seafood. Dinner for two, about $50.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward _ well, you might as well get the gambling out of your
system. One could argue that if you've seen one casino, you've seen
them all, but there are a few subtle differences. The Imperial
Palace, sister to a Las Vegas hotel, is one of the newer resorts,
opening in December '97; some of the other large-scale casinos
include Casino Magic, Isle of Capri and the Grand Casino. If you
want to go where the locals try their luck, head to Boomtown, a
western-themed, more casual spot. The casinos are clustered in
several groups along the water, too far to walk between but within
easy driving distance of each other; there's also a free shuttle
service between them, but on our visit not many people were using
it.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: Wake up with a stroll along the beach, then get an
overview of the area by taking a 90-minute tour on the Ole Biloxi
Tour Train ($8 adults, $5 children ages 5-12; (228) 374-8687.) The
open-air, narrated tour takes you past 30 sites, including Casino
Row; the Biloxi Lighthouse; the Vieux Marche, or Old Market; the
seashell roof on St. Michael's Church; and various museums.
</P>
<P>
   Again, lunch should be seafood; another local favorite is the
Old Biloxi Schooner, (159 Howard St., (228) 374-8071), whose crab
meat-and-cheese sandwiches were recently praised by ``Travel
Holiday.'' Lunch for two, about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Before or after, catch the Biloxi Shrimping Trip, ($10 adults;
two to seven departures daily from early February through early
December; call (800) 289-7908 for schedule.) Owners Corrie and
Virginia Eleuterius demonstrate how shrimping operations work
during a cruise on the bay; if you'd like, you can pick out the
shrimp from a catch that might include soft-shell crabs, eels,
squid and dozens of fish.
</P>
<P>
   There's probably time left to see a couple of museums; one best
bet is the Maritime and Seafood Industry Museum, which documents
the fishing and shrimping industries that built Biloxi and the
hurricanes that tried to destroy it. (115 First St., (228)
435-6320. $3 for adults.) And there's the George E. Ohr Arts and
Cultural Center (136 G.E. Ohr St., (228) 374-5547; $2 adults.) This
tribute to the so-called Mad Potter of Biloxi showcases hundreds of
his odd-shaped and odd-colored pots; there's also a small display
of contemporary local artworks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, even if you're not staying there, try to score tickets to
the Beau Rivage's Cirque du Soleil presentation of ``Alegria.'' The
Montreal company has its own intimate theater at the hotel, where
it puts on its circus for people who don't like circuses. There's
some kind of deeper theatrical meaning here, which we didn't get,
but we did like the acts, including a fire dancer, trapeze artists,
contortionists, gymnasts and clowns, all set to ethereal music from
a live band. (Shows nightly except Tuesday; tickets, $45 adults,
$27.50 children ages 5-12; call (888) 566-7469.)
</P>
<P>
   Have dinner before or after the show at one of the hotel's 12
restaurants; among them are spots featuring Japanese, Italian,
French-influenced seafood, Asian, Memphis-style barbecue and a
buffet.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: For a dose of history, start at Beauvoir, Jefferson
Davis Home and Presidential Library. (2244 Beach Blvd., (800)
570-3818) The tour starts in the newly opened library with a short
film on the life of the president of the Confederacy; afterward,
tour the museum exhibits, the house that served as Davis' last
home, and a small Confederate cemetery tucked on the pleasantly
groomed grounds.
</P>
<P>
   If weather permits, head for the water again. From spring to
fall, more than 50 fishing charters operate out of Biloxi's
marinas; some can also be hired to provide bay cruises. Another
option is to take a ferry from Gulfport to the deserted-but-scenic
Gulf Islands, about an hour off the mainland, to enjoy the dunes,
surf and pines. Take snacks and drinks; concessions aren't
available. (Ferries leave from Gulfport twice daily from early
March through the last Sunday in October, (800) 388-3290; $16
adults.)
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to stay landside, take time for one last seafood
lunch; try the soft-shell crab or shrimp po-boys at the casual
McElroy's Harbor House (in the Biloxi Small Craft Harbor, (228)
435-5001.) Lunch for two, about $20.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI box
</P>
<P>
   Biloxi Information: Biloxi Chamber of Commerce, (228) 374-2717;
www.biloxi.org. Mississippi Gulf Coast Convention and Visitors
Bureau, (228) 896-6699; www.gulfcoast.org.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
