<HEADER>
A0666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FERGIE30-COX     09-29 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERGIE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fergie U.S. spokeswoman for Wedgwood
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scandal of scandals: the Duchess of York setting a
table with mix-and-match china, seashells and Gummi Bears. In a
suburban Atlanta department store, no less.
</P>
<P>
   How common.
</P>
<P>
   How Fergie.
</P>
<P>
   How come?
</P>
<P>
   The ex-wife of Prince Andrew, Weight Watchers goddess and
soon-to-be NBC ``Today Show'' contributing correspondent has a new
gig _ as the U.S. spokeswoman for Wedgwood, the renowned British
china maker. And, in an ironic Madison Avenue twist, the former
Sarah Ferguson is rolling up her sleeves to show shoppers how to
take the ``fussiness'' out of entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might be wondering what on earth the Duchess of York, with
cooks and butlers, knows about setting a table,'' she told the 500
who turned out on a soggy Wednesday at the North Point Mall Rich's,
the first stop on a national tour. ``I'm a single working mother,
I've paid off lots of debt (once reaching $4 million), as you all
know, but I believe in old-fashioned standards and manners.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean, however, hosts can't have fun, especially
when the entertaining is impromptu.
</P>
<P>
   And with that, the Duchess showed the crowd how to throw a table
together in 10 minutes _ you know, like when ``suddenly Andrew
(with whom she still lives) walks in and says he's bringing 15 home
to dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clumsy scene not far removed from the famous ``I Love
Lucy'' episode in which Lucy does a bumbling sales pitch for
``Vitameatavegamin,'' Fergie demonstrated how it's perfectly proper
to mix china patterns of the same color, use conk shells as vases
and a bathroom soap dish for use as a butter plate or side dish (in
this case, for Gummi Bears). ``Do wash it first, though, you
know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, several hundred more shoppers joined the sell-out
crowd to have the duchess autograph one Wedgwood plate. Within
minutes, though, the line snaked through china, cologne, men's wear
and the Christmas shop as the ever-approachable Fergie agreed to
sign all their Wedgwood purchases, from Atlantan John Wade's four
salad plates to Decatur (Ga.) resident Stacy Ewing's lasagna
casserole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have driven here from Lawrenceville (Ga.) just to
buy china, but I keep up with her,'' said Linda McKee, waiting
patiently in line. ``She's so down to earth. She's like a regular
mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind those blistering tabloid exploits. (Who could forget
the infamous toe-sucking, topless photos of Fergie and a former
lover?) Forget the binge shopping while racking up debt. (''It
wasn't my shopping that caused that but a house we were trying to
finish,'' the Duchess emphasized in a chat before the event.)
</P>
<P>
   As with entertaining, the key to overcoming adversity, she
believes with all apparent sincerity, is to be yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a weight problem since I was 12,'' said Fergie,
rejecting a cup of not-quite-hot tea. ``You can't hide.''
</P>
<P>
   She also looks for the positive in tragedy, having lost first
her close friend Princess Di and then her mother, Susan Barrantes,
to car crashes within two years. ``Some days I look in the mirror
and say, 'Hi, Mom.' I miss her. But I look at life totally
different now.''
</P>
<P>
   And, turning 40 in 10 days, she's excited over her ``Today''
show role, covering celebrities. ``I find it absolutely curious to
meet people who, once in the public eye, think they have to
change,'' she said. ``Why can't people just be themselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
