<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SINATRA-WINE-NYTR &LR;      09-29 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINATRA-WINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CABERNET FRANK, WINEMAKERS HOPE IT WAS A VERY GOOD YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By RHONDA PARKS MANVILLE   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUELLTON, Calif. _ When the owners of tiny Kahn Winery decided
to make a wine honoring Frank Sinatra, they wanted to infuse the
bottling with the spirit of the singer.
</P>
<P>
   So winemaker Andrew Kahn and his partner Christian Garvin played
songs like ``Old Devil Moon,'' during the crushing process, and ``I
Can't Get Started'' for the pressing. And for the label, they got
the Sinatra estate to let them use a painting done by the singer,
who died last year.
</P>
<P>
   This week the team announced the release of the 1998 Kahn
Cabernet Frank, a wine made from Cabernet Franc grapes grown in
Santa Ynez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both card-carrying members of the International Sinatra
Society,'' said Garvin. He said he grew up in an Italian family in
New York, where the soothing sounds of Sinatra songs were played
everywhere, as common as beeping horns.
</P>
<P>
   Garvin likened the wine-making process to giving birth, noting
that some pregnant women listen to Mozart while their babies are in
the womb, so why not play Sinatra to mellow the wine?
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to play it while the fluid was moving from vessel to
vessel during the process, just like birth. ``Hopefully, the sound
vibrations carried through,'' he said in a telephone interview, in
which a Sinatra concert, recorded live at the Sands casino in Las
Vegas, could be heard in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to honor Sinatra, and we felt if we were going to
make a wine in his name, we wanted to take it all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The partners met while they were working together at Fess
Parker's Winery, where Kahn, 28, was the assistant winemaker, and
Garvin, 26, managed the bottling line. They decided to go into
business together in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Their tiny winery _ Garvin said they proudly call themselves
Santa Barbara County's smallest _ will produce roughly 1,000 cases
this year from varietal grapes grown in private vineyards
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Only 30 cases of Cabernet Frank were produced, so the winery is
limiting the sale to two bottles per customer, at $60 per bottle.
The Sinatra estate has given its blessing to the wine, and a
portion of the proceeds will benefit the Frank Sinatra Foundation,
which supports a variety of causes, Garvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to create a limited quantity of the best possible
wine in honor of what Sinatra had given us for so many years,''
Kahn said. ``Sinatra's songs have filled our cellar since the
beginning, and after his death we felt such a loss that we wanted
to give something back.''
</P>
<P>
   If the wine is a success, it may be offered in future years, the
winemakers say. The 1998 vintage will be ready to drink in a year
or two. It is available at selected wine stores and through the
winery, which has a website at www.kahnwines.com.
</P>
<P>
   (The News-Press in Santa Barbara, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
