<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-TENNESSEE-COX     09-29 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TENNESSEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE MOVES HEADQUARTERS TO TENNESSEE, CHALLENGES BRADLEY TO
DEBATES
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, acknowledging the
surprisingly strong challenge of Bill Bradley, dramatically
reshaped his presidential campaign Wednesday by moving his
headquarters to Tennessee, calling for ``a bunch'' of debates and
scrapping his imperial-like campaign for open, unscripted meetings
with small groups of voters in early primary states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take this campaign for the presidency directly to
the grassroots and directly to the American people,'' Gore said in
a surprise announcement at his Washington campaign headquarters
that, he declared, will be moved ``lock, stock and barrel'' to
downtown Nashville in a week.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, who has surged ahead of Gore in key primary states
after months of trailing by wide margins, gleefully declined an
immediate acceptance of the vice president's request that they
debate in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, for the last ten months, the vice president's
campaign has been ignoring me. And now they want to debate me,''
Bradley told reporters at Saint John's Well-Child Center in Los
Angeles. ``I think this shows we are making some progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged as much himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome the new shape of this campaign,'' he said. ``This is
a hard, tough fight. And I'm going to fight my heart out for every
single vote.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted, however, that the narrowing of the Democratic race
was inevitable because it involves only two candidates. ``You've
got Pepsi and Coke,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, though, Gore had largely ignored Bradley in his
quest for the 2000 Democratic presidential nomination. His
principal target has been Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
frontrunner for the Republican nomination who has consistently led
the vice president by double digits in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, polls indicate Bradley's insurgent campaign
has pulled even or ahead of Gore in such important primary states
as New Hampshire and New York, further troubling establishment
Democrats already anxious over Gore's inability to close the gap
with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he and Bradley should take time before beginning their
debates to ``refine'' their thinking, then have ``a genuine contest
of ideas.'' He said he would like ``a bunch'' of debates, but did
not specify how many.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has as reputation as a skilled debater. Likewise, as a
senator and congressman from Tennessee, he was effective in
intimate settings such as town hall meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But as vice president, with an entourage of staff and security,
he has had few opportunities for such events. ``It's been hard for
him to reach people through the bubble he travels in,'' said Kathy
Sullivan, the chair of the New Hampshire Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, though, Gore said he intends to hold a
series of open meetings in the early primary states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be speaking directly to the voters in small groups,
without intermediaries, responding to their questions, telling them
about my vision for the future, asking for their ideas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the son of a Tennessee senator who has spent much of his
life in Washington, said moving his headquarters to his home state
was ``an opportunity for transformation'' of a campaign
organization that some critics had said was top-heavy with too many
expensive consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the campaign announced Wednesday that Gore had raised
$6.5 million in the third quarter, bringing the year's total to $24
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that the vice president had $9.5
million to $10 million in cash on hand, but that the campaign had
saved just $300,000 to $800,000 of the money it raised over the
last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has not released his third-quarter figures. But earlier
reports indicated Bradley is doing as well in gathering campaign
cash _ and a better job at controlling spending.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the Gore operation out of Washington's K Street corridor,
which is famous for its expensive lobbying and law firms, will save
some money.
</P>
<P>
   But the move will also distance the Gore campaign from the
constant chatter in Washington political circles that the vice
president's campaign is teetering and that it is hamstrung by the
public's disapproval of the scandal-plagued Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore dismissed the suggestion that the move to Tennessee was a
gimmick or that his campaign cannot break free of the country's
``Clinton fatigue,'' a term widely used by pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is Clinton fatigue,'' he said. ``And I think
that ... campaigns, if conducted properly, transform the people who
are in the campaigns. And if that happens, they gain the ability to
transform the country and to renew our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But political experts questioned whether even moves as dramatic
as the ones Gore announced Wednesday would effect the vice
president's image as a Washington candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore can change his headquarters, but he can't change his life
story,'' said John Pitney, a political science professor at
Claremont McKenna College in California.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
