<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-BERENGER-PROFILE     09-29 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BERENGER-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERENGER'S `HERO' MAKES SCREEN HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ You can eat way too many meals on a publicity tour,
and for an actor, that's bad.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Berenger seems to handle it by eating light and drinking
lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over a menu last week, he sounded interested in many of
the selections, then ordered only two appetizer-size items for his
meal. He ignored the wine list to stick with water.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why he's close to the same shape now, at 49, that
he was more than 15 years ago in ``The Big Chill'' and 13 years ago
in ``Platoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's his nonstop schedule. Berenger has six or seven
films set to come out this year or next _ he's not really sure of
the number.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got all these projects that haven't come out yet,
you kind of forget what the last one was,'' he says,
apologetically, as if somehow he should be able to call each to
mind immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The film he is promoting today, ``One Man's Hero,'' is a picture
he shot a while back, about three years ago. Just now getting a
chance in theaters, it's a historical film about Irish soldiers set
during the Mexican-American War. MGM, which is distributing it _
after purchasing it from now-defunct Orion Pictures _ doesn't seem
to have much interest in promoting it, so Berenger is making the
effort on his own, because he likes the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe any of the executives have even bothered to
see it,'' he says, sounding disappointed rather than angry. ``It's
heartbreaking, is what it is. I mean, if I didn't like it, it would
be just as well, but I really like it a lot, which is why I've done
two days of press in Los Angeles, two days with Spanish national
and worldwide television shows. Dallas tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a two-screen premiere in Belfast, with Gerry Adams, head
of the Sinn Fein, as our host. It was his idea. The lord mayor of
Belfast came over. Then we went down to Dublin and did a screening
down there. I did a BBC talk show.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not by chance that Berenger has done a number of historical
films (``Gettysburg,'' ``The Rough Riders''). He's into history, a
fact that becomes more obvious as the conversation jumps from the
Mexican-American War to the Civil War to the Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
   When doing a historical movie, he says he often ends up studying
so much on the events, he knows more than the people making the
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually make a notebook out of it on these projects, for
costumes, set designs, props. I'll put what book it comes from and
the page numbers, because I've had directors (question me), and
I'll go `Look there.'''
</P>
<P>
   What fascinated him about ``One Man's Hero'' was that it was
history he had never heard, until another actor told him about it
on a set 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was intrigued by it. I found a couple of books that
mentioned it.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is about the more than 300 Irish-Catholic immigrants
in the United States Army who deserted to join the Mexican side in
the 1846-1848 war, forming the St. Patrick's Battalion (``Los San
Patricios''). Almost forgotten in the United States, they are
heroes in Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an obelisk with the names of all these guys, and every
St. Patrick's Day, they have a little ceremony there. How many
attend, I don't know. Usually the president of Mexico and the Irish
ambassador. On a few occasions, the president or prime minister of
Ireland is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of making a film about the men had been kicked around
from time to time, perhaps even by John Ford and John Wayne, but
nothing came of it until now. One reason, Berenger speculates, is
that it portrays some negative things about the United States Army
of 150 years ago. But Berenger thinks that should not be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any place you can do a film like this, it should
be the United States,'' he says, pointing out that many of the top
politicians and newspapers of the era were against the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver Stone (who directed Berenger in ``Platoon``), you can
say all his films are controversial. Or try to be. Who cares? If
they're entertaining, they work.''
</P>
<P>
   Studio executives have told Berenger if ``One Man's Hero'' does
well in a few Southwestern cities such as Houston, they will
promote and release it elsewhere. That's what Berenger is counting
on with all his travels to talk it up. He wants it to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Berenger's best-known performance is as the merciless veteran
sergeant in Vietnam in ``Platoon,'' for which he got a
best-supporting-actor Oscar nomination. But the film he's in that
probably has been watched and enjoyed most is the boomer classic
``The Big Chill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it a generation movie, like `The Graduate,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The film enhanced the careers of most of its cast _ Glenn Close,
Kevin Kline, Jobeth Williams, Jeff Goldblum, WIlliam Hurt, Mary Kay
Place, Meg Tilly and Berenger _ though Berenger doesn't think it
was such a boost for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't recognize me in `The Big Chill.' They didn't
know I was in it. It may be because of the mustache. Or because
it's a comedy, and I hadn't done that many comedies.''
</P>
<P>
   Berenger played the TV show detective who has a fling with
Williams and at one point takes a flying leap into a sports car,
with disastrous results.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it was a movie he enjoyed doing and one that had a lot
of effect on his future. The film was made by writer/director
Lawrence Kasdan (``Mumford,'' ``Body Heat''), and actors usually
say they have a great time on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' Berenger agrees. ``I think it was the easiest
film I ever did. You had to be there every day, but you weren't on
all the time. We did no overtime; the weather was gorgeous. A lot
of card games. Poker, charades.''
</P>
<P>
   He liked filming around Beaufort, S.C., so much that he moved
there from New York after completing the film. He still lives there
with his third wife, Patricia
</P>
<P>
   Millions of fans of ``The Big Chill,'' after seeing it for the
10th time on video and recalling Goldblum's last line, ``We're not
leaving; we're never leaving,'' have no doubt pondered what happens
to the people after the movie ends. Do they stay close?
</P>
<P>
   In Berenger's case, no. He's worked on films or plays or
projects with some of the cast members since, but that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in contact with Bill Hurt for a while,'' he says. ``I
just sort of lost touch. Living where I do it's hard to keep up
with people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEW-MUSICALS-ART-2TAK     09-29 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-MUSICALS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: SAMPLING TOMORROW'S MUSICALS TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They had only 30 minutes, so they got right down to
business. ``We're two guys describing a show about two guys
describing a show,'' explained the heavier-set of the two, as their
pianist fidgeted on his bench and adjusted the pages of his score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good evening everyone, I'm Jed Feuer,'' he continued,
addressing the packed audience at the Douglas Fairbanks Theater on
West 42nd Street, ``and this is my partner, Boyd Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shalom,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   How expertly synchronized this seemed. Their fledgling musical,
``The Big Bang,'' was set in the apartment of a New York
proctologist, one Dr. Lipbaum, in whose living room two writers
gather potential investors for a read-through of their new musical.
It just so happened that the Fairbanks was filled on this
particular night with producers and operators of small theaters and
musical troupes around the nation, from the Paper Mill Playhouse in
Millburn, N.J., to the Municipal Theater Association of St. Louis.
In other words, here was a group of show backers watching two men
pitch a show in which two men pitch a show to a group of show
backers.
</P>
<P>
   That ``The Big Bang'' was first in the running order seemed an
act of providence, if not divine at least divinely choreographed.
On Sunday and Monday, a total of 10 productions were rolled out at
the International Festival of New Musicals, a kind of
convention-size backers' audition. It is an annual opportunity for
presenters, purveyors and supporters of musical theater _ show-tune
workers of the world, unite! _ to sample what the organizers pick
as the top eight to 10 works-in-progress among the hundreds
submitted for the event each year. Some theaters contribute
financially to the development of one of the shows, which may in
fact be booked into their theaters one day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the musical by Graham and Feuer (the son, by the way,
of Cy Feuer, the longtime Broadway director and producer), is a
paean to a bygone method of making musicals. Today, only a handful
of producers still raise money the old way; more commonly, big
shows are being ushered to the stage by entertainment conglomerates
and better-endowed nonprofit theaters. The route represented by the
festival is yet another way, perhaps the most circuitous, involving
a growing network of loose links and partnerships among smaller
out-of-town theaters that nurture a show by giving it a workshop or
a series of preliminary productions.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the shows the festival has unveiled in its 11 years have
made it to New York, let alone to Broadway, though a few writers
and productions have broken through: the composer Jason Robert
Brown, whose musical ``Parade,'' about the lynching of Leo Frank,
ran at Lincoln Center Theater last season, had a revue in the
festival two years ago, and one of last year's selections, ``The
Bubbly Black Girl Sheds Her Chameleon Skin,'' by Kirsten Childs, is
being produced this season by Playwrights Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great questions,'' said Helen Sneed, executive
director of the National Alliance for Musical Theater, the
consortium of 115 musical theaters and troupes that produces the
festival, ``is whether musicals that don't have the New York stamp
on them can have a life of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally intriguing, though, is what exactly lyricists and
composers choose to write about nowadays. If, as the generally
dismal Broadway offerings of the past few seasons indicate, the
musical is indeed in a downward cycle, fragmenting into mushy
tourist fare and unsingable material better suited to the
conservatory, the broader question is, is there any form in which
the American musical can re-establish its hold on the popular
imagination?
</P>
<P>
   The festival cannot provide an answer, but it is a kind of
snapshot of mainstream musical ambitions. Attending is great fun _
it's like being handed a tasting menu of the musical of tomorrow _
although as an event it doesn't exactly rival Fashion Week. It
takes over just two small off-Broadway houses, the Fairbanks and
the John Houseman, where the goal is not to set a trend but to
latch onto one. The shows, for the most part, are meant to appeal
to broadly American, rather than to boutique Manhattan, tastes, to
tickle patrons of the Sacramento Light Opera more than those of the
New York Theater Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   The festival turns out to be both exceedingly well produced _
the performers in various productions included such stalwarts of
the New York stage as Stephanie Mills, Alice Ripley, Stephen
DeRosa, Nick Wyman, Jason Danieley, Jeremy Kushnier, Ken Prymus and
Carol Woods _ and surprisingly entertaining. Boiled-down versions
of the full-length musicals, culled this year from about 140
submissions, were performed in staged readings, some lasting an
hour, others half that. (Some presentations benefited greatly from
brevity.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In nervous little herds, the teams scurried into the theater;
though musicals traditionally begin with an overture, all the
musicals here start with a spiel. Actors in street clothes sing
from scripts in binders. The accompaniment is sometimes a single
piano. (One of the joys of the festival was hearing
Broadway-caliber voices unamplified _ what a novelty!) The
composers offer their best five or 10 numbers; the plot and
thematic thrust are entrusted to a narrator.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation of the festival is the sheer number of polished
writers and composers who remain hot in pursuit of a hit. But the
glimpse of the future? Well, the musical of tomorrow, it turns out,
looks a lot like the musical of today.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the writers are inspired by a popular movie (as in this
year's festival entry ``Summer of '42'') or an epic French tale of
epees and amour (``The Three Musketeers''), whether it is yet
another set of anecdotes from the annals of immigration (``Heading
East'') or the latest production infused with sass and soul (``The
Princess and the Black-Eyed Pea''), the shows often fit into
familiar categories. Although once a form that voraciously fed on
other traditions, it now feeds mostly on itself.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are not invited to review the presentations, but some
shows were clear darlings of the audience. I'll come clean: my
favorite was ``Honk!,'' a sophisticated children's musical based on
``The Ugly Duckling'' by a British songwriting team, composer
George Stiles and lyricist Anthony Drewe. What with the success of
``The Lion King'' and the early, favorable buzz surrounding the
forthcoming ``Seussical,'' a show by Lynn Ahrens and Stephen
Flaherty based on the works of Dr. Seuss, maybe the musical of
tomorrow belongs to the youngest set.
</P>
<P>
   Unrelated to its submission here, ``Honk!'' was chosen for
staging later this fall by the Royal National Theater in London,
and will be produced as well this winter at the Helen Hayes
Performing Arts Center in Nyack. (``Honk!'' also supplied the
festival with a bona fide show stopper, a number for a famished,
fowl-coveting cat titled ``Play With Your Food.'')
</P>
<P>
   The scale of productions ranged from the intimate cabaret style
of ``The Big Bang'' to the full-throated choruses of ``In That
Valley,'' a large ensemble show that illustrated one of the
recurring thrusts of earnest-seeming American musicals at the end
of the century, an effort to personalize and redefine the national
journey. ``In That Valley,'' by Richard Oberacker and Steven
Minning, is the story of an 18th-century Irish immigrant taken
prisoner with her child by Indians in the mountains of western
Virginia. In a similar vein, Robert Lee and Leon Ko offered
``Heading East,'' the saga of a 19th-century Chinese immigrant, and
Thomas W. Jones II weighed in with ``Birth of the Boom,'' a doo-wop
musical that surveys the emotional lives of black American men.
Some of the composers and writers have already seen their shows on
stages, in modest productions around the country; others wait, like
the keyed-up pleaders in ``The Big Bang,'' for the big break. It
would be satisfying to conclude on the basis of the truncated
auditions this week that there are hopeful signs everywhere in the
musical theater. But more evidence is required. Like a jilted
lover, I've been hurt too many times to make that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
