<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Streams may spill over their banks in New England on Thursday as
a soggy cold front plods slowly to the coast. A jet stream
disturbance will lift tropical air over the rugged terrain across
the interior, leading to several inches of rain, especially near
the east slopes of the northern Appalachians. Much cooler and drier
air will reach the Hudson Valley by early afternoon and southern
New England by sundown on gusty breezes from the northwest.
Residual clouds and light showers will linger south of Lake
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing skies with cooler, drier winds will spread across the
Middle Atlantic region and the Southeast early in the day. The cold
front will trigger scattered showers and thunderstorms in central
and southern Florida. The tail of the front should produce some
clouds in southern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Very pleasant weather is expected across the South, central
Plains and lower Ohio Valley. High pressure over Arkansas will
promote sunshine and near seasonable temperatures. A cold front
advancing quickly southeast toward the Great Lakes will bring a few
showers to the border region and shifting, gusty winds from the
Dakotas to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   A wedge of very cool air will be drawn into the upper Plains and
Montana. Mixed showers are expected in the Bitterroots as chilly
air circulates uphill. Most of the West will be sunny and rather
warm though the heat in coastal California will slacken. Light
winds along the Pacific coast will allow patches of low clouds to
seep into a few coastal valleys. Increasing offshore winds in
Washington should promote sunny skies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Philadelphia Follies &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than a foot of rain has fallen on Philadelphia in
September, making it the wettest month this century. With records
dating back to the late 1700s, this is quite noteworthy. The
wettest month occurred in August 1867, when 15.8 inches fell.
Oddly, the city is still under a drought emergency so residents can
not water lawns or wash cars. The water restrictions are a residual
effect of the severe drought that had afflicted the region into
August. However, abundant rains in the past six weeks have raised
the year-to-date tally to 7 inches above normal ending the
drought. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
