<SLUG> BC-CIR-DUKE-STUDENTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DEVICES GETTING ROAD TEST BY BUSINESS STUDENTS AT DUKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Colo.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ James H. Sherrill sat in an oversized chair in a
dimly lighted lounge, cradling a rectangular electronic device that
was unlike anything he had seen. It was smaller than a laptop and
bigger than a palmtop. It didn't have cables or a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   But in his first few minutes with the device, Sherrill, a
first-year student at Duke University's Fuqua School of Business,
was already becoming adept at using its stylus to open files and
applications. ``It has an infrared link here for a wireless
connection,'' he said, pointing to the tiny port on its side during
a quick demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The device _ called a Stylistic LT, by Fujitsu _ will become
part of Sherrill's life over the next few months. It is one of many
new gadgets that he and other students will be testing in an
unusual project started by the business school this semester.
</P>
<P>
   The project is something like an oversized focus group in which
students are both evaluators of new technology and research
subjects in a huge marketing experiment. The students are invited
to test what Nevin Fouts, associate dean for information
technology, calls ``next-generation devices'' that he thinks just
might replace laptops for use in classrooms and libraries, and
study lounges. ``The market hasn't even emerged enough to give them
a certain name,'' Fouts said.
</P>
<P>
   Fujitsu and eight other companies are participating in the
project, sending their latest gadgets to the business school for
testing in a variety of environments. More than 100 devices have
arrived on campus and are awaiting distribution. Fouts expects to
receive another 100 in the next few months. All told, the equipment
is worth more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   All the devices are designed to be portable, cordless, and
lightweight _ attributes that Fouts considers ideal for students on
the move from their homes to the library to the classroom. Many of
the devices look like the electronic equivalent of the stone
tablet, with liquid-crystal displays encased in heavy-duty plastic
frames. They typically include some of the same features that
people find on desktop computers, like the ability to browse the
Web or retrieve e-mail. Many also include styluses for note-taking;
some include speakers, microphones, and digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   People who follow the handheld-computer business may have
already seen a few of the devices, which have been on display
recently at computer trade shows and are on the market in limited
distribution. Some, like digital clipboards for doctors, are being
used outside the educational setting, but others exist only as
prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke project poses risks for the university, which is hoping
that the experiments will not be a distraction. It is also risky
for the companies, which in some cases are opening their research
and development secrets to an unpredictable student audience. But
the companies are willing to take the risks in exchange for an
intimate relationship with business school students who, once they
graduate to the corporate world, may have the money to become
frequent customers and the influence to sway market trends.
</P>
<P>
   And many administrators, faculty members, and students at the
business school are excited to have access to devices that are just
coming off the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the cutting edge,'' said Christopher T. Cocks, a
second-year student. ``You could even say we're helping to define
what the cutting edge will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cocks and Sherrill, the student with the Fujitsu tablet, are two
of 12 members of the Technology Advisory Council, a group of
students recruited by Fouts to help guide technology-related
decisions at the business school. This semester they have focused
almost solely on the pilot testing project.
</P>
<P>
   Each member of the council will have access to every gadget that
is sent to Fuqua for evaluation. In many cases, they will be
expected to carry the devices with them for several weeks, using
them for class notes, e-mail and Web-based research, and to trade
documents. They will be required to write journal entries about how
easy or unbearable the devices are to use. They will also test them
in controlled environments like a sound-proof laboratory typically
used by professors who are conducting market-research experiments.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, however, each member of the council will
be asked to sign nondisclosure agreements, legal documents in which
they pledge not to give away the companies' trade secrets or
attempt to create their own companies based on knowledge of the new
gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of other students, Fouts expects, will also want to get
involved in the project and will also be asked to sign agreements.
These are students who are not part of the council but who sign up
to test at least one of the gadgets in the next few semesters.
</P>
<P>
   Devices that are still being created in the companies'
research-and-development departments will not be allowed to be
toted freely around the business school. Keeping things under wraps
is essential to the project's success, those involved say.
</P>
<P>
   Aqcess Technologies, for example, will be lending Duke more than
80 copies of Qbe, its first device to go on the market. It also
plans to test the latest Qbe iterations using Duke students, if
they sign nondisclosure agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this industry, it can get hectic and cutthroat,'' said Kain
K. Johnson, vice president for sales and marketing at Aqcess
Technologies. ``Before we give anything to anyone out there, we're
going to make sure we're covered.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fuqua project will be formally announced this week, but the
ideas behind it have been percolating for years. It started, Fouts
said, when he and faculty members began to bemoan the drawbacks of
students' using laptops in the classroom. While some business
schools require students to have notebook computers for use in
classroom and group study sessions, Duke discourages them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the laptop screen up, you have a barrier between faculty
and students,'' said Joel Huber, associate dean of the MBA program.
The constant sound of clicking is annoying too, he said. Not to
mention, he added, that students have been known to surreptitiously
surf the Web or send e-mail when they are supposed to be taking
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Huber, Fouts, and several professors talked wishfully about a
different kind of digital device that could connect wirelessly to a
network yet didn't require a keyboard. They wanted something that
might allow students to beam documents or spreadsheets between
machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We conceived of a class of device that didn't exist yet,''
Fouts said.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past year, Fouts began talking to technology
companies about the idea and discovered that some of them were, in
fact, being realized. Many were simply prototypes in corporate
research labs. Some were just about to hit the market, such as the
Stylistic LT, which now sells for $3,265. Others that will be
released this fall include the QBE and the Qubit, by Qubit
Technology in Denver, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring and summer, Fouts negotiated agreements with the
nine companies, which also include Arthur Andersen, Dauphin
Technology, IBM, IPDN Corp., Laser Image Corporate Publishing, and
Nortel Networks.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, too, signed nondisclosure agreements with Duke,
promising not to reveal too much about Duke's own research on the
project. For although the companies are getting piles of journal
entries and documentation about students' responses to the devices,
Duke's researchers are using the students as research subjects as
well.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The students who choose to become involved in the pilot project
_ which Steve Hoeffler, the doctoral student who is leading it,
expects to be about 90 percent of Fuqua's students _ will be
matched with certain gadgets depending on their answers to survey
questions about their habits and current use of technology. The way
different samples of students react to the devices will be analyzed
as part of Hoeffler's own research project on how people respond to
new technology.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of an entire business school as a technology test bed
is intriguing to some experts in market research. ``I think it's an
incredibly interesting approach,'' said Jens Schlueter, vice
president for marketing and research for Informative, a company
that helps Web-based companies conduct online market research. The
big difference between Fuqua's experiments and typical focus group
projects, he said, is that the business-school students will be
exploring the limitations of the devices over weeks and months,
rather than hours or days.
</P>
<P>
   But Schlueter questions whether the companies will be getting an
accurate picture of how their devices are received, given that the
students who choose to be involved may be more enthusiastic about
technology than those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffler said he was well aware of such limitations. ``We are
already starting with a pretty biased sample,'' he said, since
business school students are typically knowledgeable about
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he argued, several companies like the idea that they
can put their devices in front of people who are aware of the
limitations of current technology. ``These students probably
already have a notebook computer right now,'' said Johnson of
Aqcess Technologies. ``They may even have a portable digital
assistant. It's a perfect audience for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But from an educational perspective the project does leave some
academics questioning the wisdom of Duke's embracing the role of
beta tester. The potential for students to be overly focused on the
devices worries Rob Kling, a professor of information science at
Indiana University and editor of the technology journal Information
Society.
</P>
<P>
   A dean might be concerned about complaints from professors about
laptops, Kling said, but ``doubtless he'll still be hearing
complaints from faculty who have students in classes who are
distracted by their new gadgets, trying to get them to work.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fuqua's professors and administrators are already
planning to have entire classes of students try out the devices,
possibly requiring everyone in a course to sign a nondisclosure
agreement before attending.
</P>
<P>
   Huber, for example, teaches a course called The Marketing of
High Technology. The devices, he said, would be perfect for his
course and could help him interact with students in the classroom.
They might enable him to transfer presentations or spreadsheets
from a gadget's display panel to a large screen in front of the
class. And with everyone operating under the same agreements to
keep quiet outside the classroom, he said, students in class could
freely talk about the technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Huber says he will watch carefully for any signs that the
devices are getting in the way of learning. ``We'll also have paper
there,'' he added, ``if we need to regroup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
