<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Meyer, an aerospace engineer at NASA's Marshall Space
Flight Center, designed the site, which is part of a package of
online tracking devices for satellites and shuttles. So far, he has
plotted 520 satellites. ``But there's more up there,'' he said,
``than you can possibly imagine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   Software for Palm VII Widens E-Mail Access
</P>
<P>
   Palm VII, the latest generation of the popular Palm electronic
organizers, is getting help from a start-up company giving away
software that lets Palm VII users retrieve e-mail from a variety of
providers.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII, soon to be released nationally by 3Com, wirelessly
sends and receives e-mail messages through a special Palm VII
iMessenger service. ThinAirApps.com aims to change all of that with
its Thin Air Mail 1.2, an application that gives Palm VII users
access to other personal e-mail accounts, including Hot Mail and
others provided by Mindspring, Netcom and AT&AMP;T Worldnet. (America
Online is not included.)
</P>
<P>
   While the software (which can be downloaded from
thinairapps.com) is free, e-mail is still subject to Palm.net
network charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accessing your e-mail from any source at any time and place is
the killer app for the Palm VII organizer,'' said Jon Oakes,
co-founder of ThinAirApps.com, now two months old.
</P>
<P>
   _Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   Headsets Get a Makeover To Match Their New Cachet
</P>
<P>
   Headsets are cool. At least that's what Plantronics is hoping.
The Silicon Valley company, which has been making telephone
headsets since 1962, recently introduced a new line of headsets for
cell and cordless phones with a decidedly younger, trendier
customer in mind.
</P>
<P>
   No longer are headsets something to associate with telephone
operators. They're the latest accessory for actors. Think ``Jerry
Maguire'' or ``The Matrix'' or ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The smallest and slickest of Plantronics' new M series headsets,
which come in blue, silver and black, pops over one ear and a small
microphone boom extends toward the mouth. That is in contrast to
the ``soap on a rope'' style of microphones sold by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never found the sound quality to be good enough on those,''
said Debbie Abbott, director of marketing at Plantronics. The
retail price of the new headsets ranges from $29.95 to $64.95.
</P>
<P>
   Plantronics is also playing up the safety angle for headsets in
the car, although the safety benefit of using a headset while
driving is debatable.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts argue that it is not the physical distraction but
the mental one that makes it so dangerous to drive while using a
cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   _Katie Hafner
</P>
<P>
   Europeans Trail Americans In Time on Line, Survey Says
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the days of de Tocqueville, Europeans and Americans
have been comparing themselves. A survey being released Thursday by
PricewaterhouseCoopers adds an Internet angle: More Americans have
home access to the Internet than their European counterparts, the
survey says, and they spend more time logged on.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 percent of Americans, 24 percent of the British, 18
percent of Germans and 10 percent of the French have access to the
Internet at home, according to the survey, which polled 800 people
in each of the four countries. On average, Americans are spending
5.3 hours on line per week, while Europeans devote half as much
time to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Americans said they were logging on to check e-mail, conduct
research, read the news and shop. The survey also showed that the
percentage of Americans with Internet access who did not purchase
anything online dropped from 30 percent last year to 19 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans also mentioned research, news gathering and e-mail as
reasons for logging onto the Internet, but fewer than a third of
those with Internet access said they shopped on line.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, however, may be well ahead of everyone else when it
comes to using an electronic checkbook: 55 percent of Germans said
that online banking and investing were reasons they logged on to
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Only 24 percent of Americans, 16 percent of the British and 15
percent of the French offered those reasons.
</P>
<P>
   _Lisa Guernsey
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
