<HEADLINE>
ONE FOR THE `MUMMY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE MUMMY'
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Universal, CC, VHS $22.98, DVD $29.98
</P>
<P>
   Some films are remakes posing as sequels. Take ``I Still Know
What You Did Last Summer'' _ please.
</P>
<P>
   But this new ``Mummy'' is another critter. Technically, it's a
remake of the creaky 1932 original ``Mummy'' with Boris Karloff,
but it plays more like a prequel to another film: ``Raiders of the
Lost Ark.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fraser is the Indiana Jones surrogate, an American
adventurer who seeks treasure in 1920s Egypt and uncovers an
ancient, supernatural menace.
</P>
<P>
   He's joined by a spunky librarian (Rachel Weisz of ``Stealing
Beauty'') and her sardonic brother (John Hannah of ``Sliding
Doors''). Arnold Vosloo (``Darkman II'') plays the mummy menace,
with help from effects that turn him into a skeleton draped with
strips of flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``The Mummy'' can be creepy. But most of its scares are
more fun than frightening, and the accent's on adventure laced with
laughs and romance.
</P>
<P>
   Director-writer Stephen Sommers deftly treads a thin line
between homage and parody. He affectionately summons ghosts of '40s
adventure movies while one-upping them with preposterous events
empowered by show-off effects.
</P>
<P>
   But also credit Fraser. After playing a sympathetic admirer of
the ``Frankenstein'' films' creator (James Whale) in ``Gods and
Monsters,'' Fraser stretches with ease into a hammy hero armed with
guts, guns and gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Add his sweetly self-effacing humor in ``Blast From the Past''
and he's shown a range far beyond his cartoonish parts in ``Dudley
Do-Right,'' ``Encino Man'' or ``George of the Jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   It's time for another young actor to play the buffoon.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WALLACE, GROMIT AND DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As animation veers more from the drawing board to computer
terminals, the work known as stop-motion animation tends to be
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Harryhausen has long since retired, and the last significant
stop-motion movie was 1993's ``The Nightmare Before Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   But Britain's Nick Park keeps the flame burning, and his superb
works are reaching DVD.
</P>
<P>
   This week brings ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit _ The First Adventures'' to
the format (BBC Video, $34.98). The disc has all three of Park's
cartoons starring the cheese-loving English inventor and his
whip-smart dog, Gromit.
</P>
<P>
   These shorts have been available for three years on individual
tapes for $9.98 or in a boxed set for $24.98. But the DVD also
offers extras, including screen tests, clips of Park's early work,
BBC Christmas promos with Wallace &AMP; Gromit, and a look at the
creation of ``The Wrong Trousers.''
</P>
<P>
   In that Oscar-winning short, the duo is immersed in an elaborate
plot involving a villainous penguin and mechanical pants.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Grand Day Out,'' they explore the moon in search of more
cheese. ``In A Close Shave,'' Gromit is framed for stealing sheep,
while Wallace falls in love.
</P>
<P>
   Park's richly entertaining work has far more expressiveness than
more sophisticated efforts from Disney, Pixar and other studios.
Call these old-fashioned cartoons quaint, if you will _ or call
them inspired.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to see a sample, look for current gasoline ads
with toothy, talking cars from Park's Aardman Animations. Then
watch for his next animated film, ``Chicken Run'' (without Wallace
&AMP; Gromit), due next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`FLYING' WACKY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, time for something completely different: British humor with
a wildly wacky bent.
</P>
<P>
   The first 13 episodes of ``Monty Python's Flying Circus'' arrive
this week from A&AMP;E Home Video.
</P>
<P>
   They're split onto two boxed sets of three videos costing $29.95
(or $12.95 for individual tapes), or two two-disc DVD sets costing
$44.95 each (or $24.95 for single discs).
</P>
<P>
   DVD extras include a ``sketch index'' for instant access to such
lunacy as ``tasty bits of dead people'' and ``musical mice.''
</P>
<P>
   DVDs also have live performances by the Python troupe, a trivia
quiz, Web links, bios, galleries of photos and illustrations and a
karaoke feature.
</P>
<P>
   Also new is the DVD debut of ``Monty Python and the Holy Grail''
(Columbia TriStar, $24.95). Extras are minimal, but that film is as
good as the Brit twits get.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A `SLEEPLESS' DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another new DVD is ``Sleepless in Seattle Special Edition''
(Columbia TriStar, $27.95), and it's packed with extras: trailers,
audio commentary, a ``Love in the Movies'' featurette and a music
video of ``When I Fall in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
