<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ALLIANCE-0930-     09-29 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ALLIANCE-0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALLIANCE COLLAPSE CALLED ``BLUNDER OF CENTURY'' FOR MEXICAN
OPPOSITION
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It was going to be called the ``Great Alliance for
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's being mourned by supporters as one of the greatest
flops for democracy in Mexico this century.
</P>
<P>
   This week, dreams went up in smoke _ for now _ of forging a
sweeping opposition coalition that could have finally ended 70
years of one-party control of Mexico's presidency. The bone of
contention was not ideological differences, but disagreements over
how various political parties would unite and select one candidate
to run for president in Mexico's July 2, 2000, election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the blunder of the century for Mexico's opposition,''
said Adolfo Aguilar Zinser, a senator who is not affiliated with a
party but has been active in Mexico's left opposition in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The participants ``were too narrow-minded, ambitious and
selfish,'' Aguilar Zinser said.
</P>
<P>
   The implosion of the alliance is a gift to Mexico's ruling
Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI, which has controlled the
country's presidency for seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   Under attack for corruption and for failing to solve Mexico's
severe poverty and inequality, the PRI is thought to be more
vulnerable than ever to electoral defeat. As a result, this year,
the party is trying to renovate its image by holding its first-ever
primary election to allow voters to select the party's nominee for
the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of an alliance also strengthens the PRI's chances
of victory once again next year. A slim chance exists that the
largest opposition parties might talk again about shaping a
coalition, but those close to the failed negotiations believe that
bad blood will prevent that from happening before a December
deadline to register an alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showed that as much as 60 percent of Mexicans supported
the idea of an alliance to confront the PRI in next year's
presidential election. The polls also showed that if the election
were held today, an alliance would defeat the formidable PRI.
</P>
<P>
   But late Tuesday night, four months of negotiations among eight
opposition parties collapsed _ primarily because Mexico's
conservative National Action Party, or PAN, would not accept a
proposal to hold a nationwide primary to select an alliance
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just changed the history of Mexico,'' said a disappointed
Sergio Aguayo, an analyst and democratic activist who served on a
``citizens council'' that came up with the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, former Guanajuato state governote Fox _ who
has already been selected by the PAN as its nominee _ appeared
well-positioned to win such an election, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   His main rival for an alliance nomination would have been
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who stepped down Tuesday from his job as mayor
of Mexico City to devote himself to his own presidential campaign
full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas is the likely nominee of Mexico's leftist Democratic
Revolution Party, or PRD, which is critical of many of Mexico's
free-market economic reforms alleged as well as PRI corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Once highly popular, Cardenas now trails in many polls that show
him in third or fourth place behind Fox and two candidates vying
for the PRI's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The same day that Cardenas resigned and alliance talks
collapsed, Mexico City's Reforma newspaper published a poll showing
that 60 percent of potential voters preferred Fox as an alliance
candidate. Only 19 percent preferred Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those outside the parties, like me, it was obvious Fox
would win a primary,'' said Aguayo. But the PAN, he said, didn't
trust that its sympathizers or Fox supporters would turn out at the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PAN has a pathological insecurity,'' he said. ``There
seems to me to be an almost suicidal drive in all this. And it
seems that Fox is going to be the one who suffers and pays the
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who seemed to take a backseat in the talks compared to
other PAN leaders, tried Wednesday to put a positive spin on the
alliance fracture.
</P>
<P>
   He told a television station that the opposition parties had
managed to come up with a platform, an achievement that might allow
them to pursue more negotiations in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly, there wasn't only oil and water,'' he said.
``What we found was yeast and flour that made a good bread.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguayo said he knew forging an alliance was ``an uphill
battle,'' given the differences between the PAN and the PRD, which
are Mexico's two largest opposition parties. The conservative PAN,
which promoted a free-market philosophy long before the PRI, has
little in common with the PRD except its goal to drive the PRI from
power.
</P>
<P>
   But Aguayo said representatives of the two parties didn't
squabble in front of the citizens council about ideology. ``That
never entered into the discussions,'' he said. ``The competition
was for power, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the PAN and the PRD _ along with some
smaller parties _ had managed to unite to successfully run alliance
candidates for governor in Nayarit, Tlaxcala and Baja California
Sur states.
</P>
<P>
   An alliance candidate also ran for governor in Coauhuila state
this past week, but lost to the PRI. Some analysts thought the
defeat helped foreshadow the collapse of the presidential alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Both the PAN and the PRD and their respective candidates are now
sharing blame being heaped on them for foiling the biggest
potential alliance of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardenas and Fox both think they are the Messiah,'' Aguayo
said, and neither wanted to let the other have the nomination of a
united front.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas is trailing, Aguayo said, ``but now he can campaign by
saying the PAN is an accomplice of the regime because they rejected
the proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar Zinser said the negotiations were ``never a game of
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Many within the two large opposition parties didn't want to
submit to an alliance, he said, but went to the table because the
Mexican public appeared to support a presidential coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The PAN said the devil was in the details of the proposal. From
the beginning, said Diego Fernandez de Cevallos, a PAN leader, the
PAN had said it was wary of holding an election to choose a
candidate because ti might be tainted by fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD held recent self-supervised elections to elect its own
party officers and the balloting was tainted by allegations of
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But Aguayo said the citizens council was trying to consider the
PAN's concerns by also calling for four independently-supervised
polls of voters to match those results against balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Any Mexican with a voting credential would have been allowed to
vote, but there would have been a pre-registration at some 12,000
stations set up around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought common sense would have forced (the parties) to
accept this was the best thing for Mexico and for them,'' Aguayo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
