<HEADLINE>
A DREAM LIVES IN A GRAND DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELVETIA, Ore. _ At midday, Matt Roloff had already pounded
nails into his four-level treehouse, mowed the soccer field, fed
the llamas. Now, he was eyeing the telephone pole on the farm next
door. Two men in hard hats were hooking a crane to the old pole,
preparing to pull it from the ground, but Roloff had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey!'' he shouted across the way. ``Wait a minute! Let me take
that telephone pole off your hands!'' Considering that earlier in
the day, Roloff could not even put on his socks without the help of
his 3-year-old son, this pole-yanking seemed a bit ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   The workers gave him the once-over. It's a dwarf! He's on
crutches! And he's coming our way! Roloff has heard all the jokes
about trolls under the bridge and crazy Munchkins, so The Look is
nothing. He not only expects it, he plays off it.
</P>
<P>
   The workers explained that somebody already had dibs on the
30-foot pole. ``Keep me in mind,'' Roloff said, hobbling back to a
golf-cart-size vehicle. And you wonder: How could they not?
</P>
<P>
   The Roloff farm is a 34-acre fantasy in the lustrous hill
country just west of Portland. Pinot noir grapes, fat blueberries
and computer labs are among the things that grow in the fertile
ground of Washington County. But Roloff has planted something else:
a world, built to his size, to match his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   There is a full-scale pirate's ship anchored next to a pond, a
Western town with jail, bank, sheriff's office, general store,
hotel and blacksmith's shop, eight bridges, a 70-foot mine shaft, a
soccer field, llama pens, a peach orchard, a real fire truck, four
barns, a 24-foot tower designed to shake and thrill and, underlying
it all, more than 300 feet of tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a commercial venture; just an idea that got seriously
out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is what you make of it,'' he said, quoting fellow
dwarf Linda Hunt, the actress, from the movie ``Silverado.'' ``If
it doesn't fit, you make alterations.''
</P>
<P>
   Try getting a Coke from a vending machine with money slots just
out of reach. Or making a call from a pay phone. He talks about all
this in a tone devoid of self-pity. It is by way of explaining how
hostile much of the world is to a 38-year-old man who stands 4 feet
2 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   So, over the last decade, Roloff has been building a little
person's paradise, a place where nobody is ever turned away because
they do not meet minimum height standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have one gripe on this planet it is those signs at
Disneyland that say you must be taller than a certain level to go
on this ride,'' he said. ``Maturity has nothing to do with size.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Roloff got his revenge, of sorts, when a visitor
from Disney dropped by the Roloff fantasy farm. ``He was
impressed,'' Roloff recalled. The two men ended up sharing tips on
how to make great-looking fake rock walls _ ``a real sandy mix of
cement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Roloff is a diastrophic dwarf, which means his joints are
deformed and deteriorating. One hip has two ball joints, and the
other has no socket, for example. And because his condition is
degenerative, the clock is running. ``Every day, I become a little
more of a cripple,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, also 4 feet 2, is a more common achondroplastic dwarf,
and has minimal physical problems. They have four children _ twin
boys, age 9; a girl, 6, and the 3 year old _ all but one of whom
are average-size. It for them, Roloff says earnestly, that he has
spent the last decade creating the fun farm. But it is also for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Roloff was a prisoner of childhood, in the words he uses in
his 1999 autobiographical book, ``Against Tall Odds: Being a David
in a Goliath World'' (Multnomah Publishers). He spent nearly five
years of his life either in a hospital bed or a body cast, his bent
frame subjected to more than 15 operations for such things as
straightening his knees and lengthening his legs.
</P>
<P>
   All he wanted were a few days playing with other children, pain
free. ``I used to look out my window and just dream about being Tom
Sawyer, floating away on a raft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dream was put on hold while Roloff, barely out of high
school, built a prosperous life as a computer programmer and
software expert in the San Francisco Bay area. Along the way, he
played a Munchkin in a film about the making of ``The Wizard of
Oz,'' and an Ewok in the third installment of the ``Star Wars''
series. He also became active in Little People of America, a
national organization for dwarfs.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, on a job-hunting excursion in Oregon, the Roloffs
spotted a run-down farmhouse and rat-infested barn at the end of a
road just outside the Portland suburb of Hillsboro. ``It was a
dump,'' Roloff recalled. They had just purchased a new home in
California. But she was pregnant, with twins, and they did not want
their children to grow up in the cramped Silicon Valley. The dream,
long dormant, came alive.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at the contour of the land, hills and dales, an old
peach orchard off to one side, overgrown fields of alfalfa and
clover, and his mind raced. He started to see the 34 acres as the
world that had been denied him. He bought the farm for $185,000.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the grand design was something the Roloffs kept to
themselves. But as Roloff scoured the Oregon countryside looking
for timbers from collapsing barns, or telephone poles, or aged
fence posts, the neighbors became ever more curious. ``I think at
first they just rolled their eyes,'' Roloff said. ``You know, look
what these crazy little people from California are doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of what he has done, perhaps, is classic guy stuff _ the
chromosomal impulse to build, tinker and remodel. And anyone who
has ever wondered why some men prefer power tools to sex can see
the guy-dream writ large on the Roloff farm. Nothing about it looks
cheap or mass-manufactured, or the least bit tacky. It is all plumb
and solidly built. Most of the project is made of reclaimed timbers
and siding _ the kind of things Home Depot does not sell.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody is always dumping off recycled wood or a load of dirt.
One person's hole in the ground becomes Roloff's magic mountain.
After Roloff put out the word that he would like to have hills on
his property for future water slides and falls, contractors have
been more than happy to build his creations from their excavation
sites.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Roloff vision started in the barn. It was reconstructed,
from floorboards to roof, with old wood that Roloff picked up from
other barns or scrap sites. Now, it is warm and inviting, with
straw bales for sitting, ancient clear fir beams and stairs that
lead up to a loft of hidden nooks and crannies, book-lined and
toy-filled. In order to complete his plan for the barn, Roloff had
to jack it above its foundation. And while the barn was on stilts,
Roloff had another idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, why not put a mine shaft underneath it,'' he said.
``That would be really cool.'' So, he built a 70-foot-long mine
shaft, which runs horizontally, just under the barn, and is
illuminated with red lights. The children have hidden treasures in
the shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he concentrated on a place that would be perfect for a
pond. But what good is a deep swimming pond without a full-scale
pirate's ship? He found a man who had built one, but no longer had
any use for it. Roloff purchased it for $2,500. The ``Rolly Polly''
has three sails, below-deck quarters for captain and crew, and a
plank, which serves as a diving board to the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the ship is a bright red 1950s vintage fire truck.
``A guy gave that to me,'' Roloff said. ``I bought some building
materials from him, and he threw in a fire truck.''
</P>
<P>
   The treehouse came about in stages, like a skyscraper, rising
around an old oak tree. The four levels are sturdy, with railing
for protection. But what is remarkable is that the constructed
material never actually touches the tree's branches _ it is wrapped
around the oak. There are six ways inside the house, from ladders
to stairs to a cargo net.
</P>
<P>
   Roloff clambered up to the top floor of the treehouse, 35 feet
above ground. It was a strain on his joints to climb, and with
crutches, it seemed a feat of considerable athleticism. ``Isn't
this cool!'' he said. ``I built this for $500.''
</P>
<P>
   The Western town is the most elaborate of the fantasy
structures. It has a boardwalk, and is covered with
cinnamon-colored siding. A thick steel vault door, reclaimed from a
merchant in eastern Oregon, opens to the bank. The sheriff's office
adjoins the jail. The entire town, though seemingly rock solid, is
built on skids so that it can be rearranged with the help of a
tractor. It cost about $18,000 to build.
</P>
<P>
   A warren of tunnels run beneath the town. To escape from jail,
you slide under a hole in the floor, and hide in the tunnels.
``When I started digging these tunnels, my wife said, `You've
really gone overboard now,''' he said. But Jeremy Roloff, 9, when
asked what his favorite part of the farm was, said, ``All the
underground roads _ they're great for playing hide and go seek.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the children rarely watch television. And
their friends are ``always bugging us about wanting to come over
and play,'' Jeremy said.
</P>
<P>
   Every Western town needs an Indian village _ for historic
tension, if nothing else _ so Roloff has started work on a native
town, raw pine structures built in a little valley. As obsessed as
Roloff may seem with his creations, he still works a day job. He
sells computer applications, a job that takes him on the road for
days on end. He uses his tractors, backhoes and other heavy
machinery for much of the farm work, but he also hires carpenters,
or relies on volunteers for help.
</P>
<P>
   The house where the Roloffs live is a 1930s, somewhat
nondescript structure full of children and music and ringing
phones. Amy Roloff, though she appreciates the fun farm her husband
has built for the children, would not mind if he focused his
energies elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like our house,'' she said. Roloff promises that a major
remodeling of the family home will be forthcoming. But first, he
has a few more things to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow me,'' he said, and he scrambled to another barn, and up
a series of tiny stairs to a cupola with an eagle's view of the
entire spread. He caught his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over there ... '' he trailed off, pointing to a
half-constructed tower that looks like a wooden oil derrick, ``
...I'm going to build a Tower of Terror, which will have a
12-foot-by-12-foot platform that will teeter and drop, just enough
to buckle your knees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And over there, I'm going to build the Titanic,'' he said. A
semi-submerged luxury liner requires a lot of water, so Roloff has
already begun digging the biggest hole yet, for a pond that will
serve as the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much to do. He plans to create a waterfall that will
tumble down one of the big mounds of dirt, splashing into a jungle
of plants that grow in Oregon's temperate climate _ ``like the
Garden of Eden, but a little more fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a master plan,'' he said. ``But it's all in my head,
and it keeps growing.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens, he is asked, when the children are grown and gone,
and he and Amy are left with the Roloff fantasy. He stared at the
34 acres, bathed in the soft light of an Indian summer afternoon.
For the first time that day, he looked puzzled. ``I don't know,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
