<HEADER>
A0720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-N     09-29 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADERS SEEK TO CREATE A UNIFIED FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Leaders of the divided opposition to
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia are making another,
slightly desperate effort to create a common front around the issue
of early elections.
</P>
<P>
   With only moderate turnouts at their nightly anti-Milosevic
rallies, the leaders of the Alliance for Change are reluctantly
seeking a reconciliation with Vuk Draskovic, who runs the largest
opposition party, the Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is being pushed to do so by Dragoslav Avramovic,
the former head of the central bank who is their choice for prime
minister in any transitional government. Avramovic said in an
interview that Milosevic could too easily ignore a divided
opposition and that the protest turnouts had been encouraging but
insufficient to bring significant pressure on the government.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at Avramovic's instigation, all the parties are to
attend a conference on free and fair elections. If the round table
succeeds, Draskovic said, he will throw his support to rallies to
press for early elections as the best and only effective way to
oust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has been insistent that Milosevic has to resign
first, if there is be a chance for fair elections. But their
campaign shows no sign of bringing about a resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has refused to join the rallies, calling them
pointless and a waste of time. He has not lent them his party's
organizational skills or helped publicize them on Studio B, the
Belgrade city television station that he controls.
</P>
<P>
   So the alliance leaders, most notably Zoran Djindjic of the
Democratic Party, are convinced that Draskovic intended to see
these rallies fail altogether, perhaps destroying Djindjic.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the rallies did nearly fail. They began last Tuesday.
But by Thursday night, the turnout was so low and dispirited _
fewer than 5,000 people _ that Djindjic talked bitterly about
calling off the rallies or resigning.
</P>
<P>
   But a chief aide, Cedomir Jovanovic, a former student leader,
urged him to forget the speeches and give in to the crowd's desire
for action _ to march, rather than listen. The numbers shot back up
to 20,000 and then to 30,000 or more on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers are dropping again, with 5,000 on a rainy
Tuesday night. Wednesday night, the alliance announced a march on
``the forbidden hill,'' the Dedinje district where Milosevic lives.
Alliance officials said this was again a response to a perceived
desire for more action.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials said that they believed that they had
saved the rallies and themselves and that they were proud that
Draskovic still had them to deal with. But the main target,
Milosevic, remains remote.
</P>
<P>
   There is some nervousness evident from the government, with the
police in riot gear carefully hidden in case of incidents and a new
crackdown on the nonpayment of taxes, indications of the increasing
economic squeeze that the government faces.
</P>
<P>
   State television remains dismissive about the opposition as NATO
agents and puppets, and counterposters have appeared to mock
alliance posters. One alliance poster shows Djindjic with his child
on his back. The new poster shows President Clinton with Djindjic
on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Important alliance leaders do not really trust Avramovic, who
had made his own approach to Draskovic, though he did tell the
Alliance about that. They apparently believe that Avramovic has his
own ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Avramovic, who will be 80 in two weeks, scoffs at those
concerns. But he said the alliance was too narrow a base to carry
the day against the government, and he is trying, no matter their
concerns, to build a bigger coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The election conference will be run by Dragoljub Micunovic, the
leader of a small party and a friend of Avramovic, and all
opposition parties have agreed to attend. Micunovic said he
expected all the opposition members would ``realize that their
competitors are not in that room, but rather somewhere outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome, if successful, will probably include demands for
elections on all levels; revised electoral districts; an open
press, especially television; a revised media law, and strict
supervision by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few ideological differences among the opposition
parties,'' Avramovic said. ``If the round table can agree, then for
the first time, the government will face a real united front. But
you have to have elections. Period. The question is how quickly and
under what conditions. And I hope Mr. Milosevic will see the point
and resign without a fight, for that would win him considerable
support here for not going to The Hague.''
</P>
<P>
   But a senior government official and an executive who had just
seen Milosevic said he was in no mood to resign or schedule early
elections. ``He's just taken 78 days of bombing by NATO,'' the
businessman said. ``Do you really think he's going to surrender to
Zoran Djindjic?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
