<SLUG> BC-TV-WORK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WORK' DOESN'T, AFTER THE FIRST LAUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WORK WITH ME 
Starring: Kevin Pollak, Nancy Travis, Ethan Embry, Emily
Rutherford 
On: CBS, Wednesday night at 8:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitcom couples don't have much less chemistry than Nancy Travis
and Kevin Pollak in ``Work With Me.'' But that's not the only
problem with this laugh-track-heavy show. ``Work With Me'' is
suffering from a full-blown case of one-joke-itis, a debilitating
disease that is just not rare enough.
</P>
<P>
   The big concept is that Travis and Pollak are a married couple
who work together. Pollak's hotheaded lawyer quits his firm after
getting passed over for partnership, and so he installs himself at
his wife's smaller firm. Can they share an office without straining
their marriage? That tedious question is the show's main source of
material. The premiere dives headlong into the most cliched plot
possible, as Pollak becomes insanely jealous of one of Travis's
handsome clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work With Me'' has two supporting characters, secretaries who
are trying to hide their love affair. Their first coverup bit is
amusing; their fifth is numbing.
</P>
<P>
   Travis, last seen on series TV in ``Almost Perfect,'' is too
tightly wound here. She appears to be going for high-strung sitcom
acting, but she'd be funnier if she relaxed a bit. Pollak is better
with his type A shtick, but the script lets him down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-POPULAR-BOS &LR;      09-29 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-POPULAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POPULAR' SHARPLY DISSECTS TEEN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
POPULAR 
Starring: Carly Pope, Leslie Bibb, Tamara Mello, Christopher
Gorham, Tammy Lynn Michaels, Bryce Johnson, Sara Rue, Ron Lester,
Leslie Grossman, Chad Lowe 
On: WB, Thursday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the special of the day at the youth market is a new series
called ``Popular.'' Yes, folks, yet another TV chronicle of life in
the pimple lane, with a cast of fresh faces coping with alienation,
isolation, exfoliation, and how to deliver self-aware dialogue
without tripping over tongue rings. Yes, more glorious high school
angst glazed with the sort of mall-savvy WB precociousness that
makes jeans companies pant. More ``Dawson's Creek'' chic.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, and yet. ``Popular,'' which premiered Wednesday at 9,
is a surprisingly promising hour that could become something
special if it doesn't cop out and decide to become a hipped-up
``Beverly Hills 90210.'' The theme is a simple one: popularity
contests amid the cafeteria tables and gym lockers. But as it
anatomizes the teen caste system, ``Popular'' is wiser and wittier
and more elaborate than you might think possible. It's an idealized
TV vision, of course _ the girls who think they're ugly are
actually quite beautiful _ but it is based on very real issues of
conformity and acceptance. And it even has a provocative
white-supremacist undercurrent, as a blond cheerleader named Nicole
rules the school's social life like a fascist dictator.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Popular'' characters are split into two cliques. The
ruling-class types include Nicole the Nasty, a sweet-natured jock
named Josh, and his recovering anorexic girlfriend, Brooke McQueen.
And the outsider types include the self-conscious Harrison, an
overweight girl named Carmen, and alternative Everygirl Sam
McPherson. There's a gulf between the groups, except that
``Popular'' muddies the water by having each of the kids flirt with
going over to the other side. Quarterback Josh wants to star in the
school production of ``South Pacific'' and be a ``drama geek,''
while Carmen desperately wants to be a cheerleader. Meanwhile,
Brooke and Sam are forced into a relationship, first as lab
partners, and then when they learn their single parents are dating.
</P>
<P>
   The plot turns in ``Popular'' are familiar, to the tune of
who's-invited-to-the-big-party and who'll
-get-the-part-in-the-school-play. But the show is resourceful in
its telling of these stories, utilizing _ without overusing _
devices like fantasy sequences, voice-overs, and a singer who
comments on the action (a very now-looking Lisa Loeb type).
Overall, it has a heightened tone that brings out the carnival
quality of the fictional Kennedy High School. The cheerleader
scenes are particularly garish and funny, as Nicole and Sam shake
their steely pompoms dressed in gruesomely blue outfits.
</P>
<P>
   The show is also buoyed by some snappy ``Clueless''-like
dialogue and pop reference. ``I am so worshipping your
Gwynethness,'' Brooke says as homage to Nicole. And Sam introduces
this great new putdown: ``Cancel my subscription. I'm over your
issues.'' There are a few too many contemporary quips, with
mentions of ``Monica kneepads,'' a dress that may be ``too Britney
Spears,'' and the rumor that ``Jewel never lived in a car by a
river.'' They are forced. But most of ``Popular'' avoids gratuitous
attitude, as it dissects high school culture like the frogs in Sam
and Brooke's lab pan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
