<HEADLINE>
WILDER STORIES; CRITICS' EYES WIDE SHUT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The October Vanity Fair has an absorbing interview with director
Billy Wilder conducted by director Cameron Crowe. It's dish with a
dependable tone, as the 93-year-old Wilder tells stories about his
great movies, including the three he most highly esteems: ``Sunset
Boulevard,'' ``The Apartment,'' and ``Some Like It Hot.'' Not
reticent, except when it comes to the loss of most of his family at
Auschwitz, Wilder holds forth on legendary actors like Cary Grant,
Humphrey Bogart, and, of course, Marilyn Monroe, who was ``very
tough to work with'' as she was always late to the set, sometimes
by eight hours. And once she got to the set, she would use nearly
80 takes for a small line like ``Where's that bourbon?'' from
``Some Like It Hot.'' ``She was either a maniac or she was very,
very soft and gentle,'' he says. ``She was just a continuous
puzzle, without any solution.'' He has less complex feelings for
Arthur Miller: ``He was an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder also had an unfavorable impression of Bogart, who would
try to ridicule him in front of the cast and crew of ``Sabrina.''
Bogart resented the director for not drinking with him, and for
wanting Cary Grant in the ``Sabrina'' role. But when he was dying
of cancer, he summoned Wilder to his home to make an apology for
his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder always wanted to work with Cary Grant, who was
``absolutely wonderful,'' if ``very stingy.'' But Grant
consistently resisted, making excuses like, ``Look, I like you,
Wilder, but I cannot explain it. I just . . . the wrong signals
come up in me.'' Wilder also had another unfulfilled wish: to make
``Schindler's List.'' But Steven Spielberg could not give it up.
``It would have been something of my heart, you know,'' Wilder
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate about ``Eyes Wide Shut'' continues to be more
engaging than the movie itself. Brill's Content looked at the
media's blind willingness to hype Stanley Kubrick's final effort,
and now the October Harper's goes after the critics for not being
able to see the movie through the hype. Writer Lee Siegel's idea is
that they succumbed to ``art-phobia,'' the fear of submitting
oneself to the power of a piece of art. Instead of processing the
movie as a movie, the critics ``decided to respond to the hype,''
he writes. ``And the result was that the hype determined their
experience of the film.'' In the pre-release barrage of sex-based
promotion and gossip about Kubrick ``as an obsessive tyrant,'' they
lost their objectivity and receptivity. Siegel effectively uses
quotes by reviewers like David Denby in The New Yorker and J.
Hoberman in the Village Voice to prove his theory, and he even
seems to nail a few who may have falsely claimed to have read the
1926 novel on which the movie was based.
</P>
<P>
   As Siegel lays out his own overintellectualized, defensive, and
reverential interpretation of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' he too doesn't
seem to have experienced the movie strictly as a movie. Maybe he's
too right, and there is no way to have a pure cinema experience in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Movieline has never been shy about the fact that there are
tabloids lurking in its family tree. In addition to being
irreverent, the magazine has always been openly gossip-mongering
and catty. For October, the magazine features a wildly gossipy epic
called ``Hollywood's 50 All-Time Hottest Rumors,'' which includes
the now-famous Richard Gere rodent tale, the purported affair
between Jacqueline Susann and Ethel Merman, and a bunch of absurd
blind items like ``One of America's beloved A-list superstars has
long been rumored to be a big honking pot addict.''
</P>
<P>
   Better reading is Joe Queenan's ``The Kids Are Alright,'' in
which he praises youth-market movies for being ``refreshingly
demented'' and for their resistance to irrelevant happy endings _ a
symptom of movies aimed at baby boomers. ``Adults see their
children watching `The Matrix' and worry they'll come away from it
with a distorted view of reality,'' he writes. ``Meanwhile, adults
flock to films like `Life Is Beautiful,' whose Italian name is
`Buonasera, Auschwitz' '' _ roughly translated as ``Good Evening,
Auschwitz.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
