<SLUG> BC-Y2K-READINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT TO INCREASE Y2K PREPAREDNESS HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Confident that key computer systems will beat the Y2K
bug, government officials are shifting into public &UR;  &LR; relations mode
as Jan. 1, 2000 approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal is to build expectations the computer glitch won't
cause major disruptions, and in a Boston visit Wednesday, John
Koskinen, the Clinton Administration's chief Y2K adviser, said
large utilities, banks and other service providers have done a good
job advertising fixes they have made.
</P>
<P>
   Attention now should center on smaller companies and public
agencies to see whether they, too, are ready for the date change,
Koskinen said. ``Ultimately, how comfortable people will be depend
on how much information they get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen spoke to a conference on Y2K preparations at the Boston
Public Library, which drew 350 people. It was billed as one of a
series of ``community conversations'' being held around the country
to talk about the potential impact of the software bug.
</P>
<P>
   The term Y2K relates to the practice, in many older computer
programs, to use just the last two digits of each year to keep
track of dates. Left unfixed, such programs could grow confused by
the last two digits of the year 2000 and malfunction or shut down,
potentially causing problems in everything from utility and
cash-machine networks to air-traffic control systems.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and public agencies have spent billions of dollars to
upgrade their systems and avoid breakdowns, and now most large
organizations say they are confident their systems will function
into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Large service providers including Boston Edison, Bell Atlantic,
and Fleet Financial Group Inc., have said since July they met
fix-it deadlines, and representatives were on hand to repeat those
assurances Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One institution cited earlier by the US Department of Energy for
lagging in preparation was a gas-fired power plant in Milford run
by American National Power of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But plant officers Wednesday said they had since obtained
documents to verify that one of its computer-networking devices
would work through the date change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
