<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH HOPES `TO WHIP' BUCHANAN IN GOP PRIMARY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ Republican presidential candidate George
W. Bush said Wednesday he wants Pat Buchanan to stay in the
Republican presidential contest because ``I'd like to whip him in
the primary.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting words were in contrast to the conciliatory remarks
he made last week. He said Buchanan should stay in the Republican
Party so it can be united for the general election campaign.
Buchanan then called Bush's remarks ``gracious'' and smart.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday _ displaying the nervous excitement of an athlete
preparing for a big game _ Bush made it clear that he blames
Buchanan and Reform Party founder Ross Perot for his father's
re-election defeat in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought in the 1992 campaign it was hard for my
dad to get traction in the race because ... first Patrick J.
Buchanan and then Ross Perot inflicted a series of cuts,'' Bush
said. ``If the adage is true that you die a death of thousand cuts
in politics, Ross Perot was a part of inflicting a part of the
thousand cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan may jump to the Reform Party, complaining that the
Republican presidential primary is not open to a debate of ideas
this year. The party establishment has been rallying around Bush,
who has raised more than $50 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   Perot created a three-way race in 1992 with Bill Clinton and
George Bush. Many analysts believe Perot's candidacy drew voters
away from Bush and helped Clinton win his first White House term.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he is open to inter-Republican debates and noted
that he supports the North American Free Trade Agreement while
Buchanan does not. The Reform Party opposes NAFTA and is generally
protectionist on trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have his ideas out there in Iowa and New Hampshire
and South Carolina and see whether or not Republicans embrace or
don't embrace what he stands for,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the campaign first got going, he (Buchanan) took some
pretty good shots at me. I'd like to be able to test our ideas in a
Republican primary,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he disagreed with Buchanan's ``revisionist'' history
that Nazi Germany was not a security threat to the United States
after 1940, but Bush declined to say whether he believes Buchanan
is an anti-Semite.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask him that question. Ask him that question,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's change in tone was insufficient for Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, the Republican presidential candidate who has been most
unequivocal on excluding Buchanan from the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``By his statements (on World War II), he has left the party,''
McCain said after a speech at the Ronald Reagan Presidential
Library and Museum in Simi Valley, Calif., near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's call for Buchanan to remain in the party and debate his
stance on issues ``was my position for quite a long time,'' McCain
said. He said he had wanted to confront Buchanan about the
commentator's views on trade and the United States' role in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when someone takes the positions that Mr. Buchanan did on
the issue of World War II, then it's no longer within the realm of
debate in the Republican Party.... I will not stoop to debate that
issue,'' said McCain, a son and grandson of Navy admirals who
himself was a prisoner of war for 5 1/2 years during the Vietnam
War.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was at the Reagan library to open a series of speeches by
presidential contenders. He had a private visit with former first
lady Nancy Reagan before his speech and she sat in the front row
for his remarks but did not join him on stage or appear with him in
public during the visit.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Buchanan said Wednesday that Buchanan would have
no comment on Bush and McCain's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   At least one poll has shown that a Reform Party candidacy by
Buchanan would draw votes away from Bush and narrow the
general-election gap between Bush and the Democratic nominee, just
as Perot did to Bush's father. But Bush said it is too early to
know whether Buchanan's defection to the Reform Party would harm
him if he is the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether some of the people who support Pat
Buchanan who are loyal Republicans, will they stay with the
Republican nominee,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said the Democratic nomination is ``up for grabs''
between Gore and Bill Bradley. Bush also noted that Buchanan is not
assured of the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear all kinds of rumors about all kinds of different
candidates thinking about running, including The Donald,'' Bush
said, referring to New York developer Donald Trump. ``It's too
early to predict what the landscape will look like a year from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump also is considering a bid for the Reform Party
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he did not know whether there was any truth to rumors
that Perot wanted Buchanan to run in order to hurt Bush's chances
of becoming president. But he noted that Perot endorsed Ann
Richards just a week before he defeated her in the 1994 race for
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's been a relationship between he (Perot) and
my family,'' Bush said. ``I hope that people enter the political
process with what's best for the country in mind and not be making
decisions based on personal vendettas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
