<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Sept. 30 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Hoping to revive his flagging
campaign, Vice President Al Gore says he is relocating his
headquarters from Washington to his home state of Tennessee. The
move is designed to pare down a bloated, top-heavy operation and to
symbolize a break from the Beltway _ and the Clinton
administration. By Katharine Q. Seelye. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the spending
bills: Republican leaders have vowed daily, and fervently, that
they will not spend Social Security funds to run the government in
the coming year. Wednesday they unveiled a new $5 million campaign
of television ads renewing their pledge. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MUSEUM (New York) _ Moving on a new front against the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, the Giuliani administration says it will
move to terminate the museum's lease, citing several factors
including the fact that its 100-year lease with the city _ signed
in 1894 _ is no longer in force. By David Herszenhorn and David
Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-MERCHANTS (Undated) _ Amazon.com says that starting
Thursday, any merchant can set up a store on its Web site for a fee
of $9.99 a month. The move will sharply broaden the products
available through the site before the holiday shopping season.
Shares of Amazon.com surge as much as 17 percent after the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INFANT-SLEEP (Undated) _ Children under 2 should never sleep
with their parents, the American Medical Association and Consumer
Product Safety Commission says in a study that is provoking furious
reactions from people on both sides. Over an eight-year period, the
researchers say, 515 babies and toddlers died in adult beds: 121
smothered when a parent rolled over on them and 394 were caught in
parts of the bed itself. By Erica Goode.
</P>
