<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CHALLENGES BRADLEY TO DEBATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to jump-start his stalled presidential
effort, Al Gore challenged his Democratic competitor Bill Bradley
on Wednesday to a series of debates and announced he was moving his
campaign headquarters to Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take this campaign for the presidency directly to
the grass roots and directly to the American people,'' Gore told
reporters at a hastily called news conference at his downtown
Washington headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president had instructed his campaign chairman, Tony
Coelho, ``to move this whole campaign, lock, stock and barrel to
Nashville,'' where Gore said he expected ``to get closer to the
American people, closer to the grass roots and out of the Beltway
and into the heartland.''
</P>
<P>
   As a former senator and House member from Tennessee and the son
of a U.S. senator, Gore has nevertheless spent much of his life in
Washington and is considered part of the political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he also will begin to hold a series of town-hall
meetings in key primary states and challenged Bradley to a series
of of debates on specific issues.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in strategy comes at a time when Gore is facing an
unexpectedly strong challenge from Bradley, whom the vice president
has tried for months to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has demonstrated surprising fund-raising prowess and is
drawing increasing support from prominent Democrats such as New
York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who said recently that he did
not believe Gore could win the White House. A half-dozen other
former Senate colleagues of Gore have endorsed Bradley, also a
former senator.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore still leads Bradley in national surveys, the former
New Jersey senator has been making gains in key primary states such
as New Hampshire, where a recent poll showed him beating Gore, and
New York, where Bradley played for the NBA Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   A number of statewide surveys show Bradley doing better than
Gore against Republican front-runner George W. Bush, who continues
to lead the vice president nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gore acknowledged that the dynamics of the campaign have
changed and that he must take his primary challenger more
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a brand new campaign. It is a competitive,
hard-fought battle for the Democratic nomination,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only two candidates. You've got Pepsi and you've got
Coke,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore denied that his abrupt change in tactics were related to
fund-raising problems that may be underscored in Wednesday's
release of third-quarter campaign finance reports.
</P>
<P>
   Previous disclosures showed Bradley doing a better job of
husbanding his resources than the Gore campaign, which has been
criticized for spending too much on consultants and pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is expected to report raising $6.5 million in the third
quarter, bringing the year's total to $24 million. He is expected
to have about $9.5 million cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said he wanted to have ``a bunch'' of debates
with Bradley on such issues as health care, education, national
defense, the environment and crime control.
</P>
<P>
   The call for debates was perhaps the most telling sign of the
reversal of fortune for Gore, who was originally considered a
shoo-in for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It is common for the underdog candidates to clamor for debates
while the front-runners often shun such face-offs based on the
assumption that they provide free publicity to their challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in California, Bradley responded to Gore's offer:
``For the last 10 months the vice president and his campaign have
been ignoring me and now they want to debate me. I think that shows
we're making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Bradley noted that he had accepted a
number of joint appearances with the vice president, including a
town-hall meeting Oct. 27 in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas political science professor Bruce Buchanan
said that Gore's latest moves stemmed from a ``a combination of a
certain sense of desperation and a healthy desire to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that while Gore's decision to move his office out
of Washington may be largely symbolic and superficial, the
challenge to debate his competitor was more substantive and carried
with it significant risks.
</P>
<P>
   While such forums could reinforce voters' impression that Gore
is a stiff creature of Washington, they could also prompt voters to
take another look at his candidacy. Gore is considered a skillful
debater, who bested Ross Perot in a widely watched duel in 1993
over the merits of the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debating with Bradley will allow people to pay more attention
to Gore. Bradley is getting all the ink right now,'' said Andrew
Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Democratic debates might put pressure on Bush to
engage his rivals. So far, the Texas governor has refused to debate
the other Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore promised to open his new headquarters in Nashville by
next week, neither he nor his staff could provide many details
regarding how many people would actually move.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Gore only made the decision to move Monday night
and informed most of his staff Wednesday morning before speaking to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president, Gore will still live in his official
residence in Washington, although he also has a home in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he had informed President Clinton on Wednesday morning
of his intentions to move.
</P>
<P>
   Some political experts have opined that one of Gore's problems
is his association with the scandal-plagued Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart said that he assumed the
president approved of moving the headquarters, noting that Clinton
ran his 1992 presidential campaign out of Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just believes you are better off closer to the people
outside the Beltway,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
