<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0791 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-SMASHMOUTH-HNS &LR;      09-29 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SMASHMOUTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMASH MOUTH LEAPS OVER THE `SUN' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smash Mouth is the band that almost wasn't _ at least in the
infectious, get-a-groove-on form that many of today's music lovers
are familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose, Calif.-based outfit was formed in 1994, when lead
singer Steve Harwell and drummer Kevin Coleman recruited guitarist
Greg Camp from a local cover band. Camp introduced them all to
bassist Paul De Lisle, with whom he played in the hip-hop/punk band
Lackadaddy. Smash Mouth was born.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, the band had pulled a few demos together. One of
those songs, ``Nervous in the Alley,'' was put into rotation on a
local modern-rock station. It earned Smash Mouth a spot on a summer
festival with Beck and No Doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The band's breakthrough, however, was ``Walkin' on the Sun,''
one of 1997's breeziest slices of retro-hipness. Camp originally
wrote the song for Lackadaddy, but the band hated it. By chance,
Coleman discovered the song on an old tape, and the group decided
to record it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really think that it was going to do anything
because it didn't sound like the rest of the record, didn't really
fit in very well,'' said Camp, calling from a tour stop in Atlanta,
Ga. ``Once we recorded it ... we came back and listened to it. We
were all like `If people get into this, it's going to be pretty
big.'''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced of the song's appeal, the group was determined to get
it on influential Los Angeles radio station KROQ. They carefully
plotted an attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of ... stormed into the radio station with the CD and
said `Listen to this,''' Camp said. ``It was on a Tuesday, and we
know that's when they have their production meetings. We handed it
to, like, an intern and said, `Go throw this in front of the
program director during this meeting and see what he thinks.' Sure
enough, he put it on. We didn't have a record deal, and the next
day we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Smash Mouth's major-label debut album, ``Fush Yu Mang,'' went on
to sell 2 million copies, but it failed to produce another
``Sun''-size hit single, mainly because the rest of the album
wasn't as radio-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The group did earn airplay for its shagadelic rendition of
``Can't Get Enough of You Baby'' (off the ``Can't Hardly Wait''
soundtrack), but critics carped that Smash Mouth was simply
rehashing its sound. The phrase ``one-hit wonder'' popped up a few
times, and the pressure was on to come up with something new. Would
Smash Mouth go the way of Chumbawamba?
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get out of that Cali-punk, ska-punk,
one-hit-wonder stuff,'' Camp said. ``We sort of went in saying',
`OK, let's take all of our individual influences,' which stem from
Van Halen to the Adolescents, Lee Scratch Perry ... lounge music.
We just wanted to take all those things and make them all blend
together and create our own sound.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting album, ``Astro Lounge,'' is a decidedly more solid
affair than ``Fush Yu Mang.'' The album culls lounge vibes,
surf-rock riffs, new-wave influences and trippy lyrics. It's the
album ``Walkin' in the Sun'' should have come from. Critics,
however, have still complained about the album's hodgepodge of
recycled styles. Guess you can't always make everyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can listen to just about anything, and somebody is
influenced by somebody,'' said Camp, who was jamming to everything
from Fatboy Slim and Eminem to Burt Bacharach and Elvis Costello
during the making of ``Astro Lounge.'' ``Most people are influenced
by the Beatles, Bob Dylan. You can totally hear that. I think our
influences are a little more eclectic than most of the stuff that's
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp also serves as the group's lead songwriter, and he looked
to a variety of places for inspiration when it came time to come up
with tracks for the new album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I locked myself into a cheap motel for a few weeks. Just to
try to get a little seedy, try to get what I had and give it a
little grain,'' he said. ``There was just a lot of pressure, and we
were on a time schedule. We wanted to strike while the iron was
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Smash Mouth finished up ``Astro Lounge,'' but the label refused
to release the album until it decided the time was right for that
kind of music to hit the airwaves. The label also wanted the group
to deliver another killer lead single, a la ``Walkin' on the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp wasn't thrilled with the idea of recycling a hit, but he
vowed to come up with an equally infectious song that everyone
could relate to. The trick was to come up with something new, and
he got it by reading through the group's fan mail. The final
product, ``All Star,'' earned the group another hit and eliminated
the one-hit-wonder peg.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids are having a tough time growing up, and so we
just figured why don't we give 'em some sort of daily
affirmation?'' Camp said. ``It's just like the vehicle that got the
rest of the record listened to, and that's exactly what we wanted
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids are an important part of Smash Mouth's audience and Camp's
life. He leased a separate bus two weeks ago so his wife and
9-month-old daughter could travel on the road with him. When the
conversation turns to his daughter, Camp's voice takes on a
lighthearted tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our roommate decided to teach her how to spit. She thinks it's
a greeting. Every time someone goes, `Oh, what a cute baby,' she
does it,'' Camp said, as his daughter chattered and fussed in the
background. ``She dances a little bit. She likes really high
voices. She likes Bjork. I think she likes Cibo Matto. Cute little
Japanese girl music.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics will likely continue to bemoan Smash Mouth's
carefree approach to music, but it's simply the sound that now
comes naturally to the band. It's also a breath of fresh air in the
face of harder-edged, angrier acts such as Korn and Limp Bizkit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of all just decided once this isn't fun anymore we're
going to go home. I like to try to write music that's fun and makes
everyone happy,'' Camp said. ``We don't want to write songs about
how we don't like drugs but the drugs like us. We don't want people
killing each other in high school because of us. We're all, for the
most part, happy people. I think a little happier than most
artists, anyway. We try to make that happen in our music and make
everyone else around us happy, too. Especially our babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Camp's experience, that's a thought many will take to
heart. After all, father knows best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
