Bridge: Ex-GIs tell of Korean War refugee killings.''
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   NY-MUSEUM (New York) _ Developments. The Brooklyn Museum of Art
files a lawsuit in federal court accusing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of
violating the First Amendment by threatening to withdraw city funds
from the museum; city officials vow to file their own lawsuit in
State Supreme Court, seeking to seize control of the museum by
arguing that it has violated its lease with the city, but they say
they will not attempt to block the exhibition opening Saturday. By
David Herszenhorn. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the spending
bills: Republican leaders unveil a new campaign of television ads
renewing their pledge not to spend Social Security funds to run the
government in the coming year; their calculations and their plans.
By Tim Weiner. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-OUTLOOK (Warsaw) _ A decade after the change known to
Poles as ``the revolution,'' capitalism is very much in evidence
here. Banners advertising Internet services hang from Stalin's vast
Palace of Culture, mobile phones are de rigeur with the smart set,
western cars sit in bottlenecks where poky Fiat Polskis once made
their way down empty streets. But beneath this impressive veneer,
all is not well with the Polish success story. By Roger Cohen. (The
story has moved in ``i'' news file.) With map. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: CLINTON-IMF (Washington) _ President Clinton announces a
major expansion of American efforts to forgive the debt of the
world's poorest nations, saying those countries will not have to
pay back any of the billions of dollars they borrowed from U.S. aid
agencies if they can show the savings are being plowed into poverty
reduction and education. By David E. Sanger. (Scheduled to move by
8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-MERCHANTS (Undated) _ Amazon.com announces that it will
reinvent itself as kind of Internet shopping bazaar, opening its
popular web site to merchants large and small and web and non-web
based for a minimal fee. In return, the selling powerhouse that
started as a bookstore will gather an unprecedented amount of
precious information on the buying habits of web consumers. By
Leslie Kaufman. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INFANT-SLEEP (Undated) _ Children under 2 should never sleep
with their parents, the American Medical Association and Consumer
Product Safety Commission says in a study that is provoking furious
reactions from people on both sides. Over an eight-year period, the
researchers say, 515 babies and toddlers died in adult beds: 121
smothered when a parent rolled over on them and 394 were caught in
parts of the bed itself. By Erica Goode. (The story has moved in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   reefer: BUSH-REFORM-PARTY (Bakersfield, Calif.) _ Gov. George W.
Bush sternly denounces Ross Perot and Pat Buchanan, suggesting that
``personal vendettas'' may be driving their apparent alliance. By
Richard L. Berke. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
