<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-LONG-DISTANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC SEEKS LONG-DISTANCE ACCESS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a step it vowed to repeat next year in Massachusetts, Bell
Atlantic Corp., the nation's largest local telephone company, asked
regulators Wednesday to support its plan to offer long-distance
service to local customers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the proposal could dramatically alter a major
portion of the nation's phone system and spark similar changes in
other regions. Bell Atlantic, which serves 13 states in the
Northeast and mid-Atlantic, would become the first of the Baby Bell
regional phone companies to enter the nation's lucrative
long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia-based Bell Atlantic, which submitted its proposal
to the Federal Communications Commission, said it planned to file a
similar application by July 2000 requesting approval to offer
long-distance service to Massachusetts customers. The company sees
the Bay State's 4.8 million customers and $2 billion long-distance
market as the biggest prize after New York's $8 billion market
covering 8 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York filing is a kind of shot in the arm to the
Massachusetts process,'' said Robert Mudge, vice president of Bell
Atlantic's Massachusetts operations. He said that an application
was more likely in the second quarter and that similar requests
would be filed for New Hampshire and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years after antitrust officials split up the AT&AMP;T
monopoly into seven Baby Bells, leaving the giant a
long-distance-only operator, change is coming to the
telecommunications landscape.
</P>
<P>
   A crush of competitors is seeking a chunk of the nation's $100
billion local phone market and $80 billion long-distance market,
now dominated by AT&AMP;T. Mergers _ like Bell Atlantic's combination
with GTE Corp. _ are spawning new companies overnight. And newer
companies are seeking to muscle in on the regionals' turf.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the 1984 AT&AMP;T breakup, Baby Bells like Bell
Atlantic are not allowed to offer long-distance service _ a market
they would dearly love to crack. The companies are betting that
customers would like to see all their phone bills _ local and
long-distance _ on one statement and promise that fresh competition
will drive down rates.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal is steeped in controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, regulators have rejected nearly half-a-dozen
applications like Bell Atlantic's, saying the companies have not
done enough to give rivals access to their local markets. Major
long-distance companies, like MCIWorldcom and Sprint, want to
compete with the Baby Bells in offering local service.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1996 federal act, companies like Bell Atlantic must
persuade regulators that they have done enough to promote
competition within their own local networks before seeking
permission to enter the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators require the regional Bells to test their systems to
prove they are physically open to use by rivals. For more than two
years, Bell Atlantic has been doing just that in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've met the requirements of the Telecommunications Act,''
Bell Atlantic chief executive Ivan Seidenberg said Wednesday in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge said the company expects to complete testing in
Massachusetts in the first quarter of next year. The review is
being carried out by KPGM, the auditing and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates worry that if the progeny of old Ma Bell are
let into the long distance market, they will have less incentive to
provide competitive, lower-cost service to their local-service
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all going to be a huge tug-of-war,'' said Douglas A.
Christopher, a telecommunications analyst at Crowell, Weedon &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-BOS &LR;      09-29 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TELLS CHECHENS TO HAND OVER GUERRILLA LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Prime Minister Vladimir Putin demanded Wednesday that
Chechen leaders denounce terrorism and turn over guerrilla leaders
whom Russia holds responsible for a series of apartment bombings,
saying only then will Russia cease its punishing bombing of the
breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the Chechen leadership to finally condemn terrorism
clearly and firmly and to express their readiness to hand over
criminals,'' Putin said in televised comments.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a ground war increased Wednesday as Russian warplanes
bombed what Moscow says are strategic targets throughout Chechnya
for the seventh straight day. Unconfirmed reports circulated all
day asserting that Russian forces had entered northern Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Segodnya reported that plans were already drawn up
for Russian forces to occupy northern Chechnya and partition the
republic. And the Interfax news service, citing unidentified high
ranking military officers, reported that Russian forces had
actually seized parts of northern Chechnya, including the districts
of Zandak and Galaity.
</P>
<P>
   Russian State Television showed footage of troops and tanks
concentrating on the border with Chechnya. ``It appears that a
ground operation could begin any time,'' the commentator said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters whether Russian forces had moved into
Chechnya, Putin, who earlier in the day said he was not ruling out
a ground invasion as an option, was coy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I will call the defense minister
and ask him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed whether forces had crossed Chechnya's border, Putin
became testy. ``We don't have a border with Chechnya,'' he said.
``Chechnya is part of Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyewitnesses in Chechnya's capital Grozny, meanwhile, said most
of those killed in the air strikes have been civilians. News
agencies here reported that over 400 people have been killed since
the bombing campaign began last week, including 11 Wednesday. The
bombing has also driven tens of thousands of Chechens from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say Chechen guerrilla leader Shamil Basayev
was behind a series of bombings in apartment buildings in Moscow
and other Russian cities earlier this month that killed nearly 300
people.
</P>
<P>
   Basayev, who since August has led a series of raids from
Chechnya into neighboring Dagestan, a mostly Muslim republic in
southern Russia, has repeatedly denied responsibility for the
bombings. He has, however, said he plans to pry Russia's volatile
North Caucasus region, including Dagestan, free from Moscow's
grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov has denied that his
government was involved in any way with the terrorist bombings that
have sparked fear and anger in Russia. Maskhadov also said that his
government did not endorse Basayev's raids into Dagestan and has
called for peace talks with Russia's President Boris N. Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   By demanding that Maskhadov turn Basayev and other militants
over to Moscow _ a virtual impossible condition for peace talks _
Putin has made it clear that Moscow is going to try to bring the
rebel province to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about Basayev. It is about proving to Chechnya that
they have lost the war,'' said Alexei Malashenko, a specialist on
the Caucasus region at the Moscow Carnegie Center.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov was elected Chechnya's president in 1996 after Moscow
withdrew its troops following a bloody 20-month war that killed as
many as 80,000 people _ mostly innocent civilians and inexperienced
Russian conscripts.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, however, still claims Chechnya as part of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov _ who has always sought good relations with Russia _
has little influence in Chechnya, which has fallen under the
control of guerrilla leaders like Basayev.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview broadcast on the BBC Russian Service on Tuesday,
Basayev accused Moscow of conducting ``ethnic cleansing'' against
Chechens. He also said that Russia's bombing campaign has
consolidated Chechen society against Moscow, adding that he and
Mashkadov _ long competitors for power in Chechnya _ are now
allies, united by the common Russian enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were differences. But in the current situation we are
united and our unity is strengthened by Russia _ and for this we
are grateful,'' said Basayev.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov was scheduled Wednesday to meet with Dagestan's leader
Magomedali Magomedov in the town of Khasavyurt, where Moscow signed
a truce with Chechen separatists three years ago. But when
Maskhadov arrived, angry villagers blocked the road into the town
and prevented the meeting from taking place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
