<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CAMPGIAN-GORE-BOS &LR;      09-29 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPGIAN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SEEKS DEBATES WITH BILL BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with a surprisingly strong challenge for the
Democratic presidential nomination, Vice President Al Gore
Wednesday called for a series of debates against Bill Bradley and
announced he would hold ``open meetings'' with voters in key
primary states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said he was moving his campaign headquarters ``lock,
stock and barrel'' from insider Washington to Nashville _ a move
expected to save the campaign money while giving it a folksier
feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hard, tough fight. I'm going to fight my heart out
for every single vote,'' said Gore, for the first time publicly
acknowledging the seriousness of Bradley's threat. ``It's a brand
new campaign now,'' Gore said at a press conference. ``There are
only two candidates. You've got Pepsi and Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, campaigning in California, indicated he was open to
debates against Gore, saying he had accepted ``a number of joint
appearances already'' and would ``look forward to more.''
</P>
<P>
   The former New Jersey senator also said he was not inclined to
``respond to every change in tactic by the vice president's
campaign,'' and added that he is also traveling around the country
to hear voters' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign shake-up was a stark admission that he can no
longer cruise along as the presumed nominee simply because he is
the sitting vice president.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost unheard of for a front-runner to challenge an
opponent to debates, because the leading candidate usually has
little to gain from them. Gore's decision to move his national
campaign headquarters south also shows how sensitive he is to being
labeled a Washington insider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking the campaign to my roots,'' said Gore, who was born
in Tennessee, but raised in Washington as the son of a US senator.
Gore also has spent most of his adult life in Washington, first as
a US representative, then as a senator and the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which stunned his campaign office here, is also
expected to save cash. Not only will costs be lower in Tennessee,
but only those workers most dedicated to Gore will endure the
personal upheaval of moving. The current campaign is larded with
high-paid consultants and contains too many people who are not
totally committed to the Gore campaign, critics of the campaign
say.
</P>
<P>
   Those willing to make the trip will be more focused on the
recently tightened Democratic race and less susceptible to
following Washington punditry at the expense of listening to real
voters, staffers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they probably want a leaner campaign,'' said someone
close to Gore. ``I bet he just woke up and said, `How did it get so
out of hand?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokeswoman Kiki Moore said she did not know how many
people would be staying, as staff members need to discuss the move
with their families. One who is making the trip is campaign
director Tony Coelho.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be packing my bags, learning country music, and moving
to Nashville,'' Coelho, a former US representative from California,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The new direction of the campaign is reminiscent of the 1992
Clinton-Gore campaign, when the candidates took bus trips and held
town meetings with voters, running their campaign from Little Rock,
Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement underscores Bradley's climb in the
polls. Bradley, who trailed 23 percent to Gore's 68 percent in New
Hampshire in May, now leads there 44 percent to 42 percent, said
Andy Smith, director of the University of New Hampshire Survey
Center. The two candidates are also running neck-and-neck in recent
polls in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has earned the endorsement of Senator Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, Democrat of New York, who said Gore was unelectable
against Republican front-runner George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A Brown University poll released Wednesday showed Gore and
Bradley in a dead heat in Rhode Island, with Gore leading 37
percent to Bradley's 36 percent. But in a hypothetical matchup
against Bush, Bradlbetter with 37 percent against Bush's 26
percent. Gore led Bush 34 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore plans to spend at least six days in New Hampshire in
October, while his wife, Tipper, will spend three days there, said
the state campaign's spokesman, Doug Hattaway. ``It's a recognition
that it's a tough campaign,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   The first time both candidates will appear together in New
Hampshire is Oct. 27, at a forum sponsored by Dartmouth College.
</P>
<P>
   Debates could tarnish both candidates, if either attacks the
other. But they could also assist Gore, who would have the
opportunity to establish himself as an individual candidate,
instead of as the man in the wings during the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore needs to be able to say, `I am not Bill Clinton; I just
worked for him,' '' said Smith of the University of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Gore benefits from the booming economy but could suffer from the
Clinton scandals. The so-called Clinton fatigue, or perception that
voters want change, also could hurt the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joke around the Bush campaign is that after Clinton leaves
office, the whole country is going to want to take a collective
shower. And Al Gore is the one who is going to be washed down the
drain,'' said Mark Corallo, a House Republican staffer.
</P>
<P>
   The polling numbers in New Hampshire buttress that theory, Smith
said, noting that Gore is strongest among those who give Clinton
high favorability ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is being seen as the administration's representative
here,'' Smith said. The primary for Gore ``is really a referendum
on the incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of his recent success, Bradley has an uphill fight if he
is to persuade the Democratic Party to cast aside loyalty to its
own vice president and nominate him instead.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats have tended to give the
nomination to sitting vice presidents who seek it. In only two
cases during the 20th century _ with Democrats John Nance Garner in
1940 and Alben William Barkley in 1952 _ have vice presidents been
denied the nomination, and in both cases, neither candidate was
taken seriously, said presidential scholar William Leuchtenberg of
the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidents have been less successful at actually being
elected president, with most getting the job after a president's
death or resignation. Former President George Bush is the only
person this century to have ever done what Gore is trying to do:
win the presidency as the sitting vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling of `enough, already' '' that could hurt
Gore, Leuchtenberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
