u a BC-MA-JUDGES-BOS &LR;      09-29 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-JUDGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT NOMINEE PRAISED BY BACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Momentarily side-stepping concerns about
anti-Catholicism raised by Cardinal Bernard Law, the Governor's
Council Wednesday heard from a parade of top political and judicial
leaders who praised Supreme Judicial Court Justice Margart Marshall
as a heroic and unbiased nominee for the court's chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, who nominated Marshall, House Speaker
Thomas M. Finneran, Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, and
retired Chief Justice Herbert P. Wilkins all testified in favor of
Marshall's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the Governor's Council said they were waiting
until a second hearing Thursday to hear from opponents and address
the controversial issues surrounding Marshall's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Those include Law's recent charges that Marshall may have
exhibted an anti-Catholic bias, and questions raised by Councilor
Edward M. O'Brien (D-Easthampton) and others who believe Marshall's
three years as a judge on the state's highest court may not have
provided her with sufficient experience to serve as chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously have concens,'' O'Brien said. ``The experience
factor has some bearing on the apptitude of a person going into a
leadership position.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, the Governor's Council confirmed by an 8-0
the nomination of Francis X. Spina to the Supreme Judicial Court,
even though his nomination was snagged by news that he had paid a
prison inmate serving time for murder to do legal work in a
Mafia-related drug case.
</P>
<P>
   Of the dozens of witness who either testified on Marshall's
behalf or wrote letters in support of her nomination, only one,
Superior Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith, addressed the charges
leveled by Law.
</P>
<P>
   Fremont-Smith, who presided over the recent wrongful death case
involving the late Boston Celtics star, Reggis Lewis, identified
himself as a Catholic and one-time president of an organization
that opposes abortion rights, and said he was ``embarrassed'' by
Law's charges.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Fremont-Smith said, Marshall personally encouraged him
to join the Superior Court bench and ``espoused my candidacy to
various persons and was the master of ceremonies at my
swearing-in.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, a native of South Africa who opposed Apartheid as a
student leader there, told reporters she would address the specific
concerns raised by Law at Thursday's hearing but also said her
career as an activist, lawyer, and judge has been directed at
eliminating bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout my entire life I have tried to learn to be fair and
open-minded to everyone,'' said Marshall, who would become the
state's first woman chief justice if her nomination is approved.
``The claim that I hold bias against anyone is a blow to my
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's hearing, a top aide to Cellucci said he
believes Marshall's testimony, along with statements from several
prominent judges, convinced a majority of the eight-member
Governor's Council to confirm her at a vote scheduled for next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll get more than enough votes,'' the aide said. ``The
testimony indicated she has the leadership ability for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Governor's Councilor Michael J. Callahan
(D-Medford) said the status of Marshall's nomination is ``fluid''
and declined to say whether she would be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Callahan and O'Brien, Councilor David Francis
Constantine (D-New Bedford) has expressed reservations about
Marshall's candidacy for the state's top judicial post. In the
event of a tie on the eight-member Council, Lt. Governor Jane Swift
would cast the deciding vote.
</P>
<P>
   As the Council heard Wednesday's testimony from Marshall and her
supporters, Law's office again declined to clarify whether the
Cardinal continues to object to her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and his aides have said Marshall and Law spoke over the
telephone on Saturday and that Law's concerns have been allayed.
But neither Law nor his office would confirm the administration's
version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Law's allegation of anti-Catholic bias arose in a Sept. 22
letter in which Law objected to the nominations of Marshall and
Superior Court Judge Judith Cowin, who has been named by Cellucci
to an associate justice's position on the Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Law referred to separate actions taken by Cowin
and Marshall. In Marshall's case, he cited Marshall's tenure as
chief counsel for Harvard University and an instance in which she
asked Mary Ann Glendon, a prominent Harvard Law School professor
who opposes abortion rights, to refrain from using university
stationary for personal or political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Glendon, in a 1992 letter written under law school letterhead,
had outlined her opposition to a federal abortion rights bill and
urged Catholic priests to work against the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after being admonished by Marshall, Glendon accused her of
enforcing a double-standard, contending that Harvard had allowed
others to use university resources to oppose the US Supreme Court
nominations of Robert Bork and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard officials Wednesday released a copy of university
policy on the use of university stationary that appears to supppot
Marshall's action.
</P>
<P>
   The policy states: ``The letterhead should not be used for
matters unrelated to the performance of academic duties and
functions. And care should be taken that any reference to the Law
School affiliation, on matters other than official Law School
business, be made only for purposes of identification.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, a Yale Law School graduate and the wife of New York
Times columnist Anthony Lewis, in her testimony never touched on
the issues raised by Law.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she spoke about her experiences as a South African
student leader fighting that country's policy of racial separation,
her journey to America in the late 1960s, shortly before the
assassinations of Martin Luther King and Robert Kennedy, and her
passion for the American judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an immigrant. I am a citizen,'' she declared. ``And I
carry within me a particular appreciation for the hard work of the
generations who have gone before me to build this remarkable
democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
