<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-ADVISORY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic shortly will move a package of stories on the
life and career of Arizona senator and presidential contender John
McCain. In addition to the seven stories, slugged MCCAIN-1 through
MCCAIN-7, are MCCAINCHRONO - a timeline of the high points of
McCain's life; MCCAINBIO - a biobox; and MCCAIN-CREDITBOX - a
bibliography of printed sources used. The stories were written by
Republic reporter BILL MULLER. The package is embargoed for Sunday,
Oct. 3. All will move in the ``A'' category. 
 
The stories will move as: 
 
MCCAIN-1 - INTRODUCTION - (Undated) - There is a grim determination
to Sen. John McCain as he rises to address the Republican faithful
in his bid to be president. McCain moves stiffly through the heavy
air of the gymnasium, his war injuries still in evidence. There is
his sore right knee, broken years ago when he ejected from a bomber
over North Vietnam. There is his aching right shoulder, shattered
by his captors. There is his hair, turned prematurely white by
mistreatment and malnutrition. Then there are his political wounds.
 
 
MCCAIN-2 - JOHN WAYNE MCCAIN (Undated) - John McCain had plenty to
live up to at the Naval Academy. There was his grandfather, Admiral
John ``Slew'' McCain, Class of '06, a grizzled old sea dog who
commanded aircraft carriers in the Pacific during World War II.  
MCCAIN-3 - CROWN PRINCE IN HELL (Undated) - Lt. Commander John
McCain was not thinking about a cell in the Hanoi Hilton when he
took off in his A-4E Skyhawk from the USS Oriskany on the morning
of Oct. 26, 1967. As a pilot, McCain had led a charmed life,
surviving a bad accident on the USS Forrestal, about a month
before. On Oct. 26, McCain would fly his 23rd sortie over Vietnam,
joining a 20-plane mission to bomb a power plant in Hanoi, a city
that had previously been off limits to U.S. attacks. An officer
warned McCain to be careful, that some of the pilots might not
return. ``Don't worry about me,'' McCain said. 
 
MCCAIN-4 - ARIZONA, THE EARLY YEARS (Undated) - In 1979, John
McCain came face to face with his future. He was in Hawaii,
attending a military reception. While there, he met a young, blond
ex-cheerleader named Cindy Hensley. It was an incredible stroke of
luck for McCain. How fortunate could one man be? Here was McCain,
who had his eye on Congress, meeting a young, attractive beer
heiress, who just happened to hail from a state that was adding a
congressional district in 1982. McCain recalls that both he and
Cindy fudged their ages at first. McCain made himself a little
younger, and Cindy made herself a little older. They found out
their real ages when the local paper published them. McCain was 43,
Cindy 25. 
 
MCCAIN-5 - CHARLIE KEATING (Undated) - - It all started in March
1987. Charles H Keating Jr., the flamboyant developer and anti-porn
crusader, needed help. The government was poised to seize Lincoln
Savings and Loan, a freewheeling subsidiary of Keating's American
Continental Corp. As federal auditors crawled all over Lincoln,
Keating was not content to wait and hope for the best. He'd spread
a lot of money around Washington, and it was time to call in his
chits. 
 
MCCAIN-6 - ARIZONA, THE LATER YEARS (Undated) - For many
politicians, the Keating scandal would have been too much to
overcome. But McCain refused to go down easily. He deployed a dual
strategy. He would make himself accessible to any reporter anywhere
who wanted to talk about the Keating Five, and he wouldn't let the
controversy detract from his work as a senator. McCain grimly
marched about the country, struggling to clear his name. McCain's
hobnobbing with the press had an unexpected side effect. Reporters
started to like McCain, if for self-serving reasons. 
 
MCCAIN-7 - THE CAREER - (Undated) - Today, as chairman of the
Senate Commerce Committee, McCain is shepherding the deregulation
of the telephone industry, as well as dealing with burgeoning
issues involving cable television. But McCain has really made a
name for himself by fighting wasteful government spending, which
often takes the form of pet federal projects - called ``pork
barrel'' - in congressmen's districts. To root out the pork, McCain
has stationed a staffer at appropriations committee meetings. He
also pushed the line-item veto. 
 
