<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, Sept. 30. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN _ (Phoenix) Doctors at the Arizona State Hospital
know how to treat the criminally insane. Advancements in psychiatry
and pharmaceuticals now make it possible to better care for the
mentally ill, often restoring them to a functionally rational
condition through the use of newly developed wonder drugs.
Unfortunately, problem facing local shrinks is: How do you medicate
an entire state? By EJ MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and
``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
OZONE (Phoenix) - The Valley (Phoenix area is on the verge of
completing three straight summers without an ozone violation, an
accomplishment that could lead to the area losing its `serious`
rating for air pollution. As the ozone season ends Thursday, Gov.
Jane Hull is expected to ask the EPA to quickly reclassify the
Valley as meeting federal clean-air standards. Why were the ozone
levels were held at bay? And this is not the end of air-pollution
woes: It can take years to get reclassified, meaning all the
clean-air requirements will stay in place (such as cleaner fuels,
the auto emissions test, etc). And other pollutants, especially
particulates, remain vexing. By MARY JO PITZL. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONET-EATS (Phoenix) - Mmmmonet. The great painter was not only a
master of the palette, but the palate as well. He lorded over his
Giverny, France, estate, a place of Eden-like gardens that yielded
wonderful meals and exquisite paintings, and he left detailed
cooking journals to preserve his preferred recipes for posterity. A
traveling exhibit of the paitings Monet produced at Giverny is at
the Phoenix Art Museum now. With recipes. BY JAIMEE ROSE. Story
moved in the ``D'' and ``E'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WILSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Given the number of privileged sons whose
political dads have given them a leg up, it's predictable that some
malcontents would grumble about Texas Gov. George W. Bush owning
much of his success to special treatment as the son of a president.
From keeping out of active military duty to getting rich in the oil
business to becoming lead owner of the Texas Rangers, George W. has
used his father's political influence to cut in line, they squawk.
The gall of these people. By STEVE WILSON. Column will move in the
``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
