<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS &LR;      09-29 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TREASURER DESCRIBES `NIGHTMARE' OF FRAUD ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joseph D. Malone, who oversaw the Treasury while
employees allegedly pulled off the largest theft of public money in
Massachusetts history, says he is ``devastated'' by the
``nightmare'' of watching his record crumble and former friends
betray him.
</P>
<P>
   In his first interview since seven men were indicted in the $9.5
million Treasury theft, Malone said Wednesday he does not want to
speak with any of those charged in the case because they committed
the ``ultimate betrayal'' against him and the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is devastating,'' he added. ``To know the effort that went
into the eight years that we were in office and to think that there
-- if the allegations are true -- was such a lack of conscience on
the part of these individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If these allegations are true, it's the ultimate betrayal,''
Malone said. ``This is a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, Malone declined to discuss what he knew about any
wrongdoing in the agency, saying no matter his response, it could
be misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against the men _ three former Treasury employees, a
top fundraiser for Malone and three others _ include stealing
$300,000 to $400,000 in bags of cash from a state employees bank on
Beacon Hill, tipping off heir-finding firms to uncashed state
checks in exchange for kickbacks, and larceny of about $9 million
from the loosely supervised Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement of criminal charges against fundraiser
Richard Arrighi, brings the scandal closer personally to Malone,
who is cooperating with Attorney General Thomas Reilly's probe.
</P>
<P>
   Arrighi was the lawyer for Malone's now-deceased mother and won
lucrative bond contracts for his law firms under Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said watching the scandal unfold has been especially
painful because he knew some of the players personally. Arrighi is
accused of concealing $1.6 million stolen from the Treasury by
laundering it through a Waltham condo development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly knew Rick,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Some sources say Arrighi arranged for former Deputy Treasurer
Robert Foley, the alleged mastermind of the scheme, to get his job
from Malone. Malone Wednesday denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Foley,'' Malone said. ``Arrighi didn't have to help
him. He came with a strong background in accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he blames himself only for trusting too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 44 years I thought I had seen just about everything,''
Malone said in a measured voice. ``But this is a whole new story.
... Seven people conspired to steal money from the people of
Massachusetts and I say, didn't one of them have the good sense to
say this is a crazy idea and let's stop it?''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who dreamed of being a governor since he was a teenager,
relinquished his position to run, unsuccessfully, for the state's
highest office last year and is now an online consultant.
</P>
<P>
   His political career has been deeply damaged by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had some antennae that led me to see what was going
on or to smell a rat, but it didn't go that way,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also said it has been months since he talked to Arrighi
or to Foley, who oversaw many of the cash functions in the
treasury, which has about $40 billion under its management.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was indicted charges of embezzlement, receiving bribes,
conflict of interest, conspiracy and concealing stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   Former Treasury supervisor John ``Trixie'' Trischitta was
indicted for his part of an alleged kickback scheme with heir
finders Martin Robbins and Thomas Ciliberto Jr., who, according to
Reilly, stole money from the state's Unpaid Check Fund with
Trischitta's help. Robbins and Cilberto were also indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Another lawyer, Robert Borino was indicted for allegedly working
with Arrighi to launder the stolen money from the Unpaid Check
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Scot Butcher, the Treasury's former head of cash management, was
indicted for allegedly stealing cash from a state employees bank at
the One Ashburton Place government building on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Malone Wednesday said he closed the teller station at Ashburton
Place but did not recall when. His closure of another teller
station within the State House was done with much fanfare earlier
in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole teller system was open for abuse and that's why we
shut it down,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
