<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AMAZON-MERCHANTS-ART-     09-29 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-MERCHANTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM TO OPEN ITS WEB SITE TO WIDE RANGE OF MERCHANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used
throughout instead of the symbol.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazon.com announced Wednesday that it would reinvent itself as
kind of Internet shopping bazaar, opening its popular web site to
merchants large and small for a minimal fee. In return, the selling
powerhouse, which started as an online bookstore, will gather an
unprecedented amount of precious information on the buying habits
of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, called zShops, begins Thursday with 500,000 new
products _ about four times the offerings of the average Kmart _
the company said. Whether Amazon customers are really looking to
buy everything from jam made by Trappist Monks to whitewater rescue
equipment is yet to be proved.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer sales over the Internet will jump to $108 billion
by 2003 from $3.9 billion last year, according to Forrester
Research, and most major merchants are trying to develop a selling
strategy to master the emerging marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, which has one of the most visited sites on the web,
expects to help these companies and to expand well beyond books,
CDs, electronics and toys. For Amazon, whose losses have been
mounting along with its sales, one big benefit is a steady stream
of cash without the costs associated with a warehouse of products.
Merchants will pay a monthly fee of $9.99 to be listed on the site
and will distribute their own goods. If they choose to have Amazon
process their credit card purchases, they will pay an additional
4.75 percentage of sales.
</P>
<P>
   To become the web shopping destination of choice, Amazon will
need to persuade at least some big retailers to participate, thus
giving up a portion of Internet sales and relinquishing data on
customers _ something they may be loathe to do.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles, Wall Street applauded the move, the
biggest in a series by the retailer to evolve from web book store
into a full-fledged shopping portal, by sending Amazon's stock up
23 percent to $80.75 in a day of heavy technology trading.
``Consumers win, retailers win, and Amazon wins big time,'' gushed
Chris Vroom, an e-commerce stock analyst with Thomas Weisel
Partners, summing up the investor zeitgeist.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon founder and chief executive Jeff Bezos said he wanted to
give his customers what they want most: endless choice. ``Sixteen
months ago, we were a place we could come to find books,'' he said.
``Tomorrow, we will be a place to find anything, with a capital
A.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon will be experimenting with a type of business now
dominated by other Internet behemoths. On one hand, its move to
become an unlimited shopping mall is an attempt to compete with
Internet portals like America Online and Yahoo!, which offer links
with millions of web sites and have substantially more monthly
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The changes also provide an opportunity to take away some of the
small business revenue flooding into auction sites like Ebay and
Microsoft, Excite(AT)Home and Lycos, which agreed to share their
auction listings earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any willing merchant will be able to to work with Amazon
and have indirect access to it 12 million customers, but Amazon
will exclude merchants its deems ``offensive,'' including sellers
of guns, hard-core pornography, live animals and hate literature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COPPER-INDUSTRY-ART-6     09-29 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPPER-INDUSTRY-ART-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUMP IN COPPER PRICES FUELS TAKEOVER TUSSLE IN ONCE-STAGNANT
INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Top executives from three of the nation's top copper
companies secretly convened in a room at the Trump International
Hotel in Manhattan last Friday to try to resolve one of the
nastiest, most convoluted corporate takeover fights in recent
years. When they emerged more than two hours later, it was nastier
and more convoluted than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting brought together Douglas Yearley, chairman of Phelps
Dodge, the nation's largest copper producer, with the chief
executives of two competitors, Asarco Inc. and Cyprus Amax Minerals
Co., that had agreed last July to merge with each other. Yearley,
rather than see his smaller rivals join hands, had launched his own
$2.8 billion hostile offer to acquire both of them for Phelps
Dodge. Finally, after weeks of rebuffing Yearley, Francis
McAllister of Asarco and Milton Ward of Cyprus Amax had agreed to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Yearley presented his best offer, he recalled. But he was not
willing to meet their demand _ $3.1 billion for the combination.
When the meeting broke up, Yearley was still determined to own both
companies and McAllister and Ward, eager to protect their
interests, quickly began a search for a white knight, adding yet
another player to the corporate chess game.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, a brawl in the copper industry was unthinkable.
Ailing economies in Asia and Latin America had left demand for
copper waning. Prices plummeted to a 12-year low then _ a paltry 63
cents a pound. Profits at copper mining companies tumbled, with
some companies forced to cut production to help arrest the price
slide. In fact, the industry's bleak outlook was the catalyst that
prompted McAllister to talk to Ward in the first place last May.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly that world has changed. Copper prices have risen 33
percent since then. Now, Asarco and Cyprus Amax, instead of being
left alone to embrace each other out of desperation, have, in
effect, become much more valuable prizes on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as soon as they walked out of the meeting last Friday,
the two sought a bid from Grupo Mexico, a little-known Mexican
copper producer and Asarco's largest shareholder. Grupo Mexico,
which had been eying the action for a while, immediately offered to
pay $1.03 billion in cash for Asarco, barely edging out Phelps
Dodge's $1.01 billion stock and cash offer. Asarco and Cyprus Amax,
essentially acknowledging that their original deal was no longer
viable, postponed shareholder votes scheduled for Thursday on the
merger, giving each other until Tuesday to reconsider their
options, even ditch merger plans altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The four-way fight is endemic of what has happened in stagnant
commodity-driven industries seeking some way to shore up production
without losing their shirts in the process. Low prices in
slow-growing industries, including oil, aluminum, copper and
chemicals, have made even the most unattractive partners appealing
to formidable competitors hoping to cut costs and restore
profitability to their slim-margin businesses. And with 1980s-style
corporate takeover tactics back in vogue, properties expected to
benefit from rising prices are now worth fighting over.
</P>
<P>
   ``When copper was 65 cent per pound, no one thought anyone would
have been fighting over these two companies,'' said Tom Burnett,
founder of Merger Insight, which is based in New York. ``The worm
has turned. Commodity prices are on the move and companies don't
want to be left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Asarco and Grupo Mexico said executives would not
comment on recent events. Executives at Cyprus Amax did not return
phone calls. But people involved in the talks said Cyprus Amax had
been scouting for another partner and could possibly strike a deal
soon with Phelps Dodge. Asarco too has been negotiating with other
suitors this week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McAllister of Asarco, who only became chief executive last
spring, never planned for his company to become a target,
executives close to him said. Instead his solution to Asarco's woes
was for him to act as buyer, squeezing savings out of any merged
entity. McAllister wanted to turn Asarco's fortunes around, one
person said, and he found a willing partner in the older Ward, who
was looking for a successor.
</P>
<P>
   Several people involved in the negotiations said Ward had
already approached a handful of potential merger partners for
Cyprus Amax last year. So it was with little fanfare that Ward and
McAllister announced July 15 that their companies would join forces
in a merger of equals, valued then at $737 million in stock. Stock
traders yawned at the news: the stock of both companies dropped 3
percent on the day the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at the time said the ho-hum response was because
neither of the companies' shareholders were paid a premium and they
did not understand how the duo could successfully improve profit
margins without cutting production. ``People wanted to see how
they'd perform before they bid up the stock,'' said Ali Agha, a
metals and mining analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. But the
merger did catch the attention of Yearley, who said he thought a
three-way merger with Asarco and Cyprus Amax could be just the
ticket to make Phelps Dodge the premier low-cost global copper
producer.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps Dodge is one of the few copper companies to turn a
profit. And after mulling over the combination, he said he called
both Ward and McAllister on Aug. 10 to propose they meet. The two
rebuffed his offer, saying their merger agreement barred them from
independently talking to other suitors. Still, Yearley followed up
with a letters to the chief executives and boards of directors,
requesting a reply within a week.
</P>
<P>
   None came, until the two companies publicly dismissed Phelps
Dodge's offer Aug. 20 and reconfirmed their own merger. So Phelps
Dodge went public with a sweeter offer that day, offering stock for
the pair with a combined value of $2.6 billion, a 30 percent
premium to the companies' trading prices the previous day. Five
days later, Asarco and Cyprus Amax snubbed that bid, suggesting
they would be willing to negotiate only if Phelps Dodge put a much
better deal on the table. To deter stockholder interest in the
Phelps Dodge bid, Asarco and Cyprus Amax also sweetened the terms
of their own merger, offering an extra payment of $5 a share in
cash once the deal was completed. Undaunted, Phelps Dodge launched
a tender offer for shares in the two companies Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Yearley was not the only interested party, however. Grupo
Mexico, Mexico's largest diversifed mining company, owned a 9.7
percent stake in Asarco, the largest single holding. Its chairman,
German Larrea, watched the brouhaha intensely. Not only was he
interested in getting the best price for his shares, executives
said, he also was potentially interested in a piece of the action
himself. Larrea, according to documents recently filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, held separate meetings in late
August and early September in Mexico City with both McAllister of
Asarco. Executives from Phelps Dodge also tried to woo him to vote
for their bid, Yearley said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Larrea was an attentive suitor. An executive
close to the company said Larrea ``didn't want to do something
hostile'' after Asarco's announcement in July. But now, with Phelps
Dodge in the picture, he said, Larrea ``perceived himself as the
good guy.'' A spokesman for Larrea said he was not granting
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Larrea had a problem, though. Because Grupo Mexico's stock did
not trade in the United States, it would have to offer cash. So the
company hired Chase Securities Inc. as its adviser and to arrange
financing for its bid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, enthusiasm for Phelps Dodge's offer was growing on
Wall Street, particularly after the company increased its bids
again, on Sept. 22, to a stock and cash offer worth about $2.8
billion for the two companies together. Regulators were believed to
be giving the nod to the three-way merger, despite initial
antitrust concerns, according to executives involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Asarco and Cyprus Amax, after finally agreeing to meet Yearley,
laid out several demands at the session last Friday. First, said
Yearley, they wanted Phelps Dodge to pay a 55 percent premium to
their stocks' prices prior to the Phelps Dodge bid Aug. 20. Next,
they wanted Phelps Dodge to take the risk of any antitrust
approval. They also wanted to avoid paying a $45 million breakup
fee for canceling their merger. Top executive pay packages would
have to be honored. If Yearley could agree to those terms, he had a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yearley said he agreed to almost everything except price.
Already Phelps Dodge was offering about a 40 percent premium to buy
the companies. ``We thought we'd gone far enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the skirmish took an unexpected twist later that afternoon.
A representative of Credit Suisse First Boston, which was advising
Asarco, contacted Larrea of Grupo Mexico, documents filed with the
SEC show, and made him an offer: Asarco would be willing to
consider ``an all cash firm offer for all of its shares at $26 per
share.'' Cyprus Amax was mentioned too, but Grupo was not
interested, said an executive close to the companies.
</P>
<P>
   An executive close to the talks said Asarco executives did not
know that Larrea was interested in buying the company _ despite
having had several discussions with key executives at Asarco _
describing the call as ``one of those interesting coincidences.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Grupo Mexico announced its plans to launch a tender
offer for Asarco for $26 a share, slightly higher than the $25.47
Phelps Dodge had proposed two days earlier. ``As you know, in the
past we have expressed an interest in exploring the possibility of
a combination of our two companies' operations,'' Larrea wrote in a
letter to McAllister that evening. ``Briefly put, we believe our
proposal is in the best interest of your shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   As advisers and executives sort through the offers this week, it
is not yet clear which company will buy Asarco or Cyprus, or if
they end up together.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, said one banker involved in the deal, ``It was a
good attempt that didn't work out that well.'' More to the point,
he added, ``Althought it will end up being good for shareholders,
it may not be necessarily be good for management.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
