<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: STOCK FUND SALES LAG AS BROADER MARKET COOLS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Be careful what you ask for, the saying goes, because
you may get it.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund investors who ignored the indexing phenomenon in
hopes that their fund would eventually beat the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 are getting their wish, as the average U.S. diversified equity
fund appears poised to top the index for the second consecutive
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But that is little comfort to investors, who liked things a lot
better when the S&AMP;P 500 was beating most other funds and posting 20
percent-plus annual returns.
</P>
<P>
   With the S&AMP;P index down 7.3 percent since June 30, and now up
only 4.2 percent for the year, investors' impatience is showing:
fund sales, which were strong in the second quarter, have slacked
off considerably in the last two months as the broad stock market
has drifted lower.
</P>
<P>
   Investors put $9.2 billion into stock funds in August, down 25.7
percent from July sales of $12.4 billion, according to new figures
from the Investment Company Institute, and September has shaped up
about the same. Charles Biderman, president of Trimtabs.com
Investment Research in Santa Rosa, Calif., estimates total
September stock-fund sales of $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the stock market declined, but it has once again
begun to narrow. While small-capitalization and mid-capitalization
funds performed better than large-cap funds this quarter, the much
noted rotation from growth stocks to value stocks earlier this year
has abated.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lipper Inc., large-cap growth funds lost an average
of 4.2 percent this quarter through Sept. 23, compared with an 8.3
percent drop for large-cap value funds. Mid-cap growth funds broke
even, but mid-cap value funds fell 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the bigger value funds, Vanguard's $32 billion Windsor II,
which had managed decent returns in recent years even though its
value style was out of favor, has slumped 14.7 percent so far this
quarter, hurt by big holdings in financial stocks and Waste
Management Inc. Its sister value fund, Vanguard Windsor, which
soared in the spring, is down 11.1 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For many diversified mutual fund managers, who are on track to
post single-digit returns for the first time in several years, the
pressure is on to improve results in the fourth quarter. Overall,
the average U.S. diversified equity fund fell 5.7 percent in the
quarter through Sept. 23, according to Lipper Inc., compared with a
loss by the S&AMP;P 500-stock index of 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That performance may be causing fund flows to narrow somewhat,
too. Robert Adler, president of AMG Data Services, which tracks
fund flows, estimates that 70 percent of fund sales in the first
three weeks of September went to technology funds and index funds,
which tend to draw a high proportion of money every month no matter
how they do against other funds because they are a mainstay of
401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is tightly focused on these two sectors,'' said
Adler, who noted that technology funds were one of the few bright
spots this quarter, up an average of 6 percent through Sept. 23,
according to Lipper. (Gold funds have soared this week and will
also rank among the top funds for the quarter, which ends
Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   Top-selling Vanguard said its stock funds have taken in $2.2
billion this month, up from $2 billion in August. The only fund
company with more assets under management, Fidelity Investments,
says its stock funds drew $500 million in September through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
