<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0904 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-29 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ATTENTION MUST BE PAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alton Fitzgerald White, one of the stars of the
Broadway musical ``Ragtime,'' let it be known this week that he
plans to sue the city for false arrest. And on Tuesday he made an
appearance at a parochial school in Harlem to commiserate with
youngsters who have had their own ugly encounters with the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would happen to me,'' said White, whose
prominent role in a hit Broadway show (not to mention the fact that
he was perfectly innocent) was not enough to protect him from being
arrested, handcuffed, hauled away, strip-searched and held for
several hours at the 33rd Precinct station house last July 16.
</P>
<P>
   The police were looking for armed drug dealers and would later
say that White and three other innocent men were arrested because
they happened to be in the wrong place at the wrong time. White
disagrees, pointing out that he was seized in the lobby of the
building in which he lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where was I supposed to be?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance Tuesday at Rice High School was a gesture of
support by White for students who are clean-cut, diligent,
well-behaved _ and frequently harassed by the police. School
officials said there have been dozens of encounters with the police
in which youngsters who have done nothing wrong have been detained,
frisked, handcuffed and otherwise abused.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are school officials immune. In a story about this problem
that ran in March, The New York Times' Kit Roane wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Administrators said that Brother Tyrone Davis, who teaches
business law at the school and is the executive director of the
archdiocese's office of black ministry, has grown so tired of being
stopped by the police that he now rarely leaves work without
donning his religious collar. Others, like McBean (Damarr McBean, a
15-year-old honors student) say they just try to stay indoors.''
</P>
<P>
   The encounters can be tragic. Leroy Jermaine Grant, a Rice
graduate, was one of three young men shot and wounded by state
troopers during a traffic stop on the New Jersey Turnpike last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is an all-boys school and the only Catholic high school in
Harlem. The problems faced by its students are the same problems
faced by so many black and Latino kids _ and adults _ throughout
the city and the nation. We are not talking about criminals here.
We are talking about only those who behave themselves and obey the
law. We are talking about solid citizens who are irresponsibly
targeted and cruelly mistreated by the police, largely because they
are black or Latino.
</P>
<P>
   This systematic outrage continues because not enough responsible
adults _ black or white _ have been willing to step forward and
declare that it must cease.
</P>
<P>
   During his appearance at Rice, White described how, with his
neighbors looking on, he was made to kneel in the vestibule of his
building with his hands cuffed behind his back. He was told by the
police to ``face the wall'' and keep his mouth shut. He was not
allowed to ask any questions or to assert his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had gotten irate I could have been killed,'' he said.
``It was beyond humiliating.''
</P>
<P>
   As he knelt on the cold tile floor, he said, he realized that in
the eyes of the police he was not a good guy, a decent and honest
man, a star in a hit show. None of that. He was a complete nobody,
just another black man with no rights and no claim to respectful
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'm dealing with now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White said he was filing the lawsuit and speaking out publicly
because he wants to call as much attention to the problem of police
misconduct as he can. ``I am an artist, not an activist,'' he said.
But he was so shocked and so devastated by his arrest and
incarceration that he felt that he could no longer remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening,'' he said, ``right now, to someone who has
no voice. People are tired of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The principal of Rice High, Orlando Gober, agreed. ``We have
several young men sitting right here who have been stopped by the
police in the past several months,'' he said. He added that those
youngsters felt as White did when he was arrested _ humiliated and
powerless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a reality,'' said Gober. ``A very sad, sick reality. But
it is reality nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-PROTEST-NY     09-29 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE BREAK UP ANIT-MILOSEVIC DEMONSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Riot police swinging batons broke up a
peaceful demonstration on Wednesday night, preventing some 20,000
demonstrators from marching to the suburb where President Slobodan
Milosevic lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 people were injured, including at least five reporters,
cameramen and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to break up the march was a clear departure from
police tactics since daily demonstrations began Sept. 21. While the
police action is likely to swell what has been a disappointing
number of daily demonstrators, it also seemed intended to advertise
and underline Milosevic's determination to use force to hold on to
his job.
</P>
<P>
   During the last major demonstrations in the winter of 1996-97,
which lasted 88 days, police were careful not to confront marchers.
Clearly, Milosevic wants no repetition of that three-month
embarrassment, which ended when he accepted opposition victories in
local elections and fired the police and television chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Alliance for Change said on Wednesday night that
although they wanted to test the police, they did not want
violence. They said the purpose of the march was designed to draw
more people to these nightly rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we're playing with dangerous stuff,'' said Milan
Protic, one of the Alliance leaders, before the police charged. But
in speeches after the march, before a thin and shaken crowd in
Belgrade's Square of the Republic, Protic and Zoran Djindjic,
leader of the Democratic Party, appealed to demonstrators not to
confront the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a marathon,'' Djindjic said. ``I beg of you to be more
wise than they are.'' But he also noted with glee: ``The regime
showed that they are more scared of us than we thought an hour
ago.'' And he announced that demonstrators would make the same
march again on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a tense standoff between demonstrators and police
blocking Kneza Milosa Street, in front of the Defense Ministry
building still blasted from NATO bombs. Opposition leaders, after
talking to the police, urged their followers to turn up another
route.
</P>
<P>
   But the marchers did not follow them, so the leaders returned to
sit in front of police lines, to prevent a confrontation and urged
protesters to sit. After about 20 minutes, 75 riot police then
marched down Nemanjina Street and started to drive the marchers
back with their shields and batons.
</P>
<P>
   A Djindjic bodyguard, Vlada, was badly beaten on the head, and
with an eye swollen shut, said on Wednesday night of Milosevic:
``It won't be that easy to make him leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday night's clash, leaders of the divided political
opposition to Milosevic moved to make another effort to create a
common front around the issue of early elections.
</P>
<P>
   With only moderate turnouts at their nightly rallies, the
leaders of the Alliance for Change are reluctantly seeking a
rapprochement with Vuk Draskovic, who runs the largest opposition
party, the Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance is being pushed to do so by Dragoslav Avramovic,
the former central banker who is their choice for prime minister in
any transitional government. Avramovic believes, he said in an
interview, that Milosevic can easily ignore a divided opposition,
and that the turnouts thus far have been encouraging but
insufficient to bring significant pressure on the regime.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at Avramovic's instigation, all the parties will
attend a ``round table'' on necessary conditions for free and fair
elections. If the round table succeeds, then Draskovic says he will
throw his support to rallies intended to press for early elections,
as the best and only effective way to oust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance has been insistent that Milosevic must resign
first, if there would be any chance of fair elections. But their
campaign thus far shows no sign of bringing about any resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has refused to join these rallies, calling them
``pointless'' and ``a waste of time.'' He has not lent them his
party's organizational skills or helped publicize them on the
Belgrade city television station he controls, Studio B.
</P>
<P>
   But Studio B covered Wednesday night's clashes, and the violence
will add pressure on Draskovic, once known for his fiery boldness
in earlier demonstrations, to join these.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-MAO-PAINTER-ART     09-29 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MAO-PAINTER-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTING, REPAINTING MAO FOR DECADES: LOW-PROFILE ARTIST RECALLS
WITH PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ For 50 years, ever since the Chinese Communist Party
came to power, a portrait of Mao has loomed over Tiananmen Square
in the heart of the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   To the countless millions who have passed under Mao's gaze, the
portrait has seemed to preside over the nation unchanged, sturdy as
a piece of Communist architecture, no matter how drastically China
itself was being transformed.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, so much about Chinese officialdom was kept
secret that even the circumstances surrounding the nation's most
prominent painting were considered off-limits to the curious.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a harmless step away from the zip-lipped past, Wang
Qizhi can openly admit that he painted Mao's portrait for 27 years.
Damage from sunlight and smog requires the Tiananmen portrait to be
replaced twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other Chinese in the early years of the People's
Republic, Wang labored behind the scenes like an industrious ant,
following orders, suppressing all urge to show any individuality
and keeping his mouth shut about what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was performing an important task for the good of the
country,'' said Wang, a slender, white-haired retiree of 72.
``There was no question about what I thought personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Wang had pangs of pride when he rode through Tiananmen
Square on his bicycle and glanced up to see his painting at the
crown of the majestic Gate of Heavenly Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few of his acquaintances knew what he did, because anything
to do with Mao or his image was so politically sensitive that he
was ordered not to talk about his job. So Wang insists that his
personal achievement was always subsumed by a sense of the
burdensome importance of his daily task.
</P>
<P>
   As the 50th anniversary of Communist rule approaches on Oct. 1
and many marvel at the vast changes _ for better and worse _ that
China has experienced in a tumultuous half-century, people like
Wang express appreciation for something that has not changed, but
offers a least a thread of continuity.
</P>
<P>
   To many Chinese, Mao's portrait is an important political symbol
that reflects the strength and independence that China gained in
1949, even if it also embodies the nationalist pride that allowed
China to fall into a leftist frenzy in subsequent decades with
terrible damage to the nation's economic, social and political
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Mao may have so single-mindedly pursued his vision of an
egalitarian state _ and personal political power _ that he did not
seem to care how many millions died or were displaced in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even today, many more Chinese seem to admire Mao than to
hate him. A remarkably large number are nostalgic for what they
remember as the idealism and collective fervor of his era, despite
the poverty they endured at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Wang has no equivocation; he is a diehard Mao fan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't let us say a bad word about Mao in the house,'' said
Wang's son, Wang Yan, who is a painter himself. ``We have to go
outside if we want to curse Mao.''
</P>
<P>
   The son does indeed curse Mao outside, seeing the political
trauma of that era, which ended with Mao's death in 1976, as
unnecessarily damaging many of China's finest traditions, like
painting, the family avocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paint in the traditional Chinese style, like my father and
my grandfather,'' he said. ``In Mao's era, traditional painting was
criticized and banned. How can that make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many painters, writers and academics were attacked by the far
left during the 1960s, when radical politics engulfed Beijing. But
Wang Qizhi was protected by the authorities because there was
suddenly so much demand for his work, since Mao's portrait was
plastered all over the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Every major workplace in Beijing wanted its own original, and
they had to be painted by Wang or the one other man officially
approved to produce portraits of the Great Helmsman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things were really busy, he would paint the bottom half
and I would paint the top,'' Wang said. ``We put a scaffolding
across the middle. The wart on Mao's chin marked the halfway
point.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, after Wang had already been painting Mao portraits for
15 years, the Central Committee of the Communist Party decreed that
the portrait be changed, apparently under pressure from radical Red
Guards who objected that the partial side view of Mao showed only
one of his ears, suggesting that he was listening to only one
political faction.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it may sound funny that members of an intensely
intolerant group insisted that their leader be portrayed as
even-eared. But the portrait that was adopted that year remains the
version that has hung in Tiananmen Square for more than 30 years
and is still there today.
</P>
<P>
   Wang said he was deeply upset in 1989, though he was retired by
then, when three men in the Tiananmen protest movement splashed
paint on Mao's portrait, a move denounced by most student
protesters at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defacing the portrait is a crime,'' Wang said gravely. ``They
should have received the harshest punishment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the record, the three men _ a bus company employee, a
journalist and a schoolteacher, all from Mao's home province of
Hunan _ were sentenced to prison terms of 16 years, 20 years and
life, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Lest it be overlooked, Wang pointed out that the task of
painting a 20-foot-high portrait is not easy. The painter must
constantly be stepping back far enough to take a look, and with
such a huge portrait, Wang had to step back 100 feet. So he was
constantly climbing and descending a scaffolding, for perspective.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as China itself takes a step back to look at itself
after 50 years, it may be hard to get a clear perspective or focus
on a nation in the middle of wrenching change from a Communist
system to a new, ill-defined one. As confusing as the outlook may
be, Wang points out that material life is far more comfortable,
just as painting the Mao portrait is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it's easy,'' Wang said. ``They have this big automatic
contraption that moves up and down. Not in my day. We had it much
harder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
