<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-BISHOP-(TRIMS)-     09-29 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-BISHOP-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP CREDITED WITH CURBING VIOLENCE IN EAST TIMOR'S SECOND CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAUCAU, East Timor _ Unexpectedly from around the corner, a
group of smiling teen-age girls appeared Wednesday afternoon,
singing a United Nations song: ``Brothers and sisters of East
Timor, it's time to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, here in East Timor's second city, people were
shopping at a small outdoor market. Power and water were operating
normally. In the lovely Portuguese-built center of town, only one
building had been burned.
</P>
<P>
   This is the East Timor that could have been, if armed men had
not rampaged through the territory this month looting, burning and
depopulating almost every town and village.
</P>
<P>
   With desolation the norm throughout East Timor, there is an
unreal, ``through the looking glass'' feel to Baucau.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The contrast with other cities was heightened Wednesday when
soldiers in the capital, Dili, discovered nine charred bodies in
the back of a pickup truck in a junkyard on the western outskirts.
Military officers said additional bodies had been lying in the
surrounding bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Though there was no initial information on who they were or who
had killed them, the nine bodies, lying in a grotesque tangle in
the small white truck, were evidence of what is apparently the
largest-scale atrocity discovered to date from the recent weeks of
terror.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the man who appears to have saved Baucau from
destruction, the Roman Catholic bishop, Basilio do Nascimento,
slipped off his sandals as he received visitors in his cool
hillside residence. His electric clock ticked quietly on the wall,
and the smell of cooking floated from his kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Such comfort and normalcy contrasted with the fate of his fellow
bishop, Carlos Belo, the winner of the Nobel Prize for peace in
1996, whose residence in Dili was burned and who was forced to flee
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, do Nascimento said, with Dili a charred
ruin 80 miles to the west, Baucau, a city of 27,000, could become
the temporary capital of the emerging new nation of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   His visitors Wednesday included representatives of the United
Nations, which has just opened an office in Baucau _ with an
initial staff of eight _ its first in East Timor outside Dili.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One of the representatives, Nicholas Birnback, said he was
stunned to hear the teen-aged girls singing the U.N. song, a sign
that at least some of the optimism that had flourished before this
month of terror was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The song was written to advertise the Aug. 30 referendum in
which nearly 80 percent of the people of East Timor voted for
independence from Indonesia, which invaded it in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is preparing to run a transitional
administration for two to three years in East Timor if the
Indonesian Parliament endorses the independence vote, as expected,
in October.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop, whose strong baritone amplifies his soft words,
professed to be puzzled that Baucau escaped other towns' fate.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody else here seemed to have any doubt. For months before
the referendum, the bishop held weekly consultations that included
representatives of the militia, of the military, of
pro-independence forces and of the local government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we tried to do something in this sense,'' the bishop
said. ``There was very good cooperation among all of us, it is
true. There was a great deal of goodwill among all of these people.
If we collaborated to preserve Baucau from all this catastrophe, I
am very glad.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that the city was entirely spared. In the
outer sector known as New Baucau, he said, about 50 buildings were
burned, only two of them private residences. As in other cities
government buildings were burned and the main marketplace was razed
along with many surrounding shops.
</P>
<P>
   And as in other cities, the militias terrorized many residents
into fleeing into the hills. But the residents are returning now in
large numbers and this is perhaps the only place in East Timor
where people feel safe enough to stroll the streets in the cool
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop seemed to confirm a report here that he had paid off
the departing Indonesian military not to destroy the power station,
as it did when it pulled out of many other towns. ``Before their
departure, they sold us oil,'' he said. ``We bought some oil from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In an embryonic sign that the East Timorese are beginning to
assert control over their land for the first time in centuries,
motor bikes could be seen in town with riders carrying two-way
radios _ a step towards filling a security vacuum left by the
withdrawing Indonesian military and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main problem at this moment is concerning authority,'' the
bishop said. ``We have no power and we have no control.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bishop suggested to his U.N. visitors Wednesday that they
coordinate their police activities with the men on the motorcycles
_ representatives of the pro-independence forces that will form the
core of a future East Timorese government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main problem at this moment is concerning authority,'' he
said. ``We have no power and we have no control.''
</P>
<P>
   But like so much else in a newly free East Timor _ like the
burned and flattened homes that can be seen all along the road from
Dili to Baucau _ the country's laws and system of justice will have
to be constructed from the bare foundations.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. official, Alan Castle, who was visiting Wednesday to put
the first four unarmed foreign police officers in place, said the
four U.N. officers, all from the Philippines, would be empowered to
carry out the full range of law enforcement activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the problem they will run into is what laws apply,'' he
said. ``Yes, you can hold someone in custody. But don't ask me
under what real power. And don't ask me where they would hold
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
