<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA STARTS TO TAKE HARD LINE AGAINST ILLEGAL CHINESE
IMMIGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)   (bl)  
 By JAMES BROOKE  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT HARDY, British Columbia _ When the Canadian navy made a
group of undocumented Chinese migrants get off a ship here
recently, a local man brought his dogs to the dock and encouraged
them to bark at the men and women wrapped in blankets against the
cold.
</P>
<P>
   For Canadian officials, the confrontation represented one
victory in what they say is a rapidly growing effort to smuggle in
illegal immigrants. This summer alone, they confiscated four
trawlers and detained 560 undocumented Chinese citizens who wanted
to make Canada their home.
</P>
<P>
   Western Canada is only one destination in a pan-Pacific surge
this year in illegal Chinese migrants. In the last 16 months, U.S.
Coast Guard ships have intercepted 20 ships carrying undocumented
Chinese in U.S. territorial waters around Guam. In the last six
months, Australia has intercepted 21 boatloads of illegal migrants,
primarily Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now experiencing the largest smuggling operation ever
experienced in Canada,'' Rob Johnston, manager of immigration
enforcement here, told reporters recently.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Weeks, an Australian diplomat in Ottawa, said of Canada's
sudden concern: ``It's deja vu. The element of the public debate
and concern is very similar to Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   As Australia, the United States and Canada increasingly share
intelligence about vessels believed to be carrying migrants from
southeastern China, Canada has started to take the harder line
traditional in the other two countries.
</P>
<P>
   After the first Chinese ship was intercepted, on July 20, the
authorities in Vancouver released 74 immigrants, pending resolution
of their petitions for refugee status. Within a month, half had
disappeared, presumably for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Canada has adopted a policy of detaining all
undocumented passengers on vessels from China. Sentiment for
immediately deporting them is markedly higher in western Canada
than in provinces on the Atlantic seaboard, opinion polls indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's population is 20 percent ethnic Chinese, and many of
these Chinese-Canadians fear that each new boatload batters a
carefully constructed racial tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vancouver is a very tolerant society,'' said Derick Y.H.
Cheng, chairman of the Chinese Cultural Center there. ``We fear
this will make a backlash, give people the stereotype that Chinese
do not abide by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Former British Columbia Premier Bill Vander Zalm has jumped back
into politics, starting his campaign for Parliament by saying that
the federal government would pay attention to the immigration issue
only if all the illegal Chinese immigrants detained in the region
were shipped to Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure you would get some action then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian newspapers portray the boatloads of migrants, largely
from Fujian province, as job-seekers rather than freedom-seekers.
Not long ago, Elinor Caplan, Canada's new immigration minister,
toured a Vancouver Island navy base where 225 immigrants are
detained and said at a packed news conference: ``We are
intercepting, boarding and apprehending those ships. We are then
using greater powers of detention to insure people on the boat do
not flee. The system is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials are also reaching across the Pacific, asking
Chinese authorities to help.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit meeting
in New Zealand, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien discussed the
migration problem with Chinese President Jiang Zemin. ``I told him
we needed collaboration because they could hopefully stop the
departure of the ships from the coast of China that are coming to
our coast,'' Chretien said later. ``He recognized that, and said he
was willing to collaborate with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-ASIANS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-29 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ASIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S DISDAIN FOR FOREIGNERS SURFACES IN CRIME ANXIETIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT35 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ With a graph of its sales mirroring the path of lemmings
falling from a cliff, Japan's largest lockmaker, Miwa Co., settled
on a recent ad strategy that fanned Japanese fears of crime, and
spiced it with a foreign twist.
</P>
<P>
   The insecurity spreading through the society, the advertisements
announce, is due to Chinese ``theft gangs'' that maintain ``secret
bases'' in the country. ``The damage by foreign theft gangs is
increasing swiftly now,'' one ad reads in boldface. ``It is time to
invest in safety like those in America and Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign, which brought a burst of interest in Miwa
locks, offers a window on a deep streak in Japanese society to look
askance at most things foreign, especially fellow Asians.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials deny that their advertisements reflect any
racism. A spokesman said, moreover, what the police confirm: that
crime by foreigners in general, and that crime by Chinese in
particular, is on the increase.
</P>
<P>
   For obvious reasons, what the advertisements do not say but the
police do is that over all the crime problem in Japan, a society
known for its safety, is considered to be well under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been expecting this kind of crime to come to Japan,
because the world is becoming borderless, and so crime is becoming
borderless too,'' said Yukio Akamatsu, the official responsible for
the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With foreigners making up less than 1 percent of the population,
Japan remains determinedly monoethnic and continuously on guard
against any ``corruption'' of its purity by fellow East Asians.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese and Koreans living in this country have long complained
that they have difficulty finding housing because of the prejudices
of Japanese landlords. Visa applications by Asians are said by many
to receive closer scrutiny than those of others, ostensibly for
fear of allowing a proliferation of aliens who outwardly resemble
Japanese. And in interviews, people here freely attribute problems
to the foreigners in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese experts on racial stereotypes say that whatever the
most recent police statistics indicate, a tendency to point a
finger at Chinese reflects a mixture of fear and contempt that has
been present since a failed Mongol invasion of Japan in the 15th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say that since its collision with the West toward
the middle of the 19th century, Japan has used Westerners and
Asians as flip sides of the same coin of racial complexes,
struggling to ``catch up'' to the one while despising the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude to this is very complicated, and discussion is
kind of taboo,'' said Hiroyoshi Ishikawa, a professor at Seijo
University in Tokyo. ``The Japanese government had a very conscious
effort to copy the customs of Europeans first, and then
Americans,'' he added. ``And in the depths of their hearts, the
Japanese people have had some kind of contempt for the Chinese and
the Koreans. Since the end of the 19th century, the attitude has
been whites are superior, other Asians are inferior.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Japanese seem openly conscious of these attitudes, or seem
to have considered that airs of superiority and aloofness may have
helped lead Japan into its brutal colonial adventurism in Asia,
which ended disastrously in World War II. Few also seem to consider
the unfair impact of negative stereotypes of foreigners on the
lives of the Asians and other non-Westerners who live here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many illegal aliens are causing crimes, but the media reports
often say it is suspected that the culprits are Chinese, even when
the facts aren't known,'' said Chiu Xiong Yin, president of the
Tokyo Association of Chinese Residents. ``The media seems to be
influenced by discriminatory feelings toward Chinese people: they
take tiny incidents and blow them up into huge affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to live as a Chinese in Japan. We are so
tired of these things, but we try not to make our anger public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
