<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-900     09-29 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING TO REVITALIZE HIS CAMPAIGN, GORE MOVES HEADQUARTERS TO
TENNESSEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, acknowledging that he faces
a serious challenge for the Democratic presidential nomination,
announced Wednesday that he was relocating his campaign
headquarters from Washington to his home state of Tennessee and
paring back a top-heavy campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Nashville is part of a broad strategy that his aides
hope will symbolize a break from the Beltway _ and the Clinton
administration. And it comes in response to the steady rise in the
polls, and in the public imagination, of former Sen. Bill Bradley
of New Jersey, the sole Democrat who dared challenge Gore and his
vast institutional apparatus for the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Gore backers have been dispirited by national polls
that show Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner,
sustaining a strong lead that Gore has been unable to dent.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the Gore campaign has only vaguely focused on Bush
and acted as if Bradley did not exist. But the former basketball
star has demonstrated his ability to raise serious money. And now
that Bradley has drawn even with Gore in opinion polls in key
states like New York and New Hampshire, the Gore camp can no longer
ignore the Bradley threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the challenge for the nomination has changed,''
Gore acknowledged Wednesday, noting that the Bradley camp had
established ``a baseline of competence and credibility.'' He added:
``We're in a completely new campaign. So we're going to adapt to it
and adjust to it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the goals is to cut expenses by limiting the number and
salaries of senior staffers. The need to conserve money is a
consequence of Gore's lackluster fund raising: He collected an
unimpressive $6.5 million in the last three months and has spent
almost all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's cash has been drained in part by efforts to raise money
and build state organizations. But that focus has resulted in
negative news accounts of a bulging campaign top-heavy with
Washington consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The move will mean lower rents in Nashville and will provide a
face-saving way for some of Gore's high-priced talent to leave the
campaign without being fired.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is reporting that it has just $10 million in cash
on hand. Bradley's campaign refused to divulge how much it raised
in the last quarter and how much it has on hand, but the
expectation is that in financial reports to be made public on
Thursday, he will show he is competitive with Gore. Three months
ago, the Gore campaign said it had $9.4 million on hand; Bradley
had $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The move to Nashville is also part of a broader effort to
revitalize the campaign. Other elements include an accelerated
schedule of debates with Bradley to showcase the vice president's
verbal skills, an emphasis on meetings with smaller and less formal
groups and a rejiggered stump speech designed to show a more
passionate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   More tactical plans include working aggressively behind the
scenes to try to win the endorsement of groups that Bradley has so
far neutralized, most prominently the AFL-CIO, which is meeting in
California in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significantly, the new campaign seeks to feature a
new Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Asked over the weekend how he planned to overcome the challenges
he faces, a suddenly plain-speaking Gore, stung by Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan's devastating pronouncement last week that he is
unelectable, had a blunt and urgent answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoeleather and hard work and a lot of handshaking and talking
with people one on one and getting out of this 4-by-4 that I ride
around in and walking down the sidewalks and Main streets and going
in stores and coffee shops and looking voters in the eye and
talking to them one by one,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley dryly noted Gore's abrupt change in strategy,
particularly the vice president's apparent eagerness to debate.
``For the last 10 months, the vice president and his campaign have
been ignoring me and now they want to debate me,'' he said while
campaigning in California. ``I think that shows we're making some
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the address of Gore's headquarters mattered little.
What the move shows, he said, is ``the Democratic side is clearly
up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers in and out of Washington have said that Gore needs to
shed the trappings of the vice presidency, and the move to
Tennessee, where he spent his boyhood summers, should help him do
that.
</P>
<P>
   The move reflects the broader need for Gore to project some of
the ``outsider'' status that has helped propel the Bradley
campaign. It also signals Gore's need to establish a presence in
the South, where Bush looms with a strong advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee itself, a poll conducted Sept. 16 for the National
Republican Senatorial Committee found Bush leading Gore among
registered voters, 51 percent to 42 percent. In the 17 states that
make up the South, a new poll conducted for the American
Association of Health Plans showed Bush leading Gore 53 percent to
35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the campaign was moving ``lock, stock and barrel to
Nashville so that we can get closer to the American people, closer
to the grassroots and out of the Beltway and into the heartland.''
He said he would formally open a Nashville office next Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers, including President Clinton, have long been
telling him that he needs to connect better with voters. They want
him in intimate exchanges with people about what really matters in
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who spent more than an hour on Sunday with 10 people in a
livingroom in the tiny outpost of Berlin, N.H., said Wednesday that
he would go ``directly to the voters in small groups, without
intermediaries, responding to their questions, telling them about
my vision for the future, asking for their ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also been told to sharpen his message, reveal some
passion and try to appear as often as possible with his playful,
spontaneous wife, Tipper, to show that he is a ``real person,'' a
family man _ and not Bill Clinton. Even so, his advisers are
divided over how much he should try to separate himself from his
political patron. A base more than 500 miles from Washington could
help keep at a distance the Clinton scandal, and the shadow it
casts over a Gore candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   His stump speech now includes a reference to an earlier period
in his life when he was ``disillusioned'' with politics, the
result, he says, of the Vietnam War, Watergate and watching his
father, a senator from Tennessee, go down to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   With these glancing references to the tumultuous 1960s and '70s,
Gore hopes to begin to add some complexity to his personal
narrative and to counter the impression that he has been a
politician and Washington insider all his life.
</P>
<P>
   Some Gore advisers say the Bradley surge is a blessing in
disguise. ``It's better than shadow-boxing out there by
ourselves,'' said one. It has energized the candidate and his
campaign staff and cast them in a role that Americans love: that of
underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is ready to fight,'' said Tony Coelho, his campaign
manager. ``We've unshackled him. We've liberated him.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not entirely. Gore is still a cautious politician. While
he is taking some stands that may be popular locally but are risky
nationally, like supporting timber cutting in New Hampshire's White
Mountains, he still refuses to say whether he believes Clinton was
right to grant clemency to a group of imprisoned Puerto Rican
nationalists. ``I have not reviewed the record,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He can also signal an air of desperation. In a recent speech to
Democratic activists, he blurted out: ``I care.'' The words
inadvertently recalled former President George Bush's struggle to
sympathize with voters. ``Message: I care,'' Bush had said in 1992,
drawing ridicule for needing to spell out what he had been unable
to convey.
</P>
<P>
   Gore often turns to this none-too-subtle approach as he seems to
regard his listeners as interest groups. ``I am FOR the veterans!''
he will announce. Or, as he said last week: ``For the
environmentalists here, the first word I learned to spell was green
_ G-R-E-E-N!''
</P>
<P>
   The move to Nashville adds to the risk that Gore will be seen as
desperate. ``It redefines the `Hail Mary,''' said one Republican
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats perceived the move as a welcome sign that
Gore was ready to take control of his campaign and put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It signals a change in attitude,'' said James Carville, the
Democratic consultant who ran Clinton's insurgent campaign from
Little Rock, Ark., in 1992. ``And it allows you to make changes, to
do things you need to do underneath without creating a three- or
four-day brouhaha,'' he said, referring to the downsizing of the
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this move to be an opportunity for transformation,''
Gore said
</P>
<P>
   Part of that transformation will be a willingness to challenge
Bradley directly and to begin drawing contrasts with a man he has
not mentioned by name until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to engage Bradley on specific issues, including
education, health care and the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
