   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN, 09-29 --
Vice President Al Gore speaks to reporters from his campaign
headquarters on Wednesday. Acknowledging he is in a tough battle
with former Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic presidential
nomination, Gore announced Wednesday he was moving his campaign
headquarters to Nashville, Tenn., and challenged Bradley to a
series of debates. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LANGHORNE, Pa. -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- BOGUS-POKEMON, 09-29
-- A display of some Pokemon cards at the traveling Pokemon Show in
April. The booming popularity of Pokemon monsters is drawing
counterfeiters. The Pokemon fad has become so hot that both
children and their parents are shelling out as much as $100 for
individual cards on the secondary market. Packets of 11 are
supposed to retail for $2.99. (Jeff Zelevansky/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- KIOSK-BLUES-BOS,
09-29 -- Tom Fosnot reads an a newspaper at Out-of-Town News on
Harvard Square. The world-famous newsstand packed with more than
3,000 different newspapers and magazines from Africa to South
America, is falling victim to an era where readers are trading
their ink-stained fingertips for instant, fresh news on the World
Wide Web. Even though magazine sales are steady, the kiosk is
having to rely more on other things to make a buck such as candies,
souvenirs, paperbacks, lottery tickets, and film. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- COFFEE-HISTORIAN-BOS, 09-29
-- Mark Pendergrast, author of ``Uncommon Grounds: The History of
Coffee and How It Transformed Our World,'' with a decaf cappuccino
at Borders bookstore cafe last week. Pendergrast's sprawling
522-page book covers a wide variety of angles of the commodity,
ranging from the seriously sociopolitical to the purely whimsical.
(Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GILMANTON, N.H. -- Sept. 29, 1999 --
EXTREME-ATHLETES-BOS, 09-29 -- From left, Travis Tripp, Todd Audet
and Kyle and Tim Cayer start their run which will reach speeds of
some 72 miles per hour in a sport called street luge. Across the
nation, extreme athletes are getting braver, bolder, and crazier.
Extreme sports have taken on a whole new degree of extremity, it
seems, and today, ``extreme'' is what used to be thought of as
``insane.'' (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 29, 1999 --
CHILD-WEB-SHOPPERS-BOS, 09-29 -- Aaron Day , an E-Commerce
consultant with Iconomy.com, stands in front of a projection of his
company's web site. Iconomy.com is expected to announce a strategic
alliance this week that may make it easier for children and teens
to buy books, CDs, and other items on line.(Dominic Chavez/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- MILLENNIUM-COX, 09-29 --
George Stevens, Jr., left, co-producer of ``American's Millennium,
A Celebration for the Nation,'' points out how the Lincoln Memorial
will be decorated for the New Year's celebration to first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Anthony Williams of Washington,
D.C., right, on Wednesday. Promising ``no ordinary party'' for ``no
ordinary time,'' first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on Tuesday
invited America to a Y2K bash in the nation's capital. (Photo by
Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
