<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- BOOK-TALK, 09-29 -- Mary
Gordon doesn't read reviews of her books. ``A good review never
feels as good as a bad one feels bad,'' she says. ``I never want to
know either way.'' (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- REAGAN-BOOK-REVIEW-B&AMP;W,
09-29 --Edmund Morris, author of the long-awaited ``Dutch: A Memoir
of Ronald Reagan.'' Morris seems at pains to animate a life that in
an earlier treatment, that of Reagan's autobiography, ``An American
Life,'' produced what Morris himself calls ``the most boring book
of its kind since Herbert Hoover's 'Challenge to Liberty.' ``
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- CALIF-THEATER, 09-28 --
David Hyde Pierce, left, and Lea DeLaria of ``Boys From Syracuse,''
Rodgers and Hart's 1938 musical sendup of mistaken identity in
ancient Greece. For Pierce, it's his first musical comedy since a
stint in ``HMS Pinafore'' in his first term at Yale. He is
beginning his seventh season in his Emmy-award winning role as Dr.
Niles Crane on NBC's ``Frasier.'' (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SHANGHAI, China -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- CHINA-MAO-PAINTER,
09-29 --Wang Qizhi, who for 27 years secretly painted the portrait
of Mao that hangs in Tiananmen Square. Like many Chinese in the
early years of the People's Republic, he labored behind the scenes,
following orders, suppressing individuality and keeping his mouth
shut about what he did. ``I felt I was performing an important task
for the good of the country,'' says Wang, a slender, white-haired
retiree of 72. (Seth faison/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
