Wednesday, with the museum claiming that artistic expression is
protected by the First Amendment and the city saying taxpayers are
not required to pay for offensive exhibits. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) VASILIYEVKA, Russia -- Sept. 29, 1999 --
RUSSIA-POTATOWARS-COX, 9-29 -- Valentina Dolgopyatova, 64, a
grandmother, sits at the edge of her potato patch where she killed
her neighbor this summer after catching him digging up her crops.
With Russia's swelling ranks of poor, four of every 10 Russians
live below the poverty line, Dolgopyatova and tens of millions of
Russians depend on their small garden plots for survival. Police
declined to prosecute her, claiming that she acted in self-defense.
(Charles W. Holmes/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- NY-MUSEUM, 09-29 -- The
banners are up Wendesday in front of the Brooklyn Museum
advertising its upcoming controversial exhibit, ``Sensation.'' The
battle over opening the exhibt moved into the courts on Wednesday,
with the museum claiming that artistic expression is protected by
the First Amendment and the city saying taxpayers are not required
to pay for offensive exhibits. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 09-29
-- If you do decide to use pressure-treated lumber for a project,
it is important to choose the boards carefully, observe all safety
precautions and wear safety gear. Wear gloves when handling the
lumber, and look for pieces with the fewest number of splits, wanes
and knots. Look carefully at the surface of the boards; they should
be free of any crystalline chemical residue. Try to choose dry
lumber. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- CIR-MUNICIPAL-SITES-2-B&AMP;W,
09-29 -- Many cities, like New York, Indianapolis and San Carlos,
Calif., are making municipal services available online. This trend
toward electronic government means that residents of many areas may
soon not have to travel downtown to pay parking fines or apply for
things like building permits. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) DURHAM, N.C. -- Sept. 29, 1999 -- CIR-DUKE-STUDENTS,
09-29 -- Nevin Fouts, fourth from left, associate dean for
information technology, with others in a project at Duke
University's Fuqua School of Business that tests innovative
electronic devices in actual classroom use. The Duke project poses
risks for the university, which is hoping that the experiments will
not be a distraction. (Jenny Warburg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
