<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1031 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-AMAZON-ZSHOPS-SPI &LR;      09-29 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-ZSHOPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM SUDDENLY OFFERS 500,000 NEW THINGS TO BUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Got a taste for turducken, that distinctive Cajun
assemblage of turkey, duck and chicken? Feeling the need for a
really distinctive cookie cutter? Try Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The new brick-red tab appearing today on Amazon's
distinctive home page means the world's largest Internet retailer
has expanded again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Seattle's Amazon has added a department called
zShops, which opens the company's Web site to any individual or
company, large or small, that wants to sell online. zShops' launch
today makes 500,000 new items available immediately to Amazon's 12
million shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   These include exotic edibles from Fran's Chocolates and Cajun
Specialty Meats, cookie cutters from Kitchen Collectibles, car
parts, maternity clothes, golf clubs, dolls, and time-share resort
accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Bigelow, owner of Fran's Chocolates in Seattle, said it was
easy to promote her ``carefully and lovingly made'' hand-dipped
candy on the small company's own Web site, but harder to handle the
mechanics of selling it there. Amazon's willingness to undertake
those details persuaded her to become one of the first zShops.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts Wednesday seemed to agree Amazon's latest venture is a
good idea _ for the world's largest Internet retailer as well as
for shops like Fran's.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they said, it will enhance Amazon's stature as the
preeminent online shopping destination, making it a potentially
limitless resource for customers. At the same time, zShops will
create a low-cost revenue stream that may hasten the day
four-year-old Amazon stops losing money.
</P>
<P>
   The department will also give Amazon additional valuable
credit-card data about shoppers' buying patterns. And a new search
engine associated with zShops will reveal who wants to buy what,
guiding Amazon's future expansion efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good move for many reasons,'' said Sue Rothberg, a
senior analyst with Gomez Advisors Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Investors cheered the news, sending the stock up 23 percent.
Shares gained 14.875 to end the session at 80.75.
</P>
<P>
   To use zShops, a person or organization pays Amazon a fee of
$9.99 to list up to 3,000 items, or 10 cents per item for fewer
than 100 items.For each sale by a zShop, Amazon collects another
fee, starting at five percent of the sale price.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers must handle their own inventories and shipping. But for
an additional charge to sellers _ $.60 plus 4.75 percent of the
price _ Amazon will process each credit-card transaction,
eliminating checks, money orders and the hassle and insecurity that
consumers and businesses alike may associate with electronic
commerce. Amazon will extend its 1-Click shopping cart service to
zShops at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   In case of fraud or dissatisfaction by either buyer or seller,
Amazon will pay up to $250, or up to $1,000 if it handled the
transaction. Having to stand behind sales by merchants it doesn't
know could tarnish Amazon's good name, a possibility that Ken
Cassar, an analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York, sees as
a greater threat to Amazon than the policy's financial or staffing
impacts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the data Amazon acquires by handling all these additional
credit-card transactions will give it new insights into who buys
what, and how often. Amazon is already well-known for using such
customer data to lead returning buyers to merchandise they're
likely to purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants can create unlimited numbers of links between Amazon's
offerings and their own, at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   Each zShop's offerings are indexed by Amazon's new
shopping-oriented search engine, so the free searches turn up items
sold by Amazon itself or the zShops. The engine even directs
shoppers to other, noncompeting Web sites if the items sought
aren't available at Amazon.com, a practice most sites avoid at any
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's explanation, as always, is that it just wants to offer
the best possible shopping experience. But learning what people
wanted and couldn't find also gives Amazon a strong indicator of
how to expand its own offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Amazon will likely encroach on some of its zShops
as it expands, though specialty and niche sites will always exist,
Cassar said.
</P>
<P>
   The revenue that zShops could yield for Amazon is a topic Joel
Spiegel, the newly appointed vice president and general manage of
zShops, won't discuss. But analysts said the potential is large.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor will be how many merchants become zShops.
Amazon won't say how many are already signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Also critical are Amazon's income and expenses. Several
additional sellers' fees can provide more income. Boldface listings
cost $2 per sale. Emphasis in a given category, such as Health &AMP;
Beauty, costs $14.95 per listing. Showcasing on Amazon's home page
costs $99.95 per listing. As to expenses, Spiegel said Amazon is
``doing a lot of work'' to create zShops, declining to provide
details.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon doesn't have to pay for the zShops' warehousing and
shipping costs. But it doesn't take a full markup on sales either,
just a percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Only time will tell just how much money zShops will make for
Amazon. Creating the new department now means zShops could provide
an extra kick in the critical fourth quarter encompassing the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Marketwatch reported that analysts Warburg Dillon Read
expect fully 25 percent of this year's estimated $12 billion in
online sales to be made at Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's costs to zShop merchants are low by comparison to those
charged by Yahoo! and Lycos, two other sites that give homes to
businesses lacking their own, said Rothberg. And because Amazon is
a site designed for shopping, while those sites are designed for
broader use, Amazon will probably steal vendors from them, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegel declined to say whether the new department will mean
additions to staff.
</P>
<P>
   Why the name ``zShops''?
</P>
<P>
   ``The `shops' part was easy,'' Spiegel said. ``The 'z' is for
zero hassle, zero risk, and A-to-Z selection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
