u i BC-RUSSIA-BANK-NYT &LR;      09-29 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS BEGIN INVESTIGATION OF MOSCOW BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian prosecutors have opened the first criminal
investigation into a Moscow bank since the government was rocked by
accusations of money laundering through the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the prosecutor's investigative unit, Vladimir
Minayev, said Russian authorities had uncovered evidence of
suspicious deals carried out by the Flamingo Bank, a small bank
based in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Minayev declined to say whether Russian officials had uncovered
information that Flamingo had channeled money through suspicious
accounts at the Bank of New York. He said the investigation was
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Russian executives say Flamingo was one of several Russian banks
suspected of funneling under-the table payments from Russian
importers through foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
   The practice is a widespread means of avoiding taxes and
tariffs. And some Russian businessman have said it may account for
some of the money that passed through accounts at the Bank of New
York that the FBI is examining. Some $7.5 billion passed through
their accounts over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Flamingo Bank did not respond to repeated requests
for comment. The bank received a license in October 1994, according
to the Central Bank. It has a license to deal in foreign currency,
as well as rubles. But its official assets are so small that it has
escaped attention by some Western bank-rating agencies.
</P>
<P>
   After the suspicions involving the Bank of New York were
publicized, Russian officials first denounced the charges as a
conspiracy to humiliate Russia. More recently, however, leading
officials and tycoons have argued that Moscow should take visible
steps to crack down on corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that Russia's business community has suddenly been
swept by a new sense of rectitude. There is, however, a pervasive
sense that many Russian executives, legitimate as well as shady,
will be hurt as long Russia is seen as deeply corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Minayev was among the officials who recently traveled to the
United States to discuss the money-laundering case that is swirling
around the Bank of New York. He insisted in an interview that the
investigation into the Flamingo Bank had not been prompted by the
United States, but was based on Russian law-enforcement sources.
</P>
<P>
   Minayev said the investigators who searched the bank had found a
sum of hard currency with no documentation to indicate where it
came from. Russian press reports said the hard currency totaled
$430,000.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions of money laundering, Minayev said, were one reason
that Russian authorities began their investigation. ``We have not
launched a campaign against the banks,'' he said. ``But we are
trying to investigate illegal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flamingo is not the only bank that Russian executives said
might be linked to schemes to avoid tariffs. Other banks include
Depozitarno-Kliringovy Bank and the Sobin Bank. Those banks have
denied violations.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers questioned whether the case against Flamingo was
the start of a serious anticorruption drive. Rather, they said, the
authorities are making an example of Flamingo to impress the West.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Kommersant published an article on the case under
the headline, ``The General Prosecutor's Office Launders
Reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Flamingo, Kommersant wrote, is a ``scapegoat in a noisy
anticorruption campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
