<P>
   FOR THURSDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   Business Day Front Page
</P>
<P>
   (All stories coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted; transmission
times are Eastern)
</P>
<P>
   (Lede story)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LONG-DISTANCE (Undated) _ At about 8:30 Wednesday morning,
Bell Atlantic Corp., the nation's biggest local telephone company,
dropped off 30 boxes of documents at the Federal Communications
Commission. The boxes contained copies of Bell Atlantic's
application to sell long-distance communications services to
consumers and businesses in New York state. But for all of its
physical heft, Bell Atlantic's application was matched in
significance by a statement of merely four sentences issued a few
hours later by Maureen O. Helmer, chairwoman of the N.Y. Public
Service Commission, who all but formally endorsing Bell Atlantic's
long-distance aspirations. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   (Main Display)
</P>
<P>
   COPPER-INDUSTRY (New York) _ Last Friday, top executives from
three of the nation's top copper companies secretly convened in a
room at a Manhattan hotel to try to resolve one of the nastiest,
most convoluted corporate takeover fights in recent years. When
they emerged more than two hours later, it was nastier and more
convoluted than ever. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   (Right Side)
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA-OUTLOOK (Detroit) _ Despite the soaring value of the yen,
Toyota introduced a new subcompact car Wednesday that will be
imported from Japan and will be priced well below models made by
Detroit auto makers. The Toyota Echo starts at just $9,995. It
marks the first time in five years that Toyota has sold a car in
the United States for less than $10,000. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom Center)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Be careful what you ask for, the saying
goes, because you may get it. Mutual fund investors who ignored the
indexing phenomenon in hopes that their fund would eventually beat
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 are getting their wish, as the average
U.S. diversified equity fund appears poised to top the index for
the second consecutive quarter. But that is little comfort to
investors, who liked things a lot better when the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 was beating most other funds and posting 20 percent-plus annual
returns. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's columns, other features:
</P>
<P>
   WEB-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ One television commercial for
Outpost.com featured gerbils shot out of a cannon. Another, for
Ecampus.com, featured a college kid belching the alphabet. Welcome
to the world of dot-com _ home of some of the best and worst
advertising in the industry.
</P>
