<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-B     09-29 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD SAYS HE FOUGHT SICK AGAINST LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evander Holyfield says he was sick the first time.
Lennox Lewis says it makes him sick to hear such talk. Thus began
the tub-thumping for Holyfield-Lewis II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander always makes excuses after a poor performance, but the
only problem he had was Lennox Lewis punching him,'' Lewis said
Wednesday with disgust after hearing Holyfield's claim that a virus
and leg cramps conspired against him when they first squared off
last spring in a heavyweight unification fight that produced little
fighting and nothing heavy but a controversial draw that left a
sour taste in everyone's mouth _ apparently including Holyfield's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a virus 10 days before the fight,'' the WBA-IBF champion
said when asked to explain his decidedly lackluster performance
that night at Madison Square Garden. ``I had stomach cramps going
into the ring and my leg started to cramp after the first round. My
doctor told me I didn't need to go fight but I told him, `You think
I trained all this time and I'm pulling out?' All that work and you
the only one who don't get paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would lay down (that week) and have a big knot (cramp) in my
stomach. I didn't want to believe these type things were happening.
I felt your mind always tells you something is wrong (as a big
fight approaches), so when I got really sick I just thought it was
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured once the bell rings, I'd feel better. It didn't go
away, but I'm so quick to change my mind. I switched up and
thought, `What difference do it make? I'll get him in the third
round (when he had predicted he would knock Lewis out at God's
insistence).' When I didn't, I lost a little zeal. I started
thinking, `It just ain't going to get no better.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't for Holyfield until the three judges' scorecards were
read and the fight was declared a draw even though the crowd and
most ringside observers believed Lewis had done enough to win. Some
believed he had done quite a bit more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, frankly, saw Holyfield as the winner, a point he didn't
try to dispute Wednesday as his Nov. 13 rematch with Lewis was
officially announced in a ballroom at the New York Hilton in
Manhattan. The difference was Holyfield didn't see himself losing
either under a unique scoring system that has been in effect for as
long as there have been champions and challengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fight was even,'' Holyfield said. ``I didn't get
to him and he shouldn't be rewarded just for keeping me off him.
We're both champions and we didn't take anything away from each
other. When you have two champions, you can't win the fight if you
don't take it from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The champion remains the champion until he is dethroned. He is
defending his title while the other man is seeking it and by their
very definition defending is different from challenging.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, both men were champions. Both were
defending titles and it was clear Lewis did a far better job
defending the WBC portion from Holyfield than Holyfield did keeping
Lewis's mitts off the WBA and IBF portions. Yet in the end, neither
fought well enough to convince the world he was the superior
fighter, which is why they will do it again at Las Vegas's Thomas
and Mack Center for big money.
</P>
<P>
   But when they do, one thing will be clear even before the first
bell rings. Evander Holyfield may not have lost his titles to
Lennox Lewis on the night he cramped up, but that doesn't mean he
didn't lose anything to him.
</P>
<P>
   That June night, Holyfield was paid over $20 million to Lewis's
$10 million. On Nov. 13, they'll receive $15 million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   That's a loss of something bigger than title belts. It's a loss
of leverage and a concession by Holyfield that he needs this fight
as much as Lennox Lewis needed their first one . . . which is
probably enough to make him feel sick all over again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
