<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1054 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AMAZON-MERCHANTS-1STL     09-29 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-MERCHANTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: hate literature.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an important difference from real-world and Internet malls,
however, zShops will be essentially organized by product and
product category _ for example, fishing rods and sporting goods _
not by stores. Only after a customer has picked a particular item
from a list _ say, an Orvis fly rod for $150 _ would he be sent to
a page controlled by the merchant that would include a picture and
description of the item.
</P>
<P>
   To make the offer more enticing, Amazon is giving merchants a
chance to use several of the marketing tools it has refined.
Through what it calls relationship marketing, a small seller of
Indian Spices could have a link to its web site pop up every time a
customer calls up a book by ``Satanic Verses'' author Salman
Rushdie or a CD by sitarist Ravi Shankar. This service will be
offered free until Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, for a percentage of the sale, Amazon will let any
merchant offer one-click shopping. That allows customers to click
on the shipping address and credit information stored in the Amazon
data bank to make a purchase through another merchant. Amazon
charges the card and then deposits the money directly into the
seller account. The seller is responsible for shipping and product
quality.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to say how many stores are participating in
the experiment, but the arrangement will be less appealing to
larger business. Matt Hyde, vice president of online sales for
sporting goods retailer REI.com, said he had turned down the
opportunity because he aims to control the quality of the shopping
experience for his customers. ``Amazon commoditizes the product,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would consider it,'' said Anna Schryver, a spokeswoman for
clothing retailer Lands' End. ``However, we believe the greatest
place for our customer is our web site, because of the service
component.''
</P>
<P>
   This strategy is not without risks, the most pressing of which
is quality control. Amazon now has a brand name that is widely
recognized for trustworthiness. Since the retailer will only do
minimal screening of its prospective partners, it could easily find
itself processing orders for inefficient or dishonest merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon is optimistically counting on self-policing by consumer
ratings to eliminate most fraud. ``If you are selling online, your
digital reputation is all you have,'' said Jaleh Bisharat, Amazon's
vice president of marketing. ``They have a tremendous incentive to
deliver high-quality goods.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Amazon has said it will guarantee merchandise that
never arrives or differs materially from how it was described up to
$1,000 it if handled the credit card payment and up to $250 if it
does not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, company analysts see a downside that could be
substantial. ``If the Tiffany lamp I order through zShops turns out
to be a fake, will I still blame Amazon? Yep,'' said Alan
Braverman, head of Internet Research at Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   But the risk to Amazon could be well worth the while if it
becomes the pre-eminent vault of information of Internet shopping
habits. In theory, Amazon could gather information on products that
were most popular with its customers. ``One of the reasons behind
adding these shops will be to help them determine what products
their customers are interested in so they can offer it
themselves,'' said Mike May, a digital commerce analyst with
Jupiter Communications, an Internet research firm. ``If a specific
product category, say sweaters, gets hot, they have a lot of
incentive to sell direct to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Amazon does not eventually choose to expand into new
products, it still has a lot to gain by learning more about
consumer shopping habits. ``The data could become the most valuable
asset,'' predicted Braverman. He hypothesizes about a future where
manufacturers like Procter &AMP; Gamble, for example, would pay Amazon
to test market new products.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of how such an arrangement could benefit Amazon,
one need look no farther than when Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. started its
Mutual Fund Marketplace. The financial services giant offered to
customers the ability to go to one spot to buy mutual funds from
dozens of companies. Schwab took no ``inventory'' from the
companies and had no responsibility for managing the money, but it
did collect fees on the transactions. Schwab also kept the most
valuable part of the transaction for itself: information on
customers investing habits.
</P>
<P>
   The fund companies do not know who their customers are, they
simply get the money. As a result, the fund companies cannot
communicate directly with the investors who buy through Schwab, so
have no hope of repeat sales or targeted marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, on the other hand, has used this method to establish a
base of customers about whom it knows habits, preferences,
investment ability and more. As it has expanded its business, it
has started to pick off these customers from the companies whose
funds it also sells. Schwab has been the most successful company in
its industry in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
