u k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     09-29 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS TO THE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I would like to personally thank the people of Boston and 12
talented American golfers for giving us the most exciting Ryder Cup
in memory.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's final-round TV-ratings were the highest in Cup history
and we owe it all to you.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many special moments.
</P>
<P>
   Like when a fan spat in the face of European captain Mark James'
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Like that little spike-shoed clog-dance the American players so
thoughtfully performed in the line of Jose Maria Olazabal's
potentially Cup-winning putt on the 17th green.
</P>
<P>
   Or the cheering when the Europeans hit a bad shot or missed a
putt.
</P>
<P>
   Or heckling Colin Montgomerie so mercilessly that his father
couldn't stand it anymore and walked back to the clubhouse after 7
holes.
</P>
<P>
   Or steering Andrew Coltart in the wrong direction when he was
looking for his ball in the rough and suddenly ``finding'' it 30
seconds after he had to take a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it takes to win, I say.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, these are some of our bitterest enemies, these Brits,
Swedes and Spaniards. Wasn't it Ireland that was responsible for
stealing our nuclear-weapons secrets a while back? No, wait. That
was China. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Now the British tabloids are whining that we're a bunch of bad
sports.
</P>
<P>
   United Slobs of America they're calling us. James doesn't want
to play over here anymore. Montgomerie's having second thoughts,
too.
</P>
<P>
   What a bunch of babies, I say.
</P>
<P>
   I mean it's not like Tom Lehman bashed a folding chair over
Olazabal's head or bowled him over with a flying drop-kick just as
he drew back his putter.(Though that might have been necessary if
Justin Leonard hadn't made that long putt seconds before.)
</P>
<P>
   All the American team did was ``modify'' the line of Ollie's
putt a little, sort of the way the Department of Transportation
modifies the surface of interstates before repaving.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he would have been happier if we had set out some orange
construction cones or some detour signs.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy har har.
</P>
<P>
   One of the guys I was watching the Ryder Cup with Sunday
afternoon _ a person who clearly fails to appreciate how ``edgy''
golf has become _ said that if Jack Nicklaus had been in that
situation Sunday afternoon and seen the American team turn
Olazabal's line into a cattle trail, he would have given the
Spaniard his putt, all 30-feet of it.
</P>
<P>
   That's good, Ollie. Pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   My team, in its exuberance, thoughtlessly breeched a fundamental
tenet of golfing etiquette. I will not allow you to suffer for it,
even if it means losing the Ryder Cup. The game is not played that
way, and the game is more important than some cheesy trophy.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think that Nicklaus, the greatest and fiercest
competitor in the history of golf, would have done just that.
</P>
<P>
   What I don't know is how some U.S. fans might have reacted to
Nicklaus' demonstration of sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   But I bet Mark James' wife has a clue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
