<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-SEASON-ART-NYT &LR;      09-29 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SEASON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME IS NOW FIVE MINUTES IN HOCKEY HEAVEN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT9 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly before the 28 teams opened their training camps, the
National Hockey League executive Steve Solomon attended the revival
of ``Death of a Salesman'' on Broadway. Solomon, second in command
to Commissioner Gary Bettman, spied a hockey-friendly journalist at
intermission and went into sell mode. The topic was the NHL's new
four-on-four overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most exciting five minutes in sports!'' Solomon said. ``It
will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be, but Solomon won't be around to hype it. A couple
weeks later, he announced his resignation, effective Friday, the
opening night of the NHL season. Solomon is going to Univision, the
Spanish television network, where he will head the sports division.
</P>
<P>
   While Bettman seeks Solomon's replacement, the league skates on,
with the Dallas Stars defending their first Stanley Cup and the
2000 playoffs set to end next June. Along with the new overtime
concept, the NHL has partly changed its video-review policy. No
longer will television tape nullify apparently good goals because
an attacking player had a skate in the goalie's crease. The
decision regarding goalie interference will be made only by the
referees, the way it used to be. And there will be two referees for
50 of each team's 82 regular-season games, up from 20 last season.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a new team in Atlanta, in a new arena, with plenty
of tickets sold for the Thrashers. The Carolina Hurricanes have a
new arena in Raleigh, N.C., where tickets are not selling as well.
The Los Angeles Kings have a new building, too, and so does the
Colorado Avalanche. Locally, the Rangers signed six free agents and
the Devils stood pat. The Islanders are still in their old
building, with the same ownership considering a sale as the payroll
shrinks, the season-ticket base dwindles and local television
exposure remains uncertain. As for national TV, Fox is gone with
all its incomprehensible camera angles and ABC is in with fewer
regular-season games than Fox and camera work still to be
determined. More games will be seen on ESPN and ESPN2, the cable
partners of ABC and all under the Disney umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   When the puck drops Friday, with the Rangers at Edmonton, it
will be the first season in two decades without Wayne Gretzky, who
began in 1979 with the Oilers and finished in 1999 with the
Rangers. Gretzky and his No. 99 jersey will be honored in pregame
ceremonies Friday night and he will enter the Hall of Fame in
November. And this season could be the last for Hall-bound Dominik
Hasek of Buffalo, who said he plans to retire. Hasek has won the
Vezina trophy for the past three seasons as the league's best
goalie. But Bettman emphasized that the returning younger stars
include Paul Kariya of Anaheim, Jaromir Jagr of Pittsburgh and Eric
Lindros of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of sports in all ages is that there is always
another generation,'' Bettman said. As for rules changes, Bettman
said, ``The feedback we've gotten has been overwhelmingly
positive'' for the new overtime format. Under it, teams tied after
60 minutes will each get 1 point in the standing, as they always
have for ties. The five-minute, sudden-death overtime will be
played, however, with four skaters apiece, instead of five. If a
team scores to win in overtime, it gets a second point in the
standing for a victory while the losing team keeps its point for
the tie in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Scotty Bowman, the dean of NHL coaches, said he is not
sure how this will affect strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things you put in your mind,'' Bowman said.
``What the standings are. Your opponent. How you're playing in the
game. It will cause a lot of parity. If you tied every game, you'd
have 82 points, going for another 82. You might see some real
offense for five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   This should highlight players like Brian Leetch, the Ranger
captain, who is a skilled attacker from his defensive position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the rule, it's exciting,'' Leetch said. ``Teams will
put skill players out there. It will help the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter, the Ranger goalie, said that eliminating video
review for crease violations will lead to more collisions between
attackers and goalies.
</P>
<P>
   Off the ice, there are serious issues. With the collective
bargaining agreement in place until 2004, some teams are resisting
the wage inflation that has raised the average salary to almost
$1.3 million. Among the stars in contract squabbles are: Aleksei
Yashin of Ottawa, Keith Primeau of Carolina, Bill Guerin of
Edmonton, Byron Dafoe of Boston and Darren McCarty of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Free agents still seeking teams include Ulf Samuelsson, Pat
Verbeek, Dmitri Khristich and Joe Murphy. Among old faces in new
places: Theo Fleury from Calgary to Colorado to the Rangers;
Zigmund Palffy from the Islanders to Los Angeles; Niklas Sundstrom
from the Rangers to San Jose, via Tampa Bay; and Grant Fuhr from
St. Louis to Calgary. Kevin Lowe, the former Ranger and Oiler, is
coaching Edmonton. Mario Lemieux, the former Pittsburgh star, now
heads an ownership group that bought the Penguins out of
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the NHL has not commanded the higher profile that
seemed its destiny five years ago. After Bettman's first full
season, 1993-94, the Rangers had won the Stanley Cup and Solomon
was helping to negotiate big national television deals. Rap artists
wore team jerseys and hockey seemed hip. The cute, new, successful
expansion team was the Anaheim Mighty Ducks, founded by the Disney
Co., an encouraging straw in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   With baseball on strike that autumn, hockey had a wider space on
the big sports stage. And then Bettman, negotiating a collective
bargaining agreement, ordered a labor lockout that lasted 15 weeks.
Perhaps it was only coincidental, but hockey's momentum seemed to
slow.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman, as sensitive to criticism as he is dedicated to his
mission, is quick to counter perceptions that hockey has not
attained its expected share of the American sports audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous fragmentation out there,'' Bettman said,
referring to the sports marketplace, especially its television
component. ``The competition, in terms of distribution, is fiercer
than ever before. On a regional basis, we continue to do great. We
have a strong fan base. Our attendance has never been stronger.
We're in more places than ever before. Go back to 1990. We were in
11 U.S. markets. For next season, we will be in 21. All of these
things will take time. We've been heading in the right direction.
It's a long road. We think we're on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
