<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOYOTA-OUTLOOK-ART-NY     09-29 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYOTA-OUTLOOK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA'S LOW-COST ECHO IS GREETED BY SILENCE IN AUTO INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Despite the soaring value of the yen, Toyota Motor
Corp. introduced a subcompact car Wednesday that will be imported
from Japan and will be priced well below comparable models made by
Detroit auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, such a move would probably have outraged American
auto executives, prompting them to call for federal investigations
into whether Japanese cars were being dumped on the United States
market. But there was silence Wednesday from the industry in
Detroit, which has become increasingly global.
</P>
<P>
   The new subcompact, the Echo starts at just $9,995, the first
Toyota in five years to be priced in the United States for less
than $10,000. The Echo costs thousands less than competitors
including the Ford Escort ($11,760), Dodge Neon ($12,460) and even
Ford's newest small car offering, the Focus ($11,865).
</P>
<P>
   Still, Toyota executives say that selling the car at that price
is profitable for the company and that the low price comes from
engineering advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, the low price was prompted by the last surge in
the yen's value,'' said Donald V. Esmond, group vice president and
general manager of Toyota's United States arm. ``It probably was
due to the yen four years ago, when the yen was so strong and our
cars were so high-priced.
</P>
<P>
   The yen briefly peaked at just 79.85 to the dollar in April 1995
before retreating below 100. The yen closed Wednesday at 106.98 to
the dollar, after climbing more than 15 percent over the last 10
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The yen rally, which tends to make all imports more expensive,
has been powered by Japan's apparent emergence from its longest
recession since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroshi Okuda, the chairman of the Toyota, said in a telephone
interview Wednesday that the globalization of the auto industry had
made trade frictions less severe between the United States and
Japan. ``That is how we in private business, as well as in the
government, see it,'' Okuda said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is harder now for American executives to call for
people to ``buy American.'' The Chrysler Corp., whose former
chairman, Lee Iacocca, prominently accused Japan of dumping cars in
the United States, was acquired by a German company and is now
DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many other auto makers with headquarters in foreign
countries are building huge numbers of cars and trucks in the
United States. In the 1999 model year, Toyota built in North
America 74 percent of its cars and trucks sold here, Honda built 82
percent and Nissan built 58 percent. BMW, Mitsubishi, Mazda and
Subaru also build cars in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the General Motors Corp. and the Ford Motor Co. sell
cars around the world and own major auto makers in other countries.
Ford even owns 33.4 percent of Mazda.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Wednesday, investors can buy Toyota's American
depository receipts under the symbol TM on the New York Stock
Exchange. Toyota shares also began trading Wednesday on the London
Stock Exchange. Okuda even rang the New York Stock Exchange's
opening bell Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The current surge in the yen marks the first real potential for
trade issues to roil the waters in the auto industry since
Daimler-Benz bought and Chrysler last November.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler still employ their
longtime trade lobbyist, Stephen J. Collins, as president of the
Automotive Trade Policy Council. He continues to warn about the
threats from Japanese competition and said Wednesday, ``There's a
sense of renewed aggressivity of Japan in the U.S. market.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the country's trade deficit with Japan is once
again widening but conceded that part of the increase is coming
from cars imported to help quench an unexpectedly strong American
auto market _ one that United States auto makers are also
struggling to supply.
</P>
<P>
   Though such comments used to be backed up with frequent
pronouncements by the chief executives of Detroit auto makers, that
is no longer the case. DaimlerChrysler, Ford and GM officials
declined to comment Wednesday on the yen or Toyota's pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Okuda said Toyota had set a goal of capturing 10 percent of the
American market _ compared with 8.6 percent in the first eight
months of this year _ but had set no timetable. ``The rise in the
value of the yen will not affect our future activities here,'' he
added. ``It will not affect how soon we attain that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyota also plans to increase its share of the European market
from 3 percent to 5 percent by 2005. Worldwide, Toyota sells about
9 percent of cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Okuda said the yen's effect on Toyota's American operations
would continue to shrink in the future as more of the company's
vehicles are assembled in the United States. But the Echo, a
subcompact with expansive headroom and crisp handling, will be
imported from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota expects to sell at least 50,000 of the 2000 model year
Echos in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers shaved about $2,600 off the price of the Toyota
Tercel, the car the Echo replaced. Michael J. O'Brien, a Toyota
executive, said engineers designed the Echo with fewer separate
components and with parts that were easier to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they saved $12 a car by redesigning the Echo's
air-conditioning unit in one piece instead of three. And they saved
$30 to $35 a car by bolting the power-steering pump, alternator and
air-conditioning compressor directly to the Echo's engine block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those changes added up,'' he said. ``Anytime there's a part,
there's handling requirements, and that all adds up to money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SMITHSONIAN-DONATION-     09-29 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHSONIAN-DONATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLIONAIRE, ONCE REFUGEE, DONATES MILLIONS TO SMITHSONIAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A refugee from the 1956 Hungarian uprising who came
penniless to the United States will give the Smithsonian
Institution $60 million, its largest donation ever, the Smithsonian
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The donor, Steven F. Udvar-Hazy, became a billionaire by leasing
airliners, and his gift to the Smithsonian will be directed to a
new museum at Dulles International Airport to open in four years
that will contain objects too big _ like the space shuttle and a
747 jetliner _ for its National Air and Space Museum on the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the gift, the Smithsonian is expected to name the
Dulles museum for Udvar-Hazy (pronounced OOD-var HAH-zee), perhaps
at the next meeting of its governing board of regents in January.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the space shuttle and the 747, the Dulles museum will
also house the Enola Gay, the B-29 that dropped the atomic bomb on
Hiroshima in 1945; an SR-71, once a secret spy plane, and a B-17,
another World War II bomber.
</P>
<P>
   Udvar-Hazy was traveling in Asia Wednesday and not available for
comment, but the chairman of his leasing company, Leslie Gonda,
described how Udvar-Hazy's knack for aviation had brought him a
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when he was an undergraduate at UCLA, he gave classes to
graduate students in airline management and administration,'' Gonda
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the University of California at Los Angeles that
Udvar-Hazy learned that he could make money by buying an airplane
from one company and selling it or leasing it to another.
</P>
<P>
   According to an interview with The Wall Street Journal in 1990,
Udvar-Hazy learned in 1967 that Air New Zealand was trying to sell
an old Lockheed Electra and told the airline that he would sell it
for a 5 percent commission. Air New Zealand agreed and Udvar-Hazy
sold the airplane and made a $50,000 commission.
</P>
<P>
   He was then 21 years old and he said that he carried on the deal
via Telex because, he said, ``I was afraid if someone saw me,
they'd be disappointed in how young I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Udvar-Hazy is now 53 and earlier this year The Los Angeles
Business Journal estimated his fortune at $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Udvar-Hazy, Gonda and Gonda's son, Louis, sold their
company, the International Lease Finance Corp., to American
International Group, the insurance company, for $1.3 billion in
cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   Udvar-Hazy and the elder Gonda stayed on to run the company for
the new owners.
</P>
<P>
   Gonda is also a Hungarian refugee, now 80, who lost much of his
family in the Holocaust and came to the United States in 1963 after
going first to Venezuela in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   He said Udvar-Hazy and his brother, Andre, were taken by their
parents, Ernest and Ethel, to Sweden when the Soviet Union put down
the Hungarian uprising in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   The family then moved to New York City, where Udvar-Hazy
attended elite Stuyvesant High School, and then to California.
Udvar-Hazy lives with his wife, Christine, their four children and
his mother (his father has since died) in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Morten S. Beyer, chairman of MBA, an aviation consulting firm,
said the company Udvar-Hazy founded is one of the largest owners of
Boeing and Airbus planes, although it has no 747s like the one that
will be installed at Dulles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't like the economics for the lessor,'' Beyer said of
Udvar-Hazy's aversion to the 747.
</P>
<P>
   After word of the donation got out, the secretary of the
Smithsonian, I. Michael Heyman, noted that it was the latest in a
series of ``exemplary gifts to the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent was the bequest by Dr. Paul Singer of his huge
collection of ancient Chinese artifacts to the Smithsonian's Arthur
M. Sackler Gallery announced on Sept. 8. The collection has been
valued at $50 million to $60 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1110 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MANICHAEAN MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's assume the curator of the National Gallery in Washington
came up with a show called ``Outrage.'' It featured a statue of
Moses wearing a Nazi swastika on his chest, a painting of a violent
Martin Luther King Jr. forcing Elizabeth Cady Stanton into
submission, and an avant-garde collage of the cutest puppy you ever
saw being tortured to death by a sadistic homosexual. As Mort Sahl
used to say, ``Is there anybody I haven't offended?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes; Christians. In a real-life abuse of public responsibility,
good taste and artistic license, the curator of the Brooklyn Museum
of Art is presenting ``Sensation,'' featuring a portrait of the
Virgin Mary with her breast decorated by a piece of what is
described delicately as elephant dung. (As they say with a smirk at
the Brooklyn Museum, ``dung happens.'')
</P>
<P>
   The museum's serenely elitist board members are either
incredibly stupid or knew _ and did not care _ that this would (a)
offend the religious, (b) anger and divide the city, (c) make a ton
of money for the exhibition's owners, and (d) make the museum's
staff the heroes of free expression with their own set.
</P>
<P>
   They also knew, or should have, that their publicly financed
thumb in the eye of the faithful was a supremely political act.
Mayor Rudy Giuliani had to respond to reflect his values, and did;
the artist's press agent in London had to denounce the mayor's
withdrawal of funds as ``totalitarian and fascist,'' as he
delightedly did; and the mayor's senatorial opponent, Hillary
Clinton, had to march in liberal lock step with the rest of the
city's embarrassed, unhappy but principled cultural establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Thus has the hubristic Brooklyn Museum plunged the city into a
lose-lose battle. It's now the ``right to free artistic
expression'' versus ``the accountability of the spending of public
funds.'' Everybody to the ramparts and to hell with comity.
Absolutists of the world, unite: Go to court over the issue of free
hate speech and grind the losers' faces in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   But whoever wins, everybody loses. When basic principles are in
conflict, democracies work out compromises that reflect the
majority and protect the minority. A civil libertarian believes not
only in liberty but in civility.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think of myself as a big First Amendment type. I was
all for the Nazis' right to parade through Skokie and think the
flag-burning amendment is a travesty and sedition must be defended.
I'm for a private gallery's right to display outrage and sensation
and an offended public's right to picket peaceably.
</P>
<P>
   But limits exist: you can't steal this essay, protected by
copyright, and put it on your Web site. Nor can a museum defiantly
spend money raised by taxation for causes opposed by the majority
or disgust a significant minority. Sooner or later, the public's
elected representatives direct that spending or are replaced.
Freedom of expression is a right, but public payment for it is not
an entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   Free-speech lawyers I know and respect say the mayor will lose
because the Supreme Court frowns on any ``penalty on disfavored
viewpoints.'' Maybe so; maybe the court's decision last year that
governments could impose a decency standard on taxpayer-paid
expression will not apply in this case.
</P>
<P>
   But believers in unfettered expression looking for an exciting
``Kulturkampf'' to drive the Yahoos from the temple should stop
before they win a Pyrrhic victory. If public museums win in federal
court the right to offend egregiously without being punished by
losing their subsidies, they will lose their subsidies beforehand.
The art world is thoughtlessly flirting with a democratic public's
pre-emptive censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Surely artists would be freer to shock if unworried by the loss
of taxpayer support. Privately financed institutions and commercial
galleries have that constitutionally protected advantage. But is
heavier reliance on private philanthropy what our cultural
Houyhnhnms really want?
</P>
<P>
   Why don't the authors of this Manichaean madness _ museum
curator, chairman and the benefactors of ``Sensation'' _ send their
contributions directly to the Buchanan campaign? Nothing is helping
bigots more in dividing religions and races.
</P>
<P>
   New York needs mediators, not gladiators. This is not the Good
Fight; this is the wrong fight. Settle it before everybody loses.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
