</P>
<P>
   Thus has the hubristic Brooklyn Museum plunged the city into a
lose-lose battle. It's now the ``right to free artistic
expression'' versus ``the accountability of the spending of public
funds.'' Everybody to the ramparts and to hell with comity.
Absolutists of the world, unite: Go to court over the issue of free
hate speech and grind the losers' faces in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   But whoever wins, everybody loses. When basic principles are in
conflict, democracies work out compromises that reflect the
majority and protect the minority. A civil libertarian believes not
only in liberty but in civility.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think of myself as a big First Amendment type. I was
all for the Nazis' right to parade through Skokie and think the
flag-burning amendment is a travesty and sedition must be defended.
I'm for a private gallery's right to display outrage and sensation
and an offended public's right to picket peaceably.
</P>
<P>
   But limits exist: you can't steal this essay, protected by
copyright, and put it on your Web site. Nor can a museum defiantly
spend money raised by taxation for causes opposed by the majority
or disgust a significant minority. Sooner or later, the public's
elected representatives direct that spending or are replaced.
Freedom of expression is a right, but public payment for it is not
an entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   Free-speech lawyers I know and respect say the mayor will lose
because the Supreme Court frowns on any ``penalty on disfavored
viewpoints.'' Maybe so; maybe the court's decision last year that
governments could impose a decency standard on taxpayer-paid
expression will not apply in this case.
</P>
<P>
   But believers in unfettered expression looking for an exciting
``Kulturkampf'' to drive the Yahoos from the temple should stop
before they win a Pyrrhic victory. If public museums win in federal
court the right to offend egregiously without being punished by
losing their subsidies, they will lose their subsidies beforehand.
The art world is thoughtlessly flirting with a democratic public's
pre-emptive censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Surely artists would be freer to shock if unworried by the loss
of taxpayer support. Privately financed institutions and commercial
galleries have that constitutionally protected advantage. But is
heavier reliance on private philanthropy what our cultural
Houyhnhnms really want?
</P>
<P>
   Why don't the authors of this Manichaean madness _ museum
curator, chairman and the benefactors of ``Sensation'' _ send their
contributions directly to the Buchanan campaign? Nothing is helping
bigots more in dividing religions and races.
</P>
<P>
   New York needs mediators, not gladiators. This is not the Good
Fight; this is the wrong fight. Settle it before everybody loses.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
