<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Many of the interrogation techniques used during Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's dictatorship in Chile were the same used by British
forces in Northern Ireland and found by the European Court of Human
Rights not to constitute torture, the lawyer leading the general's
defense told a London court. Spain is seeking the extradition of
Pinochet, 83, to stand trial on torture charges.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: BLAIR INVITATION TO TORIES
</P>
<P>
   A day after assailing ``conservative forces,'' in his address to
the annual Labor Party convention, for holding Britain back, Prime
Minister Tony Blair invited Conservatives to desert their party for
his, saying Labor now represented ``traditional'' conservative
values better than a ``Conservative Party more extreme than ever.''
The Tory leader William Hague said Blair's attack showed
``incredible hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND: GAELIC SCHOOL OPENS
</P>
<P>
   Scotland opened its first all-Gaelic public primary school in an
effort to safeguard a traditional language spoken by only 60,000
people, most of whom live in the Highlands and the Western islands.
The school, in Glasgow, has 109 students and will hold all classes
solely in Gaelic, with English offered as a separate course
starting in the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: EXPATRIATES GET VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Parliament approved a law that allows Italian citizens abroad to
vote in Italian elections. Government statistics show that about
3.6 million Italian citizens live outside the country, more than
300,000 of them in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: WOMEN CAN ENLIST
</P>
<P>
   Up to 20,000 women are expected to apply to join Italy's armed
services after Parliament passed a law that allows women to serve
as volunteers in the military. Most other European countries
already allow women to serve.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: NEW VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Yet another outbreak of violence by armed groups of the left and
right has resulted in the deaths of at least 15 people and the
kidnapping of another 16. Right-wing death squads killed 10 people
and abducted 10 in Magdalena and Antioquia provinces, authorities
said, while a unit of the Marxist-Leninist People's Liberation Army
stormed into a village in the same northern region, executing five
people.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: NEW MAYOR
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City's legislative council has ratified Rosario Robles
Berlanga to succeed Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano and become the
first woman to be mayor. Ms. Robles served for nearly two years as
the chief of staff of Cardenas, who stepped down on Tuesday to run
for president.
</P>
</TEXT>
