<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-ASSEMBLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. IS READY TO CONSIDER SENDING PEACEKEEPERS TO SIERRA LEONE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council is preparing to consider
whether to dispatch peacekeepers to Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   A British draft resolution circulating Wednesday among Security
Council members proposes sending peacekeeping troops for an initial
period of 12 months. Secretary-General Kofi Annan recommended last
Thursday that 6,000 soldiers be deployed in Sierra Leone, which has
been ravaged by years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told the Security Council Wednesday that Africans are
closely watching its deliberations on Sierra Leone and Congo,
another country torn by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not be surprised to hear me say that many Africans,
remembering the failure to intervene effectively in Rwanda to stop
the genocide, at times regard the council as indifferent to the
continent's plight,'' Annan said. He referred to the ethnic
slaughter of more than a half-million Tutsi by Hutu militias in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers are needed in Sierra Leone to enforce a fragile
peace agreement between the government and rebels that was signed
in July in Lome, Togo, by helping to disarm as many as 45,000
combatants and restoring stability in a country reeling from
lawlessness and atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the numbers, but in general we are very
supportive of the idea,'' an American diplomat said. ``I think
there is a general recognition that the U.N. needs to be involved
following a reduction in the numbers of Nigerian troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigerians account for most of the 12,000 troops in the West
African peacekeeping force now in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's president, Olusegun Obasanjo, has said that
intervening in Sierra Leone is costing his country $1 million a
day, which it cannot afford, and he has told Annan that he would
have to begin withdrawing his troops at the rate of 2,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, several diplomats said, the deployment of
U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone would involve transferring as
many as four battalions of the Nigerian troops to U.N. command,
because they are already there and know the problems, and paying
their costs through the U.N. peacekeeping budget.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo is said to be amenable.
</P>
<P>
   In his report last Thursday, the secretary-general estimated
that the U.N. mission would need six infantry battalions and other
support units with helicopters and armored personnel carriers.
Annan expressed the hope that ``a significant part'' of the
peacekeeping force would come from West Africa, including Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. has only an observer mission in Sierra Leone, amounting
to 105 military observers and two medical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Annan envisaged deploying U.N. peacekeepers throughout Sierra
Leone, while leaving the security of the capital, Freetown, and the
international airport at Lungi to what remained of the existing
West African force.
</P>
<P>
   John Hirsch, the former U.S. ambassador to Sierra Leone, said
that the country could slide back into chaos without a U.N.
presence. ``After 30 years of internal collapse and eight years of
war, if there's ever going to be a revival of Sierra Leone, it is
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The British draft resolution also urges Foday Sankoh, the leader
of the principal rebel group, the Revolutionary United Front, to
return to Sierra Leone and assume his obligations under the Lome
peace accord. The rebels were promised a number of ministerial
posts in a coalition government, but in return were expected to
help disarm their fighters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
