<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      09-29 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SEEKS TO ONCE AGAIN MAKE HEALTH CARE A PRIORITY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley's health care proposal
seeks to put the issue back on the national agenda after the
failure to pass universal health insurance in 1994 humiliated
President Clinton and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And while his Senate career was not marked by leadership on
health care, it was distinguished by spotlighting important,
complex and sometimes stupefyingly dull issues, from the debt of
developing countries to tax simplification. He made Washington pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Bradley argued insistently that having nearly
one-fifth of the population uninsured was an urgent national
problem and that it could not be solved on the cheap. His $65
billion-a-year plan, he said, involves ``a great deal of money.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, it is far from clear that it can be solved as cheaply
as Bradley proposed; subsidies of up to $1,800 a year may not get
all that many lower-wage earners insured. A Bradley aide
acknowledged on Wednesday that the sum was ``probably a little bit
low,'' adding, ``It gets people in the door, if not the parlor.''
</P>
<P>
   His plan, and he said it was evolving, skirted two major rocks
that sank the Clinton program _ requiring employers to insure their
workers and an attempt to control costs.
</P>
<P>
   Compelling employers to insure their workers was central to the
president's plan, and stirred deadly opposition from small
business. Cost containment, a health-care problem beginning to
emerge again now after several quiet years, antagonized health-care
providers whose support the administration had counted on.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley plan is also an important political token _ both
much broader than anything Vice President Al Gore, Bradley's
opponent for the Democratic presidential nomination, has advocated
and a venture into an area widely regarded, in the capital at
least, as political quicksand.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, it is not unlike the senator's position on gun
control, demanding registration of all handguns _ a step
conventionally considered politically unattainable, especially when
House Democrats recall that their anti-gun votes helped cost them
control of the House in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And while no one argues that the administration's occasional
efforts to pass legislation to curb soft money and issue
advertisements have cost it political support, campaign finance is
another area where Bradley is now demanding more ``reform'' than
either the Clinton-Gore administration or any sizable faction in
Congress is now pushing.
</P>
<P>
   But his health-care proposal is more than another effort to
one-up the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an example of Bradley's promise to focus on a few
major issues in his campaign, and, he hopes, his presidency. That
was a style he showed in the Senate, where he sometimes buried
himself in a single subject for months.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that can work in a presidential campaign over the long
run, let alone in the White House, where problems are thrust upon
presidents, is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short run, at least, his initiative was welcomed on
many fronts as an important attention-getting move.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Feder, a veteran of the Clinton effort who is now dean of
policy studies at Georgetown University, said, ``I think it's great
to hear an expression of support for a move toward universal
coverage, and a commitment particularly that all low-income people
ought to have full government support and a recognition that it
takes money to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Chip Kahn, president of the Health Insurance Association of
America, which brought the nation the ``Harry and Louise''
commercials against the Clinton plan, praised the proposal as
``realistic and thoughtful.'' But Kahn did say he feared that
details of the Bradley proposal would lead to ``expensive so-called
patient protection mandates.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is far from a finished plan, and some very obvious
questions lead only to guesswork. (But the completeness of the
Clinton plan of 1993-94 seemed to present a new target with every
difficulty it anticipated.)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of the obvious questions is what would be the effect
of opening up the federal Employees Health Benefit Program, which
now insures nine million people from a stable, educated and
above-average-income work force, to any American who wanted to
join.
</P>
<P>
   Would that be likely to draw in many people whose poor health is
a factor in their not being insured today, thereby making the
federal pool more expensive to insure? The Bradley aide said no one
could know, but it was just as possible that it would draw in more
young, healthy people and reduce the costs.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bradley sailed around the politically ruinous issue of
requiring employers to provide insurance, he could not put it over
the horizon. Most Americans now get their health insurance through
employers, but why should hard-pressed employers insure their
workers if the government will? Again, no one knows how many
employers might stop insuring their workers, but it could be enough
to have a serious impact on the health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for supporters of universal care, if not necessarily of
the Clinton variety, the doubts were outweighed by just seeing
their issue on the front pages again.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Rowland, senior vice president of the Kaiser Family
Foundation here, said, ``It really goes beyond some of the
incremental stuff we've been looking at.'' Ms. Rowland said Bradley
had acknowledged this problem ``needs to be addressed in a bigger
way than just hoping everyone will get insurance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
