<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-LONG-DISTANCE-820&AMP;     09-29 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LONG-DISTANCE-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS SMILE ON BELL ATLANTIC'S LONG-DISTANCE PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas, La., S.C., Okla.)   (bl)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around 8:30 a.m. Wednesday, workers dispatched by Bell Atlantic
Corp., the nation's biggest local telephone company, began
unloading 30 boxes of documents from trucks outside the Washington
offices of the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The boxes contained three copies of Bell Atlantic's application
to sell long-distance communications services to consumers and
businesses in New York state. If the petition is granted, Bell
Atlantic will become the first regional Bell admitted to the $80
billion long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its physical heft, Bell Atlantic's application was
matched in significance by a statement of merely four sentences
issued a few hours later by Maureen Helmer, chairwoman of the New
York Public Service Commission, which is highly regarded at the FCC
and which has been jawboning Bell Atlantic to open its local
network for years.
</P>
<P>
   All but formally endorsing Bell Atlantic's long-distance
aspirations, Ms. Helmer insured that Bell Atlantic's rivals, which
will try to convince the FCC to reject the application, have a
difficult task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that Bell Atlantic's progress in meeting the
terms of the 271 checklist has reached the point of a filing with
the FCC,'' her statement read, referring to the section of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996 that details the steps that a Bell
company must take before entering the long-distance market. ``The
cooperation of all the parties during the course of this review has
facilitated a tremendous amount of progress by the company in
opening its local market to competition. If the filing is
consistent with the terms and conditions that we have established,
and the record we have developed over the past 2{ years, I am
optimistic that I could offer my support.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Helmer was under no obligation to share her optimism
Wednesday; the New York PSC will not make its formal comments to
the FCC for about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the days and weeks leading up to Bell Atlantic's application
Wednesday, many communications experts said that the FCC was likely
to follow the guidance of the New York regulators _ or at least
give New York's recommendation far more weight than it had lent to
earlier long-distance endorsements for other regional Bells from
regulators in other states. Applications in some states _ including
Louisiana, South Carolina and Oklahoma _ were rejected, with people
close to the FCC saying that the commission had not been convinced
of the rigor and independence of the regulators in those states.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, FCC Chairman William Kennard was positively glowing
Wednesday in his praise of the New York PSC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud the New York Public Service Commission for its work
on Bell Atlantic's application to enter the long distance market,''
he said in a statement. ``The dedication and expertise displayed by
New York's Public Service Commission and its staff are truly
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard's regard for the New York regulators may be enhanced by
the fact that his chief of staff, Kathryn Brown, spent three years
as director of the New York PSC's consumer services division.
</P>
<P>
   So at this point the tea leaves indicate that the application
will be approved. That still does not necessarily mean Bell
Atlantic is set to define the One True Path for other Bells to
reach their long-distance nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, SBC Communications Inc. is scheduled to receive
results of a test of the openness of its network Friday, with the
next meeting of the state's regulatory commission to discuss SBC's
long-distance plans set for Oct. 21. If SBC is lucky _ and good _
it will be able to apply to the FCC for permission in Texas soon
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But the way SBC has opened its network in Texas is in some
technical aspects quite different from Bell Atlantic's model.
Because of the high concentration of lucrative business customers
in New York, especially in Manhattan, many competitive local phone
companies in New York City have found it economical to assemble
relatively extensive networks of their own and to buy access to
Bell Atlantic's systems piecemeal. In working with the state's
regulators, Bell Atlantic has spent a lot of time and effort
developing the capacity to sell access to many discrete parts of
its network.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive local carriers in Texas, on the other hand, appear
to have more appetite for bigger chunks of SBC's network, perhaps
putting more focus on less lucrative residential customers because
the Texas business market is not quite as attractive as that of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``SBC is following a different model and also has a pretty good
chance of getting in on a slightly later time track,'' said former
FCC Chairman Reed Hundt, who is now a consultant for McKinsey &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting is whether or not both of them are
accepted,'' he said. ``If they are, the country will see two
different models and different states will go with different
models.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To many telecommunications analysts and executives, Bell
Atlantic's model seems to require more work on the part of the
incumbent. That is why executives at other regional Bells have been
heard to complain that Bell Atlantic has been too conciliatory,
perhaps setting a bar too high for the other Bell companies to
hurdle easily.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has every reason to be more conciliatory because
it has already lost so much corporate business in big metropolitan
markets to upstarts. It is not a new pattern. In 1990, for
instance, Nynex _ later acquired by Bell Atlantic _ became the
first Bell to set aside space within its switching centers for
competitors to place their own equipment. The other Bells howled
that Nynex was making them look bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people would say that's being conciliatory,'' said Ivan
Seidenberg, who was chairman of Nynex before becoming chairman of
Bell Atlantic. ``I would say we're the first company that faces
competition in the industry every time. And I can go ahead and say
we have been right every time because everybody has followed suit
sooner or later, though they tend to do it kicking and scratching
because it's convenient to say, `New York made us do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to trade some things to get access to larger
markets, I think that's the right trade-off,'' Seidenberg added.
``While I could get excited about the word conciliatory, I might
want to replace that with savvy and strategic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1169 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-     09-29 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PLAN DELAY OF EARNED-INCOME TAX CREDIT PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS quote marks in 2nd, 10th grafs; ADDS 2nd take with 11 grafs) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans, desperate for money to
finance their spending bills without raiding Social Security funds,
Wednesday devised a plan that relies almost entirely on delaying
billions of dollars in federal tax credits for millions of
working-class families.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was immediately questioned by Democrats and some
Republicans, who called it an accounting gimmick that could hurt
people on the lower rungs of the economic ladder. Frank Salizzoni,
the chief executive of H&AMP;R Block Inc., said it ``could cause
confusion and disrupt the personal lives of hard-working American
families.''
</P>
<P>
   A chart detailing the plan, obtained from a senior House
Republican leader, shows Congress on course to spend $7.6 billion
in surplus contributions to Social Security to run the government
in the 2000 fiscal year, which begins on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But because under the new plan about $8 billion would not be
spent in the 2000 year, the Republicans' calculations show $400
million in black ink, rather than a $7.6 billion dip into Social
Security money.
</P>
<P>
   But the figure could be higher. The Congressional Budget Office
released new figures Wednesday night estimating that Republicans
were actually on course to spend $17.9 billion out of the Social
Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Republican leaders, who have vowed daily, and
fervently, that they will not spend the funds, stood together
Wednesday under a banner reading ``Stop Robbing Social Security''
and unveiled a new campaign of television commercials renewing
their pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans' own calculations show that the only way
they can avoid raiding Social Security is to distribute the
politically popular earned-income tax credit payment in 12 monthly
payments next year, rather than paying it in a lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Because the fiscal year ends Sept. 30, payments for October,
November and December 2000 would be counted against the 2001
budget, according to John Feehery, spokesman for Speaker Dennis
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   So the plan actually saves no money, but instead uses an
accounting device that allows three months of the tax-credit
payments to be counted in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Feehery said delaying the payments would hurt no one and help
the government ``weed out waste, fraud and abuse'' that he said was
rampant in the earned-income tax credit program.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old tax credit payment program was designed to be an
incentive to keep people working and paying taxes. About 20 million
Americans in households earning from $10,200 to $30,580 are
eligible for the credit. They received $28.5 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The average family received $1,890 in a single annual payment,
allowing some to pay off debts, make a down payment on a car or pay
tuition. Under the Republican plan, that same family would receive,
instead, a check for $157.50 a month, a sum better suited for
buying groceries or paying utility bills.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, director of the White House's National Economic
Council, called the plan ``a forced interest-free loan to the
government'' from ``people scraping to get by.'' The White House
budget director, Jack Lew, called it ``kind of Dickensian.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican idea of using the tax credit to offset billions
in spending was first floated two weeks ago, but not as the
centerpiece of a plan to leave Social Security alone. Even then, it
was received unenthusiastically by much of the Republican
rank-and-file. Wednesday some conservative Republicans said the
plan still made them uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have real concerns,'' said Rep. Mark Souder, R-Ind., who
called the plan ``a gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to move people from welfare to work,'' Souder
said. ``But a number of our proposals seem to hit people moving
from dependency to independence. Regardless of how you look at it,
it's a reduction in benefits for those people.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Republican aide expressed confidence in the plan. ``It
can be passed and it will be passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress were skeptical. ``Why don't they go after
some corporate tax break instead of the poorest of the poor?''
asked House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee, said, ``It boggles my mind that they
would be that callous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' calculations directly conflict with the new
figures released Wednesday night by the Congressional Budget
Office. The budget office's figures, requested by Rep. John M.
Spratt Jr. of South Carolina, the ranking Democrat on the House
Budget Committee, show Congress on course to spend $17.9 billion in
Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   The differing figures can be explained by the fact that the
Republicans have ordered the budget office to make billions of
dollars in what are called ``directed scorekeeping'' adjustments.
That means they have told their numbers-crunchers not to count
those billions, a process that Stan Collender, a federal budget
expert at Fleishman-Hillard, defines as ``lying about the
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, Spratt said, ``were not playing by the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Calculations by the Republicans also assume that almost
everything else in the increasingly chaotic congressional spending
process will turn up as they hope, which may be unlikely. Congress
made no progress today in passing spending bills, leaving eight of
the 13 measures incomplete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1171 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      09-29 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY ACCUSES BROOKLYN MUSEUM OF CONSPIRING TO PROMOTE PRIVATE
COLLECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a new line of attack in the city's vehement
opposition to a controversial art exhibition, senior City Hall
officials on Wednesday accused the Brooklyn Museum of Art of
conspiring with an auction house to inflate the value of the
artwork in the show, all of which is privately owned by the British
advertising executive Charles Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   The administration officials vowed to file a lawsuit in State
Supreme Court seeking to seize control of the museum by contending
that it had violated its lease with the city in part by misusing a
public institution to promote a private collection.
</P>
<P>
   But they said they would not try to block the exhibition from
opening on Saturday and were instead preparing for a tough legal
battle. On Tuesday, the museum filed a lawsuit in federal court
accusing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of violating the First Amendment by
threatening to cut off the museum's city financing.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Wednesday afternoon, Deputy Mayor Joseph
J. Lhota, Deputy Mayor Randy L. Levine and the city's corporation
counsel, Michael D. Hess, accused the museum of ``hucksterism'' and
of perpetrating a ``scam'' by conspiring with Christie's auction
house, which is a sponsor of the exhibition, to enrich Saatchi by
inflating the value of his art collection.
</P>
<P>
   In making the allegations of conspiracy, officials capitalized
on news reports that noted the awkward role of Christie's, which is
a promoter and financial supporter of the exhibition as well as a
purveyor of artwork belonging to Saatchi, who is a major collector
and an important client. Christie's also supported an installation
of the show at the Royal Academy in London.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To avoid conflicts of interest, some museums do not exhibit
private collections unless they have been promised to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a scam and taxpayers dollars should not be used to
support that,'' Hess said at Wednesday's news conference.
``Taxpayers' dollars should be used for educating children, for
building roads, for supporting the homeless, not for pushing up the
value of a private art collection.'' He added, ``We'll bring all of
this out in court. We are going to do some aggressive discovery.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum and Christie's quickly rejected the allegations as a
desperate and feeble attempt by the mayor to quash the museum show,
which Giuliani has called ``disgusting'' and offensive to Catholics
because it includes a painting of the Virgin Mary surrounded by
elephant dung and pornographic pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With Giuliani away on a three-day political trip to the West
Coast, officials at City Hall were clearly seeking to retake the
offensive in the museum dispute. The Giuliani administration had
been on the defensive since late Tuesday when the museum abandoned
its efforts to resolve the dispute through negotiations with City
Hall and announced the show would go on as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that every day, the city comes up with a new
pretextual claim,'' said Floyd Abrams, the lawyer who is
representing the museum in its suit against the city. ``Now they
have come up with another argument. Each and every one of them is
nothing more or less than further pretext in an effort to punish
the museum for the exercise of its First Amendment rights.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christie's, which was said to have given less than $50,000 to
the show, also rejected the conspiracy charges. ``We are aware of
these bewildering accusations,'' the auction house said in a
prepared statement. ``They have absolutely no substance, are not
true. Christie's has a long history of sponsorships of exhibitions
in the United States and internationally. Nothing in this
exhibition is for sale nor is their any expectation for any of the
works from the exhibition to be sold by Christie's.'' The statement
was followed by a long list of shows that the auction house has
supported.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the museum, through a spokesman, issued a statement calling
the accusations ``preposterous and misleading.'' It said, ``The
Mayor's latest charge simply reflects the depths to which he will
go to undermine the First Amendment.'' The spokesman, Fred
Schroeder, said Christie's financial contribution to the show
represented a small fraction of its total cost. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
