<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PLAN DELAY OF EARNED-INCOME TAX CREDIT PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:40 p.m. ET)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans, desperate for money to
finance their spending bills without raiding Social Security funds,
Wednesday devised a plan that relies almost entirely on delaying
billions of dollars in federal tax credits for millions of
working-class families.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was immediately questioned by Democrats and some
Republicans, who called it an accounting gimmick that could hurt
people on the lower rungs of the economic ladder. Frank Salizzoni,
the chief executive of H&AMP;R Block Inc., said it could cause
confusion and disrupt the personal lives of hard-working American
families.''
</P>
<P>
   A chart detailing the plan, obtained from a senior House
Republican leader, shows Congress on course to spend $7.6 billion
in surplus contributions to Social Security to run the government
in the 2000 fiscal year, which begins on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But because under the new plan about $8 billion would not be
spent in the 2000 year, the Republicans' calculations show $400
million in black ink, rather than a $7.6 billion dip into Social
Security money.
</P>
<P>
   But the figure could be higher. The Congressional Budget Office
released new figures Wednesday night estimating that Republicans
were actually on course to spend $17.9 billion out of the Social
Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Republican leaders, who have vowed daily, and
fervently, that they will not spend the funds, stood together
Wednesday under a banner reading ``Stop Robbing Social Security''
and unveiled a new campaign of television commercials renewing
their pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans' own calculations show that the only way
they can avoid raiding Social Security is to distribute the
politically popular earned-income tax credit payment in 12 monthly
payments next year, rather than paying it in a lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Because the fiscal year ends Sept. 30, payments for October,
November and December 2000 would be counted against the 2001
budget, according to John Feehery, spokesman for Speaker Dennis
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   So the plan actually saves no money, but instead uses an
accounting device that allows three months of the tax-credit
payments to be counted in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Feehery said delaying the payments would hurt no one and help
the government weed out waste, fraud and abuse'' that he said was
rampant in the earned-income tax credit program.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old tax credit payment program was designed to be an
incentive to keep people working and paying taxes. About 20 million
Americans in households earning from $10,200 to $30,580 are
eligible for the credit. They received $28.5 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The average family received $1,890 in a single annual payment,
allowing some to pay off debts, make a down payment on a car or pay
tuition. Under the Republican plan, that same family would receive,
instead, a check for $157.50 a month, a sum better suited for
buying groceries or paying utility bills.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
