<HEADER>
A1193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-PROTEST-NY     09-29 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE BREAK UP ANIT-MILOSEVIC DEMONSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Riot police swinging batons broke up a
peaceful demonstration on Wednesday night, preventing some 20,000
demonstrators from marching to the suburb where President Slobodan
Milosevic lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 people were injured, including at least five reporters,
cameramen and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to break up the march was a clear departure from
police tactics since daily demonstrations began Sept. 21. While the
police action is likely to swell what has been a disappointing
number of daily demonstrators, it also seemed intended to advertise
and underline Milosevic's determination to use force to hold on to
his job.
</P>
<P>
   During the last major demonstrations in the winter of 1996-97,
which lasted 88 days, police were careful not to confront marchers.
Clearly, Milosevic wants no repetition of that three-month
embarrassment, which ended when he accepted opposition victories in
local elections and fired the police and television chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Alliance for Change said on Wednesday night that
although they wanted to test the police, they did not want
violence. They said the purpose of the march was designed to draw
more people to these nightly rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we're playing with dangerous stuff,'' said Milan
Protic, one of the Alliance leaders, before the police charged. But
in speeches after the march, before a thin and shaken crowd in
Belgrade's Square of the Republic, Protic and Zoran Djindjic,
leader of the Democratic Party, appealed to demonstrators not to
confront the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a marathon,'' Djindjic said. ``I beg of you to be more
wise than they are.'' But he also noted with glee: ``The regime
showed that they are more scared of us than we thought an hour
ago.'' And he announced that demonstrators would make the same
march again on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a tense standoff between demonstrators and police
blocking Kneza Milosa Street, in front of the Defense Ministry
building still blasted from NATO bombs. Opposition leaders, after
talking to the police, urged their followers to turn up another
route.
</P>
<P>
   But the marchers did not follow them, so the leaders returned to
sit in front of police lines, to prevent a confrontation and urged
protesters to sit. After about 20 minutes, 75 riot police then
marched down Nemanjina Street and started to drive the marchers
back with their shields and batons.
</P>
<P>
   A Djindjic bodyguard, Vlada, was badly beaten on the head, and
with an eye swollen shut, said on Wednesday night of Milosevic:
``It won't be that easy to make him leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday night's clash, leaders of the divided political
opposition to Milosevic moved to make another effort to create a
common front around the issue of early elections.
</P>
<P>
   With only moderate turnouts at their nightly rallies, the
leaders of the Alliance for Change are reluctantly seeking a
rapprochement with Vuk Draskovic, who runs the largest opposition
party, the Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance is being pushed to do so by Dragoslav Avramovic,
the former central banker who is their choice for prime minister in
any transitional government. Avramovic believes, he said in an
interview, that Milosevic can easily ignore a divided opposition,
and that the turnouts thus far have been encouraging but
insufficient to bring significant pressure on the regime.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at Avramovic's instigation, all the parties will
attend a ``round table'' on necessary conditions for free and fair
elections. If the round table succeeds, then Draskovic says he will
throw his support to rallies intended to press for early elections,
as the best and only effective way to oust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance has been insistent that Milosevic must resign
first, if there would be any chance of fair elections. But their
campaign thus far shows no sign of bringing about any resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has refused to join these rallies, calling them
``pointless'' and ``a waste of time.'' He has not lent them his
party's organizational skills or helped publicize them on the
Belgrade city television station he controls, Studio B.
</P>
<P>
   But Studio B covered Wednesday night's clashes, and the violence
will add pressure on Draskovic, once known for his fiery boldness
in earlier demonstrations, to join these.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
