<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-RACE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA RACIAL PROFILING BILL IS VETOED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Playing both sides of a divisive racial issue,
Gov. Gray Davis of California has vetoed a bill requiring
law-enforcement agencies to provide information to determine
whether they are stopping a disproportionate share of racial
minority members. But while he questioned the usefulness and cost
of the measure, which is strongly supported by civil rights groups,
Davis ordered the state highway patrol to collect that information
and urged local police departments to do so voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill contended that at a cost of less than $2
million a year it would have produced evidence of whether motorists
from minorities were being stopped by law-enforcement officers for
questioning because of the driver's race. The bill would have
required police to record the race, sex and other information about
every motorist they stop.
</P>
<P>
   In his veto message late on Tuesday, the governor, who was
supported in his election campaign last year by the usually
conservative police groups that opposed the measure, disputed the
cost estimates of the bill's supporters and said ``it is
questionable whether the information gathered _ at a potential cost
of tens of millions of dollars _ would provide any more meaningful
information than is currently available.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that although there might be a few specific instances
of racial profiling ``there is no evidence that this practice is
taking place statewide.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Davis noted approvingly that more than 30 local
law-enforcement agencies around the state were voluntarily
collecting information on the people being stopped by police, and
said he had ordered the sole law-enforcement agency under his
direct control, the California Highway Patrol, to record the
ethnicity as well as other data on the people stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' communications director, Philip Trounstine, said he
believed that there was no contradiction in the actions and that
what the governor principally objected to was mandating every
police agency in the state to collect the statistics. He said the
governor felt police should undertake the collection of racial data
on their own and only where it seemed necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights groups have said that the targeting of minorities,
largely black and Hispanic motorists, is a longstanding practice
among some police departments and, most recently, President Clinton
ordered federal law-enforcement officials to collect information on
the race and sex of people they stop. Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey has acknowledged that state police there had engaged in
racial profiling and she has appointed a new chief to attack the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   California's attorney general, Bill Lockyer, a Democrat,
supported the bill, saying it would increase public confidence in
law enforcement. But several police associations said having to
record the data would be an unnecessary burden and would contradict
the training officers receive to ignore the race of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have required police officials to record the
apparent ethnicity of every motorist they stop, as well as other
information like age, sex, whether they conducted a search and
whether a citation was issued. The officers would not have asked
the racial background of the motorists, but would have relied on
their own visual determination.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would have lapsed at the end of 2004, included
no provisions to halt the practice of racial profiling, if it were
found to exist, but would have provided the first comprehensive
data in the state on what kinds of people were being stopped by
police and whether the figures varied by district. Civil rights
groups have argued that such information is an important first step
in rooting out what they contend is a pattern of racism.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was sponsored by state Sen. Kevin Murray, an L.A.
Democrat and an African-American who earlier had sued the Beverly
Hills Police Department, contending that he had been stopped by a
policeman there purely because of his race.
</P>
<P>
   Murray harshly criticized the governor Wednesday, saying, ``What
we have now is the largest state in the union, with the largest
population of minorities, which has now said it's not going to do
anything on this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Trounstine disputed the suggestion that Davis was doing nothing
and insisted that the dispute was largely over the best way to
achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may argue about whether mandating the collection of
data is the proper state function,'' Trounstine said, ``but no one
can question Governor Davis' commitment to civil rights and equal
protection under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis followed up his veto by writing to Mayor Richard Riordan
of Los Angeles, whose police chief had criticized the bill, and
urging him to begin collecting the data voluntarily, as some other
cities are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor can't rely on volunteerism, rely on
law-enforcement agencies to volunteer to do this,'' said Elizabeth
Schroeder of the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern
California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
