<HEADLINE>
BUSH DENOUNCES PEROT AND BUCHANAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas sternly
denounced Ross Perot and Pat Buchanan on Wednesday, suggesting that
``personal vendettas'' may be driving their apparent alliance to
have Buchanan seek the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush asserted that both men helped undermine his father's
unsuccessful campaign for re-election to the White House in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought the 1992 campaign was hard for my dad to
get traction in the race because of, first, Patrick J. Buchanan,
and then Ross Perot inflicted a series of cuts,'' Bush said in
response to questions at a news conference during a two-day
California campaign swing. ``If the adage is true _ you die a death
of a thousand cuts in politics _ Ross Perot was a part of the
thousand cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's display of a festering resentment toward Perot and
Buchanan was unusual in a campaign in which he has tried to strike
an accommodating tone to win over a broad spectrum of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks reignited the feuds that started with his father
_ and make it less likely that Bush would ever reach an
accommodation with Perot or Buchanan. Buchanan weakened President
George Bush by taking him on in the primaries in 1992; Perot's
independent candidacy cost him voters in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Many other politicians have taken care not to criticize Perot,
the founder of the Reform Party, whose profile has diminished but
who still has considerable influence among some in the party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the front-runner for the Republican nomination, and many
of his advisers view Buchanan as a serious threat because if he
wins the Reform Party nomination he could siphon Republican support
from Bush in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's expected bid for the nomination had thus far had the
tacit backing of Perot, whose advisers have briefed the Buchanan
campaign on the byzantine Reform Party nominating process. Even
Buchanan's advisers said they know the unpredictable Perot could
undermine their effort by plunging into the nomination race himself
_ or backing another contender.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was particularly critical of Perot, recalling the Texas
business executive's endorsement of Gov. Ann Richards, the
Democratic incumbent, when Bush ran against her in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a personal relationship with Mr. Perot in that about
one week before the 1994 election, up pops Mr. Perot and he
endorsed my opponent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Buchanan and Perot were motivated by bad blood
toward his family, Bush said, ``I hope not.'' But he went on to
raise the notion of vendettas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the people enter the political process with what's best
for the country in mind _ not making decisions based on personal
vendettas,'' Bush said. ``I don't know Mr. Perot well enough to be
able to tell you whether or not he's got personal animus toward me.
All I got to tell you is the one time I did have political
experience with him is when he endorsed my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot was traveling and could not be reached for comment. But
Russell J. Verney, the Reform Party chairman who is close to Perot,
dismissed Bush's remarks as ``paranoia'' from the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   ``After '92 the Bushes couldn't accept responsibility for their
loss, so they call it a vendetta,'' he said. ``There's no vendetta.
There's no animus. The Bushes have to take full responsibility for
`read my lips _ no new taxes' and a miserable campaign in '92.''
</P>
<P>
   In commenting on reports that Buchanan was considering running
for the Reform Party nomination, Bush made his most vigorous appeal
to Buchanan not to defect _ even as other Republicans are
condemning Buchanan for his comments about the West's response to
Hitler in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, his revisionist history about World War II is
wrong,'' Bush said. Still, making clear that he is trying not to
alienate Buchanan's supporters, he added, ``If he goes, he's gone,
I understand that. The question is whether some of the people who
support Pat Buchanan who are loyal Republicans stay with the
nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a rival for the nomination who
has declared that Buchanan no longer has a place in the Republican
party, sought to draw a contrast with Bush's handling of the
renegade Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance Wednesday at the Reagan Library in Simi Valley,
Calif., where Nancy Reagan sat in the front row, McCain cloaked
himself in the memories of Reagan, whom he recalled as a great
American hero who would never stand for aggressors like Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let Ronald Reagan's words stand too as a challenge,'' McCain
said in a passage that his advisers said was a reference to Bush's
handling of Buchanan. ``For not only must Americans be prepared to
defend the honor and glory of our country, but to speak out
forcefully against those who would urge us to abandon our world
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reagan did not endorse McCain or speak publicly Wednesday,
but she met with him before his speech and people close to the
senator said she has privately encouraged his bid.
</P>
<P>
   McCain first met the Reagans in the early 1970s when they had
dinners to welcome prisoners of war home from Vietnam. Meeting with
reporters in front of a chunk of the Berlin Wall on display at the
library, McCain said he disagreed with Bush, who said of Buchanan,
``Let Republicans decide whether or not his ideas make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain put forth a different view: ``When someone takes the
positions that Mr. Buchanan did on the issue of World War II, that
is not longer in the realm of debate of the Republican Party,'' he
said. ``I won't stoop to debate that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed Buchanan as a ``marginal figure now _ he's gained
no traction in New Hampshire or anyplace else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
