<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-KILLINGS-NYT &LR;      09-29 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-KILLINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SAYS IT HAS NO PROOF OF U.S. TROOPS' MASSACRE OF KOREANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: The Times is running this story with the Associated Press
story, ``Death at the Bridge: Ex-GIs tell of Korean War refugee
killings.''  
 (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Without denying that Korean civilians were killed
at the Bridge of No Gun Ri 49 years ago, Pentagon officials said
Wednesday that a search of their archives turned up no documents
that prove that U.S. soldiers massacred the civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Army Center for Military History has reviewed its
records and has found no information that substantiates the claim
that United States Army soldiers perpetrated a massacre of South
Korean civilians at No Gun Ri,'' said Col. Ed Vega, spokesman for
the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department officials said there are no plans to conduct
a far-reaching investigation. In the absence of archival records,
the Pentagon would have to undertake a major research project
pulling records, interviewing Korean and American witnesses and
cross-checking the information with other documents in order to
find evidence about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Military and academic historians interviewed said they were not
surprised that civilians were killed in the early months of the
Korean War, although they disagreed about the meaning of the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cumings of the University of Chicago, who first wrote
about reports of an incident near the bridge in his book ``The
Origins of the Korean War, Volume II'' (Princeton, 1990), said he
relied in part on the contemporary reporting of Walter Sullivan in
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Though in his July 22, 1950, article about the fighting,
Sullivan did not report the killing of civilians, he did write
this: ``The American G.I. is now beginning to eye with suspicion
any Korean civilian in the cities or countryside. Watch those guys
in white! _ the customary peasant dress _ is the cry often heard
near the front.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the diary of a dead Korean soldier and U.S. military
records, Cumings said he had showed that Korean civilians had died
during U.S. aerial bombardments.
</P>
<P>
   This bombardment and strafing could have driven the civilians to
take refuge under the bridge. Cumings said that The Associated
Press reporting ``makes it unquestionable that tens or hundreds of
Koreans were killed by Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   William Stueck, a history professor at the University of Georgia
and author of ``The Korean War: an International History''
(Princeton, 1995), said that since there was infiltration of United
States lines by enemy troops posing as civilians, the reaction of
U.S. soldiers was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the incident happened, Stueck said, ``it wouldn't
surprise me that American soldiers were very sensitive to that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a violation of the rule of law for the military to use
civilians to mask their operations in war.
</P>
<P>
   Both Stueck and Cumings said there was no previous report of any
atrocity of this magnitude by U.S. forces in the Korean War. They
and other historians noted that the many atrocities committed
during the conflict were largely by Koreans against each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
