<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      09-29 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPTION CHARGES HAVE HURT U.S.-RUSSIA-TIES, SAYS FORMER
PREMIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Russian Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin
said Wednesday that accusations of Russian corruption and
money-laundering had poisoned relations with the United States, and
he urged political and business leaders in both countries to help
keep the investigation from derailing the larger strategic
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who was prime minister from 1992 to 1998, also
defended Vice President Al Gore's leadership skills and insisted
that President Boris Yeltsin of Russia was ``incapable'' of
profiting from corruption. He said he could not vouch for members
of Yeltsin's family, whose bank accounts in the Cayman Islands are
under scrutiny by investigators and who have been accused of using
credit cards provided by a Swiss construction company that did work
for the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's remarks at a luncheon given by the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce came during a visit to Washington and New York this
week that seems intended to tamp down fears among American
corporate investors in Russia, who have expressed alarm at the
money-laundering allegations as well as the flight of capital from
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said that critics had exaggerated the scope of
corruption in Russia. ``Of course, we have lots of problems, but
they're trying to present everything being corrupted in Russia, and
that the whole of Russia is criminal,'' Chernomyrdin said through a
translator. ``We do not deserve that.''
</P>
<P>
   He defended his own role in Russia's painful evolution toward a
free-market democracy. ``I can face anyone,'' Chernomyrdin told
business leaders and reporters in free-wheeling remarks laced with
humor. ``All the allegations, all the speculation won't get anyone
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, of course, has every reason to play down the
reported corruption. As the head of Russia's huge gas monopoly,
Gazprom, he has been publicly accused of using his influence over
the company's privatization program to make himself rich.
</P>
<P>
   And the CIA uncovered what its analysts believed to be
conclusive evidence of Chernomyrdin's personal corruption in 1995.
But when the classified report was sent to Gore, it was rejected
and sent back to the CIA with a barnyard epithet scrawled across
it, U.S. intelligence officials said last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's critics say this example illustrates how the
administration is dismissive of ``inconvenient'' intelligence about
foreign leaders with whom White House and State Department
officials have developed close personal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said Wednesday that Gore repeatedly expressed
concern about corruption in Russia and how the United States could
help combat it during semiannual meetings between the two leaders
beginning in 1993. ``I could always pick up the phone and call Al
Gore, and he helped out,'' Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
   Combating capital flight from Russia, both in legal transactions
and criminal enterprises, is difficult, he said. Russia has no
legal mechanisms to stop capital flight or to monitor
money-laundering. ``If someone is involved with dirty money, we
have to sort it out and punish someone,'' Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
   The former prime minister urged American business leaders to
ride out the current problems. Executives from Enron, Caterpillar
and Lockheed-Martin who attended the lunch nodded in agreement.
Caterpillar, for example, plans to open a new $50 million plant
south of St. Petersburg that will employ 300 Russians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
