<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SS-0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS FISCAL YEAR BEGINS, PARTIES BLAME EACH OTHER FOR EXPECTED
RAID ON SOCIAL SECURITY
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With two days to go until the start of a new fiscal
year, Democrats and Republicans on Wednesday could have been
celebrating a near halt to the decades-long practice of raiding the
Social Security surplus to finance the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the two parties were laying the groundwork for blaming
each other when, as predicted by budget experts, they dip into the
pension surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The final budget is still in the works. Congress has passed a
temporary spending bill to give itself three more weeks to resolve
remaining differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under no circumstances will I vote to spend one penny of the
Social Security surplus on anything other than Social Security,''
vowed House Republican Whip Tom Delay, R-Texas. ``It's time to stop
the Democrats and the president from raiding Social Security, as
they have done for almost _ since 1967 _ to pay for more big
government programs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all ``in the best schoolyard tradition,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart replied. He ticked off a list of the
bookkeeping gimmicks that Republicans are using, such as labeling
the census count as an off-budget ``emergency,'' to hide what he
said are their budget-busting ways.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also blasted a House Republican plan to stretch tax
credits for the working poor over 12 months instead of making a
lump sum payment. That would push some $9 billion into the
following fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the squabbling, some budget watchers are stepping
back to note a historic reversal.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the two parties have joined in using billions of
dollars in Social Security trust funds. In the year that begins at
week's end, forecasters say the government will borrow a relatively
modest $30 billion from the pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   Although that does not fulfill their solemn promise, even some
budget hawks are optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made great progress,'' said Robert Bixby, policy
director for the Concord Coalition, which has been pressing
Congress to stop deficit spending. ``They tried to go cold turkey
this year'' and largely succeeded, even if they fell off the wagon
a couple of times, Bixby said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the finger-pointing now, Bixby said, ``I don't think
either one trying to blame the other is going to have much
credibility with the American public.'' He predicted that it would
take two more years before the Social Security funds are left
completely untouched.
</P>
<P>
   At the liberal-leaning Center on Budget and Policy Priorities,
Robert Greenstein offered a similar forecast.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Greenstein said that the country has benefited because
the two parties have been so deadlocked in the budget battle this
year. President Clinton has failed to enact major new social
spending he proposed, and his veto killed the tax cut that
Republicans passed.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a rising overall surplus, which will be used to
reduce the publicly held debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paying down the debt is one of the best things we can do
now,'' Greenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
