<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK OF SCOTLAND, PUSHING FOR NATWEST, REPORTS EARNINGS RISE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Top executives of the Bank of Scotland went on a road
show of sorts Wednesday, traipsing around London in the rain in an
effort to persuade shareholders of National Westminster Bank of the
merits of their $34 billion hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Scots had some impressive evidence in support of their case:
the bank reported a 12 percent increase in pretax earnings for the
fiscal first half, better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps to allay concerns about taking on a bank twice its
size, the Bank of Scotland also said Wednesday that it was
exploring an alliance with an American partner. ``We are talking to
a number of major U.S. companies and a number of smaller ones,''
the bank's chief executive, Peter Burt, said. It declined to
identify possible partners.
</P>
<P>
   While The Bank of Scotland is the only bidder so far for
Natwest, The Royal Bank of Scotland is said to be mulling over a
counteroffer of its own, according to executives that have been
briefed on the plan. Abbey National PLC is also said to be
interested in Natwest.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Natwest are still trading above The Bank of Scotland's
original bid around 12.50 pounds a share, or $20.55, as investors
eagerly await a suitor to announce a counteroffer. Wednesday, they
declined 28 pence to close at 14.23 pounds, or $23.40.
</P>
<P>
   In a related matter, the Bank of Scotland reported Wednesday
that pretax profit for the six-month period ending on Aug. 31
increased to 471 million pounds , or $776.8 million, from 420
million pounds in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts seemed impressed with the bank's financial
performance, Natwest, which has been desperately trying to fend off
the Scottish suitor, had harsh words about its would-be parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rapid lending growth and buying market share are storing up
problems for the future,'' said Sir David Rowland, the chairman of
Natwest, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Bank of Scotland's net interest margin shrank 9
percent and expenses increased 10 percent, adding, ``Natwest Group
is totally committed to achieving the best value for its
shareholders and continues to believe that the offer by Bank of
Scotland is ill-thought-out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland, in a statement of its own, responded:
``With all their problems and their track record, how can Natwest
criticize a bank with one of the lowest cost-income ratios?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this war of words, most analysts here seemed more
interested in the takeover battle than they were in the the
company's financial results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results were OK,'' said John Tyce of SG Securities, and
then immediately changing the subject. ``Where is the next bid
coming from?'' he asked. ``Who's coming to the rescue?''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Bank of Scotland rose as much as 5.3 percent in
early trading, and then fell back later in the day, as analysts
became worried about the company's future growth prospects and
about the emergence of another suitor for Natwest. The stock closed
at 7.24 pounds, down 21.5 pence, or 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholders are fed up with Natwest,'' said Peter Walters, a
banking analyst at ABN Amro here. ``The market looks at this so
much more positively than at the Legal and General deal,'' he
added, referring to Natwest's planned acquisition of Legal and
General PLC, a big British insurer, which has been suspended
pending the outcome of the Bank of Scotland's bid for Natwest.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprisingly, the Bank of Scotland said Wednesday that
it had actually considered acquiring Legal and General itself
months ago and had discussed the idea on a preliminary basis with
the life insurance and pension group.
</P>
<P>
   Burt, who has harshly criticized Natwest's intended acquisition
of Legal and General, said that the Bank of Scotland decided
against buying the company because he saw no merit in such a deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
