<SLUG> BC-ED-GOPSPENDING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP again bumbles budget bills
 &HT;    By Joe Geshwiler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Republicans in Congress are making like the Gang Who
Couldn't Legislate Straight. For the fourth year out of the five
they've been in the majority this decade, they've failed to pass
crucial appropriations bills before the start of the federal fiscal
year. And this year they aren't even close to fulfilling their vow
to meet the deadline, completing just five of the required 13
spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Only by postponing the day of reckoning by three weeks with a
stopgap measure passed Wednesday did they avert another
embarrassing government shutdown. Dissension within the GOP is a
major reason for this legislative breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   The agriculture bill is stymied because of internal wrangling
over the Cuba trade embargo and milk pricing policies for the South
and Northeast. And leading GOP lawmakers are divided over the fate
of the F-22 stealth fighter, thus holding up action on the defense
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the riders, the perverse legislative attachments
so popular with legislative mavericks and meddlers. The foreign
operations bill is being held up as the single-minded
anti-abortionist Chris Smith (R-N.J.) attempts to rewrite U.S.
population-control policy. Several other bills are littered with
riders that invite and deserve Clinton's veto.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP leaders may be tardy, but they're determined to stay
within spending caps enacted two years ago. So where do they look
first to economize?
</P>
<P>
   One big chunk of savings, they say, can come from deferring
earned-income tax payments to the working poor. And they hope to
recoup billions more by retrieving excess welfare funds made to
state governments to finance their welfare-reform programs; that's
money the states are wisely holding as a hedge against the
consequences of the next economic downturn. Both proposals are out
of the question.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of vying with Clinton, Republicans in Congress
continue to stumble through the appropriations process like the
Mets folding before the Braves. Isn't it time their Senate and
House teams tried new managers?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
