<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warm-up starts for millennial finish
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Major magazines are anticipating the millennium with
special editions that usually look at past achievements and ahead
to what the experts think life in the 21st century will be like.
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (Oct. 4) looks at ``the Internet age'' in a
special edition that also marks the publication's 70th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power to navigate the world at the click of a mouse is a
force that is transforming our lives like none before,'' says the
theme story. ``Anyone with a computer is a citizen of the world _
and a richer world at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes ASAP (Oct. 4), a publication of Forbes magazine, devotes
its millennial edition to ``the great convergence,'' with articles
by Tom Wolfe, Bill Gates, George Gilder, Kurt Vonnegut and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something immense is occurring around us,'' says ASAP in
explaining convergence. ``Everywhere you look, things are flowing
together, creating new connections, new hybrids, new ways of seeing
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The boundaries that separate technology, science and religion
are giving way as these disciplines move closer to each other, the
magazine contends.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THEIR HITS
</P>
<P>
   Two Atlanta-based blue chips _ beverage giant Coca-Cola and home
improvement retailer Home Depot _ get smacked in the chops in the
latest Worth (October).
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Nick Pachetti says the recall of Coca-Cola products
in Belgium last summer ``raises a worrisome question for Coca-Cola
investors: Who's looking after the world's greatest brand?''
</P>
<P>
   The company has since sought to heal these ``self-inflicted
wounds,'' but Pachetti says some investors ``wonder if management
is up to the job of stewarding one of the world's most valuable
brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnist John Rogers puts Home Depot on his list of ``stocks to
avoid,'' arguing that rising interest rates could hurt the company
in two ways: All high-priced stocks are susceptible to rising
rates, and higher rates may hurt the company's housing market.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR DIVIDENDS
</P>
<P>
   Even the Federal Reserve has become concerned that corporations
don't pay out enough of their profits in dividends. Kiplinger's
Personal Finance Magazine (October) also looks at this situation in
its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
   That dividends don't get much respect shouldn't come as much of
a surprise, given the sharp increase in share prices in this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   While a strategy of buying only dividend-paying stocks has its
problems, ``dividends and income-oriented stocks still have a place
in many investors' portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund manager Stephan Klaffke gave Kiplinger's this
diversified income portfolio of stocks whose yields range from 0.2
percent to 9.7 percent, and average 3.8 percent: Bell Atlantic,
Chevron, First Union, Ford, Intel, H.J. Heinz, First Industrial
Realty Trust, International Flavors &AMP; Fragrances, National Fuel
Gas, J.C. Penney and Washington Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
