<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0786 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CITIES-FUTURE30-COX     09-29 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIES-FUTURE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 Atlanta pioneers toast city rebirth
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta today is facing problems that come from
growing up too fast, says John Portman Jr., one of Atlanta's
premier architects and developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving faster than our maturity is able to keep up,''
Portman said. ``We grew up too fast _ from a country town, to a
bigger town, to a regional city and then an international city.
That's all been done in the last 50 years. There's been such rapid
change. Looking back, I can tell you I never envisioned Atlanta
being where it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman has been a key player in the growth of Atlanta in the
past half century _ Peachtree Center, the Hyatt Regency, the Westin
Peachtree Plaza, the Marriott Marquis, the Atlanta Merchandise
Mart, the Atlanta Gift Mart, the Atlanta Apparel Mart, Inforum,
SunTrust Plaza _ to name a few of his projects.
</P>
<P>
   Portman and his longtime colleague _ Mickey Steinberg (who left
Portman to later become chairman of Sony Retail Entertainment) _
sat down for lunch earlier this week and reflected on the changes
in Atlanta, a city that is partly their creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we had to do it over again what we could
change,'' said Portman, who welcomes Atlanta's inward development
shift after decades of growth moving farther and farther out.
``What happened had more to do with demographics. There's no way to
go back and change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, however, said Atlanta had ``great missed
opportunities'' in how it developed. ``Development in downtown
Atlanta was fractured and there became competing nodes. It's
happening today. You have Underground Atlanta and what they are
trying to do with the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman, 74, attributed those forces to a downtown in
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once retail left, the southside of downtown lost its
raison-d'etre. We tried everything. But there was no there,
there,'' he said. ``Now there is great substance coming from
Georgia State University, the government and CNN. And housing is
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing has always been a key missing ingredient for downtown,
and Portman acknowledged that Peachtree Center would have been
stronger had there been a residential component.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to everything is financing,'' Portman said. ``All of
Peachtree Center was financed one building at a time by different
lenders. We couldn't finance a residential tower.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg agreed. ``We drew housing every way you could imagine
it. There was no way it was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they understood how critical housing was to central
Atlanta's success, Portman said they had to rationalize development
plans. ``Our rationale was that the bigger the job base we created
in downtown, the more demand there would be for housing in the
future. We wanted to build a job base for housing.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Atlanta has changed in the past 50 years, it's the
pace of current change that intrigues Portman.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we are getting ready to enter the 21st century, more things
are happening in a shorter period of time. Technology is moving at
such an unbelievably blinding speed, it's mind-boggling,'' Portman
said. ``We are in an era that is similar to the last turn of the
century when we were moving from an agrarian economy to an
industrial economy. At the end of this century, the engine that's
driving us now is not industry, but technology.''
</P>
<P>
   NO CONFLICT FOR ISAKSON
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.) wanted to make sure there was
no conflict of interest when the Trust for Public Land approached
him about buying some land in which he has a small interest.
Isakson is a minority owner in the Wilde Timber residential
development. He and his partners were approached by the trust ,
which is interested in buying about 22 acresalong the Chattahoochee
River for a greenway.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is providing $25 million to help in the
$100 million-plus effort to create the Chattahoochee Park. That's
an effort Isakson supports, but he wanted to be sure that no one
thought he was doing so with thought of personal gain.
</P>
<P>
   So he asked the U.S. House of Representatives Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct for guidance. The committee ruled
that Isakson's small interest in the property (1.3 percent) should
not bar him from debating or voting on the park.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson took it a step further. If he should ever receive any
money for the sale of his interest in theland, he will donate it to
the Trust for Public Land.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Saporta is assisted by Amy Winn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
