<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. governor visits Japan to seek trade increase
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes departs Saturday for Tokyo on his
first trip abroad to drum up more foreign investment for the state.
</P>
<P>
   The governor will attend the annual meeting of the Japan/U.S.
Southeast Association, a trade and investment conference for
Southeastern governors. He will also drop in on several companies
that are considered prospects for new or expanded investments in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is the leading foreign investor in Georgia, pumping $3.5
billion into the economy by the end of last year and accounting for
more than 28,000 jobs. It's also the No. 2 market for Georgia
exports, or $1.5 billion worth last year, after Canada. Though the
Japanese economy has been in a recession for several years, Barnes
hopes to set the stage for more investment when it recovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their economy is rebounding, and as they rebound there'll be
more investment,'' Barnes said. While his visits will also focus on
export promotion, ``investment is what I'm looking at,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will the trip be Barnes' first overseas trade mission,
but it will be his first trip outside the United States, except for
vacations within the Western Hemisphere. Barnes, 51, grew up in
Mableton, was educated at the University of Georgia, then served in
the General Assembly for 16 years and practiced law before his
election as governor last year.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the trip, he was briefed on Japanese customs and
protocol by the Southern Center for International Studies, an
Atlanta-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also spoke with former Govs. George Busbee, whose
administration saw the first rush of Japanese investment in 1975;
Joe Frank Harris, who serves on the board of AFLAC, the
Columbus-based insurer that gets 80 percent of its revenue from
Japan; and Zell Miller, who lured a number of foreign companies to
the state during trade missions and now works for a German real
estate firm. During his weeklong visit to Tokyo, Barnes will also
get the chance to compare notes with other Southeastern governors
on how they handle foreign trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who is being joined by his wife, Marie, and is flying
commercially, will also be accompanied by R.K. Sehgal, board
chairman of the state Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism;
Randolph Cardoza, commissioner of the department; and a Georgia
business delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, citing the crush of business at home, is opting out of a
trade and investment conference for the governors in Korea and
sending Cardoza in his stead.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the members of Barnes' trade delegation were attending
the business confabs in Japan and Korea anyway but were asked to be
part of the official Georgia delegation. Barnes said many of them
have local contacts that have been helpful.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation includes Raymond L. MacCain, vice president at
Cartersville-based Chemical Products Corp.; Ki Man Nam, president
of Good Nutrition of Norcross; Kevin Young Park, president of
Fashion World Enterprises of Union City; and Young Kyo Shinn,
chairman of Atlanta Oriental Food Wholesale Co. of Doraville.
Harris is also expected in Tokyo because of his AFLAC connection.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
