A0802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA30-COX     09-29 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    People's Republic turns 50
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The whole world will be watching as the People's
Republic of China observes its 50th birthday Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Brown Bullock, president of Agnes Scott College, needs
no special occasion to pay attention to China. She's been a
professional China watcher throughout her career.
</P>
<P>
   Her father was born there. She grew up in Asia _ Korea and Japan
_ where China was always a looming presence. And, after graduating
from Agnes Scott, she earned a Ph.D. in Chinese history at Stanford
University. Since 1974, she has traveled to mainland China at least
once a year.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent conversation, Bullock shared her views on China
as its Communist government began its anniversary celebration.
Excerpts from the interview follow:
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was your most recent visit?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was most recently there this summer in June. I was with the
National Committee on U.S.-China Relations. We were talking with
Chinese government leaders about the aftermath of the bombing of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade (during NATO's air strikes against
Yugoslavia) and the freezing up of U.S.-China relations at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What sort of response did you get?
</P>
<P>
   A: At that moment, the atmosphere was very hostile, and everyone
we met _ students, taxi drivers, old friends of mine as well as
government officials _ was exceedingly angry at not just the U.S.
bombing but the aftermath and the explanation. They did not believe
the explanation. ... We met with students at Beijing University who
had participated in the demonstrations at the American Embassy.
These were bright (students), and they were really insulted at the
way CNN and the American press had characterized their
participation. The American press, the world press, characterized
them as being manipulated by the government _ being bused in there
to demonstrate at the embassy. And there was undoubtedly some of
that. But they said, `You know, we had a legitimate right to be
angry.' And they reminded us that when the two American embassies
in Africa were bombed (by terrorists), we ordered (retaliatory)
military strikes in Afghanistan and Sudan. Someone said, `Well,
haven't you been influenced by the Chinese media?' And they said,
`We read the world media. We're on the Internet everyday, so we've
read The New York Times, we've read all the European media. We feel
well enough informed to make an independent judgment.'
</P>
<P>
   Q: China is observing the 50th anniversary of the People's
Republic. Has this 50-year period been more significant than other
50-year periods in China's long history?
</P>
<P>
   A: This has been a tremendously significant period for China.
... On the 50-year indicators of life expectancy, literacy, per
capita income, the move to international prestige, China has
improved more for its people in this 50-year period than in any
period in its history. ... Also, China was a pariah state in 1950,
isolated from the world. Today, whether people like the government
or not, it's a major player.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are some of the most likely scenarios you see emerging
there?
</P>
<P>
   Q: My crystal ball, you mean? ... I think the most likely
scenario is the continuation of a fairly authoritarian government
but with increasing pluralism, a continuation of the model somewhat
as you have it. I don't see a full-scale democratic government
emerging in a 10-year period. ... But you do find far more
pluralism in local government, in village elections, within the
organizations that comprise the party system. ... But I think that
the other issue is the extraordinary economic and social challenges
China faces today that are very destabilizing. They are committed,
and the Jiang Zemin government seems to be reaffirming the effort,
to continue restructuring the state-owned enterprises. ... They are
trying to turn them over to the market, and this brings with it
significant unemployment. And the level of unemployment in China
has risen dramatically. Q: You don't see them going to a full
market economy any time soon, though?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you look at other models in Asia of a market economy, you
find a variation on how much state involvement stays in the market.
Japan, (South) Korea, Taiwan, Singapore, all have more government
involvement in the market than we do. There are Asian models that
they are looking at that have more government involvement. And it
will take longer for them to develop some of the banking
infrastructure ... and to fully deregulate their state-owned
enterprises. Q: China's crackdown against the Falun Gong
meditational movement got a lot of attention here. Did that
surprise you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was surprised that their crackdown was as severe as it was.
But if you know anything about Chinese history you know why they
are so worried about Falun Gong. Falun Gong brings together
elements that are deep in Chinese history of cults, of heretical
religious groups and of very indigenous Chinese traditions. ... And
it has been movements of groups like that in the past that have
brought down dynasties. ... Another reason is the Chinese communist
state is at its core very modern and very anti-superstition.
They're embarrassed. My Chinese friends who are not party members
but are intellectuals are embarrassed by the continuation of deep
cults and superstition in Chinese society. So it has been also a
theme of this century to cut out superstition, and that is not just
a communist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you describe China's relations with other Asian
nations?
</P>
<P>
   A: China is paying a lot of attention right now to the nature of
its relations with other Asian countries. ... You could say it has
never enjoyed better relations. It has very active relations with
South Korea, economic and political. Its relations with Japan took
a downturn six months ago but they're trying to bring that back up.
It is an active player throughout the area. It has worked hard to
improve its relations with India, at the same time continuing as an
ally with Pakistan. China has been a behind-the-scenes player in
the Pakistan-India issue and did not give Pakistan all the support
it wanted in this latest conflict. So it was playing an important
positive role. By all accounts it has been an important force _
maybe not as key as we would like but nevertheless important _ in
keeping down North Korean adventurism, maybe not solving the
problems but keeping the lid on them. It plays a very important
role in the region. There is no question that (Asian) countries
worry about the power of China. It is the 800-pound gorilla that
they worry about economically and politically. And that is why many
of the Asian countries would like to have the U.S. stay involved in
the region as a potential counterweight to China.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of rising generation do you see in China?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you take a 19 year old in China today, they were born in
1980. Mao had been dead four years. They were born into the Deng
Xiaoping era. They do not know the Cultural Revolution; their
parents do not like to talk about it. They are 9 years old at the
time of (the) Tiananmen (Square massacre). And they have only seen
rising affluence and technology and sort of prosperity in their
time. There's no particular reason for them to be opposed to this
government as a generation, and they would be far more oriented
toward economic success than toward political revolution. In that,
they are not that different from my students.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the state of U.S.-China relations today?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we need a new start. I think the next administration
needs to give high priority to developing a new bipartisan
consensus on China _ and on Asia, for that matter. China is too
important of a relationship to be held to single-issue American
domestic politics. ... There needs to be consistency and there
needs to be leadership. ... We need an administration that will pay
as much attention to Asia as to the Middle East and NATO. ... You
have India and Pakistan, you have Korea, you have Indonesia, you
have China, you have the No. 2 economy in the world _ Japan. ... I
feel that we're muddling through and that's not good enough. There
are genuine differences between our government and China's
government. We should be concerned about human rights and we should
be concerned about trade imbalance. But it's how you put that in a
broad consistent policy. ... I get discouraged by the lack of deep
understanding on both sides. I think it's going to take a lot of
hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
