<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting the `there' back into politics
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Note from the campaign trail: There have been big
strides in the technology of ticker tape.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at Sen. John McCain's kickoff rallies this week
in Nashua, N.H., and Charleston, S.C., was made more festive by the
use of a couple of gadgets generically called confetti guns.
</P>
<P>
   One, a sort of cross between a wood chipper and a cannon, blasts
showers of confetti into the air with the use of CO2 cartridges.
Another, a device that appears fashioned out of PVC pipe, shoots
out long streamers with bulletlike speed. According to Roberta
Greenspon at Party Land, a local emporium of celebratory items,
confetti guns have been around a year or so, but this presidential
campaign marks their first appearance on the political scene.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the pressing issues being thrashed out in this
presidential campaign _ such as whether the United States should
have gotten into World War II, a question that preoccupied the chat
shows for a weekend after the publication of Pat Buchanan's new
book _ it may seem trivial to dwell on confetti guns.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything any of the candidates are saying right now,
however, this innovation points to a significant fact about the way
politics is practiced as we approach the millennium. In an age of
fax debates and Internet campaign contributions, confetti guns
point to a fundamental urge to gather some place, listen to a
speech, stand in a shower of colored paper and feel a visceral
connection with the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   To borrow from Gertrude Stein, the use of new gadgets to liven
up rallies suggests that in politics, there still needs to be some
``there'' there.
</P>
<P>
   To a great degree, modern politics is still shaped by a couple
of 19th-century inventions, the railroad and the telegraph, which
allowed candidates to vanquish the challenges of distance and
appeal to voters with a revolutionary immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   Whistle-stop tours long ago gave way to campaign fly-arounds,
and much of the significant communication in politics is done these
days by cell phone. But the dramatic staging of campaign politics _
the breathless arrival from the last stop on the trail, with the
latest word on the candidate's lips _ still borrows heavily from
the days when high-speed transportation and instantaneous
communication were a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   There was more evidence of the enduring primacy of place in Vice
President Al Gore's announcement that he's moving his campaign
headquarters from Washington to Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, it might have been more convenient to
keep the headquarters in Washington, where Gore lives _ although
with modern technology, it could as easily be located in Minot,
N.D., or Truth or Consequences, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   While it no longer matters much where a campaign installs its
phone banks, however, there's an enormous symbolic meaning _ only
belatedly realized by the Gore camp _ in where a campaign lifts its
standard.
</P>
<P>
   The location of a headquarters, in the age of the Web, remains
central to the question of who a candidate is, and where a
candidate goes still signifies who a candidate cares about. How
long this will remain the case, in an era when the meaning of place
and distance is being transformed, is uncertain. But for the first
campaign of the next century, at least, being there still counts
for something.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
