</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tipper Gore talks to Atlanta airport vendors
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tipper Gore used the Atlanta airport Wednesday as a
backdrop to demonstrate her husband's support for affirmative
action. But where Vice President Al Gore stands on the city's
beleaguered program of race-based preferences remained an open
question.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's wife campaigned for her husband's
presidential bid by talking with Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell and a
group of women and African-Americans who own businesses at
Hartsfield International Airport. Many told Gore they have
succeeded only because of the city's affirmative action program _ a
program that a conservative legal foundation has sued to overturn.
</P>
<P>
   She praised Campbell's ``extraordinary leadership for small
businesses experiencing and finding access here in the airport,''
which she described as a ``climate of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband,'' she added, ``has a strong, long-standing
commitment to affirmative action. ... It's very important the
federal government stands for affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   But when a reporter asked Gore what she thought of Atlanta's
program, Campbell interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Mrs. Gore knows much about our particular
program,'' the mayor said. ``I think it's unfair to ask her about
the specifics of the court challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Such questions did not fit into an event orchestrated so tightly
that the pocket of Gore's navy blue suit held the exact change for
the decaf cappuccino she bought at an airport coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and Secret Service agents escorted Gore into the airport's
Terminal B from the tarmac, even though she had driven to the
airport after spending Tuesday night in Atlanta and attending a
luncheon earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And she had little to say about politics, even about speculation
that actor Warren Beatty would announce later in the day whether he
will challenge her husband and former Sen. Bill Bradley for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard the speech yet,'' she said. ``I think he's a
wonderful actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
