<HEADER>
A0821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOD-RECOVERY-COX     09-29 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-RECOVERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shelters shift to Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The 600-plus displaced Pitt County residents
who remain in six school shelters after flooding caused by Hurrican
Floyd will be moved today so classes can resume Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With more permanent housing for some likely not available for
another two weeks, emergency officials decided Wednesday to shuttle
the 626 remaining shelter residents to Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after Hurricane Floyd hit the area, officials
scrambled to find housing for the hundreds of displaced residents
who can't return home because of flood damage.
</P>
<P>
   Crews continued Wednesday preparing foundations and utility
hookups on a County Home Road site earmarked to accommodate 200
trailers, which the Federal Emergency Management Agency will assign
to displaced residents. Those units won't be ready until the
weekend at the earliest, said FEMA spokesman Rudy Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Two more trailer sites, north of the Tar River, have been
identified, but officials aren't sure whether there will be enough
trailers there to accommodate all those displaced on the north side
of the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the shelters are the first concern,'' said
Arlen Holt, Pitt County spokesman. ``We are working on every
possible angle. Hotel rooms are full. Apartments are full _ at
least the ones that are open. We are doing everything we can.''
</P>
<P>
   As officials search for housing, city and county teams continue
to inspect dwellings that have been flooded. While some of those
renters and homeowners are able to return, about three-fourths of
the structures county teams examined need some repair before they
can be lived in, Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's anything from as small as replacing electrical outlets
to demolishing the structure,'' he said. ``(Inspectors) are finding
a mixed bag of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city has extended a state of emergency into a
third week.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration, which will expire Monday evening, allows
Greenville officials to restrict access to areas that remain
flooded or haven't been inspected for health and safety hazards.
</P>
<P>
   After spending 11 days in a school shelter, Evette and Gregory
Cogdell moved to their cousin's house Tuesday night. With their
Grifton home a total loss, they started looking for a permanent
place to stay Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for another home, but it's a fight because a lot
of people are looking for a home,'' Evette Cogdell said after
completing paperwork for Red Cross assistance. ``It's very
frustrating ... think about all the people who lost their houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of residents fled their homes after Hurricane Floyd
dumped more than a foot of rain on already saturated ground two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   After cresting at a record-shattering 29.72 feet Sept. 21, the
Tar River fell to 20.1 feet at 4:15 p.m. Wednesday, about a foot
less than the Tuesday night level.
</P>
<P>
   Rain showers during the past few days are keeping the river from
subsiding as quickly as officials had estimated, said Katie
Veilleux, the city's public information officer. It is dropping
about 1.5 feet daily.
</P>
<P>
   The rain also has hampered efforts to install the FEMA trailers
because of the soggy ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it very difficult to get the heavy equipment on
there. That has to happen before the trailers can move in,''
Hernandez said. ``We are working as hard as we can. Weather
permitting, we should start seeing some real progress in four to
five days.''
</P>
<P>
   In four days, students at the Pitt County Schools will return to
class for the first time since Sept. 15, a day before Hurricane
Floyd hit. Teachers and staff report to work today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are optimistic that there will be alternate housing for the
folks in the shelters so we can get school going,'' said Barry
Gaskins, the schools' public information director. ``We are moving
forward at a feverish pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Classes resume Monday on a two-hour delay, which will give the
busses time to maneuver around damaged roads, Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   In arranging housing at the Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs, county officials
tried to find a spot where the evacuees could stay for several
weeks until permanent shelter is found, Holt said. Displaced
residents who fled to Greenville shelters were moved last week
after the city lost water service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we are concerned about is we don't want to keep
moving people around. We want to be sensitive to that,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also are developing a mobile home site north of the
Tar River, which was hit hard by the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   Crews are conducting environmental assessments on a site east of
Oak Grove Estates. If the site is approved for mobile homes,
residents could move there by mid-October, City Manager Ron Kimble
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a race to make sure we get temporary housing on the
ground before those families have to hit the streets,'' Kimble
said.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two weeks of staying in shelters, some evacuees are
anxious to find some type of housing somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to leave. I'm ready to get settled,'' said Sandra
West, who has stayed at the Ayden Elementary School shelter for
more than a week. Her Grifton home isn't inhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   Stephlee Simmons, who has stayed at a shelter since she fled her
Grifton house Sept. 19, returned home for a peek at the damage
Tuesday. Mold had already started growing inside the house and
nearly all the contents were soaked, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'm going to go to right now,'' Simmons
said while thumbing through photos of her damaged home. ``It's just
questionable. You just wonder what you are going to do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, city officials estimated the flood has cost
the city $23.5 million in damage, cleanup and overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   That includes $5.5 million each for the Pitt-Greenville Airport
and the housing authority, $5 million for debris removal, $4.5
million in damage to buildings and facilities and $1.5 million each
for street damage and overtime for emergency workers.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate will be forwarded to FEMA, which reimburses
governments for costs incurred during natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary county estimates top $200 million, but are likely to
increase as county officials continue assessing damages.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville Utilities, which had its water plant, electric
substation and operations center submerged, is still compiling its
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA already has earmarked $2.9 million for temporary housing in
eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   About 6,835 Pitt County residents _ the most of any North
Carolina county _ have applied for all types of FEMA aid, including
housing, small business loans and unemployment assistance,
Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials aren't sure how many of those applicants need housing
or whether the trailers arriving here will be enough to accommodate
the homeless. Still, Hernandez says, the government will do
whatever it takes to arrange housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something we are constantly reassessing,'' he said.
``Will there be enough travel trailers? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
