<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Equipment big issue for `sewn products'
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Outsourcing and technology are the top issues facing
the apparel industry as the Bobbin Americas show opens in Atlanta
today at the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of manufacturing overseas and the increased
competition from foreign investors have long been issues in the
industry. But the traditionally labor-intensive industry is
increasingly relying on technology to make manufacturing and
distribution more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the primary draw is the equipment,'' said Jack
Morgan, a spokesman for the Virginia-based American Apparel
Manufacturers Association, which co-sponsors the event. ``This is a
competitive business. Everybody is looking to see how technology
can enhance competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 buyers and sellers of equipment, products and
services for the ``sewn products'' industry will be in Atlanta for
the show and the annual convention of the AAMA. Sewn products
include apparel, home textiles, carpets and rugs, footwear,
luggage, accessories, medical products, toys, crafts and
upholstered furniture. Apparel, alone, represents a $180 billion
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The show attracted about 14,000 last year in Atlanta. Exhibitors
are down to 1,900 from 4,200 last year. But organizers say the 1998
show, an exhibit called Bobbin World that is held every three
years, always attracts more interest. Bobbin Americas, held in the
two years between international exhibits, focuses on the Western
Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt the convention is probably smaller because
of attrition among U.S. manufacturers. The United States continues
to lose manufacturing, said Sergio Cruz, a vice president of Kurt
Salmon Associates, although Asia is no longer the hot spot.
Increasingly, manufacturing is moving to the Caribbean and Mexico,
where labor is cheap but plants are close to the United States
market.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of sales from goods made in the United States is
expected to fall to 36 percent in 2000 compared with 41 percent
this year, while it will rise to 16 percent from 13 percent in
Mexico and 18 percent from 16 percent in the Caribbean and Central
America. Asia will remain steady at 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturing is going south,'' Cruz said. ``In Mexico, there
is a more favorable trade environment. We're seeing more Asians _
especially Hong Kong-based and Taiwanese investors setting up
capacity in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
