<SLUG> BC-OLY-HOMEDEPOT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot boosts Olympics dreams
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Derek Mills certainly is one of the fastest recruits
at Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   If you see an orange streak dashing through the electrical
department, it's probably him. Mills is part of a new crew of
Olympic hopefuls employed by Home Depot during the countdown to
next year's Summer Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   As a sponsor of the U.S. and Canadian teams, the Atlanta-based
home improvement retailer has hired 71 sprinters, boxers, kayakers
and other athletes as part of an Olympic job program.
</P>
<P>
   The company pays the athletes full-time wages and benefits, but
they work an average of 20 hours a week. The rest of the time is
used to train for competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program works perfectly for the athletes because it
allows us to train at top speed and make money,'' said Mills, who's
hoping to compete in the 400-meter run. Mills won a gold medal in
the 1996 Summer Games in Atlanta as part of the men's 1,600-meter
relay.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Depot effort, which includes the opportunity to buy
stock, is a lucrative option for the amateur athletes. Many are
used to cobbling together a living by waiting tables or coaching
kids at summer camps, said Kelli James, a field hockey player who
just finished her second year at a Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to retire from hockey because I couldn't support
myself financially before I got this job,'' said James, whose team
won a bronze medal in the 1996 Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Field hockey competition requires trips abroad that may last up
to three months, James noted. The athletes typically work
additional hours while not training to make up for extended travel
time. Home Depot is the largest Olympic supporter among three U.S.
companies that pay athletes full-time wages for part-time work. The
other two are JC Penney and U.S. West Communications. Home Depot
also sponsors a similar Olympic program in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 other companies employ athletes through typical
part-time arrangements, said Keith Bryant, manager of the U.S.
Olympic Committee Athlete Services division. The committee acts as
a broker between athletes and sponsors. Home Depot spent more than
$1 million a year to subsidize salaries and benefits for athletes
in the 1996 Olympics. The retailer won't say how much it is
spending now.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a goal of employing 100 Olympic and Paralympic
athletes and has Olympic sponsorships through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
