<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEARNS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investor accused of attempting to defraud companies of $26
million
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Federal authorities believe Austin investor
Brian Russell Stearns conspired with unidentified accomplices to
defraud two foreign corporations of $26 million earlier this year,
according to documents filed in a New York federal court.
</P>
<P>
   None of Stearns' alleged accomplices has been arrested,
authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. postal inspectors in New York City have accused Stearns,
29, of telling a trust administrator that he owned $48.4 million in
bonds, which later turned out to be nonexistent, according to a
wire fraud complaint filed in court.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns is accused of conspiring with others to use the fake
bonds as collateral to secure $26 million in loans from the trust
representing the Panama-based Ivor Wolfson Corp., and Tremmer Ltd.,
headquartered in the British Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the loans, Stearns, working with an unidentified
``investment adviser,'' promised in February to repay double the
trust's initial $20 million loan by March 2000 by trading in
medium-term notes, according to the complaint signed by U.S. Postal
Inspector Robert Mignogna.
</P>
<P>
   The two corporations filed a civil lawsuit against Stearns in
August seeking to recover their money.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns rejects claims that he defrauded the companies and
denies any criminal wrongdoing, said his attorney, Laird Palmer of
Mason. Stearns' attorneys in New York have filed a counterclaim
against Wolfson and Tremmer, alleging the companies charged him an
excessive fee for the $26 million in loans, Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies charged Brian a highly usurious rate for the
loans,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   New York attorney Thomas Moreland, who represents Wolfson and
Tremmer, declined to comment when contacted by phone Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and Internal Revenue Service agents raided Stearns' $2
million-plus Lake Austin estate last week, charging him with
defrauding a Georgia investor of $3.3 million. Authorities also
seized Stearns' property, including two jets worth more than $10
million, a $2 million helicopter and $800,000 worth of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns had hired several area off-duty police officers,
including Austin Parks Police and city marshals, to guard his home.
An Austin police detective was paid to run personal errands for
Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns, convicted of felony grand theft in Maryland in 1994,
faces additional charges of illegally possessing firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities also are investigating allegations that
Stearns may have defrauded more than 100 residents of the town of
Brady of more than $4 million in another investment scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns married Brady's then-reigning Miss Heart of Texas,
19-year-old Raegan Martin, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, her parents and about 30 of Stearns' friends and
relatives from Brady were in federal court in Austin on Wednesday
as a show of support for Stearns, making an initial appearance on
the New York wire fraud charge.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing handcuffs and a jail-issued jump suit, Stearns gave his
supporters a double thumbs-up sign as U.S. marshals ushered him
into the courtroom. After the hearing, Stearns, a naturalized U.S.
citizen from Korea, turned around to the packed gallery and said,
``Thanks for coming, guys.''
</P>
<P>
   He is being held in federal custody at the Bastrop County Jail;
bail has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   According to the wire fraud complaint, Stearns and his
unidentified Texas attorney met with the trust director in New York
City in March to close on the $20 million loan from Wolfson using a
$40 million Federal Home Bank bond as collateral. About this same
time, the Texas attorney faxed the trust director what turned out
to be a forged bank letter confirming Stearns' ownership of the
bonds, the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns later agreed to wire the bonds to a New York securities
firm, which would hold them as collateral until Stearns repaid the
debt, according to the complaint. But when the trust director
contacted the securities firm to verify it had the bonds, he
received a letter saying the firm did not receive the bonds and
that Stearns' account had been closed, the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   When the trust director confronted Stearns with that
information, Stearns allegedly had Austin-based Trans-Global Asset
Management Group Inc. send the director copies of the lien on the
bond. What Stearns did not tell the director, the complaint says,
is that Stearns owns Trans-Global.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in April, Stearns persuaded the trust director to loan him
another $6 million from Tremmer with the promise that Stearns would
repay the trust $8.4 million by June 28. As security for the loan,
Stearns put up what turned out to be fraudulent Barclay's Bank
bonds purporting to be worth $8.4 million, according to the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   When the June 28 repayment deadline passed with no word from
Stearns, the trust director flew to Austin to talk to Stearns, the
complaint says. Stearns allegedly agreed to have $10 million wired
directly to Tremmer, but when the director contacted the company's
bank, he learned only $10,000 had been wired to the account,
according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns then allegedly picked up the phone, dialed a number and
handed the director the phone. A person identifying himself as a
bank employee was on the line and confirmed that the full $10
million had been deposited, according to the postal inspector's
report.
</P>
<P>
   The trust director hung up the phone and then called the bank
back and was told the money had not arrived, the complaint says.
The trust director filed a complaint with the U.S. Postal Inspector
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
