<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATECH30-COX     09-29 0296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech goal: Take care of business
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before the season, Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary
said one goal for the program was to maintain its lofty standing.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 9-ranked Yellow Jackets have done that. Now, they must
live up to it.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, upstart Maryland visits Bobby Dodd Stadium. The
undefeated Terrapins not only are determined to prove they are for
real, they also are relishing the chance to measure themselves
against one of the elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly Georgia Tech has become, in the last two years, a
top-10 program,'' Maryland coach Ron Vanderlinden said Wednesday.
``That's such a weighty statement that they are in that company,
and deservedly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have done a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech has stayed true to its slogan of approaching the year as
``Eleven One-Game Seasons,'' but it is doubtful that this date
against Maryland _ which, with three victories, has matched its
1998 total _ was lumped into the big-game category.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, every Tech game has major implications, with no margin
for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chore (tonight) to make sure that we take care of
business,'' O'Leary said. ``We're 0-1 (in the ACC), and we can't
afford any other losses. It's a big game, and our players
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ESPN cameras on hand, the game presents another
opportunity for quarterback Joe Hamilton to impress Heisman Trophy
voters and for the Jackets to make a mark with poll voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you play on Thursday night, it's a good game, because
it gives you so much exposure _ good and bad,'' O'Leary said. ``We
have to go out and do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
