<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurting personnel slowing pass rush
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In falling from Super Bowl team to 0-3, the Atlanta
Falcons' pass rush has been awful.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has gotten only two sacks, both in the same game, and
has just 16 quarterback pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are last in the NFL, with one sack every 41 passing
plays; the NFL average is one every 13.9 passing plays.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, they will end up with 11 sacks and 85 pressures.
Last season, Atlanta had 38 sacks and 159 pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really bad right now,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``We've
got to keep working... because you don't... become that bad that
quick with the same people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester Archambeau, 32, led the team with 10 sacks last year.
Travis Hall, 27, Shane Dronett, 28, and Chuck Smith, 29, are not
old by NFL standards. But they are beat up.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has a sprained right big toe, and, because he is slowed at
right end, offensive lines sometimes cheat their pass protection on
that side toward tackle Dronett.
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Hall tore left thumb ligaments two weeks ago and
will continue wearing a cast for a couple of months. He also has
battled a deep hip bruise, and his reduced effectiveness lets
offenses cheat toward left end Archambeau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Smith has been a shadow of his former self,'' defensive
coordinator Rich Brooks said. ``Travis' hand is a problem. We're
not shrinking the pocket with pressure up the middle. Without that
push up the middle, Lester has not been effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side is we're not covering (receivers) well enough
to force the quarterback to hold the ball'' long enough to be
sacked, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Dronett has a badly strained right calf, and, although he said
he will try to practice today, Reeves expects him to miss at least
one game.
</P>
<P>
   Backup tackle Ed Jasper is definitely out at least two weeks
with a partially torn left knee ligament. The team's fourth
defensive tackle, Ben Huff, spent last season on the practice
squad, and right foot and ankle injuries have bothered him.
</P>
<P>
   And blitzing brings inherent dangers. ``When you do that, they
get man coverage, or you have zones... you can't account for,''
Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone has injuries. The players must compensate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play nicked in this game,'' Archambeau said. ``Winning the
NFC Championship, people study your defense, study your players,
and they have better answers. But part of it is we're just not
playing well, especially our four starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to come out there with more intensity, more
enthusiasm, flying around, knocking balls loose, like we did last
year? Or are we not?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
