<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revamped line clears the path for Peterson
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even with three new starters, Georgia Southern's
offensive line has opened up enough holes for the Eagles to average
404 rushing yards and 55.3 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   With senior Tom Jiles taking over at center, junior Michael
Anderson at right tackle and Brian Scott at left guard, Georgia
Southern also is averaging 7.1 yards per rushing attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But the coaching staff is proving to be a tough bunch to please.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're making progress, but they're not where we want
them to be,'' head coach Paul Johnson said. ``They're playing hard,
and when that happens, it gives you a chance to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson admits to being extremely tough in grading each player
game by game. His Eagles (3-1, 2-0 Southern Conference), headed by
senior quarterback Greg Hill and All-American fullback Adrian
Peterson, use six plays, for the most part. The wrong footwork or a
bad read or reach on a block affects a player's grade.
</P>
<P>
   In a 49-10 rout of conference foe Chattanooga, Tenn., over the
weekend, senior tackle Rich McGrath of Snellville, a four-year
starter, had the highest grade among offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGrath graded out a little above 30 percent,'' Johnson said.
``We're not like a lot of coaching staffs that grade players at 95
percent even when the team is winning by only six or seven points.
Our players understand that if they get over 50 percent, they've
played well.''
</P>
<P>
   The player who had the highest grade against Chattanooga was
Peterson, with 84 percent, Johnson said. Peterson carried the ball
21 times for 222 yards and four touchdowns. Against Virginia
Military on Saturday, he can tie the Division I-AA record of 20
consecutive 100-yard rushing games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
