<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daly: `I did it my way'
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ John Daly says he's loose again, as in
relaxed and free and no longer depriving himself of booze and
blackjack.
</P>
<P>
   People who know and love Daly also say he's loose, as in, ``God,
please help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fired by Callaway Golf on Sept. 15 after refusing to enter a
treatment facility for his alcohol and gambling addictions, Daly,
33, has decided to fight the battle by himself. He is drinking and
is confident he can control the disease. He can handle a few beers,
he says. He's well-schooled in the advice from others: When you're
an alcoholic, it's like trying to stop the falling hammer of a
loaded gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I know the odds are not great,'' Daly said while hitting
range balls at Callaway Gardens, site of today's first round of the
Buick Challenge. ``I'm truly able to accept that.... I'm not saying
it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the scariest part. Daly, his chocolate-brown shirt
sweat-drenched in heavy humidity, talks as if his battle finally
has ended. Instead, he could be approaching the worst part of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Elvis, baby,'' said Daly, who has decided that
living according to others' wishes is like laying up on par-5s.
``When I die, and they bury me on the 18th teebox up at Bay Ridge,
six feet above the ground, I'm going to put, `I did it my way,' and
they're going to play that song.''
</P>
<P>
   That Daly mentions death only makes the prognosis more
frightening. While Daly is smoking Marlboros and mashing golf
balls, a steady stream of people come by _ PGA Tour commissioner
Tim Finchem included _ to ask how he's doing. Hugely overweight and
bloated, Daly breaks out a cigarette every few shots.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial question is obvious: What makes Daly think it will
be different this time? What evidence is there that the furniture
in his hotel room will survive?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: There is none. Daly simply decided that he would
rather crash and burn than continue a life of avoidance. ``It's in
my blood,'' he explained last week, the statement featured later on
a Golf World magazine cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say it's not going to go to the extremes it
did before,'' Daly says. ``Who's to say? I'm thinking and hoping
maturity has a lot to do with it. I feel like I've grown up a
little. Maybe not a lot. I think I've signed every scorecard this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he won the British Open four years ago, Daly has generated
few performance-related headlines. The news has been of divorces,
drinking binges, tournament withdrawals and double-figure scores.
He hasn't managed a top-25 finish since February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's neat to get a front cover on a golf magazine when I
hadn't played worth a crap for four years,'' Daly said. ``I felt a
little bad because (Brad) Faxon won (at the B.C. Open) and (Tom)
Watson wins his first senior tournament, and they don't get on the
cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly still plays his Callaway's Hawkeye woods and irons _ ``Mr.
C is still like a father to me,'' he said _ but caddie Brian
Alexander carries a brown leather bag with a red Arkansas Razorback
logo, given to him by a Memphis, Tenn., car-dealer pal who won it
in a tournament. Daly owns the ``Grip-It-And-Rip-It'' name, which
will be on a new white bag that's on order.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name, the hog on it, white with big letters _ it's gonna be
sweet,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's PGA Tour colleagues are confused. They glance at him,
eyes widening at his newly expanded girth. The goggled sunglasses
already give him an Elvis-type look. That he owns two major
championships, the 1991 PGA and the 1995 British Open, is sometimes
a staggering reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to think,'' Jay Haas said. ``I suppose past
history shows he shouldn't be doing what he's doing. Whether he can
handle it this time remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Faxon said last week after hearing about Callaway's
decision, ``It's about time we stopped feeling sorry for John and
somebody kicked him in the (rear).''
</P>
<P>
   For 1998 U.S. Amateur champion and rookie Hank Kuehne, an
alcoholic at 19 who has now been sober for nearly five years,
Daly's choice is particularly troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's his own man, and obviously he's making whatever decisions
he thinks are right for him,'' Kuehne said. ``At least I got to go
through my recovery on my own. He's in the spotlight. Man, the
lowest point I've ever seen was when he's on ESPN (during play at
the 1998 Vancouver Open) crying and cold-sweating, and it's 90
degrees outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Daly has multiple addictions _ alcohol, gambling,
sugar, cigarettes _ Kuehne said, ``It's all the same demon. It just
takes on different forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked the status of his gambling, Daly says, ``Uh, not good....
But it's fun. It's so damn much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions in gambling losses have added to Daly's near-$40,000
monthly obligations for child support, alimony and mortgage. He
recently had to sell one of his cars, a $50,000 Corvette. His only
endorsement contract, now that Callaway has fired him, is with the
Ancona shirt company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be able to live the way the way I used to
live,'' Daly said, ``but the way I look at it, as long as I've got
enough money to pay for my caddie, Brian, enough that my house is
paid for, enough gas in the cars, enough to pay my girls each
month, what else do I need?''
</P>
<P>
   Daly contends that his personal life is better. His fiancee,
Shanae Chandler, is able to understand him, he says, where the
women of three failed marriages have not. And he's more relaxed on
the golf course. Daly said now that he's drinking again, he enjoys
``being able to sit at home with some buddies, have a beer and
watch some football games.'' The social chains, he said, have been
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to stay sober and trying to play golf, I wasn't the
same guy,'' he said. ``For the last three years, I've been so damn
tense out here, worrying about it, afraid if I missed one shot....
It was weird. I felt like I'd lost a lot of contact with the
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind amber sunglasses, Daly will step to the first tee today
at 8:59 a.m., embarking on the improbable mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any expectations this week,'' he said. ``Just go
out and play, enjoy the fans, quit worrying. I don't need to worry
about it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
