<SLUG> BC-GLF-FEATURE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love speaks from heart
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Davis Love III doesn't want to hear any
more about it. For the Europeans to be griping about poor behavior
from American fans and players at the Ryder Cup, he said, clearly
indicates either sour grapes, short memories or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just got pounded into the ground Sunday, and they're
embarrassed by it, as we were at Oak Hill (in 1995), '' Love said
Wednesday after arriving to begin play today in the Buick Challenge
at Callaway Gardens. ``We didn't cry when we lost two in a row . .
. . It's too bad there's all this bickering when it was the best
Ryder Cup ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Love said the fans were rude to both Americans and Europeans
last week. Love heard snide references to his 0-4 record at
Valderrama in 1997. Playing a team match with David Duval, he heard
several barbs thrown at the former Georgia Tech player, asking,
``So, how do you like the `exhibition' now?''
</P>
<P>
   Love also remembers the 1993 Ryder Cup matches at The Belfry in
England and ``people poking umbrellas through the fence trying to
trip us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And how long,'' Love said, ``have they been calling our wives
`flight attendants' and `blond bimbos'?''
</P>
<P>
   At Valderrama in Spain in 1997, Love said, people ``were
downright ugly to us . . . coughing and yelling and cheering when
we missed a putt.''
</P>
<P>
   European players and captain Mark James this week have hinted of
a boycott of the matches at Oakland Hills in 2003 as fallout from
the Americans' celebration on the 17th green Sunday and fan
rowdiness at The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad that they're whining so much,'' Love said. ``I guess
when you get pounded like that, you've got to find some reason for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard, the man of the moment Sunday, said, ``If grudges
are held, there's nothing I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If one thing really bothers Love, it's the relentless, personal,
embarrassing attacks on Scotland's Colin Montgomerie. Not only are
they unfair, they're pushing Montgomerie to some tremendous golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our fans need to do is quit doing it, because it's making
Monty play better,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Love said he is not worried about relationships among the
American players being strained, because they survived comments by
Montgomerie before Valderrama. Montgomerie later apologized for
remarks he made about Brad Faxon's divorce and Scott Hoch's missed
putt at the 1989 Masters influencing their Ryder Cup play.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the American players were upset all week with the
Europeans' slow play. Love insisted it was an intentional motive on
their part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet you a million dollars their strategy was slow play,
because they knew it frustrated us,'' Love said. ``Somebody's got
to have told them, `Put it into `Four Corners. It will bother these
guys.'. . . Nobody heard Mark O'Meara complain about (Padraig)
Harrington taking 10 minutes to get off a shot at 18.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the fan conduct, which has grown worse by the month on
the PGA Tour, Love would favor another look at beer sales. Combined
with the close proximity of the fans last week in an event oversold
by about 10,000 persons per day, beer consumption loosened plenty
of tongues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that if they cut off beer sales at a baseball
game in the seventh innning, they ought to cut it off at 2 o'clock
at a golf tournament,'' Love said. ``They sold an awful lot of
tickets last week. There were an awful lot of people there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
