<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Door open for Arsenal
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just when it looked as if Barcelona would be the only
team with a perfect record emerging from the first half of
first-round group play in the European Champions League, Arsenal
had a dramatic answer to keep the dreaded Group B race tight.
</P>
<P>
   Nwankwo Kanu slammed home a rebound in the 81st minute, and the
Gunners earned a 1-1 draw Wednesday at the formidable Estadio Nou
Camp. Barcelona still leads the London club seven points to five.
Fiorentina, with only two points, lost ground in a scoreless draw
with AIK Solna in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   The Champions League takes a three-week break before the final
three group match days resumes on Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenal appeared to be a beaten team just a minute before the
equalizer, when Gilles Grimandi was sent off for elbowing Barca's
Josep Guardiola. But Kanu, who had come off the bench in the second
half, finished off Davor Suker's initial strike at goalkeeper Ruud
Hesp, who couldn't clear. Luis Enrique's 16th-minute goal
symbolized the early dominance of the Spanish club, but the second
half was all Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the only late comeback Wednesday. Manchester United's
bad form looked like it would sink the defending European
champions, who trailed Olympique Marseille 2-1 late at Old
Trafford. But Andy Cole tied the match in the 79th minute and Paul
Scholes got the winner with seven minutes left as the Red Devils
won 2-1 to take a one-point lead over the French club in Group D.
</P>
<P>
   And in Group C, Rosenborg Trondheim rallied from a 2-0 deficit
to tie Borussia Dortmund, with John Carew's 68th-minute goal
getting the Norwegians a point to keep them tied with the German
giants at the top. Bayer Leverkusen couldn't hold on to a 1-0 lead
at home in Group A, as Dynamo Kyiv pulled out a 1-1 draw in the
71st minute. Lazio leads the group thanks to a 4-0 romp over
Maribor of Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid took charge in Group E by defeating previously
spotless Porto 3-1 on Tuesday. In Athens, Barcelona castoff
Giovanni struck for two goals for the second time in the Champions
League, and Olympiakos routed Norwegian side Molde 3-1 to stay a
point behind Porto. ... Bayern Munich managed a testy 1-1 home draw
with Valencia, with both teams tied at the top of Group F. Glasgow
Rangers got an 83rd-minute goal from substitute Jorg Albertz to
defeat PSV Eindhoven.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea earned its first Champions League victory 1-0 over
Galatasaray, with midfielder Dan Petrescu scoring in the second
half. But the English side remains a point behind Group H leaders
Hertha Berlin and AC Milan, which tied 1-1 on Tuesday. Oliver
Bierhoff evened up matters in the 74th minute for the Italian
champions.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: IS 'ANIMAL' CRACKERS?
</P>
<P>
   Eccentric Vasco de Gama forward Edmundo scored four goals last
week, but the player known as ``The Animal'' got more headlines for
the way in which he threw a party for his son's first birthday.
Authorities in Rio de Janeiro said they might prosecute the former
Fiorentina player for animal abuse after he served beer to a
chimpanzee borrowed from a local circus troupe. On Sunday, Edmundo
scored two goals as Vasco stayed in contention for the Brazilian
national championship with a 2-0 win over Internacional.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: 'GOLES' GALORE
</P>
<P>
   The eight games played on the Invierno schedule over the weekend
produced 39 goals, none more surprising than in the 5-0 rout by
mediocre Atletico Celaya over Guadalajara. Carlos Pavon had a hat
trick and Luis Fernando Soto had the other two for Celaya. ....
Carlos Maria Morales scored a hat trick as Toluca ripped Toros Neza
6-1 to remain on top of the overall league lead with 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
