<SLUG> BC-FBC-WISC-DAYNE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When Dayne was little, he was big
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ With size now one of his greatest assets, it's
hard to believe Ron Dayne once was too big to play football.
</P>
<P>
   As a 5-9, 230-pound eighth-grader in Berlin, N.J., Dayne was
banned from youth football because coaches feared he'd hurt the
smaller players. He hadn't been allowed to play as a sixth- or
seventh-grader, either. Instead, he played soccer, where his
imposing figure made opponents scatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine kids getting in his way?'' said Dayne's uncle,
Rob Reid, who raised his nephew from the eighth grade on. ``He'd
kick that ball and you didn't want to be in front of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, Wisconsin's 5-10, 255-pound record-breaking tailback, has
a similar effect on college defenders. Though they've dared to get
in his way, they've had little success stopping him or even slowing
him down. On Saturday, No. 12 Ohio State will get its chance.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne comes to Ohio Stadium as the Big Ten's all-time rushing
leader (5,703 yards) after recently surpassing former conference
rushing king and two-time Heisman Trophy winner, Archie Griffin of
Ohio State (5,589 yards). These statistics include bowl games. If
he averages 157.9 yards in Wisconsin's seven remaining
regular-season games, he will replace Ricky Williams (6,279) as the
NCAA's top career rusher. NCAA statistics do not include bowl
games.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to get Dayne, a Heisman Trophy candidate, to talk
about his run for the record is as tough as trying to tackle him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think about it,'' he said. ``I'm all about team.
I'd rather win than get the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne gave himself the opportunity to make NCAA history when he
decided to stay in Madison, Wis., for his senior season instead of
leaving school early for the NFL. Friends and family say his
predicted status in this past spring's draft as a second- or maybe
third-round pick and his desire to earn a college degree and be
with his 1-year-old daughter, Jada, all influenced him to stick
around for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really the joy of his life,'' Wisconsin senior
linebacker Donnel Thompson said of Jada. ``He kind of melts around
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has a 4-year-old son, Donnel Jr., and he and Dayne
often take their kids to the zoo or the beach together. Dayne said
he spends every Friday with Jada, who turns 2 in November, and
stops by his girlfriend's apartment almost every night to tuck his
daughter into bed. On game day, she wears a miniature version of
her daddy's No. 33 jersey or a red and white Badgers cheerleader
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said Dayne didn't expect to be a father this soon, but he's
proud that his nephew hasn't shirked his responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly could have disconnected himself, but he really
stepped up,'' said Reid, a social worker who is Dayne's legal
guardian along with his wife, Debbie. ``Ron has a special affection
for little kids. He will sign autographs for little guys until his
hand drops off. I think because he went through a period of time
where his parents weren't doing the best and he had to raise his
younger sister (Onya) himself, he was kind of used to being the
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's parents divorced when Ron and Onya were young and drug
problems made it difficult for his mother to care for the kids. Rob
Reid said he didn't want his nephew to become ``another black kid
who was just swallowed up without a father figure,'' so Dayne moved
in with him, his wife and three kids. Onya went to live with
another aunt and uncle nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Being a kid in a man's body was a burden for the young Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was misunderstood by people,'' Reid said. ``He was
always the biggest kid in his class, so he got special attention
from students who wanted to be his best friend and from teachers
who thought, `I'd better stay on top of this kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne found his place on the football field where he was a
bruising All-American fullback who occasionally spent time at
tailback. Wisconsin coaches thought his greatest potential was at
the latter position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had great vision,'' Alvarez said. ``And he had legitimate
track times (Dayne runs a 4.5 40-yard dash) and was very good in
the open field. We thought regardless of his size he could be a
very good tailback.''
</P>
<P>
   If Dayne rushes for 1,105 yards more, he could be the NCAA's
best.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
