A1026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS-ANALYSI     09-29 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-ANALYSIS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers get serious
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ School opened in earnest Wednesday for the Atlanta
Thrashers. The last exhibition had been played, the roster
shrinkage nearly complete and Curt Fraser felt the time was right.
</P>
<P>
   When the Thrashers coach sensed his players were suffering from
mental lapses during drills at practice, he called the team
together at center ice and dropped a few verbal grenades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make sure they got the point that we have to be
creative in practice so that when we get in games we can use that
to our advantage,'' Fraser said later. ``The game is all about
habits. When I see players bring poor habits from other teams here,
I'll put a stop to it. We want them to start fresh. Create better
habits. Down the road, it will make us a better team. Bad habits,
bad team.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense of urgency now because Fraser realizes that,
short some tweaking by general manager Don Waddell, the team is
complete and the season opener is Saturday against New Jersey at
Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks after opening training camp in Orlando, Fla., with 65
players, the Thrashers are left with pretty much what Waddell
anticipated when he was penciling mock expansion drafts in June: a
team that should be strong in goal, solid on defense and short on a
scoring touch.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, this doesn't leave the Thrashers dramatically
different than most other NHL teams. As center Ray Ferraro said,
``There's probably only 10 gifted goal scorers in the league. We
don't have a Brett Hull who can sit around and bury goals on the
power play. We don't have a (Joe) Sakic or a (Peter) Forsberg. But
most other teams don't either.'' A breakdown of the likely
opening-night roster, with the number likely to be kept at the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   _ Goaltenders (2): Damian Rhodes and Norm Maracle both looked
sharp in exhibitions, rarely allowing what could be termed a weak
goal. Maracle probably had the strongest showing of any goalie in
training camp and figures to start about 25 games. Fraser,
envisioning a tilted ice surface, smiled and said, ``Believe me, he
will get his work.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Defense (7): The Thrashers still have nine on the roster, with
Maxim Galanov and Brett Clark (neither of whom played in the final
exhibition) the likely players to go. The play from the blue line
generally has been strong, particularly that of Darryl Shannon,
Petr Buzek and Yannick Tremblay. Gord Murphy, Kevin Dean, Chris
Tamer and David Harlock round out the unit. Dean, Tamer, Buzek and
Harlock all can be physical players. Buzek, Tremblay and Murphy all
are strong with the puck. Shannon has been solid all the way
around. Galanov probably is the best offensive defenseman on the
roster but has made several errant passes in his own end.
</P>
<P>
   _ Left wingers (5): Andrew Brunette, Johan Garpenlov, Denny
Lambert, Matt Johnson and Vladimir Vujtek are the keepers. But
there are problems. Vujtek (facial cut) is at least one week from
returning, more likely two weeks. Brunette and Garpenlov both have
been counted on for goal scoring but neither is getting near the
net. Roster movement is possible, although Garpenlov's salary
($975,000) makes a trade or demotion to the minors unlikely.
Lambert, a physical spark plug, had a strong preseason. Johnson
started slow and finished strong. In Orlando (IHL) is Jason
Botterill, who impressed coaches but was the victim of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Centers (4): Ferraro (back) and Patrik Stefan (groin), the No.
1 and No. 2 centers, were ailing as the preseason ended, but
neither injury is considered serious. Mike Stapleton's play led to
Terry Yake being lost in the waiver draft. The No. 4 spot currently
is filled by Per Svartvadet. But the Thrashers like Andreas
Karlsson, who is in Orlando, and Svartvadet could be moved back to
left wing, pending vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right wingers (5): Toughness and size aren't a problem with
Kelly Buchberger, Steve Staios and Ed Ward. Nelson Emerson, being
counted on for offense, hasn't stood out, and Fraser believes he is
putting too much pressure on himself. Martin Prochazka, signed as a
free agent out of the Czech Republic, also has yet to break loose.
Potential has won him a job for now. Jody Hull will be either sent
down or traded.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line?
</P>
<P>
   Lambert, who played with the expansion Predators last year,
said, ``In Nashville, a lot of guys had career years. I'm sure
that's what they're looking for here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
