<SLUG> BC-ANKIEL-DRUGS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ankiel pleads not guilty to drug charges
 &HT;    By Michael Van Sickler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Richard Ankiel pleaded not guilty
Wednesday morning to federal charges that he and three others
conspired to distribute marijuana and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-year-old father of Rick Ankiel, a promising rookie
pitcher for the St. Louis Cardinals, did not speak to reporters as
he and attorney Juan Torres of Fort Pierce left the federal
courthouse in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the courtroom, Ankiel clutched his hands and stared at
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Linnea Johnson set Ankiel's bail at $100,000.
She set the same amount for Dale Jackson, 41, and Cindy Rohn, 42,
both of Fort Pierce. All were charged Sept. 22 after a lengthy
investigation into the so-called Captain Jump-Off gang, a Bahamian
smuggling network.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip W. Kennedy, 25, will appear in court to hear the charges
against him at a later date because of a scheduling conflict, said
assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel, Jackson and Rohn do not have to post the $100,000 bond
unless they break the conditions set by Johnson. Among the
conditions are that they not get arrested for a felony offense,
that they are prohibited from contacting other government
witnesses, and that they have to be tested for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that could signify that they want to cooperate with
federal authorities, the three agreed to waive their right to be
indicted by a grand jury, which will save the U.S. attorney's
office time it otherwise would spend preparing information for the
grand jury. Instead, the three agreed to have U.S. Attorney Thomas
Scott sign off on the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson scheduled an Oct. 29 status conference with the U.S.
attorney's office and the attorneys for the defendants _ including
Mark Orr of Fort Pierce, representing Jackson, and Jack Goldberger
of West Palm Beach, representing Rohn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
