<SLUG> BC-BODY-BARREL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New York police identify body found in barrel
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ New York police have identified the
pregnant woman whose long-dead remains they pulled from a barrel
beneath a home once owned by a suburban Boca Raton family.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna Angelica Marroquin, a native of rural Tonacatepeque, El
Salvador, was 28, the mother of a toddler and nine months' pregnant
when someone killed her with a single blow to the skull at least
two decades ago, homicide detectives in Mineola, N.Y., said
Wednesday. When the killing was complete, someone stuffed Marroquin
into a barrel that was hidden beneath a suburban home in Jericho,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for Marroquin's killer led police to Palm Beach County
and Howard Elkins about three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Wednesday that Marroquin was pregnant with Elkins'
baby when she called his wife, Ruth, to confront her with the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidante we talked to remembers a telephone call in
which (Marroquin) says she called the wife,'' Nassau County Police
Lt. Kevin Caslin said. ``Marroquin told her friend, 'Now Howard is
so mad he could kill me.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a frantic phone call made in early 1969, Marroquin asked the
confidante, whose name was not revealed by police, to come to a
residence in New Jersey where her boss, Elkins, had put her up. The
confidante was a volunteer at a home for women operated by nuns in
Manhattan, where Marroquin lived shortly after coming to the United
States in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman arrived, the front door was wide open and she
found a meal still warm on the table, but Marroquin was not there.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, she went to the local police department but they
told her since she was not a family member she could not file a
missing persons report. The woman returned home to New York. That
was 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were able to identify the body after finding
Marroquin's Social Security number and the name, address, and
telephone number of the confidante inside a barely legible,
decaying address book found still soaking in body fluids on the
bottom of the tightly sealed drum, Nassau County Police Detective
Sgt. Robert Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pages were like pulp, stuck together and saturated,''
Edwards said. ``Detectives in our documents unit brought the book
back to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Also found in the book was Elkins' name.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins was 70 and living with his wife and son in a $130,000
home in the gated Crescent Lakes community west of Boca Raton when
Nassau County police came calling on Sept. 8. It had been nearly 30
years since the Elkins family lived at 67 Forest Drive in Jericho,
N.Y. Police said Marroquin's remains lay hidden under that house
since at least 1972, when the Elkins family moved to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said earlier this month that he spoke with Howard Elkins
for more than an hour that day. He asked what Elkins knew about the
crime and requested a saliva sample that could be used to match DNA
with that retrieved from the body.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins refused to provide saliva, Edwards said. But Elkins did
admit to having an affair with a woman who worked at Melrose
Plastics, the Manhattan maker of plastic flowers that Elkins once
co-owned. And police have since confirmed that Marroquin worked on
the assembly line at Melrose Plastics.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins asked Edwards for time to discuss the matter with his
wife. The next day, he killed himself with a shotgun in the garage
of a family friend. Police are careful not to call Elkins a
murderer. They admit they may never solve the mystery of how
Marroquin died.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have spoken to Ruth Elkins once since her husband's
suicide, Caslin said.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the investigation said she is not being
investigated in Marroquin's death.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Elkins could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   New York police released the photograph of Marroquin on
Wednesday in the hopes that someone will call (800) 244-TIPS to add
details of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that would really break the case would be for
someone to come forward _ an accomplice, maybe,'' Caslin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
