<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0708 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d BC-MONET-EATS-AZR &LR;      09-29 2209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-EATS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONET WAS A MASTER OF THE CANVAS AND CUISINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Mmmmonet.
</P>
<P>
   The great painter was not only a master of the palette, but the
palate as well.
</P>
<P>
   As much time as he spent in ``continual torture'' capturing the
reknowned haystacks on canvas at perfect light, he spent in agony
each Sunday over which vegetables from the garden would make it
into that week's stockpot. If the vegetables had not been picked at
precisely the right time, the gardener would hear about it, and
loudly.
</P>
<P>
   The infamous rage of 1908, when Monet destroyed three years'
worth of paintings after deeming them unsatisfactory, was
reproduced in miniature on those occasions when Marguerite, the
family cook, committed culinary heresy by altering one of his
beloved sauces.
</P>
<P>
   The meticulous timing that he brought to catching the lily pond
at the instant the sun turned the water to fire was also carried to
his noon meal; Monet would not allow the servants to offer seconds
if his stepson-in-law, Theodore Earl Butler, a notoriously slow
eater, was visiting from America. It vexed him to watch Butler plod
his way through his plate.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, to call Monsieur Claude Monet a master is precise in all
senses of the word.
</P>
<P>
   Monet lorded over his Giverny, France, estate, a place of
Eden-like gardens that yielded wonderful meals. He had waited for
so long to net the recognition to afford the sprawling home, and he
worked so fervently to make it the spot that produced some of the
world's most beautiful paintings, that we can hardly frown upon his
ways.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibit of the canvases Monet completed during this time is
now at the Phoenix Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   At Giverny, he would finish his life, see the country through
the turn of the century, and produce work so modern, so
contemporary, that it befuddled the world just to look at his
splotchy canvases. And it was here, at a time when France's modern
haute cuisine movement was just taking off, that Monet and his
family enjoyed a cuisine quite contemporary as well.
</P>
<P>
   The family adhered to strict rules of freshness in an era not
graced by the Frigidaire. Careful selection was already warranted
for the blend of dishes at each meal during the time when formal
menu compilation became a standard. For Monet, ``style, you see,
style (was) everything,'' and he carefully tailored his dishes,
interior decor and entertaining menus to reflect his dedication to
the good life.
</P>
<P>
   Monet was just so very ahead of his time.
</P>
<P>
   And he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that his life and correspondences are well
documented and kept today. It has been said that Monet was keen to
his future position in history and took steps to preserve all of
his writings and correspondence for posterity. Indeed, that bearded
pack rat, wherever he may be, is no doubt grinning as we write
about him today.
</P>
<P>
   Among Monet's carefully preserved writings are his cooking
journals, which detail carefully the ways (begin ital) pour faire
un bon consomme (end ital) (to make a good clear broth) and which
share the recipe for ``Christmas pudding (a good one).''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a distant relative, Claire Joyes, compiled them into
``Monet's Table,'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35) a cook/history book that
chronicles his life, especially as it relates to the table.
</P>
<P>
   We've included a few of his recipes on this page, but know that
counting fat grams was not on the mind of the average (begin ital)
fin-de-siecle (end ital) French cook. The Tarte Tatin is an ode to
butter and the Coq au Vin could do just as well without it. Made
with less butter, and even none at all, the method still produces a
lusty sauce worthy of the best crusty baguette available.
</P>
<P>
   But oh, what recipes. Take an afternoon, listen to Debussy (an
Impressionist composer), and prepare these dishes favored by Monet.
Oddly, it makes his genius seem a bit closer.
</P>
<P>
   Monet's day nearly revolved around his meals, a tidbit perhaps
evident by his portly figure.
</P>
<P>
   He would rise early to check the day's light, bathe and come
down to the table in his (begin ital) tres moderne (end ital)
lemon-yellow dining room. He favored a host of foods gleaned from
his world travels _ English or Dutch cheese, eggs and bacon, toast
and tea.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it was back to the canvas until 11:30, the strictly kept
time of the noon meal, which was the main meal in the Monet
household. Because Monet nearly went to pieces if he was in bed
later than 9:30 p.m., guests were invited to the household only for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   If food was on the table a minute later than he required, he was
known to terrorize the cooks by making coughing sounds. Dinner was
served, always, at 7 p.m., and involved a soup of some sort. Never
did the Monets begin an evening meal without a soup.
</P>
<P>
   Much is known about the specifics of the holiday meals of the
household, courtesy of Monet's cooking journals. Yet there was
little written on the subject of his everyday cuisine by the scores
of journalists who trekked to Monet's home in Giverny to talk and
sup with this master. (The writers did mention, however, that they
often were invited for lunch, and always at 11:30 a.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it would have been a sin to write of the food when
surrounded by all of that prowess and uniquely conceived painting.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness Monet didn't feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   From his journals, we know that for Christmas every year,
Marguerite would make a special banana ice cream (just add banana
puree to your own), and that one year, she accidentally seasoned it
with salt, much to Monet's annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Each year on his birthday, Monet would demand that one of his
sons or staff members hunt for a woodcock for his main course.
Monet would always personally carve the meat at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Monet can say he invented only one recipe _ wild mushrooms
sprinkled with garlic and parsley, then drizzled with olive oil and
roasted in the oven. The rest of his collection is a lifetime of
loved dishes. There is a bouillabaisse recipe from fellow painter
Paul Cezanne, a favorite egg dish made with truffles, and a recipe
for creme brulee.
</P>
<P>
   There is a process for making Tarte Tatin, a dish Monet and his
family would visit the Tatin sisters to taste. When he discovered a
dish he liked so well, he would set his cook to replicating it.
</P>
<P>
   He was especially particular about his vegetables. He had a
2{-acre kitchen garden at another end of town attended by a
specially hired gardener. Monet liked his vegetables picked at the
height of ripeness, simply steamed, and he did not include many
recipes for cooking them in other ways. He enjoyed a salad, but
would blacken it with so much pepper that only his daughter-in-law,
Blanche Hoschede-Monet, would share it with him. The rest of his
family had to have a separate bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Monet prided himself on impressing company. He would spare no
expense to procure the freshest pike fish for a visit from his
dealer, Paul Durand-Ruel, and would be sure to set out the special
lemon yellow and robin's egg blue dinnerware the family favored on
such occasions.
</P>
<P>
   (If you really want to be true to his table, the Phoenix Art
Museum will be selling paper versions of Monet's yellow and blue
plates, and Crate &AMP; Barrel has a similar pattern, called Capri.)
</P>
<P>
   For everyday, a Japanese-style blue-and white-pattern was used,
always set on a yellow tablecloth.
</P>
<P>
   To imagine his table, set and waiting for guests, is to see
patches of blue sky peeking through the rays of a jubilant yellow
sun, a scene Monet painted so many times outdoors. We can't help
but think that maybe this is why he so favored the pair.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the table was always an ode to Monet's beloved
flower beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, I must have flowers, always, always,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That yellow tablecloth was quite the canvas, indeed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tarte Tatin (Upside Down Apple Tart) &QL; 
(Modified from ``Monet's Table'') &QL; 
2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unsalted butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   6 dessert apples, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Pour flour into a bowl, make a well in the center and in it put
half the sugar, the salt, the egg yolk and warm water. Mix well,
then add 1/2 cup of the butter. Mix the dough until smooth, then
roll out into a rectangle. Fold up the rectangle by folding 1/3
toward the center, then folding the remaining over the top of the
folded part. Cover with a damp cloth and let it rest for 1 hour.
Roll out the dough again into a circle 1/4-inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Arrange apple slices in a deep pie
dish. Add rest of the pieces of butter, and sprinkle with the rest
of the sugar. Cover with the dough. Bake for 45 minutes. Turn the
tart out onto a plate so the pastry is on top.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 411 calories, 26 g fat, 92 mg
cholesterol, 43 g carbohydrates, 3 g fiber, 4 g protein, 38 mg
sodium, 55 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Coq au Vin &QL; 
(Modified from ``Monet's Table'') &QL; 
1/4 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced lean bacon (preferably low-sodium)
</P>
<P>
   12 pearl onions
</P>
<P>
   1 boiling fowl (about 5 pounds), cut into serving pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1 bouquet garni
</P>
<P>
   6 cups mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons brandy
</P>
<P>
   2 cups burgundy
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Fried 1/2-inch croutons
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a Dutch oven or flame-proof casserole dish with a
lid and saute bacon pieces and pearl onions until onions are
transparent. Remove and reserve bacon and onions. Saute chicken
pieces, turning them several times as they cook. Add garlic clove,
bouquet garni, and mushrooms (if any are rather large, slice them
in half). Cover casserole and cook for 15 minutes. Skim off surface
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Add brandy and flame. Add burgundy. Cover casserole and cook for
an additional 35 minutes. To check whether the chicken pieces are
cooked, prick them with a fork. If the juice runs clear, they are
cooked; if the juices are pink, continue cooking. When chicken is
cooked, set it aside in another dish and keep it warm. Remove
garlic clove and garni, and return remaining sauce in the casserole
to low heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine the rest of the butter with the flour
until you have a smooth, thick paste. Break off bits of it and stir
them into the sauce, stirring until each has melted before adding
the next. As soon as the sauce is thick and smooth, return the
pieces of chicken to it, and bacon and onions, if you wish. Garnish
chicken with fried croutons.
</P>
<P>
   This dish is excellent if left to cool, refrigerated and then
reheated in a bain-marie.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 912 calories, 37 g fat, 218 mg
cholesterol, 38 g carbohydrates, 5 g fiber, 80 g protein, 2,011 mg
sodium, 41 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Potage Fontange (Vegetable Soup) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``Monet's Table'') &QL; 
Cut 2 cups dried green or yellow peas, or substitute fresh or
frozen
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 leeks, white parts only, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (1/4 pound) sorrel, trimmed and shredded
</P>
<P>
   1 head iceberg lettuce, trimmed and shredded
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs chervil, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-size potatoes, peeled and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   6 cups Rich Broth (recipe follows) or water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rich Broth
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds beef chuck or other inexpensive cut of meat
</P>
<P>
   1 beef marrow bone
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig thyme
</P>
<P>
   3 celery leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves
</P>
<P>
   3 medium-size carrots
</P>
<P>
   2 small or 1 large turnip
</P>
<P>
   1 onion
</P>
<P>
   1 large leek, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Pour faire un bouillon gras (To make a Rich Broth): Pour 3
quarts water into a large soup kettle. Add the pieces of beef and
the bone and bring to a boil. Boil, partially covered, for 1 hour
over medium heat, skimming occasionally. Tie the parsley, thyme,
celery leaves and cloves together in a piece of cheesecloth to make
a bouquet garni. Add the vegetables and the aromatics tied in the
cloth and bring the liquid back to a boil. Reduce the heat and
simmer, covered, for 3 hours. Strain the liquid. For a lighter,
clearer broth, strain the liquid through cheesecloth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
For the soup: Soak dried peas in water for 2 hours, then drain.
Melt 2 tablespoons of the butter in a pot. Add onion, leeks,
sorrel, lettuce and chervil. Cook over low heat, stirring with a
wooden spoon, until the vegetables are well-coated; do not let them
brown. Add the dried peas and potatoes, then the Rich Broth or
water. Season with the salt and pepper and bring to a boil. Cover
and simmer over low heat for at least 2 hours. Strain and reheat
for a few minutes, stirring constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the rest of the butter into a smooth cream, then beat in
the egg yolks and cream. Pour this mixture into a soup tureen and
pour the boiling hot soup over it. Serve with thinly sliced bread.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 657 calories, 58 g fat, 276 mg
cholesterol, 29 g carbohydrates, 7 g fiber, 10 g protein, 458 mg
sodium, 77 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaimee Rose can be reached at (602) 444-7975 or at
Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
