<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPENDING-HNS     09-29 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LOOKS FOR WAYS TO PAY FOR SPENDING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After spending their summer recess promoting a tax
cut to be paid for out of projected budget surpluses, Republican
leaders are now scrambling to find ways to meet their spending
priorities without tapping into the Social Security Trust Fund they
have vowed to protect.
</P>
<P>
   The job is ``hard work,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert said
Wednesday. But he joined other GOP leaders in pledging once again
to keep Social Security money off limits to congressional budget
negotiators as they head toward another showdown with President
Clinton over annual spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy. Because there's a lot of different spending
priorities around here,'' Hastert said, referring not only to
disagreements over funding and policy issues with the president but
within his own party as well.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Congress passed a temporary spending measure to keep
the government operating through Oct. 21, a move that gives
lawmakers more time to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
   But as the start of the 2000 fiscal year approaches Friday,
Republican leaders are still showing little interest in negotiating
a deal with Clinton _ especially one that calls for closing
corporate tax loopholes or increasing cigarette taxes to cover new
spending, as he has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republican leaders seem determined to pass a number of
controversial 2000 appropriations measures that fall short of
Clinton funding requests, knowing that he will veto them. The goal
of the strategy appears aimed at forcing Clinton's hand on his own
pledge to protect Social Security, while trying to finance some of
his more expensive proposals like his plan to hire 100,000 new
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are so sure that Clinton will try to ``raid the
Social Security Trust Fund,'' as House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, put it Wednesday, that they have already prepared a series
of ads to be aired this fall and in next year's elections accusing
him and the Democrats of doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Democrats say that GOP leaders have already broken
``the pledge'' themselves by using accounting gimmicks to hide the
fact that some of their own spending increases may end up having to
be paid for with Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have already floated a number of proposals that
would declare some routine government expenditures as
``emergencies'' to avoid spending limits agreed to in 1997 or that
would borrow from future budgets to help finance current programs.
They also advocate cutting or delaying a number of programs
designed to help the poor, including housing vouchers and home
heating credits.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said earlier this
week that GOP lawmakers are also considering a plan that would
delay the full benefit of an earned income tax credit for the
working poor by spreading it out over 12 months rather than making
lump sum payments. A Republican leadership aide said the change
would save about $8 billion next year ``without hurting anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican appropriators have already used up nearly $15 billion
in non-Social Security surpluses taken in this year to help pay for
so-called emergency spending. By borrowing money from future
budgets and delaying funding for some programs, they hope to find
enough money to pay for increased defense and other spending, and
to cover the cost of ``local'' projects demanded by some Republican
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office has warned in an analysis that
the Republican budget proposals, as they stand now, will have to
borrow $16 billion to $30 billion from Social Security to finance
increased spending next year.
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay said that the CBO analysis ``is based on false
assumptions'' about what the final appropriations bills will look
like when all 13 of them are finally approved and sent to Clinton.
Only five have been approved so far, and Clinton has vetoed two of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all said and done, we will have maintained the
balanced budget (agreement) and we will not have spent a dime of
Social Security surplus, and it will be certified by the
Congressional Budget Office,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Texan declined to say just how the GOP spending
would be offset to avoid tapping Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said that the president
doesn't have to wait for the GOP's final offsets to know that this
year's budget process is a ``horror show'' and that Republicans are
``doing exactly what they say they're not doing'' _ borrowing from
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the proposals put forward by Republicans to cut or
delay programs for low-income Americans resembles the ``bleak
stories'' found in the novels of Charles Dickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at this approach, when you've got Armey and
you've got Rep. DeLay, you don't need Dickens,'' Lockhart quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., called on Republican
leaders to open budget negotiations with the White House, warning
that there are no guarantees a government shutdown can be avoided
when the temporary funding bill expires in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
