<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. CANS ISSUE-ORIENTED GHOSTWRITER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; George W. Bush  &LR; has fired  &UR; Mickey Herskowitz &LR; , ghostwriter of
his autobiography, ``A Charge to Keep,'' because Herskowitz kept
pressing him for positions on various issues. According to MSNBC,
the book was to be 30 percent biography, 70 percent policy.
Herskowitz, who writes for the Houston Chronicle and has written
books about  &UR; Bear &LR;   &UR; Bryant &LR;  and  &UR; Mickey Mantle &LR; , couldn't make his
subject conform to the ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz told MSNBC that when the book's deadline approached,
Bush and his people ``felt it would be a mistake to talk about
issues because position on those issues is still evolving. It
wasn't that the issues were scary or sensitive or whatever, it was
just that it didn't make sense to come out now with positions that
might change.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer said that Bush's staff had given him hundreds of
speeches from which he was to cull ideas, but ``if you know
politicians, it was really four or five speeches slightly altered.
The press office already had at its fingertips what it thought
should be the book, so I swallowed my pride and said OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz, who said he has no ill feelings, said that  &UR; Karen &LR; 
 &UR; Hughes &LR; , who works for the Bush campaign, is completing the
forthcoming book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIGHTY FINE ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Metropolitan Opera on Monday night, where New York
Mayor  &UR; Rudy Giuliani &LR;  was backstage to present a plaque to
 &UR; Placido &LR; 
 &UR; Domingo &LR; , His Honor was booed. ``The liberal-arts crowd sticks
together,'' noted the New York Post; the booing was because of
Giuliani's attempt to cut funding for the Brooklyn Museum of Art
because he is offended by an artist's use of elephant dung in a
work that involved the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a quote in a new book about painting on velvet,
``Leetig of Tahiti'' by  &UR; John Turner  &LR; (Last Gasp; $29.95), includes
one educated opinion about artists' use of unconventional
materials:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is no longer a hierarchy of materials that
establishes the seriousness of a work of art,'' said  &UR; John Lane &LR; ,
who was then the director of the San Francisco Museum of Modern
Art &LR; , &LR;  in 1988. ``Since  &UR; Marcel Duchamp &LR;  called a urinal a
sculpture, those kinds of hierarchies have been out the window. ...
I believe that what you are looking for is the significance of the
work of art, and I don't believe whatever the material is made of
either elevates or denigrates its value.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Istanbul last week,  &UR; Muhammed Sevim &LR; , 21, attacked two
paintings by  &UR; Salvador Dali &LR;  _ portraits of  &UR; Michelangelo  &LR; and
 &UR; Leonardo da Vinci &LR;  _ breaking glass, cutting his hand, &LR;  and leaving
blood stains on the paintings. Police said he had suffered from
depression, and he was admitted to a mental hospital shortly after
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Art Vandals Web site www.art.a.se/artvandals,
constructed by Swedish artist  &UR; Felix Gmelin &LR; , describes 12 works
that had been previously subject to vandalism. Among them is
``Painting Modernism Black,'' an example of vandalism committed in
1996 against ``Away From the Flock,'' a work by the controversial
 &UR; Damien Hirst &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The original work included a fluffy white lamb floating in
formaldehyde. Artist  &UR; Mark Bridger &LR; , the vandal, poured black ink
into it and retitled it ``Black Sheep.''
</P>
<P>
   He told a prosecuting court that he was inspired to do the act
the minute he saw the work, &LR;  and didn't think Hirst would object.
``To live is to do things. I was providing an interesting addendum
to his work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Matt Salinger &LR; , 39-year-old son of  &UR; J.D. Salinger &LR; , told
foxnews.com that he and his father are not speaking to his sister,
 &UR; Peggy Salinger &LR; , whose new memoir is ``The Dream Catcher.'' ``I
guess she's got a lot of anger,'' he said. ``But to write a book,
and put the word `catcher' in the title, just isn't right. It's
kind of pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   _ There's talk on Broadway of a musical based on the life of
 &UR; Jesse Ventura &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh2,10p10  &LR; high culture &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EARTHQUAKES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Tom Sweeney &LR; , Beefeater doorman at the Sir Francis Drake,
will be at the Giants' last game at Candlestick Thursday, with fond
memories of the 20 years he worked there as a vendor. Sweeney says
his biggest take, $500, was on Oct. 17, 1989, the day of the World
Series earthquake. ``Nobody knew what to do,'' he recalls, ``so
they bought souvenirs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Woodstock '99 may have ended in chaos, but Rolling Stone says
that the event ended with more than $200,000 worth of medical
supplies unused. The leftovers have been donated to earthquake
relief in Turkey, says the magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
