<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD, THE BAD OF TALES OF SURVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One of the greatest feats of survival is finally
getting the attention it deserves. Caroline Alexander has captured
the drama, horror and heroism of the 1914 voyage of the British
sailing ship Endurance in a book of the same title (Alfred A.
Knopf; $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, Ernest Shackleton was eager to achieve his
longtime goal of hiking across the Antarctic from the Weddell Sea
to the Ross Sea after failing on a previous endeavor. To modern
eyes, the risks so far outweighed the possible gains as to make the
voyage seem mad; back then, exploration was done for the hell of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton and his men never succeeded. That they survived at
all is a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   The ship was trapped in pack ice in January 1915, just a month
and a half after leaving a whaling station in the South Atlantic.
The men lived aboard in relative comfort for nine months as they
looked ahead to a time when they might free the ship.
</P>
<P>
   That never happened. Instead, the ship was crushed by ice in
October, accompanied by the eerie, mournful crying of emperor
penguins. The men moved onto an ice floe. Then their descent into
misery began.
</P>
<P>
   They drifted on ice floes for hundreds of miles before they were
forced to take to the small boats they had carried with them. Their
only chance was to make land, so they rode lifeboats to Elephant
Island. When they reached the island seven days later, they were
sick, dehydrated and wasted. It was their first day on solid ground
after 497 days on their ship and ice floes. But their ordeals had
barely begun.
</P>
<P>
   The party's provisions were running low. Shackleton decided the
only chance was to ride one of the boats _ at 22 feet long with two
tiny sails, hardly designed for the open sea _ and make for the
same whaling station from which they had originally embarked, some
800 miles away. Six men undertook the journey; the rest of the
group stayed behind, fully appreciating their only chance rested on
the perfect navigation of their comrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men were soaked to the bone and frostbitten,'' Alexander
writes of the nightmarish odyssey. ``They were badly chafed by wet
clothes that had not been removed for seven months, and afflicted
with saltwater boils. Their wet feet and legs were a sickly white
and swollen. Their hands were black _ with grime, blubber, burns
from the Primus (heater) and frostbite. The least movement was
excruciating.''
</P>
<P>
   The 214-page ``The Endurance'' is an engrossing account of a
superhuman feat of derring-do written in crisp, plain language. New
Hampshire author Alexander does not get carried away by the scope
of the tale, which could easily have led to overwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the crew found the experience transcendent.
Shackleton wrote afterward: ``We had pierced the veneer of outside
things. We had `suffered, starved and triumphed, groveled down yet
grasped at glory, grown bigger in the bigness of the whole.' We had
seen God in his splendors, hear the text that nature renders. We
had reached the naked soul of man.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 140 incredible photographs help bring the story to life.
Australian Frank Hurley took photos that are Ansel Adams-like in
their stark beauty; he ensured the images would endure by soldering
the film into metal containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition''
is well-rendered, even inspiring. Our rating: Four stars &QL; 
X X X
</P>
<P>
   Another 214-page title about staying alive is not nearly so
well-written.
</P>
<P>
   Lene Gammelgaard, the first Scandinavian woman to conquer Mount
Everest, has added to the growing collection of works about the May
1996 disaster on its summit in which eight climbers were caught in
a storm and died. But her journal-like style in ``Climbing High: A
Woman's Account of Surviving the Everest Tragedy'' (Seal Press;
$25) subtracts from what should be a powerful story, while annoying
New Age-speak further weakens the narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: ``But it's obvious that now I must grow, I must strive
to reach my full potential.'' And: ``To grow up is to learn that
one's mature life consists of a personal choices and decisions, and
to realize the options gives true freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that Abba music I hear in the background?
</P>
<P>
   When she finally does get around to describing the storm that
precipitated the crisis on the peak, the storytelling is strong;
she slid down the mountain, using a rope, and barely survived.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts are composed with imagination. But Gammelgaard has
neglected to prune out unnecessary details, especially the arrival,
amounting to an overwritten and choppy account.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing Everest is a great accomplishment, but is not
necessarily material for a book. This first-person account offering
no research pales in comparison to Jon Krakauer's fine account of
the episode, ``Into Thin Air.'' Our rating: One-and-a-half stars
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
