<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORCH FITS PALMEIRO IN HIS OWN `HOUSE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not exactly true what Rafael Palmeiro always said about The
Ballpark in Arlington _ that it was built for him.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Rangers team president Tom Schieffer explains:
</P>
<P>
   ``Rafael took more interest in the design of the park than any
player we had at the time. He was always dropping by the office,
looking over the plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what we did was set the dimensions of our park with Yankee
Stadium in mind. Make it handy for left-handed hitters, yet have
the deep left-field power alleys that favor pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Schieffer willingly copied a long-standing successful
model in building the new yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Rafael's swing fit that model,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Fit it so perfectly that after only one season back ``home,''
Palmeiro already owns the park's right-field porch, not to mention
every home run record in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   No, he's not Sammy or Big Mac, but Palmeiro is challenging
Junior Griffey for long-ball supremacy in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, home run feats in baseball are becoming almost a blur.
Biceps have taken over the game. The once fabled ``61'' is long
gone as the most magical number in sports. Fences are being cleared
in record numbers, so much so that the ``juiced'' ball conspiracy
theory is almost accepted as fact, while the splendid art of
consistently hitting home runs has been cheapened.
</P>
<P>
   Which for the Rangers, by the way, is nothing new. It was
forever a franchise that was both cursed and cussed for being too
home run intensive while wasting away in such areas as pitching and
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, however, is going this season where Burroughs, Zisk,
Parrish, Sierra, and even Gonzalez have never been. And it does
make you wonder what would have happened if Rafael had played the
previous five seasons at the new Arlington park.
</P>
<P>
   He left, of course, in a contractual huff after the season
(1993) that Arlington Stadium was closed. Rafael's parting words
were that the Rangers would dearly miss him at the new ballpark. He
was clearly right.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro has tied Juan Gonzalez' 1996 club record for home runs
(47), and 28 of those have come at home, the most ever at either
Arlington park.
</P>
<P>
   During five seasons in Baltimore, Palmeiro certainly took
advantage of Camden Yards' right-field porch. But this season has
produced career home run numbers (his high with the Orioles was 43
last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Rafael, we've seen for the first time the design of
the ballpark benefit the club,'' Schieffer said. ``He's a
left-handed hitter who is making it work on behalf of the
Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Schieffer is also the first to admit ``much
concern'' over the current home run glut in baseball. And although
no longer a member of Tom Hicks' executive-level team (he resigned
in May), when Schieffer speaks, it pays to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Here was and is a heart-and-soul baseball man who once also had
the ear of commissioner Bud Selig and other owners. The Rangers
dearly miss that, particularly on such issues as the back-room
politics involved in having the club finally removed from a Pacific
time zone division.
</P>
<P>
   But when those of us in the media need ``background'' on
something like the ``juiced-ball conspiracy,'' Schieffer remains
the best local source.
</P>
<P>
   Compare the 1993 season, the last one before the devastating
lockout and shutdown of baseball, to this season, and home runs are
up a large 25 percent. And that percentage has grown every year
since 1993. A long-standing theory says the ball was secretly
doctored to create home run excitement in hopes of soothing an
angry fandom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just never happened,'' said Schieffer, laughing. ``I was in
all those meetings. I would have known. And besides, there has
never been any issue in baseball all the owners would first agree
on, and then take a vow of silence. It would be impossible to keep
something like that a secret. With owners, there are no secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer said the only ``conspiracy'' has been the desire to
build home run-friendly parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Arlington, we went against that trend,'' he added, ``but
what baseball also has are hitters who are stronger than ever,
diluted pitching, and smaller parks. All that adds up to more home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season, with McGwire and Sosa, that was great for the
game. But if you are going to have a home run hitting contest
``every'' year, then the appeal is quickly gone.''
</P>
<P>
   One local exception, however, is Rafael Palmeiro. He has given
the Rangers new appeal, and a new dimension in a ballpark built for
a sweet swing from the left side. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
