<SLUG> BC-FBC-WILLIAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH'S RICKY WILLIAMS IS OUT FOR THE SEASON 
CANSECO SOUNDING UPBEAT ABOUT FUTURE WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Tech's injury-marred season took another disappointing
turn Wednesday when tailback Ricky Williams was declared out for
the season after reinjuring his left knee in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Medical tests performed Wednesday showed that Williams, the Big
12's top returning rusher from 1998, will need surgery after
aggravating a sprained knee suffered Sept. 6 against Arizona State.
Williams, a junior from Duncanville, slumped to the turf while
making a cut during noncontact drills in a Tuesday night practice
and had to be carted off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Tech coach Spike Dykes, who watched his team lose four offensive
starters for extended periods in the Arizona State game, called the
injury ``gut-wrenching.'' He said Williams' spot will be taken by a
trio of backs when the Red Raiders (1-2, 0-0) begin Big 12 play
against No. 5 Texas A&AMP;M (3-0, 0-0) at 6 p.m. Saturday in Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks my heart to see something like this happen to good
people,'' Dykes said. ``The worst thing about athletics is
injuries, because these kids put their whole life into it. And it
can be taken away in an instant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Tayrien, Tech's running backs coach, said the Red Raiders
would ``play it by committee and go with the hot hand'' when
dividing playing time for backup tailbacks Shaud Williams (no
relation), Rickey Hunter and James Easterling.
</P>
<P>
   A preseason candidate for the Heisman Trophy and the Doak Walker
National Running Back Award, Ricky Williams rushed for 1,582 yards
and 13 touchdowns in 1998. He was cleared last week to return to
practice after suffering the sprained knee against Arizona State.
Williams will be redshirted and will have two years of eligibility
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Tech players said they were disappointed to lose one of their
team co-captains for the season, but vowed press on in Williams'
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just going to have to play harder,'' said left guard
Curtis Lowery, a senior from Stephenville. ``We can't get too upset
about losing one person. He isn't the whole team. He's just a good
part of it. If we just go out there and give up, then we might as
well not go out there at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Tech's two most productive rushing performances of
the season came with Williams sidelined. Easterling, a Crowley High
School graduate, ground out 105 yards and two touchdowns in a 38-17
victory against Louisiana-Lafayette. Shaud Williams, a freshman
from Andrews, had 151 yards and two touchdowns in the team's 21-14
loss to North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Morris, Tech's starting fullback who has not played since
the Arizona State game because of a bruised shoulder, is expected
to start against A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes said Shaud Williams (5-foot-8, 175 pounds) is the tailback
most likely to emerge as Tech's primary playmaker in the absence of
Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives us a little different dimension than we're used to,''
Dykes said of Shaud Williams. ``He has great quickness and a
tremendous burst of speed. He's just going to get better and
better.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
