<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-DEBT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS TO OVERLOOK DEBTS OF POOR COUNTRIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling it an economic and moral imperative,
President Clinton said Wednesday the United States would forgive
all debt owed it by poor nations if they use the break to lift
their citizens from poverty and disease.
</P>
<P>
   His offer would cost about $1 billion and could affect 36
nations. Those nations collectively owe $5.7 billion, but their
debts, most dating from the 1970s and 1980s, already have been
written down.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's gesture before the annual meeting of the International
Monetary Fund and World Bank officials received a standing ovation
from the executives who specialize in trying to save troubled
economies.
</P>
<P>
   It followed a renewed pledge this week by the IMF and the
world's seven wealthiest nations to make good on a June agreement
to forgive 90 percent of the debt owed by poor countries if their
governments used the debt relief to begin education, health and
other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton asked Congress to add $120 million over four
years to his previous requested $850 million for debt forgiveness
under that Group of Seven agreement. Congress must approve the
debt-relief request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I am directing my administration to make it possible to
forgive 100 percent of the debt these countries owe the United
States ... to help them finance basic human needs,'' Clinton told
the executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an economic and moral imperative that we use this moment
of global consensus to do better,'' Clinton said, pledging ``I will
do everything I can to aid this trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the debt forgiveness issue will become his personal
priority. He said it was unacceptable that at a time when the
United States is enjoying historic prosperity more than 1.3 billion
people live on less than $1 a day and 40 million die annually of
hunger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't believe we can possibly agree to the idea
that these nations that are so terribly poor should always be that
way,'' Clinton said. ``I don't think we can, in good conscience,
say we support the idea that they should choose between making
interest payments on their debt and investing in their children's
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the effort by the Group of Seven, the world's
wealthiest nations, to reduce the debt load on poor countries will
benefit 430 million people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This initiative seeks to tie debt relief to poverty reduction
and to make sure that savings are spent where they should be: on
education, on fighting AIDS and preventing it, on other critical
needs,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bolivia, it could mean double the number of people with
access to clean water by 2004. For Uganda, it could mean a 50
percent increase in education and health spending by 2001, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Uganda has new anti-poverty programs in place, it was
among the first to qualify for the G7 debt-relief initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very welcome, of course, most welcome,'' Tumusiime
Mutebile, permanent secretary to the Ugandan treasury, told the
Washington Post after Clinton's speech. Uganda owes about $3.5
billion to foreign creditors, about half the country's economy as
measured by gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   The G7 program, amounting to $27 billion in relief, applies to
debt owed to international agencies such as the World Bank.
Clinton's announcement concerned money owed to U.S. government
bodies such as the Agency for International Development and the
Export-Import Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also used the annual meeting to highlight a request by
Pope John II and other church leaders that rich nations provide a
gift for the new millennium to poor countries. ``Simply put,
unsustainable debt is helping to keep too many poor countries and
poor people in poverty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said he wants the World Trade Organization,
the international body that governs trade rules, to focus on jobs
and development when it convenes for a new round of trade talks in
Seattle this November.
</P>
<P>
   The president's initiative drew praise from groups who have long
lobbied for more G7 help in developing nations. ``This will put a
lot of pressure on the other rich countries to increase their debt
relief proposals,'' said Carole Collins, national coordinator for
the Jubilee 2000-U.S.A. campaign, which includes church leaders,
environmentalists and nonprofit groups fighting hunger and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Clinton's request is embodied in a debt-relief
measure introduced by U.S. Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, chairman of the
House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
