A0956 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:NEWS:HISPANIC-MO     09-29 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:NEWS:HISPANIC-MONTH-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID YOU KNOW ... ALL ABOUT HISPANIC HERITAGE MONTH? 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you know that Hispanics are expected to be the United
States' largest minority group, with 36 million people, by 2005,
according to Census Bureau projections?
</P>
<P>
   So it makes sense that we should all learn about the cultural
contributions to the nation by people of Hispanic origins, such as
Mexicans in North America, Salvadorans in Central America or
Ecuadorians in South America.
</P>
<P>
   We're in the midst of Hispanic Heritage Month, Sept. 15 to Oct.
15, a period devoted to recognizing and celebrating the many
cultural and political contributions and talents shared by
Hispanics. Hispanics can be of all races and skin colors.
</P>
<P>
   The observance of a weeklong celebration was made into law in
1968 by President Lyndon B. Johnson, a Democrat from Texas.
Congress extended it to a month in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Other facts: If Puerto Rico ever becomes a state, it would be
the first state with a population almost entirely Hispanic. The 3.5
million Puerto Rican residents are U.S. citizens. Puerto Rico
consists of one main island and three small ones.
</P>
<P>
   After the Spanish-American War in 1898, Puerto Rico came under
the control of the United States. It now has its own elected
government and is called a commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   (Source: ``Amazing Hispanic American History: A Book of Answers
for Kids,'' by George Ochoa and the American History Desk
Reference.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
