<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:CHURCH-SHOOTING-REACT-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SHOOTING TRAGEDY ELICITS MORE LETTERS FROM AREA KIDS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many students wrote to CLASS ACTS and the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram to tell us how they felt after the deadly shooting at
Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth, Texas. Here are some of
their responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard the news, I was at my church and my heart broke.
I have never prayed so hard for someone as I did that night for the
victims. I feel that if we can't be safe in our own church, where
can we be safe? The church in general has been known as a place for
refuge, safety, since the beginning. That man took that feeling
away from me and everyone else. That is the most painful part of it
all for me. I will never have the same safe feeling I had before at
the church. I will never be the same; he changed my life forever. I
never thought something like this could happen so close to home.''
_ Rachael Lyn Ragsdale, junior high school student, Arlington,
Texas
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this would never happen here but I was wrong. You
can't even go to church without being interrupted by a maniac. The
world has a weird way of affecting people's minds. There are some
crazy people in the world. _ Stacey Palmek, 18, high school
student, Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch the news and put myself in the children's position
that were at the church during the shooting. What would I have
done? Would I have prayed or screamed or just run for my life?
Honestly I don't know what I would have done and I'm hoping that
I'm never in that situation. Thinking about what those kids went
through makes me get goosebumps all over and makes my mind rush.''
_ Sarah Hargrove, high school student, Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our world is filled with hate and violence, but God can bring
good out of any situation. For example, the world got to see young
people at Wedgwood worshipping God. The Christian faith has been
discussed on the news a lot and pastors have been interviewed.
Also, this tragedy has caused many people to pray for the dead and
their families, the wounded and their families, and everyone who
was there. Many Fort Worth residents have been working together to
plan memorial services and other acts of kindness for the victims'
families. All of these actions show that goodness can grow out of
tragedy. I have to live my life as if I could die any second, I
also have to realize that wherever, whenever and however, God has a
plan for my life and is in control of my life.'' _ Cameron Leitch,
high School student, Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
