<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0961 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:FACES:JOEL-SERNA     09-29 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:FACES:JOEL-SERNA-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACES: JOEL SERNA, ``JEOPARDY!'' BACK TO SCHOOL WEEK WINNER 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By MEREDITH RAINE 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Name: Joel Serna.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 12.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Claim to fame: won the Jeopardy! Back to School Week contest.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: reading, meteorology.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old Fort Worth student was in last place, he had
wagered all his winnings, and he didn't know the question to the
final answer on Alex Trebek's game show.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Jeopardy!'' show tune was playing and time was running
out, so the seventh grader from Wedgwood Middle School took a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The answer: ``It is reported that on this date King George III
wrote in his diary, `Nothing of importance happened this day.'''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Serna guessed ``this day'' was July 4, 1776. He was right.
The other two contestants, ages 11 and 12, were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He can't help but smile about the show, which was taped in July
in Los Angeles and televised nationwide on Sept. 9. He won $12,200,
plus a $5,000 bonus for having the highest earnings at the end of
the show's Back to School Week. He also won a trip for four to
Universal Studios in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to buy some things that I need,'' Joel said.
Translation: Nintendo 64, a television and videocassette recorder,
a few CD-ROMs and a Pokemon video game.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his winnings will go into a bank account for
college, where he'll prepare for a career in meteorology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm projected to be in the Class of 2005, but in all
probability I'll be graduating in 2004,'' Joel said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel goes through ``periods,'' as he likes to call them, where
he gets interested in a subject and reads every book he can about
it.
</P>
<P>
   And when he reads it, he remembers it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have somewhat of a photographic memory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel wasn't always so sure of himself, his mother, Shelia Serna,
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before `Jeopardy!' he was considered a troublemaker in
school,'' she said. ``People tried to put labels on him. We had
some real tough years, and he had a real low self-esteem before
this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
