<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:FALL-TV-ROUNDUP-     09-29 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:FALL-TV-ROUNDUP-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL TV ROUNDUP 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By Student Reporters MOLLY FRISINGER, High School; CHRISTOPHER
KELLERMAN, Junior High School; and THANE ``WOODY'' TUTTLE, High
School 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLASS ACTS student reporters review TV's latest hot shows. (Air
time is Central.)
</P>
<P>
   Show: ABC's ``Odd Man Out''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Erik von Detten.
</P>
<P>
   Tune in: 8:30 p.m. Fridays, starting this week.
</P>
<P>
   What's it about? The show centers on Andrew, the only male in an
all-female family. Being surrounded by women has its good and bad
sides. Andrew, 15, understands girls better than most guys his age
as he is surrounded by the female friends of his older sister
Paige, but he is constantly barraged with stereotypes about
teen-age guys. Andrew and his best friend, Keith, try to survive
teen-age life as Andrew's sisters _ who are somewhat cruel to their
brother _ and mother comment on their attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: I did not really like this show. It reminded me of a
cross between ``Full House'' and ``Ally McBeal.'' The corny way the
family deals with problems seems odd alongside all the sexual
jokes, which are neither funny nor original, and are frequently in
bad taste. None of the characters shows any kind of real emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1-10 rating: 3.
</P>
<P>
   Show: NBC's ``Freaks and Geeks''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: John Daley and Linda Cardellini.
</P>
<P>
   Tune in: 7 p.m. Saturdays, starting this week.
</P>
<P>
   What's it about?: You've seen ``Saved by the Bell.'' You've seen
``Beverly Hills, 90210.'' What is high school like for everyone
else, though? In this show, you'll find out. A 103-pound freshman,
Sam Weir, and his older sister, Lindsay Weir, are students in the
1980s who get picked on and are always having problems that aren't
always solved in 30 minutes, like those of other TV characters.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: This show has viewers walking away with a smile and
excited about what's going to happen next. The actors are very
real-to-life, and the script is well written. Some scenes for
example _ the ones with a mentally disabled child named Eli _ are
quite depressing, but the show somehow transforms this sadness.
This might sound like a drama, and it is in some ways, but other
scenes will have viewers laughing like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, this show is a real treat, and I believe it will get
top-notch ratings in the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1-10 rating: 8.
</P>
<P>
   Show: UPN's ``The Parkers''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Countess Vaughn and Mo'Nique.
</P>
<P>
   Tune in: 7:30 p.m. Mondays. Premiered Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   What's it about?: Vaughn, who co-stars with singer Brandy in
``Moesha,'' takes her character, Kim Parker, off to Santa Monica
Junior College. But when her mother, Nikki, decides to attend the
same school, Kim begins to chafe at the invasion of her personal
life. There's also Twilight Zone-style narration done by Brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The phrase ``canned ham'' comes to mind. In fact,
canned seems to be the running adjective for this show. Everything
from the canned jokes to the canned laughter to the cookie-cutter
characters who have virtually no distinctive personalities smacks
of LSS. That stands for Lame Spin-off Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1-10 rating: 4.
</P>
<P>
   Show: UPN's ``Grown Ups''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Jaleel White, best-known as Steve Urkel from ``Family
Matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Tune in: 8 p.m. Mondays. Premiered Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   What's it about? J. Calvin Frazier is a single young man living
in an apartment in the same building as his longtime best friend,
Gordon. In the pilot, Calvin is competing with his friend Marcus
for his old high school crush. While Marcus has the upper hand in
the beginning, Calvin seems to gain an advantage toward the end.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: While Jaleel does have a certain boyish charm, his
jokes and sophomoric romantic fantasies fall flat. His friendly
enemy, Marcus, is actually the most appealing character, but even
he seems a bit one-sided. The show has potential, but in its
current incarnation leaves much to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1-10 rating: 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
