<P>
   &UR; CHEVRON &LR;  _ In a move that could set the stage for new merger
talks, Kenneth Derr announced yesterday that he will retire at the
end of December after 11 years as chairman and chief executive of
Chevron Corp. Vice Chairman Dave O'Reilly, long seen as Derr's
chosen successor, will ascend to the top spot of America's
third-largest oil company on January 1. By David Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; VISA _ &LR;  Credit card giant Visa International made official
yesterday a far-reaching reorganization that will cost up to 140
jobs at the Foster City association. Visa officials provided few
details on the job cuts, other than to say that the association is
notifying employees who are losing their jobs and expects to finish
handing out pink slips by tomorrow. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; AMAZON  &LR; _ Amazon.com, already the largest retailer on the Internet,
is angling to become a one-stop shop for every imaginable consumer
product, from priceless antiques to customized T-shirts. Starting
today, the online giant will rent space on its highly trafficked
Web site to any merchant willing to pay a monthly fee and fork over
a percentage of sales to Amazon. By Tom Stein
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ATHOME  &LR; _ ExciteAtHome plans to launch a Web site today that
focuses on business users, joining a growing crowd of Internet
companies that offer services to small and medium-size businesses.
By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PACBELL &LR;  _ Three District Attorneys who filed a lawsuit against Pac
Bell last month submitted new evidence to the court yesterday,
alleging that the phone company has continued to use misleading
marketing tactics to get customers to sign up or change phone
services. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIABYTES &LR;  _ Try to figure this one out: PC Computing is
putting the wraps on what most would call a banner year _
circulation grew to more than 1 million and it won a prestigious
National Magazine Award _ and yet the San Francisco monthly
magazine is making almost a complete U-turn. It's not a computer
magazine anymore; it's being revamped and repositioned as a
business publication. By Dan Fost
</P>
