<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MAO-PAINTER-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTING, REPAINTING MAO FOR DECADES: LOW-PROFILE ARTIST RECALLS
WITH PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ For 50 years, ever since the Chinese Communist Party
came to power, a portrait of Mao has loomed over Tiananmen Square
in the heart of the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   To the countless millions who have passed under Mao's gaze, the
portrait has seemed to preside over the nation unchanged, sturdy as
a piece of Communist architecture, no matter how drastically China
itself was being transformed.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, so much about Chinese officialdom was kept
secret that even the circumstances surrounding the nation's most
prominent painting were considered off-limits to the curious.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a harmless step away from the zip-lipped past, Wang
Qizhi can openly admit that he painted Mao's portrait for 27 years.
Damage from sunlight and smog requires the Tiananmen portrait to be
replaced twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other Chinese in the early years of the People's
Republic, Wang labored behind the scenes like an industrious ant,
following orders, suppressing all urge to show any individuality
and keeping his mouth shut about what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was performing an important task for the good of the
country,'' said Wang, a slender, white-haired retiree of 72.
``There was no question about what I thought personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Wang had pangs of pride when he rode through Tiananmen
Square on his bicycle and glanced up to see his painting at the
crown of the majestic Gate of Heavenly Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few of his acquaintances knew what he did, because anything
to do with Mao or his image was so politically sensitive that he
was ordered not to talk about his job. So Wang insists that his
personal achievement was always subsumed by a sense of the
burdensome importance of his daily task.
</P>
<P>
   As the 50th anniversary of Communist rule approaches on Oct. 1
and many marvel at the vast changes _ for better and worse _ that
China has experienced in a tumultuous half-century, people like
Wang express appreciation for something that has not changed, but
offers a least a thread of continuity.
</P>
<P>
   To many Chinese, Mao's portrait is an important political symbol
that reflects the strength and independence that China gained in
1949, even if it also embodies the nationalist pride that allowed
China to fall into a leftist frenzy in subsequent decades with
terrible damage to the nation's economic, social and political
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Mao may have so single-mindedly pursued his vision of an
egalitarian state _ and personal political power _ that he did not
seem to care how many millions died or were displaced in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even today, many more Chinese seem to admire Mao than to
hate him. A remarkably large number are nostalgic for what they
remember as the idealism and collective fervor of his era, despite
the poverty they endured at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Wang has no equivocation; he is a diehard Mao fan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't let us say a bad word about Mao in the house,'' said
Wang's son, Wang Yan, who is a painter himself. ``We have to go
outside if we want to curse Mao.''
</P>
<P>
   The son does indeed curse Mao outside, seeing the political
trauma of that era, which ended with Mao's death in 1976, as
unnecessarily damaging many of China's finest traditions, like
painting, the family avocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paint in the traditional Chinese style, like my father and
my grandfather,'' he said. ``In Mao's era, traditional painting was
criticized and banned. How can that make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many painters, writers and academics were attacked by the far
left during the 1960s, when radical politics engulfed Beijing. But
Wang Qizhi was protected by the authorities because there was
suddenly so much demand for his work, since Mao's portrait was
plastered all over the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Every major workplace in Beijing wanted its own original, and
they had to be painted by Wang or the one other man officially
approved to produce portraits of the Great Helmsman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things were really busy, he would paint the bottom half
and I would paint the top,'' Wang said. ``We put a scaffolding
across the middle. The wart on Mao's chin marked the halfway
point.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, after Wang had already been painting Mao portraits for
15 years, the Central Committee of the Communist Party decreed that
the portrait be changed, apparently under pressure from radical Red
Guards who objected that the partial side view of Mao showed only
one of his ears, suggesting that he was listening to only one
political faction.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it may sound funny that members of an intensely
intolerant group insisted that their leader be portrayed as
even-eared. But the portrait that was adopted that year remains the
version that has hung in Tiananmen Square for more than 30 years
and is still there today.
</P>
<P>
   Wang said he was deeply upset in 1989, though he was retired by
then, when three men in the Tiananmen protest movement splashed
paint on Mao's portrait, a move denounced by most student
protesters at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defacing the portrait is a crime,'' Wang said gravely. ``They
should have received the harshest punishment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the record, the three men _ a bus company employee, a
journalist and a schoolteacher, all from Mao's home province of
Hunan _ were sentenced to prison terms of 16 years, 20 years and
life, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Lest it be overlooked, Wang pointed out that the task of
painting a 20-foot-high portrait is not easy. The painter must
constantly be stepping back far enough to take a look, and with
such a huge portrait, Wang had to step back 100 feet. So he was
constantly climbing and descending a scaffolding, for perspective.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as China itself takes a step back to look at itself
after 50 years, it may be hard to get a clear perspective or focus
on a nation in the middle of wrenching change from a Communist
system to a new, ill-defined one. As confusing as the outlook may
be, Wang points out that material life is far more comfortable,
just as painting the Mao portrait is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it's easy,'' Wang said. ``They have this big automatic
contraption that moves up and down. Not in my day. We had it much
harder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
