<HEADLINE>
COMPUTING Q&AMP;A/DAVID EINSTEIN  &HT;     COMPUTING Q&AMP;A/DAVID EINSTEIN
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   &HT;     Your Choice _ Dell or Gateway 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I am replacing my old 486 with a new Pentium III system. I have
narrowed my choices down to Dell and Gateway. I have read magazine
reviews and asked friends for their opinions, and now I am more
confused than ever. I get stuff like: ``Dell is expensive'';
``Gateway service sucks`'; ``Dell this, Gateway that.'' I'm leaning
toward Gateway, but I'd like to get your take on that company's
computers, especially on their performance, and how they compare to
Dell's.
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Gateway is one of the largest PC-makers in the world and the
second-largest direct seller behind Dell. But where Dell has
focused primarily on the business market, Gateway makes a concerted
effort to sell computers to consumers, and it has generated lots of
public awareness through its TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? There's almost no difference technically between
a Gateway computer and a comparable Dell. That's because neither
company actually makes the PCs. They take parts like hard drives
and chips from other companies, put them in boxes and slap their
nameplates on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dell and Gateway offer good service and technical support,
although Dell generally gets higher marks in surveys done by trade
magazines. In the final analysis, however, you probably should make
your choice based on who offers the best deal.  &LR; sh  &LR; Keyboards for
Kids
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My question is, with the flurry of computer software targeted at
children under the age of 3, why is no hardware made for them?
Specifically, kid-size keyboards. Do you know of a company that
makes them? I'd like to get one for my soon-to-be 3-year-old
nephew.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: If you're looking for keyboards with big, colorful keys, two you
might consider are My First Keyboard from KidTech, which costs
$59.95, and Big Keys Plus from Greystone Digital, which goes for
about $135.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't tried either one, so I can't give a recommendation.
For more information, including photos of the keyboards, go to
www.kidtech.com and www.bigkeys.com. To tell the truth, I feel a
little bit uneasy about the whole idea of a 3-year-old using a
computer. I suppose it's the wave of the future, but it seems to me
that toddlers would be better off playing in the park and learning
about the world around them, rather than trying to figure out a
machine that probably will be obsolete by the time they're
teenagers. If readers have any thoughts on this issue, please send
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Cookie Jar
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible to delete cookie files from my hard drive? I
notice a folder where cookie files are placed. Are there any
ramifications if I do that? I realize that I'll probably just pick
up more next time I visit a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: You're referring to the Cookies folder inside the Windows
folder on your hard drive. This is where you'll find all the
cookies you've collected while surfing the Web using Microsoft
Internet Explorer. Netscape puts its cookies in a file called
Cookies.txt.
</P>
<P>
   Just to bring Internet novices up to speed, cookies are small
files that Web sites plant in your PC so they can keep track of
information about you. Some of it is used for marketing purposes,
but cookies also contain ID and password information so that you
don't have to sign on to secure sites every time you visit them.
</P>
<P>
   You can dump cookies without hurting anything, but if you do, be
sure to spare the ones used for sites that have automatic sign-ons.
You should be able to identify them because each cookie carries the
identity of the site that sent it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; A small Israeli company has come up with a boffo Internet-based
reference tool. It's called GuruNet, and it gives you instant
dictionary definitions for almost any word, encyclopedia articles
on many subjects and financial information for most public
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the company plans to add in-depth info on movies
and sports. GuruNet works with any Windows application. You can
download the free beta at www.gurunet.com. To use it, all you have
to do is press the Alt key and click your mouse on the word you
want to learn about. You can be in your browser, your word
processor, your e-mail or any other program that uses text. Way
cool.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  David Einstein is West Coast bureau chief of Forbes Digital Tool.
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
