<SLUG> BC-PRINTERSIDE-PRINTERSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Few Companies Divvying Up the Inkjet-Printer Pie  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Compared with the PC marketplace, the inkjet-printer market is
remarkably concentrated. According to figures provided by analyst
Paula Bursley of Dataquest, just six companies accounted for about
98.6 percent of sales of sub-$150 inkjet printers in the United
States in the first half of this year.
<P>
   Among those six companies, according to Bursley, Hewlett-Packard
accounts for 35 percent of the total, and that doesn't even include
Apollo, a separate group HP set up this year to cater to the $50
printer market.
</P>
<P>
   Canon has a 30 percent share, but it's been losing ground at the
low end to Lexmark, which now accounts for 18.5 percent with its
own products, plus another 4.3 percent through Compaq. Epson, which
has only a couple of models under the $150 limit and none below
$100, has an 8.9 percent share, while Xerox brings up the rear with
just under 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among these companies, Canon and Lexmark dominate the under-$100
category, though both also offer higher-priced models. HP (aside
from its new Apollo venture) and Epson have shied away from the
very low end, where profit margins _ if any _ are minuscule.
Instead, they've focused heavily on higher-performance,
higher-quality models that sell for $150 to $300, as well as
business-oriented models that carry even higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a large discrepancy in average selling prices.
According to figures cited by Pradeep Jotwani, senior vice
president of marketing for HP's Inkjet Imaging Solutions business,
the average price for HP inkjets is about $280, and Epson's is
similar, while the equivalent figures for Lexmark and Canon are
below $200.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relative concentration of the inkjet industry,
prices have declined dramatically in recent years. Jotwani put the
rate at 16 to 18 percent per year for each of the past three years,
and he said there's no letup in sight.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1996, according to Dataquest's Bursley, sub-$150
units accounted for less than three-quarters of 1 percent of total
U.S. inkjet sales. In the first half of 1999, they represented
about 40 percent of all units sold, she said.
</P>
<P>
   With prices this low, it's no surprise that the inkjet market is
beginning to see the printer as equivalent to the ``free PC''
movement: Under a recent deal between Lexmark and Juno, a New York
Internet service provider, customers who sign up with Juno for a
year are eligible for rebates of up to $200 on Lexmark printers _
enough to cover the full cost of the company's best-selling models.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
