<HEADER>
A1103 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PRINTERS-PRINTERS_SFC     09-29 1591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINTERS-PRINTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Impressive New Printers Offer a Bewildering Variety of Affordable 
 Models 
 &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
If you've purchased a PC lately, you probably know the routine:
<P>
   A printer is bundled with the computer, or the ads tout printers
with ultra-low prices. But as soon as you've picked your PC, the
clerk begins to ``upsell'' you, explaining why the cheap printer
isn't really a bargain and how you really need to spend an extra
$100 or more on a better model.
</P>
<P>
   But once you start to consider the alternatives, things quickly
get complicated. If the clerk has his patter down, you'll be
bombarded with numbers and acronyms, plus terms and technologies
you never heard of _ Micro Piezo, PhotoREt, IEEE 1284 and plenty
more.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, today's printers generally deliver excellent-quality
output at astonishingly low prices compared with just a few years
ago. But picking the model that's best for you can be almost as
confusing as choosing a PC.
</P>
<P>
   So before you embark on the process, it pays to arm yourself
with some basic knowledge about the printer market, plus some tips
on sensible shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Some 70 percent of all printers made today, and upward of 90
percent of those sold for home use, are inkjet models. Dot-matrix
technology, the standard for low-cost printers through the 1980s,
is now limited almost entirely to devices that print multipage
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Inkjet devices form words and images by squirting tiny droplets
of ink at the paper. Usually, this is done by heating the ink to
the boiling point, until it bursts through a tiny nozzle. One major
printermaker, Epson, relies on a pistonlike mechanism to force the
ink onto the page.
</P>
<P>
   And to print as fast as modern inkjets do _ anywhere from 3 to
12 pages per minute for draft-mode text _ they have to do their
squirting in a hurry: Hewlett-Packard's latest model, for example,
produces about 7.3 million droplets per second.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all inkjet printers made today are capable of color
output. Most have two separate cartridges, one for black ink and a
separate one for cyan, magenta and yellow inks. (Sometimes each
color gets its own cartridge.) The black ink is used for text,
while all four colors may be used in printing graphics. The
advantage of a separate black cartridge is that most people use
much more black than any other color; if there's a separate black
cartridge, you can replace that when it runs dry without wasting
unused color ink.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of a printer's output is a function of many
variables. One rough indicator is ``resolution'' _ the number of
dots per inch. The cheapest inkjets made today have base
resolutions of 360 dpi, and most deliver at least 600 dpi. Those
with the highest resolution, such as Epson's Color Stylus 660, can
produce up to 1,440 dpi. That's overkill for text, but the extra
resolution does help Epson earn top ratings at printing digital
images.
</P>
<P>
   Not all dots are created equal, though _ some are a lot neater
than others. Part of the problem is that squirting a liquid tends
to produce splatter and ``bleeding'' around the edges of the dot,
which translates into rough edges around letters.
</P>
<P>
   You may not be able to see this phenomenon directly unless you
use a magnifying glass. But even with the naked eye, you probably
will notice the resulting difference in overall quality between
better and worse inkjets. And only the very best inkjet output is
as crisp as what office laser printers produce.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, though, inkjet printermakers nowadays do a pretty
good job of managing the splatter problem, and only the fussiest of
readers will quarrel with the quality of text printed on most of
today's models, at least when it's done in high-quality mode.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their standard text-and-graphics models, some
manufacturers offer models optimized for printing images: Alongside
its best-selling DeskJet line, for example, Hewlett-Packard has a
separate series called PhotoSmart (such as the $399 PhotoSmart
P1000), while Epson complements its general-purpose Stylus Color
series with models called Stylus Photo (such as the $249 Stylus
Photo 750).
</P>
<P>
   In past years, these photo-optimized models delivered image
quality that the standard models couldn't match. Today, thanks to
steady improvements in image quality from the mainstream models,
the difference is no longer so dramatic. In fact, HP now uses the
same print engine in its new PhotoSmart models and in its
top-of-the-line, general-purpose model; the difference is not in
output quality, but in extra features in the PhotoSmart series to
simplify connections with digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of spectrum, for those who don't need color
printing, it might be worth considering a laser printer (or an
equivalent technology called LED printing). Laser printers
generally are faster and quieter than inkjets; consumables are less
expensive per page. Best of all, the text they produce looks great
and it's less susceptible to smudging and fading.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, laser printers haven't sold well in the home
market, for one obvious reason: They've been much more expensive
than inkjets. But that gap has narrowed in recent years, at least
for entry-level lasers. Oki's new 6-page-per-minute OkiPage 6w, for
example, starts at just more than $200.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another option that's well worth considering if you're
setting up a home office or other small office, is what's known as
a ``multifunction'' machine _ one that combines a scanner/copier
and in some models a fax machine with a printer (either laser or
inkjet) in one unit. Hewlett-Packard markets multifunction devices
under the OfficeJet brand. Xerox, Brother, Panasonic and many
others also offer competitive models.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, these machines are more expensive than a simple
printer _ they generally start at about $300 _ but they cost less
than buying separate peripherals for each function, and of course
they take up less space. In past years, you often sacrificed
printer and scanner quality for the convenience of an all-in-one
approach, but that's not necessarily true these days.
</P>
<P>
   For most home users buying a new PC, however, the choice is
between an ultra-low-cost _ sub-$100 _ inkjet and spending an extra
$50 to $150 for a higher-priced model. What do you lose by settling
for the cheapest models, and what do you stand to gain by spending
more?
</P>
<P>
   There's one notable disadvantage to the ultra-inexpensive models
often bundled with low-cost PCs, including the Canon BJC-1000 and
-2000 and the Lexmark Z11 and 1100: These printers hold only one
cartridge at a time. Typically, they come with a three-color (cyan,
magenta and yellow) cartridge. To produce black text and graphics,
they combine those three shades.
</P>
<P>
   There are several problems with that approach: Printing text
takes much longer when the printer has to apply three colors. The
black produced by combining colors often looks grayish. The edges
of the letters are often a little rough. And your color cartridge
will run dry in a hurry if you're printing a lot of text.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you can replace the three-color cartridge with an
all-black one. That's pretty easy to do, but it typically will set
you back $20 or $30 _ which isn't chump change when you're talking
about a printer that costs only $49 or $69 to begin with. Besides,
whenever you want to include color in your documents, you'll have
to go back to the three-color cartridge _ assuming that it hasn't
dried out while you were using the black one!
</P>
<P>
   You can avoid these issues by going up a step or two in product
line: The Lexmark 3200 ($149 before $50 rebate) and Canon's
BJC-5100 ($179 before $30 rebate) and BJC-6000 ($229 before $50
rebate), as well as the HP DeskJet 612C ($129 before $30 rebate)
and the Epson Stylus Color 660 ($159 before $30 rebate) all have
dual-cartridge designs.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond models like those, you can of course spend more. Epson
and HP, for example, offer several models in the $150 to $300
range, and their respective top-rated models, the Stylus Color 900
and the DeskJet 970C, both are priced at $399.
</P>
<P>
   What do those premium prices buy? Often, you'll get somewhat
superior quality from the higher-priced models, and more expensive
models have higher monthly ``duty cycles'' _ that is, they're
designed to hold up under heavier printing loads.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest differentiator, however, is speed. Epson's Stylus
Color 900, for example, can print 12 pages of text per minute in
either draft or normal mode, according to the company; HP rates the
DeskJet 970C at a similar 12 ppm in ``EconoFast'' mode and 6.5
pages per minute in normal mode.
</P>
<P>
   In confronting these purchasing choices, the key is to focus on
how you actually intend to use the printer. If you'll be printing
lots of images _ snapshots from a digital camera, for example _
give top priority to image quality.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of home users, however, still print mostly
text, notes Charles LeCompte, editor of an industry newsletter
called the Hard Copy Observer. In that case, text quality should be
the critical issue.
</P>
<P>
   Most families simply don't print many pages, so duty cycles and
speed aren't critical. But if you're running a home business and
plan to crank out letters or flyers by the hundreds, it makes sense
to pay for extra performance and robustness in the form of a
higher-priced inkjet or, if you never expect to use color, a laser
printer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
