 _ SF CHRON  
 Visa May Cut 140 Workers in Foster City  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Credit card giant Visa International made official yesterday a
far-reaching reorganization that will cost up to 140 jobs at the
Foster City association.
<P>
   Visa officials provided few details on the job cuts, other than
to say that the association is notifying employees who are losing
their jobs and expects to finish handing out pink slips by
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The association's board approved the plan late last week. The
Chronicle reported Visa International's plans to reorganize earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   While partly designed to cut costs, the restructuring also is
directed toward giving more power to Visa's six worldwide
affiliates. ``They're going to allow each region to decide what
services are appropriate,'' said Pete Hisey, editor of the trade
newsletter Credit Card News.
</P>
<P>
   Those affiliates, including the powerful Visa U.S.A.
organization that oversees credit and debit card programs in the
United States, may, in turn, give the banks that issue cards
greater flexibility in customizing the products they offer.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean Visa cards will no longer be cookie-cutter
products, in which the 21,000 banks worldwide that issue cards
offer nearly identical features and enhancements. Customers would
have a wider array of choices.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, for example, all Gold credit card programs worldwide
must offer customers insurance on rented cars. Under the new setup,
the regional Visa organizations may permit issuers to offer Gold
cards that drop auto rental insurance and, instead, offer any
combination of features they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more opportunity for competition and
differentiation of card products at the bank level,'' said Visa
U.S.A. President Carl Pascarella.
</P>
<P>
   Under Visa International's plan, basic services needed by
issuers around the world, such as a standard setting that ensures
Visa cards can be used globally, would remain with a central
organization dubbed ``The Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Other functions, such as transaction processing, will be housed
in a new unit called ``Shared Services.'' Banks will be able to buy
services from the unit on a fee-for-services basis instead of the
one-size-fits-all assessment currently charged. That will let some
banks dramatically reduce Visa membership costs.
</P>
<P>
   Visa International's reorganization is the product of a gradual
power shift that has witnessed giant U.S. credit card issuers, such
as Chicago's Bank One and North Carolina's Bank of America,
increase their clout in the organization to the point that they now
call the shots.
</P>
<P>
   The big banks are demanding lower fees and more ability to
tailor products, so that they can make their offerings stand out in
the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, Visa lorded over its members,'' said Hisey.
``Now, the big ones are saying, `We don't need you so much.'''
</P>
<P>
   The new system also reflects gains for Visa U.S.A. in its
long-running power struggle with its parent, Visa International. As
a result of the reorganization, Visa U.S.A., which represents more
than 50 percent of global credit card volume, will get more
authority and divert less of its revenue to the international unit.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Visa U.S.A. said marketing and product management
chief Michael Beindorff has resigned to become chief operating
officer of PlanetRx.com, a South San Francisco Internet drugstore.
Beindorff, who joined Visa after 14 years as a marketing executive
for Coca-Cola, oversaw Visa U.S.A.'s highly successful ``It's
everywhere you want to be'' ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
