<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Kenneth Derr to Relinquish Reins of Chevron 
 &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In a move that could set the stage for new merger talks, Kenneth
Derr announced yesterday that he will retire at the end of December
after 11 years as chairman and chief executive of Chevron Corp.
<P>
   Vice Chairman Dave O'Reilly, long seen as Derr's chosen
successor, will ascend to the top spot of America's third-largest
oil company on January 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a very easy transition,'' said Eugene Nowak,
an analyst with ABN AMRO in New York. ``O'Reilly has been the heir
apparent for quite some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street gave a thumbs-up to the announcement. Despite a down
day for the Dow Jones industrial average, Chevron gained 56 cents
to close at $88.19.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference at the company's San Francisco
headquarters, Derr, 63, dismissed suggestions that his retirement
is related to undergoing surgery last year for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to say everything looks very, very good,'' he said
of his health. ``All the signs are positive, and the cancer had no
impact on my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Derr added that he is looking forward to spending more time with
his grandchildren and ``maybe play a little more golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Fischer, an analyst with Burnham Securities in New York,
speculated that Derr's exit was timed to demonstrate a clear sense
of direction prior to a November meeting with oil-industry experts
in the financial community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron takes such meetings seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a wave of industry consolidation, including the pending
merger of heavyweights Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., analysts will
be looking for a fresh intent on Chevron's part to explore new
strategic partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Merger talks with Texaco Inc. collapsed in June amid reports
that the two sides could not agree on who would head the combined
company. Derr was said to have insisted that 52-year-old O'Reilly
be boss, while Texaco CEO Peter Bijur, 56, wanted that decision to
be made later.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, had it come to pass, would have been worth about $40
billion, or roughly half the Exxon-Mobil marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Fadel Gheit, an analyst with Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York, saw
O'Reilly's promotion as a clean-slate opportunity for Chevron to
reopen talks with Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was O'Reilly, and I wanted to start with a bang, on
January 1, I would call Peter Bijur and say `happy new year' and
`let's talk,''' Gheit said.
</P>
<P>
   ABN's Nowak agreed that a Chevron-Texaco merger remains a
possibility. ``There's a 1-in-3 chance it could be resurrected,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly gets high marks from industry observers for his
leadership and grasp of issues. He has been with Chevron since
1968, when he joined the company as an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Among other assignments, O'Reilly has served as manager of
Chevron's El Segundo refinery and president of Chevron Products
Co., overseeing the subsidiary's refining and marketing operations.
</P>
<P>
   He was appointed vice chairman and director last November as
Derr groomed him for eventual succession.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, O'Reilly said yesterday that he intends to
concentrate on improving shareholder returns and to be ``very
focused on the business.''
</P>
<P>
   As for how his management style differs from Derr's, Dublin-born
O'Reilly said, ``I tend to be impatient at times.''
</P>
<P>
   With crude oil prices now more than twice as high as a year ago,
he is unlikely to have trouble keeping his temper in check when
Chevron reports its third-quarter earnings in about a month.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the company said its second-quarter income fell 39
percent from a year before to $350 million. Nearly half of the
decline was attributed to troubles at Chevron's Richmond refinery,
which was rocked by an explosion in March.
</P>
<P>
   California safety regulators hit the company earlier this month
with a $30,000 fine in connection with the blast.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly said the Richmond facility has been repaired ``to a
large extent'' and that the refinery is now operating at
approximately 85 percent capacity.
</P>
<P>
   He said the financial fallout from the refinery's difficulties
will prove to be ``significantly less'' in the third quarter than
in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced output at the Richmond plant contributed to summertime
concerns that California would run short of specially treated
gasoline meeting the state's stringent environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chevron never took advantage of a one-time-only waiver
to sell untreated fuel at its service stations, worries of a
shortage contributed to record-high pump prices during the peak
driving season.
</P>
<P>
   Under Derr, Chevron said its market value jumped fourfold to
about $60 billion and that the company was able to increase its
stock dividend for 10 consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll still be a pretty significant stockholder,'' Derr said.
``I'll sleep very, very well at night knowing Dave O'Reilly's in
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   In other appointments, Chevron said Dick Matzke, 62, will
succeed O'Reilly as vice chairman and that Peter Robertson, 52,
will replace Matzke as head of Chevron Overseas Petroleum Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
