<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-AMAZON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Amazon to Let Other Retailers Sell on Its Site  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Amazon.com, already the largest retailer on the Internet, is
angling to become a one-stop shop for every imaginable consumer
product, from priceless antiques to customized T-shirts.
<P>
   Starting today, the online giant will rent space on its highly
trafficked Web site to any merchant willing to pay a monthly fee
and fork over a percentage of sales to Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazon initiative, called zShops, brings the company one
step closer to its stated vision of being the premier shopping
destination on the Net, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon has always wanted to present itself as the place to go
for anyone who wants to buy anything,'' said Ken Cassar, an analyst
with Internet research firm Jupiter Communications. ``With this
offering, they can start to make that statement accurately.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors took a real shine to Amazon's concept of a virtual
megamall. Amazon's shares rocketed 23 percent, or $14.88, to close
at $80.75. Analysts said Wall Street was enamored with the fact
that Amazon, which has so far failed to turn a profit, can sell
third-party products on its site without having to incur inventory
and shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants can list as many as 3,000 items on zShop for $9.99 per
month. Amazon will also collect a transaction fee of anywhere from
1 percent to 5 percent, depending on the sale price of the product.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, merchants gain access to the nearly 12 million
consumers who visit the Amazon site each month. Jaleh Bisharat,
Amazon's vice president of marketing, said sellers can also benefit
from cross-marketing promotions. For example, if a shopper comes to
the Amazon site looking for a Mexican cookbook, that person could
conceivably be shown a Web link to a zShop salsa merchant.
</P>
<P>
   Bisharat said merchants must stock all items they list as well
as deliver all orders in a timely fashion. The zShops program is
targeted at small companies that don't have a Web presence as well
as large retailers, such as the Gap, looking for another sales
channel on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said it will launch the zShops service with 500,000 items
already listed. That's well behind the 3.75 million items sold on
Yahoo's competing service called YahooShopping. Yahoo said it had
6,000 merchants on its program as of June.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon was founded four years as an online seller of books. But
over the past year, the company has branched out in many new
directions, including music CDs, videos, toys, electronics and
auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Amazon ultimately wants to sell everything itself,
and the zShops initiative could provide a platform for gaining
critical market research on which products do best on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   But is Amazon spreading itself too thin? ``Without a doubt,
Amazon is opening itself up to new risks,'' said Alan Mak, a
analyst with Argus Research. ``In terms of customer service, what
does Amazon do if a zShop owner does not deliver on what he
promises? Or what happens to Amazon's brand name if zShops turns
into a den of firearms and pornography?''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said it is taking the appropriate precautions to protect
consumers from shady merchants. For example, it will guarantee
refunds of $250 to $1,000 for shipped items that do not meet with
the buyer's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Some San Francisco business owners remain skeptical of Amazon's
plans. ``I may take a close look at how this works,'' said Ken
Uyehara, owner of SFO Snowboard Shop. ``But if they're letting in
any merchant to the program, how do I know this won't become
uncontrollable for the consumer and for Amazon themselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mark Luhn, owner of Jeffrey's Toys, ``I don't see this as
anything more than building a billboard on yet another road.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
