r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     09-29 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   PC Computing Tries Businesslike Makeover 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Try to figure this one out: PC Computing is putting the wraps on
what most would call a banner year _ circulation grew to more than
1 million and it won a prestigious National Magazine Award _ and
yet the San Francisco monthly magazine is making almost a complete
U-turn.
<P>
   It's not a computer magazine anymore; any more;  &LR; it's being
revamped and repositioned as a business publication.
</P>
<P>
   It has hired art and creative directors from Outside magazine
and is shifting to such a business-heavy focus that Editor in Chief
Paul Somerson brags that it ``won't have a single picture of a
computer or a screen shot in the first 90 pages.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not look like your father's computer publication,''
publisher Greg Mason says.
</P>
<P>
   It's not inconceivable that a name change might also be in the
works, although Somerson is mum on the subject and Mason is coy.
``It's an interesting question,'' Mason says, ``one we've
researched and continue to research.''
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, they don't want to turn off potential readers
who would be drawn to a hot business book but couldn't care less
about PC computing. On the other hand, Mason notes, the existing
name ``has a lot of brand equity and existing loyalty.'' It sells
150,000 copies a month on the newsstand, he says _ twice as many as
Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   In tech media circles these days, the word PC is an emblem of a
withering industry _ companies give PCs away, while consumers are
using smaller, more portable devices. Meanwhile, all the
``dot-com'' advertising flocks to New Economy magazines like the
Industry Standard, Business 2.0, Red Herring and Upside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every computer magazine is down in ad pages,'' Mason says.
``That's why we're going after this as aggressively as we are.
That's why Ziff-Davis is willing to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   PC Computing doesn't plan to tackle the New Economy books
head-on. ``We're not trying to be an Internet insider,'' Mason
says. ``We want to be a hands-on, practical magazine for
businesspeople business people  &LR; of all stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   Its ad campaign will show PC Computing on a newsstand cluttered
with business magazines, with one big word: ``Huh?'' Below, Mason
says, it will say: ``Believe it. PC Computing is transforming
itself into a new breed of business magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of features ranking 100 different modems, it will
scrutinize the best airlines and hotels for the business traveler.
</P>
<P>
   The December issue that hits newsstands next month includes a
look at the 10 most wired companies in America, the top technology
mistakes businesses make, marketing secrets of the new economy and
how to outsource business services to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine will have a monthly feature on how companies
supplement their workforce by outsourcing. It will have product
reviews and a ``cheat-sheet'' list of the best printers, digital
cameras and other products toward the back; and its last page will
be a feature titled Escape, telling rich geeks how they can buy a
ride in a Russian MiG Mig  &LR; or take a trip to the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``A word we use around the magazine a lot is `edgy,''' Somerson
says.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a word heard at too many traditional computer
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine will still rely on its multimillion-dollar testing
lab. With cameras and two-way mirrors, editors watch real live
businesspeople use computers, and see what works and what doesn't.
The lab can even calculate how long it takes a company to get a
return on its investment in a particular technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the untrained eye, we were just another computer
magazine,'' Somerson says. ``We figured, instead of incremental
tiptoes, we needed a dramatic change.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HERRING HOOPLA: &QL; 
Like most New Economy magazines, Red Herring is looking fat _ but
it wants to get fatter. While its November issue will have 180
pages of advertising, more than double last November's 88 pages,
the Herring is launching a $5 million advertising campaign that it
hopes will build both circulation and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Herring's campaign pales next to the $100 million
marketing effort from Cnet that you see everywhere, but Cnet is
going for the mass market, while the Herring remains a niche
publication.
</P>
<P>
   After all, reasons Chris Alden, the Herring's interim chief
executive, as technology expands throughout the business world, the
audience for a tech-biz pub like the Herring should expand as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a CEO in America today who's not thinking about
technology,'' he said. ``They need to become Red Herring customers,
and come to our magazine and our Web site and our conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a lot of other publications make the same claims. And
the Herring ads are more about building the brand than lighting
anyone on fire: They feature simple black type on a white
background with a red border. No fancy graphics; no edgy hype.
``We're about helping you soberly figure out what's hype and what's
not,'' Alden said.
</P>
<P>
   One ad says, oddly enough, ``Our competition is trying to reach
the same people who are trying to reach us.'' Odd, because such ads
will run in magazines like Forbes and Fast Company _ which the
Herring views as competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Alden said the ad campaign comes at a pivotal time for Red
Herring, and he's probably right. Not only is competition stiff,
but the company has hired the executive recruitment firm
Ramsey-Beirne to seek a CEO to take the place of Alden's co-founder
Tony Perkins. Perkins remains chairman while he assumes more of a
role outside the company, raising money for presidential candidate
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Stafford, who ran the company's online operations, left in
the spring after only several months on the job and still has not
been replaced. The Herring is also looking for an executive editor
to serve under Jason Pontin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ziff-Davis, which has a reported 10 percent stake in
the company, is for sale; it's unclear what kind of effect new Ziff
ownership could have on the Herring. And the company continues to
eye an initial public offering, although Alden said he's taking his
time in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going public to me is not a finish line,'' he said. ``The `I'
in IPO means initial.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VCs WITH ART &QL; 
Just because venture capitalists get to play with lots of money
doesn't mean they have no appreciation for the arts, as two
upcoming events prove.
</P>
<P>
   The Flying Other Brothers, a rock band made up of investment
bankers, software programmers and tech marketers, is about to
release its first CD, titled, appropriately, ``IPO.'' The release
party will be at 8 p.m. October 9 at the Great American Music Hall,
859 O'Farrell St. in San Francisco. The $10 admission gets you a
copy of the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art will open an
exhibition October 15 of ``Selections from the Pamela and Richard
Kramlich Collection of Media Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Kramlich of New Enterprise Associates was one of the
guiding forces behind Silicon Graphics and Progress Software; now
he's putting on public display, for the first time, what MOMA calls
one of the world's pre-eminent collections of film, video and
photo-based artworks. The exhibit runs until Jan. 9, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW KID IN TOWN &QL; 
This column will go on a brief hiatus while I spend this week and
next immersed in the life of a new next-generation startup: Harry
Benjamin Barker-Fost, born Sunday at Marin General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
