<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1121 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PRINTERTIP-PRINTERTIP     09-29 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINTERTIP-PRINTERTIP </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PRINTER BUYING TIPS  &HT;     BY Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Think about how you'll really use your printer.  &LR; Compare printers
in terms of what you expect to do most. If you'll mostly print
words, don't worry about the pretty pictures _ focus on text
quality and speed. If you intend to print lots of pictures _ from a
digital camera, say _ don't just look at manufacturer's samples,
which invariably look great; instead, check trade magazines for
comparative reviews.
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Get a black-ink cartridge.  &LR; Many sub-$100 printers use only one ink
cartridge, and the one they come with has only three color inks, no
black; they create black by combining three colors, a process
that's slow, sloppy and wasteful. Pick a printer that has at least
two cartridges _ one for black, one or more for colors _ or else
figure in the extra cost of buying an all-black cartridge for text,
plus the extra hassle of swapping it for the color cartridge
whenever you want to print colors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Don't be bamboozled by the numbers.  &LR; Quoted print speeds are
usually for ``draft-mode'' (lowest-quality) text _ it takes longer
to produce higher-quality text and much longer to produce graphics,
especially at top quality. Resolution beyond 600 dpi is hardly
noticeable with text; with images, higher resolution tends to
improve output quality, but it's not the only important factor. As
for other numerical specifications, like number of nozzles and
droplet size, don't worry about them unless you're a professional
photographer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Pay attention to the fine print on prices. &LR;  Advertised prices often
are based on rebate offers. The manufacturers bank on the fact that
many customers won't ever bother with all the paperwork. Remember
to request the rebate coupon when you buy, and send it in promptly.
Save copies of all documents. Expect to wait at least six to eight
weeks for payment. If you don't want the delay or hassle, pick your
printer based on actual up-front prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Don't forget the cost of ``consumables.''  &LR; Printer manufacturers
make most of their money not on their printers, but on the extra
ink cartridges and specialty paper you buy later. Text pages are
fairly cheap _ typically 3 to 5 cents per page _ but color output
can cost many times as much just for ink, not counting the fancy
paper required for photo-quality graphics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Consider the alternatives.  &LR; If black text is all you need and you
can afford to spend a bit extra, consider a laser printer instead
of an inkjet. If you're setting up a home office, a
``multifunction'' machine _ one that scans, copies and sometimes
faxes, in addition to printing _ can save you space and money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Don't forget the cable.  &LR; Printers typically don't include the cable
you need to connect your PC _ you have to buy it separately, and it
can cost almost as much as a cheap printer. If a printer-maker
recommends ``bidirectional'' or ``IEEE-1284'' cable, as most do
today, it's a good investment. If a printer you're considering is
available with a Universal Serial Bus interface, and your PC has
USB ports and Windows 98, using USB instead of a traditional
parallel-port connection may help you avoid a lot of hassles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
