<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0538 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1133 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BOFA-FORWIRES &LR;      09-29 3340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-FOR </SLUG>
 WIRES  
 Breaking the Bank: The untold story of how David Coulter
lost  BofA 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A grim BankAmerica Chief Executive David Coulter telephoned top
deputies as he was winging his way back to San Francisco from a
European conference. His message: BofA must kill its pending merger
with North Carolina's NationsBank.
<P>
   Coulter's desperate move 16 months ago came after NationsBank's
leader Hugh McColl insulted him in a private conversation, a clash
that left Coulter horrified and unable to sleep. Coulter believed
that the incident revealed McColl's real intent. To the North
Carolina banker, BofA was not an equal partner, but the latest in a
long line of conquests.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter abandoned his revolt after lawyers told him he was
locked into the deal.
</P>
<P>
   And so, exactly a year ago, the combination became official.
Sixteen days later, Coulter's worst fears were confirmed when
McColl fired him, blaming him for a $372 million loss in a risky
investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   This is the inside, and to a large degree, untold story of how
Coulter let BofA slip through his fingers. It provides a rare
glimpse of how the fate of a venerable San Francisco institution
was sealed by miscalculation, naivete and misguided trust.
</P>
<P>
   The story is based on a year of reporting, including
confidential interviews with more than two dozen people directly or
indirectly involved with the takeover. Coulter declined to be
interviewed, while McColl made only brief references to his
relations with BofA's chief in an interview earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dallas, Atlanta, Baltimore, St. Louis and Jacksonville,
Fla. _ cities whose banks were swallowed by NationsBank _ San
Francisco today is little more than a provincial capital, albeit a
major one, in McColl's empire.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the bank has remained an active supporter of the
community and McColl has kept his promise to keep the new BofA's
corporate and international banking operations based in San
Francisco. But only three of the top 13 executives of the old BofA
are still with the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The old BofA's proud tradition, which traced back to the
institution's founding in 1904 by immigrant financier A.P.
Giannini, has been ripped apart. ``California lost one of its
founding institutions, a bank that supported so many of the
businesses that started here,'' lamented a former director.
</P>
<P>
   The BofA-NationsBank saga began in late 1997 when Coulter and
Chief Financial Officer Michael O'Neill realized that their growth
plans for the San Francisco bank had hit a wall.
</P>
<P>
   The bank had performed well during Coulter's two years as chief
executive officer. Profits had risen every quarter, thanks partly
to his moves to jettison low-return units, such as the bank's weak
branch networks in Hawaii, and invest in businesses that made more
money. BofA's stock price had tripled. And Coulter was promising
investors that he would double shareholder returns every four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the surface, though, all was not well at the nation's
fourth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter had already taken the easy steps to boost profits. Now
he faced some daunting trends: slow revenue growth amid stepped-up
competition; collapsing markets in Asia and Russia; and the need to
lay out billions of dollars to update computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had run out of ways to grow earnings,'' said one former
BofA executive.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter and O'Neill concluded that they would miss their
performance targets unless they took dramatic action. They quickly
dismissed the idea of a major acquisition. Takeovers were too
expensive, likely to dampen earnings in the short term. The only
solution they saw was a merger with a bank roughly the same size as
BofA's $275 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   There was one other factor, BofA insiders said. The bank's
consumer and small business operations were a management nightmare
_ inefficient and technically backward, and service quality ratings
were poor. Fixing the retail unit was the key to revving up
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter had hired former MasterCard CEO Eugene Lockhart the year
before to turn retail operations around. But in Coulter's view
Lockhart was not getting the job done and his abrasive style
alienated his colleagues. With no solution in sight, a merger
seemed the best way out.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said in an interview that strategic issues, not his
management style, were behind the merger.
</P>
<P>
   A merger of equals was the buzzword in banking by 1997. Even
megabanks realized that they had to grow larger through mergers to
be more cost efficient and afford the huge investments in computer
technology needed in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The trend was a reaction to the huge premiums banks had been
paying to buy out their rivals, weakening future financial
performance. Under the merger-of-equals formula, banks paid no
premium for each other because neither side was considered the
buyer. They simply exchanged stock at close to market price and
combined their balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter and O'Neill were not the sort of leaders who would try
to avoid a merger for tradition's sake. Coulter was a
by-the-numbers manager focused on financial results and performance
of the bank's stock. O'Neill was a hard-boiled transplant from
Chicago's Continental Bank who had arrived at BofA only four years
before and had no sentimental attachment to his new bank.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, BofA hired the investment bank Goldman Sachs to
analyze mergers with about half a dozen major American financial
institutions. In February 1998, Coulter and O'Neill got a go-ahead
from BofA directors.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter and O'Neill settled on two candidates: Citicorp, the
nation's second-largest bank, with far-flung global operations; and
NationsBank, the No. 3 bank, whose retail branch operations,
spreading from Maryland to New Mexico, closely resembled BofA's
network.
</P>
<P>
   BofA adopted the code name ``International Alternative'' for
Citicorp, signifying that it fit best with the San Francisco bank's
extensive foreign operations. NationsBank was dubbed ``Domestic
Alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   At a February 25 meeting in Washington, D.C., of the Business
Council, an elite business conference, Coulter approached Citicorp
CEO John Reed who said he would get back in touch.
</P>
<P>
   When Reed did not reply to Coulter after several weeks, BofA
switched its attention to Domestic Alternative. Citicorp would
eventually announce a merger with the insurance and securities
conglomerate Travelers Group.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time BofA considered a deal with
NationsBank. In 1995, under former CEO Richard Rosenberg, the two
banks came within a hairsbreadth of merging. The deal fell apart
when McColl, after agreeing to move the combined bank's headquarter
out of Charlotte, changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank's mix of consumer, small-business and corporate
banking operations meshed well with BofA. A merger promised to
yield as much as $2 billion in annual savings from cutting
overlapping administrative functions.
</P>
<P>
   McColl, a short, fiery 63-year-old who bragged that his
management philosophy came from the Marines, was known as banking's
toughest predator. NationsBank's chief had presided over dozens of
bank combinations and not one had been a merger of equals. ``We
never think about giving up control of anything,'' he explained in
an interview earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Using prominent New York merger lawyer Edward Herlihy as a
go-between, O'Neill arranged to talk with NationsBank chief
financial officer James Hance. The two drew up the outlines of a
deal at San Francisco's Mandarin Hotel on March 27.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill negotiated financial terms that split ownership of the
combined companies based on their respective market values, with a
slight tilt toward BofA because its stock traded at a higher
multiple to earnings than NationsBank's. The North Carolina bank's
shareholders would own 55 percent of the combined bank, while BofA
shareholders would get 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill and Hance agreed to divide directorships equally, a key
matter, because control of the board is the ultimate source of
power in a corporation. They also decided to create six top
management jobs, three for each side. McColl would be chairman and
CEO, and Coulter would be president and chief operating officer,
with all major business lines reporting to him. Coulter would have
the inside track for the CEO job when McColl retired.
</P>
<P>
   The two CFOs postponed a decision on what to name the bank. Only
on the matter of headquarters did O'Neill make a flat-out
concession, agreeing to base the bank in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter had already decided he was willing to give on the
location of the headquarters, partly because he was furious over a
city of San Francisco lawsuit charging the bank with siphoning
money from municipal bond accounts, a case BofA settled for $187
million.
</P>
<P>
   Later, O'Neill negotiated a severance agreement to protect
Coulter in case McColl reneged on his commitment to back him for
the top job. Its value was calculated to be as much as $100 million
and included a pension of $5 million a year for the rest of
Coulter's life.
</P>
<P>
   McColl flew to San Francisco and joined Coulter and his wife,
Susan, for dinner at their Pacific Heights apartment March 31.
According to Ross Yockey's soon-to-be-published authorized
biography ``McColl: The Man with America's Money,'' the
NationsBank's chief was bristling. He felt that Susan Coulter was
inspecting him to determine whether he was worthy of merging with
her husband's bank.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the two CEOs flew to Phoenix in separate jets to
attend the Bankers Roundtable, an industry conference. They met in
McColl's cottage at the Biltmore, an elegant 1920s-style desert
resort. There, behind closed doors, Coulter let a merger of equals
slip away.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon of April 2, he and McColl emerged with a
one-page memorandum that outlined a new agreement. The deal was now
an out-and-out takeover.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank would now control 13 of 24 board seats. Coulter
would give up the chief operating officer title and take a job
outside the chain of command, with little authority. And the
commitment to make him CEO when McColl retired was reduced to a
weak statement of intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave undid a deal that was basically done,'' said one person
familiar with the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, BofA corporate banking chief Michael Murray, strategic
planning chief Doyle Arnold, and the bank's lawyers and investment
bankers all warned Coulter that he was setting himself and the bank
up to be eaten alive.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter shrugged off the complaints. He told his advisers that
he and McColl had worked out an understanding. He reminded his
lieutenants that McColl would be the CEO of the combined bank and
that it was important not to crowd him.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Coulter _ by all accounts a decent, profoundly
intelligent manager _ sign the bank away? Former colleagues said a
combination of naivete and a blind spot in judging character doomed
him.
</P>
<P>
   It is now clear that Coulter was utterly out of his league
bargaining one-on-one with McColl. NationsBank's chief was acting
the biggest role of his life, and he played it to the hilt.
Coulter, with little artifice, was striving for a meeting of the
minds.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Southern Charm
</P>
<P>
   The merger was now on the fast track. A special meeting of
BofA's board was called for April 9. The night before, the
directors met at a private dinner at which they received a copy of
the McColl-Coulter memo.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Coulter began the meeting, touting the advantages
of combining with NationsBank. He noted how much he had enjoyed
meeting McColl. O'Neill, by then the loyal soldier, gave a forceful
presentation on the deal's financial benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Several directors raised questions. Former Pacific Gas and
Electric Co. CEO Richard Clarke wondered whether there was a way to
keep the new bank's headquarters in San Francisco. Richard
Rosenberg asked whether Coulter should have gotten a stronger
commitment to succeed McColl as CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Only two directors pressed the issue of control. Sandy
Robertson, chairman of BofA's Robertson Stephens investment banking
unit, asked whether any other mergers of equals had uneven
divisions of board seats. He was told that in almost all other
cases directorships had been split down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bedford, a blunt East Bay real estate developer, asked
Coulter whether he had been disarmed by McColl's good-old-boy
manner into giving away the store. Coulter assured directors that
he was comfortable with the proposed terms.
</P>
<P>
   Then McColl appeared. Robertson asked him whether he would
consider an equal board split. McColl noted that he and Coulter had
considered such an arrangement but decided they should divide seats
based on the relative size and market value of the two banks.
</P>
<P>
   Flourishing a copy of a biography of A.P. Giannini, McColl
compared his attempts to build a nationwide bank with those of
BofA's founder. He told directors he had never met anyone like
Coulter before. ``Maybe I can learn something from him and maybe he
can learn something from me,'' he said. He waxed patriotic,
declaring that the new institution would be America's greatest
bank, and its colors would be red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   McColl ``was his most charming Southern self. It was a masterful
performance,'' recalled one director.
</P>
<P>
   Directors approved the deal unanimously. Four days later, the
second-largest merger in U.S. banking history was announced at a
New York City news conference. McColl sported a San Francisco 49ers
cap, while Coulter donned a cap emblazoned with the Carolina
Panthers team emblem.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after the merger announcement, NationsBank managers
began making decisions without consulting their BofA counterparts
even though O'Neill formally headed the transition team. More than
a month passed without an all-important first meeting of the
six-member managing committee of the combined bank.
</P>
<P>
   As the first rounds of executive appointments came in,
NationsBank officers got most of the plum jobs, including heads of
personnel, public relations, and technology.
</P>
<P>
   At the first postdeal meeting of the BofA board's executive
committee, held in Portland, Ore., on May 21, several directors
griped about ``the characterization of the proposed merger in the
media and by some employees as an acquisition of BankAmerica by
NationsBank,'' according to the meeting's minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Both McColl and Coulter were scheduled to go to the
International Monetary Conference in Vienna at the beginning of
June, an annual conclave of the CEOs of the world's largest banks.
David and Susan Coulter stopped to pick up McColl wife, Jane, who
spent much of the transatlantic flight telling stories about her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the conference hotel, Coulter called McColl's
room to invite him for a drink. Coulter was joined by his wife.
McColl came alone.
</P>
<P>
   Over drinks, McColl began a personal attack against Coulter, the
BofA CEO later told associates. The two also clashed then or
shortly after over the appointment of Gene Taylor, a senior
NationsBank official, as head of retail banking in BofA's old
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter was moving toward a momentous decision. Flying back to
the United States, he ordered corporate secretary Cheryl Sorokin to
call an emergency meeting of the board's executive committee. He
phoned O'Neill instructing him to hire a lawyer to determine
whether BofA could halt the merger.
</P>
<P>
   McColl, meanwhile, was on his way to Budapest with his wife on
the first vacation they had taken together in years. Hance called
to tell him he had to fly back to the United States to save the
deal. NationsBank's chief headed immediately to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   At emergency meetings of BofA's executive committee, several
directors were ready to cancel the deal. But the attorney hired by
BofA, Chicago merger lawyer Robert Helman, told them that Coulter
had signed a binding contract. Walking out on the deal would be
prohibitively expensive and open the bank to shareholder lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helman said, `You've been talking about how wonderful the deal
is for shareholders and now you're going to take it apart because
McColl wasn't nice?'''
</P>
<P>
   As a fallback, committee members prepared a list of terms they
wanted added to the merger agreement, including a more specific
promise that Coulter would get the CEO job by a set date.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter took the demands to McColl, who was waiting _ and fuming
_ at the Mandarin. The NationsBank CEO said he needed to consult
with his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   McColl ultimately refused many of the demands, but he agreed to
make a videotape for distribution to employees pledging that
Coulter would follow him as CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter's aborted rebellion seemed to knock the wind out of his
sails, associates said. ``He knew people were increasingly upset.
He began to withdraw,'' said one BofA executive.
</P>
<P>
   The next few months brought a series of humiliations. In August,
merger documents disclosed the terms of Coulter's golden parachute.
Angry BofA employees accused their chief of selling the bank to
enrich himself.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Coulter insist that he did not push the merger
for the money, a point they say is proved by his campaign to kill
the deal, which would have left him empty-handed. Nevertheless,
disclosure of the enormous sum he would receive if he quit left the
indelible impression of a man who already had one foot out the
door.
</P>
<P>
   To shore up his standing, Coulter's publicists let it be known
that he was hunting for a house in Charlotte. And he made a voice
mail recording for employees declaring, ``I'm not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In a July 29 letter to directors, Coulter wrote: ``I am acutely
aware of the criticism, second-guessing, and in some cases,
hostility, you may have encountered since we announced the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many of you, I am sometimes discouraged by this,'' he
added. ``But not for long.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, a bomb blew up in Coulter's face in the form of
the bank's stake in a risky fund managed by the New York investment
firm D.E. Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw used advanced software to pinpoint subtle differences in
the prices of similar securities, buying or selling based on
statistical models showing how such securities performed in the
past. Coulter was enamored. Despite the qualms of BofA's risk
managers, Coulter lent the firm about $1.4 billion to invest for
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the investment spewed profits. But as markets
around the world crashed, BofA's Shaw stake began producing oceans
of red ink. Losses multiplied many times over because the Shaw fund
borrowed heavily to finance the BofA investments.
</P>
<P>
   As Shaw was unraveling, BofA shareholders overwhelmingly
approved the bank's merger with NationsBank on September 24.
</P>
<P>
   On October 1, McColl announced at a Dallas press conference that
the combination of BofA and NationsBank was official. Coulter
watched McColl's performance on a video screen from an auditorium
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Inside BofA, it was apparent that McColl was seizing on the Shaw
affair to get rid of Coulter. The new bank released combined
third-quarter earnings on October 14. The Shaw investment
necessitated a $372 million write-off, a major factor cutting
profits by half. Charlotte-based executives made it clear they were
furious.
</P>
<P>
   McColl sent W.W. ``Hootie'' Johnson, chairman of the executive
committee of his board, to San Francisco to demand Coulter's
immediate resignation. The bank announced Coulter's departure three
days later.
</P>
<P>
   McColl has scrupulously avoided commenting on his relations with
the San Francisco executive. But in an interview last March, he
offered a hint about his reasons: ``I'm very frank, very
straightforward, very candid. I also expect people who deal with me
to be the same way. I don't expect people to renege on a deal that
they've made or change their mind after they've shaken hands. You
can't stay here if you do that.''
</P>
<P>
