<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S GOAL: POCATELLO PAYBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The returning Cal State Northridge football
players all remember what happened last year in Pocatello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who was there ... we all know what it felt like,''
said Chazz Moore, a senior cornerback. ``We were talking rings.''
</P>
<P>
   But CSUN's dreams of a Big Sky Conference championship vanished
in the closing minute, when underdog Idaho State scored a touchdown
and beat the Matadors 32-29. No championship, no playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN finally gets a chance to take out a year's frustration on
the Bengals Saturday, when it hosts ISU at 3:05 p.m. at North
Campus Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly who we've been looking for,'' Moore said. ``If
there's one game we could be strictly focusing on, it would be
Idaho State, because of what (the Bengals) did to us last year.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN is 1-2, 0-1 in the Big Sky. Idaho State is 2-2 and 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Strong words: After two consecutive losses, Jeff Kearin and the
rest of the coaching staff have been vocal in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensity is up a little this week,'' he said Tuesday.
``Last week was a very, very frustrating loss. There's been all
this talk about all this greatness, me included, and when push
comes to shove, we lose a game we should have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time now for everybody who's been talking to get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinning out: Kearin is reluctant to play fourth-string tailback
Brandon McElvaine, not because McElvaine has performed poorly but
because he wants to redshirt the promising freshman from Highland
High.
</P>
<P>
   But with starter Jaumal Bradley (tonsillitis) doubtful for Idaho
State, and No. 2 tailback Alan Taylor hobbled with a knee injury,
McElvaine might be needed. Kearin also isn't ruling out playing
time for freshmen Crayton Milton (St. Francis) and Marquis Brignac
(Taft).
</P>
<P>
   ``(McElvaine) has got a shot,'' Kearin said. ``I'm going to have
Marquis Brignac ready, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeat performer: Kick returner Terrence Jones, who returned
Saturday's opening kickoff at Eastern Washington for a 86-yard
touchdown, was named the Big Sky's special-teams player of the
week. Jones has earned the honor twice this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones returned three kickoffs for 121 yards against the Eagles.
Before Saturday, the last time the Matadors had a kickoff returned
for a touchdown was on Nov. 9, 1991, when Paul Peters returned one
95 yards against Portland State.
</P>
<P>
   Factoids: Quarterback Marcus Brady broke the CSUN record for
total offense in a game with 513 yards against Eastern Washington.
Brady threw for 484 yards and rushed for 29, topping Aaron Flowers'
mark of 496 set in '96, also against Eastern Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, a sophomore, leads the Big Sky in total offense,
averaging 334.7 yards per game. Wide receiver Aaron Arnold, who set
the school record for career receiving yards last week, leads the
conference in catches per game (8.7) and is second in receiving
yards (296).
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, again: Idaho State quarterback Kevin McCarthy, a
junior who lost his job to Shane Griggs to start the season, is
back in the lineup. Griggs tore the ACL in his right knee on
Sept.11 and is out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy won't be asked to do a lot against CSUN because junior
tailback Nick Whitworth is the Big Sky's second-leading rusher,
with 625 yards and six touchdowns. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
