<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROME-ANTIQUITIES-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ROME, ANCIENT RUINS STALL RAMP TO `GOD'S PARKING LOT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Workers building a ramp to a vast Vatican garage for
pilgrims recently stumbled on walls of an ancient Roman villa.
</P>
<P>
   Now work has halted on the ramp to ``God's parking lot,'' as it
is known locally, while Italy decides what is more important:
preserving remnants of Rome's imperial past, or building modern
amenities to insure a smooth pilgrims' progress for as many as 30
million visitors expected in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real test, a clash between modernity and the past,''
said Oreste Rutigliano, a spokesman for Italia Nostra, a
conservation association that is lobbying to close down the ramp
and resurrect the ruins. ``To permit modernity to win out would be
a terrible symbol for the jubilee.''
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments draw eye-rolls from some of the engineers and
city officials who have to get Rome and its roads ready by
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rome already has plenty of Roman walls, perhaps too
many,'' said Luigi Scavizzi, an engineer with Geosonda, the
construction company that is building the access ramp. ``This may
be a famous site to some, but to me it's just a bother.''
</P>
<P>
   Those bothersome walls date from about the first century A.D.
</P>
<P>
   Government archaeologists who are now gingerly sifting through
the site say they have not determined who built them, but already
some Italian archaeologists are saying it may have been a villa of
Agrippina, Caligula's sister and Nero's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Though not remembered for her sweetness (among other things, she
is accused of poisoning several husbands, including Claudius),
Agrippina had a cheery taste in decor; the walls still show traces
of delicate floral patterns and songbirds.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost impossible to dig in Rome without stumbling on some
ancient artifact. Two weeks ago, archaeologists at a different site
found a second-century A.D. base of a statue, covered with reliefs
of Hercules, as well as pavement and walls that were once back of
the stage of the theater of Marcellus. In that case, however, the
discovery did not compete with new construction.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say the walls discovered under the Janiculum Hill
next to the Vatican last month were the first archaeological find
that required tough choices since preparations for the year 2000
began.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there are close to 700 construction sites snarling
traffic in Rome, and more than half are repairs undertaken
specifically for the jubilee celebrations of the Roman Catholic
Church. Holy Years, when the faithful are exhorted to make
pilgrimages to Rome, were introduced in 1300 by Pope Boniface VIII,
and now take place every 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rome is a city haunted by the way previous generations
recklessly bulldozed through buried Greek columns and Roman villas
to modernize the capital. After World War II, construction crews
destroyed whole Roman neighborhoods to build subways and the train
station of Termini, which was inaugurated for the 1950 jubilee.
</P>
<P>
   The country's feelings of guilt were most powerfully invoked in
a scene in Fellini's ``Roma'': subway workers digging underground
crash through a wall and stare silently as giant frescoes flake and
vanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Rome,'' said Emanuele Gatti, a classical archaeologist
who specializes in central Rome. ``We have found a lot. We have
destroyed a lot. And underground there is still an unquantifiable
amount of treasures to be discovered.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rome is undergoing an extraordinary, $950 million make-over for
the year 2000, but some of its most ambitious plans have been
shelved.
</P>
<P>
   A highway underpass beneath Castel Sant'Angelo was scrapped
after environmental groups, urban planners and archaeologists
protested that the digging would damage the foundations of the
second-century mausoleum built by the Emperor Hadrian. Other
projects have hit different snags. Earlier this month, heavy rains
drove a gaping hole in a newly completed highway tunnel built under
the Appian Way.
</P>
<P>
   The underground parking lot, which is still being built to
accommodate 115 buses and 800 cars, is on Vatican territory near
St. Peter's, a $45 million project whose cost is being evenly
divided by the Italian government and the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The parking lot is the Vatican's only major jubilee expense;
pilgrims will have to pay to book spaces at big public Masses and
major Holy Year events. The Italian government and the city of Rome
are paying for street repairs and restoration of historic
buildings, including churches.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican did not even have to pay to clean up St. Peter's.
The gleaming $5.4 million restored facade, which was unveiled on
Tuesday, was executed and paid for by ENI, the Italian energy
giant.
</P>
<P>
   The ramp is on state-owned land, and its fate falls under the
jurisdiction of the Culture Ministry, which must determine the
value of the find. A special committee is expected to decide soon
whether to stop building the ramp. Italia Nostra officials argue
that since the project envisions two ramps, the Vatican and Rome
can manage with only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could have managed with one, we wouldn't have spent the
money to build two,'' Scavizzi retorted.
</P>
<P>
   Claudio Mocchegiani-Carpano, an archaeologist for the
government's Rome office of archaeology, said: ``This is not the
find of the century, but we would never destroy the ruins. If they
are of less importance, they could be moved, but such decisions
will be up to the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Even that option could significantly delay the completion of the
ramp. Officials responsible for readying the city are worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to accept the decision that is made,'' said Maurizio
Pucci, an official with the Rome Agency for the Preparation of the
Jubilee, which is coordinating year 2000 projects. ``But we are
awaiting it with trepidation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
