<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 ( bl )  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMAZON PLANS TO EXPAND TO AN ONLINE WAREHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com plans to become an Internet shopping bazaar by
opening its Web site to a variety of merchants for $9.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon hopes to capture part of the online sales market, which
is expected to reach $108 billion by 2003. The move would give
Amazon a steady stream of cash without the costs associated with a
warehouse of products.
</P>
<P>
   BANK OF SCOTLAND GOES ON THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Scotland chief executive Peter Burt took his rationale
for the bank's takeover of National Westminster Bank for $34
billion to London on Wednesday to try to win over Natwest's
investors. Reports also emerged that Bank of Scotland was exploring
an alliance with an investment partner, possibly an American bank.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL AS RALLY ATTEMPTS FAIL
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were down Wednesday as attempts to build on Tuesday's
late rally failed to generate enthusiasm. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 62.05 points, to 10,213.48. The NASDAQ composite index
fell 25.98 points, to 2,730.27. And the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index dropped 13.83 points, to 1,268.37.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-MOBIL DEAL WINS AN APPROVAL
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission on Wednesday approved Exxon's planned
takeover of Mobil, which would create the world's largest publicly
held oil company, on the condition that they sell assets in Europe
to preserve competition. But the merger still awaits action by the
U.S. Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON CEO
</P>
<P>
   Chevron on Wednesday named its vice chairman, Dave O'Reilly, as
its chairman and chief executive, succeeding Ken Derr, who will
retire at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF AVON FALL AFTER WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Avon Products on Wednesday fell $9.875, to $25.8125,
after it said third-quarter profit would meet analysts' estimates,
but that its fourth-quarter might fall short.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA ONLINE ENTERS HONG KONG
</P>
<P>
   America Online chairman Steve Case went to Hong Kong to
introduce AOL Hong Kong, a partnership with a highflying local
Internet provider, China.com. The new service offers the usual
America Online features plus Cantonese pop music, Chinese cooking
tips and horse-racing forums.
</P>
<P>
   ABBOTT DIPS AFTER F.D.A. COMMENT
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Abbott Laboratories on Wednesday fell $2.50, to
$37.50, after the Food and Drug Administration threatened to halt
sales of some of its diagnostic products because of concerns about
quality controls at plants near Chicago. The setback is the latest
in a string of manufacturing problems for Abbott. In December, the
FDA held up shipments of Abbott's clot-busting drug Abbokinase.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE OF CRUDE TOPS $25 A BARREL
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil on Wednesday jumped 36 cents, to $24.69 a
barrel, after briefly trading above $25 a barrel for the first time
in two and a half years. The price move came after an industry
group reported that domestic inventories of crude oil had fallen to
the lowest level since January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE GOODS ORDERS INCREASE
</P>
<P>
   Orders to factories for big-ticket manufactured goods rose 0.9
percent in August, led by an increase in demand for airplanes,
automobiles and other transportation equipment.
</P>
<P>
   FANNIE MAE TO EASE MORTGAGE LOANS
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae will ease the credit requirements on mortgage loans
that it buys from banks and other lenders, which could help
increase home ownership rates among minorities and low-income
consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
