<HEADER>
A1512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GROWING-OLD-NYT &LR;      09-29 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWING-OLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT DEATH WITH OLD AGE NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIQUIU, N.M. _ The men and women who had gathered for a
conference on aging and wisdom at Ghost Ranch, the mountain retreat
where Georgia O'Keeffe once lived and painted, were asked by their
workshop leader to imagine their own deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Hedy-Jo Huss, a professional caregiver from Oregon in her early
50s, told the group she wanted to be making love to the owner of
the liquor store in a certain small town in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rollins, 59, a retired Pan Am pilot from Arizona, said, ``I
want to be by a stream of running water in a hammock. All my
friends are going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Hurst, 77, a retired teacher from Los Angeles, said her
greatest hope was that when the time to die came, she did not deny
it.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about growing old and dying has long been taboo in
youth-obsessed America, but in coming years, as their numbers
skyrocket, it may begin to seem as though older Americans talk of
little else. The generation that is retired and approaching its
last years, and especially the baby boomers following them, are
examining what it means to age as no generation before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about being yourself, whatever that is,'' said Loretta
Wrobel, 55, a psychotherapist with long gray hair, who had traveled
to Ghost Ranch, an hour north of Santa Fe, from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop at Ghost Ranch _ where O'Keeffe painted into her
90s _ is one of scores of events this year at which ``conscious
aging,'' a term that refers loosely to aging as an opportunity for
human growth and social contribution, is the focus.
</P>
<P>
   Where society has tended to look at old people as patients or
problems, and another popular new school of thought, ``successful
aging,'' celebrates hard-charging octogenarians on skis, conscious
aging is less about physical vitality, and more about learning to
live with these inescapable facts of life, aging and dying.
</P>
<P>
   At one extreme is Deepak Chopra, whose book ``Ageless Body,
Timeless Mind: The Quantum Alternative to Growing Old'' (Crown
Publishers, 1993), suggests that meditation and yoga can keep old
age at bay. But the mainstream is made up of self-professed
realists who say that there is no denying that the body fails _ and
that there lies the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrate the John Glenns, and the sexy grandmothers, but
that's trying to transform old age into middle age,'' said Rick
Moody, the former director of the Brookdale Center on Aging at
Hunter College, and author of ``The Five Stages of the Soul''
(Doubleday Anchor Books, 1997), a guide to spiritual growth in the
second half of life. ``Conscious aging is saying that the big
adventure is the inner journey, and that does not have to stop when
you can no longer ski downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Cole, a University of Texas historian who wrote a
cultural history of aging, ``The Journey of Life'' (Cambridge
University Press, 1991), says conscious aging is an effort to break
through the American tendency to think either entirely positively
about old age or entirely negatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either all bad _ people get decrepit and they should be
put away in nursing homes,'' Cole said, ``or it's all good _ we all
automatically become wise.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to face the complex reality of growing old, Cole
and others say, is to talk about it. And at Ghost Ranch, there was
a full weekend of talk, on subjects from retirement communities to
Hindu, Buddhist and American Indian views of aging and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we do with these extra years?'' asked Dr. Drew Leder,
a 44-year-old professor of Western and Eastern philosophy at Loyola
College, in his opening talk.
</P>
<P>
   Proposing that aging be used as ``a curriculum for the soul,''
Leder asked the participants to talk about their own awakening to
aging.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Greensmith, 64, a retired teacher from Prescott, Ariz.,
talked about her role in a community theater production of ``The
Velveteen Rabbit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else in the cast was a child,'' Mrs. Greensmith said.
``I was the fairy godmother, but they called me the fairy
grandmother. I suddenly saw myself through their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   While the thought had not occurred to her, said Mrs. Greensmith,
who has gray hair, to the children she was undeniably old. And that
was three years ago, when she was 61.
</P>
<P>
   For Paul Rollins, the epiphany was his parents' unhappy old age.
As a young couple, and even well past middle age, he said, they had
been part of a vibrant community in North Carolina. But they did
not anticipate growing old, Rollins said, and almost overnight
their friends moved away, or died.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents died alone in a nursing home,'' he said. ``That
transformed me. I decided I wanted to age with friends, not
strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar experience motivated Geoffrey Landis, a 47-year-old
artist, to found Jubilados, the Buddhist-based group that sponsored
the conference and is planning an affordable, spiritual retirement
community in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   Landis told the group that his mother, Elizabeth Landis, who had
been a prominent lawyer in Philadelphia, had died, marginalized and
invisible, in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion turned to the wisdom of old people in general.
Melinda Hurst offered a cautionary view, saying, ``You're not going
to get wise just because you get old.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurst, who sits on the ethics board at Cedars Sinai Hospital
in Los Angeles, said later that she had come to the conference to
explore her deepest fears about aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid of being left behind,'' she said. ``I'm afraid of
the fact that I can't figure out the damn computer. I think the gap
is very painful between people who are plugged into technology and
those of us who aren't. Things went very slowly when we were
growing up. Now, my god, you get a computer, and six months later,
they tell you to get a new one.''
</P>
<P>
   She will probably replace her Powerbook soon, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roszak, the author of the book about the 1960s ``The
Making of a Counterculture'' (University of California Press,
1968), talked about his latest book, ``America the Wise'' (Houghton
Mifflin, 1998), and his view that baby boomers would bring about a
more compassionate society in their old age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who are sitting in this room today are the wave of
the future,'' said Roszak, who recently retired as a professor of
history at California State University at Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, and with all the emphasis at the conference on the
joys of later life, it is not easy growing old in America. Carol
Segrave, 57, who did the publicity for the conference, is a
consultant on conscious aging. She meditates and quotes the
68-year-old author Ram Dass on the spiritual growth that can come
with physical decline. At the same time, she is mindful of the
youth culture that reigns in Southern California, where she lives
and works. And when the subject of plastic surgery came up, Ms.
Segrave, who is from Santa Monica, did not hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want it,'' she said. ``I'm going to start with my eyes.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
