<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A FAN OFFERS SCORESHEET INSPIRATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Bobby Valentine hurried into Shea Stadium for
Wednesday night's game with the Braves, a middle-aged fan, James
McCahan of Brooklyn, handed the Mets' manager a big white envelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me: `Hey, Bobby, do me a favor. I scored every game
this season and here are my scoresheets,''' Valentine was saying
during batting practice. ``He told me: `I love the team. Show the
guys these scoresheets so they'll know how good they've been all
year.' I haven't yet, but I'm going to show it to them before the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything for inspiration. Anything to snap the Mets out of their
seven-game losing streak that began last week in Atlanta when John
Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux put them into a tailspin that
continued in Philadelphia and has now jeopardized the Mets' hope
for a wild-card berth in the National League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night the Mets lost again to Glavine, now 13-11, and
Wednesday night they were confronted by Maddux, who went to the
mound with a 19-8 record. In Thursday night's finale, they will be
facing Kevin Millwood, the 24-year-old right-hander with an 18-7
record and a 2.69 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   In talking about the reasons for any slump, Valentine mentioned
``injuries, fatigue, and sometimes good pitchers put you in a
slump.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that maybe those good pitchers in Atlanta
had triggered this Mets' slump, he agreed, saying: ``Yeah,
probably. That was the start of this whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Mets don't recuperate in time, they will be the first
team to have blown the wild card in a collapse since the wild card
was dealt into the postseason in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams have blown the pennant when the pennant meant first
place either in the league or the division, notably the 1964
Philadelphia Phillies, who were 6 1-2 games up with 12 games
remaining. But the Phillies proceeded to lose 10 straight before
winning their last two in Cincinnati. Too little, too late, as the
St. Louis Cardinals rallied to win the pennant and then disposed of
the Yankees in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Mauch, then the Phillies' manager, acknowledged that he
``just wore the pitching staff out,'' alluding to having started
Jim Bunning and Chris Short on two days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   When the Phillies returned on their charter flight from
Cincinnati that final Sunday of the season, some 2,000 fans were at
the Philadelphia airport to cheer and console them. As their plane
rolled up to the gate, Mauch turned to his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the first one off,'' he said. ``You guys didn't
lose it. I did.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Phillies' owner, Bob Carpenter, didn't hold Mauch
responsible. Mauch, who had been hired in 1961, remained the
Phillies' manager until he was dismissed during the 1968 season. He
later managed the Montreal Expos, the Minnesota Twins and the
California Angels, but he's mostly remembered as the best manager
never to guide a team to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Two other teams _ the 1951 Brooklyn Dodgers and the 1978 Boston
Red Sox _ blew big leads, but didn't really collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Between games of a doubleheader on Aug. 11, 1951, the Brooklyn
Dodgers were 13{ games ahead of the New York Giants, who would
catch them on the final weekend of the season and then win the
pennant on Bobby Thomson's home run off Ralph Branca at the Polo
Grounds in the ninth inning of their decisive third playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers had not really collapsed. They finished with a
26-22 stretch, but the Giants were a remarkable 37-7.
</P>
<P>
   The 1978 Red Sox were 14 games ahead of the Yankees on July 11.
Then the Yankees, sweeping four games at Fenway Park in a September
massacre, jumped past them before the Red Sox won their final eight
games to force a one-game divisional playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been prouder of anybody in baseball,'' Don Zimmer,
then the Red Sox manager, told his players. ``Don't nobody ever
tell me this team choked.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day Bucky Dent hit a home run, only his fifth that
season, off Mike Torrez into the screen above the Green Monster at
Fenway Park. The Yankees went on to win the American League pennant
in a playoff with the Kansas City Royals, then won their second
straight World Series.
</P>
<P>
   So those '78 Red Sox didn't really collapse. Neither did those
'51 Dodgers. But the '64 Phillies did. And now the Mets might be
discarding a wild card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
