<HEADER>
A0784 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLOOD-ECU     09-29 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-ECU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some settled, others not as ECU resumes classes
 &HT;    By T. Scott Batchelor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The attitudes of students returning to ECU
Wednesday varied like the condition of the dormitories they
returned to.
</P>
<P>
   Some students sat on residence hall porches, opening care
packages from home, excited to be back; others sat in the ECU Flood
Relief Resource Center, uncertain about things as basic as where
they would be living for the rest of the semester.
</P>
<P>
   The East Carolina University administration called school back
into session at 8 a.m. Wednesday, two weeks after Hurricane Floyd
slammed the doors shut and ran most students away from campus.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimated Tuesday that about 900 students still had no
place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Corri Zajicek was one of them, and she was not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that all the ECU students are in town is
complicating cleanup efforts,'' said Zajicek, a junior from
Winston-Salem whose Village Green apartment sustained substantial
water damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all rainwater, but it flooded the apartment,'' Zajicek
said. She and her roommate saved many of their possessions by
stacking them on bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Zajicek sat at a table in the relief center clasping several
forms _ paper keys used to unlock the doors to disaster-relief
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Cards and handwritten messages posted on a wall outside the
center carried words of support for the students victimized by
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember: You are not alone,'' urged one card. Another read,
``Have faith: Things fall apart so that things can fall together.''
</P>
<P>
   Zajicek said her apartment still had no electrical service.
Someone offered a loft for temporary lodging, but that dwelling had
not materialized Wednesday afternoon, Zajicek said.
</P>
<P>
   For her, Chancellor Richard Eakin's decision to bring the
students back was not wise, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just put it after Christmas and start it over,'' she said of
the semester. ``I think he's endangering our grades.''
</P>
<P>
   Zajicek expected the adversity to take a ``big toll'' on her
grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the work we've got to do on the side to keep up, on
top of working, on top of the stress of moving and cleaning,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Eakin appealed to the ECU faculty members to be
sympathetic to their students' plight, but Zajicek said one of her
professors wasn't heeding that call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got like five projects this guy handed me today,'' she
said. ``They expect us to remember stuff from two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Her perspective sharply contrasted that of freshmen Leah Vaughn
of Apex, N.C., and Kate Herlehy of Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Herlehy hung out with Vaughn at her family's home after the
students evacuated the campus two Saturdays ago. Other than being
forced from campus, the Jones Hall residents were unfazed by Floyd
and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all glad to be back,'' Vaughn said as she explored the
lollipops and other provisions in a parcel sent by Herlehy's
parents. ``We missed everybody so much.''
</P>
<P>
   During roll call in class, Herlehy said, her professors noted
which students had been affected by the flooding, ``so they can
make sure they can get all the help to the students.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be real lenient about tests, homework and
quizzes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Herlehy and Vaughn said attendance in their classes had been
high, an observation that jibes with reports from university
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anecdotal evidence indicates there were full classes all
over campus,'' said ECU spokesman John Durham.
</P>
<P>
   That bodes well for the objective of keeping students in school
stated by Eakin and Molly Broad, president of the 16-campus
University of North Carolina system, who visited the campus and the
relief center Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,800 students and employees have used the services at
the relief center in Todd Dining Hall. A relief fund to aid
students, faculty and staff members affected by flooding totaled
more than $275,000 as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said she came on the first day back after the catastrophe
to view for herself the efforts by ECU to set things aright. She
also hoped to be a cheerleader for students, to make sure
floodwaters don't wash them out of the halls of academe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming back is very important,'' Broad said, urging them not
to withdraw from school if at all possible.
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday, four students have officially withdrawn from
classes in the wake of Hurricane Floyd's flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Broad commended East Carolina's administration, faculty and
staff for turning in a ``tremendous performance'' in the face of
Floyd's wrath, and afterward, when things went from bad to worse.
</P>
<P>
   The UNC system is ``working in many places simultaneously,''
including the U.S. Congress, to get funds to help ECU in its
journey back to normalcy, Broad said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as students returned to the soggy campus Wednesday,
evidence that all was not normal on campus. A small wall of
sandbags ringed steps leading to the basement of Christenbury
Memorial Gymnasium; a construction gate blocked off a section of
gutter and bricks that had washed out on Wright Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Variously worded signs recalled Saturday's football game between
the ECU Pirates and the University of Miami Hurricanes _ a game
that became an allegory: ``ECU Beats Hurricanes _ Floyd and
Miami,'' read a button worn by staffers on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Hunt, one of the football players who helped defeat Miami,
returned home to find a refrigerator full of spoiled food inside
his flooded apartment in Tar River Estates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of close to the front (of the apartment complex), but
it still came up there,'' he said of the swollen Tar River.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt visited the flood-relief center Wednesday afternoon and
picked up a cash gift of $100 to jump-start his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this I'm probably going to do a lot of food shopping,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Hunt's geography class on Wednesday, ``there were four or
five people whose places had been flooded out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his teachers had been ``pretty understanding'' of their
students' plight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, concentrating on academic pursuits must be a trying
affair for those who returned to destroyed or damaged dwellings,
said Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's still going to be a distraction,'' Hunt said.
``That's got to be hard, them trying to concentrate on class and
tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
