<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-BODIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Town prepares to handle the dead
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Burials in at least one of Greenville's
cemeteries have been delayed by Hurricane Floyd, but contrary to
rumors, the county morgue is not overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral homes are keeping the bodies of people who have died of
hurricane-related and other causes and can't be buried, said Dr.
M.G.F. Gilliland, a county medical examiner. The morgue at Pitt
County Memorial Hospital is nowhere near full, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital, preparing for the worst, brought in a refrigerated
truck that holds about 20 bodies, in case there were more deaths
than the morgue _ with room for 16 bodies _ could handle, Gilliland
said. But the truck hasn't been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we are grateful,'' she said. ``Agencies have had long
lists of missing persons, but most of them are being found at
shelters or at relatives' homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Five people in Pitt County have died from storm-related causes,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliland was eager to dispel the rumor that bodies were
``piling up'' at the morgue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad, but it's not that bad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownhill Cemetery, a public cemetery, hasn't been fit for
burials for two weeks because the ground is too soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the need to get equipment in and around
existing graves and with the ground so wet, they don't want to
destroy those graves,'' said City Engineer Jim Jatko. The city has
three public cemeteries. City officials say they hope to start
digging at Brownhill by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Brothers Mortuary has delayed burying two women in
Brownhill, said secretary Cathy Venable. Neither death was
flood-related. One woman, who died at 88, has been at the funeral
home for more than 10 days, she
</P>
<P>
   said. She is embalmed so there is no need to refrigerate the
body, Venable said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The families haven't complained, because they know there's
nothing anybody can do,'' she said. ``They prefer to wait than have
us put Mama down in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   The families delay only the burial, not the funeral services,
Venable said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilkerson and Sons Funeral Home had to delay two funerals,
but they were scheduled during the height of the hurricane, two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
