a k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1003-COX     09-29 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1003-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: IN SEARCH OF THE REAL REAGAN
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 3.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON On our way to a White House party, we strolled past a
sidewalk photographer hawking his wares. For $5, he offered to snap
a picture of us standing beside the two-dimensional ``president.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in the State Dining Room, the president made a similar
offer. Turning to my wife, Ronald Reagan said: ``Let's have a
picture of us together with Nancy.''
</P>
<P>
   As the official photographer obliged, my wife recalled the bid
we'd received from beyond the confines of the Executive Mansion.
``Mr. President,'' she said, ``I hope people will be able to tell
if it's you or if it's a cardboard cutout.''
</P>
<P>
   If her jest carried an edge, he missed it. Inclined to quiet
chuckles, this time Reagan laughed uproariously. ``Yes,'' he said,
``that's the trouble with this town. It's hard to tell the
difference between a phony fake and a real fake.''
</P>
<P>
   That scene, from more than a decade ago, came in mind while
reading reviews of ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' Edmund
Morris's newly published and widely controversial book. As his
biographer, Morris agonized for years over his seeming inability to
define his subject.
</P>
<P>
   As he tells it, Morris overcame his writer's block by touring
Reagan's boyhood haunts and spawning a fictional observer.
Fittingly, the real Morris also portrays the fake Morris as a
screenwriter. For the best clues to Reagan's often engaging and
not-so-enigmatic character are to be found in his long career as a
movie star.
</P>
<P>
   An incident from the Reagan presidency illuminates his Hollywood
roots. One morning, for what's known as a ``two-on-one,'' I was
ushered into the Oval Office, along with George Skelton, then a
White House correspondent of the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton, seated in a wing chair opposite Reagan, posed the first
question. ``Well, Lou ...'' Reagan began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not, Lou, it's George,'' Skelton interjected.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan completed his reply. But he was clearly off his game.
Some moments later, his face suddenly brightened. ``I know why I
called you 'Lou,''' he said. ``Because they told me it was going to
be Lou.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Lou'' in question was Lou Cannon, then a White House
correspondent for the Washington Post. As California political
reporters, both Cannon and Skelton had been in frequent contact
with Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, some hours before our interview, the president
was given a seating chart which had put Cannon in the facing wing
chair. After Reagan had committed the chart to memory, Skelton's
alternate visage, a last-minute switch, failed to register.
</P>
<P>
   Morris deals with Reagan's seeming passivity by reminding
readers that ``actors remember forward, not backward. Yesterday's
take is in the can; today is already rolling: tomorrow's lines must
be got by heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, on the campaign trail, a drama student asked Reagan to
what he attributed his success as a communicator. Few questions
struck Reagan's fancy. But that one did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always imagine,'' he replied, ``that I'm still talking just
with a few of my good old buddies, as I did long ago, in that
barber shop back in Iowa. That makes it all work.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a snapshot of the real Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
