u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-1STLD-WRITE     09-29 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY ACCUSES BROOKLYN MUSEUM OF CONSPIRING TO PROMOTE PRIVATE
COLLECTION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ADDS 5th graf with quote; REWRITES following 8 grafs to conform;
ADDS 2nd take with 9 new grafs)  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT18, 20, 32 _ have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK In a new line of attack in the city's vehement
opposition to a controversial art exhibition, senior City Hall
officials Wednesday accused the Brooklyn Museum of Art of
conspiring with an auction house to inflate the value of the
artwork in the show, all of which is privately owned by British
advertising executive Charles Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   The administration officials vowed to file a lawsuit in state
Supreme Court seeking to seize control of the museum by contending
that it had violated its lease with the city in part by misusing a
public institution to promote a private collection.
</P>
<P>
   But they said they would not try to block the exhibition from
opening on Saturday and were instead preparing for a tough legal
battle. On Tuesday, the museum filed a lawsuit in federal court
accusing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of violating the First Amendment by
threatening to cut off the museum's city financing.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday afternoon, Deputy Mayor Joseph J.
Lhota, Deputy Mayor Randy L. Levine and the city's corporation
counsel, Michael D. Hess, accused the museum of ``hucksterism'' and
of perpetrating a ``scam'' by conspiring with Christie's auction
house, which is a sponsor of the exhibition, to enrich Saatchi by
inflating the value of his art collection.
</P>
<P>
   Lhota accused Christie's of planning to profit from controversy
surrounding the show. ``I guarantee you,'' he said, ``immediately
following this exhibition, Christie's will have an auction wherein
the artwork that is being proposed to be shown at the Brooklyn
Museum will be sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's swiftly rejected allegations that it had conspired
with Saatchi and the museum to profit from the show. ``We are aware
of these bewildering accusations,'' the auction house said in a
statement. ``They have absolutely no substance, are not true.
Christie's has a long history of sponsorships of exhibitions in the
United States and internationally. Nothing in this exhibition is
for sale, nor is their any expectation for any of the works from
the exhibition to be sold by Christie's.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum and Christie's quickly rejected the allegations as a
bizarre attempt by the administration to quash the museum show,
which Giuliani has called ``disgusting'' and offensive to Catholics
because it includes a painting of the Virgin Mary surrounded by
elephant dung and pornographic pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With Giuliani away on a three-day political trip to the West
Coast, officials at City Hall were clearly seeking to retake the
offensive in the museum dispute. The administration had been on the
defensive since late Tuesday, when the museum abandoned its efforts
to resolve the dispute through negotiations with City Hall and
announced that the show would go on as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that every day, the city comes up with a new
pretextual claim,'' said Floyd Abrams, the First Amendment lawyer
who is representing the museum in its federal suit against the
city. ``Now, they have come up with another argument. Each and
every one of them is nothing more or less than further pretext in
an effort to punish the museum for the exercise of its First
Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum, through a spokesman, issued a statement calling the
city's accusations ``preposterous and misleading.'' It said, ``The
mayor's latest charge simply reflects the depths to which he will
go to undermine the First Amendment.'' The spokesman, Fred
Schroeder, said Christie's financial contribution to the show
represented a small fraction of its total cost.
</P>
<P>
   In making the allegations of conspiracy, city officials
capitalized on news reports that noted the dual role of Christie's,
which is a promoter and financial supporter of the exhibition as
well as a purveyor of artwork belonging to Saatchi, who is a major
collector and an important client. Christie's also supported an
installation of the exhibition at the Royal Academy in London.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid conflicts of interest, some museums, like the Museum of
Modern Art, do not exhibit private collections unless they have
been promised to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a scam and taxpayers' dollars should not be used to
support that,'' Hess, the corporation counsel, said at Wednesday's
news conference. ``Taxpayers' dollars should be used for educating
children, for building roads, for supporting the homeless, not for
pushing up the value of a private art collection.'' He added,
``We'll bring all of this out in court.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The controversy reached as far as Capitol Hill Wednesday, when
the Senate passed a nonbinding resolution sponsored by a
conservative senator, Bob Smith from New Hampshire, who recently
left the Republican Party. The resolution calls for an end to
federal financing for the Brooklyn Museum unless the exhibit is
immediately canceled. The measure, which passed on a voice vote,
has no bearing on federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, speaking against the
resolution, said the issue should be decided by the courts, not the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Floyd Abrams, who is perhaps the most significant First
Amendment lawyer of our age, is taking this case to a federal
District Court, urging that a First Amendment issue is involved and
that the proposed measures of the city of New York are in violation
of the First Amendment and cannot be allowed to stand,'' he said.
``In that circumstance, I should think that any member of this body
ought to defer to the courts before which this issue has now been
placed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the museum Wednesday, workers were racing to finish
preparations for the exhibition, about 90 pieces of contemporary
art from a crop of young British artists. Silk-screen artists were
completing labels for the pieces as electricians put the final
touches on the lighting and senior museum officials were
considering adding more security officers and surveillance cameras.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this was out of their concern over possible attempts to
vandalize some of the artwork, as happened when the exhibition was
first shown at the Royal Academy of Arts in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what is possible,'' Arnold Lehman, director
of the museum, said. ``Our phones are ringing off the hook, and
everyone is saying, `We'll be there, we'll be there.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We intend to make this orderly.''
</P>
<P>
   A citizens' group from Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, has already
announced plans to demonstrate against the exhibit on Saturday. The
American Civil Liberties Union said it would stage a demonstration
in support of the show on Friday, when the museum's 25,000 members
will be given a chance for an advance viewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do our very best to make sure people have every
opportunity to either show their support or protest,'' Lehman said,
adding his thanks to the local police precinct for its cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
