<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0574 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-LEGAL(TRIMS     09-29 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-LEGAL(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM FIGHT PITS FREE EXPRESSION AGAINST CONTROL OF PUBLIC
SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
(With NY-MUSEUM)  (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn Museum of Art says its battle with the
city is about free expression. The city says it is a
landlord-tenant fight over taste and the proper role of museums:
``I think it is a disgusting show,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle moves into the courts, legal strategies are
clearly shaping those pronouncements. The museum's legal position
is that artistic expression is protected by the First Amendment, it
asserted in the federal lawsuit it filed Tuesday. The city says
taxpayers are not required to underwrite offensive exhibits,
particularly for what it says are commercial aims. It is expected
to make that claim in a suit in state court soon.
</P>
<P>
   Both positions are to some extent correct under the law, said
legal experts on Wednesday. But the legal territory where the two
propositions meet is murky, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a black hole of First Amendment law,'' said David A.
Strauss, a professor of constitutional law at the University of
Chicago Law School. ``No one really knows how to think about it,
including the Supreme Court justices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand,'' Strauss continued, ``government officials can't
have carte blanche in deciding what to fund and what not to fund.
But on the other hand, it is clear the government is entitled to
make some decisions on what it will fund and what it won't fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Several First Amendment experts said the law seemed to favor the
museum, because of legal principles that protect the expression of
even unpopular ideas and forbid official punishment of unpopular
expression. Anti-religious sentiments, like those Giuliani said
were present in some of the artworks in the museum's exhibit, have
been protected by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   There are court decisions in the museum's favor. In a 1991 case
in Miami that was similar to the Brooklyn Museum battle, U.S.
District Court Judge James Lawrence King agreed with a Cuban arts
museum that the city government violated the First Amendment when
it refused to renew a lease after the museum had been criticized
for showing pro-Castro artists.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts said Wednesday that government clearly has
some right to control how taxpayer money is spent on cultural
events. The U.S. Supreme Court has sidestepped defining how the
First Amendment limits that power when the issue is cutting off
money for unpopular exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has ducked a straight-on resolution in every
case involving funding,'' said Richard H. Fallon Jr., a professor
of constitutional law at Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   There have been three rulings from the Supreme Court on related
issues since 1991. The most recent, a 1998 Supreme Court ruling
involving the National Endowment for the Arts, for example,
approved a federal ``decency test'' for federal arts funding.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said the decency standard was acceptable partly
because it was only advisory. Justice Sandra Day O'Connor's
majority opinion suggested that the law would violate the First
Amendment if the so-called decency test was imposed to limit
unpopular viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One problem in clarifying what legal principles apply to battles
over financing is that much of First Amendment law has developed in
cases involving government efforts to punish people criminally for
statements or artworks. The rulings in such cases have been clear
that the First Amendment prohibits punishment of artistic
statements, even those that offend many people.
</P>
<P>
   It is partly because of those rulings, several lawyers said
Wednesday, that the museum's lawyer, Floyd Abrams, has focused his
public comments on the contention that Giuliani is trying to punish
the museum for mounting the exhibit. If the courts agreed that
coercion or punishment was involved in the Brooklyn fight, they
would be more likely to rule that the mayor violated protections
for the free expression of viewpoints, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also clear, lawyers said, that government officials
have some authority to control how public money is spent. Some
legal experts said Wednesday that the city might properly decide in
advance, for example, that it would pay for one type of art _
opera, say _ but not another, like ballet.
</P>
<P>
   In some circumstances, such as where a municipality owns an
exhibit space, it might have especially broad authority over
esthetic judgments. The city leases the Eastern Parkway building to
the Brooklyn Museum and provides it with funding. That, lawyers
agreed, would not give it as much legal power over the content of
exhibits as the city might have in a government-owed museum.
</P>
<P>
   But, they said, the city would have some rights as a landlord
and financing agency. Whatever those rights might be, the lawyers
said, none would supersede the free expression guarantees of the
First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the U.S. Constitution, it is an open question how much the
city might be able to impose taste limitations in advance for
exhibits it helps underwrite, said Amy Adler, a New York University
law professor. It could be, she said, that the city might even be
able to impose rules aimed at barring museums financed by the city
from showing offensive art.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, the fact that Giuliani reacted in fury after the
exhibit was in place would make it difficult for the city to
prevail with the claim that it was merely imposing standards
limiting the use of city funds for certain types of exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   She said the mayor's remarks could be used to suggest that he
was trying to limit the expression of what he decided were
unacceptable artistic viewpoints. The courts, she said, would be
skeptical of such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be an easier case for the mayor,'' Professor Adler
said, ``if he had sat down with the museum people and said, `I've
been thinking about your mission, and I think your mission should
include not offending people.' But that is not what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Smolla, a First Amendment expert at the University of
Richmond, said that when it subsidizes a museum, a city, in effect,
creates a forum for private expression that gains some First
Amendment protections. As a result, he said, an effort to try to
bar funding that was based on disagreement with an artwork's
message _ like a supposedly anti-religious message _ could be held
to be a violation of the First Amendment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In separate interviews Wednesday, lawyers for the city and the
museum worked to define the dispute in the way that would help each
of them frame the case.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, the First Amendment specialist who is representing the
museum, focused on decisions that have barred officials from
imposing punishment for unpopular expression.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Giuliani's apparent grounds for attacking the
museum were the kinds of things the First Amendment was intended to
forbid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city,'' Abrams said, ``may take into account in its
prospective funding decisions matters of taste and, to some extent,
content, but not religious content and not whether it is, quote,
`sick' or anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   City Corporation Counsel Michael Hess focused on what he said
were the museum's lease and contract agreements with the city. But
he acknowledged that both sides were looking at the cases through
different legal lenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what the court will focus on,'' Hess said. ``Our
job is to answer whatever First Amendment questions the judge will
have, but also to show that we have rights as a landlord.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
