<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-MOBIL-EXXON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN COMMISSION CLEARS EXXON-MOBIL MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The European Commission on Wednesday gave approval to Exxon
Corp.'s planned takeover of Mobil Corp., which would create the
world's largest publicly held oil company, on the condition that
they shed assets in Europe to preserve competition.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said the companies, which still need the approval
of the U.S. Federal Trade Commission, had agreed to the
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Key among the conditions was that Mobil divest itself of its 30
percent interest in a joint venture with BP Amoco to refine and
market gasoline and other products in Europe. BP Amoco had said
that it was in talks with Mobil about the future of that alliance.
John Hervey, an oil analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, said
the book value of those assets was about $1.7 billion, which he
said would be a reasonable purchase price for BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Mobil agreed in early December 1998 to merge in a
stock transaction then valued at $80 billion. It would create a
giant worldwide oil company with revenues of about $147 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This did not surprise anybody'' Hervey said.``It had been
widely anticipated that they would have to disengage from the BP
joint venture.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the European Commission, the executive arm of
the European Union, said: ``As initially notified, the operation
would have created or strengthened dominant positions on eight
markets. Exxon and Mobil have made a series of undertakings to
eliminate those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies are still in negotiations with the enforcement
staff of the FTC. In the United States, talks have also focused on
the refining and marketing of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC has demanded that the two companies spin off about 1,500
service stations in the Middle Atlantic and Northeast regions as
well as a major refinery in California.
</P>
<P>
   California uses a cleaner-burning gasoline, and the number of
refineries that can produce it are limited. This has led to price
spikes for gasoline when a refinery has a problem. Thus the FTC
staff contends that the control of the refineries should not be
further concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, who has been
following the negotiations at the FTC, said in an interview earlier
this week that there had been progress.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Exxon had realized ``that there has to be some
significant divestitures for the states and the federal government
to approve the merger.'' Exxon chairman Lee Raymond said the
European approval was ``a major step toward the completion of the
merger.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the companies were continuing their discussions
with the FTC and the attorneys general of the affected states.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the European approval, Exxon and Mobil also agreed to
these conditions: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Mobil will sell its 28 percent interest in the German joint
venture marketing company Aral, which operates a large chain of
gasoline stations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exxon and Mobil will sell a portion of their lubricant
manufacturing operations in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mobil will sell some pipeline capacity that serves Gatwick
Airport near London.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exxon will sell assets connected with its worldwide commercial
airline lubricant business.
</P>
<P>
   There were also changes that would affect natural gas marketing
in Europe including divestiture of Mobil's Dutch gas trading
company Megas and Exxon's 25 percent interest in Thyssengas, a gas
distribution company in western Germany.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the European Commission also approved BP Amoco's
acquisition of ARCO for $32.7 billion. That approval was contingent
on BP's sale of its interests in British natural gas pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon shares rose 6.25 cents, to $74.75, while Mobil rose 12.5
cents, to $98. BP Amoco's American depository receipts rose 93.75
cents, to $107.1875, and ARCO gained $1.0625, to $86.1875. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
