<SLUG> BC-BEANIES-JUDAIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM SELLS JEWISH-THEME STUFFED ANIMALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS SIEROTY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Last winter while buying Beanie Babies for his
children's Hanukkah gifts, Steven Hoffman felt some regret the
animal-shape bags of beans didn't contain some religious
significance for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman forgot about the Beanie Babies until a family dinner a
few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone at dinner used the word fetch,'' Hoffman said, ``and I
said, `Kvetch the golden retriever.'''
</P>
<P>
   If only every dinner could be so lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Because from that one idea, Hoffman and his friend, Michael
Silver, have created a company that has sold thousands of
Judaic-themed beanbag animals within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Kvetch the Golden Retriever isn't among them. But Macca-Beanies
LLC is selling Gefilte the Fish, Cantor the Horse, Jacub the Bear,
Mooses the Moose, Muttzah the Dog, Purrim the Cat, Shofar the Ram
and Torah the Bull.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, 37, said the toys were designed to help introduce
children to elements of their Jewish heritage. Each Macca-Beanie
includes poems on the hang tags, along with the word ``Oy.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the inscription written by Hoffman's wife, Lauri,
for Torah the Bull reads, ``I hold my stories rolled up tight, in
the ark, under the eternal light.''
</P>
<P>
   Mooses the Moose reads, ``I led my people through the sand, all
the way to the Promised Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman added, ``Eight toys, one for each night of Hanukkah,
allows people to present a different Jewish theme each night of the
holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   As for how his company came up with the names of each stuffed
beanie, Hoffman said it was ``a family affair where everyone put
together their thoughts to come up with the names.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver, 36, arranged for production of the toys at overseas
factories. Once the production details were finalized, the
collectibles were manufactured in China and shipped back to the
United States for sale at delis, stores and synagogues throughout
Los Angeles and Orange counties.
</P>
<P>
   Macca-Beanies retail for $5.99 to $7.99. Hoffman said he and
Silver expect to exceed $300,000 in sales in the last quarter of
the year, with the majority of sales coming around Hanukkah, which
starts Dec. 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lorin Stein, manager of Fromin's Restaurant, said sales have
been ``pretty good'' since the Macca-Beanies went on sale about a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold a lot of Shofar the Ram during Rosh Hashana (the
Jewish New Year),'' said Stein, whose father opened the Encino
landmark 37 years ago. ``I think we will sell a lot of them over
Hanukkah.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the company has produced about 80,000 Macca-Beanies,
enough to cover the start-up costs and reach the financial
break-even point. ``I would be happy where we are now, but I could
sell millions of them,'' said Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Gorman, an editorial assistant with Mary Beth's Bean Bag
World, a Chicago-based online magazine devoted to the bean bag toy
industry, predicted Macca-Beanies will sell well within a limited
market, but she doesn't think they will spark widespread interest
from collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to introduce a Macca-Beanie key chain Oct. 15
that would retail for $2.99. A 2-foot-tall version of the
Macca-Beanie is still in development.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to Kvetch the Golden Retriever? It will be in
next year's batch, along with Kibbitz the Parrot and six others.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
