<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0577 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1545 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      09-29 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLERUD'S SLAM HALTS SLIDE AS METS BASH BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editors: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page) (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rey Ordonez sauntered over to the New York Mets' bat
rack about two hours before Wednesday night's game, puffing cigar
smoke around the lumber, a sort of makeshift blessing for a team
very much in need of a little divine intervention from the baseball
gods.
</P>
<P>
   Someone buy this man another cigar. The Mets, with a burst of
offense so furious that it seemed to explode all the tension stored
up for a week, pummeled the Atlanta Braves, 9-2, and stayed very
much in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   They are 1 1-2 games behind the Astros and Reds, who are tied
for the lead in the National League Central after Houston beat
Cincinnati, 4-1, Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   At least for a night, the Mets put aside a dark, surreal week
that included two team meetings, three lineup switches and one
manager saying he should perhaps be fired.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had made baseball look terribly difficult during their
seven-game skid _ they hit .211 in that span and were 6 for 53 with
runners in scoring position _ and this seemed like an almost
impossible circumstance to salvage a season. They were facing
future Hall of Famer Greg Maddux, who had beaten the Mets three
times this season and compiled a 0.86 earned run average in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   But Bobby Valentine, in grasping for something positive to say
before the game, noted that the Mets, with Al Leiter pitching, had
halted Roger Clemens' 20-game winning streak to end the Mets'
eight-game losing streak in June and start the Mets' remarkable
second-half run. With Leiter pitching again, Valentine pointed out
that Maddux was going for his 20th victory of the season.
Coincidence? Whatever. Finally, the Mets sifted through the rubble
of their losing streak and uncovered a nugget of gold.
</P>
<P>
   It came in the form of a seven-run fourth-inning rally off
Maddux that was as shocking as the Mets' losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets trailing, 2-1 _ they had taken a 1-0 lead, their
first edge since leading the Phillies Sept. 24 _ Darryl Hamilton
slapped a first pitch single to right. Roger Cedeno followed with a
single to shallow left. Ordonez, his bat behaving appropriately
under the hex, smacked an infield hit to shortstop Jose Hernandez
that loaded the bases.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Leiter, whose bloop dropped in front of a diving
Andruw Jones in short center. That tied the score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson was next. On the second pitch, Henderson hit a
hard roller that went under the glove of a diving Brian Hunter at
first. It went into short right and scored two runs to give the
Mets a 4-2 lead. Edgardo Alfonzo, who was 4 for 26 during the
losing streak, went to a 1-2 count, looking frustrated. But then he
singled in the gap between third and short to load the bases again.
</P>
<P>
   That brought John Olerud up. He, too, had suffered, going 7 for
29 in the seven losses. He took strike one from Maddux. Valentine
had said repeatedly during the slump that just one great hit, one
great play could turn thewhole thing around. If the Mets manage to
extricate themselves from the quicksand, they may point to Olerud's
at-bat as the pivotal moment. He lofted the ball high into the sky
and, in the seconds it took the grand slam to reach the right field
bullpen, the Mets leaped to the top step of the dugout. The Mets
led, 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   The drought was over. Nothing after that mattered, except in
what it told about the Mets' fortunes. Mike Piazza's single was the
eighth straight hit of the inning, and Maddux was gone after just
three innings, having given up eight runs _ seven earned _ on 11
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, the struggling ace, gave up just two runs on five hits.
The Mets made two sterling defensive plays in the fourth, one when
Ordonez fielded a bad hop for a groundout and the other on the next
play, when Maddux popped up in foul territory and Piazza slid to
make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza landed face first in the dirt, but bounced up with the
ball in his glove. He was messy-looking, but he had made a critical
save _ a pretty clear metaphor for the Mets when the smoke had
finally cleared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
