<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAB-DISNEY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arab demands on Disney exhibit called `blackmail'
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Disney's unwitting entry into the quagmire of
Middle Eastern politics began with a warning from Israel, likening
a threatened Arab boycott of the Magic Kingdom to political
blackmail Wednesday evening at a gathering that included about 300
Jews from Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political blackmail is just another word for terrorism,'' said
Israel's U.S. ambassador, Zalman Shoval, before the opening of an
Israeli exhibit that has raised international hackles because
according to reports, it originally referred to Jerusalem as the
eternal and indivisible capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,400-square-foot Israeli Pavilion is one of 25 countries
represented in the 15-monthlong exhibit at the Millennium Village.
The exhibit opens to the publicFriday. About 700 Jews from across
the country took a private tour Wednesday night at the request of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The pavilion includes a virtual ride through the history of
Jerusalem and showcases the county's high-tech, energy and
agricultural industries. In an eight-minute movie that is the
exhibit's main attraction, Jerusalem is called ``the heart of the
Jewish people'' and ``the capital of the millennium.'' But there
was no reference to Jerusalem as the eternal capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The city, which is sacred to Christians, Jews and Muslims, was
captured by the Israelis in 1967 from Jordan. Palestinians claim
the city is the future capital of their independent state.
</P>
<P>
   Israel _ which partially financed the pavilion to the tune of
$1.8 million _ said it was always its understanding that Jerusalem
would be described as the nation's capital. Both the Arab League
and Israel claimed victory after the compromise Disney executives
brokered last weekend. Still, Shoval was stern in his condemnation
of the Arab demands.
</P>
<P>
   The mostly Jewish audience came to Orlando at the request of
several embassies who asked Jewish leaders to arrange the trips as
a show of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to send the message that we Jews stand as one when it
comes to Israel,'' said Angela Lampert, the Chair of the Community
Relations Council of the Palm Beach Jewish Federation.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of the boycott threat at Disney and a dispute
last month over a Burger King near Jerusalem on disputed territory,
the growing power and sophistication of Arab lobbying groups is
starting to become evident.
</P>
<P>
   Two icons of U.S. capitalism have suffered public relations
nightmares and raised the profile of Arab concerns over land
disputes in and around Jerusalem just as final status negotiations
are beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been a revolution in the Arab-American political
establishment over the last few years,'' said Walid Phares, a
professor who teaches about ethnic and religious conflicts at
Florida Atlantic University's department of political science.
''There are more organizations, they are more grass-roots an they
are are becoming more sophisticated in their language and their
political culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab-American and Muslim-American leaders have learned lessons
from the lobbying efforts of other ethnic communities in the United
States, such as the Jewish and Armenian communities, and their
organizational efforts have been fueled by the speed of
communication through the Internet. At the forefront of this second
generation of pro-Palestinian movement is a 5-month-old
Washington-based organization called American Muslims for
Jerusalem. The group claims a membership of 50,000 and at one point
during the Burger King stand-off sent out 30,000 e-mails a day to
members to use as talking points.
</P>
<P>
   Khalid Turaani, the organization's 33-year-old executive
director, said the group is trying to balance what he called the
asymmetry of power between the Jewish and the Muslim lobbies in
America by leveraging the 3 million Arab-Americans and 6 million
U.S. Muslim's voices.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were really formed around the idea of telling our side of
the story _ the story of this holy city has not been told,''
Turaani said. ''We realize that a lot of decisions are made here in
the United States and here in Washington, D.C., that happen to be
unfair to the Christian and Muslim population and are to a large
extent influenced by the power of a pro-Israeli lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Turaani said he expected to bring about 100 protesters to EPCOT
on Friday to leaflet the exhibit and that his organization as well
as several other Arab-American and Muslim-American organizations
were going forward with a boycott. Their voices likely will be
heard. A public relations spokesperson for Disney said between 600
and 800 media outlets were expected at the opening ceremony. Also
in attendance were about 300 Jews from the Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going there to celebrate the opening of a wonderful
pavilion,'' said Ted Lampkin, community relations director for the
Jewish Federation for Palm Beach County. ``We felt it was important
for the American Jewish community to support Israel and support the
pavilion. There is a solid wall-to-wall consensus that Jerusalem is
the indivisible capital of the Jewish people in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
