<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS DOUBT THAT DEUTSCHE TELEKOM COULD BEAT MCI OFFER FOR
SPRINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 by TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Sprint Corp. and rival MCI WorldCom ponder a possible merger,
talks between the Westwood company and its French and German
partners in the Global One international venture have been shoved
to the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, local sources hesitate to discount the possibility that
Deutsche Telekom _ seen locally as a preferred partner because such
a deal probably would have less effect on area employment _ could
resurface with a superior offer for Sprint, or block an MCI
WorldCom deal.
</P>
<P>
   Market observers say it is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Investment analysts border on breathless in their enthusiasm for
an MCI//Sprint deal. They think there is little chance that
Deutsche Telekom could offer Sprint's shareholders better financial
returns than MCI WorldCom, the prime consideration of Sprint's
management team in any transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Strumingher, an analyst for PaineWebber, said a combined
Sprint and MCI would immediately benefit from increased scale,
improved distribution, sizable cost savings and the elimination of
a prime competitor.
</P>
<P>
   He pegged the first-year cost savings from a merger at $1.5
billion as the new company put Sprint's long-distance traffic over
MCI's network, eliminated a brand and its associated marketing
expenses and cut corporate overhead by eliminating redundant legal,
finance and other corporate positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal would play to one of MCI WorldCom's great strengths _
cost cutting,'' Strumingher wrote in a research note this week.
``What sometimes goes unsung is how stingy these guys are with
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Strumingher thinks a Sprint merger would be an explosive
catalyst to MCI WorldCom's stock price, which he projects at $105
to $110 within 12 months. MCI WorldCom closed Wednesday at 72 5//8,
down 1 9//16.
</P>
<P>
   That projection may be overly optimistic. But it resembles the
model that investment bankers and Sprint's management team, led by
a former investment banker, might use to analyze a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Strumingher assumes that Sprint shareholders would get 0.95
shares of MCI WorldCom in exchange for each of their shares. If the
new company's shares reached $100 in the first year after the
acquisition, Sprint shareholders would be looking at more than a 70
percent increase based on Sprint's closing price of 55 1//2, up
3//4 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS, the company's wireless venture, closed at 77 3//16,
up 3 11//16.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, on the other hand, would have little opportunity to
generate cost savings or improved distribution and are generally
seen as having less disciplined management than Sprint's.
</P>
<P>
   That might be good news for Sprint's local employees and
fretting civic leaders, but it is unlikely to result in big gains
to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Germans made a bid for Sprint, they'd have to give me
one heck of a premium to want to have them for a partner rather
than WorldCom,'' said Tony Ferrugia, an analyst at A.G. Edwards.
``If the Germans did make an offer to shareholders that was so
good, I don't think I'd want to be a longer-term shareholder.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's stock has performed well this year, but
analysts say it might not fare well if the company offered a big
premium for Sprint. Conversely, the company could realize a
substantial return if it were to sell its stake in Sprint, money it
could use to help fund another acquisition in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want a position in the U.S., they would have to start
looking at other network carriers like Qwest,'' Ferrugia said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the German and the French companies would be hit hard by a
merger between MCI WorldCom and Sprint, but particularly Deutsche
Telekom, which is under pressure to deliver on its longstanding
commitment to become a more global player in the telecommunications
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a strategic perspective, it would be an egregious loss
for Deutsche Telekom to lose their relationship with Sprint,'' said
James Downie, an analyst with ABN Amro in London.
</P>
<P>
   The German government, which owns most of Deutsche Telekom, also
is looking to sell its 65 percent stake in the company. The
government hopes to liquidate its position a soon as next July,
which could complicate any acquisition plans.
</P>
<P>
   A German bid for Sprint would also face complications stemming
from the company's troubled relationship with France Telecom. That
decadelong strategic partnership soured when the German company
failed to inform the French of its bid for Telecom Italia _ a bid
that ultimately failed.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom is suing the German company for violation of
partnership agreements. The same agreements would govern any move
on Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us has the right to increase our stake in Sprint
without informing the other'' or getting its approval, said Estelle
Rozine, a spokesman for France Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives at Deutsche Telekom were more cagey about the
status of their agreements and the possibility that Deutsche
Telekom would be permitted to make an offer under those
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for negotiation,'' said Stephan Broszio, a spokesman
for Deutsche Telekom. ``All options are open.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the partners refused to comment on the status of
negotiations to resolve differences at Global One. They do say that
they will have some news by the end of the year, and it will
probably involve a change in ownership structure.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Sprint still is not commenting on its discussions with
MCI. Regulators forbid companies to deny merger talks if they are
indeed proceeding, but they can refuse to comment _ indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail from Sprint employees Wednesday crackled with concern
about the merger discussions. Information was in short supply
internally because management had yet to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Manhattan law offices of Cravath, Swaine &AMP;
Moore, where MCI WorldCom and Sprint negotiators reportedly have
been meeting this week, also were n't in a talkative mood
Wednesday. They declined, through a security guard, to speak with a
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Chief Executive William T. Esrey is scheduled to appear
at a dedication ceremony Friday at the company's new $920 million
campus in Overland Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
