<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER FOOD EMBARGOES DELAYS ACTION ON FARM-AID BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 by KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A dispute over whether the United States should
stop using food embargoes to punish foreign countries has split
senators down unusual political lines and blocked $8.7 billion in
aid to distressed farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. John Ashcroft of Missouri and Sam Brownback of Kansas have
joined many Republicans and some Democrats in pushing for an end to
food and medicine sanctions. They said the embargoes closed
lucrative markets for farm products.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago the Senate voted 70-28 to amend the agriculture
appropriations bill to lift sanctions against Cuba, Iraq, Iran,
North Korea, Syria and the Sudan. The amendment, sponsored mainly
by Ashcroft, also would require the president to get congressional
approval of any future sanctions against those or other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of a House-Senate conference committee said America
should not do business with repressive or terrorist nations,
especially Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the House and the Senate have tried for
several days to get the conference committee to remove the Ashcroft
amendment. An impasse continued Wednesday, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership is making a tragic error, not just on its own
behalf but on the part of the agricultural community,'' Ashcroft
said in an interview. Lifting sanctions ``isn't just good farm
policy, it's good foreign policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said that some of the countries in question would use
some of their money to buy food and medicine instead of weapons and
that the United States would be seen as compassionate in allowing
starving nations to import farm products.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft joined Brownback and two Democratic senators at a news
conference Wednesday to lament efforts to remove the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when we're already suffering from low agricultural
prices, to add this burden is truly adding insult to injury,''
Brownback said. ``Unilateral trade sanctions...are effective in
punishing our farmers, but they are not effective in forwarding our
interests in other nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sens. Byron Dorgan of North Dakota and Richard Durbin
of Illinois and Republican Chuck Hagel of Nebraska joined Brownback
and Ashcroft at the news conference. All represent major farm
states.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas, however, urged conference committee
members to pass the bill without the amendment and get farmers
needed aid by Thanksgiving. The $8.7 billion is largely to
compensate farmers for low prices, meager foreign demand for goods
and losses due to drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing before us is to expedite that
emergency money,'' Roberts said. Roberts favored the Ashcroft
amendment to lift the sanctions but said he did not think it should
be insisted upon if it held up the larger bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kit Bond, a Missouri Republican, backs Ashcroft, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Farm Bureau, in step with the American Farm Bureau,
strongly favors lifting the sanctions as long as the United States
is not in military conflict with the countries in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ever there was a time when we needed to make sure we have
every opportunity available for farmers to sell what they produce,
it's now,'' Missouri Farm Bureau President Charles Kruse said.
</P>
<P>
   Kruse recently visited Cuba and said he found a strong desire to
do business with the United States instead of making distant and
more expensive purchases from Australia and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that really impressed me is that they genuinely like
Americans,'' Kruse said of the Cubans. ``They absolutely want to
buy our agricultural products.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Farm Bureau is urging rejection of the bill, saying
it does not provide farmers enough markets for their products and
did not provide enough overall assistance.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill first went to the conference committee, it called
for more than $7.4 billion in relief. An additional $1.2 billion
was added by Republican leaders for drought relief as an incentive
to remove the amendment to end sanctions and to remove another
amendment that deals with establishing dairy price compacts among
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-99 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990929.0583 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BREAKOUT-NYT     09-29 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREAKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE OF FORTUNE MEANS END OF SLUMP FOR METS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evidence that the New York Mets' fortunes have
changed abounded at Shea Stadium Wednesday night. Balls that in the
previous week's worth of games would have been caught fell just out
of the reach of Atlanta fielders. Balls hit by the Braves that
would have eluded the Mets' fielders found their way into Mets'
gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling sign was something that didn't happen. What
didn't happen didn't happen before 9:15 p.m. That was when Rickey
Henderson caught Chipper Jones' fly ball for the third out of the
Braves' half of the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   No, it wasn't that Jones didn't get yet another damaging hit
against the Mets in general and Al Leiter in particular (see
three-run home run, fifth inning, last Thursday night). It was that
Henderson's catch made the game official.
</P>
<P>
   What didn't happen was it didn't rain. If the Mets had battered
Greg Maddux, or any pitcher, for eight consecutive hits and seven
runs in the fourth inning in the previous week, the rain that had
been forecast for sometime Wednesday night would have descended on
Shea Stadium with the force of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would never have completed their fifth inning. The
biggest and most meaningful inning of the Mets' season would have
been washed away in the torrential downpour. The game would not
have counted. It would have been played again Thursday as part of a
doubleheader. The Mets would still be gasping for breath.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they're still not really breathing easily. Their 9-2
victory Wednesday night that ended their losing streak at seven
games did not alter the Mets' 1 1-2 game deficit in the National
League wild-card race. They still stand that much behind Houston
and Cincinnati with only four games to play. They still can't
afford to lose another game unless they have information that the
Astros and the Reds are going to lose two or three of the remaining
three games each team has.
</P>
<P>
   But the life they showed Wednesday night was a necessary
development in this end stage of the playoff race. A loss Wednesday
night, and the Mets could have sung ``the party's over.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as baseball has been played, no one has been able to
figure out how a collection of .300 hitters stops hitting at the
same time anymore than anyone has figured out why a team, any team,
can collect eight consecutive hits against a pitcher the caliber of
Maddux, the pitcher of the '90s playing for the team of the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   In their previous three tries against Maddux this season, all
losses, the Mets managed to score only three runs (two earned) and
stroke 11 hits in 21 innings. They had faced him seven times
without success since beating him three years ago this month. He
had compiled a 6-0 record with a 2.15 earned run average in those
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   More dire for the Mets, their squad of seven .300 hitters had
batted a combined .211 in the seven-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of sense a lot of them are pressing,'' said Don Baylor,
the Braves' hitting coach, when his view of the Mets was solicited.
``They're not relaxed. They're swinging at pitches they never did
swing at.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a turnaround for a bunch of players who, Baylor added, in
winning 92 games leading up to their lost week, ``were one of the
most feared teams in the National League.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no outs to be had,'' he said. ``They were scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets started losing, and the hitters began pressing.
``You really can't explain why it happens,'' Baylor said. ``It's
the same guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``Sometimes when you doubt yourself as a hitter,
it spreads. The next guy says I'm slumping, too, and the next guy,
and it becomes a team slump.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressing induces strange reactions. ``I think you try to get a
hit even before the ball's pitched,'' Robin Ventura said. ``You
want to get a rally going and knock it in all at the same time. You
can't do that. We have to realize that Mike isn't going to hit a
five-run homer. He can't. Everybody has to just get a hit instead
of trying to knock in every run all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   This, Edgardo Alfonzo said, ``is no time to think about hitting
two home runs in one swing. It's hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   No one hit two home runs in one swing against Maddux. John
Olerud hit one, and it produced four runs. He hit it after Leiter,
suddenly a hitting pitcher, blooped a ball into short center field
that fell just out of the reach of a diving Andruw Jones, the best
defensive outfielder in the game.
</P>
<P>
   And after Henderson hit a hard grounder between first and second
that Brian Hunter, the first baseman, dived for and got his glove
on but couldn't hold it. And after Alfonzo hit a grounder just out
of the reach of shortstop Jose Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's bases-loaded single, the fourth in a row against
Maddux, drove in the first run. Henderson's bases-loaded single,
No. 5, knocked in the second and third runs. Alfonzo's single, No.
6, reloaded the bases. Olerud's home run into the Mets' bullpen in
right field, delivered four more runs. Mike Piazza then lined a
single to left for consecutive hit No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
